<SLUG> BC-BABY-DEATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS REMAIN ABOUT WHY BABY DIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GORDY HOLT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January 1998, a 3-day-old Port Angeles, Wash., baby died
abruptly, and still, nobody knows why.
</P>
<P>
   Medical investigators were never sent to interview the parents
of the baby, Conor Shamus McInnerney, nor was a forensic
pathologist brought in to perform the autopsy. Instead, a hospital
pathologist in private practice did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like sending a general surgeon in to do brain
surgery,'' said the pathologist, Joel Ziebarth. Neither he nor a
partner is trained in the procedures that forensic pathology
requires to prepare medical evidence for disclosure in court, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, nevertheless, a doctor in the case, Port Angeles
pediatrician Eugene Turner, stood accused of suffocating the infant
and faced a second-degree murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Reay, King County's just-retired chief medical examiner,
said no one knows what a forensic examination might have found _ a
chemical imbalance, incomplete nervous-system circuitry, an injury
or maybe nothing at all _ but now no one will ever know.
</P>
<P>
   As the physician in charge the night Conor died, Turner is the
one who called off resuscitation efforts after he, the Olympic
Memorial Hospital emergency-room staff and paramedics were unable
to revive Conor.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor admitted to a serious mistake made more than an hour
after he declared the boy dead. He placed his hand over the baby's
nose and mouth to pinch off what he described as the agonal gasps
of a body in the final throes of death.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he intended it as an act of compassion. But the act
triggered a complaint from nurses, which fueled a state medical
board investigation and led to the murder charge by Clallam County
Prosecutor David Bruneau nearly eight months later.
</P>
<P>
   While that charge was subsequently reviewed in another county
and in January was dropped, Turner still could face a civil claim
by the baby's parents. No such claim has been filed.
</P>
<P>
   And while last month the state medical board stopped short of
stripping Turner of his license to practice medicine, it did place
an official censure in his file.
</P>
<P>
   Questions nevertheless remain about why the baby died, and
Clallam County is being reproached for mishandling the medical
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also wonder why the county prosecuting attorney's office
still handles the duties of coroner and why the death investigation
budget is not larger.
</P>
<P>
   Gaps in the medical investigation first came to light in June at
a medical hearing to determine if the doctor should lose his
license.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying via videotape before the state Medical Quality
Assurance Commission and in a separate interview later, King
County's Reay said the baby's autopsy record was sorely deficient.
</P>
<P>
   The former chief examiner said his review of the record showed
that X-rays were not taken; the baby's spinal cord was never
examined, and tissues and bodily fluids were never scrutinized
microscopically. Such tests are routine in King County, and should
be everywhere, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``An infant died,'' Reay said. ``It's unexplained. The record is
incomplete.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziebarth, the private pathologist who did the autopsy, would not
discuss his work on the infant. But he did say the cases he and a
partner typically accept from Clallam County ``are not cases we
feel would involve criminal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Also routine in King County, according to Reay, would have been
next-day attempts by specially trained medical investigators to
reconstruct what happened that night at the baby's home. But that,
too, was not done for the McInnerney baby.
</P>
<P>
   Always difficult, such interviews are important to clear the air
if nothing else, Reay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a child dies like this without apparent cause, you have
to think dirty,'' Reay said. ``You have to be suspicious, or you
can miss an awful lot. You must always think the worst before you
back away.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, all that is known about Conor McInnerney's death is
that his heart stopped beating, and he quit breathing while nursing
at his mother's breast at home.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, experts who testified on both sides of the case at
Turner's medical-board hearing cited biological and chemical
evidence to support the conclusion that Conor died at home _
possibly as much as an hour before paramedics arrived _ but none
could say why.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic question that remains,'' said Reay, ``is, what was
the underlying pathology that caused this child's death not what
happened at that hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the county's death-investigation system itself comes under
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Bruneau, who was determined to prosecute Turner after an
eight-month criminal investigation, tried to win a fifth term in
November but was defeated at the polls by Sequim attorney
Christopher Shea. Bruneau has since moved to Colville, where he was
hired as assistant prosecuting attorney for Stevens County. He did
not respond to requests for comment on this story.
</P>
<P>
   Bruneau's successor, on the other hand, said he is uncomfortable
with Reay's criticism and the gaps in the case that Reay revealed.
Shea also is uncomfortable with a quirk in the law that continues
to force his office to handle coroner duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at this 19th-century setup, and I'm wondering why
it isn't time for a more sophisticated system,'' Shea said. ``What
strikes me is, who are we as coroners? We're not doctors, we're
lawyers. So there's nobody here with the appropriate medical
skills, and that worries me.''
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, prosecutors have to be lawyers and medical
examiners like King County's Reay must be physicians certified in
forensic pathology.
</P>
<P>
   Those who campaign for a separate coroner's office, however,
need only know how to get elected, and those who do may or may not
choose to hire experts when they're needed.
</P>
<P>
   As constituted, Clallam County's 2-for-1 office saves taxpayers
an estimated $100,000 or more a year in salary and expenses, no
small amount at a time when their economy, once thriving on timber
and fish, isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Clallam County stretches nearly 100 miles along the Strait of
Juan de Fuca east from the Pacific Ocean. Most of it _ 93 percent _
is federally controlled park or forest land or is state-managed or
commercial forest land. Today's unemployment rate is 7.3 percent,
nearly double the 4.3 percent average statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring coroners and other medical investigators see Clallam
County's prosecutor/coroner system as a magnet for continued
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As an item in the prosecutor's $1 million budget, for example,
coroner duties were earmarked for just $18,000 this year, half of
what it was in the years from 1990 to 1993 and only a fraction of
what counties of similar size and smaller set aside for death
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``just asking for trouble,'' said San Juan County
Prosecutor Randall Gaylord who, like Shea, also wears two hats.
</P>
<P>
   San Juan County, he said, budgets $15,000 for death
investigations, but San Juan has a population of just 12,400
compared to Clallam's 66,400. In Eastern Washington's Grant County,
with a similar population at 69,400, Coroner Peggy Silbey said her
budget is $179,000, and she described the Clallam County situation
as ``woefully shortsighted.''
</P>
<P>
   Island County (Whidbey Island and Camano Island) also has a
population only a few thousand greater than Clallam County's
(70,300). But Island budgets $150,000 for death investigations,
according to Robert Bishop, the elected coroner. In Mason County
(population 48,300) $137,000 is earmarked for death inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Mason County Coroner Martha Reed said the disparity among county
systems and budgets underscores the need for hard state standards
or a way to harden newly developing national guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Training is available,'' she said, ``but it's not required.''
</P>
<P>
   Although state law does require separate officials for counties
with populations greater than 40,000, Clallam County's system slips
past that line because the voters want it to. In 1976 voters
elected to adopt a ``home rule charter'' that permits locally
contrived rules, and since then they have kept coroner duties
wedded to the prosecuting attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   If the Conor McInnerney case suggests it is time for a change,
so be it, said Clallam County Commissioner Martha Ireland of
Sequim. Her mind is open. ``If this is now a new concern,'' she
said, `I hope we can learn from it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
