<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-DRIVER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN'S DEATH MAY LEAD TO TESTS OF OLDER DRIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mark Mitock's 15-year-old daughter was hit and
killed by a 96-year-old motorist, who stopped but was unable to
understand what had happened and continued on his way to the dry
cleaner's shop.
</P>
<P>
   Mitock's grieving has never ended, and the Woodland Hills man
has campaigned for a law that would stiffen regulation of drivers
75 and older. Senate Bill 335, which would require road tests for
drivers after they turn 75, will come before the Assembly
Transportation Committee one week from today.
</P>
<P>
   State records show that California motorists continue driving
into their 80s and 90s, and Mitock says that makes the bill a vital
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel this is the beginning of something very, very
frightening,'' Mitock said in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   A car driven by Byron Cox killed Brandi Joy Mitock in a Santa
Monica intersection on Nov. 5. Cox suffered a major stroke the day
after the death, and physicians determined that he had sustained a
series of smaller strokes sometime before his car hit the
teen-ager, said his attorney Karen Filipi.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded no contest to felony hit-and-run charges and was
fined $5,000 and placed on probation. Cox was allowed to pay the
fine into a fund supporting the bill, Filipi said.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi's father has made a circuit of policymakers' offices and
centers for senior citizens since state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los
Angeles, introduced SB335 in February. The Senate passed it in
June.
</P>
<P>
   To Mitock, the issue is one of common sense and responsibility.
To opponents of the legislation, it is an arbitrary proposal
ignoring highway safety improvements and variations in how people
age.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Retired Persons opposes the bill,
arguing that it amounts to age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that triggers it is achieving a certain
birthday,'' said Helen Savage, the AARP's state legislative
representative. ``People do not age identically.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden's bill would reduce the periods licenses are valid for
drivers 75 and older, and they would be required to pass
behind-the-wheel tests every time they apply for license renewal.
Drivers 90 and older would have to take the road tests annually.
</P>
<P>
   Now drivers 70 and older must renew their licenses in person and
take written and vision tests.
</P>
<P>
   Mitock said the premise of the bill is that motor skills and
reaction ability deteriorate as people age. Hayden said 75 was
chosen as the action-triggering age because that is when at-fault
and fatal crashes spike upward, according to DMV statistics.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 968,000 drivers older than 75 in
California, but there is no estimate of how many of them might lose
their licenses because of the tests the bill would require.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
