<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY HAS TRANSFOMRED MAYOR INTO PIPELINE-SAFETY CRUSADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Growing up in Bellingham, Wash., Mark Asmundson was
only dimly aware that a pipeline went through town, and throughout
his years on the City Council and then as mayor, not much changed.
</P>
<P>
   But Asmundson did know the King family, and the Woods, and the
Tsiorvases.
</P>
<P>
   So Asmundson, who was traveling in Russia at the time, was
heartbroken when he received an urgent fax from City Hall,
informing him that each of those families had lost a son in the
June 10 oil-pipeline explosion in Bellingham, a city about 90 miles
north of Seattle, in Whatcom County.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Asmundson's job as mayor has been transformed. He
has been attending funerals, holding meetings and hiring two
environmental lawyers _ one of whom represented Alaska in the Exxon
Valdez case _ to make sure Bellingham knows how much it can demand
from The Olympic Pipe Line Co.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he was in Washington, D.C., lobbying for pipeline
reform. And Asmundson says he'll be back: He expects to make
pipeline reform a major crusade and is encouraging his constituents
to turn their anger into involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more informed I become about pipeline-safety issues, the
more nervous I become about pipeline safety,'' Asmundson said in an
interview. ``It's just good luck that these pipelines are not
blowing up homes and burning up kids every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Asmundson, 48, has been in politics much of his life. A
Bellingham native, he was the student body president at Bellingham
High School, where he graduated in 1969. After going to college,
managing a ski lodge and graduating from law school, he was elected
to the City Council in 1985. Ten years later _ after voters angry
about property rights had kicked him off the council _ he was
elected mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Asmundson considers himself a Democrat, but his office is
non-partisan, and his issues have been the basic staples of local
government, such as growth management and water-quality protection.
He runs a mid-sized city _ Bellingham has 64,000 residents and an
annual budget of about $175 million _ and had rarely thought about
what might lie under those warning signs marking the rights of way
for two interstate pipelines running through the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know what products went through them,'' he said.
``Five or six years ago the Kulshan Middle School was built 30 feet
from a pipeline. Knowing what people know now, that would never
occur again. But it just was not something people thought about.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffering a dramatic tragedy in his community has opened doors
in D.C. for Asmundson. He met not only with both of Washington
state's senators and six of the seven House members representing
Western Washington but also with several Democratic congressmen
concerned about pipeline safety, the staffs of committees with
jurisdiction over pipeline safety, the National Transportation
Safety Board and the Office of Pipeline Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Asmundson's message this trip is simple: He wants Bellingham
officials to be consulted before Congress renews the nation's
pipeline safety laws next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My basic message is this: The federal government has taken
complete control of the regulation of the safety of pipelines and
along with that goes a significant responsibility,'' Asmundson
said, referring to the fact that the federal government bans states
from imposing stricter regulations on pipeline safety. ``I want
members of Congress and the administration to understand that out
of sight is often out of mind, and it is not within the purview of
the average citizen to monitor the quality of the physical
conditions of pipelines. ... The public does not maintain constant
vigilance over things that are buried below the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Asmundson is planning to try to form a coalition with other
local officials from states that have had pipeline accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put this in the category of enlightened self-interest,'' he
said of his involvement in a federal battle. ``This pipeline that
goes through Bellingham is part of a very complex system, and it
needs to be safe up and down the pipeline to be safe here. We need
to have long-term assurance that the safety standards applied
nationally are sufficient to provide protection here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
