r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BROWNS-TE     08-09 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BROWNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS COACH WON'T BE FIXATED ON SCORE, BROWNS HOOPLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ Cowboys coach Chan Gailey expects a circus-like
atmosphere for tonight's preseason opener against the expansion
Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   With the backdrop of the annual Pro Football Hall of Fame Game
and the national stage of ``Monday Night Football'', Gailey knows
what to expect from the Browns, who are playing in their first game
since Art Modell moved the original team to Baltimore in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey believes a pumped-up Browns team will undoubtedly be
motivated to put on a good show for their football-starved fans,
including the raucous ``Dawg Pound.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the Cowboys is to not get caught up in the
hoopla and remain focused on their goals _ and winning is not at
the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``They \Rthe Browns\S will treat it more seriously,'' Gailey
said. ``I can't control them. We'd like to win, but that's not the
No. 1 thing we are trying to accomplish. We are on our own agenda.
What they do doesn't affect us. We will play according to what we
think we need.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys need is to get live-action assessments of
several rookies and young players expected to play major roles this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list of players to watch are rookie defensive end
Ebenezer Ekuban, the team's top draft pick; second-year defensive
tackle Michael Myers, who is replacing the suspended Leon Lett in
the starting lineup; and second-year free safety Izell Reese, who
is battling George Teague for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran starters such as quarterback Troy Aikman, receiver
Michael Irvin and running back Emmitt Smith will play one or two
series at the most in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games are the younger players,'' Irvin said. ``It's more
important for the coaches to find out who they can and can't count
on among the younger guys. I don't know if Troy needs to play a
whole lot for Chan to understand what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will also focus on several young players who are
vying for backup roles and roster spots, including defensive
tackles Darren Benson and Nate Davis, rookie defensive end Peppi
Zellner, linebackers Dat Nguyen, Robert Thomas and Darren Hambrick,
receivers Wane McGarity and Jeff Ogden and rookie offensive guard
Solomon Page, who is in the starting lineup because of a host of
early camp injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said preseason games are where you find out what is real
and what is fake as far as practice performances go.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of veterans, defensive end Alonzo Spellman and
linebacker Quentin Coryatt, also figure into the live-action
evaluation because they are both coming off yearlong layoffs and
need as much as work as they can to get rid of some rustiness.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, Gailey would have also liked to focus on some group
aspects of the game _ like four wide-receiver sets and the
communication in the secondary and on the offensive line. However,
he said that type of evaluation against the Browns was rendered
moot by the rash of early training-camp injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will play without their top four cornerbacks. Deion
Sanders (toe) and Charlie Williams (forearm) are sidelined by
precamp injuries. Kevin Smith (back) and Kevin Mathis (back) have
been hobbled in the past week, likely putting rookie Duane
Hawthorne and Zebbie Lethridge in the starting lineup tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the top four receivers are injured as well _ Raghib
Ismail (shoulder) and Ernie Mills (hamstring) for a week or so and
James McKnight (knee) for the season. Ogden will start opposite
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the injuries, this will be more of individual game
than groups, sections or sides of the balls,'' Gailey said. ``We
are looking at individuals to see how they play in context of
offense, defense and special teams. And find out if what I see on
the practice field holds up in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the specter of the occasion is an added bonus for
him because he'll get to see how the young players react in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban, expected to contribute immediately in the defensive-end
rotation, is looking forward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an exciting moment playing the Browns in Canton in
the Hall of Fame Game on ``Monday Night Football'','' Ekuban said.
``It's a chance for all of us young players to showcase our talents
and put on a good show for the coaches. it will definitely be a
memorable experience.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
