<HEADER>
A0228 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COUCH-DEBUT-TEX     08-09 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COUCH-DEBUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNS' COUCH TO TAKE FIRST PRO EXAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio _ Rookie Cleveland Browns quarterback Tim Couch has
a $48 million contract, recently became engaged to] his longtime
girlfriend, and has a whole bunch of football trading cards to
sign. Yet the game attached to his fame isn't quite ready for prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   After missing an open wide receiver in practice last week, Couch
had this conversation with coach Chris Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer: ``Hey, didn't you see the Z?''
</P>
<P>
   Couch: ``Uh, I forgot the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer: ``I guess you don't want me to sleep at nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch: ``I couldn't lie to you.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked later about Couch's mental development at the most
demanding position in football, Palmer said this about the
exchange: ``That's a typical routine for a rookie. He was so proud
of getting \Rthe offensive line\S in the right protection, and then
he just kind of went blank on what the play was really going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it has gone with the 6-foot-4, 227-pound Couch
this summer in his transition from college to pro quarterback. The
player taken with the first pick in the NFL draft last April can be
brilliant one minute, able to hit a wide receiver 60 yards
downfield on the dead run; bumbling the next, throwing left when
the play he called in the huddle was meant to go right.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one should be surprised. Nine other quarterbacks have
been selected No. 1 in the NFL draft since the AFL-NFL merger in
1970. And each one _ Terry Bradshaw, Jim Plunkett, Steve
Bartkowski, John Elway, Vinny Testaverde, Troy Aikman, Jeff George,
Drew Bledsoe and Peyton Manning _ had considerable growing pains
their rookie seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Like the nine before him, Couch was drafted to eventually start.
But his day has not come yet. Journeyman quarterback Ty Detmer, who
is on his fourth team in eight NFL seasons, will start and play the
first 12 to 15 plays against the Cowboys tonight in the Pro
Football Hall of Fame Game in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Couch will come off the bench some time in the second quarter.
And in the coming weeks, Couch will unseat Detmer as the starter
and begin writing a new chapter in the Browns' history of
quarterbacks, which includes Otto Graham, Brian Sipe, and Bernie
Kosar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's no secret _ they drafted Tim to be the guy for the
future,'' Detmer said. ``...I'm supposed to be the backup here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about the past No. 1s, the Aikmans, the Elways, and I
realize the expectations and the pressures of being a No. 1 pick,''
Couch said. ``But I've just got to be myself and do what got me to
that point of being a first pick.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to start with getting the plays down. When he set
every meaningful passing record at the University of Kentucky, he
did so without a playbook. ``We had a right and a left,'' he joked,
``Coach \RHal\S Mumme would draw stuff up on the board and we'd
just learn them in practice.'' Here, the Browns' playbook is four
inches thick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot to learn,'' Couch said. ``But I'm getting it
down.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also trying to get down how much faster the action is in
the pros than it was in college. He talked to Manning a few weeks
before camp, and the Colts quarterback tried to warn him of the
differences in the pro and college games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really see it in the running game,'' Couch said. ``You
hand the ball off, look back and you see a big hole open up. It
looks like the play is going to go for 40 yards. Then, bam!
Somebody makes the play at the line of scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   There were questions about Couch's arm when he was drafted. But
Palmer said Couch's arm is strong enough to throw any pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was dropping back to pass the other day, and he falls flat
on his rear end,'' Palmer said. ``He's sitting on the ground and in
one smooth motion he throws a hitch outside. As a coach, I'm ready
to yell, `Hey, you don't do that in the NFL.' Then I said to
myself, `That was a pretty impressive throw for a guy that doesn't
have a strong arm.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the guy is a playmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   A nationally televised audience will begin to see the
possibilities for themselves tonight.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
