<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0229 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLLINS-LADN     08-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLLINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS HOLDS IN FRUSTRATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Terry Collins recently stood among a group of
reporters in the Anaheim Angels' dugout and asked them a peculiar
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is anybody else having trouble sleeping lately?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   No, Terry. Just you. After all, you're the one managing a
major-league club that was expected to contend for a division title
but instead has fallen out of the race and into last place.
</P>
<P>
   You're the one that has had to piece together your lineup all
season because of injuries to key players.
</P>
<P>
   You're the one that faced a clubhouse divided over your contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   And you're the one that had to answer the same questions after
each loss during an 11-game losing streak, the longest in the big
leagues this season.
</P>
<P>
   Collins isn't the type to go home after a loss and kick the dog
or punch a hole in the wall. But it might not be such a bad thing
if he were able to release his frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold it in, and that's never been good,'' Collins said.
``When I go home after the game's over, there's no such thing as
leaving it here at the ballpark. I'm not going over the game we
just played, but I'm trying to figure out what to do to make
tomorrow more successful.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the reason why Angels general manager Bill Bavasi
quickly dismissed the players' concerns about Collins and extended
his contract for two more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is as competitive as they come, so losing isn't
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to win probably as much as anybody I've ever seen,''
said Angels third-base coach Larry Bowa. ``He's kept his cool
through all the frustrating times and lets the players know he's
positive. But it's a tough time. We had high expectations. Terry
takes it very personal. He cares, and he doesn't just leave it
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It eats at him. He tries to mask it the best he can. He's very
competitive and there are nights he doesn't sleep. He's never been
through this as a manager. He's been successful his whole career as
a manager.''
</P>
<P>
   In Collins' five previous big league seasons as a manager --
three with Houston and two with the Angels -- he had five winning
seasons. However, he had no playoff appearances, either. In all
five seasons his teams finished in second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``All winter I heard crap about `You finished second again,'''
Collins said. ``Well, how would it feel if we were in second right
now?''
</P>
<P>
   It might feel better than last place, but it still wouldn't be
good enough for Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels like we all feel,'' Angels closer Troy Percival said.
``He's out there every day with us. He takes it home like every one
of us. If you had a manager that handled this well, you wouldn't
want him here.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the first time Collins has found himself trying to
piece together an injury-riddled roster. In 1984, his second year
as the Dodgers' triple-A manager in Albuquerque, things got a
little crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an outstanding team,'' said Collins, who managed the
Dukes from 1983-88. ``We had so many injuries at the end of the
year, Dave Wallace, my pitching coach, was pitching and I was
playing second base and shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he isn't playing anymore, Collins practically lives
at the ballpark. It's surprising he doesn't have a cot in his
office. He often arrives before noon for a 7:05 p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many minutes in a day that are mine,'' he
explained. ``It's why I get here so early, so I have time that is
mine. The phone isn't ringing, there aren't people coming in and
out. It gives me time to work out and put together that night's
lineup. I'm giving myself my space, which everybody has to have.''
</P>
<P>
   While it all may seem like Collins is a poster child for stress
management, he doesn't want anybody feeling sorry for him. Save
your pity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody forced me into this job, so you'd better be ready for
the tough times,'' he said. ``Because it's a tough game. It can
humble you in a hurry. ... When I got into this is as a manager, I
gave myself a time frame. I said, `I'll give all I got for as long
as I can.' When it becomes work, it's time to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through all the stuff we've been through this year, I like
those guys (players). I respect them. I respect all they have to do
to play at this level. It's not always going to go good and
sometimes everybody thinks they have all the answers, but I enjoy
coming here every day, trying to win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, things will get better for Collins and the
Angels. It may be too late this year for it to make a difference,
but Collins won't settle for less than the best -- from himself or
his players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
