<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0230 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIPLOMAMILL-AZR &LR;      08-09 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIPLOMAMILL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMA MILLS THRIVE ON NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you hoping for ``a prosperous future, money earning power,
and the admiration of all''?
</P>
<P>
   If so, you might be interested in obtaining a diploma from a
``prestigious'' university _ especially one that involves ``no
required tests, classes, books or interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, you can get your diploma in only a few days, and
``no one is turned down.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no joke. It's an example of what one educator calls the
``new age of diploma mills on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Palmers Green, which even its own registrar
described as ``a diploma mill'' based in London, is offering
diplomas on the Internet for a mere $1,400.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seems sure whether it's legal, but some officials fear
that such fake credentials may be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Crow, executive director of the North Central Association
of Colleges and Schools, said the Internet is ``a rich seedbed''
for questionable enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in for a new age of diploma mills on the
Internet,'' Crow said. ``Anybody can throw these things up
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same thing as setting up a physical place and
putting your shingle out _ where folks actually see you and can
find out if you have legal authority to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to stop people from doing some fast, hard
business on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Palmers Green, a bachelor's degree costs
$1,400, minus $500 if you sign up today. A second degree costs
$450. A third degree runs $400.
</P>
<P>
   Leave a message at a phone number with a New York City area
code, and a diploma could be yours in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give you full credit for your work and life experience,''
said Lee Karo, the registrar. ``We give you your diploma,
transcripts, recommendation letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people we deal with are highly qualified, but for
whatever reason it isn't practical for them to complete their
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diploma really just gets you in the door (with an
employer). You have to be qualified to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Karo declined to give any information about the university's
owners. He referred a reporter to another number, where the person
who answered said he didn't know anything about the university.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Thackeray, special counsel for technology crime at the
Arizona Attorney General's Office, said law enforcement authorities
are still sorting out the jurisdictional complications of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Although state statutes may reach across geographic boundary
lines, enforcement is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go find 'em,'' Thackeray said. ``You can often
find the guilty server, but not the people behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Davis, who oversees consumer fraud for the Attorney
General's Office, said state law prohibits her from commenting on
whether her division has received complaints about the University
of Palmers Green.
</P>
<P>
   In general, she said, advertisements for diploma mills must make
a misrepresentation or omission of fact to be regarded as
fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   Thackeray added, ``It's legal to sell a certificate of nothing.
But if they are misleading people into thinking it will lead to
jobs, the same as a university degree, that might be illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   People who pass off phony degrees as legitimate to prospective
employers could be guilty of fraud or forgery, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Driggers, vice president for finance and administration at
the Greater Phoenix Economic Council, said employers are more
likely to check out an applicant's degree if he is coming straight
from school, with no work experience.
</P>
<P>
   More experienced job candidates are evaluated mainly by their
work history and references, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see something on a resume and you tend to believe it is
true rather than not true,'' Driggers said.
</P>
<P>
   Employment agencies do background checks that might reveal phony
claims, she said. And during interviews, Driggers said she and
other employers ask technical questions designed to reveal the
applicant's competency _ a strategy that works best in technical
fields such as accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Crow said people who buy a degree from a diploma mill
``shouldn't be surprised when they try to market it and it doesn't
get them anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The association frequently gets calls from prospective employers
wanting to know whether a school is accredited, Crow said.
Employers also consult the association's Web site, which lists
accredited institutions. &QL; 
Beverly Medlyn can be reached at 444-8213 or at
bev.medlyn(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0240 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SLUG-TEX     08-09 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOOSE-SIZE HEART WON'T LET COWBOYS' JOHNSTON FINISH ON SOUR NOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ In your heart, which some have compared
to the massive motor of a Mack truck, you understand that nothing
lasts forever and that your days as a Dallas Cowboy are numbered.
</P>
<P>
   You, better than anyone, know that the familiar cries of
``Moooooooose!'' at Texas Stadium and around the NFL will soon be
only a distant and fading echo.
</P>
<P>
   This, you're the first to admit, could be the last training camp
for Daryl Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK, but you're here, dragging yourself through the waves
of Texas heat, not because you don't know how to say goodbye, but
because you just can't allow yourself to quit with the bitter taste
of regret so fresh in your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates and friends have asked why you're even here, after all
that's happened over the past two years. Why, at 33, put yourself
through this torture? Why subject yourself to the aches and pains
and the sweltering heat when you could easily step from here into
the Dallas business world and never miss a beat?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, lies in that massive heart that has
driven you to be the best from the moment the Cowboys selected you
in the second round of the '89 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd quit after last year,'' you tell people who ask, ``then
you walk away with a feeling that they beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're name is Daryl Johnston, that's not something you can
stomach. You came back last year after that horrendous and
near-tragic neck injury in 1997, and coaches, teammates and fans
alike applauded your courage and your determination.
</P>
<P>
   But in your heart, you know that you didn't play to the level
you expected to play. The fullback was a forgotten position in Chan
Gailey's new offense (77 combined rushing and receiving yards for
the season). It was not the way you had envisioned your comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The positive was that you could feel yourself making solid
progress throughout the season. You were getting stronger. Your
weight was coming back. You were becoming more familiar with the
offense. All that combined to make you believe that with another
off-season of training, you could finally be back to where you were
before the herniated disk in your neck.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that tonight, in Canton, Ohio, you'll probably be
butting heads with Browns linebacker Chris Spielman, who had an
almost identical herniated disk two years ago as well. If anything,
his was even worse than yours _ he was actually completely
paralyzed for a few seconds while yours manifested in loss of
strength and mobility in your left arm and upper body.
</P>
<P>
   But there was never a doubt in your mind that you'd play again
this season, if the Cowboys would have you.
</P>
<P>
   There was some question about that during the off-season, and
that hurt deeply. Being exposed in the Cleveland expansion draft
was a shock, but that was just the tip of the problem. With your
role in the offense reduced, owner Jerry Jones felt a need to
reconstruct your contract.
</P>
<P>
   The way that it was handled, that no one came forward to talk to
you about all this until the morning of the expansion draft, was
the biggest disappointment of all. You even had agent Leigh
Steinberg looking around the league as you contemplated the
unthinkable: moving to another team.
</P>
<P>
   It took a meeting with Jones before your feelings were soothed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood what he was trying to accomplish, and he
understood why I was disappointed,'' you would say later. ``It was
an important meeting to have because it cleared the air. I think
after that meeting we're basically back to the point where we were
beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   The renegotiated contract cut your base pay from what would have
been $1.25 million this year to $400,000, but there's no
resentment. You're the first to say that you've already made more
money playing football than you ever dreamed you'd make.
</P>
<P>
   The events of the past year, however, have brought home the
reality that your football career is now on a year-to-year basis.
No more looking to finish out contracts and then beyond. From this
point, it's just one year at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The aches and pains of 10 NFL seasons sit heavy on those broad
shoulders that have brought such terror to linebackers around the
NFL. But the physical part you've always been able to take. The
mental and emotional strain has become just as demanding. You were
as wrung out as a dishrag by the time the season ended last year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, you've decided you'll finish your career as a
Dallas Cowboy. You even talked to Tony Dorsett about the
difficulties of moving to another team late in your career. He
recommended you try to close it out the way you came in _ with a
star on your helmet. That's the only way you ever wanted it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of your life, the idea of picking up and moving
your family to another city, just to prolong your playing career
for another year or two is just not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   And we are talking family. Wife, Diane, is expecting your first
child Jan. 23, 2000, NFC championship Sunday. It could be quite an
eventful day.
</P>
<P>
   The day you found out she was pregnant was one of the happiest
moments of your life, and you think about it every day now. How
will you do as a father? How will it impact your life?
</P>
<P>
   All you can do, you figure, is rely on what you've learned from
your own parents and then devour all you can read on the subject.
It's a scary thought, being a parent in today's society, but you'll
attack the problem head on.
</P>
<P>
   It's the only way the ``Moose'' knows how to play.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-09 0948
