<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0248 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-SLOCUM-     08-09 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-SLOCUM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M MAY BE READY TO GO FOR THE BIG PRIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time since joining the Big 12 Conference, Texas
A&AMP;M heads into a football season as the favorite to win the league
championship. As such, the Aggies figure to be the highest-ranked
conference team when The Associated Press' preseason
college-football poll is released Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   That makes them flagbearers for a league that has seen its
members win four national championships in the 1990s (three by
Nebraska, one by Colorado). Can the Aggies, who return 16 starters
from an 11-3 team, make a serious run at becoming the Big 12's
fifth team to capture college football's ultimate prize in this
decade?
</P>
<P>
   Coach R.C. Slocum welcomes his incoming freshmen today,,] with
the veterans scheduled to report Thursday. Slocum talked recently
about the defending Big 12 champs' hopes and expectations for 1999:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does this team have the personnel it takes to win a national
championship?
</P>
<P>
   A: In all honesty, that's hard for a coach to say. But I know
we've got eight starters back on offense and eight on defense, and
I feel good about all of those people. I think the defense can be
as good or better than last year, and the offense should be better.
We've got the best group of receivers we've had since I've been
here. At most positions, I feel very comfortable with these
players. The only position I don't know about is tight end. We lost
two talented players \Rboth to the NFL draft\S and need someone to
step forward.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A year ago, you knocked off teams ranked No. 1 (Kansas State)
and No. 2 (Nebraska) despite entering both games as double-digit
underdogs. Those stand as the two highest-ranked opponents an A&AMP;M
team has ever defeated. Given the high percentage of returning
starters, how much confidence can this team draw from those
breakthrough victories in 1998?
</P>
<P>
   A: Quite a bit, I think. Over time, you get to the point there
are some psychological things you have to get over. Until you get
it done, you have that monkey on your back. Those wins helped us
clear a hurdle. There seems to be a carryover from last season,
with the guys wanting to achieve more. That's natural. But you
don't automatically do better just because you have a lot of guys
returning from a strong team. The team chemistry last fall was the
best I've ever been around. I'll be anxious to see how this club
comes together.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The last time A&AMP;M players entered a season talking about a
national championship was 1995. That team lost its third game, at
Colorado, then failed to even win the Southwest Conference
championship. What did you learn that season that can help you in
1999?
</P>
<P>
   A: I felt I made a mistake in that Colorado game. The guys were
so tight, they could hardly respond. I didn't do a good job of
sensing that we weren't ready mentally to go out and play our best
game. We could have won that game by two touchdowns. But we weren't
over that mental hurdle yet. We were playing a good team on the
road, and we came out there and screwed it up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Toward that end, what will be different when you travel to
Nebraska on Nov. 6 for what should be your most important road game
of the season?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we'll be able to go in with the mental frame of mind
to go out there and say, `Let's just play.' We have grown a little
bit in the last few years, which is a natural thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've already declared this your best group of receivers in
your 11 seasons at A&AMP;M. Can quarterback Randy McCown throw well
enough to make use of all those weapons?
</P>
<P>
   A: Randy's capable of being a real good passer for us. I thought
he was better in the spring in his understanding and overall
abilities. He made great strides. Plus, if you have a guy who can
jump and make one-handed catches, all of a sudden, your stats look
a whole lot different.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Speaking of that type of guy, you've been raving about wide
receiver Bethel Johnson since he was working with the scout team
last fall. Now that he's eligible to play, how much of an impact do
you anticipate?
</P>
<P>
   A: If he'd been out there last fall, we wouldn't have struggled
throwing the ball early in the season, like we did. He's got
big-play potential, speed, excellent hands. In the spring, I'd see
a ball look like it was overthrown, then he'd hit another gear,
catch it and be in the end zone. He'll really help our passing
game. I'm anxious to see him in a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all this talent at wide receiver, will we see 40 passes
a game from the Aggies? Or will tailback Dante Hall still carry
enough to have a chance to break the 1,000-yard mark again this
season?
</P>
<P>
   A: We'll still run more than we throw. But I think we're making
progress and building to where we are a balanced offensive team.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How difficult will it be to replace Dat Nguyen, as both a
playmaker and emotional leader?
</P>
<P>
   A: We won't be as good as we were with Dat at that position
\Rinside linebacker\S. But we'll still have a good group of inside
linebackers. Cornelius Anthony is an excellent candidate for
all-star honors. He's already stepped up to provide some of Dat's
leadership, but he's not Dat Nguyen. We'll miss Dat.
</P>
<P>
   Q: McCown missed two games last season because of injuries,
including the Big 12 championship game. Your choices behind him are
a redshirt freshman (Vance Smith) and a freshman (Mark Farris) who
has spent the past five years playing minor-league baseball. How
does the backup quarterback spot look at this point?
</P>
<P>
   A: We like Vance Smith. He's got good size \R6-foot-5, 225
pounds\S, a strong arm and he's been in the program an extra year.
But I think Mark Farris has done an amazing job of getting back
into football. He just turned 24, so he's remarkably ahead of what
you'd expect from a true freshman because of his maturity. He
figures very strongly into the backup picture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During the summer, quarterbacks coach Ray Dorr was found to
have ``Lou Gehrig's disease.'' How is his health status and what is
his prognosis?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ray has handled everything with tremendous courage and
character. He hasn't asked any quarter, does his job, worked the
summer camp, and carries on like nothing ever happened. I've told
him as long as you can physically do the job and want to do it,
you'll be our quarterbacks coach. No question, his situation brings
some reality into this whole thing. We don't know what course the
disease will take. But I admire how he's handled this.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Among the incoming freshmen, who are the guys likely to have
the biggest impact?
</P>
<P>
   A: \RDefensive lineman\S Ty Warren is 282 pounds and he can
move. I would say that going back to Sam Adams \R1991-93\S, we've
not had a defensive lineman with the physical talents that Ty
Warren has. And \Rrunning back\S Joe Weber played in high school at
225 pounds and averaged 8.2 yards per carry. He has thick thighs,
he's quick-footed, catches the ball, makes cuts and has another
gear when he gets in the open field. I think he's a special running
back.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you concerned that too much may be expected of this team?
</P>
<P>
   A: Every year, you want to do better and achieve more. And
that's where we are. If you look at last year and really analyze
it, we won some games that could have gone either way. So you don't
know if you'll be as good as last year. But if all goes well, we
can be as good as we were last year. We can be better.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are fans' projections of an undefeated season unrealistic?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fans, to a large degree, stay frustrated. They're looking for
a Utopia to the point where no one ever beats you. In modern-day
football, with scholarship limits, that doesn't happen any more.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
