<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS SWEEP M'S OUT TO SEA AND WELL BELOW .500 MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Like many of the 45,195 people at Safeco Field on
Sunday, Mariners manager Lou Piniella checked out early. The bats
stayed in the racks and the baselines went untouched when Piniella
was ejected for arguing balls and strikes in the seventh inning.
There were loud words, unidentified gestures and coaches acting as
offensive linemen, but nothing of great significance.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever was said, there seemed to be one message for the whole
scene: enough, already. By the time Paul Abbott walked his third
straight hitter in a 9-3 loss to the New York Yankees, there was
nothing left to see in the Mariners' lost weekend.
</P>
<P>
   No four-game series in Seattle has ever attracted more fans. And
few, perhaps, have been more deflating. The Mariners were swept in
the series, and are now five below .500.
</P>
<P>
   The M's have hit .206 over their past five games. Their earned
run average is 6.60. In the past five weeks, they have had a
winning streak of six and losing streaks of seven and five. New
York had something to do with the current slide, but not
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need measuring sticks right now,'' said
catcher Dan Wilson. ``We're not playing very well right now, not
doing the little things, not doing what it takes to win. It doesn't
matter who's out in the field against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella, ``If everything had gone right for us this
series, we could have won a couple of these games. We didn't, and
we've got to regroup. They're a world champion team for some reason
_ they can rest their team, they can do a lot of things. But
outside of (Saturday), we really didn't play all that well,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a pitchers' duel between the Yankees' David Cone and the
Mariners' John Halama turned on one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Through three innings, Halama (9-3) had thrown first-pitch
strikes to 10 of 11 hitters and allowed no runs. Two Yankees
reached with one out in the fourth, but with Halama, the last thing
that would happen in that situation is a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Halama had allowed seven homers prior to Sunday, six with the
bases empty. Since hitters become more aggressive with men on base,
Wilson explained, Halama counters by taking something off his
pitches. That's what he did against Scott Brosius, going with a
``good changeup,'' Halama said, on the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees' third baseman popped it over the left-field
fence, giving his team a 3-0 lead and surprising Halama, his
catcher and his pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was going out, because it was hit off the
end of the bat,'' Halama said. ``Dan didn't think it was going out,
neither did Stan (Williams). I thought by the way it was hit, it
wasn't going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone (11-6) won for the first time since his perfect game, four
starts ago. Through six innings, he had allowed two walks and an
infield single, striking out nine. Consecutive singles knocked him
out in the seventh, but he threw 79 wicked strikes among his 118
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got late-breaking stuff,'' said first baseman Raul
Ibanez, who struck out twice in his first game against Cone, whose
assortment of pitches and deliveries can be baffling. ``He throws
sliders inside, sliders away, he cuts the ball in, sinks it, he's
got a split. He's pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Cone, Halama was lifted in the seventh with a run in, a man
on and two outs. Paul Abbott _ who will start on Wednesday as Jeff
Fassero returns to relief _ walked two to load the bases, then
walked Tino Martinez to force in a run. That was when Piniella
started barking at home plate umpire Ted Barrett from the dugout.
He was gone by the time Brosius singled to give New York a 7-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them the Yankees were intimidating them,'' said
Piniella, who was ejected for the second time this season.
``(Barrett) didn't appreciate that very much. ... Cone was getting
those pitches, and our guy was not treated to the same luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   But Piniella and Abbott acknowledged that the pitcher's wildness
did not help him on the pitch to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard for him to give it to me when I hadn't thrown that
many strikes,'' Abbott said. ``That was a pretty good pitch, but
the stage was set by me being wild in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Todd Williams and Steve Sinclair finished up, with
both newcomers allowing one run in one inning of work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
