<SLUG> BC-GLF-AREAWEB.COM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUNN SECOND TO NONE 
</HEADLINE>
 CHALLENGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ Sunday morning, she went out looking for birdies
and collected three within the first five holes. Mardi Lunn seemed
on her way to firing the round of 66 she said she needed to have a
chance at winning the areaWEB.com Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Australian's tee shot on No. 6 caromed off a tree, and
it appeared Lunn's dramatic run toward a first LPGA Tour victory
had taken a turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the white sphere landed in a playable spot just to the
right of the woods. Two shots later, it rested in the bottom of the
cup for par. They might as well have made the $120,000 first-place
check out to Lunn right there. No doubt it was her day.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old came to within one stroke of her goal with a
round of 67, then took her place in the winner's circle with a
total of 13-under-par 275.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe this was meant to be my day, because that was
really the worst shot I hit all day,'' said Lunn about the tee shot
on No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Following a third-round 71 Saturday that consisted of one birdie
and 17 pars, she finished Sunday with six birdies and one bogey en
route to her first Tour win since turning professional in 1994. It
was her fourth pro victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing. Obviously, it's a big relief,'' said Lunn. ``I
think not winning can start to grind on you after awhile. You just
have to keep hitting the greens and rolling in putts and hope that
it will happen one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunn's performance was one stroke better than that of her idol,
fellow Australian Jan Stephenson (276), who also shot a final-round
67.
</P>
<P>
   Her birdie putt on 18 would have forced a playoff if Lunn, who
played in her trio, had bogeyed the hole.
</P>
<P>
   But Lunn sealed the title with a 5-foot putt for par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the yardage and what shot I needed to hit,'' said Lunn,
who added that she took deep breaths on 17 and 18 to calm her
nerves. ``You just have to believe in yourself. I've hit that shot
a million times. I knew I could do it once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I birdied the second and the third, I was hitting good shots
to the putt, and I felt I was going to make putts today,'' Lunn
added. ``(Saturday) I was hitting good putts and they just kept
lipping out. That was the key (Sunday): making a few putts early.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian Rachel Hetherington also fired a 67, taking third
place and giving the women from Down Under the top three finishes.
Afterward, Lunn and Stephenson called it quite a triumph,
considering the fact that Australian Karrie Webb, the hottest
player on the Tour, did not participate.
</P>
<P>
   Lunn took the lead after a 2-foot birdie putt on the ninth hole,
which put her at 11 under. Hetherington, who played in a trio ahead
of her, birdied 10 to tie Lunn at 11 under.
</P>
<P>
   But Lunn then birdied 10 with another 2-foot putt to go 12
under, and she maintained her lead the remainder of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Mardi get off to a good start, and that's what you have
to do,'' said Lorie Kane, who bogeyed two of her first three holes
to fail in her attempt to win her first LPGA event. ``Mardi's been
knocking on the door the last couple of weeks. She's a very patient
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lunn admitted to being nervous over the later holes. Adding
to pressures was the fact that her fiercest competition played
right beside her.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson's late charge delighted the crowd, and the
47-year-old figured that one error by the leader and she could put
herself in position to win her first Tour event since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``On 18, I really thought it was almost too late, but you never
know _ stranger things have happened,'' said Stephenson. ``I've
lost tournaments because you get so nervous coming down the
stretch. I knew if she was above the pin, something could happen.
But from 5 feet, she just had to lag it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunn's round was two shots off her career best (she fired a 66
in the first round).
</P>
<P>
   Her efforts spoiled the hopes of other notables.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Daniel (279), who entered the day tied with Lunn for third,
bogeyed the second and seventh holes to fall back. When she birdied
13, it appeared she would make a late charge, but bogeys on 16 and
17 took care of that.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Steinhauer (280) entered the final round with the lead,
marking the seventh time in her career she had done so. She had won
three of those previous events but all but ruined her chances for a
fourth when she double bogeyed the second hole, then bogeyed seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is a funny game. Today, my mind wasn't clear,'' said
Steinhauer. ``There were a lot of things going on in my mind, and
that's just golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Dottie Pepper (278) took fourth place after a strong back nine
that made up for bogeys on the first two holes. A birdie on 13
brought her to within three shots of the lead, but she shot par the
rest of the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
