<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SEND JEFF FASSERO BACK IN THE BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The last time Jeff Fassero was sent to the bullpen, it
was meant to be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   But that was two months ago, and the main goal was to give
Fassero a mental and physical break. Now, the veteran left-hander
is returning to the bullpen, and this move could be permanent.
Reliever Paul Abbott, who nearly replaced Fassero two weeks ago,
will join the rotation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the move was only temporary, manager Lou Piniella
gave no indication that Fassero could pitch his way back into the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, we've got three rookies in the rotation, and we've
got (Jamie) Moyer and we want to give Abbott a chance to pitch,''
Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero said he was not told about how he will be used in relief
or how long this stay might last. On Saturday, he asked pitching
coach Stan Williams about his throw day between starts, which would
have been yesterday. When Williams told Fassero he was going to the
bullpen, Williams said, the pitcher said little.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their decision,'' Fassero said yesterday. ``I'll live
with it. Just go down there and throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero has held left-handers to a .246 average, compared to
.338 off right-handers, but said he hoped he would not be used as a
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be happy if I'm just facing lefties,'' he said. ``If
that's all I'm going to do, I won't be happy, period.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Fassero's role is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitched well against left-handers, and that affected the
decision,'' Piniella said. ``It gives us two left-handers in the
bullpen, and we'll see how it works out. ... I think it'll help
Jeff out.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be nothing more Fassero can do _ as a starter _ to
salvage the season. He was 3-7 with a 7.23 earned run average in 15
starts before moving to the bullpen in June. He had been allowing
home runs at a lower rate until surrendering four on Friday, but in
nine starts since rejoining the staff, he is 1-6 with a 6.99 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the 36-year-old veteran is 4-13 with a 7.11 ERA and
leads the majors with 34 home runs allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point our goal was just to get him back to .500, when
he was 4-8,'' Williams said. ``But he's 4-13, so it hasn't been
working there. We'll try it in shorter stints. I think he's better
in shorter stints right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also to the M's benefit to get an extended look at Abbott.
The club controls Abbott's rights after this season, but Fassero is
a free agent. Abbott was impressive over four starts last
September, and had a five-inning no-decision in his one start in
'99.
</P>
<P>
   APPEALS MOVED UP: Friday's brawl with the New York Yankees came
before the Mariners had resolved the punishments from their
previous fight, with the Los Angeles Dodgers on July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Jose Paniagua, who was suspended for five games, and
right fielder Jay Buhner (four) originally had appeal hearings
scheduled for the last weekend in August, when the M's play in New
York. The hearings have since been rescheduled for a week from
today in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with the prospect of Frankie (Rodriguez) being suspended,
too, we need to get it resolved,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit Chuck Knoblauch with a pitch Friday, and the fight
followed. AL spokeswoman Phyllis Mehrige said the AL has requested
a tape of the incident and will review it today or tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   CROWDED HOUSE: The Mariners set a new club record for attendance
in a four-game series with 180,849 fans coming out to see the
Yankees. As of yesterday morning, there were 6,000 tickets
available for tonight's game against the Chicago White Sox, and
8,500 left for tomorrow's. Fifteen of the 18 games at Safeco Field
have been sellouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
