<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST WEEKEND SPOTLIGHTS MARINERS' PITCHING MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It wasn't a totally lost weekend for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   During the brawl Friday night, Don Zimmer fell down, causing the
68-year-old Yankees coach to limp away on a bum knee that is
scheduled to be surgically replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners sure taught him a lesson: If you're an old,
creaking man, stay away from our bad selves.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Yankees, however, failed to detect a scratch
from their four days in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's lightning was a bigger threat.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 9-3 win completed the four-game sweep by the world
champs, although four games is a pitiful measure of the gap between
the Yankees and Mariners. But since baseball doesn't use fathoms,
miles or light years, a 28-15 combined score is a decent gauge.
</P>
<P>
   Another one is two World Series titles the Yankees have won
since they lost to the Mariners in 1995. Since that postseason, the
Mariners have won a single playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   While it isn't exactly fair to compare the Mariners with the
club in the world's biggest media market _ although in a wallet
contest between George Steinbrenner and Chris Larson, I'll take the
Mariner part-owner and spot the Yankee boss a billion _ it is fair
to compare the Mariners to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And they match up _ sad to say for Mariners fans, 180,000 of
whom showed up at the Guilty Pleasure to create a club record for a
four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The season after the Yankees-Mariners epic postseason saga, the
Mariners shuffled through a club-record 25 pitchers mostly in an
effort to make up for the injury absences of starters Randy Johnson
and Chris Bosio.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, rookie reliever Todd Williams' first appearance Sunday
boosted the total to 26 pitchers, breaking the '96 club record for
aimless futility with seven weeks left, and well ahead of the
annual September callups. At this rate, the Mariners may have need
to reach back into the '96 bucket of pitchers, which you may recall
was Rusty (Meacham), full of Blas (Minor) and frequently went Klink
(Joe).
</P>
<P>
   In apparent celebration of the dubious milestone, manager Lou
Piniella had himself tossed from the game in the seventh inning for
arguing balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella maintained afterward that plate umpire Ted Barrett was
intimidated into a more generous strike zone for Yankees pitchers,
especially David Cone. But Piniella also allowed that since his
reliever, Paul Abbott, walked three straight batters and was wilder
than a night with Dennis Rodman in Vegas, maybe he was a tad
off-base in expecting an umpire to recognize a strike after going
so long without seeing one.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't Sunday's most ill-timed flip-flop. Before the game,
it was announced that Abbott had replaced flailing Jeff Fassero
(4-13) in starting rotation. So Abbott came in as a reliever, and
apparently found the ball so heavy that he left two pitches several
feet shy of the plate. He faced five batters and managed one out
besides the three walks and a leadoff double.
</P>
<P>
   And Abbott's collapse after the removal of John Halama (9-3),
who saw his remarkable nine-game winning streak ended with five
runs in 62/3 innings in the first start against his hometown club.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that the Mariners _ with 14 rookies used,
including eight making their major league debuts and six still on
the roster _ have for a pitching staff a roaring, boiling mess.
</P>
<P>
   Still.
</P>
<P>
   But you knew that. In fact, you've known that for years.
</P>
<P>
   A big difference between now and '96, when the decay set in, is
that the Mariners still had some clutch hitters to compensate for
pitching trouble. But now, at least over the last 19 games, the
Mariners are hitting less than .180 with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nothing can be done about that problem, since the club
has already ridded itself of offensive depth with trades and no
worthy position players are ready in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Another big difference between now and '96 was results. Bad as
things were, the Mariners still won 85 games and finished with a
team ERA of 5.21, about half a run better than the current cast of
dozens.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees series results established what was apparent at the
nonwaiver trading deadline: It's audition time for 2000. Bring your
sheet music to the stage door, kids, and line up quietly. Piniella
admitted as much Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to look at everyone in the system to know exactly
what we have,'' he said. ``There will be no guesswork involved this
winter.''
</P>
<P>
   This winter? What happened to this summer? (Please, no weather
jokes).
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way,'' he said. ``If someone deserves to come up,
he'll get the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   So there's a solid chance that the Mariners will shatter the '96
Angels' major league record of 29 pitchers used. And if Fightin'
Frankie Rodriguez hangs on to his boxing license long enough to
start a third brawl (remember, the relief pitcher started the July
11 dust-up at Dodger Stadium too), the Mariners will have so few
arms left that Meacham, Minor and Klink will be recalled in the
fashion of Cy Young, Lefty Grove and Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   But remember, Zimmer wants no part of these Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
