<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' JOHNSON TO HAVE SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ The sun has not yet risen on a new NFL
season, but an ominous eclipse swept across the Patriots Sunday
when it was confirmed that Ted Johnson, the club's brightest star
on defense, likely will be lost for up to four months with a torn
left biceps tendon.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, eerily similar to the torn right biceps tendon that
ended Johnson's 1998 season on Dec. 6, was confirmed by an MRI exam
Sunday morning, and the 27-year-old linebacker is expected to
undergo surgery Monday or Wednesday at Massachusetts General
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose a guy of great impact on our club, and it's a
tragedy,'' said coach Pete Carroll, who saw his prized linebacker
tear the biceps tendon during the club's intrasquad scrimmage _
Patriot Preview '99 _ Saturday afternoon in Foxborough. ``Ted's put
so much into it, he's been such a diligent worker for so long, and
it's a crusher to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, following the MRI exam in Wellesley, met Sunday &UR;  &LR; night
with Dr. Bert Zarins, the MGH orthopedist who long has been the
club's physician. Neither Johnson nor Zarins was available for
comment. Carroll said he expects Johnson to miss 3-4 months. ``If
it's the long end of it,'' he said, ``that's right around playoff
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll will divulge the details of Zarins's meeting
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night with Johnson Monday in his daily late-morning news
conference here at Bryant College, but the coach made it clear
Sunday that his star linebacker will go under the knife, and the
New England defense will undergo some immediate suturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Marty Moore will hold these guys together until we
can get Andy (Katzenmoyer) ready to play that position,'' said
Carroll, looking for Moore, about to enter his sixth season, to
tutor Katzenmoyer, the rookie first-round draft pick out of Ohio
State. ``That's where we'll turn our sights until we know more.
Fortunately, we've got a guy of (Katzenmoyer's) stature who can
take over the spot. It's the spot that Andy played at college, so
that's where we'll turn our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Injured early in the second quarter Saturday, his arm wrenched
when he tried to slow down rookie running back Kevin Faulk, Johnson
said to a reporter, ``What is it? I'm not sure yet.'' He added,
``It feels just like last year.'' His self-diagnosis was confirmed
when the MRI showed the tear, believed to be where the muscle
attaches to a tendon at the crook of the arm. Johnson has a scar
some 4 inches long near the crook of his right arm, where Zarins
and Dr. Jesse Jupiter repaired the tear last Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson may be the best-conditioned athlete on the
team, the wear and tear of the position has extracted a heavy toll
on his chiseled body. He is about to undergo his fourth surgery in
two years. Last January, just over a month after the biceps
surgery, he underwent his second shoulder operation.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Johnson signed a new contract worth $25.4 million
over five years. Nearly one third of the deal was guaranteed in the
way of a signing bonus _ $3 million last year, $5 million this year
_ and the club could see the 2000 season begin with Johnson having
played only the 13 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Torn biceps tendons are rare, even in the punishing, often
brutal game of football, and Carroll is at a loss as to how the
same injury could happen twice to the same player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Ted and I tried to figure out, talking in the
locker room, you know, `Why's this happening?' '' said Carroll, who
didn't discount the possibility that the Patriots will try to trade
for help at the position. ``He works out more than anybody we have.
He's the No. 1 workout guy in the program, so we're a little bit
baffled by why this would happen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll also discounted the possibility that perhaps the
injuries were a product of Johnson overtraining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's the case,'' said Carroll, before leading
his charges through a 90-minute afternoon workout. ``I just don't
think that's the case. I don't think he's overpumped. He weighs
about the same weight he did in college. You know, his strength is
tremendous. He's well proportioned, all those types of things, so .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson on the sidelines last year after surgery, and with
quarterback Drew Bledsoe working with a fractured right index
finger, the Patriots lost three of their last four games, including
a playoff loss to Jacksonville. To replace Johnson at the center of
the defense is a daunting assignment. Agile and mean, he forges the
defense's personality when he's on the field. In his 57
regular-season games over four seasons, he had 453 tackles,
approximately 70 percent (302) of those unassisted. In five
postseason games, his numbers were just as steady: 44 tackles, 33
unassisted.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's scrimmage, Faulk, the 5-foot-8-inch running back
from LSU, didn't run directly down Johnson's path. If he had,
Johnson wouldn't have needed, or been tempted, to flail out with
his arm, looking only to slow the rookie down. But Johnson got a
piece of Faulk and immediately felt the familiar pain searing in
and around his muscular arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the ball carrier was going by him, and he reached out
just like he did with (Jerome Bettis) last year, very much the same
situation,'' said Carroll. ``He wasn't trying to tackle the guy, he
was just reaching out to make a play on him. It's different than
the Pittsburgh game in that sense, but the same result.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to figure out more, get more information on it,
maybe dig it to find out why, and try to point the finger at
whatever it could be as to why this would happen _ not necessarily
in a negative sense _ but right now we don't know any more that
what we're telling you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
