<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE WAS NO DOUBT _ LUN WAS SMOKING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ Mardi Lunn won her first LPGA tournament Sunday.
If you'd like to celebrate with her, hold all victory cigars and
congratulations. Instead, it might be a good idea to buy her a pack
of cigarettes. Make it two if you can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably smoked about 50 zillion more today than usual,''
Lunn said. And that's nothing compared to her mother, Val, who held
a lit cigarette at Pleasant Valley Country Club's 18th hole. Val
was there to praise her daughter and light up. ``She probably had
about 100 zillion,'' Lunn said of the woman she referred to as
``Mum.''
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't guessed by now, Lunn does not say things you
would expect from a pro athlete. Many of them go to schools and
speak of the dangers of nicotine. But Lunn says she has the soul of
a rebel. She grew up viewing the world from a different angle _
she's from Australia _ and it has definitely carried over to her
golf game.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the 31-year-old Lunn won an event called the areaWEB.com
Challenge. She won even though she trailed Sherri Steinhauer by
three strokes at the start of the day and told herself that she
would have to shoot close to her career best (65) to win. She shot
a 67. She won even though one of her shots on No. 6 banged off a
tree and then, eerily, righted itself. She won even though on No.
17 one of her idols and playing partners, Jan Stephenson, noticed
that she was breathing heavily and uncomfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Was she losing her cool or searching for a pack of Kools?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty nervous,'' Lunn said. ``I don't care if you're
Tiger Woods or Karrie Webb, you're going to be nervous in that
situation. I don't think you're human if you're not a bit nervous
at least. I was just trying to take some deep breaths and calm
myself down.''
</P>
<P>
   She knew that if her tension began to control her, she could
always find her mother in the gallery and bum a cigarette. She says
she never has a problem finding Mum, even in large crowds. She has
been known to break her own concentration by asking her mother if
she needs to take a sip or drag of something. I wouldn't be
surprised if she asked the course marshals to lower those
``Quiet!'' signs and instead encourage the fans to make some noise.
Those who walked this tree-lined course with her Sunday may not
have known that she has suspended her drives to attend to her
mother, but anyone watching could see that there was something
different about her game.
</P>
<P>
   One of the truly bizarre things to do on the final round of a
tournament is to wait for leaders to lose their leads. You can
actually tell that some people are disappointed when it doesn't
happen. It's as if everyone wants to see the Greg Norman redux, the
horrible time in 1996 when the golfer blew a six-stroke lead over
Nick Faldo on the final day of the Masters. Norman, also an
Australian, shot a 78 in the final round and Faldo won the tourney
by five strokes. Sunday, Lunn took the lead on No. 9 and never lost
it.
</P>
<P>
   That's even more impressive when you consider that Stephenson,
yet another Aussie, was playing with her. Lunn is 16 years younger
than Stephenson. She played basketball and cricket as a child, but
she idolized two golfers, Norman and Stephenson. So there was Lunn
making difficult shots in front of her idol. But her idol wanted to
win the tournament, too. That would be like telling a singer who
grew up admiring Aretha Franklin to outsing the Queen. Face to
face. Lunn did that, with much support from Stephenson, who
finished second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country really doesn't support women's sports very much,''
said Stephenson, who was one shot from making her own history
Sunday. ``So it's nice to see so many of us (Lunn, Webb, Rachel
Hetherington) doing well. I hate to admit that I'm old enough to be
their mother. That's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   If Stephenson had defeated Lunn Sunday, she says she would have
walked away from the game. Eight years ago outside Miami Arena,
Stephenson suffered hand and shoulder injuries when she was mugged.
She said her attacker tried to snatch a ring from her left hand,
which still throbs. And she hurt her right shoulder when she was
thrown to the ground during the same assault. Now 47, she simply
wants a peaceful and winning close to a long career.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson will eventually get her final, walkaway win. But
Sunday, she embraced Lunn on the 18th green when the tournament was
officially over. She watched as the cool Lunn signed autographs for
young fans. She told herself that her score on Friday, 70, probably
cost her the tournament. She listened as Lunn thanked her and Jane
Crafter for a great Sunday of golfing.
</P>
<P>
   (Crafter also has an unusual approach to golfing. Sunday, she
told two men to freeze because they were walking as she was
preparing to putt. They stopped, she putted, and then she thanked
them for their cooperation.)
</P>
<P>
   Before the 31-year-old woman with the rebellious soul left for
London, she was asked if winning this tournament would change
anything about her. ``Only my bank account,'' she said with a grin.
She earned $120,000 for her win. That means she won't have to worry
about cigarette money for a while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
