<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGGS A BIG HIT _ OUTSIDE BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ It was true then, it's true now: Wade
Boggs always has been more appreciated outside of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When he was hitting .350 for the Red Sox every year, Boggs had
respect around baseball that eluded him in the Hub. This was
evident again this weekend when he cracked the 3,000-hit barrier.
</P>
<P>
   I had to put cynicism on the shelf for Wade's wonderful
celebration at Tropicana Field. Being from Boston, I felt like an
uninvited guest whom everyone was too polite to banish. There was
no one else around to remind him of the tumultuous 11 seasons he
spent in the Hub. It made me want to hide in the corner when Wade
held press conferences to talk about making baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night was electric at Tropicana Field. Everything went
Wade's way. Wade's dad, Win, and his wife, Debbie, sat in Section
106. His son, Brett _ named after George Brett _ sat on a stool
next to the on-deck circle, wearing a Devil Rays uniform. Daughter
Meagann was on the way back from a wedding in West Palm Beach,
scanning past Spanish-language stations on her car's AM radio,
trying to hear the Devil Rays broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Wade grounded to second in his first at-bat against Charles
Nagy, leaving him stalled at 2,997. It seemed like the Wade Watch
might stretch into a new week. But then he hit prototype Boggsian
singles to right in his second and third at-bats and walked to the
plate at 9:05 with a chance to become the 22d player in big-league
history with 3,000 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine thousand fans stood and cheered in anticipation. I
couldn't help but think about all the bad stuff that happened on
the way to this moment . . .
</P>
<P>
   Boggs was buried in the Red Sox minor league system for six long
summers. Every major league team passed on a chance to acquire him
for $25,000 when the Sox left him unprotected after he hit .306 in
1980. The Red Sox traded for Carney Lansford the year after Wade
led the International League with a .335 average. Only when
Lansford got hurt in a home-plate crash (June 25, 1982) did Boggs
get a chance (``If Carney doesn't get hurt, none of this happens,''
Boggs said Saturday night).
</P>
<P>
   He finished his rookie season with a .349 average, then began a
string of seven consecutive 200-hit seasons (the only time that's
been done this century). But according to Wade, ``Nobody wrote
anything'' except stuff that was bad.
</P>
<P>
   There was bad stuff. He was ripped by (among others) teammates
Bill Buckner and Roger Clemens (remember Rog saying, ``I'm out
there busting my butt while he's in the clubhouse sitting on his
average''?). Eddie Andelman killed him on sports talk radio, and
Boggs came into the studio to fight back, saying, ``Eddie, I'd love
to hit your weight someday.'' The Sox kept taking him to
arbitration. Boggs was in the visitors' clubhouse in Yankee Stadium
in June 1986 when he got the call telling him his mother had been
killed when a prisoner on work release crashed into her car in
Florida. Boggs wept in the dugout when the Sox lost the '86 Series
at Shea. Then came a seedy affair and Delta Force and depositions.
</P>
<P>
   He was wounded when the Sox gave him a take-it-or-leave-it offer
in the spring of 1992 and left Boston in a huff at the end of that
season. We thought he'd be a tabloid topic when he left the Hub for
the Apple, but that never happened. Boggs got some revenge on the
Red Sox when he won a World Series, then elected to play out his
golden days in the pressure-free atmosphere of Tampa, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was heartwarming to see Debbie Boggs crying and
applauding her husband when he stepped to the plate to face
Cleveland lefty Chris Haney. Who deserved this moment more than
Debbie Boggs? A nice girl from a poor Tampa family, she married
Wade in December 1976 after his first year of pro ball. She stuck
with him through Winston-Salem, Bristol, Pawtucket, Boston, and
Margo. Hers was the most public of pains, but she fought for what
she believed in and prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Wade crushed Haney's 2-2 curveball, sending it four rows past
the right-field fence and into the hands of a 32-year-old college
sports PR guy who works at Meagann's school. En route to second
base, Boggs blew a kiss skyward, in honor of his mother, and did it
again before he knelt and kissed home plate. Wade hugged Brett, and
by then Debbie and Win were being led onto the field. Boggs
embraced his dad, the man who made him read Ted Williams's ``The
Science of Hitting'' when Wade was in high school. Then he embraced
Debbie.
</P>
<P>
   It was Capra-esque, right down to the champagne toast/postgame
press conference, when a breathless, gown-clad Meagann Boggs
appeared in the back of the room and ran up the aisle while her dad
announed, ``Ah, here's my lovely daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing the feeling of hitting the home run for No. 3,000,
Boggs said, ``You couldn't imagine when you are running around the
bases and it's like you're not even touching the ground. Then, when
I got to the plate, it was like a Little League home run because
all the guys were at home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggs has a 12-year-old son. He knows the Little League
etiquette that holds that the entire team must greet a homer hero
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Boggs played his Little League ball in Tampa, just one long
bridge and a few miles from where he earned immortality Saturday
night. It was a beautiful moment for a man who worked harder than
anybody to make himself a great major league hitter.
</P>
<P>
   History will treat him far better than Boston ever did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
