<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAN AM GAMES PUT ON GOLD-MEDAL SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
 AM GAMES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba _ The local organizers had said they couldn't
stage more than 32 sports. There wasn't room or money enough in
this prairie province to put up 5,000 bowlers, judokas,
triathletes, squash players, roller skaters, and water skiers. Yet
when the 13th Pan American Games ended here Sunday night with a
Guess Who reunion concert at Winnipeg Stadium, the hosts had
managed one for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gold-medal performance,'' said US Olympic Committee
executive director Dick Schultz, whose star-spangled side topped
the medal table for the 12th straight time at this hemispheric
block party. And so it was.
</P>
<P>
   These Games were superbly organized. They broke even at the cash
till. Except for the usual political turmoil around the Cuban
delegation, they came off with minimal fuss. And, almost certainly,
they were the last of their size.
</P>
<P>
   Don MacKenzie, the man who brought the Pan Ams here for the
second time, has already recommended that the program be chopped
from a gargantuan 41 events to as few as 28. And Santo Domingo, the
Dominican capital, which will hold the 2003 event, agrees. ``We do
recognize that the Pan American Sports Organization has the last
word, but we have to do some kind of reduction,'' says organizing
committee president Jose Joaquin Puello. ``We have to think about
the most popular sports in the Americas, and which of the others
will be left out of the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   On the endangered list are the non-Olympic sports: bowling,
karate, racquetball, roller skating, men's softball, squash, and
water skiing. Unless their federations agree to pay the freight,
they'll probably be axed. The fact is, the Pan Ams have grown so
large (from 29 countries and 2,400 athletes when they were held
here in 1967 to 42 and 5,000 now) that only a handful of countries
in the Americas can handle them. And the bigger they've grown, the
more the Games have tilted the medal count in favor of the US, the
only nation that can afford to bring a full squad in every sport.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the number of medal events slashed from 435 to 327
since last time, the Americans still hauled off 295 _ and that was
using their B+ team, since the top runners, swimmers, boxers, and
rowers were missing. Nobody else could bring their second string
and still win 37 swimming medals.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians, who spent $90 million on the Games and pumped
loads of development cash into their teams to boost their medal
count, brought their varsity (except for a handful of no-show track
stars such as Donovan Bailey). They grabbed a record 196 medals in
38 sports, vaulting ahead of the Cubans for the first time since
1967. ``We achieved beyond our realistic expectations,'' said Alex
Carre, Canada's chef de mission. ``These Games provided us with a
magic moment we will remember for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Cubans complained bitterly from the start about
everything from security to taunting tabloid coverage to a
``false'' positive doping result on high jumper Javier Sotomayor,
they still won 158 medals in 26 sports and claimed more golds than
the Canadians. For a poor island nation that has been losing
athletes to defection for a decade (seven delegation members
decamped here), that is extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Pan Ams would likely expire if Uncle Sam didn't keep
showing up in force, they survive because nearly every hemispheric
mouse gets a chance to roar at least once. Eighteen countries heard
their anthem played here, including the Netherlands Antilles, which
won a gold in karate. And 27 of the 42 countries put at least one
athlete on the podium. Even the Cayman Islands got something for
the trophy case.
</P>
<P>
   These Games may have grown unwieldy and expensive, but there's
always an eager host or two waiting to roll out a red carpet for
5,000 of their neighbors. ``It is a great challenge for us,''
admits Puello, who insists that Santo Domingo will be ready several
years early. ``Maybe Hurricane No. 48 will destroy us, but we will
do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
