A0263 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     08-09 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDOWELL INEFFECTIVE, WILL BE DROPPED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Jack McDowell made his last start as an Angel
on Sunday night in the Boston Red Sox's 9-3 win, and quite possibly
McDowell's career is over for good.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels want to take a look at some of their young pitchers
now playing in the minors, and McDowell's spot will open up today.
McDowell, the Cy Young Award winner in 1993, is expected to be
released or traded, if there are any takers. He hopes to catch on
with a pennant contender for the stretch run but admits interest
won't be high, considering the way he's pitched lately.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Notre Dame High graduate lasted only four innings,
giving up five runs and eight hits before 31,664 at Edison Field.
Red Sox starter Pedro Martinez lasted only five innings but yielded
just two runs (one earned) and three hits to earn the victory and
improve to 16-3. Martinez and Houston's Mike Hampton lead the
majors with 16 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary led the Boston offense with three hits, including
his team-leading 22nd homer. Brian Daubach also homered (No. 16)
and Jason Varitek added a two-run double as the Red Sox took three
of four in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Angels to 46-64, the first time this season
they've been 18 games under .500. They're on a pace to lose 94
games, something they have done only three times in 38 seasons
before this year.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't lost as many as 94 since 1980, when they went
65-95. They went 68-94 in 1974 and 67-95 in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell (0-4), who had shoulder surgery Feb. 2, said his arm
and shoulder are fine. He knows his past two starts were bad but
points to his first two, when he allowed only three runs in 12
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If no one's going to give me the ball, there's not a whole lot
I can do,'' he said. ``I know in my heart if I'm allowed to go out
there, I'm better than a ton of guys. But the ball's not in my
court right now. I have to wait and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If there are no takers for McDowell, he indicated he'll probably
retire. Although he said he was retiring after last season, he said
he means it this time, even though he's only 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at my age and you would think the second half of my
career is ahead of me,'' he said. ``But I don't envision sitting
around the next six or seven months and then get to spring training
and try to make somebody's team. And even then, still not know if
I'm going to hold up for the season. . . . I may never be a (No.) 1
or 2 gy again, but I know I can still get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be with the Angels. Out of the race and looking
ahead to next season, they need to see a number of young arms.
Either Scott Schoeneweis or Jarrod Washburn is expected to take
McDowell's spot initially. Ramon Ortiz might get his chance later
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange,'' McDowell said. ``I'm only four starts out of
surgery. There's a lot in this game that's good, but you can get
kicked in the face. It's a question of how many times you're
willing to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have seen him before his arm injuries,'' Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``When he was throwing in the 90s, with
his competitiveness, he must've been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   For Martinez, who like McDowell has one Cy Young Award to his
name, Sunday's victory was the 100th of his career. It was his
second start since missing 2{ weeks with a sore shoulder, but it
was far from a memorable performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My performance today was not as good as I expected, but I'll
take it,'' said Martinez, whose ERA fell to 2.46. ``I was behind in
the count all the time. I had problems with my control. That's not
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
