<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0265 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     08-09 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR PERSONNEL MOVES LEFT PATRIOTS VULNERABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Pete Carroll was born and raised in northern
California, spending most of his developmental years in Marin
County, just across the Golden Gate Bridge from San Francisco. It
is a place where a lot of people believe in karma, although,
frankly, few football players think much about it.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Grier was born and raised on the streets of Detroit, a
tough blue-collar town where they know a lot about cars but not
much about karma. Out there they believe in General Motors, not
general mysticism.
</P>
<P>
   Karma, as defined by the third edition of the American Heritage
Dictionary, is a Hindu and Buddhist idea as simple as this: ``The
total effect of one's actions during the successive phases of one's
existence, regarded as determining one's destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carroll and Grier ask themselves today why so many things
seen to be befalling them that they have no control over but are
destroying their best efforts to erase the memory of Bill Parcells,
they should think about that word. When rookie running back Robert
Edwards's career ended on a Hawaii beach in a flag football game in
February and then middle linebacker Ted Johnson went down Saturday,
probably for the year, with a torn biceps tendon that duplicated an
injury of a year ago and left the Patriots thunderstruck at the
consequences, karma came to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll called the odd injuries in what were basically
non-contact situations terrible breaks, and that they were. But
just maybe there's more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   Why are these things happening? Carroll, Grier, and owner Bob
Kraft all have to be asking themselves that question today. The
answer is difficult to ascertain, especially in the case of kids
such as Edwards and Johnson, who were among the team's
hardest-working players, both during the season and in the
offseason, but karma may be as good a place to start as any.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to put it, if you hail from the North End instead of
northern California, is this: What goes around comes around.
</P>
<P>
   During the brief tenure of Carroll and Grier, they have run off
much of the soul of the team Parcells left behind. New brooms sweep
clean, and bosses like their own employees, not someone else's, for
some odd reason. Often it's for all the wrong ones.
</P>
<P>
   But what the Patriots' bosses have done time after time is more
than just move good people out, which is their right. They've tried
to send them off under a cloud, which is not right. It is an
unconscionable thing that has happened too many times to be an
accident. Maybe, just maybe, what's gone around is now coming
around like a freight train.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Curtis Martin, after three brilliant seasons in New
England, wanted to get paid for his work? Suddenly you heard how he
wasn't smart enough to have taken a good deal when New England put
one the table, even though it would have quickly left him underpaid
and unhappy again. Remember how after he left to join Parcells and
the Jets, we suddenly heard all these ``sources'' whispering he was
probably used up after too many injuries, and rookie running backs
gain most of the yardage in the NFL anyway, and oh, by the way, he
produced too many negative yards, as if it was his fault the team
didn't run as effectively as it would have liked?
</P>
<P>
   Remember what happened to Sam Gash a year ago, when the Patriots
refused to re-sign him and then whispered about him, too? They
claimed he was a greedy, injury-prone, malcontent clubhouse lawyer,
when the fact was all he ever wanted to do was win. Perhaps Gash's
view of his worth in dollars and cents was inflated, but whose in
sports these days is not? The fact is the Patriots offered him
nothing, lied about the circumstances of his leaving, and then
talked behind his back to cover themselves. So Gash went off to
Buffalo and became a Pro Bowl blocking back, while his replacement,
Tony Carter, struggled through an injury-plagued season.
</P>
<P>
   They whacked Corwin Brown and traded Jimmy Hitchcock despite
having no one to replace either. Then they tried to tell you the
special teams were fine without Brown and Chris Canty, or Steve
Israel would easily fill Hitchcock's spot, because, as one
management insider said at the time, ``We couldn't do any worse.''
Oh really?
</P>
<P>
   Worse than merely making those moves, Carroll, Grier, and the
rest whispered that Brown couldn't be put on the field and
Hitchcock was a critically limited player. The two of them were so
limited that both started in their divisional championship games
last year (Brown, admittedly, because of injuries to other Jets),
while New England's rebuilt team sat at home for the second
straight January. Hitchcock, in fact, played every snap on a team
that went 15-1, and he intercepted seven passes, returning three
for touchdowns, so just how limited was he? Meanwhile, back at the
ranch, the players Carroll and Grier had touted as their
replacements struggled, and so did the team.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two days before training camp opened this year, the
Patriots here reached a new low when they fired Willie Clay at a
time when they knew he could not get another job because nearly
every team was capped out, money-wise. It was a low point even by
the Patriots' standards, the kind of thing you don't do to people
who have worked and bled and sweated for you for three seasons,
even if you hate their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots claimed they didn't want to do it, but they had cap
problems themselves and somebody had to go. Yet they conveniently
failed to mention they had twice redone the contract of Vincent
Brisby, who has been as productive as a Russian wheat field for
years but is a quiet company man. If they had not done this, they
could have let him go and solved the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they fired Clay, who had always been at odds with
Carroll over many things, including what Clay saw as his coach's
political, two-faced approach to life. Then they began the same
sort of whispering campaign against him. Suddenly a guy who hadn't
missed a start, a practice, or an offseason workout in five years
was a clubhouse lawyer who had grown too slow to play his position
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was Clay who was limited. Now it was Clay who didn't have
it anymore. Now it was Clay who wasn't as smart as they had always
said he was. Now it was Clay who wasn't as responsible for the
improvement of Ty Law and Lawyer Milloy as we'd been led to
believe. Now it was Clay who wouldn't tackle and couldn't cover _
and why'd we keep him around, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Just the way the Patriots' management had whispered falsehoods
about good soldiers such as Gash, Brown, Hitchcock, and even
Martin, it started again with Clay. Only management knows why it
has to do business this way, but less than 10 days later, Ted
Johnson was gone, perhaps for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Are these things related? Maybe not if you're from Detroit.
Maybe not if you've spent your life concerned with football and not
the more ethereal sides of northern California life.
</P>
<P>
   But if you believe in karma, or just in the fact that what goes
around usually comes around, you have to wonder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
