<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANGELS-BOS     08-09 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ, RED SOX DISPATCH ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANGELS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Hall of Famer Steve Carlton, winner of 329
games, was 27 when he won his 100th game. Hall of Famers Don Sutton
(324 wins) and Tom Seaver (311) were the same age when they reached
100, as were Roger Clemens, the five-time Cy Young Award winner,
and Greg Maddux, the four-time Cy Young winner.
</P>
<P>
   So, it was only natural that someone would ask Pedro Martinez, 2
1/2 months shy of his 28th birthday, whether he could foresee
another couple hundred wins after he claimed career victory No. 100
Sunday night by surviving five cranky innings in the Red Sox' 9-3
win over the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   It was all Martinez could do to keep from laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred? That's so hard to get, I'm not even thinking
about it,'' said the Sox ace (16-3). ``Look what they had to do,
play 20-something years. I'm not going to play 20-something years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I hope I do, but I don't think I will. I need time to
spend with my family, and the lady I will make my wife and with our
kids. Twenty-something years? If I get it before then, fine. But
20-something years? I'm not going to last that long. I'll be at
home, raising my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning number Martinez preferred to talk about Sunday night
was three. As in, three straight wins over the Angels after losing
the series opener, 8-0. Three straight wins for the first time in
six weeks. Three straight wins, which were needed to stay even with
the Toronto Blue Jays in the wild-card race while maintaining a
one-game edge over the where-did-they-come-from Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows, doesn't it?'' Martinez smiled when asked if the Sox
were finally cultivating some much-needed momentum. ``I'm back,
we're starting to work through some injuries, it shows we're making
some improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Brian Daubach and Troy O'Leary treated Team Mickey Mouse
like rat poison all weekend as the Sox, who had 19 hits in a 14-3
blowout Saturday, followed up with 13 in Sunday's twilight affair,
including home runs by Daubach, O'Leary, and Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Donnie Sadler, playing his second straight game in center
field, had two doubles, a sacrifice bunt, and a walk in four plate
appearances, Jose Offerman jump-started the offense again with two
hits, and catcher Jason Varitek delivered a two-out, two-run double
in the fifth as the Sox seized a 7-1 lead for the second straight
game.
</P>
<P>
   While Mo Vaughn, who has one home run in his last 22 games, sat
out the finale of the series with a staph infection, just as he had
missed the previous four games, Daubach stood out by hitting home
runs in three consecutive games for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting out the series opener, Daubach went 6 for 13 in
the last three games, with three home runs, two doubles, and five
RBIs. O'Leary, who played in all four games, went 9 for 19, with
two home runs, a double, and six RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, meanwhile, hit a two-run home run in the ninth for his
first homer in nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's going to take,'' Stanley said. ``It's a
matter of being consistent. At times, we've played just great
baseball, and then we don't. And ever since I've been here, it
seems like it's always been tough to come to the West Coast. We
started off losing the first one, and you think, `West Coast, here
we go again,' but then we won three in a row playing consistent
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got to forget this and play the same way in Kansas
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who was one batter away from being lifted with a 7-2
lead in the fifth because of his pitch count, said he never felt
comfortable in his second start since coming off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit off with everything,'' said Martinez, who
walked three, including back-to-back hitters in the third, and
allowed three singles and two runs, one unearned after Daubach's
error in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was visited with two outs in the inning by Jimy
Williams, who presumably conveyed the message that Martinez would
not be permitted to go another batter past the one at the plate,
Tim Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, not one to give away a win when he was one out from
qualifying for the decision, took Williams at his word, then
rendered Salmon mute by striking him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way I expected to feel after my first start back
in Boston, but this time I felt it,'' Martinez said of his
discomfort. ``When you don't throw the ball the way you want, it
could be mechanical or physical. I think tonight it was more
mechanical. I felt the strength in my arm, but I couldn't spot
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, he didn't need to. Rich Garces spelled him in the
sixth with 1 2/3 innings, and Rheal Cormier got the last seven outs
as large pockets in the crowd of 31,664 rang out with chants of
``Let's Go, Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, who went to high school in nearby Cypress and had
almost as many fans here as fellow homey Nomar Garciaparra, was
asked if he were sorry he had to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got family here,'' he said. ``It was fun to see them. I
stayed with my mom for four days, but that's enough, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who reportedly intend Monday to release
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's starter, Jack McDowell, surely feel the same way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
