<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0291 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      08-09 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ With all due respect, a contingent of Astros could have
spent the weekend lounging on the beach at Lake Michigan, cruising
the Magnificent Mile or challenging what's left of the Chicago
Bulls to a game of pickup basketball.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What about the Cubs?
</P>
<P>
   Just leave them to Carl Everett, who was at it again Sunday,
driving in three runs in the Astros' 6-2 victory on a chilly night
at Wrigley Field. Mike Hampton became the National League's first
16-game winner and established a career high for victories in a
season.
</P>
<P>
   Everett concluded a huge weekend with two more hits, giving him
a .692 batting average (9-for-13) in the series.
</P>
<P>
   How big was his impact? Everett, who was activated from the
disabled list Friday, factored into 11 of the Astros' 22 runs in
the series with 10 RBIs and four runs scored, three on homers. The
only game the Cubs won was the one Everett spent on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to find out what Carl's been eating,'' Astros second
baseman Craig Biggio said. ``Thank God he was activated in time for
this series. We would have been in trouble without him. Carl is a
tremendous player, and he was huge this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Hampton (16-3) would have been in trouble
without command of his pitches, but he clearly has learned to win
with less than his best stuff. Hampton has walked 11 batters in his
last two starts, including a season-high six Sunday, but he managed
to win each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a battle,'' said Hampton, who allowed two
runs on four hits in seven innings. ``So much of pitching is
rhythm, and I never got into one. I was trying to make adjustments
the whole game. But I'll take two runs in seven innings every time
out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being atop the NL in wins (Boston's Pedro Martinez also
has 16 to lead the American League), Hampton said: ``It's very
satisfying. But I've learned that you can't control wins and
losses. Sometimes you pitch well and lose; sometimes you don't
pitch so well and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won for the 21st time in their last 28 games and
maintained a three-game lead over Cincinnati in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   Since manager Larry Dierker returned to the dugout following
brain surgery, the Astros are 18-7. No wonder there was a fan at
Wrigley Field with a sign that read, ``Larry Dierker for
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think I'd win that vote in my own clubhouse,''
Dierker joked.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros collected 14 hits, and every player Dierker sent to
the plate reached base at least once except Richard Hidalgo, who
entered in the bottom of the seventh inning and batted only once.
Hidalgo did, however, have two assists, giving him 15 for the
season, tops among big-league outfielders. Everett, Russ Johnson,
Jeff Bagwell, Matt Mieske and Randy Knorr had two hits apiece.
</P>
<P>
   After taking three of four games from the Cubs, the Astros move
on to Atlanta, where they figure to face tougher competition from
the Braves over the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who has won seven consecutive decisions, enjoyed a
1-2-3 first inning but struggled with his control in the second,
walking Cubs pitcher Micah Bowie with the bases loaded for the
game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamp had a good performance, but he was far from being at his
best,'' Dierker said. ``He was wild at times, and he was falling
behind in the count. He has learned to keep the ball out of the
hitting zone at all costs, which is smart to a point. But if you
walk too many guys, eventually you're going to have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sent nine batters to the plate in the third, scoring
three runs _ all after two were out _ on four hits and a pair of
walks. Everett hit a two-run single up the middle, and Mieske
chimed in with an RBI single that glanced off shortstop Jose
Nieves' glove and into shallow left field.
</P>
<P>
   Everett struck again in the fifth, scoring Bagwell from third
with a single to left. The switch-hitting outfielder extended his
hitting streak to 10 games, dating to before he went on the
disabled list. He's hitting .486 during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an explanation for it,'' said Everett, who was
5-for-6 with runners in scoring position during the series. ``I was
just making contact at the right time and hitting the ball where no
one was. I was focused the entire time, but other than that, who
can explain it? Like I've been saying: I'm just going to ride it
out for as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton retired six of the next seven batters he faced after
Bowie's bases-loaded walk, then walked Benito Santiago to start the
bottom of the fifth. Santiago went to third on Chad Meyers' first
career hit _ a double to right _ and scored on Jeff Blauser's
ground ball to second base.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie (0-3), making only the second start of his big-league
career, was replaced by Rod Beck with one out in the sixth inning.
The rookie lefthander allowed four runs on 10 hits and three walks.
The Astros, who scored two more runs in the eighth inning, improved
their record to 24-10 in games started by lefthanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
