<HEADER>
A0378 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      08-09 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Aug. 8, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GRIDLOCK-REVIEW (Washington) _ Congress has recessed
with little to show for itself beyond an arsenal of political
soundbites stockpiled to serve as campaign themes for a high-stakes
election that is still more than a year away. Still, hasn't it been
said that in a democracy the people get the government they
deserve? Can voters really expect anything but gridlock if they
elect a Democratic president, a Republican-dominated Senate and a
House nominally under Republican control but actually divided
nearly in two? By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-REINVENT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The AARP is trying to
retrofit itself for the baby boomers, the next great wave of the
aged, who began turning 50 three years ago and thus became eligible
for that incredibly fraught rite of passage, membership in the
AARP. Officials say they have no intention of short-changing their
older members, who in many ways have more traditional expectations
of retirement and what they want from a senior citizens'
organization. But the boomers are different. And the mighty AARP's
struggle to adjust says a lot about how the boomers will remake the
aging process. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   MALLS-DECLINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at why so many shopping
malls are dead or dying. One reason is greater competition _ in
some cases from re-imagined downtown blocks that developers, in an
interesting about-face, have remodeled to mimic malls. Usually,
where a mall has failed, a bigger, more state-of-the-art shopping
mecca looms on the horizon. Some are being `de-malled' to create
drive-up-to-the-door strip centers, which an increasing number of
shoppers find more convenient than the vast, multi-level centers
with miles of parking lots and walkways. But some critics feel
shopping centers have reached their saturation point. By Elin
Schoen Brockman.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-MUSIC-KIDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Businesses across North
America are deploying symphonies to drive people away. In tactics
akin to psychological warfare, merchants, building owners and
transit officials switch on the classics to scatter loiterers,
especially teenagers. Criminologists trace the trend to a 7-Eleven
store in Victoria, British Columbia, which began bombarding its
parking lot with classical music in 1985 to dissuade teenagers from
congregating there. By David Wallis.
</P>
<P>
   FARM-AID-REVIEW (Washington) _ Federal farm policy is creating
bigger farms and fewer farmers, converting tens of billions of tax
dollars into cattle fodder, creating big profits for big
agribusiness and underwriting cheap hamburgers, but bringing little
benefit _ and, some argue, great harm _ to small farmers trying to
make a living. A system that began in the Depression to help
farmers survive is now `planting a seed that is going to destroy
American agriculture as we know it,' says Sen. Phil Gramm. By Tim
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   DUBIOUS-SCIENCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ It seems that almost any
scientific-sounding extrapolation for taking off pounds or putting
on IQ points can quickly gain a seal of approval from public health
groups or educators and help set policy for untold years to come.
Sometimes it has nothing to do with science. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-PAY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ask a teacher what needs to be
done to improve dismal student performance, and it's a good bet the
first answer will be to raise teachers' salaries, thereby
attracting and keeping better teachers. But there is scant evidence
that higher salaries alone make a difference in student
performance. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   PETS-FAKE-TESTICLES-REVIEW (Undated) _ `Neuticles' are
artificial testicles implanted for cosmetic reasons in dogs, cats,
horses and other pets that have been neutered. By Douglas Martin.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-TREATIES-REVIEW (United Nations) _ Over the last decade,
many countries concerned about problems that transcend their
borders and threaten to overwhelm them have been signing on to one
treaty or convention after another aimed at reigning in abusive
regimes, ending the mistreatment of the weak and cutting back on
the proliferation of all kinds of weapons. Washington often watches
all this with an array of not-very-positive reactions: diminishing
enthusiasm in the White House, unease in the Pentagon, and mounting
outrage in Congress, always on the lookout for invasions of U.S.
sovereignty to beat back. By Barbara Crosette.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MYSTICISM-REVIEW (London) _ The approach of the first
full solar eclipse in Britain in 72 years, and the last of the
millennium, is being hailed by pagans, druids, doomsayers and New
Age Travelers who interpret it in many ways, from divine felicity
to the end of the world _ anything except celestial science. And
that says something about a nation whose stereotype of proud
pragmatism seems mirrored, or even challenged, by this strain of
mysticism and quest for alternative meanings. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-GUNS-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ Guns are everywhere in
Africa, a legacy of conflict and a result of lax gun control. There
are gun stores in fancy malls, including designer gun shops where
the rich buy slick, showy little guns hoping to protect themselves
from the high crime rate. Police and army roadblocks are standard
practice all over the continent, manned by young men with huge
automatic weapons dangling carelessly from their shoulders. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
