<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     08-09 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 The Week in Review  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Stock With Attitude  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the shortcomings of professional wrestling as a sport _
and purists say they are many _ it is definitely a business, and a
highly profitable one.
</P>
<P>
   Just how profitable became clear when World Wrestling Federation
Entertainment Inc., which promotes and stages Wrestlemania and the
top-rated cable television program ``Raw Is War,'' filed documents
with federal securities regulators indicating that it intends to
sell up to $172 million in stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12 months ended April 30, the WWF earned pretax profits
of $58 million on revenues of $251 million, a rate of return that
puts the company in a league with the most lucrative sports
franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Few true sports, however, prize an athlete's ``acting ability''
as much as his physical presence, as the WWF says it does, and few
leagues script performances right down to each combatant's entrance
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it too farcical to pay attention to,'' said Andrew
Zimbalist, an economics professor at Smith College who studies the
business of sports. ``The question in my mind is whether it should
be considered sport or theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The WWF's stock offering is likely to get an enthusiastic
reception from individual investors. Professional portfolio
managers, however, might cast a more skeptical eye on the fact that
the company's chairman also participates in wrestling matches, his
wife is the chief executive and the board, as yet, has no
independent directors to help make sure that only the matches are
rigged.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EDWARD WYATT
</P>
<P>
   A Star Is Born, in Queens
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite the same as the 1920s, when the motion picture
industry was centered in New York and Gloria Swanson, W.C. Fields,
the Marx Brothers and Paul Robeson were making movies at the Famous
Players-Lasky Studio in the Astoria section of Queens, New York
City. But the studio and New York are undergoing a remarkable
revival of film and television production.
</P>
<P>
   The studio, now known as Kaufman Astoria Studios, said it would
build an $8.3 million, 18,000 square-foot soundstage, the seventh
at the complex. ``Ransom'' and the ``First Wives Club'' were shot
at Astoria, which serves as home to the CBS comedy ``Cosby'' and
the Children's Television Workshop program ``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a great surge of business over the past five
years,'' said Mitchell Brill, director of operations at Lifetime
Studios, a tenant at the complex. ``The broadcast and cable
television business is extremely robust. I've got clients three
deep on hold.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of films shot in New York soared to 221 last year, up
from 69 in 1993. And even if there's been a slowdown in the film
industry this year, television production has plugged the gap. The
HBO series ``Sex and the City'' and ``The Sopranos'' are taped at
Silvercup Studios in Queens, while ``Law and Order'' has set up
house at the Pier 59 Studios in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question New York is hot. The number of prime-time
television series shot here will double to 12 this fall, with the
addition of ``Third Watch,'' ``Now &AMP; Again,'' ``Special Victims
Unit'' and ``The Beat.'' Some of it is location driven, but the
trend is also fueled by the simple desire of Bill Cosby, Kyra
Sedgwick, Ron Howard and Michael J. Fox to go home at night when
they finish shooting, respectively, ``Cosby,'' ``Talk to Me,''
``Bellevue'' and ``Spin City.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By CHARLES V. BAGLI
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ruling Creates Logjam In the Pacific Northwest  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Various species of snails, salamanders and the red tree vole, a
small rodent, could take on the importance of the famed northern
spotted owl in the Pacific Northwest's continuing battle over
logging. The same federal judge who once halted logging in the
old-growth forests in the Pacific Northwest to protect the owl
ruled that two federal agencies had failed to insure the monitoring
and protection of 77 other species.
</P>
<P>
   Judge William Dwyer of the U.S. District Court in Seattle
blocked nine major logging deals and threatened to hold up more
than 100 others. Hailing the decision, environmental groups said
Dwyer had stopped the agencies from ``putting logging activities
ahead of their responsibilities to protect wildlife, fish, clean
water and old-growth forests.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
<P>
   Christian Coalition's Win
</P>
<P>
   After months of internal upheaval, the Christian Coalition got
some good news: A U.S. District Court judge threw out most charges
in a lawsuit that accused the group of illegally trying to boost
Republican candidates through voter guides and other efforts. The
verdict does little to clarify just how far nonpartisan
organizations of all stripes can go in activities that verge on
political.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition, the largest group of religious conservatives, was
not completely exonerated. It must pay a civil penalty for efforts
that promoted the candidacies in 1994 of Newt Gingrich, who soon
became the House speaker, and Oliver North, who lost his campaign
for the Senate from Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   A Post Filled After 14 Months  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a drawn-out nomination battle, the Senate voted to confirm
Richard Holbrooke as chief U.S. delegate to the United Nations. The
14-month delay left the Clinton administration without a high-level
representative at United Nations during military conflicts in the
Balkans and the Persian Gulf. The administration hopes Holbrooke
can improve relations with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   India, Tripled
</P>
<P>
   India is set to pass the billion mark sometime this month,
United Nations demographers said, and it is closing in on China for
the title of world's most populous nation. The milestone is
expected to renew a moribund debate in India over family-planning
policies that have failed to stop the population from tripling in
half a century of independence. India has the world's largest
concentration of poor people, illiterate adults and malnourished
children.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Film Fetches $16 Million
</P>
<P>
   A divided federal arbitration panel decided that the government
must pay the heirs of Abraham Zapruder $16 million for his film of
President John F. Kennedy's assassination. The award, about halfway
between the $30 million sought by the family and the $1 million
offered by the Justice Department, was the highest price ever paid
for any American historical artifact.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   China's Missile Test
</P>
<P>
   Nothing makes China go ballistic as much as moves by Taiwan that
look like a step away from Beijing's goal of reunification. China
tested a new long-range missile that has the capability of reaching
America. The launch comes in the middle of a crisis over Taiwan
that started last month when President Lee Teng-hui asserted that
his country will now only talk with China on the basis of ``special
state-to-state relations.'' The test occurred the same day Beijing
excoriated Washington for selling military equipment to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH FAISON
</P>
<P>
   A Money Trail
</P>
<P>
   When Cayman Islands banker John Mathewson was nabbed in San
Antonio in 1996 for helping cable pirates launder profits offshore,
he quickly offered federal agents an investigative gold mine:
investigators got their first ever access to computer tapes of a
Cayman bank's transactions and the real names behind some 2,000
bogus depositor names. Overnight the American and his Guardian Bank
&AMP; Trust Co. became the worst nightmare of the British
protectorate's bankers. The Caymans are the world's fifth largest
financial center because of strict confidentiality laws, no
taxation and a determined non-cooperation with U.S. tax probers.
</P>
<P>
   Mathewson drew a lenient sentence of five-years probation for
his cooperation in present cases that have put $50 million in taxes
and penalties in federal coffers. Future cases could bring $250
million more.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RONALD SMOTHERS
</P>
<P>
   Farm Teams' Hoop Dreams
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association has never had a minor-league
farm system where it could nurture young talent. Isiah Thomas, a
former NBA superstar with the Detroit Pistons, said he hoped to
fill that void by buying control of the Continental Basketball
Association for $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes at a time when the NBA is seeking to impose a
minimum age of 20 to enter the league, and the CBA could act as a
proving ground for raw, teen-aged talent leaping to the pros from
high schools and colleges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD SANDOMIR
</P>
<P>
   Gun Toll in Dollars
</P>
<P>
   Most discussion about gun violence focuses on the human toll.
But a new study shows that when guns are fired, everyone gets hit _
in the wallet. It costs $2.3 billion a year to treat America's
gunshot wounds, said a study by a group of economists that appeared
in The Journal of the American Medical Association. Nearly half
that cost is picked up by taxpayers. ``It is really everybody's
problem,'' said the study's chief author, Dr. Philip J. Cook of
Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Court Overturns Ouster Of a Gay Boy Scout  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does the pledge of ``morally straight'' in the Boy Scout Oath
mean homosexuality is immoral? Lawyers for the Scouts say yes and
argue that this guaranteed a First Amendment right of ``expressive
association'' to expel a gay Eagle scout in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous opinion, the New Jersey Supreme Court disagreed,
saying morally straight meant goodness, with no sexual
connotations. The justices likened treatment of the former Boy
Scout, James Dale, now 29, to discrimination against women and
blacks. Scout officials said they will take their case to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT HANLEY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
