<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CONGRESS-GRIDLOCK-R     08-09 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CONGRESS-GRIDLOCK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WASHINGTON, COMPROMISE TAKES A HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress went home for the August recess late last
week with little to show for itself beyond an arsenal of political
sound bites stockpiled to serve as campaign themes for a
high-stakes election that is still more than a year away.
</P>
<P>
   The achievements of the 106th Congress so far are scant _ mainly
a measure giving states more flexibility in using federal education
funds and another requiring deployment of a national missile
defense system. And across an array of fronts, Republicans and
Democrats seem more interested in campaigning than legislating.
</P>
<P>
   For example, President Clinton is so certain to kill the
far-reaching $792 billion tax cut passed by the Republican Congress
that its leaders decided not to send it to him until after Labor
Day so that he would not be able to make a showy White House
ceremony out of vetoing it while lawmakers were away. Republicans
nonetheless were elated that they had used the tax cut bill as a
way to distinguish themselves from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a dramatic difference between Republicans and
Democrats in this capital city,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,
``and this is the dividing line.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to regulate the managed care industry passed the
Senate but has yet to make it to the House floor because of
Republican fears that they could lose control and give the
Democrats a victory on the issue. Despite the school shootings in
Littleton, Colo., another school year will open without any new gun
control measures. And although Clinton has proposed restructuring
Medicare and adding a new prescription drug benefit, the issue has
simply drifted into the fall.
</P>
<P>
   It's still early to make any definitive judgments about this
Congress, and some grand political bargain on tax cuts, spending
and Medicare might yet materialize in the fall. But at the moment,
compromise does not seem to be in the air. Some lawmakers are
despairing at the focus on political point-scoring in the
all-campaign-all-the time Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep saying, `the election,''' said Sen. Olympia Snowe,
R- Maine. ``And I say that's a year and a half from now. In the
meantime could we just sort of legislate?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it has been said that in a democracy the people get the
government they deserve. The voters put in place a recipe for
gridlock when they elected a Democratic president, a Republican
Senate and a House nominally in Republican control but actually
divided nearly in two.
</P>
<P>
   Issues like gun control and health care are complicated and
emotional. Sorting out what the nation's fiscal priorities should
be across a decade that is expected to bring in a $3 trillion
surplus is a profound political decision with far-reaching
consequences. So it's no wonder that the two parties want to fight
out their differences in the 2000 campaign in hopes that next
year's election _ unlike the last presidential year of 1996 _ will
help settle some of the arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had a surplus of the magnitude projected, at least
in my lifetime,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle.
``There's a legitimate philosophical debate over what you do with
it,'' he said. ``This is the noise of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say the tenuous balance of power is a sign to
Congress and the president that they should compromise. And they
briefly did, after the bruising 1995 fight over budget priorities
that led to the government shutdown, and after the inconclusive
1996 election. Unable to carry a Democratic Congress into office
with him, Clinton began his second term pledging to build a ``vital
center'' in U.S. politics. Republicans, chastened by their failure
to capture the White House, said they would cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later there was Newt Gingrich and Bill Clinton
standing side by side on the White House lawn celebrating a
bipartisan milestone: a plan to balance the budget and cut taxes in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the spirit of compromise was short-lived. No matter how much
Clinton has tried to create a ``New Democrat'' or George W. Bush
looks for his own way as a ``compassionate conservative,'' the
partisan divisions in Congress have only been widening.
</P>
<P>
   The reapportionment of 1990 left many congressional districts
safely Republican and others overwhelmingly Democratic, giving most
House members little need to search for a center ground. The
Democrats who were once willing to vote with Ronald Reagan have
become Republicans. Liberal Republicans are almost extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Low voter participation in mid-term elections has also pushed
Republicans and Democrats, most particularly in the House, to cater
to their most devoted core voters and donor base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly Congress has become polarized,'' said Marshall
Wittmann, a congressional analyst at the conservative Heritage
Foundation. ``This has been a long-term development over the last
20-odd years. What you essentially have is a conservative party
versus a liberal party.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that even when the two parties sound alike, their
rhetoric masks profound differences. Democrats say they support a
tax cut too _ just a smaller one than the Republicans. But most
Democrats put their passions into new programs like one to help
with school construction or a new Medicare prescription drug
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   And while Senate Republicans came up with a ``Patients' Bill of
Rights Plus'' to counter the Democrats ``Patients' Bill of
Rights,'' the Republican managed care bill was so much weaker than
the Democrats' version that it almost seemed to highlight the
Republicans' aversion to government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a reservoir of trust and good will to find a way
around such differences. But the impeachment battle left trust
between the parties in short supply. And the razor-thin majority in
the House has made matters worse: The parties judge every issue by
its likely effect on the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   So Democrats accuse Republicans of passing a large tax cut to
create a campaign issue. Republicans insist that Democrats are
blocking bills, like a Republican version of gun control, because
they want to run against a do-nothing Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers still try to swim against the tide. One
bipartisan group in the House reached agreement on a managed care
bill Thursday, hours before Congress recessed.
</P>
<P>
   As they announced the details in the late afternoon heat
Thursday outside the Capitol, Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., said,
``Let's put the election of 2000 where it belongs _ November 2000.
Today let's work on issues that face every American. ''
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed like a throwback to another era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 0902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
