<HEADER>
A1926 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MALLS-DECLINE-REVIE     08-09 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MALLS-DECLINE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MALLS DIE, THE NEXT GENERATION RE-CREATES THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ELIN SCHOEN BROCKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Wolcott Street in Waterbury, Conn., on a recent afternoon
earth-movers prowled the wreckage of the Naugatuck Valley Mall,
scooping up the rubble of what was once the main shopping center
there. For miles on either side, roadside signs announce Arby's,
Shop-Rite, Sleepy's the Mattress Professionals _ today's typical
suburban vista.
</P>
<P>
   But now dead or dying shopping centers are also typical. It's
known as ``going dark,'' the theatrical term that seems
particularly apt given the April closing of the Galleria Mall, in
Sherman Oaks, Calif., where ``Valley Girls'' and ``Fast Times at
Ridgemont High'' were filmed. In Fishkill, N.Y., the once vibrant
Dutchess Mall is ailing. Payless Shoes, Deb Shops and Foot Locker
are among the few remaining tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Gibbs, a retail consultant and urban planner from
Birmingham, Mich., who is regularly on the road monitoring these
things for cities and developers, estimates that there are 500 to
1,000 ghost shopping centers in the country.
</P>
<P>
   To observers of this changing scene, such ferment seems natural.
``Babylon was done in in part by certain conquerors who sacked
it,'' says William W. Hallo, the Laffan Professor of Assyriology at
Yale University. ``But what really did it in was the location of
new capital cities in close proximity that undercut the economic
base for its prosperity. This happened all over the ancient
world.''
</P>
<P>
   And it went on happening, not only with cities but also with the
buildings within them and now with the malls beyond, which were
created in the image of downtown centers. Witold Rybczynski, who
chronicled the history of shopping centers in ``City Life: Urban
Expectations in a New World'' (Touchstone, 1996), says it is part
of the nature of any building to have a life cycle that ends in
obsolescence. Shopping centers are no exception. ``They've been
around in various forms since the turn of the century,'' he said,
``and they've evolved, they've changed a lot over that time.'' The
early town centers that mixed shops with apartments were followed
by hybrids of strip centers and enclosed malls, including today's
neo-traditional town centers that some planners see as an antidote
to suburban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, where a mall has failed, a bigger, more
state-of-the-art shopping mecca looms on the horizon. ``You
remember that movie `One Million B.C.,' with Victor Mature as a
caveman?'' asks James Howard Kunstler, whose book, ``The Geography
of Nowhere'' (Touchstone, 1994), helped establish him as an
outspoken proponent of the New Urbanism, a design movement to
restore a sense of community to cities and suburbs. ``Well, at one
point the cavemen are sort of cringing in the foreground while
these two dinosaurs battle it out in the background, and in the end
one of them has his feet up in the air and he's dead. And this is
pretty much the mall situation in American towns. The citizens are
standing around like the cringing cavemen watching these monsters
battle each other for world domination. Of course, behind it all we
know they're both headed for extinction anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Shopping centers, some critics feel, have reached their
saturation point. The new mall threatening the old one is perhaps
symptomatic of a much larger problem _ ``too much shopping space
per American,'' Rybczynski says. That includes cyberspace and the
incalculable square footage that mail order catalogs would take up
if laid end to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will always be malls,'' Gibbs said, ``but fewer
of them. And they will face greater competition'' _ in some cases
from downtown blocks that developers, in an interesting about-face,
have remodeled to mimick malls.
</P>
<P>
   David Livshin, president of the Dagar Group Ltd., which manages
the Dutchess Mall, admits that the sight of it ``sitting there
basically on life support'' could be viewed as a harbinger of
suburban decay. Instead, this 70 acres of interstate-front property
is a new frontier, ready to be reconfigured, Livshin says, with
offices, retail stores, restaurants, perhaps a conference center, a
gym and ``an interesting common area where people can sit.'' In
other words, he hinted at an environment akin to Gibbs' current
project at the defunct mall in Levittown, N.J. The new center will
have housing, a community college, a post office and about 2,000
square feet of retail shops.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, some failed malls are turning into industrial parks
and corporate or college campuses. Or they're being ``de-malled''
to create drive-up-to-the-door strip centers _ often anchored by
retailers like Walmart or Home Depot, which an increasing number of
shoppers find more convenient than the vast, multi-level centers
with miles of parking lots and walkways.
</P>
<P>
   What time-challenged shoppers want these days, Gibbs said, is
``to park close to the store and run in and run out without having
to go through the whole mall process.''
</P>
<P>
   An outdated center is easier and cheaper to recycle than, say,
the abandoned old brick mills or factories haunting some towns,
Rybczynski says. Their lightweight construction is an advantage in
restructuring them. Or in demolishing them. And, said Gibbs, who
prefers retrofitting to starting over, ``Local people generally
have a love and loyalty for the old mall. A lot of them grew up
there as kids, or they're senior citizens and raised their families
there, so they want to see it survive.'' Rybczynski says that
shopping centers have become a part of who Americans are and how
they live. Several are on the National Register of Historic Places,
including Highland Park Village in Highland Park, Texas, built
between 1931 and 1941, which is also a National Historic Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   But less distinguished examples of what architectural historians
now recognize as ``a distinctive American building type'' will
always be vulnerable to the vicissitudes of commerce and
demographics. ``The perception was, the mall's gone, now the area's
dead,'' said Rob Kane, who owns Kartele Cellular Phones near the
recently razed Naugatuck Valley Mall. ``We had to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Local merchants are aggressively promoting the area as the
``Magical Retail Mile.'' Although the nearby Barnes &AMP; Noble and
Toys ``R'' Us moved to Waterbury's brand-new regional mall, which
put the old one out of business, a new movie theater, a day care
center and a video store have opened here since the old mall's
demise. What will replace it is still undecided, but just the sight
of the rubble is ``progress,'' Kane said. ``It means there's
activity going on. It's not like when it was just sitting there,
empty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
