<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 09:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1933 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-KID     08-09 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-KIDS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUM-BUM-BA-BUM: EINE KLEINE BUS-TERMINAL-CLEARING MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID WALLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a muggy Monday night in July, some 80,000 classical music
fans ignored forecast thundershowers and flocked to New York's
Central Park to enjoy the music of Dvorak and Tchaikovsky.
Meanwhile, businesses across North America are deploying similar
symphonies to drive people away.
</P>
<P>
   In tactics akin to psychological warfare, a growing number of
merchants, building owners and transit officials are switching on
the classics to scatter loiterers, especially teens. Criminologists
trace the trend to a 7-Eleven store in Victoria, British Columbia,
which began bombarding its parking lot with classical music in 1985
to dissuade teens from congregating. Margaret Chabris, a 7-Eleven
spokeswoman, says about 150 franchises have followed suit, as have
many other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying teens with classical gas seems out of synch with the
genre's growing acceptance by mass culture. After all, sales of
classical CDs rose nearly 20 percent in 1998. And in response to
recent (albeit controversial) studies suggesting that classical
music stimulates brain development, Georgia and Tennessee now
dispense free classical CDs for newborns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're noticing is a much broader use of orchestral music
on television, in advertising, and in public spaces,'' said John
Sparks, vice president of the American Symphony Orchestra League.
But he thought the idea of using classical music to disperse people
``says more about the person making that selection than the people
they're aiming at.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, recent experience suggests that the classical deterrent
is effective.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bernie Naiman started booming ``Horowitz at the Met'' and
``La Traviata'' outside the commercial building he owns in downtown
Denver four years ago, he considered an adjacent outdoor plaza ``a
country club for bums.'' Sidewalk preachers in particular irritated
Naiman. ``Religious fanatics would scream unintelligible messages
from 11 a.m. until 2 p.m.,'' he said. ``It got so bad that our
tenants couldn't open their windows.'' His deejaying proved as
unpopular as intended; the preachers and most of the vagrants soon
vanished. ``The arias by Luciano Pavarotti really drove them
crazy,'' recalls Naiman.
</P>
<P>
   The aversion of teen-agers to what used to be called ``long-hair
music'' is well documented. A spree of wildings and a gang-related
murder in 1996 prompted the Toronto Transit Commission to pipe
classical pieces like Chopin's ``Fantasie-Impromptu in C Minor''
into Kennedy Station, long a hub for subways, buses and
troublemakers. ``The bottom line is that kids don't like classical
music,'' declared Mike Walker, the commission's chief security
officer, who plans to play the canned music at at least three more
stations next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bach's ``Lute Suite in A Minor'' alone won't eliminate muggings
or panhandling, says Ken Philmus, director of tunnels, bridges and
terminals for the Port Authority in New York. But that piece and
others play an important role in a comprehensive environmental
redesign at the Port Authority's midtown bus terminal that has made
the place less threatening. Before the overhaul in 1991, the
terminal's seediness was the butt of jokes by David Letterman. Then
the authority installed brighter lighting, opened up nooks where
the homeless camped, beefed up police patrols, brought in roving
social workers _ and introduced classical music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Classical music didn't stop muggings,'' Philmus said. ``What
it did was make people walking through the building say, `You know,
this place is different.''' Upon reflection, Philmus added: ``I'm
sure some folks decided, `I'm not going to loiter under this
speaker.'''
</P>
<P>
   As a piano concerto played in the background, a Port Authority
police officer, J.D. Levi, credited the music system's repetition
with dispersing derelicts. ``It's on a loop, so if you are standing
in one place it gets annoying,'' conceded Levi. ``Sometimes,'' he
joked, `` &UR; I  &LR; want to shoot the speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   His opinion was seconded by Chop, as he called himself, a young
man hanging out in front of the bus terminal's 42nd Street entrance
on a recent Friday evening. ``They need to change the music,'' he
griped. ``Anything but classical.''
</P>
<P>
   How about a little Perry Como? According to Tim Crowe, a
criminologist and author of ``Crime Prevention Through
Environmental Design,'' business owners must discern the dislikes
of the ``market'' they aim to annoy _ in much the same way that the
U.S. armed forces pursuing Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega figured that
blasting ``I Fought the Law'' over loudspeakers would bother the
Panamanian strongman when he was holed up at the Vatican embassy in
Panama City in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't play classical for the Goths _ they like ethereal
music,'' noted Crowe, referring not to the sackers of Rome but to
American youths known for wearing funereal black clothing and white
makeup.
</P>
<P>
   To discipline violators of the town's public noise ordinance,
Paul Sacco, a judge in Fort Lupton, Colo., mandates a medley of
classical and other styles of music. Once a month on a Friday
night, offenders arrested for blaring music from their cars undergo
a 90-minute music immersion class _ a sentence recalling ``A
Clockwork Orange,'' the Stanley Kubrick film in which the
authorities prop open a rapist's eyes and force him to watch scenes
of violence while listening to Beethoven. Sacco's play list of
punishment includes Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, Wayne Newton and
Barry Manilow tunes, bagpipe solos and the cruel and unusual theme
song from ``Barney.''
</P>
<P>
   No consensus exists on just why teenagers and classical music
don't mix. Perhaps they think of it as their parents' music. Or
maybe they didn't hear enough of it while rocking in the cradle.
Dr. William Anderson, a psychiatrist at Massachusetts General
Hospital, theorized that youths reared in an environment of
unpredictability and chaos would find classical music not terribly
pleasant, since it has predictable patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the notion that classical music can repel listeners
instead of entertain them saddens many concert-goers. At a recent
performance of Schumann at Lincoln Center in New York, Jeannine
Wilson, in a flowing purple chiffon skirt, was rueful. ``When I
think of classical music, I think of something beautiful, poetic,
invigorating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And what would Mozart think of classical deterrence? She
brightened a bit: ``He'd be really excited. He composed music to
move people, and I guess it still does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
