<SLUG> BC-KATIE-HOLMES-IN-TEACHING-MRS-TINGLE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATIE HOLMES: `TEACHING,' BUT STILL LEARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Katie Holmes with Helen Mirren, Barry
Watson and Marisa Coughlan in a scene from ``Teaching Mrs.
Tingle.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Katie Holmes may be only 20, but she's learned a few tricks of
the trade.
 &HT;    About to do her first big-screen love scene, on the set of her
new movie, ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' she handed co-star Barry
Watson a breath mint.
 &HT;    ``I just think love scenes are better with nice breath,'' she
says in a matter-of-fact tone.
 &HT;    Everything about Katie Holmes is nice, as far as anyone can
tell. She loves her mother and four siblings. She loves her
co-stars, her pets and her fans.
 &HT;    Why, even after she became a big-time television star, she not
only had a curfew from her parents _ she followed it.
 &HT;    ``Thank God I'm the youngest of five and I had older brothers
and sisters working for me,'' she says, sipping orange juice during
an interview at Manhattan's Essex House. ``They were even like,
`Mom, come on. Katie is a TV star, and she lives in North Carolina
for most of the year by herself.'''
 &HT;    Even so, she says, her parents wanted her back in that house of
her own by 12:30 a.m.
 &HT;    ``I usually complied,'' she says sheepishly.
 &HT;    She may be a dutiful daughter, but Holmes is no babe in the
woods. Her acting capabilities are vouched for by a most competent
authority: her ``Mrs. Tingle'' co-star, the British stage legend
Helen Mirren.
 &HT;    ``Katie was the consummate professional,'' Mirren says in a
separate interview. ``She is technically able as an actress, and
experienced. She is also the sweetest girl on this planet.''
 &HT;    It figures that in ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' which will open
Aug. 20, Holmes plays a goody-two-shoes high-school honor student,
a working-class girl desperate to get a scholarship to college and
ditch her small-town life.
 &HT;    Her only obstacle is Mrs. Tingle (Mirren), an evil, spiteful old
hag of a teacher who wants her students to fail because she herself
never got out of town.
 &HT;    One thing leads to another, and soon Holmes and Watson have
kidnaped their teacher and are up to their necks in trouble.
 &HT;    With, of course, some time out for a little teen love.
 &HT;    Holmes is charmingly embarrassed about her first love scene.
 &HT;    ``It was just awkward to have all these Teamsters watch me take
my shirt off,'' she says, rolling her eyes, ``and they're just
standing there yawning and eating a doughnut.''
 &HT;    She also had a hard time getting into the mood with Watson, the
handsome heartthrob of television's ``7th Heaven.''
 &HT;    ``I mean, one minute we're eating Altoid mints and the next
we're supposed to be all in love and ripping each other's clothes
off?'' Holmes says, shaking her head. ``I guess I learned that love
scenes are not as easy as they look.''
 &HT;    More worrisome to her, however, is what her parents will say.
 &HT;    ``I showed my older brother Marty, who is a very intimidating
lawyer, a rough cut of the film,'' she says. ``And it was pretty
rough on him. He just shielded his eyes during the makeout part and
said, `Gross, you're my sister. I don't want to see this stuff.'
 &HT;    ``I'm worried about what my mother will think.''
 &HT;    Holmes grew up in Toledo, Ohio, daughter of a housewife and an
attorney. Life was fairly normal until her senior year of high
school, when Holmes and her mother found out about pilot seasons in
Los Angeles, in which young, unproven actors audition for new
television series.
 &HT;    Inspiration struck, and soon a video camera was set up in their
Toledo basement.
 &HT;    ``My mom and I would send for four scripts a month,'' Holmes
recalls, ``and we'd go downstairs and put me on tape. I would play
the teen, and my mother would play all the other parts.''
 &HT;    One of those tapes landed on the desk of Kevin Williamson,
creator of ``Dawson's Creek'' and director of ``Teaching Mrs.
Tingle.''
 &HT;    ``I pop in this videotape,'' he recalls in a separate interview,
``and it was just a girl in her basement playing Joey. Her mother
played Dawson. And it took about one minute for me to say, `Get her
in here to test for the network.'''
 &HT;    That was easier said than done, though, since Holmes was all set
for the school play, ``Damn Yankees.''
 &HT;    ``I was playing Lola. I even got to wear the feathered boa,''
the young actress says defensively. ``I thought, `There is no way
I'm not playing Lola to go audition for some network.' So I told
Kevin and the WB, `I'm sorry. I just can't meet with you this week.
The other kids at my school are counting on me.'''
 &HT;    ``Here is maybe the only girl on this planet who says, `My
friends mean more to me than being in this highly publicized TV
series,''' Williamson says, grinning. ``It was heartbreaking. So we
waited the week and then flew her out.''
 &HT;    Holmes got the role, and virtual overnight stardom in the
bargain. Besides the series, she also has a flourishing movie
career that has included roles in Ang Lee's ``The Ice Storm''
(1997), the horror movie ``Disturbing Behavior'' (1998) and the hip
drama ``Go'' (1999).
 &HT;    Next year she'll make her biggest film to date, the drama
``Wonder Boys.'' Moving up in the world, she'll play a college
freshman, one with a big crush on one of her professors (Michael
Douglas).
 &HT;    ``My character is a very strong, smart girl,'' Holmes says.
``She's savvy, but a little precocious. She also has some feelings
for Michael Douglas' character. Unfortunately they are not
returned.''
 &HT;    In real life, Holmes reportedly has some strong feelings of her
own for ``Dawson's'' co-star Joshua Jackson. When his name comes
up, she almost blushes and then heads for safe ground.
 &HT;    ``Actually,'' she says, ``I like to keep my personal life
personal.''
 &HT;    She may be playing a college student, and even have been
accepted into Columbia University in New York, but Holmes has put
her education on hold for the duration of ``Dawson's Creek.''
 &HT;    ``College is not something I look upon lightly,'' she says. ``I
want to give it my entire attention, and that's not possible right
now.
 &HT;    ``I will definitely stay with the show as long as it runs.''
 &HT;    And as long as she's there, fans will doubtless be buzzing about
the relationship between Joey and Dawson (James Van Der Beek),
currently on the outs on the show.
 &HT;    And then of course there's the biggest question about the
thus-far-unconsummated romance. Will Joey and Dawson ever go
R-rated?
 &HT;    ``Well,'' Holmes says, ``I'm a hopeless romantic, and I would be
upset if they didn't eventually get together in that way.''
 &HT;    A nervous smile plays on her lips.
 &HT;    ``I just hope my mom isn't watching that night.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,''
consult the Miramax Website at www.miramax.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
