<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0422 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMES-CAAN-IN-MICKEY-     08-09 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-CAAN-IN-MICKEY-BLUE-EYES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES CAAN, MIRRORED TO THE MOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of James Caan in a scene from ``Mickey Blue
Eyes.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    James Caan will say anything.
 &HT;    To anyone, even the much-reviled press.
 &HT;    About anyone, even Hugh Grant, his co-star in the mob-themed
romantic comedy ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' and also his boss, since the
film was produced by Grant and Elizabeth Hurley.
 &HT;    ``Hugh's very nervous, very neurotic,'' Caan says with obvious
glee. ``He's very British, I guess. Him being British and me being
pretty New York, it was pretty funny.
 &HT;    ``I just kept him nervous all day long,'' Caan says. ``I'd tell
him lies. He was so easy, such an easy mark.
 &HT;    ``I saw him the other day after not seeing him for a while,''
the actor adds, ``and I said, `You're going to wear that shirt
today?' He goes, `What?' He called Elizabeth, `I've got to get
another shirt!'''
 &HT;    Caan guffaws.
 &HT;    Grant, on the other hand, can only shake his head, a smile
battling his scowl.
 &HT;    ``I can't believe the lack of respect shown by that man,'' he
says in a separate interview. ``We pluck him from his old-people's
home, give him a job and we get this crap?''
 &HT;    The British actor grins.
 &HT;    ``He's got wonderful spirit,'' Grant says, ``but a lot of it is
drugs, you have to remember.''
 &HT;    ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' which will open nationwide on Aug. 20,
casts Caan as a New York gangster whose beloved daughter (Jeanne
Tripplehorn) gets engaged to a prim-and-proper British auctioneer
(Grant).
 &HT;    Grant and Hurley happened to run into Caan in New York while
they were in pre-production for the film, and it's no wonder that
the idea of casting him clicked immediately. After all, if you're
casting a Mafioso, why not a man who, despite a long and impressive
career, remains best known as Sonny Corleone in ``The Godfather''
(1972)?
 &HT;    ``I'm sure that Sonny Corleone had something to do with it, and
that's fine,'' Caan says during a interview at Manhattan's Regency
Hotel. Dressed casually in blue jeans, a plaid shirt and sneakers,
the actor is relaxed, effusive and, oh yes, ready to rattle off
language that would make a sailor blush.
 &HT;    If he tries, though, he can actually plug his film and even
dissect his performance in it.
 &HT;    ``Even though `Mickey Blue Eyes' is a comedy, I tried not to
play Frank any differently than I would a similar kind of character
in a drama,'' he says. ``The trick to comedy is concentrating a
little harder, because you have to walk through situations as if
everything is perfectly normal.
 &HT;    ``I believe that if you try to be funny, you usually aren't,''
he adds. ``If you play it straight and just be unaware of what's
happening around you, it becomes funny.
 &HT;    ``The accent is the same,'' he concludes. ``The mannerisms are
the same. This guy is loyal to his family and loyal to his other
Family, if you know what I mean, and trying to be loyal to both is
the problem. That's where the humor comes through.''
 &HT;    Everyone on the ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' set felt the same way, Caan
thinks, and the end result is a pretty amusing piece of
entertainment.
 &HT;    ``The intent here, as far as I was concerned, is that people
have a good time,'' he says. ``We're not curing cancer. It's not
`Hamlet.' There's no message.
 &HT;    ``If you wake up in the morning, don't even remember what you
saw, but know you had a good time, then I think it's successful.''
 &HT;    ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' is only the first installment in a virtual
Caan film festival. He has two more films due later in the year _
``The Yards,'' a drama with Mark Wahlberg, Charlize Theron and Faye
Dunaway, and ``The Way of the Gun,'' a crime saga with Ryan
Phillippe and Benicio Del Toro.
 &HT;    In fact, Caan's been on a roll since the early 1990s, after
hitting bottom at the box office with ``Bolero'' (1982) and ``Kiss
Me Goodnight'' (1982), a dismal doubleheader that in large part
contributed to a five-year absence from the screen.
 &HT;    The 1990s have been another story, however. His compelling
performance in ``Misery'' (1990) as a novelist held prisoner by a
deranged fan reminded Hollywood that he was still a talent to be
reckoned with, and he demonstrated his range in such diverse films
as the screwball comedy ``Honeymoon in Vegas'' (1992), the
brilliant-but-little-seen drama ``Flesh and Bone'' (1993), the
Arnold Schwarzenegger action picture ``Eraser'' (1996) and the
cable-television private-eye movie, ``Poodle Springs'' (1999).
 &HT;    Not that anyone ever doubted Caan's ability, at least not after
such early films as ``Brian's Song'' (1971), ``The Godfather,''
``Cinderella Liberty'' (1973) and ``Thief'' (1981). But it was no
secret that the actor had a major drug problem, one that made him
little more than an accident waiting to happen.
 &HT;    ``Of all the drugs in the world, cocaine was probably the worst
one I could have chosen,'' Caan says unblinkingly. ``I was never a
drinker _ I was a purist.
 &HT;    ``I'm hyper by nature,'' he says. ``People think I'm as high as
a kite anyway. In the old days, I'd do (cocaine) with the girls,
you know. Then all of a sudden it was a way of life _ and it came
at a time in my life when everything was good, too good.''
 &HT;    Caan's wakeup call came seven years ago, when his eldest son
Scott _ now an actor, with credits that include ``Varsity Blues''
(1998) _ was still only a teen-ager.
 &HT;    ``You always think you fool your kids _ that they don't know,
that they're stupid,'' he says. ``One night I was at some dope
dealer's place. I'd just gone upstairs.
 &HT;    ``And here comes Scott with a baseball bat. He was gonna kill
this guy,'' Caan says, misting up. ``I was kind of smiling out of
one eye and crying out of the other. I was so proud of him.
 &HT;    ``If there was one thing that probably straightened my butt out,
it was right there and then,'' the actor says. ``We all went
through it, and not everybody survived it.''
 &HT;    Caan survived it, and eventually got his act together. At 59,
he's married again and a father of five children.
 &HT;    ``I've got two new ones,'' he says. ``The youngest one is named
Viagra!''
 &HT;    Actually, the 9-month-old is named Jake. Then there's 3-year-old
Jimmy Jr., 7-year-old Alexander, 23-year-old Scott and 34-year-old
Tara.
 &HT;    ``I'm not a grandfather yet,'' Caan says. ``People are like,
`Oh, my mother loves you' or `My grandfather ... ' I'm like, `Get
out of here.'''
 &HT;    Caan can still play the maverick, but it's obvious that one of
Hollywood's legendary wild men has settled down more than somewhat.
 &HT;    ``I'm a little bit more at peace with myself,'' he says. ``I
went through my period of doing really destructive stuff, just
excessive behavior. I got so tired of being so tired _ that s--t
stinks.
 &HT;    ``I'm glad I can be there for the kids now, that they've got two
parents,'' he says. ``Two of the kids are even with the same
wife.''
 &HT;    He grins.
 &HT;    ``You see? I really am maturing.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
