<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLE-BERRY-AS-DOROTHY-DANDRIDGE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLE BERRY RE-INTRODUCES DOROTHY DANDRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Halle Berry in a scene from
``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge.'') 
 By JEAN OPPENHEIMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Hollywood in the 1940s and 1950s wasn't a good place to be
beautiful, talented and black _ especially for actresses, who were
usually limited to playing domestics or jungle queens.
 &HT;    Times have changed, of course, and today Halle Berry is one of
an increasing number of black leading ladies who have earned
respect _ and solid box-office numbers _ in the movie industry.
 &HT;    Berry thinks the biggest single link between then and now was
Dorothy Dandridge, the gifted singer/actress who became the first
black woman ever nominated for a Best Actress Academy Award for her
performance in ``Carmen Jones'' (1954). But despite her one-time
fame _ she was also the first black woman to grace the cover of
Life magazine _ today Dandridge is virtually unknown.
 &HT;    Berry hopes to change that with ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge,'' an HBO movie airing on Aug. 21, in which she does
double duty as star and producer.
 &HT;    Making the film was a crusade for Berry, who has starred in such
films as ``Executive Decision'' (1997), ``Why Do Fools Fall in
Love'' (1998) and ``Bulworth'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``Getting this movie made has been my waking thought for six
years,'' the actress says over lunch at Barnaby's, a fashionable
Los Angeles restaurant. ``When one door closed, I went to another
door. And when that one closed, I went to another.''
 &HT;    Most of those closing doors belonged to movie studios, where she
was told again and again that the project didn't have enough
commercial potential. Only after three years of studio rejections
did Berry approach HBO.
 &HT;    ``Dorothy was a movie star, not a TV star,'' she says, ``and I
really wanted a movie to reflect her legacy.''
 &HT;    But with its reputation for producing feature-quality films for
television, HBO was interested in Dandridge's unquestionably
dramatic story, which includes her meteoric rise to success but
also two failed marriages, the birth of a mentally retarded
daughter, drug dependency, a devastating love affair with director
Otto Preminger and, finally, death by a drug overdose in 1965 at
only 42.
 &HT;    Berry hasn't had to face the kind of racism Dandridge battled
daily _ even at the height of her popularity as one of America's
most successful nightclub performers, she was not allowed to stay
in some hotels which booked her act. She often was denied access to
backstage restrooms, and was forced to use service entrances to
reach the stage.
 &HT;    But Berry believes that it was Dandridge and people like her who
made it possible for her to be what she is today _ a successful
actress, model and now producer.
 &HT;    ``Dorothy lived that I can be where I am,'' she says. ``She
passed the ball, and now I pass it. That's how evolution works.''
 &HT;    Making the movie is part of her effort to pass that ball, Berry
adds.
 &HT;    ``I really want to feel that I have made a contribution,'' she
says. ``One day after I am gone, I want someone sitting in an
interview to say, `Because Halle Berry lived, I was better able to
do this. Because of her, I am afforded this opportunity.'''
 &HT;    Berry has had her own encounters with racism, of course. Her
celebrity status as one of the world's most beautiful women shields
her from many slights and insults suffered by the less famous, but
she remembers many episodes in her youth.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I've had my share,'' she says, ``especially since my
mother was white.''
 &HT;    The actress' maternal grandparents stopped speaking to their
daughter after her marriage to a black man. Only after her parents
separated did her grandparents come back into the picture. Her
mother moved Halle and her older sister, still children, out of
Cleveland's inner city and into an all-white suburb.
 &HT;    ``It was the best thing for us, but it made it difficult because
I was so different from everybody else,'' Berry recalls. ``I got a
lot of `How can you be this when your mother's that?'
 &HT;    ``I know a lot of interracial kids who won't tell you they're
black,'' she continues. ``They'll say, `I'm ``other'' _ I'm mixed.
I'm just as white as I am black.'
 &HT;    ``And on one level that's true,'' Berry adds. ``But unless you
want to walk around with a sign on your head that says, `Hey, I'm
half-white,' nobody is going to treat you that way. They may not
treat you better anyway.
 &HT;    ``My mother taught me early on that it's how you are perceived
by the world, not what you really are.''
 &HT;    An honors student in junior high school, Berry was voted class
president, head cheerleader and editor of the school newspaper, but
when she was also elected prom queen the principal, Mr. Morrelli,
accused her of stuffing the ballot box _ a humiliating accusation
which still stings.
 &HT;    But Berry got sweet revenge by winning the Miss Teen Ohio
pageant, then the Miss Teen America pageant and then the Miss Ohio
pageant. In 1986 she was first runner-up in the Miss America
pageant.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to go to Mr. Morrelli and say, `Who stuffed the
ballot boxes this time?''' she admits. ``But I didn't. I felt the
point had been made.''
 &HT;    The pageant led to a modeling career, which in turn led to
acting. Her television debut was in ``Living Dolls,'' a
not-especially-inspired series about four models that was cancelled
after 13 episodes.
 &HT;    Nonetheless Berry was intrigued by acting, and the television
credit helped get her in to audition for Spike Lee's film ``Jungle
Fever'' (1991).
 &HT;    She'd been brought in to read for the part of a yuppie-ish,
middle-class wife, but she was more interested in the less
glamorous role of a strung-out drug addict.
 &HT;    ``I'd like to read for the role of the crackhead instead,'' she
told Lee.
 &HT;    The director agreed and, after a quick trip to the bathroom to
remove all her makeup, Berry did a reading that landed her the part
_ and transformed her career almost overnight.
 &HT;    ``It allowed me to shed all the beauty-modeling stuff,'' she
says, ``and show people I had been studying acting and could do
it.''
 &HT;    ``Losing Isaiah'' (1995), in which she co-starred with Jessica
Lange in a child-custody drama, earned her more respect, though the
film, like ``Jungle Fever,'' didn't do well commercially.
 &HT;    Since then, however, she's found few meaty roles _ which is, of
course, part of her motivation for developing her own projects.
Meantime, she continues to make high-profile Hollywood films: Her
next, to be filmed in Canada in the autumn, is ``The X-Men,'' an
action picture based on the popular comic-book series.
 &HT;    Her maiden voyage as a producer has whetted Berry's appetite for
more behind-the-scenes duties, but next time she thinks she'll look
for a project she won't be starring in.
 &HT;    ``I want to enjoy each role to the fullest, and when you are
doing both you really can't,'' she says. ``When I'm producing I'd
like to just be thinking about the money and stuff, and not have to
worry about character and emotion. Conversely, when I was Dorothy I
didn't want to break and think about Halle's stuff.
 &HT;    ``As a producer, though, when they come to you and say, `We
don't have any more money, what are we going to do?' ... well, I
had to stop being Dorothy and come back to 1999.''
 c.1999 Jean Oppenheimer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jean Oppenheimer is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge,'' consult the HBO Website at www.hbo.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
