<HEADER>
A0424 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELLIE-MARTIN-IN-ER-S     08-09 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLIE-MARTIN-IN-ER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLIE MARTIN'S UNPREDICTABLE ROAD TO `ER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kellie Martin with Juliana Margulies in
a scene from ``ER.'') 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to be a fan of a hit television show _ at least if you
suddenly find yourself hired to join the cast of that show.
</P>
<P>
   Kellie Martin, for example, had been a longtime aficionado of
the top-rated series ``ER'' before being cast as bumbling but
precocious medical student Lucy Knight for the show's 1998/99
season.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't hard to convey Lucy's awkward nervousness, she admits,
because that's exactly what Martin herself was feeling when she
found herself standing next to actors she'd admired for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a definite parallel for me in there,'' Martin says,
``because Lucy was intimidated by a lot of things at the beginning,
and it's the same thing with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked onto the `ER' set that first day, and I felt I had
never acted a day in my life,'' she admits. ``I was intimidated by
the people I was working with, because I had watched `ER' for
years. I totally forgot I had been acting since I was 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Things eventually settled down for character and actress alike
in their rookie ``ER'' season. It helped that Martin's character
was kept hopping: Among other developments, Lucy received an
instant baptism in emergency-room medicine, battled a
prescription-drug addiction and even had a brief romantic interlude
with her medical mentor/nemesis, Dr. John Carter (Noah Wyle).
</P>
<P>
   ``Those scenes with Carter were the best, because they're such
opposites in many ways,'' she says. ``Carter drives her nuts,
because he tries to be so damn perfect _ and Lucy is a lot looser,
but she still puts a lot of pressure on herself. Toward the end of
the season Lucy had learned to stand up for herself more, and
that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, though Martin only recently turned 24, she's still
been acting for longer than most of her ``ER'' co-stars. When she
was 7, her aunt _ who worked as a governess for actor/producer
Michael Landon _ showed Landon a picture of her niece. That led to
a guest role on Landon's series ``Father Murphy,'' which was
followed by offers to appear in commercials and other dramatic
series.
</P>
<P>
   A child star had been born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acting was definitely an extracurricular activity for me,''
Martin says with a shrug. ``Some kids played soccer, some kids
played tennis, I worked on TV shows. It was just what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Her breakthrough came in 1989, when the 13-year-old was cast in
the earnest ABC dramatic series ``Life Goes On.'' As Rebecca
Thatcher, she earned an Emmy nomination as the loving sister to a
brother (Chris Burke) with Down Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unique because we did a lot of things that other shows
don't have the guts to do,'' Martin says. ``We had an HIV-positive
character, and I don't think anyone has ever dealt with Down
Syndrome the way we did. To this day, people come up to me and tell
me that one of their family has Down Syndrome. I think the show
really made a difference in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   After four seasons of ``Life Goes On,'' Martin graduated to her
own series _ ``Christy,'' about a headstrong young woman who heads
off to teach in the rugged Tennessee foothills, circa 1912.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard-core,'' she recalls. ``I was living in Tennessee
in a town of 200 people and working 14 to 16 hours a day. I was in
every scene. I actually fell asleep once in the middle of a scene!
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I had been away from my family,'' she
adds. ``And I had to wear a corset, which didn't help anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Christy'' faded after a half season, after which Martin became
a fixture on the television-movie circuit in the early 1990s. She
specialized in traumatized characters, playing the teen killer of a
cheerleader in the fact-based ``A Friend to Die For'' (1994), a
battered wife in ``If Someone Had Known'' (1995), a drug addict in
``Her Last Chance'' (1996) and a deaf woman with abusive parents in
``Breaking Through'' (1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``During the period when I made a lot of TV movies, they were
all about issues and true stories,'' she says. ``I thought all
those issues were really important. I don't want to do any TV
movies now, unless it's something really important.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Martin enrolled at Yale University in New Haven, Ct.,
and _ except for an occasional summer-vacation movie and a brief,
quickly canceled series, ``Crisis Center'' _ stopped acting
entirely. It wasn't an easy decision, she says, but it was the only
way she could survive at college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day at Yale was tough,'' she admits, ``whether it was
trying to make friends or learning how to study for a final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' she explains, ``the entire time I was in high
school, it was with a tutor on a set. I never went to a regular
school. Students at Yale already know how to study or how to write
an essay. I didn't have those basics, and I had to learn them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she did what she had to do, and had made it to her
junior year when she got a telephone call from ``ER'' executive
producer John Wells. It was an offer she couldn't pass up, even
though it necessitated a temporary hiatus in her college education.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she says, things happened so quickly that she's still
sorting out everything that went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he asked me to be on the show, all I knew was that my
character would be a medical student,'' the actress says. ``That
was a month before I started filming, so I had no idea what they
wanted to do with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin didn't rush out to spend time with real-life medics in
preparation for the role, as many actors do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' she says. ``I know enough med students that I can call
up and ask questions. I already knew what it was like to be a
student, and we have a doctor on set at all times, so they can
explain the details.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays Martin spends her time away from the set basking in
nuptial bliss. Earlier this summer she married her longtime beau,
Yale Law School graduate Keith Christian, in a storybook New
England wedding, with her ``Life Goes On'' co-star Patti LuPone
singing at the reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part about being married is that I get to see my
husband every day,'' she says happily. ``Keith is taking the bar
exams this summer, and he already knows he's clerking for a judge
next year. He's Mr. Make Plans _ he would map out his whole life if
he could. But then he married me, so now he can't.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 20 years in show business, Martin says, she's
learned never to make long-range plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have and I never will, because you can't count on
them,'' she says firmly. ``I signed a six-year contract with `ER,'
but the ball is always in their court. If they choose not to renew
my contract at any time, they are allowed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I hope that never happens,'' she says with a glint
of a fan's zeal, ``because I'm on the best show on television.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor of TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``ER,'' consult the NBC Website
at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York Times
Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0439 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN10-COX     08-09 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    May we live with interesting candidates
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The spectacle of TV schlockmeister Jerry
Springer running for the Ohio U.S. Senate seat could be more fun
than a stageful of transvestite biker-bar strippers in leather
begging their boyfriends' forgiveness for secret affairs with rodeo
clowns.
</P>
<P>
   And in the process, it would represent a milestone in the merger
of celebrity entertainment and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Springer is still noncommittal about the job. A former mayor of
Cincinnati, he has more experience in elected office than Ross
Perot, Jesse Ventura, Steve Forbes and Florida Gov. Jeb Bush
combined.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible opinion nevertheless is aghast. But responsible
opinion is like Margaret Dumont in Marx Brothers' movies. It exists
to be aghast. That's its role.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible opinion wants bread without circuses. It wants
high-fiber policy discussions. It wants sober-minded debate. It
wants to pay down the deficit, slow global warming, think in the
long-term and find bipartisan common ground. And I want to agree
with it. I really, really do.
</P>
<P>
   But I am also a newspaper columnist. And the reptilian part of
my brain that allows me to perform that function says only one
thing, over and over:
</P>
<P>
   Jer-REE, Jer-REE, Jer-REE ...
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate has precious few chantable names. Nearly half
the body _ 48 members out of 100 _ have one-syllable names. We are
run by Jims, Tims, Bobs and Johns. Especially Johns. Eight senators
are Johns or Jons, enough to form a serious voting block. Almost
enough to form a softball team. Of the names remaining, none is
chantable.
</P>
<P>
   Orr-IN, Orr-IN, Orr-IN ...
</P>
<P>
   See, it just doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   But a name you can chant is only a small advantage for a
candidate. The name needs to be attached to a person who can get
the crowd out of their folding chairs. That's where the current
political field falls short.
</P>
<P>
   This is not necessarily a bad thing. On one level, we should be
reassured by the number of bland and short-named candidates among
us. The old Chinese curse, ``may you live in interesting times''
has a corollary in politics _ may you live with interesting
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of entire slates of lively, colorful candidates
with lurid nicknames should keep us up at night. That would take a
national crisis. The return of '60s and worse.
</P>
<P>
   These are prosperous, easygoing times. A time for preventive
maintenance, not revolution. It takes a boring candidate to step up
to that job. The kind of candidate who promises to be a good
listener, a compassionate conservative, a practical idealist, a
regular guy for regular times. Someone who, like Warren G. Harding,
promises ``not nostrums but normalcy ... not surgery but
serenity.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, such a public mood would bode ill for Springer's
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Except there is another trend at work. The wall between show
business and the public's business _ always lightly mortared and
missing a few bricks _ has fallen altogether. Ronald Reagan took on
this wall before he could turn his attention to the Berlin Wall.
Ventura's surprise election last year proved that even the loud and
stagy, low-rent theatrics of professional wrestling translate well
from the squared circle to political circles.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura crashed through the wall like a character in a Warner
Brothers cartoon, leaving a candidate-shaped opening anyone else
might stroll through.
</P>
<P>
   Jes-EEE, Jes-EEE, Jes-EEE ...
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who can both run for governor and be marketed as an
action figure is formidable, indeed. By contrast, an Al Gore action
figure would be a contradiction in terms. (Its knees bend so it can
sit politely and stand up straight!)
</P>
<P>
   Al-LLL, Al-LLL, Al-LLL ... Just can't be done.
</P>
<P>
   In post-Ventura America, any celebrity candidacy appears a
reasonable option. Why should Springer be any different? It's not
as though a Senate that holds the likes of Jesse Helms would get
too much stranger. Would Springer really be much hammier than
Robert Byrd? Are the fights on Springer's show much more staged
than the matchups on C-SPAN?
</P>
<P>
   It is not a stretch to imagine him there. They could have used
him during the impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Jer-REE, Jer-REE, Jer-REE ...
</P>
<P>
   That's the sound of columnists chanting, and they don't have
everyone's best interests in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is associate editor at The Daytona Beach News-Journal.
He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
