<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enjoying the Bahamas, onboard
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHUB CAY, Bahamas _ My shipmates can't believe it. Here we are
in the lap of paradise _ pink and white sand beaches and water so
clear that 30 feet down looks like the bottom of my bathtub, and I
don't want to get off the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just swing your legs over the side and slip into the water.
I'll catch you,'' my friend offers. I shake my head and tell him if
I wanted to, I could dive in and swim, but that I'm just not in the
mood right now. He tells me diving would not be a good idea unless
I intend to make like a clam and bury myself in the sand. He points
to the water gently lapping at his kneecaps. I should be
embarrassed but I'm not. I'm too busy making a fool of myself.
</P>
<P>
   The sun is lowering in the afternoon sky as our little boat
rides at anchor on a pristine beach at an uninhabited island in the
Berry chain. It's Shangri-la, the Garden of Eden without apples;
it's a trip most folks would mortgage their kids for, and I won't
get out of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Just the morning before, we had left the marina on Harbour
Island where we'd spent an idyllic week sipping rum and coke and
listening to the fish fry, and aimed the big boat toward an 11-mile
stretch of reef-strewn treachery known as The Devil's Backbone. We
were taking the shortcut to Spanish Wells to refuel before we set
out for Chub Cay, a little spit of land at the southern end of the
Berry Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Having already read the 1999 Yachtsman's Guide to the Bahamas, I
knew what we were getting into. ``The passage (Devil's Backbone)
must be attempted in good light, when the reefs are visible, and
under favorable weather conditions.'' It recommends hiring a local
pilot to take you through and warns that in northerly conditions it
is impassable.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I remained fearless. My old friends have been
navigating these waters half their lives. I know Richard isn't
going to risk ripping open the bottom of his boat on a slightly
submerged coral head, and I know Jeanne, his wife and my best
friend, can't swim. Besides, it isn't drowning I fear, although I'd
rather not. What scares the hell out of me is having my feet touch
the bottom and the subsequent host of yukky critters that live
there.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday I was an intrepid mariner.
</P>
<P>
   Today is a different story. ``Don't you want to see the Blue
Hole?'' Jeanne asks, trying to coax me into the water. I shake my
head because I really don't. ``There's a path from the beach,'' she
assures me. ``Real wide and not long. You'll love it.'' I know I
won't but I want to be a good sport so they'll ask me back again. I
give in and swing a tennis-shoed foot over the side. Artfully, I
dodge a couple of killer starfish and make it to shore. Richard
goes first, then Jeanne. I insist on being next so my friend can
guard my flank (read that
</P>
<P>
   however you like).
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you, I have seen wider paths than this one beaten to
brand new outhouses, and the jungle is closing in on me. ``Are we
there yet?'' I whine at every turn. Jeanne assures me it's just a
little further and Richard warns me not to step on the curly-tailed
lizards.
</P>
<P>
   A light year later, I emerge at the rim of a big hole only to
discover it's black, not blue. Jeanne leans over to check it out
and loses her sunglasses. In the meantime, an armada of crazed
mosquitoes has attacked in an attempt to bleed us dry before we can
get back to the beach. We escape, but each of us is a pint low.
</P>
<P>
   On the run back to the marina, I have managed to stay pretty
busy whimpering and scratching myself, but in an effort to make
like a tourist I point to a large island to starboard and ask
Richard if it has a name. ``Cockroach Cay,'' he answers. I ask why
it's called that. His only answer is a wicked grin.
</P>
<P>
   I just hope it's not on next year's itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
