<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL's campus is a quiet happening
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like Alice in Wonderland, I had a chance to step
behind the America Online sign-on screen and see what life was like
at the company's headquarters in Dulles, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, AOL doesn't call it a headquarters. It's a campus.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear if AOL has extended its rivalry with Microsoft _
which also calls its headquarters a campus _ onto the real estate
front. But the AOL campus is big. There are two very large
buildings and two more being built.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you notice is how quiet it is. The only noises
are people typing and the infamous ``you've got mail'' and
instant-message chimes ringing out from the endless rows of
cubicles and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every computer screen is cluttered with open mailboxes
and stacks of instant-message screens. One AOL executive said he
seldom answers his phone or checks his voice mail. Amenities for
staffers include a gym, concierge service (where there are people
who will dash out to pick up employees' kids or dry cleaning), a
cafeteria and a gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   The second thing you notice is the decor. It's steel, glass and
Italian modern (and oddly shaped) couches, chairs and computer
chairs. The cool computer workstations are oak with sharp black
accents.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to check your e-mail or surf the Web here, come
armed with an AOL account, because that's the only way you'll get
online. The computers the company makes available for visitors in
the lobby don't even have a stand-alone version of the Netscape
browser, although tour guides are careful to walk visitors past the
office of Netscape creator Marc Andressen _ now an AOL employee.
They deliberately point it out as if to say, ``Yeah, here's the guy
who developed the idea of the Web browser in the first place, but
he works for us now. So there.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL and its employees all seem to radiate a sense of confidence,
self-satisfaction, entitlement and inevitability that is
breathtaking. And why not? They work for the No. 1 online service
in the world, with 17 million subscribers and an estimated 20
million users.
</P>
<P>
   The company's closest competition _ if you can even call it
competition _ is from Internet service providers that average
anywhere from 1 million to 2 million subscribers. Atlanta-based
MindSpring would be in that pack.
</P>
<P>
   Sniffing at numbers like that, Matt Korn, AOL's network
operations senior vice president, estimates that about 2 million
people are online on AOL at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the long hallways and winding rows of cubicles
and offices talking with the people who make AOL happen, it is
clear the company didn't reach the 17 million subscriber mark by
wishing and hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the olden days of AOL, the company wowed computer users
by creating an online service that would let people talk to each
other in real time. This single concept, now known as chat, has
become a staple of any successful Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   AOL also pioneered the instant-messaging service. The fact that
Microsoft has developed a similar technology, a cornerstone of
AOL's service for years, has sent AOL into a frenzy for a variety
of reasons both monetary and personal. It's pretty simple to figure
out: AOL thought of it first, lots of people like it, now the
copycats come in.
</P>
<P>
   The senior vice president and general manager of AOL's
interactive services, Jonathan Sacks, says the service is all about
communication on a variety of levels that include not just instant
messaging but chat, e-mail and message boards as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of ways to think about what AOL is,'' he says.
``I think of what can we do to make people's lives easier. We used
to think people just wanted to surf the Web. Now we know they want
to see the benefits of being online. They want to know `How can I
communicate better?' `How can I make my life less complicated?'
`How can I help my kids do better in school?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sacks and most of the decision-makers at AOL know there are
thousands of things to do online.
</P>
<P>
   They also know AOL's killer application is connecting real
people to other real people in real time.
</P>
<P>
   As its members become more sophisticated, AOL has developed new
products to help people stay in touch, even while they're pumping
gas. Another product its getting ready to roll out is the AOL
calendar, which allows groups of friends or business associates to
keep up with changing plans for everything from a soccer match to a
business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody in Dulles can stop talking about ``You've Got
Pictures,'' a partnership with Kodak and 38,000 retailers across
the country to let members have their family photos sent to AOL to
be put online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers have to have a comfort level,'' Sacks says.
``AOL should be like coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   Bless their hearts, the folks at AOL can't imagine why anyone
would want to live anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
