r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN10-CO     08-09 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net freedom issues shaded in gray
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few things are more fun in the infancy of this mass
communications renaissance than a little piece of free software
with big ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Zimmermann's standoff with the U.S. government a couple
years ago over PGP _ his uncrackable encryption program for e-mail,
which undersells itself as Pretty Good Privacy _ was a thrill to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Zimmermann's software got uploaded to the Internet.
Uncle Sam, citing the threat of cyber-terrorism and other
techno-scenarios designed to scare people, wanted the software to
be classified, essentially restricting it from everyday use.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it was already widely distributed across the Net,
and eventually the Justice Department caved in, after threatening
Zimmermann with treason for several years. PGP remains, for the
most part, freely available, and Netizens are allowed to keep their
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Third Voice, which hit the Web at the end of May, is nowhere
near as sophisticated as PGP. But the waters it may stir, and the
basic rights it invokes, run just as deep.
</P>
<P>
   In a simplistic explanation, Third Voice allows any Web surfer
to paste a comment onto any Web page. Any other surfer whose
browser is armed with Third Voice can read the note, render an
addendum expounding on the theme or start a new thread entirely
with a posting of his own. To add a bit of sophistication, notes
can be public, private or personal.
</P>
<P>
   How it works is fairly simple, too. All of the notes _ along
with their positions on the Web page _ are stored on Third Voice
servers. When someone's browser requests a page, the software kicks
in, checking the URL against its database, and displays a copy of
the Web page's HTML code with little icons inserted where the notes
are. Clicking an icon opens the note _ which is stored on the Third
Voice servers _ using the same process. The original Web page code
isn't altered, so the icons are invisible to anyone not using Third
Voice.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the implications of such a program:
</P>
<P>
   People who get ripped off by a company online can warn other
Netizens with a posting right on the offender's home page.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of a particular band or movie could run a Third Voice
thread at the official Web site.
</P>
<P>
   An individual's log-in and password for a Web site can be posted
on a protected note to themselves at the log-in page.
</P>
<P>
   A schoolteacher could leave notes on Web sites she assigns her
class to visit for homework.
</P>
<P>
   Is that cool or what?
</P>
<P>
   Well, some people don't think so _ but that's the stuff that
helps make great philosophical issues fun. Even though Third Voice
is so beta it isn't yet available for Netscape _ coming soon, they
promise _ there's already an opposition party called Say No To
Third Voice, made up of some 400 concerned Web page designers and
developers.
</P>
<P>
   They warn that there are other uses of Third Voice that aren't
so cool:
</P>
<P>
   A vendor could post advertisements on a competitor's site,
offering to undercut prices.
</P>
<P>
   A pornographer could litter hundreds of pages with links to his
Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Obscene rantings could be posted on otherwise pedestrian Web
sites, bloating the Web with even more spam, vulgar spam at that.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. The Net is supposed to be the new global mass
communications medium that gives the power back to the people. It's
the tool that will further the cause of free speech, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a slippery slope.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of other ways _ good and bad _ the program can
be put to use. The Net's teeming hordes will undoubtedly find
several more _ better and worse _ that aren't even apparent yet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Third Voice has already spawned an imitator called
Utok. (The Netscape version of Utok is ready now.) Then there's a
program called Gooey that allows users to open chat windows with
each other while browsing the same site. There's one called Odigo
that does both _ chat windows and notes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting comments I've seen on the issue came
from Jonathan Zittrain, director of the Berkman Center for Internet
&AMP; Society at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arguably, this is the way to draw a mustache on the site,'' he
told Wired magazine, alluding to copyright law that says,
basically, painting a mustache on someone's painting is not
protected under free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' he said, ``if all you're doing is
painting a mustache on a transparency and you look through it, is
that a derivative work?''
</P>
<P>
   There is one point, though, I haven't seen raised about these
kinds of programs that could keep them from ever catching on at the
grass-roots level. In order to work properly, they have to keep
track of your Web surfing movements very closely. That info, as we
all know, is very valuable out on the market.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons it might not catch on, too. If the
signal-to-noise ratio gets too high _ i.e. puerile comments and
advertising spam outweigh useful info _ then no one will use it.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, at this point, the issue is in the hands of the
people to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   Once the virtual cat is out of the virtual bag, there's no
turning back.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Phil Zimmermann.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
