<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A few precautions can keep your computer humming
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I liked home computers best when they were totally
useless beasts.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when my Altair computer _ one that I put together
from a kit and that used toggle switches instead of a keyboard _
acted up (and it did that with the frequency of a spoiled
12-year-old), nothing important was affected. About all I did with
that computer was play a game called ``Life'' that involved
watching tiny dots multiply and then disappear _ by flipping the
toggle switches in just the right combination _ on the screen of
the 13-inch GE TV that I used as a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   I saw how much things had changed this weekend when my home
computer screwed up for reasons that I still do not understand.
</P>
<P>
   In one fell swoop, I lost the ability to exchange e-mails with a
retired nun whom I know very well but have never met; I could no
longer work on the book that I'll never finish; and I was barred
from the only computer game that I play anymore _ an electronic
version of canasta.
</P>
<P>
   Probably you are in the same boat _ you'd miss your computer if
it became an expensive beige paperweight. All electronic devices
are born to die, but there are some really easy things you can do
to postpone that day. So, for today, let's take a look at how to
keep your computer healthy.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, let's get to know two small programs that come
with Windows _ Scan Disk and Defrag _ that provide preventive
maintenance for your hard disk.
</P>
<P>
   Once every week, run Scan Disk _ which finds and sometimes fixes
problems that are going wrong on the hard disk. Then run Defrag.
Think of it as a housekeeper for your hard disk. It finds fragments
of programs that become scattered all over the disk and puts them
back together again.
</P>
<P>
   Just running these two programs on a weekly basis can be a big
factor in keeping your computer healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will make sure that it eats right.
</P>
<P>
   If you hooked a good voltage meter up to your household current,
you'd probably be surprised at how variable the voltage is.
</P>
<P>
   It dips and soars like the stock market on steroids. All those
surges and dips can do harm to a PC. They won't toast it like a
lightning strike; instead, they slowly damage the components. Get a
good voltage surge protector (avoid the $14 models that are little
more than fancy extension cords), or better yet, get an
uninterruptible power supply.
</P>
<P>
   This gadget, universally referred to as a UPS, both filters the
current before it gets to your computer and then _ when the power
goes out _ automatically switches to battery power so you can shut
down your computer normally. A UPS was once too pricey for all but
business users, but now you can get one for a little over $100. Do
it _ that's cheap insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I've told you some things that you should do, let's
talk about some stuff not to do.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't turn your PC on and off every time you use it. Leave it
on until you're done with it for the night. Turning the machine on
and off creates current surges that can age components.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't block ventilation holes in the PC or on the monitor.
(Some folks pile papers on top of the monitor. I once saw an
impressive monitor fire right here in the newsroom because of
that.) When it comes to the PC, keep it several inches away from
the sides of a desk or a wall _ or from anything that might block
its intake of air.
</P>
<P>
   _ Periodically open up the case of the PC and look for
accumulations of dust inside. While the case is open, firmly reseat
internal modem cards and any other accessory cards.
</P>
<P>
   The contacts on these cards expand and contract with heat and
cooling and can work themselves loose, creating intermittent
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
