<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shareware, freeware simple to find
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If butcher shops worked the same way as shareware
software, then you'd be able to take a nice roast home and serve it
to your family. Then _ if everyone thought it made a pretty good
meal _ you'd pay for the roast.
</P>
<P>
   Shareware is software that you can download for free, use and,
if you decide to keep it, send in the money. There's also a
category of software called freeware that you also download for
free, but you never pay a penny.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any type of program, from games to word processors, from
spreadsheets to weird little special purpose programs, is
available. There's shareware for the Mac, PCs, Linux _ almost any
type of operating system or computer you can name is represented.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays most shareware is distributed over the Internet. It's a
perfect distribution system for software of this type, since the
whole idea is to keep the overhead low. Even if you decide to keep
and use a program, the fees are usually small, often in the $20 to
$25 range.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best sites for shareware is at a place called _
appropriately enough _ Shareware.Com (www.shareware.com). Just use
the pull-down menu on the start page to tell it the type of
computer system you are running. Even if you have an Atari or an
Amiga computer, you'll find a selection that's right for your
machine and software.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can use the search feature and a keyword or two to find
your software. Or perhaps you aren't looking for a specific program
but would like to see what's available in a category like games.
You'll find links that take you to shareware libraries organized
according to topic.
</P>
<P>
   Our next site is called Pass the Shareware, located at www
</P>
<P>
   .passtheshareware.com/. This place is really a search engine
that searches various download areas on the Web to help you find
the program you want. The selling point for Pass the Shareware is
that it supposedly searches only for the best available shareware
programs. A claim like that is difficult to evaluate without
thousands of uses.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice feature of this site is a special link that takes
you to sites for freeware. That way, if you want to avoid spending
any money at all, you can restrict your search to freeware.
</P>
<P>
   If _ like many computer users _ you spend most of your computer
time using the Internet, you really need to know about Tucows. When
it comes to freeware and shareware for the Internet, this site at
www.tucows.com/ is simply the best there is.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find Internet programs grouped according to category, and
each has a Tucows rating _ sort of a minireview _ that lets you
know how the gurus at this site view a program. Obviously, you'll
find common programs like Web browsers, FTP programs, newsgroup
readers and e-mail applications here.
</P>
<P>
   But since this site specializes in Internet stuff, it's very
deep. You'll find really esoteric Net software here, too: programs
that let you trace the route to a Web site, programs that time
response time on the Net and other stuff so specialized that you
practically need a degree in computer science to know how to use
it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, CNet's Download.Com is also a great place for general
purpose shareware services. You'll find it at www.download.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
