<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer filled with floods and droughts
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ People in Asia are struggling to recover from weeks of
summer flooding. At least 900 have been killed and millions left
homeless. In Southeast Asia, more monsoon rains are predicted,
which may cause more flooding, as residents begin to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in the United States, many farmers on the East Coast
are suffering a lack of rain. Maryland, facing its worst drought in
70 years, has shut down car washes, turned off fountains and banned
lawn watering. Delaware declared a drought emergency and imposed
restrictions on two-thirds of its residents. Officials in New
Jersey, New York and West Virginia also are cutting water use and
trying to assist farmers.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is expected to declare a drought this week. Last
year's summer was so dry for South Carolina farmers that the state
was declared a federal disaster.
</P>
<P>
   HAVE DOG, WILL TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old William Dowell is back in England after a
kidney transplant and cancer treatments in France. And his dog,
Cassis, is home, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cassis traveled across the English Channel on the first of
Britain's new pet passports. The passport certified that Cassis is
rabies-free and made it unnecessary for the dog to stay in
quarantine for six months, as English law used to require.
</P>
<P>
   William wrote a letter to England's prime minister, Tony Blair,
asking that the 100-year-old law be changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I was worried I may never see Cassis again _ which
could go two ways because dogs die in quarantine, so it wasn't just
me,'' explained William.
</P>
<P>
   Each passport certifies that the pet has a tiny ID microchip
implanted, has been vaccinated against rabies and has been treated
for ticks and tapeworms.
</P>
<P>
   VIEW THE SOLAR ECLIPSE
</P>
<P>
   If you've always wanted to see a solar eclipse, but just haven't
been around long enough _ the last total solar eclipse in the
United States took place in 1979 _ here's your chance.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the Discovery Network this Wednesday for three hours
of live eclipse coverage. The cable channel's cameras will follow
the 70-mile-wide path where the sun is totally obscured by the
moon, from southern England, through France, Germany, Austria,
Hungary, Romania to the Middle East and its conclusion near India.
</P>
<P>
   Eclipse coverage runs from 6 a.m. to 9 a.m., with an hourlong
wrap-up that night at 10.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
