<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good things happening for Braves' Brian Jordan
 &HT;    By Andy Staples
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves outfielder Brian Jordan finally is getting his
due.
</P>
<P>
   Last year as a St. Louis Cardinal, Jordan did not make the
All-Star team even though he had the highest batting average in the
National League at the All-Star break. This year, he made the team
when NL manager Bruce Bochy named him as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   From 1989 to 1991, Jordan also played safety for the Atlanta
Falcons. But Jordan feared one bad move in football could cost him
his career. He decided in 1992 to play baseball only.
</P>
<P>
   The injury bug has caught him in baseball, though, and he has
had to miss recent games because of a pinched nerve in his neck and
a sore hand.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan does not like sitting and he promises he will come back
stronger than ever from his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   NFK caught a chat with Jordan:
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did it feel making the All-Star team this year after not
making it last year?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a new team and a new beginning, and I finally got
rewarded. Of course, I was upset last year about not making it. But
if you continue to work hard, good things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did it feel to step on the field in Boston for the
All-Star Game?
</P>
<P>
   A: It felt great. The first day of practice with all the media,
it just felt like I was back in St. Louis with Mark McGwire. The
day of the game, when you saw all the great players _ the century's
best _ that's when it was like ``Wow, I'm on the All-Star team.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How frustrating are these recent injuries?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've tried to play through the pain. I'd see how I was
performing, and it was really bothering me more than I'd like. I
finally had to get it checked out. You hate missing games,
especially when you lose a player for the whole year. (Pitcher
Odalis Perez and catcher Javy Lopez will miss the rest of the
season because of injuries.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did you decide to quit playing football?
</P>
<P>
   A: You last a lot longer in baseball. I can play this game a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
