<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book recounts AOL's bumpy rise to top
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kara Swisher's best seller, ``AOL.Com,'' has been
released in paperback. The book tells the story of the turbulent
rise of America Online as it became the largest online service.
</P>
<P>
   For AOL, the road to success was rocky from the start. The book
tells the story of how the company kept changing business lines and
products _ until it finally hit on the idea of a mass-market online
service. Even then, the going was rough for most of the company's
history.
</P>
<P>
   The August issue of Yahoo Internet Life takes on the issue of
music on the Internet. You'll find interviews with such Net music
pioneers as the Beastie Boys and Sarah McLachlan. The magazine also
includes more-intellectual fare, such as stories about copyright
protection on the Net and the financial prospects of distribution
music online.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   IBM has released an updated version of its electronic coloring
book program, ``Crayola.'' The latest version is called ``Crayola
Magic 3D Coloring Book Favorite Places'' and includes 100 pages to
color in 3-D. The selection includes color-by-the-numbers pages and
those that involve connecting the dots. Available only for PCs with
Windows 95 or higher, ``Crayola'' retails for about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel has released its latest Barbie computer CD, this one
featuring sports activities. Called ``Barbie Super Sports,'' it
features Barbie snowboarding and inline skating. She can compete
against others in either sport on five different tracks. When
Barbie wins, she gets to pick out new clothes from the sport shop
as a reward. ``Barbie Super Sports'' is available only for PCs with
Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   It's summertime, and the trivia comes easy. Especially on the
Net. Here's a site that offers lots of fun but admittedly useless
info. The site is called _ you guessed it _ Useless Knowledge.com.
At Useless Knowledge.com, you can find out such things as the fact
that Lily and Herman Munster were the first TV couple to be shown
sleeping in the same bed. Another tidbit on the site is the fact
that France _ not Scotland _ invented the kilt. You get the
picture. Useless Knowledge.com can be found at www
</P>
<P>
   .uselessknowledge.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
