</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHREPORT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intel microscope ready for school
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Intel has a handful of new products for the child or
young adult heading back to school.
</P>
<P>
   The QX3 computer microscope, which sells for about $100, is a
digital microscope that lets users magnify and display microscopic
images on their PC screen and then manipulate those images.
</P>
<P>
   The microscope and software, developed by Intel and Mattel, let
users create still and moving images as well as time-lapse movies.
The images can be printed in the form of posters and stickers. They
can also be used to make on-screen slides, video shows and image
files that can be sent as e-mail attachments.
</P>
<P>
   The microscope and software are expected to be in stores by
October.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel PC Camera Pack is a combination camera and videophone.
The software lets users make videophone calls over broadband and
dial-up Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   The device requires that the person with whom you are
communicating also have the same product, which makes it a kind of
PC walkie-talkie. But the camera pack comes with a free,
ready-to-mail CD with an extra copy of the videophone software.
</P>
<P>
   The camera pack, designed to make it interesting for college
students to phone home, will sell for about $80 once it reaches
stores in November.
</P>
<P>
   SITE AIDS IN DESIGNING WEDDING ANNOUNCEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Web sites help people make plane reservations, buy cars, order
best sellers. Now the level of detail is getting a bit more
specific. An Orlando, Fla.-based Web site is putting the act of
designing and ordering wedding announcements on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.ourbeginning.com, was launched in March. It lets
you pick stationery by style, theme, presentation and color.
Another part lets you search by manufacturer and model number, in
case you saw a style in a store and wanted to compare prices.
</P>
<P>
   Other features include ``Ask Susan,'' a question-and-answer
wedding consulting and etiquette guide, and a personal preview,
which lets you create a page of your favorite choices that can be
viewed by others.
</P>
<P>
   OurBeginning.com delivers orders in seven business days.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCHERS SPEED UP CHIPS BY STACKING THEM
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Purdue University have developed a way to make
computer chips smaller and faster. The idea is to stack the chips
in an unlimited number of layers.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional way of making chips shapes the silicon in
several steps. The new method, epitaxial growth, grows the silicon
into distinct ``islands'' that extend vertically, linking up with
the next layer. The resulting chip has several layers of
transistors with short connections, which makes for a faster,
denser circuit. Fast circuits make faster chips, which make faster
PCs.
</P>
<P>
   NET-SAVVY DO SOME HOUSE-HUNTING ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   If you're already Internet-savvy and in the market for real
estate, chances are you will use the Web during your search,
according to a new online study by NPD Online Research.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted in June, involved 2,355 people from NPD's
Web panel, a group recruited on the Web to participate in Web-based
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 88 percent of those who have browsed the
Web for property said they looked for residential real estate
online.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent looked for houses, 11 percent sought
condominiums and 2 percent were interested in co-ops. Among the
online house-hunters, 42 percent were looking for their first home.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the searches do not lead to actual meetings with
Realtors and actual purchases, however. Among those polled, 19
percent said they went to a Realtor, and 7 percent said they bought
property they saw on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Those polled said convenience was the main reason they
house-hunted on the Web. Fewer people, about 38 percent, said they
searched online because of the huge selection.
</P>
<P>
   Homes selling for less than $200,000 were the ones visited most
often by online house hunters. The study found that Realtor.com and
century21.com were the Web sites most often visited by the sample
group.
</P>
<P>
   NPD Online Research is a division of the NPD Group, a marketing
information company in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
