<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ To listen to talk radio shows from
around the country in the days after the Atlanta massacre was to be
very afraid for the future of this country. For while there were
individual exceptions and no doubt some exceptional shows, too, the
overwhelming cry was for more guns. What this country needs is a
citizenry armed and cocked to shoot. To hear talk radio tell it,
the sure-fire answer to gun play is more gun play. (Teepen, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Weren't we supposed to have
robots following us around by now, protecting us with their
metallic arms and helping with the housework?
</P>
<P>
   (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ CHUB CAY, Bahamas _ My shipmates can't believe
it. Here we are in the lap of paradise _ pink and white sand
beaches and water so clear that 30 feet down looks like the bottom
of my bathtub, and I don't want to get off the boat. I should be
embarrassed but I'm not. I'm too busy making a fool of myself.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ In post-Ventura America, any celebrity candidacy
appears a reasonable option. Why should Jerry Springer be any
different? It's not as though a Senate that holds the likes of
Jesse Helms would get too much stranger. Would Springer really be
much hammier than Robert Byrd? Are the fights on Springer's show
much more staged than the matchups on C-SPAN? It is not a stretch
to imagine him there. They could have used him during the
impeachment hearings. Jer-REE, Jer-REE, Jer-REE ... (Lane, Daytona
Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
