<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I have an odd-jobs man I pay about $50 a
week. Surely I need to do something regarding taxes and Social
Security, but what? Can you guide me?
</P>
<P>
   _ H.J. Hewitt
</P>
<P>
   A: Your odd-jobs man sounds like an independent contractor to
me. If he is, then he is responsible for his own taxes and Social
Security payments, not you. As an independent contractor this
odd-jobber is the same as the pest control man or a landscape
service. Kenneth Vargas of the IRS notes some of the signs that you
are paying an independent contractor: provides service for others
besides you; uses his own equipment (hammer, nails, etc.); and is
not required to work set, scheduled hours. Q: I recently handled a
real estate sale for an elderly gentleman whose Social Security
card was issued Jan. 27, 1937. Seems to me to be one of the first
groups of cards issued. Can you find out when the government first
issued cards and what the middle two numbers were at the beginning?
_ Don Sanders
</P>
<P>
   A: The newly formed Social Security Administration, having no
field offices, distributed blocks of cards via local post offices
throughout the country. No card should have been issued before Nov.
24, 1936. However, some cards have slightly earlier dates. The
lowest numbers were issued in blocks to New Hampshire. Grace D.
Owen of Concord was issued the first, 001-01-0001. Easy to
remember.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend is moving to Minnesota and needs to store a
refrigerator for a while. She is receiving all sorts of advice on
the best way to store it. Do you have any ideas? _ J.F.
</P>
<P>
   A: Clean the inside and outside of the appliance thoroughly with
vinegar or with baking soda and water. Dry well. Empty any
reservoirs such as the water dispenser or ice maker. Store the unit
in a dry area where the climate is controlled (this one might be
tough in Minnesota). The temperature should not dip below 50
degrees for extended periods of time. Leave the doors ajar. The
accumulated dust is a small price to pay for preventing the plastic
smell. Cover the unit with cloth, not plastic, to prevent moisture
buildup and rust. If you are an odor overachiever, place crew socks
filled with coffee grounds, charcoal or baking soda inside the
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My question is about ``The Mod Squad'' television show from
the '60s and '70s. In its first season, what kind of station wagon
did the three characters travel in? _ Robert G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Julie, Pete and Linc were tooling around Los Angeles in a
station wagon named Woody. On this much many agree. I found one
``Squad''-o-phile who insists the wagon was a two-door Mercury
station wagon, 1951 vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recently deceased friend left everything in his will to his
sister and a friend. The named beneficiary of his retirement fund,
however, is someone else. On several occasions he specifically told
me and several other people that this retirement money should also
go to his sister and his friend. The retirement beneficiary plans
to claim the money. Doesn't the will supercede everything else? _
R.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: This is a common problem. A will does not change the named
beneficiaries of retirement funds and life insurance policies, says
Duncan Osborne, board certified attorney in estate planning and
probate law. When reviewing assets during the estate planning
process, clients have to be reminded repeatedly to change the
beneficiary names on these accounts, notes Osborne. All the
witnessed declarations in the world do not change the named
beneficiary's rights; however, you can always hope the friends and
family of the deceased will honor such wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Someone told me that the new quarters with the states on them
are more valuable or possibly will be in the future than regular
quarters. We have acquired a few recently and my husband wants to
spend them, but I won't let him. I told him you would be able to
settle this! _ J. Martin
</P>
<P>
   A: The coin market, like the stock market, can be fickle. For
example, Brian Owens of Village Coin Shop says a 1995 proof set of
coins when issued sold for $12.50 and today is worth $40. On the
other hand, the 1986 Statue of Liberty silver dollar proof was
issued at $30-$35 and now goes for a mere $8.50. Spend the quarters
you receive in change. Then begin the 10-year task (only five coins
issued each year) of collecting 200 commemorative quarters: the
Philadelphia and Denver uncirculated quarters as well as the proof
issue and 90 percent silver proof issue of each of the 50. Maybe
the collection gods will shine on you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have always written on the backs of our family photos with
a ball-point pen, but I recently read an article that advised
against it. Can you tell me what the concern is? I tried a 6B
pencil, but it doesn't write well on photo paper. Any other
suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   _ K. Witt
</P>
<P>
   A: Lose the pen and the pencil. They mark the photos and do not
last. You need film print marking pens that write on plastic and
film, do not smear, and are acid-free and nonwater soluble. All for
less than $2 a pen.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Skillet aficionados have shared their secrets for cleaning
cast iron when culinary efforts go awry. Jim Washburn puts his
skillet in the oven during the self-cleaning cycle, reducing
burned-on glops to ash. (Make sure you use an old rack since this
cycle damages most oven racks.) Transplanted Louisianan Roxanne
Barrilleaux cleans crusted-on iron skillets by building a safe fire
outside or in the fireplace. When fire and coals are extremely hot,
toss in the pans. The fire bakes off the crusted grease, inside and
out. Reseason the pan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unsolicited faxes clogging your machine? Faxes generally
specify the fax number of the sender. Let the sender know you do
not want to receive these missives and that violations of your
request could result in a payment to you ($500 in damages).
EcoFuture recommends you fax a complaint letter to the advertiser
in 72-point font (1-inch height), which produces, when faxed, for a
typical two-paragraph letter, about 17 or 18 pages of text easily
read from across the room.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
