<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
   Monday, August 9, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-BEES (Houston) _ Little has been said recently about
Africanized bees, which not so long ago were feared as a deadly
scourge invading Texas. If the invasion was indeed stopped, what
stopped them, or did the onslaught simply move to another part of
the United States? By TERRY KLIEWER.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-WAR-VETS (Hesperia, Calif.) _ Ex-Marine Brent Roberts is
one of many ailing Gulf War veterans facing impoverishment. Across
the country, veterans are losing jobs as disabling diseases rob
their bodies of strength, endurance and vitality. By KATHLEEN
SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-STRAWPOLL (Washington) _ The Ames, Iowa, straw poll
Saturday technically means nothing; perceptually, it means almost
everything to the Republican presidential field. The 20-year-old
ceremony has been given new weight by front-runner George W. Bush's
declaration that ``I intend to win.'' Lamar Alexander's struggling
campaign has put all its efforts in to Iowa, and the rest of the
field has been camped there for weeks in preparation for the event.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-NEWSPAPERS (San Francisco) _ The media landscape is shifting.
The regional economy is sizzling. And three newspaper groups are
likely to spend the next few years slugging it out for Bay Area
readers, advertisers and journalistic laurels. By ELIZABETH
FERNANDEZ and VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS-DOWNTOWN (Dallas) _ Along with Atlanta, Dallas is now
listed as one of the top U.S. cities experiencing a boom in
downtown living. Population growth patterns suggest that more
affluent young singles and empty-nest suburbanites yearning for an
urban lifestyle will follow, eventually turning downtown into a
24-hour neighborhood. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOLAR-ECLIPSE (Undated) _ It'll be ``lights out,'' celestially
speaking, for the last time this century when a solar eclipse
Wednesday plunges much of Europe and Asia into darkness. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERGROUND-RAILROAD (New York) _ Brooklyn is a brash,
open-faced place. Yet quieter sanctuaries and secret places here
speak, hauntingly, to one of the nation's most traumatic and
dramatic historic chapters: slavery and the Underground Railroad.
By MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BATHTUB-GLAZE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Wish you could flush your
porcelain, Fiberglas or acrylic tub and vanity sink down the toilet
because the colors are outdated, stained or badly chipped? Don't
worry about buying new or ripping your old bathroom apart. Get your
tub and sink resurfaced, which isn't nearly as costly as
replacement. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A readers asks, ``What is the web that
is starting to cover trunks and heavy branches of oak trees, and
what should we do if it is a hazard to the trees' health?''
Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GRAHAM-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ Heather Graham mixes comedy
and sex appeal as she turns heads as Hollywood's latest funny girl.
The actress, whose breakthrough film was ``Boogie Nights'' in 1997,
stars in the upcoming Hollywood satire ``Bowfinger.'' She was also
in the summer hit ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' By
LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-VIETNAM (Undated) _ The Discovery Channel's ``The Vietnam
War: A Descent into Hell'' asks a complex question _ Why did the
United States get so deeply involved in Vietnam? _ and settles for
an easy answer. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GRAHAM-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ Heather Graham mixes comedy
and sex appeal as she turns heads as Hollywood's latest funny girl.
The actress, whose breakthrough film was ``Boogie Nights'' in 1997,
stars in the upcoming Hollywood satire ``Bowfinger.'' She was also
in the summer hit ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' By
LOUIS B. PARKS
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Many people wish they could
turn the years back to an earlier time, like the days of the
frontier, of Joe Walker, Kit Carson and Jim Bridger. Two fellows in
the Sierra foothills do exactly that almost every weekend. They
specialize in setting up camps and adventures modeled after the era
of the 1830s and the Rocky Mountain fur trade. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-MORA (Stockton, Calif.) _ Don't tell Jim Mora about
pressure. The man has known nothing else since he walked into the
NFL. Talk to Mora about pressure and you'll hear stories about his
coaching in New Orleans earlier this decade, working as a secondary
coach under his father Jim, the team's head coach from 1986-95.
Back then, the young Jim wasn't a popular man at times. By JEFFRI
CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-McGWIRE-A'S (Oakland, Calif.) _ Will anyone remember that
Mark McGwire hit his first 363 home runs with the Oakland A's? Or
49 homers as a rookie? Or 50 in his final full season in Oakland?
Or used to take batting practice in peace? Or played in the A's
organization for 131/2 years? We've seen so much of McGwire the
last two seasons that it's become difficult to picture him in any
color but St. Louis red. By JOHN SHEA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Air rage has escalated to new _ and
more dangerous _ levels the past few weeks. It's time to look for
answers to this serious problem. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Ponder these public
contradictions about privacy: Last week, the Boy Scouts were told
by the New Jersey Supreme Court that they could not expel gays. The
scouts had claimed they could do so because they are a private
organization. Next March, right-wingers will try to end recognition
of gay marriages in California, claiming marriage is a public
institution. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Like it or not, the personal lives
of presidents tend to have bearing on public affairs. So, sorry,
but what Hillary Rodham Clinton says about her marriage really is
legitimate news. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ When the American Academy of
Pediatrics last week cautioned parents that children under the age
of 2 should not be permitted to watch television because it
endangered their health, it was not breaking new ground. The
pediatricians joined a long list of others who have warned about
the negative impact of television watching on young people. By
HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
