<HEADER>
A0501 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKING-LIFEBEAT-ART-     08-09 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKING: ONCE A PLEASURE, NOW A VICE
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color graphic on secondhand smoke 
 By MARTHA NOLAN MCKENZIE 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ashtrays have gone the way of manual typewriters in many
workplaces. As concerns about the dangers of secondhand smoke have
risen, smokers have been banished to tiny outdoor patios by many
businesses. Some employers won't let employees smoke on the job,
inside or out. And others won't let them smoke at all _ even on
their own time _ refusing to hire smokers.
</P>
<P>
   In the pitched battle between those who choose to light up and
those who don't, nonsmokers have clearly been gaining ground.
Today, 41 states restrict smoking at state government work sites
and about 74 percent of large U.S. companies have a formal policy
restricting smoking _ despite the fact that one in four adults
still smokes.
</P>
<P>
   But last year a federal judge dealt antismoking forces a blow.
In July, U.S. District Judge William Osteen, a former tobacco
industry lobbyist, ruled in favor of the tobacco industry when he
threw out a finding by the Environmental Protection Agency that
secondhand smoke caused lung cancer. The 1993 EPA report had been
used as the basis for banning smoking in many workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates on both sides of the issue debate the significance of
Osteen's ruling. Weighing in for the tobacco industry is Thomas
Humber, president of the National Smokers Alliance, a nonprofit
advocacy organization based in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we are starting to see is when fair, objective and
knowledgeable people begin to look at the so-called science on
environmental tobacco smoke, what they are finding is there is not
much there,'' Humber said. ''We will absolutely see ripple effects
from Osteen's decision. I think we'll see a reversal in policy by
some companies that have banned smoking. We are going to get back
to accepting all the diversity in this country and respecting
individual freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco opponents expect Osteen's ruling to be overturned on
appeal. ''The only fallout I've seen from Judge Osteen's decision
is misinformation,'' said Graham Kelder, managing attorney at the
Tobacco Control Resource center at Northeastern University School
of Law in Boston. ''Some people at the state and local level are
mistaken in assuming that the EPA report is the only foundation out
there on which to build local and state smoking restrictions. There
are hundreds of other studies that provide ample basis for
restricting smoking. Judge Osteen's judgment doesn't change the
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelder, as well as some academics and government officials,
contend it would be difficult to turn back the tide on nonsmoking
policies in the workplace, regardless of whether Osteen's ruling is
eventually overturned. The momentum against smoking is just too
strong.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, approximately 46 percent of all indoor employees worked
for an employer who had a smoke-free policy, which meant that
workers were required to either leave the building to smoke or go
to separately ventilated rooms, according to the National Cancer
Institute in Bethesda, Md. By 1996, the number had risen to 64
percent and investigators expect that to rise to 85 or 90 percent
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the restrictions is a growing belief _ regardless of
Osteen's ruling _ that secondhand smoke is harmful. Indeed,
compelling evidence is presented in myriad studies other than the
EPA's. To date, more than 50 compounds in tobacco smoke have been
identified as carcinogens.
</P>
<P>
   A recent widely quoted study by the California EPA _ which
contains data unrelated to the 1993 EPA study _ claims
environmental tobacco smoke causes 3,000 lung cancer deaths each
year; 35,000 to 62,000 heart-disease deaths; and 1,900 to 2,700
deaths from sudden infant death syndrome. The study also linked
environmental tobacco smoke to low birthweight babies, asthma and
other respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people still don't realize that breathing tobacco smoke
might be dangerous,'' said Beverly Kingsley, an epidemiologist with
the Office on Smoking and Health at the CDC. ''They feel that if
they are not smoking, they are not in danger. But evidence is
really accumulating that tobacco smoke is tobacco smoke is tobacco
smoke. Any level of exposure _ even a very low level _ may carry
some risk.''
</P>
<P>
   And while most studies have focused on secondhand smoke in the
home _ a nonsmoker living with a smoking spouse _ the workplace is
an important source of exposure. ''If someone is at work eight
hours a day breathing in someone else's smoke, that can be a
significant health risk, as much as living with a smoker,'' said
Kingsley. ''Workers in blue collar and service occupations are
particularly at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Curbing that risk was the impetus for Milliken &AMP; Co.'s
smoke-free policy. Since 1990, the 16,000 employees of the
Spartanburg, S.C.-based textile and chemical manufacturing company
have been required to go outside to light up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our smoking policy was a natural outgrowth of our corporate
safety policy, which says we believe all accidents are preventable,
all health risks are controllable and management is accountable,''
said Richard Dillard, Milliken's director of public affairs.
''Cigarette smoke is a known health hazard, and our primary concern
is for the health of our associates.''
</P>
<P>
   Smokers can impose other costs on their employers, as well.
According to the American Cancer Society, smokers miss work more
often than nonsmokers, use more medical benefits and raise costs
for building maintenance and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies believe curtailing these costs comes at too high
a price. ''Our smoking policy says that smoking tobacco is an
individual preference,'' said Sandra Deem, vice president of
corporate relations for First Union Corp. in Charlotte, N.C.
''Smoking is prohibited in certain areas, such as in vaults. In
other areas, we trust our employees to use good judgment. We want
to respect the differences in choices among our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   But many other employers contend smoking restrictions make good
business sense. In addition to restricting smoking to outdoor areas
or separately ventilated rooms, a growing number of businesses are
charging smokers more for their health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   At Arthur Andersen, an international management consulting firm,
for example, employees who smoke must pay $300 more per year for
their health insurance. ''It is stated very plainly on the printed
information we give out that it costs more for smokers to pay for
their health insurance,'' said Ellen Wile, spokeswoman for Arthur
Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are going even further, refusing to hire workers
who smoke. In Atlanta, for example, Turner Broadcasting System has
a policy against hiring smokers. While many states have passed
legislation making it illegal to discriminate based on smoking
status, in other states it is perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the absence of a statute, private employers can make any
decision they want in regard to hiring and firing,'' said John
Banzhaf, executive director of Action on Smoking and Health and a
professor at George Washington University in Washington, D.C. ''We
prohibit discrimination only based on race, origin and gender,
because these are characteristics that we can't change. But when
you look at smoking, people can choose to do it or not. And there
are very rational reasons why one would want to have a smokefree
work force.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Martha Nolan McKenzie writes for the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group. Stephen G. Reed, a writer for the Herald-Tribune
in Sarasota, Fla., contributed to this article.) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
