<HEADER>
A0502 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICE-CREAM-HISTORY-LIF     08-09 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-CREAM-HISTORY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE CREAM: FAVORITE OF NERO, GEORGE WASHINGTON AND ALL AMERICANS
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a little boy eating an ice cream cone 
 By LORI B. MURRAY 
 c.1999 Lori B. Murray 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I scream. You scream. We all scream for ice cream.'' And
people have been screaming for the popular dessert for centuries.
When the not-so-popular Roman emperor, Nero, wanted a cold dessert
for his lengthy feasts, he sent slaves up the mountains to fetch
snow and mix it with fruit pulp, honey, and nectar.
 &UR; HISTORY OF ICE CREAM &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Marco Polo refined the concept of cold desserts. When he
returned home from his travels in the Orient, he brought with him a
recipe for the flavored ices the Chinese were so fond of. Unlike
Nero's treats, the Chinese added milk to their ices, making a type
of sherbet. The valued recipe spread throughout Italy, and
eventually France.
</P>
<P>
   But ice cream as we know it today was not created until the time
of the exploration of the New World. In the Chinese sherbets, ice
was one of the ingredients, and it was mixed in a bowl with crushed
fruit, juice or milk. The new ice cream, however, required that the
milk or cream be placed in a bowl, combined with fruit, sugar or
chocolate, and surrounded with ice instead.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream was a favorite of some of our country's early
presidents. George Washington is reputed to have spent $200 on ice
cream during the summer of 1790. Thomas Jefferson learned how to
make ice cream while he was a diplomat of France, and he continued
making his 18-step recipe after returning home. James Madison's
wife, Dolly, created a sensation when she served pink ice cream as
a dessert in the White House at the second Presidential Inaugural
Ball in 1812.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream took a big step in 1846 when Nancy Johnson invented
the hand-cranked ice cream freezer. She failed to patent her
invention, however, and a similar type was patented in 1848. It
wasn't long after this, in 1851, that Jacob Fussell established the
first commercial ice cream plant.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream sodas grew in popularity at soda fountains throughout
the United States. During the 1890's in America, a law was passed
against serving ice cream sodas on Sundays. It was believed that if
sodas were prohibited that people would quit hanging around
drugstores on Sunday, a day which was intended for rest and quiet.
But in Evanston, Ill., one drugstore owner fought the battle by
pouring soda syrup over ice cream in a dish. He called this
soda-less soda the ``Ice Cream Sunday,'' later changed to
``sundae'' to avoid getting into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   America's favorite treat _ the ice cream cone _ emerged at the
St. Louis World's Fair on July 23, 1904. Ernest Hamwi was making
waffle pastries in a booth next to one of the many popular ice
cream booths. When the ice cream stand ran out of dishes, Hamwi
quickly rolled one of his waffles into the shape of a cone, and he
gave it to the ice cream vendor, who wasted no time in filling it
with ice cream. The rest is history.
 &UR; ICE CREAM FUN FACTS &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Today, each American consumes an average of approximately 15
quarts of ice cream a year. The big business of ice cream causes
people across the country to stand in line for their favorite ice
cream and their favorite flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it be frozen custard, sherbet, or sorbet, no one can
question the phenomenal growth of the treat that everyone loves.
And in spite of the creation of an innumerable amount of flavors,
at least half of the ice cream eaten in this country is vanilla.
Chocolate comes in second place, followed by strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite flavors are as varied as the United States itself. In
New England, for example, coffee ice cream is popular. If you visit
Texas, you'll discover that butter pecan is the hands-down
favorite. In many areas of the South, peach is prominent. In
central Ohio, black walnut is a big seller.
 &UR; ICE CREAM CELEBRATIONS &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An easy way to entertain friends and family during the summer is
with an ice cream sundae or tasting party. Have a
``Make-Your-Own-Sundae'' party where guests can create their own
extravaganza. Just dish up the ice cream and offer a line-up of
condiments including toppings, fruits, nuts, jimmies, crushed
candies, chocolate chips, coconut, and whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Or host a ``Taste Test'' party, offering your guests several
brands of the same flavor, including supermarket and gourmet ice
creams. Secretly label the bottoms of the dishes with the names of
the brands, fill the dishes, mix them up, and start sampling. It'll
be fun to discover that the same flavor can, indeed, taste very
different. Perhaps your family members or guests could vote on
everyone's favorite ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you make your own, buy it at the supermarket, or visit
your favorite ice cream parlor, one thing is certain. All screaming
aside, ice cream brings a smile to everyone's face.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lori B. Murray is a Columbus,Ohio-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
