<HEADLINE>
GIVE THAT OLD TUB A NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Wish you could flush your porcelain, Fiberglas or
acrylic tub and vanity sink down the toilet because the colors are
outdated, stained or badly chipped?
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about buying new or ripping your old bathroom apart.
Get your tub and sink resurfaced, which isn't nearly as costly as
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a popular way to go,'' said Terry Thomas, owner of Perma
Glaze in Westford, N.Y. ``Everything is done right in your home
without removing anything. It takes about 4 1/2 hours to resurface
a standard-size 5-foot-long tub and 48 hours for it to cure before
you can use it.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost for the tub is approximately $300, depending on the
amount of prep work involved, such as filling in chips and removing
old paint. Fiberglas tubs may cost more, because the walls that go
around them are often resurfaced to match.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas doesn't resurface toilets, hot tubs or kitchen sinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can transform a tub into any color, even from black to
white, although 90 percent of the tubs I do are refinished in
white,'' said Thomas, who has owned her franchise for seven years.
Thomas said that refinishing a tub also allows you to match or
coordinate your tub and sink with your wallpaper or tile.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the tile is in relatively good shape, it can be resurfaced
to match your existing or resurfaced tub,'' Thomas explained.
</P>
<P>
   The resurfacing process involves cleaning the surface with an
etching cream, filling any chips, priming it and spray painting
with the desired color.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on use and care, a resurfaced tub or sink will hold up
for 10 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   Special care means rinsing the tub or sink after each use to
keep soap and water deposits from building up on the surface. Don't
leave rubber tub mats on the bottom of the tub, where water
deposits, dirt and mold can collect.
</P>
<P>
   Use only liquid cleansers, not abrasives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The care is really just like the directions you'd find on new
tubs or sinks,'' Thomas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
