<SLUG> BC-UNDERGROUND-RAILROAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD DOWN UNDER RECALLS THE SCOURGE OF SLAVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Brooklyn is a brash, open-faced place, where a church
festival culminates when 100 men parade an 85-foot devotional tower
through the streets, where coffee drinkers cut to the chase by
ordering, in their consonant-light accent, ``Light, one sug-a,''
and where patrons sit, shoulder-to-shoulder, to eat Puerto Rican
fare in a steaming cuchifrito stand.
</P>
<P>
   Still, quieter sanctuaries and secret places here speak,
hauntingly, to one of the nation's most traumatic and dramatic
historic chapters: slavery and the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Under the borough of New York City that launched great ships and
Jackie Robinson, and made bubble gum and beer, is the vestige of
the Underground Railroad's secret escape route. In the basement of
Lafayette Avenue Presbyterian Church is a labyrinth of dark, grimy
brick tunnels, their arched openings reported to have led to safe
havens for the enslaved on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Above ground, on a sparkling July afternoon, are more definitive
artifacts: the poignant garden statue of famed preacher Henry Ward
Beecher, who conducted auctions at Plymouth Church, not to sell
slaves, but to buy their freedom; or the church's Pew 89, where
Abraham Lincoln worshiped on Feb. 26, 1860, the day before he
outlined his position on slavery in a speech that won him the
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Ducking and squinting in the cool darkness of Lafayette's
subterranean tunnels imparts a sense of the experience of the
enslaved, groping their way to freedom in a borough that was once a
major slaveholder, in a North that upheld fugitive-slave laws.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans in particular who visit the tunnels for the
first time sometimes have, in the words of tour guide Fred B.
Laverpool Sr., a ``visceral experience, of being in the presence of
their ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   Such moments consolidate what Laverpool calls ``the single most
dramatic statement against slavery.'' The Underground Railroad
``encouraged people to run away.''
</P>
<P>
   Slavery and the Underground Railroad may not seem to appeal to
tourists accustomed to theme-park vacations. But Laverpool, who
began this tour a year ago, and others in the tourism trade, are
riding a tailwind of public interest in such history.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service almost a decade ago began studying how
to organize and interpret hundreds of Underground Railroad sites.
The research fueled grass-roots interest, which in turn influenced
passage of the 1998 federal law authorizing the agency to create
this historic freedom trail, said Diane Miller, the service's
Midwest Region Underground Railroad coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Underground Railroad tours have begun in New York and other
states. In New York City, a task force is working to promote black
heritage in tourism, introducing this history to the mainstream and
beyond Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Laverpool's ``Braggin' About Brooklyn'' bus and walking tours
introduce their audience to New York beyond Manhattan with an
emphasis on the borough's African-American roots.
</P>
<P>
   A Brooklyn native whose African-American family dates back four
generations here, Laverpool, courteous, almost courtly, brings
hometown pride to his narrative.
</P>
<P>
   On a mid-July afternoon, Laverpool, 52, a New York City Transit
Authority undercover investigator who is on medical disability
leave, combined aspects of the bus and walking tour. He started by
driving across the Manhattan Bridge, for a brief detour to lower
Manhattan, and the once-forgotten 18th-century African Burial
Ground.
</P>
<P>
   Here, near City Hall, a grassy plot surrounded by a chain-link
fence seems an odd oasis amid a land of concrete at Duane Street
and Broadway. But it is a somber reminder of early African history
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath five city blocks here are the remains of 20,000 Africans
buried in the 1700s, and forgotten, until excavation for a federal
office complex in 1991 unearthed hundreds of coffins. The unearthed
remains were studied at Howard University in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery reveals what had been an underestimated, largely
enslaved African population in colonial New York; one study of the
remains found that many who were buried here were worked to death
even before the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
   Bystanders, overhearing Laverpool, walked up to hear him stress
the importance of remembering this patch. Was the cemetery
presumably erased because it held the remains of blacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, my answer to that is, `correct,''' Laverpool said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across the East River, Plymouth Church of the Pilgrims, in the
leafy, genteel neighborhood of Brooklyn Heights, is an 1850
Congregational meeting house whose placid atmosphere today cannot
convey the exciting leadership of Henry Ward Beecher, brother of
abolitionist writer Harriet Beecher Stowe.
</P>
<P>
   The forward-thinking Beecher is best known for his anti-slavery
sensibility, but he also championed women's rights, early
Christian-Jewish dialogue and Darwin's theory of evolution, the
church's historic notes say.
</P>
<P>
   Plymouth was known as the ``Grand Central Terminal'' of the
Underground Railroad, with a reported serpentine trail underneath
the church.
</P>
<P>
   Beecher also publicly rescued slaves in his auctions to buy
their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In the church's Orange Street garden, a statue by sculptor
Gutzon Borglum, who created Mount Rushmore, depicts Beecher,
standing benevolently by Pinky, the 10-year-old girl whose freedom
is about to be secured.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibit in Plymouth's Hillis Arcade makes the story more
personal. It includes a photograph of Pinky as a mature woman, Rose
Ward Hunt, radiating dignity. The freedom ring Beecher gave her in
1860 is on display as well.
</P>
<P>
   She returned the ring to the church on Plymouth's 80th
anniversary in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   Lafayette has a long tradition of community activism. As an
example, the New York Times several years ago reported how this
integrated congregation is given to protesting child labor in
Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Laverpool on his tour brings people to the foundation of this
activism, in the church's basement tunnels. ``This church was one
of the safe houses. The slaves were brought here and hidden in the
basement,'' Laverpool said, citing church oral and written history.
</P>
<P>
   Such sanctuary was temporary, since these tunnels are believed
to have led runaway slaves to other neighborhood locations where
they'd find safe shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the eerie basement catacomb, Laverpool said, ``Freedom
is not a gift. These are some of the places you had to go to be
free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
