<HEADLINE>
CENTURY'S LAST SOLAR ECLIPSE AVAILABLE ON WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It will be ``lights out,'' celestially speaking,
for the last time this century when a solar eclipse plunges
portions of Europe and Asia into darkness on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if you don't plan to be in the United Kingdom, Turkey or
other countries destined for a blackout that day, don't fret: The
rare cosmic show will be available on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   A solar eclipse occurs when the moon passes between the sun and
the Earth, causing the lunar shadow to fall on our planet. To the
ancients, a solar eclipse was good reason for wailing and gnashing
of teeth. Even today, some traditional cultures bang drums and sing
songs to drive away the monster presumed to be eating the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The coming eclipse will start over the western Atlantic and
extend to Karachi, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Television pictures of the eclipse _ to be recorded by a team
from San Francisco's Exploratorium science museum at the town of
Amasya, located east of Ankara, Turkey _ will be transmitted to the
Web and the Exploratorium via a NASA satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The Amasya team also will conduct scientific observations of the
eclipse, including one of its eeriest phenomena, shadow bands.
These are faint, fast-moving, shadowy ripples seen on the ground
during total eclipses.
</P>
<P>
   Exploratorium physicist Paul Doherty recalled seeing shadow
bands during a 1970 solar eclipse, and ``they looked exactly liked
ripples in water. ... Now we strongly believe they are caused by
refraction (of light) caused by temperature differences in the
Earth's atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty and his colleagues plan to observe the ripples as they
move across a large white sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a top-notch astronomical spectacle, the sky show
will indirectly shed light on a pressing terrestrial question: Is
Earth's climate changing? The question is complicated partly
because scientists are unsure whether the sun's diameter or
brightness vary subtly over time, enhancing planetary cooling or
warming.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, scientists scattered across the ``path of
totality'' _ the path of the moon's shadow, thousands of miles long
_ will gauge the solar diameter by measuring the precise times that
totality begins and ends.
</P>
<P>
   Solar eclipses have played important roles in the history of
astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   During eclipses in the 18th and 19th centuries, astronomers
noticed flame-shaped eruptions from the solar surface. These are
now known to be ejections of subatomic particles that interfere
with terrestrial power lines and radio communications.
</P>
<P>
   The most renowned eclipse discovery came in the late 1910s, when
British scientist Arthur Stanley Eddington measured the precise
positions of stars near the eclipsed sun.
</P>
<P>
   The stars' apparent positions varied slightly from those
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   This observation verified Albert Einstein's then-controversial
prediction that the mass of the sun would distort the path of a
beam of starlight by a certain angle. Einstein thus became an
overnight celebrity, and his general theory of relativity
revolutionized physics and cosmology.
</P>
<P>
   The eclipse begins at 7:28 a.m. Eastern Wednesday. Further
information is available at a Web site:
www.exploratorium.edu/eclipse. The eclipse also will be televised
live over NASA Select and on the Web site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
