<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GARDEN STATE LOOKS BETTER ALL THE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Consider these public contradictions about
privacy:
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Boy Scouts were told by the New Jersey Supreme
Court that they could not expel gays. The Scouts had claimed they
could do so because they are a private organization.
</P>
<P>
   Next March, right-wingers will try to end recognition of gay
marriages in California, claiming marriage is a public institution.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Definition of Marriage Initiative'' basically says
marriage is such a foundation of American society that government
should control it.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon my confusion, but are the thousands of scouts meeting in
public schools doing something more private than what couples do in
bedrooms?
</P>
<P>
   The only consistency here is that some Americans think gays
shouldn't be allowed to tie any knots, whether they require
licenses, or bring merit badges.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, New Jersey, for bringing sanity to this. The state
that gave us Bruce Springsteen's songs of the working man, George
Washington's victory over the Hessians and the Meadowlands' gift to
football owners, struck another blow for individual freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court in a unanimous decision rejected
the Boy Scouts' argument that homosexuality is immoral, saying the
Boy Scouts are ``not distinctly'' private and can't expel a scout
for being gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``One particular stereotype that we renounce today is that
homosexuals are inherently immoral,'' wrote New Jersey Supreme
Court Justice Alan B. Handler.
</P>
<P>
   I wish California had that attitude about gays who want to get
married. I'm not laughing at any more jokes about the smells of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a New Jersey guy, and I just think it's poetic justice,''
said Tom Ammiano, president of the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors. ``I'm a Bruce Springsteen fan, a fan of New Jersey
girls with their big hairdos, and I'm proud as hell of New
Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden State hasn't shone on this issue. Last year the
California Supreme Court said the Boy Scouts are a private
organization and can expel gays.
</P>
<P>
   Right. The Scouts are so private they sign up any kid willing to
wear a scarf. That included Ammiano when he was young. He quit out
of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, when Ammiano was on the school board, he fought
to bar the Boy Scouts from recruiting in public schools because the
Scouts are a discriminatory organization.
</P>
<P>
   That caused a controversy, but most San Franciscans have come
around to as progressive a position as New Jersey has.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey case is likely to end up in the U.S. Supreme
Court, and the Boy Scouts again can argue on the basis of the First
Amendment right of freedom of association.
</P>
<P>
   Here in California, anti-gay forces are going in the other
direction, against freedom of association in marriage with the
Definition of Marriage Initiative, sponsored by Republican state
Sen. William ``Pete'' Knight of Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the ballot measure have raised about $1 million.
The Mormon Church has caused a stir because its leaders in Salt
Lake City have urged members to contribute money to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of bad jokes about the Mormons' polygamous
definition of marriage that held until 1890. Multiple wives weren't
outlawed until Utah was in line to become a state.
</P>
<P>
   I get queasy when San Franciscans make fun of Mormons, and not
just because religion should be respected as much as marital
choice.
</P>
<P>
   In 1846 the ship Brooklyn arrived here from New York with Elder
Samuel Brannan and 237 other Mormons. They doubled the population
of San Francisco, then called Yerba Buena, and Brannan founded the
first public school in this town.
</P>
<P>
   It's also worth remembering that Joseph Smith, the founder of
the Church of the Latter-day Saints, enjoyed wrestling, dancing and
even an occasional drink. He once wrote, ``Men are that they might
have joy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon Church should remember that line. It's unfortunate
that a church persecuted in the 19th century, partly over marriage
practices, should try to do the same to other Americans a century
later.
</P>
<P>
   The Definition of Marriage Initiative is in the mean-spirited,
empty tradition of the anti-immigrant Proposition 187 and the
anti-affirmative action Proposition 209.
</P>
<P>
   Much money will be spent, much ink spilled and much ill will
stirred. In the end, we'll be left with a stench in California, and
maybe even an urge to move to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
