<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-09 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY THE FIRST FAMILY IS FAIR GAME FOR THE NEWS MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I'm not sure precisely how it happened, but I
seem to have been selected as the unofficial spokesman in my town
for American journalism.
</P>
<P>
   When John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane went down off Martha's Vineyard
a few weekends ago, I heard from dozens of e-mail correspondents
and callers to my voice mail complaining about an excess of news
coverage on the topic, like I really have something to say about
how CNN covers stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Trust me, CNN seldom requests my guidance. NBC does not solicit
my advice. OK, Dan Rather does call me several times a week,
begging me to tell him what to do, but I've told the guy repeatedly
that he's totally on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the calls and e-mails roar in, demanding that I explain
why some event or other gets too much or too little coverage. It
happened again after an interview with Hillary Rodham Clinton in
the premier edition of Talk magazine made news.
</P>
<P>
   In this interview, Mrs. Clinton explained that her husband's
inability to keep his paws off other women stems from his
childhood. His mother and grandmother fought for his affection, she
said. So what choice did he have in adulthood but to live life as a
compulsive horndog?
</P>
<P>
   Why did Mrs. Clinton say this? Who knows? She might just have
blurted it out. She's a bright, capable person, but she has been
under some strain lately. Maybe the remark was carefully calculated
to portray her husband's most conspicuous character flaw as sort of
a medical disorder. In any event, her approval rating in a Zogby
Poll went up after that interview and, oddly, after she backed off
the remark a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who contacted me felt that this was not newsworthy.
Why does the media _ and I recall with some wistfulness when we
were reviled merely as the press _ insist on digging into this
couple's marriage? Is nothing scared? Is privacy totally dead?
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, you reasonably can expect a certain infringement
on your privacy when you become president. If you're willing to
respond to questions about what kind of underwear you wear, you
probably shouldn't be too surprised at questions about why you feel
compelled to pounce on every female who winks in your direction.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this news? Because it's the stuff of history, I guess.
That's why there's so much interest on the part of historians in
whether Thomas Jefferson really did father one or more of Sally
Hemmings' children. That's why the true nature of the relationship
between Franklin Delano Roosevelt and his activist wife, Eleanor,
has been of such interest to scholars.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, Nancy Reagan's influence on her husband's
policies had a huge impact on people around the globe. Abraham
Lincoln's rocky marriage with his wife, Mary, was part of who this
enormously significant man was and why we should care about him.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most crucial presidential marriage was the one
between Woodrow Wilson and his wife, Edith. When he suffered a
horrible stroke that virtually blinded him and left him
half-paralyzed, she served as a de facto president. Surely she had
impact on his firm, adamant refusal to compromise with Congress on
American membership in the League of Nations, a decision that
played a huge role in the creating World War II.
</P>
<P>
   And I would love to say more about this, but my phone is
ringing. It's probably Rather again.
</P>
<P>
   The poor schnook won't give me a moment's peace.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
