<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV: THE GREAT AMERICAN SCOURGE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When the American Academy of Pediatrics last week
cautioned parents that children under the age of 2 should not be
permitted to watch television because it endangered their health,
it was not breaking new ground.
</P>
<P>
   The pediatricians joined a long list of others, including
psychologists and social scientists, who earlier warned about the
negative impact of television watching on young people.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, America's kids devote more time to the tube, by
all reports even more than their counterparts in other parts of the
world. Their parents are not interfering with this particular bad
habit. And the ugly truth is that television is for many parents
too convenient a baby sitter or youth companion to be monitored too
closely.
</P>
<P>
   In more and more households, both parents are off to work during
the week, and when they finally get home, they are confronted with
the ever-present chores of housekeeping. Mothers in general bear
most of that burden and single ones have to deal with it by
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The price paid for using television to occupy kids' time is that
they are relentlessly exposed to mind-crunching programming.
Watching television without let or hindrance dulls the mind,
deadens the senses and makes you fat. No more studies are needed to
document that television watching is not good for the kids, who, it
is also argued, can become sociopaths from seeing too much violence
day after day.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the small mountain of studies of kids and television may
not be as reliable as their authors suppose. Nevertheless, common
sense should teach us to rely on what we can see for ourselves.
Kids are exercising less and consequently becoming more portly.
Their school work, as measured in standard examinations, is
underwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is more at stake in television watching. If it's bad
for the kids, it is no better for the grownups.
</P>
<P>
   Television is putrefying American culture with its lack of
sensibility and nuance. Not everything on television is worthless;
valuable or entertaining programming is there to be found. But
taken together, the good television is routinely swamped by the
garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Now it may be argued that popular culture by definition is
kitsch. Through the decades, mass entertainments have had little to
recommend them except their banality. But television made it much
worse, more quickly, because of the immensity of its reach, its
singular ability to define and then dominate popular culture. It
imposes a continental uniformity, finding riches without end in
nurturing the lowest common denominator and then talking down to
it.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always thus. When television first appeared, it was
hailed as a marvel that would bring the wider world into every
home, expanding exponentially the possibilities for educating and
informing multitudes. Those early years were by definition
innovative, as the art of the new communication form evolved.
</P>
<P>
   In drama and in comedy, in news programming and in special
events coverage, television did much to bring the world into
tighter focus, and to expose its audiences to people and places
they would otherwise have never seen close up.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively early on, however, the owners of television imposed
on themselves imperatives that led programming into the wasteland.
The battle ever since has been to get the proprietors to improve
their product. It is a battle that is harder to win each successive
season.
</P>
<P>
   Except for sporting events or those ever-rarer programs with
content and sense, television has become a big bore. Even if it
were not to encourage slothfulness and apathy, television's
mindlessness kills time, dispirits creativity and annoys, all at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Commercialism is devouring the very thing that made possible
entirely new lines of business. Save for a couple of stations, you
cannot watch a film without suffering through constant break-ins
for ads. Advertising is certainly legitimate in and of itself, but
its heavy-footed imprint on the total presentation has overwhelmed
content.
</P>
<P>
   It makes little sense to watch a movie on television unless you
are interested in the ads, some of which, ironically or otherwise,
are much cleverer than what appears in the short intervals between
them.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, neither doctors nor social workers can
protect children from the punishing habits of television watching
if parents continue to abdicate their responsibilities to supervise
their children.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, unless and until adults reject their exploitation by
the medium, there's no chance that television will revive those
values that once made it an authentic phenomenon of culture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
