<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-BRUCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIME HAS COME FOR LENNY BRUCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lenny Bruce is back in style and the ironies are so
crushing, you don't know whether to laugh or cry.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a stand-up comedian who was hounded and hammered to his
knees for saying words now uttered routinely on HBO. So it's
fitting _ a thank-you note, of sorts _ that HBO is airing a
documentary of his life, ``Lenny Bruce: Swear to Tell the Truth,''
Monday at 10:15.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, the Museum of Television &AMP; Radio in Manhattan is
showing, through Oct. 3, a compilation of all of Bruce's TV
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer risky to hail Bruce as a great social critic and
satirist. His monologues on race relations, sexual mores, and
organized religion are widely admired as pathbreakers _ and they
remain as trenchant as any comic's reflections since.
</P>
<P>
   But in his heyday _ from the late-1950s until 1966, when he OD'd
at the age of 40 _ Bruce was more commonly denounced as a ``sick
comic.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, he reveled in both images. There was a menacing
quality to Lenny Bruce that time has not erased. It was what so
thrilled his fans and so shocked everyone else. You see it now and
then in the HBO and museum films _ those too-penetrating eyes, that
machine-gun cackle of a laugh, the shifty cocksureness of being on
to a hushed-up truth.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce was an authentic hipster, a living prototype of Norman
Mailer's ``White Negro,'' teetering defiantly on the edge. He
considered himself as much jazz musician as comic. In the HBO film,
Nat Hentoff says Bruce ``turned around the notion of what American
comedy could be,'' much as Charlie Parker and John Coltrane turned
around jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Hentoff is talking about not just substance but rhythm. Bruce
may have been the only white entertainer to speak in jazz argot _
``dig,'' ``man,'' ``flip,'' ``cool,'' ``cook,'' ``swing,''
``crazy'' _ without sounding ridiculous. He improvised like a
jazzman, too, riffing on his routines, altering and adding ideas as
they came to him, right on stage, spontaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Both films fall short in conveying this vitality. They offer a
taste of it in an excerpt from a 1959 Steve Allen Show, in which
Bruce does his bit about the first boy to get high off airplane
glue (``I'll be the Louis Pasteur of junkiedom!''). But his TV
spots were fairly tame, and the few films of live performances were
made late in his career, after deterioration had set in.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce was first arrested in Philadelphia, for possession of
narcotics, on Sept. 29, 1961. Five days later, he was busted in San
Francisco on obscenity charges, for using the famous 10-letter
word. Over the next 2 1/2 years, he was arrested five times, in Los
Angeles, Chicago, and New York. Appeals courts overturned the
charges in every case, but gigs dried up. He died a pauper, if also
a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krassner, his friend and spiritual heir, says Bruce's real
offense was blasphemy, not obscenity, and indeed his troubles came
mainly from DAs and judges who despised his digs at the Catholic
Church. (I suspect, even now, HBO might think twice about
broadcasting ``Religions, Inc.'' or ``Christ and Moses'' in their
entirety.)
</P>
<P>
   His busts set off a spiral of self-destruction, and he grew less
and less funny. On Feb. 3, 1961, before his legal troubles began,
Bruce gave a sold-out midnight concert at Carnegie Hall that still
stands as one of the funniest and most profound comedy shows ever.
(You can hear it on CD.) Nine months later, soon after his first
two busts, the decline was already apparent. His act became more
about his busts, less about the rest of the world. His comic bits
were jumbled, his delivery clouded in rage.
</P>
<P>
   By 1965, he was obsessed. A concert that year at Berkeley was
one long harangue, a recitation of court transcripts and _ as if he
wanted more trouble _ an endless stream of obscenities. (The
Carnegie Hall concert contained almost no profanity.)
</P>
<P>
   The saddest part of the HBO film comes near the end _ a photo of
Bruce, deep dark orbs encasing half-dead eyes. For all his jabs at
society, he revered the American system and couldn't quite believe
how blatantly its guardians were breaking their own rules. It
unnerved him, twisted him.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock, the closest thing to our day's Lenny Bruce, always
denies he's a social critic. ``I'm just a comedian,'' he insists.
He must know this is nonsense, but he's smart to keep up the
pretense. Lenny Bruce went sour when he began to act otherwise.
``I'm not a comedian, I'm Lenny Bruce,'' he told a nightclub
audience in 1962. He never pulled out of the trance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
