<HEADER>
A0630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      08-09 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!!! ``Autumn Tale'' There's more autumn sun than autumn rain in
this beautifully detailed and compassionately observed masterpiece
by France's Eric Rohmer. The film is set in motion when Marie
Riviere's Miss Fixit sets out to find a mate for her shy single
pal, Beatrice Romand, who mostly sticks to her small vineyard. It's
the vineyard that supplies the film with its central visual
metaphor of ripeness _ ripeness with a lot of mischievously
light-textured comedy. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Dick'' A very funny reinvention of the Watergate scandal, as
told through the eyes of a couple of dizzy teenage girls who,
through a fluke, were in on everything. Kirsten Dunst and Michelle
Williams are fine as the loose cannonettes, but what really puts
this one into orbit is Dan Hedaya's Nixon, from his tense shoulders
to his glowering, bulging-eyed paranoia. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``The Iron Giant'' A winning animated version of Ted Hughes's
children's classic. It successfully transplants its Cold War
anti-weapons message from England to a coastal village in Maine,
and charms us into make-believing in the friendship between a boy
and a giant robot from outer space. They reverse traditional
parent-child roles, as the sharp kid clues in the formidably lethal
but innocent robot. (G) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``My Life So Far'' A glowingly tender evocation of a
charmed boyhood in the Scottish Highlands between the wars.
Hastening the maturing of its 10-year-old protagonist are the
rambunctious energies of his family of eccentrics, from his
exuberant crackpot father to his stern but wildly romantic uncle,
who upsets the family's routines when he brings home a vivacious
young French bride. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Mystery Men'' This dark comic-book spoof of superheroes
and losers who aspire to superhero status begins on a terrific note
of comic neurotic irony, then dwindles into something very ordinary
and very long. Ben Stiller's Mr. Furious, Janeane Garofalo's
Bowler, and William H. Macy's Shoveler are the best of the bunch
who barely have power, much less superpower. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The Sixth Sense'' This slow, ponderous ghost story is
worth sticking with. First, because elements that don't quite add
up finally do make sense in a surprise ending. Second, because it
avoids the obviousness of special effects for a genuinely eerie
atmopshere and a permanent look of sadness weighing down the face
of an 8-year-old boy picking up the emanations of an unhappy ghost.
Bruce Willis is a surprise, too, turning in the most subdued
performance of his career as a troubled therapist determined to
help the boy. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' This classic heist caper and
sexual chess game has been moved from Boston to Manhattan, with
Pierce Brosnan and Rene Russo in the roles originated by Steve
McQueen and Faye Dunaway. This time, the bored, emotionally
unreachable zillionaire robs a museum, not a bank. This remake has
more clever plot twists than the original, but it also spends more
time trying to be touchy-feely instead of just relaxing into its
trashiness. Besides, Brosnan lacks the nervous physicality McQueen
projected with such jumpy ease. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Trick'' A sweet little boy-meets-boy story set in
Greenwich Village and Chelsea. Christian Campbell plays a guy who
wonders if trying to write Broadway musicals is a cool career
choice; John Paul Pitoc is the go-go dancer who catches his eye and
proves surprisingly and refreshingly sensitive. The film loses
points, though, for its caricaturing of a straight woman, played
with good-sport energies by Tori Spelling. Similar stereotyping and
scapegoating of a gay character would invite storms of scorn. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``The Wounds'' Potently stylized satire focusing on the
civilian casualties of the war in the former Yugoslavia from 1991
to 1996, specifically the lost youth of kids turned into nihilistic
killers. Influenced by Depression-era American gangster movies, it
begins with three 13-year-old pals throwing rocks at one another in
a graveyard in Belgrade and ends five years later with a shootout
in a city that has become one big graveyard. (Unrated)
</P>
</TEXT>
