<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS AND THAT IN PHYSICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do you get heavier or lighter when you get to the top of a
high mountain?
</P>
<P>
   F.B., Peabody, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Lighter, and not just because of all the calories you burned
getting there. The further away from the center of the earth you
get, the weaker its gravity. But even at the top of Mt. Everest you
will only weight an ounce or two less.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. If you dug a hole all the way through the earth and dropped a
ball in one side, would it go all the way through or would gravity
make it stop in the middle?
</P>
<P>
   C.W., Concord, Mass., and D.G., West Roxbury, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. NASA physicist Doug Blanchard says if the hole was full of
air, the ball would accelerate until it reached terminal velocity,
when air pressure and friction resisting the object equal the
gravitational pull so the object can't accelerate any more. It
would be going fast enough to speed past the center of the earth.
Then it would start to slow, since more of the mass of the earth,
and therefore more of the gravitational pull, would be behind it.
It would stop just as it got to the other end of the hole, then
oscillate back and forth through the hole like a pendulum making a
shorter trip each time, until it came to a stop suspended right in
the middle, where gravity was pulling equally on it from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How fast do you have to go to escape gravity?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``You never escape gravity,'' explains NASA's Blanchard.
``It's always pulling on you. Objects that fly are just falling
slower than they're traveling.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's start from the top. Gravity is a rate of acceleration.
That's why falling objects fall faster and faster, until they reach
terminal velocity. That acceleration equals 32 feet per second per
second.
</P>
<P>
   So if you want to ``escape'' gravity, you have to jump
powerfully enough so you're going 32 feet per second (21.8 MPH)
after the first second, 64 feet per second (43.6 MPH) after two, 96
feet per second (65.4 MPH) after three, and so on. Blanchard says
for a rocket to achieve escape velocity, the speed necessary to get
far enough from the mass of the earth so gravity is weak enough
that a spacecraft can achieve orbit, it has to be reach seven miles
per second, 25,800 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   How about a pebble, or a feather? Same speeds apply. The rate of
gravity is constant. If you vary the weight of the object, you just
have to vary the power necessary to get it going fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Since it is the mass of an object that gives it gravitational
pull, as you get further from that mass, gravity weakens. The
further you get from the earth, the weaker gravity gets. Remember
our mountain climber example above.
</P>
<P>
   But even out in orbit gravity is still pulling spacecraft down.
To stay in orbit they have to fly at just the right speed to pull
away from the curve of the earth precisely as fast as gravity is
pulling them down. Travel too slowly and the craft will drop.
Travel too fast and it will outdo the pull from below and fly off
into space.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts and anything else in a spacecraft escape gravity and
float around weightless because, like the ship they're in, they're
moving at the precise speed at which their travel away from the
curve of the earth counteracts the gravity pulling them down.
</P>
<P>
   The higher they orbit, the slower that satellites need to go to
match the reduced gravitational pull. Communications satellites all
fly at 22,500 miles above the earth in what's called geosynchronous
orbit _ a technique first envisioned by author Arthur C. Clarke _
because at that height, the speed they need to match gravity, 5,968
MPH, keeps them over the same spot above the spinning earth below.
That way terrestrial transmitters and receivers always know where
to aim.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
