<SLUG> BC-ETHNIC-SYMBOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD SYMBOLS, NEW DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Back when Irish immigrants confronted signs declaring
``No Irish Need Apply,'' they rallied around a symbol of their
heritage: the shamrock. But as the Irish-American community grew in
power, the shamrock took on new meaning in some of the city's
racially and ethnically diverse housing developments: Only Irish
Need Apply.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, in Charlestown's Bunker Hill housing development, the
Puerto Rican flag first appeared about a decade ago as a sign of
pride among the development's newest ethnic group. But as their
numbers increased, longtime white tenants began to see the flag as
a symbol of Puerto Ricans claiming the development as their own
turf.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of old symbols and new meanings rocketed around the city
this week, as Boston Housing Authority officials rushed to dispute
reports that the agency had equated the lucky shamrock with symbols
of hate and intimidation during sensitivity classes for its
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy, which made headlines from South Boston all the
way back to Ireland, caused such an uproar among Irish Americans
that Mayor Thomas M. Menino addressed the issue, and BHA officials
scrambled to emphasize that cultural symbols are not being banned
from the housing developments.
</P>
<P>
   But while few people seriously compared the shamrock to such
potent emblems as the swastika or the Confederate flag, the dispute
highlighted a problem that Boston institutions like public housing
and the Fire Department have struggled with for years _ the
shifting meanings of cultural symbols.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symbols can be very beautiful for one person and very ugly for
another,'' said J. Lorand Matory, a cultural anthropologist at
Harvard University. ``Symbols have multiple meanings and they tend
to circulate around similar emotions, but every viewer can
interpret the sign according to his perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Matory said oppressed groups often begin using emblems of
cultural identity as a sign of strength. But as their numbers grow,
the symbol acquires more power. And what was once a sign of
confidence can become, in certain situations, a claim of dominance.
</P>
<P>
   In the abstract, ``The shamrock has no more of a negative
connotation than the American flag,'' said state Representative
Byron Rushing, a Democrat from the South End who is
African-American. ``I've always seen shamrocks on cars in Boston
for years and I've always seen it as good luck for the Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   But when used as a rallying point by those intent on showing
their power over other groups, he said, the shamrock can become as
intimidating as the clenched fists raised as black-power salutes by
some African Americans in the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many blacks continue to see the clenched fist as
nothing more than a show of pride, and they regard John Carlos and
Tommie Smith, the two Olympic sprinters who displayed the salute
during the medal ceremony at the 1968 games, as heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The salute ``meant power and unity just by the fact of the
clenched fist and the fingers united,'' said Carlos, 56, now a
track coach in Palm Springs. ``But when we did it, they tried to
say it was negative because black people were doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same confusion over meanings exists over today's symbols.
And in Boston this week, members of different racial and ethnic
groups generally defended their rights to display whatever emblems
they choose.
</P>
<P>
   David Cortiella, the former BHA director who is Puerto Rican,
said residents of the city's housing projects who display the
Puerto Rican flag are merely showing their pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were a majority force imposing our flag, then our symbol
would be threatening, it would have a force,'' said Cortiella. But
unlike Boston's white Irish community, ``we don't control power, we
don't control institutions, and it's the same thing with blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Irish Americans see it differently.
</P>
<P>
   When Frank Gillespie, a native of Ireland, first opened The
Black Thorn, a restaurant in South Boston, he proudly displayed the
beloved three-leaf clover all over his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put it in my window, in the house, and carry it around in my
pocket for luck,'' Gillespie said. ``It reminds us of where we came
from. It means we have a little Irish in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who believes the symbol means anything other than Irish
pride, he said, is taking political correctness too far.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Jennings, a first-generation Irish American from
Dorchester agrees. To her, the shamrock _ believed to have been
used by St. Patrick to explain the mystery of the Holy Trinity _
connects her to her parent's homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she acknowledged that its emotional meaning lies ``in the
eyes of the person looking at it. If someone thinks it's a sign of
dominance, then they will probably find bad in anything.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Bill O'Sullivan, a regular at the M &AMP; M
Tavern, a predominately black bar in Roxbury, was the only white
man in the place. Sipping his Budweiser, he struggled with the
varied meanings of the shamrock, and related it to his experience
at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all perception,'' O'Sullivan said. ``They call me `white
boy' here. I can take it two ways, it's all tongue in cheek. But if
they were wearing a dashiki and saying `white boy,' then it might
have a different meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   But James Boldin, an African-American who was standing nearby,
said he sees the shamrock as a sign of white dominance in his
hometown; a reminder that Irish in South Boston fought hard to keep
blacks out of their schools and neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shamrock means Boston is for white and not for black,'' he
insisted. He said he found it ironic that the Boston Celtics, a
predominantly black team, sports the shamrock on its warmup suits.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Twiss, the Celtics spokesman, said the name of the team as
well as its trademarks have become as much a sports tradition as
the pinstripes on the uniforms of the New York Yankees. When the
Celtics began play 50 years ago, Twiss said, its founder decided
that the team's new name and its symbol perfectly matched the city
it would represent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked around and said, `There are a lot of Irishmen in
Boston, so let's name it Celtics,' '' Twiss said. ``You could be
offended or impressed by it _ depending on what angle you are
looking at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
