<HEADLINE>
`SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE' IS CRACKLING GOOD FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Shakespeare in Love'' _ This bright comedy
features wonderful performances and a great gimmick. The
interlacing of Shakesperean plots and character makes for crackling
good fun. But it sometimes seems as if the script, co-written by
Tom Stoppard, was designed to be played faster, at an almost
slapstick pace, instead of the slowed-down version we see here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mod Squad'' _ Another vintage TV show that dies big-time
on the big screen. The TV show, even with Clarence Williams 3d,
wasn't that good; in this incarnation, it's much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' _ Clint Eastwood stars in, and directs, this
mystery about a crusading journalist. The older Eastwood gets, the
better he looks. In this film, his wrinkled, hardtack face is
perfect for the aging reporter. While the plot is fairly
predictable, Eastwood isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``20 Dates'' _ Ever since Albert Brooks's `Real Life'' in 1979,
the mock documentary has been a fascinating sub-genre. It peaked
with ``This Is Spinal Tap''; it hits rock bottom with this lame
effort from the egomaniacal, exploitative Myles Berkowitz. Neither
funny nor provocative, Berkowitz, as star-director-writer, has only
himself to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' _ This English import
suffers a bit from the heavy accents and slang of its gritty
gangsters, but it should be easier to comprehend on home video. You
can always hit the rewind button for an instant replay. Director
Guy Ritchie's debut is remarkable. If you liked ``The Brothers
McMullen,'' this one's for you, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: Aug. 17: ``Analyze This'' (DVD), ``EDtv,''
``The Duchess of Duke Street,'' ``Wishmaster 2,'' ``Keeping Up
Appearances,'' ``200 Cigarettes.'' Aug. 24: ``The Dreamlife of
Angels,'' ``Sense and Sensibility'' (DVD), ``Go,'' ``Chameleon.''
Aug. 31: ``Cleopatra,'' ``Titanic'' (DVD). Sept. 7: ``The Other
Sister,'' ``Twin Dragons,'' ``The Crow: Stairway to Heaven.'' Sept.
14: ``The Prince of Egypt'' (DVD), ``God Said Ha!,'' ``Children of
Heaven.'' Sept. 21: ``My Favorite Martian,'' ``Lulu on the
Bridge.'' Sept. 28: ``The Mummy.''
</P>
