<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-POWERMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WORLDS COLLIDE: PM5K MAKES IT BIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The limousine is parked across the street from the
outdoor cafe in the Fenway on a sunny July afternoon, and its owner
_ the guy whose head looks like an overgrown fluorescent-green
tennis ball _ clearly is the rock star having lunch. But Spider
One, frontman for Powerman 5000, is less a rock star than a local:
This was his neighborhood before he and the band moved to Los
Angeles two years ago, and though people say hi and glance his way,
no one disturbs his space.
</P>
<P>
   Fame, though, or a more heightened version thereof, may be
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Worlds Collide,'' Powerman 5000's first single from its
second major-label album, ``Tonight the Stars Revolt!,'' was the
most frequently added song on modern- and active-rock radio formats
when it was released last month. Powerman 5000's style _ hard,
aggressive, a mix of rap and singing _ is a chart-topping one. And
this group is no genre jumper; the guys have been at it for nearly
a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our first record came out,'' says Spider, of the February
'97 DreamWorks re-release of '95's ``The Blood-Splat Rating
System'' (remixed and renamed ``Mega!! Kung Fu Radio''), ``I don't
know if there was a rock album on the charts that I can remember.
But now with the success of Korn, Limp Bizkit, Orgy, Kid Rock . . .
I think a lot of people assume that you want to see those other
bands fail, but I'm the opposite; I'm rooting for everybody. If
Limp Bizkit is on the radio, then we are going to be on the
radio.''
</P>
<P>
   The band's first album, Spider says, sold about 80,000 copies
without benefit of radio or MTV play. That's not bad at all. This
time, with the industry machinery behind it and the zeitgeist in
synch, Spider is optimistic. He says, ``Everybody has been avoiding
the numbers game, trying to guess what it will do, but things are
looking good. Radio is blowing up, MTV added the video _ actually
playing it during the day, which floored us.''
</P>
<P>
   This optimism seems to be warranted because in the album's first
week on the charts, it came in at No. 46 in Billboard's Top 200; it
has sold 60,000 copies in two weeks. Powerman 5000 _ nicknamed PM5K
and comprising guitarists Adam 12 and M.33, bassist Dorian 27, and
drummer Al 3 _ plays Avalon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less rooted in rage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While PM5K shares a kind of sonic-assault approach with Limp
Bizkit and company, it is on the whole smarter, more progressive,
more willing to deviate from form, and less rooted in the
overwrought demonstrations of rage and anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick for us,'' explains Spider, ``is to be aggressive and
heavy, but not brutal. Because I know how I feel when I hear a band
that's just so over the top it's just like beating me over the
skull with this sort of thing that's, like, fake. . . . I think
that most people's tortured-soul trip is so contrived it's
pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal . . . has always been to have the kind of band
that can go wherever we feel like it should go and not seem like an
uncomfortable shift in music. So on the next record, if we want to
get heavier, or we want to go back to more funky stuff, or
incorporate more rap like we used to do, nothing is going to stop
us. A lot of bands, for better or worse, paint themselves in a
corner. . . . I think if you set it up at the beginning as the type
of band where people don't know what to expect, but still stay
somewhat focused and have your sound. . . . I think people like
Nine Inch Nails can do that, have that industrial rock sound, but
take it wherever. People don't get freaked out because they expect
the change. That's the kind of band that we all wanna be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight the Stars Revolt!'' is nobody's idea of a soft album _
it's certainly riff-heavy _ but the band incorporated some spacy
interludes, emphasized melody more, and even ended the disc with a
Cars cover (``Good Times Roll'') and a jazzy selection (``Watch the
Sky for Me''). It's a multilayered disc, and not, as Spider says,
``the white boy rap/rock thing again. That was essentially what we
were doing, but I always saw the band as more than that.'' Indeed,
with the Cars cover and a certain robotic Devo-esque feel in
evidence, Spider says, laughing, ``we have always suffered from the
rap slash rock slash hard-core slash metal (tag) and I suppose now
they can add slash new wave and maybe even slash disco.
</P>
<P>
   As to the pop shift, Spider says, ``We realized that most of the
stuff that we listened to leaned almost to a poppier edge. Those
are the songs that we love and that everybody knows _ and you can
sing along to 'em. We wanted to try to do a little bit of that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `An evil word'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spider, the group's lyricist and younger brother of Rob Zombie,
loves sci-fi and cartoon images. If he can raise the
phantasmagorical level in a song, he will do it. This time, there
may even be a concept behind this album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every interview I have done,'' says Spider, ``I think the word
`concept album' comes up, so I am beginning to believe that maybe
it is one. It is such an evil word, because what is a concept
album? I think people equate it with sort of this '70s pretentious,
progressive rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why it is focused like that is because it was the
first record we got to make in a relatively short period of time.
Everybody's head was sort of focused in the same place.'' That
place is not specifically the world of comic-book characters and
action figures, he says. Rather, the focus came about this way: ``I
started to get really into sort of a 1940s-'50s version of the
future. I thought it was really interesting how people's vision of
what tomorrow is supposed to be like has changed drastically. There
used to be a sense of hope and a positive outlook _ like technology
will prevail and we'll all be happy and the streets will be clean
and we'll all wear like matching jumpsuits. I thought what was
really interesting was how at a certain point in time that vision
of the future has become a `Bladerunner'-esque'/`Alien' thing,
overpopulated with death and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pick up those old 1940s magazines like `Amazing
Stories' there's this real sense of adventure _ that the one hero
with the laser gun is gonna save the world. And I just thought,
`What a refreshing outlook on things.' And so to me that was at
least the starting point of the inspiration for the record. It
doesn't really mean that all the songs are about that _ the concept
intrigued me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not, then, reality-based rock. ``I keep saying, there are
so many bands now,'' says Spider, ``and their whole trip is `We're
keepin' it real,' and I think `Powerman 5000 is keeping it unreal.'
That's what rock's about, that's what entertainment's about, and .
. . it certainly keeps it much more interesting to me. I wouldn't
make the assumption that my life as it is is that interesting that
somebody would want to hear about it in a song.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Spider is not a fan of your-diary-as-your-art
songwriting. ``I don't even wanna hear my diary,'' he says, with a
laugh, ``so I would never make that assumption that other people
would.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
