<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0647 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CONTENDER-BOS &LR;      08-09 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CONTENDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO WOULD BE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CONTENDER 
Richard Nixon: The Congress Years 1946-1952 
By Irwin F. Gellman. Free Press. 590 pp. Illustrated. $30. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, Richard M. Nixon became the only man to
resign the presidency. Human nature being what it is, it's unlikely
Nixon will remain alone in presidential ignominy (lest we forget,
less than a year ago Bill Clinton came perilously close to joining
him). No, the single most extraordinary thing about Richard Nixon's
singularly extraordinary career isn't how he left public life but
the rapidity with which he rose in it. In slightly more than seven
years, he went from a lieutenant commander in the Navy to vice
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The steps he took on that ascent are well documented: the upset
victory over a nationally known liberal Democrat, US Representative
Jerry Voorhis; the pivotal role in the Alger Hiss affair; the
bruising defeat of another nationally known liberal Democrat, US
Representative Helen Gahagan Douglas, to gain a US Senate seat in
1950; and the wheeling and dealing among the camps of Republican
presidential contenders Dwight Eisenhower, Robert Taft, and Earl
Warren that led to what would have seemed all but unthinkable six
months before: the spectacle of Nixon, not yet 40, poised to be a
heartbeat away from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   It would be another 16 years, in their own way even more
improbable and event-filled than the preceding seven, before he
attained the White House _ but attain it he did. Even as they set
him on his way, those first seven years would set the pattern for
the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   From the very start, controversy surrounded him. This, too, has
been copiously _ and often tendentiously _ documented. Against
Voorhis, Nixon ran, if not a dirty campaign, then certainly one
that was far from pristine. On the other hand, Voorhis was
increasingly unpopular in his district, and 1946 was perhaps the
best possible year in this century to be running as a Republican.
Nixon won fair, if not altogether square.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly exploited the Hiss scandal for all its very
considerable political worth, and may or may not have been
previously tipped off to reports of Hiss's communist involvement.
But the fact remains that much of the bad odor surrounding Nixon's
conduct depends on the assumption of Hiss's innocence, an
assumption that long ago ceased to be tenable.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950 Senate campaign was famously mephitic _ but on both
sides. For all that Nixon stooped to calling Douglas ``pink right
down to her underwear,'' she popularized the name ``Tricky Dick''
and all but called him a fascist.
</P>
<P>
   As for the vice-presidential nomination, Nixon behaved with
breathtaking disingenuousness in the weeks leading up to the
convention, trying desperately to play each camp off against the
other for his own advantage. Even so, his selection as Eisenhower's
running mate was virtually ordained by political considerations.
Who better to stand alongside an elderly nominee, backed by the
Eastern wing of the party and presented as being explicitly ``above
politics,'' than a youngish Californian and famously ferocious
campaigner whose impeccable anticommunist credentials endeared him
to Midwestern hard-liners?
</P>
<P>
   The great fascination of Nixon's early career lies not in these
justly famed events but rather in what went on in between them. How
did this least clubbable of men navigate the dense thicket of
protocol and backslapping that is life in the House (the world's
largest Rotary meeting) and the Senate (the self-styled ``world's
most exclusive club'')? California elections, where personality and
advertising took precedence over party and organization, were a
kind of political laboratory for the rest of the nation. To what
extent was Nixon a creature, or creator, of Golden State-style
campaigning? A candidate who started out in politics professing
``practical liberalism'' _ a rubric that works as well as any,
actually, in describing the career of the man who gave us the
Environmental Protection Agency and peacetime wage-and-price
controls along with ``the Southern strategy'' and the White House
Plumbers _ how did his politics evolve and mesh with those of a
party that claimed Joseph McCarthy as well as Margaret Chase Smith?
</P>
<P>
   In describing public life, Nixon loved to cite Theodore
Roosevelt's image of ``the man in the arena.'' It's not the arena
but the man who usually gets attended to in studies of Nixon _ and
understandably so. During these seven years, though, it's the arena
_ the context in which he moved _ that's perhaps even more
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin F. Gellman thinks otherwise. The author of three books on
Franklin D. Roosevelt's foreign policy, he claims to have examined
``every catalogued item . . . covering Nixon's congressional
career'' at the presidential library in Yorba Linda, Calif. There
is no reason to doubt it. ``The Contender,'' the first volume of a
projected trilogy, offers an unrelenting parade of unmediated fact.
Gellman sees himself as presenting a revisionist view of this
period, showing us a Nixon more sinned against than sinning. ``His
political rise demonstrates that while he was not perfect, he was a
dedicated, efficient public servant. The time has come to let his
record, for good and ill, speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a valid, if simplistic, interpretation of these years,
and the aim expressed in the second sentence is laudable, but
Gellman's plodding presentation and predictable argumentation do
little to further either. Dedicated and efficient the young Nixon
surely was. But even as Gellman again and again demonstrates that
Nixon did not violate the letter of a given law, we see a man so
consumed by ambition _ and so caught up in a headlong rush of
events _ that he found himself unable to recognize the law's
spirit. Worse, as the contender moved on to ever-greater arenas,
the rules kept changing, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mark Feeney is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WRACK-BOS &LR;      08-09 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WRACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST IN THE SANDS OF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WRACK 
By James Bradley 
Holt. 340 pp. $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The search for the past, however illusory, is usually an
admirable pursuit for writers. When they reach for meaning in
yesterday, we call it literature; when they reach toward tomorrow,
we call it science fiction. We have Herodotus to thank for this, as
well as the detritus left by every century hence. As much as
Einstein might protest, what's already gone seems eminently more
concrete and knowable than what hasn't yet occurred.
</P>
<P>
   These mutable issues of time _ its promises, deceits, and
forever shifting sands _ are what consume Australian writer James
Bradley, providing the arc of his first novel as well as most of
its poetic ventures. Published in Australia in 1997, ``Wrack''
received a number of literary accolades (including a couple of
prizes) and the critical acclaim of the British and Australian
press. With its collusion between history and geography, its
mirrored cruelties of love and war, and its wounded, morphine-mad
witness, it will call to mind Canadian Michael Ondaatje's 1992
novel, ``The English Patient.'' Bradley's American publisher has
prepared us for this comparison with the insistence that the novel
is ``at once reminiscent of `The English Patient' and `Heart of
Darkness.' '' But the plot is so similar to Ondaatje's _ a pair of
lovers tending a dying man in a remote locale, with narrative
voices woven between past and present _ that ``Wrack'' can't help
feeling derivative. At the very least, it's difficult not to be
thinking of one while reading the other.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the sandy provinces of New South Wales, ``Wrack'' careers
between the maritime quests of 500 years ago and an archeological
dig of the present, and its most compelling story swings gracefully
between both tenses. Historian turned archeologist David Norfolk
has spent years searching for the remains of a ghostly Portuguese
ship, one he believes to have been commanded in the 15th century by
an explorer named de Cueva. Its remains, if discovered, could
explain the myths of the past (among them a lost land mass called
Java la Grande) and rewrite the white man's ``discovery'' of
Australia. Norfolk's pursuits are not without precedent: He has
pieced together a great deal of research, both evidentiary and
theoretical, from the 1930s, most of it the work of academic
mavericks who wound up discredited for their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   On his last leg of funding from the university, David and his
team uncover a corpse, probably secreted in the dunes some 50 years
ago, near the presumed site of the shipwreck. Their discovery leads
David to a meeting with a former lover, Claire, the physician now
in charge of the autopsy. However dismaying this find, it seems
irrelevant to David's mission until a detective on the case
mentions ``the old bloke down in the shack'' _ a hermit who has
been on the same beach for decades and who, according to local
lore, was once searching for a ship.
</P>
<P>
   What David unearths is the stuff of history as well as fiction,
and that intersection _ that pact of intrigue and regret _ is what
elevates ``Wrack'' to a tale of great pacing and emotional punch.
The old man turns out to be Kurt Seligman, once an assistant to the
renegade historian Fraser McDonald, who had believed in and sought
the lost Portuguese ship. Grotesquely maimed years earlier, now
dying from cancer, Kurt begins to reveal the long, bitter truth to
David _ aware that he has found a deathbed witness for his story,
and more than ready to pull him into the vortex of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Claire has begrudgingly joined David in caring for the dying
man; less invested in Kurt's mysteries, she is also less trusting
of him, and her wariness serves as a warning to the reader. But
Kurt sways us as well as his confidant, for his past is something
out of ``Casablanca'' _ a prewar tale of three lovers entwined,
with Fraser and Kurt both vying for an opera singer named Veronica.
The shards of this anguished recollection are delivered in Kurt's
own narrative voice, so that the reader is thrust among different
viewpoints (David's present, Kurt's past, Bradley's distanced
narrative about time and history) with riveting ease. By the end of
``Wrack,'' one is as consumed with the struggle for Kurt's soul _
with the ``facts'' and memories of his alliances and betrayals _ as
with the hidden shipwreck that has claimed a piece of everyone
here.
</P>
<P>
   You can sense Bradley's background as a poet in ``Wrack,'' which
has a lofty feel to its prose even when it's cast in somewhat
brittle machismo (all the lovers tend to talk like Hemingway's men
and women). While dialogue may not be Bradley's strength, he is
masterful at the occasionally lovely, terse description: Veronica
delivers a perfect soprano while David imagines ``her ribs a
cathedral of bone and air.'' And Bradley's own sojourns into time
and space _ into cartography, Euclidean geometry, the juncture
where memory meets want _ provide a well-plotted course for a story
that, in the end, is beholden to mystery itself.
</P>
<P>
   What James Bradley has set out to capture in this delicate novel
may be the same grail that so eluded and consumed his protagonist:
the etchings traced by human experience upon the map of history,
with one enhancing, rather than obscuring, the other. I do wish his
publisher had thought to illustrate with a map of Australia, or
Terra Australis, or Java la Grande. The novel begs for this blend
of artful myth and history, and such a guide would have made Kurt's
and David's passions seem more tangible, or at least more real. But
then ``real'' is a relative construct within the world of ``Wrack''
_ a place of dreams and landscapes constantly in motion, where even
love has a way of leaving before you see its face.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BENJAMIN-BOS &LR;      08-09 1530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BENJAMIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE BENJAMIN RETURNS TO TANGLEWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX _ George Benjamin was born in 1960, and he has been an
internationally prominent composer for nearly half his life. He was
only 20 when the BBC Symphony Orchestra programmed his first major
orchestral piece, ``Ringed by the Flat Horizon,'' during the annual
Proms concerts in London's Royal Albert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   This summer Benjamin is one of the composers in residence at the
Tanglewood Music Center. Earlier this week he could be discovered
playing Frisbee in the lawn with some of the students, and he could
easily have been mistaken for one of them. Two of his remarkable
works were heard during the annual Tanglewood Festival of
Contemporary Music a week ago. Last weekend conductor Robert Spano
will lead soprano Dawn Upshaw and the Boston Symphony Orchestra in
a performance of Benjamin's ``A Mind of Winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Composed in 1981, this qualifies as an early work. ``I wrote it
while I was still studying at Cambridge University,'' Benjamin
says. ``I wrote it because I had fallen in love with the poem by
Wallace Stevens; the piece wasn't commissioned by or for anybody. I
wrote it because I had to. The poem has this metaphysical
description of a landscape with a snowman in it. The piece lasts
about nine minutes, and it is mostly quiet and meditative, but
there are also some places that pull out all of the stops. There is
a wind that blows through and across everything, and then
everything settles down again. The focus throughout is on the vocal
line. It was premiered at Benjamin Britten's Aldeburgh Festival,
but after Britten died.'' Benjamin talked about his life and music
over lunch in a Chinese restaurant near Tanglewood he was eager to
return to because he liked the spiced eggplant so much. He's a
cheerfully unpretentious, sunny person, with both the pixie humor
and the earthiness of Papageno in Mozart's ``The Magic Flute.''
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier youth, Benjamin was a pianist of virtuoso
standard, but he says he was composing from the moment he first sat
down at the keyboard. The piano was not his first instrument. He
began playing the recorder along with all the other children in
preschool; at age 5 his exceptional musical gift was already
apparent. The school music teacher, Miss Trury, was a pianist, and
encouraged him to start studying the instrument when he was 7.
``She was a bossy little lady, but a good and a demanding teacher.
As I learned to read music, I started scribbling down little pieces
of my own. By the time I was 13, it was time to move up one level,
so I went to Peter Gellhorn, a man of huge musical culture, a
wonderfully civilized man, who had been trained in Berlin before
World War II. He was my general music teacher _ piano, composition,
everything. Then when I was 16 he took me to Paris and turned me
over to Olivier Messiaen. I didn't realize then how extraordinarily
generous that was; teachers are usually possessive, aren't they? I
think Messiaen was intrigued by me because of this gesture of Peter
Gellhorn's.''
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen was one of the towering figures of 20th-century music,
and young Benjamin became a particular favorite of the old
master's; Benjamin also studied piano with Messiaen's wife, the
formidable Yvonne Loriod. ``Imagine what this was like for me. I
was still a schoolboy, writing incidental music for plays at
school. Messiaen had such sweetness, dignity, and courtesy; I was
his `Benjamin,' his baby one. He never told anyone to do anything _
you didn't even have to go to class, which he held three times a
week, four or five hours a session. He would analyze music of the
past or his own music, or talk about subjects that interested him,
like rhythm, or color, or birdsong. It was an enthralling time.''
</P>
<P>
   While studying with Messiaen, Benjamin lived with a series of
French families. ``They kept throwing me out because I was
composing my piano sonata at the instrument, and no one could stand
it.'' He made quite an impression when he would perform his sonata.
``I broke strings every time I played it, and in Paris a key flew
right off the piano and into the audience. I don't play it anymore,
and I don't even like it very much, but (British pianist) Peter
Donohoe still plays it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ringed by the Flat Horizon'' is the principal work Benjamin
composed while working with Messiaen. ``Every time I had a new 10
pages, I would take them to the class, much to the annoyance of my
fellow students. It was first performed by the student orchestra at
Cambridge, and then the conductor, Mark Elder, took it down to the
Proms, and that gave me a push.''
</P>
<P>
   Hailed as a genius and the bright hope of British music at 20,
Benjamin wisely followed his own course and did not pour out a
series of sequels to ``Ringed by the Flat Horizon.'' He stayed in
school, at Cambridge University, where his final teacher was
Alexander Goehr, a composer of considerable distinction who has
served as mentor to several generations of prominent British
composers and whose impact on Benjamin was ``considerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the two decades of Benjamin's prominence, his list of
compositions, like that of Henri Dutilleux in France, has not grown
long. Benjamin is a fastidious craftsman, and his works are
notable, among other things, for attention to detail. ``Well, I
haven't written that little,'' Benjamin says; he's probably heard
more criticism of his perfectionism than he needs to. ``After all,
there are eight or nine orchestral pieces _ and it could have been
only five! It is true that I am a very slow composer, or, to put it
better, I'm slow to start; starting is the slow bit. The first
measure is the most important because everything else is implicit
in it, so it can take me up to a year to find the beginning. But
once I've done that, then everything moves quite fast; most of my
pieces have been finished within two weeks. The process is about
failing and failing and failing until I discover what I'm doing.
I'm particularly careful about the harmonic side _ I like
complexity, but the kind that doesn't necessarily show itself. I
like the kind of powerful harmony that spreads itself across a
whole piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Benjamin no longer puts himself forward as a pianist,
he did astonish a late-night Tanglewood audience with his
improvised accompaniment to Fritz Lang's classic silent film
``Metropolis.'' His preferred medium of performance these days is
conducting, and though he has been highly successful, the art and
skill of conducting still fascinate him. He's been sitting in on
Robert Spano's conducting classes at Tanglewood, and this summer he
has become a particular admirer of the physical specificity and
emotional suggestiveness of Seiji Ozawa's rehearsals and
performances. Benjamin conducted his own pieces during the
contemporary music festival and volunteers that Seiji Ozawa Hall is
the most beautiful space he has ever performed in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lessons of conducting
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some composers have found that conducting interfered with the
amount of time that composition takes _ Pierre Boulez is the most
prominent contemporary example. Benjamin believes that conducting
has helped his composing: ``Conducting helps me learn new things
about other music, about my own music, and about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently Benjamin advised the BBC on 500 broadcasts surveying
the music of the 20th century; he also conducted his first opera,
Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande,'' at the Theatre de la Monnaie in
Brussels, with Jose van Dam as Golaud. Asked if he plans to compose
an opera himself, Benjamin responds with a question: ``Who knows?''
Then he says he will do no further conducting for the next six
months because he needs to write a piece commissioned for Boulez
and the London Symphony Orchestra; he also owes one to the Berlin
Philharmonic. ``But one piece a year is all I aspire to,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's music has the sensuousness of surface and
intellectual rigor one would expect from a composer with his
background, and he is unapologetic about it. `` `Accessibility' is
an awful word, isn't it? Some of the `accessible' music being
written today is music no one really likes or no one really needs;
it is based on a vague idea of what people who don't like music
might like if they liked music. There is no potential for tears, or
for anything glorious. It is terribly sad when someone with an
original talent gets derailed by the need to be accessible. We need
a system which allows, encourages, demands composers to be
courageous _ and with all the supporting systems in place as well.
We need an intelligentsia to listen to and support new work, and to
argue about it at the very highest standard. I believe in elitism,
not as a matter of class or of wealth, but as a matter of quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am not as pessimistic about the situation of music as
some people are. There are always young people who are willing to
play new music _ there are lots of them here at Tanglewoood _ and
there are always composers who are passionate about the things they
have to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
