<HEADLINE>
GOP'S GREEDY TAX-CUT PLAN IS MORE GOOD NEWS FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans really outdid themselves this time.
The 10-year, $792 billion tax cut bill they passed last week is so
bad for the majority of Americans that criticism of it can hardly
be overstated.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the GOP has accomplished two results with this bill. It
has managed to insult the intelligence of millions of Americans who
know the tax cut is not for them.
</P>
<P>
   And it hands President Clinton another victory when he keeps his
promise and vetoes the unpopular bill. That will only add to his
political strength as he campaigns for Vice President Al Gore to
succeed him and for other Democrats seeking congressional seats.
</P>
<P>
   The question might be asked about the GOP bill: ``Just how bad
is it?'' It's so bad it's rightfully called a tax cut for the
wealthy. And the higher the taxpayer's salary, the more the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Based on research from the Citizens for Tax Justice, an
independent tax foundation in Washington, and from the Clinton
administration's Office of Management and Budget, the tax cut isn't
so good for working families struggling to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, 20 percent of the nation's taxpayers, including
members of Congress, would reap 82 percent of all the benefits. The
remaining 80 percent of taxpayers would reap only 18 percent of the
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The richest, the 1 percent who earn more than $300,000 a year,
would receive 42 percent of the tax benefits under the bill. Their
average cut would be $46,000 a year. In contrast, working men and
women would receive an average savings of only $138 a year, less
than 40 cents a day.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut bill would devastate domestic programs _ from Head
Start to medical research to law enforcement _ that are both
important and necessary to millions of working families.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining the same level of funding for these programs over
the next 10 years would require $595 billion additional real
dollars to cover inflation. With the GOP tax cut bill, that money
woiuld no longer be there, and the programs would suffer at least a
38 percent cut in funding.
</P>
<P>
   This would mean, for example, that 6.5 million fewer children
would be served by the Title I education program, with 140,000
fewer biomedical research grants, 6,300 fewer FBI agents and
100,000 fewer local police.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans estimate the budget surplus is $964
billion, but that amount includes the $595 billion needed to fund
the domestic programs at the same level during the decade of the
tax cut. That leaves a real surplus of only $370 billion, which is
far less than the $792 billion bill.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton has stressed, the nation would be better
served if the budget surplus was geared toward protecting Medicare
and Social Security. Clinton and other Democrats are willing to
have a limited tax cut, but only after there is fiscal assurance
that those major programs are protected.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP cut would put the Republicans' own interest, if not
special interests, before the people's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare has severe funding problems, and if additional
resources are not forthcoming, the program is likely to become
insolvent, broke, in the next 15 years. Under Clinton and the
Democrats, the projected surpluses would be used to extend the
healthy life of the program as well as to pay for prescriptions and
other drug benefits for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security could face similar trouble under the GOP bill.
Currently, the program has enough resources to continue through
2035, but a shortfall is predicted after that. The Democrats would
use the surplus to help keep Social Security going strong far
beyond 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   During the current recess, House and Senate Republicans are
hitting the trail to persuade voters to support the bill before
they put it on Clinton's desk early next month. But the fact that
the Republicans still think they can persuade the majority to
support a bill for the rich shows just how much out of touch the
GOP still is with the country.
</P>
<P>
   And since the media has gone to town outlining who actually
would benefit most from these cuts, the chances are slim and
slimmer that the GOP could muster enough national support to
persuade Clinton to rescind his promise or even override his
expected veto of the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats point out that the bill includes $60 billion worth of
tax breaks sought by lobbyists. For example, business and
restaurant lobbyists would gain an increase in their deductions,
from 50 to 60 percent, at a cost of $3.8 billion. And
manufacturers, including Silicon Valley firms, would receive a
five-year extension of their research and development tax credits,
worth more than $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Republicans decided to give a little more to the
average American to get the bill passed, their arguments still
would not be persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   The average American _ not in the 1 percent or even 20 percent
income bracket _ knows that maintaining important domestic programs
and keeping Medicare and Social Security fiscally solvent are far
more important goals than a tax cut that could bankrupt their
futures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
