<HEADLINE>
PRE-PAID CELLPHONE CARDS STARTING TO CONNECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We thought we'd discovered all the good cellular phone deals
until we got an e-mail last week from Tom Metro, a computer
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   He asked us why we never wrote about pre-paid cell phone cards
as a low-cost way for skeptics to try wireless phone service. Metro
had been shopping around for a plan for his elderly mother, who
wants a cell phone for emergencies only. He found a Cellular One
pre-paid analog plan for $90 that includes 120 minutes and lasts an
entire year.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cost for each minute is a hefty 75 cents, this plan's
one-year $90 cost compares favorably to most standard monthly plans
that cost at least $200 a year. And the offer lasts a year, while
most pre-paid minutes expire in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   With analog handsets so cheap these days (maybe even free if you
can find someone who has abandoned an analog handset after
converting to a digital phone), this pre-paid option struck Metro
as a smart solution for a safety-oriented user.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. And he's also onto a new trend in the wireless
world: promoting pre-paid cards not only to serve those who don't
financially qualify for standard contracts, but to first-timers or
transient folks who don't want big commitments or monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless analysts say companies in New York, Miami, and
Philadelphia have already slashed prices on pre-paid cards and
sweetened the terms to attract a wide mix of consumers. Some
discount resellers are getting into the act there as well.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the pre-paid cellular phone market is just starting
to heat up. AT&AMP;T Wireless has yet to offer any pre-paid cards here,
but other major carriers have begun lowering prices and tinkering
with terms of their pre-paid cards.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Thigpen, vice president and general manager of pre-paid
services for Boston Communications Group in Woburn, Mass., which
runs pre-paid card systems for carriers, said Boston lags behind
other cities in this niche market. But he sees signs that carriers
view these cards as ways to draw in first-time users, as well as
teenagers, college students, or temporary residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're extending beyond the credit-challenged,'' he said,
using a phrase frequently heard in the industry to describe people
with nonexistent or bad credit histories that disqualify them for
standard contracts.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a cell phone with any regularity you're far better
off going with a standard contract, assuming you qualify. Permanent
charges on standard plans are as low as a dime or a quarter a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the most aggressive pre-paid seller is Omnipoint, and
roughly half its customers are pre-paid users. This company's $50
pre-paid card buys 125 minutes, for instance. It comes to 40 cents
a minute, the lowest pre-paid price in the Boston market. Minutes
expire in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS revamped its pre-paid offerings this past May,
promoting lower per-minute prices and no expiration dates. But
there's two negative surprises in the package: There's a $125
activation fee and you must pay a 50-cent daily maintenance charge
on top of your usage, which amounts to a $15 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Duncan, marketing manager for Sprint PCS in New England,
said the company is trying to turn its ``credit-challenged''
customers in another direction, to its ``Account Spending Limit''
program that puts a spending lid on an account. In this way, people
can go with cheaper per-minute standard contracts.
</P>
<P>
   If you must buy your own handset, keep in mind that analog ones
may become defunct in a year or so as the entire cellular world
goes digital. Don't pay a lot for an analog phone if you have to
buy one.
</P>
<P>
   While a Yankee Group study finds that prepaid accounts represent
about 4 percent of wireless subscribers, analysts predict more
people will flock to this option as prices drop and expiration
dates become more distant. That's likely to bring in many who might
now be on the sidelines, turned off by the upfront costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies are starting to focus more on the neophytes and
skeptics,'' said Lowenstein of the Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
E-commerce and sales tax
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the growth of Internet buying, we've gotten more questions
about when buyers have to pay Massachusetts sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   State revenue officials say Internet purchases are viewed the
same as mail-order buys. If the company selling the product has ``a
physical presence in Massachusetts'' _ such as a retail store,
warehouse, phone banks or sales offices _ it must collect sales tax
from the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this covers only ``taxable items'' as defined by this
state. So if you buy a $50 sweater on-line from the Gap clothing
store, which has a physical presence here, the store can't collect
sales tax because a clothing item under $175 is not taxable.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, associate general counsel for the state Department
of Revenue, said shipping and handling charges are generally
considered exempt from sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Now get this: The law goes further to say that if the company
does not have a physical presence here and you buy a taxable item
from them, such as a computer, it is your responsibility to send in
the appropriate sales tax amount to the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   (State revenue officials say this is a ``tough tax to
collect.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   --Cell phones and 911: If you have a spare cell phone, keep in
mind that Federal Communications Commission rules require carriers
to put through any 911 emergency call on any handset. That includes
handsets that no longer have an active service contract. That means
if you had an old analog phone with Cellular One, but let the
service contract lapse, you can still use that phone for 911 calls.
Cellular One has to put through the call, at its own expense. So
spare cell phones, which might now be used as a child's toy, might
be better off charged-up and in a car's glove compartment.
</P>
<P>
   --Minimum purchases on credit cards? A reader recently asked if
merchants are allowed to set minimum purchase requirements when
using a Visa card. She recently wanted to charge $5 in gasoline.
She said the clerk insisted on an $8 minimum for credit card
purchases. The clerk also offered to charge $8, then return $3 back
in cash. There's no state or federal law on the subject, but Visa
regulations prohibit merchants from setting minimum purchase
requirements or giving cash back. If such violations are brought to
Visa's attention, their contract can be terminated. Said a Visa
spokeswoman: ``Technically, you can charge a pack of gum.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(We want your consumer ideas and tips. Please call 617-474-2510 or
e-mail Wen at wen(at)globe.com or Mohl at mohl(at)globe.com. Their
postal address is PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
