<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEPOT-BLANK-COX     08-09 2019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-BLANK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Executive pushes new concepts, expansion in other countries.
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe Atlanta Braves manager Bobby Cox should've kept
Arthur Blank on the mound this season.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's chief executive officer threw out the first pitch
July 28, just before the night quickly turned into a 10-4 Braves
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Blank's ceremonial toss was a little high but not far off the
mark. Pretty decent for a guy throwing with a toddler on his hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't bad, huh?'' said a smiling Blank as he returned to
his seat with his 2 1/2-year-old son, Joshua.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Blank has collected plenty of wins at Home
Depot. In his third year as chief executive of the world's largest
home improvement retailer, he's aiming at more targets than ever in
the company's 20-year history.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Atlanta Journal-Constitution during the
baseball game, Blank explained how his job is changing as the
company charts new territory, and how he's building the troops to
keep up. The strategy is designed to keep the bottom line solid and
Wall Street happy.
</P>
<P>
   New generation
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and co-founder Bernie Marcus bequeathed the CEO post to
Blank in 1997, following nearly two decades of incredible growth.
Revenue climbed from $7 million in 1979 to more than $30 billion
today.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several years, Home Depot has evolved from its
scrappy built-from-scratch roots, and the job of the CEO has
matured along with it, Blank said.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking on the new title, Blank was known as the
numbers-crunching president who kept the bottom line lean. Now he's
showing off his visionary side.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role is certainly very different than Bernie's was in the
earlier days of our company,'' Blank said. ``Back then, we were
just trying to open the stores. Now the role is much more complex
because we're thinking about how to drive deeper into the industry
and how to serve customers differently in other segments of the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming CEO, he has taken a swing at several new areas
outside the company's foolproof retail warehouse domain, including
a new-and-improved Expo Design Center, the first Home Depot outside
North America and the brand-new Villager's Hardware retail concept.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the company isn't still busy peppering the landscape
with its bread-
</P>
<P>
   and-butter warehouse stores. Now at roughly 800 locations, Home
Depot plans to have 1,600 by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Blank leaves the logistics of day-to-day
operations to his tactical team.
</P>
<P>
   Pausing to check out a perfect bunt by the Brewers, he explained
he spends most of his time plotting growth opportunities 15 years
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   As the company prepares to double in size, he also has to find
the talent to support that growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of boundless thinking to make sure that people are
moved around regardless of divisions and to find the best available
person to attack an issue,'' Blank said. ``We don't restrict our
promotions by divisions. We look at the whole company and find the
best person.''
</P>
<P>
   Blank has shown he's willing to look beyond the home team if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, as the company embarked on an international
expansion and a national rollout of the Expo stores, he hired
outsiders to fill two high-ranking posts:
</P>
<P>
   -- David Suliteanu, a former vice chairman of Macy's East, was
put in the newly created position of group president of diversified
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dennis Carey, a former vice president of AT&AMP;T with
international experience, became the new chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an easy time for the Home Depot veterans who were
passed over for the new positions, Blank recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people moved from center field to left field to nurture
the standards of our core business, while the other areas of growth
got new support,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's to our senior managers' credit that they looked at
these (outside) folks and realized they have certain backgrounds
and expertise ... that some of our folks just didn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotshot or not, all recruits put on an apron for a baptism that
begins in the aisles of Big Orange. It's a training tradition the
company will likely never get rid of.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Marcus, still very active in training at age 70,
conducts about eight ``Bernie Road Shows'' a year at the company's
stores. Home Depot also requires its board members to visit stores
frequently and interview employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always believed that the culture of our company and the
essence of our truth is in the stores,'' said Blank, who visits
about 100 stores a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets an important role model for our management to see the
president and CEO is visiting the stores, especially for the people
we bring into the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blank is well-suited for the store walks. Athletic and
competitive, he said he likes to be where the action is. As a high
school baseball player, Blank relished being catcher because he
could be in the middle of every play.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's sweltering game, Blank and his family passed up
the luxury suites to eat hot dogs and peanuts in the stands with
the rest of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has been grooming the next generation of leaders,
Blank indicated he has plenty of years left at Home Depot's
headquarters in Vinings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no clock ticking. I'm relatively young (56), and I
have a very good balance in my life,'' the CEO said. ``The board is
very supportive, and my wife, Stephanie, is very supportive. As
long as I have that balance and I'm having fun, there's no reason
not to keep doing what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing new concepts
</P>
<P>
   Blank has his hands full steering Home Depot in new directions.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the long-term growth strategy is the rollout of
its upscale Expo stores. The five-year plan calls for 200 Expos
nationally. The division will end this year with 15 stores, and the
company plans to double its size next year. Metro Atlanta, which
has one store, will soon get two more Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Blank is confident that consumers will continue to be able to
afford $6,000 refrigerators, $16,000 Oriental rugs and other pricey
items aimed at home designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to see a recession, at least not across the
entire country. We may see something regional, but even so, we're
an international company, so we are supported in other areas,''
Blank said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, every Expo decision is made on a long-term basis. If the
economy gets hit for six months, or even a year, it won't make a
long-term difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Blank and Marcus have always had a careful, methodical strategy,
often testing a new idea for years before taking the concept
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Expo was nearly 10 years in the making. Also, while other
retailers are leaping into cyberspace, the company is showing its
trademark caution in opening an Internet site for sales.
</P>
<P>
   Another long-range venture is Villager's Hardware, a new
convenience home-repair concept that just debuted in New Jersey.
Early sales are running ahead of expectations, but it will be in
the test mode for an unspecified time, Blank noted.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally have favored all of the growth plans, but
they're especially eager about Home Depot's ``pro initiative.'' The
company has been testing ways to aggressively court small
contractors, plumbers, electricians and other commercial customers
because they represent a big opportunity in repeat business.
</P>
<P>
   These small professionals spend about $215 billion a year for
supplies. Currently, however, they represent only 20 percent to 30
percent of Home Depot's sales. ``The pro business will probably
influence sales and profitability more than any of the other
initiatives,'' said analyst Dan Wewer of Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, Arthur is really pushing the needle on growth,''
Wewer added. ``He has been a much more aggressive CEO than
Bernie.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing globally
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves fought for their first run of the evening, Blank
talked about one of his biggest challenges: How do you spread the
do-it-yourself fever overseas?
</P>
<P>
   With Canada under its belt, Home Depot has looked at other
countries from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the retailier made its first farflung effort with a
store in Santiago, Chile. The move into Latin America continues
next year with more stores in Chile and new locations in Buenos
Aires, Argentina. Next on the map could be China or England,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Home Depot announced it had hired Swedish executive
Anders Moberg to run its international operations. Moberg, former
president of home furnishings company Ikea Group, starts his global
tasks this month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Blank's choice was a big clue that the
globe-trotting could begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``International growth is going to be very important in the next
five to 15 years,'' Blank said. ``We'll be planting seeds in the
next five years, maybe in the Far East, or it could be in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Blank has said repeatedly he won't expand globally just for the
sake of collecting flags. ``There are challenges in all of our
growth initiatives, but the international realm is the most complex
because of real estate and the logistics of the supply chain.
Obviously, there are language and cultural differences to overcome,
too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the bottom line
</P>
<P>
   Even as the company finds new ways to sell home improvement _
whether it's through new store concepts, over the Internet or
overseas _ the expanding base of Home Depot stores will continue to
drive earnings, Blank said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the booming construction market and consumers who are
nuts about remodeling, Home Depot posted a 45 percent increase in
first-quarter profit. The second-quarter earnings report comes out
Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong growth sets the bar increasingly higher for the
company on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with Wall Street is that it's a
what-have-you-done-for-me-lately kind of business,'' said analyst
Wayne Hood of Prudential Securities in Atlanta. Hood has dropped
his rating on the stock to a ``hold'' because he sees more
potential for a rise in interest rates, which would likely slow
housing sales.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Wewer points out that Home Depot has met its overall
goal of 21 percent to 22 percent growth a year. ``And I don't see
any problem with keeping up that kind of growth for the next five
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Home Depot had a per-share profit of $1.06. This year
the retailer is expected to earn $1.38 a share, according to a
survey by IBES International.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's stock, meanwhile, has risen 50 percent in the past
12 months. The stock closed Friday down 37 1/2 cents to $63.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer or be hammered
</P>
<P>
   As far as the industry outlook, there's market share to pick up
as Home Depot and Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse, the distant
No. 2, continue to knock off the competition.
</P>
<P>
   While the No. 3 chain, Menard, has hung on with solid regional
growth in the Midwest, some other chains are downsizing. Hechinger,
the country's fourth-largest chain, has steadily shut stores that
overlap with Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot currently has about 18 percent of the $172 billion
home improvement market, and it could grow to 33 percent by 2003,
Wewer said. He estimates Lowe's will have as much as 13 percent
market share in that time.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Home Depot has lapped the competition several
times over, there's no room for coasting, Blank insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a poster of a lion and a gazelle outside my conference
room,'' Blank said as it became apparent that the Braves would lose
to the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gazelle has to get up in the morning and get running or
else it'll get eaten. The lion has to get up and get running, too,
or else it doesn't eat,'' Blank said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're a lion or a gazelle, you've got to get up and
get running. You don't walk. You don't trot. You run.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the philosophy of our company.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
