<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-VIOLENCE-BOS &LR;      08-09 1775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PEOPLE IN TV ARE TALKING ABOUT RESPONSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ A couple of weeks ago, while rehearsing a
shootout scene for an episode of CBS's ``Martial Law,'' Arsenio
Hall asked his director to change the scene so his cop character
would stop the bad guy with a single shot rather than a fusillade
of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before, Hall had recoiled when he was shown publicity
photos displaying him in dramatic gun-wielding poses. ``Throw those
away,'' he ordered his publicist.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times we get requests from kids for photos,'' Hall
explained. ``I can't send these pictures out of me with Berettas.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the Columbine High School massacre, which
put a harrowing exclamation point on a string of other school
shootings in the past two years, a rethinking of violence has
quietly threaded its way into decisions being made each day in the
conference rooms and on the sets where TV shows are created.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the upcoming fall season will not contain its
share of gunfire and gore, nor to say that everyone in the TV
industry accepts the notion of a causal link between small-screen
violence and the real-life kind. The prospect of censorship repels
many, who say the lion's share of the blame belongs with gun
manufacturers and their allies in Congress, not with Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But some who create the images that stream into the nation's 99
million TV homes _ especially those, like Hall, whose shows are
popular with young viewers _ say there is much more soul-searching
now about the possible effects of those images. ``It comes into my
life constantly,'' Hall said somberly.
</P>
<P>
   That theme echoed through numerous interviews with TV producers,
performers, and scriptwriters _ and, in some cases, words have been
backed up by action. On several programs slated to air this fall,
violent scenes are being reduced or rewritten so the bloodshed
occurs off-screen. On others, the story lines have shifted to
emphasize the consequences of violence, or to make the programs
``character-based'' rather than mayhem-based.
</P>
<P>
   At the WB network, whose primary audience is teenagers,
executives have urged producers of individual shows to explore
Columbine-linked themes like teen alienation. ``Does Columbine wake
you up a little bit? Yes,'' said WB president Jamie Kellner, though
he contended the network has always tried to treat violence
responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   Even Dick Van Dyke, whose ``Diagnosis Murder'' appeals primarily
to older viewers, took his writers and producers out to lunch a few
weeks after Columbine and laid down the law, saying, ``There will
be no AK-47s, no mass killings'' on the program, according to
supervising producer Steve Brown. Producers of the new mob drama
``Falcone'' promise that a graphic ice-pick murder seen in the
pilot episode will be reedited so the scene focuses on the reaction
of witnesses rather than the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's changing,'' remarked actress Christine Lahti, who
starred in ``Chicago Hope'' for five years. ``I think that people _
writers, producers, directors, and actors _ are feeling a kind of
accountability, that there shouldn't be so much violence on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Marshall, president of the Academy of Television Arts &AMP;
Sciences, said the TV industry is becoming more receptive to the
program ratings system and the content-blocking V-chip, both
designed to keep children from seeing violence (or sex or
profanity) on TV. ``The Hollywood community is focusing on its
responsibilities,'' said Marshall.``There's a consciousness about
their role, and the consequences, that's been heightened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new stigma
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If lurid violence was once seen as adding an edge, it now is
viewed as possibly adding a stigma, at least for the time being. TV
writers and producers, many of them parents themselves, say they
had a visceral response to the shootings at Columbine and five
other high schools since 1997. (So did network executives: Kellner
delayed airing the finale of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' because
it involved violence at a high school graduation, and CBS president
Leslie Moonves decided not to put ``Falcone'' on the fall schedule
because its violence was jolting when seen just after Columbine.
However, it is now slated for midseason.)
</P>
<P>
   But there is another, more basic reason, articulated by writer
Terry Curtis Fox, who admits he has written his share of scenes
involving violence: ``I want there to be shows for my kid to
watch.'' Fox said those who work in television have gotten the
message loud and clear that ``parents are really, really upset.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the TV industry's concerns about violence last when
political pressure and public outrage begin to abate, or if lower
body counts turn out to mean lower ratings? There is ample reason
for doubt.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, some vehemently contend the medium is being
scapegoated, along with movies and video games, for violence that
should be blamed on the proliferation of guns and the failure by
many parents to act parental. Calls for restraint on TV violence
awaken deeply held fears about censorship, even among those who are
not fans of bloody fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there's too much violence depicted, and yes, people use
violence cheaply and exploitively,'' said ``ER'' star Anthony
Edwards. ``But that's the flip side of our freedom to express
yourself. People have the right to turn their computers off and
turn their TVs off, be responsible parents, act like adults. We act
like children in this country. We point fingers at everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That line of reasoning rings a bit hollow to writer-producer
David E. Kelley of ``The Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal,'' and
``Snoops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Producers have to be cognizant of the fact that what they do
is seen by millions of people,'' said Kelley. ``It's a nice little
idea to say, well, `Parents should supervise what their kids
watch,' but the reality is that they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always wary of condoning any kind of censorship, but I'm
just as wary of stapling `Censorship' to a flag and then wagging it
over your head as an automatic license to do whatever you want,''
added Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where the line is drawn, but I certainly don't
think producers should be saying `Responsibility? It's not up to
me. I'll just be an artist and put the images up that I want and if
people get hurt, well, that's the price of a free society.' I think
that's just a little too glib and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Many feel as Kelley does, and their views are buttressed by
studies, sponsored by the American Medical Association and the
American Psychological Association, that have found a link between
youthful aggression and violence on TV and in the movies. It seems
likely, however, that some of television's other talented
writer-producers, who specialize in pushing the outside of the
thematic envelope, will continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Three such producers interviewed by the Globe _ Chris Carter of
``The X-Files,'' Steven Bochco of ``NYPD Blue,'' and David Chase of
``The Sopranos'' _ are clearly unshaken in their conviction that,
in Bochco's words, ``an artist's responsibility is to his art or
her art,'' and not to gauging the possible societal effects of that
art.
</P>
<P>
   While saying he is ``very conscious that you can't scream `Fire'
in a crowded theater,'' Bochco said his ``deepest belief is that
the overwhelming majority of Americans are not violent, are not
psychotic, see entertainment for what it is, and understand they
have choices about what they watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read about a tragedy like Columbine, that's not the
fault of television or the movies or Sunday-afternoon football,''
he added. ``That's probably the fault of a mental disease. . . . I
have such contempt for politicians who saddle us up to ride us for
political ends.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Standards unchanged
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carter, whose new ``Harsh Realm'' for Fox is among the more
violent new shows this fall, said that ``for me, Columbine didn't
change anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal standards are the same, which is to be a
responsible storyteller, to use the elements and conventions of
storytelling that provide the best story, and not to water anything
down, not to shrink from anything, and to try to deliver the most
powerful message, to entertain, and to edify whenever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase, whose ``The Sopranos'' was the TV event of last season,
does not rule out a link between entertainment and violence _ just
not the link many others suppose. ``People alway say, `Oh, the
violence in television, the violence in movies causes violence.'
What about the rest of our entertainment, which is so bland, so
soulless, embraces horrible values of consumerism and fake
happinesss. . . . All those lies that everybody's fed, what about
that?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a 15-year-old kid and I watched some of the crap
that's around, I'd go crazy too. I really would. So much of it is
so at odds with what you're feeling in your own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the best dramas on TV _ ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``The
Practice,'' ``ER'' _ do not traffic in gratuitous violence.
Concerns about violence on TV could stem partly from changes in the
medium itself. ``Network television has gotten a bad rap, lumped in
with what people can see on cable from motion pictures,'' said John
Wells, executive producer of ``ER.'' ``As the conduit into the home
has changed, you don't really distinguish between what's on NBC and
what's on Showtime or HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of other parents, filmmaker Martha Coolidge had to
cope with heart-rending fallout in her own home from the Columbine
High School massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy, I'm scared to go to school,'' Coolidge's 10-year-old
son told her in late April, shortly after gunshots claimed more
than a dozen young lives in Littleton, Colo. ``Is somebody going to
come in and shoot me?''
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge, the director of numerous television and feature films,
including the upcoming ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge'' for HBO,
is no friend of censorship. Indeed, she has often fought for
artistic freedom as cochair of the Directors Guild of America's
creative rights committee, and she does not want concerns over
violence to lead to outside ``controls over what we see.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is also no friend of what she calls ``exploitive
violence'' on TV or in films, voicing dismay that ``it is
everywhere, everywhere in our culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creative community is living in this country too,'' said
Coolidge. ``Everybody needs to take responsibility for what is
going on in our country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
