<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Russian President Yeltsin fires Prime
Minister Stepashin and his Cabinet, apparently in a bid to reassert
his influence in maneuvering over next July's presidential
election. He then names Vladimir Putin, a former spy and head of
the main successor agency to the KGB. Putin, who is likely to be
approved by Parliament, would be the fourth prime minister in last
year and a half. Putin in turn announces that he will run for
president. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic on recent prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ A profile of the new prime minister,
Vladimir Putin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HONGKONG (Shanghai) _ China says that Pope John Paul II
cannot visit Hong Kong next year, dashing hopes of improved
Vatican-Beijing ties. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-FLAG (Tokyo) _ In a measure that spoke of strongly rising
nationalist sentiment among Japan's politicians, the upper house of
Parliament voted resoundingly Monday to designate the longtime
unofficial national anthem and the rising-sun flag as legal symbols
of the nation. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-U.S. (Jerusalem) _ Secretary of State Albright's visit
to the Mideast is delayed as Palestinians and Israelis continue
wrangling. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton gives the Medal of
Freedom to President and Mrs. Carter and addresses the American Bar
Association about, among other things, gun control. By Melinda
Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-POLITICS (Washington) _ The statements of George W. Bush,
Elizabeth Dole and John McCain about homosexuals signals a
softening of the Republican oratory on this subject, alarming some
conservatives in the party. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KY-PLUTONIUM (Washington) _ Energy Secretary Richardson orders
an investigation into Washington Post report that thousands of
employees at a Kentucky uranium plant were exposed to plutonium. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SWEATSHOP-SUIT (Undated) _ Nordstrom, J. Crew and several other
defendants reach settlement in class action suit against sweatshops
in the American territory of Saipan. The defendants agree to pay
for independent monitor and vow not to use factories there that
break the law. Lawyers hope this settlement serves as model for
other defendants. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SURPLUS-PARTIES (Washington) _ The heated battle over how to use
projected federal budget surpluses has exposed deep rifts between
the two parties, both in political and economic terms. Most of the
fight is over the portion of the surplus generated by general tax
revenues, $996 billion. Republicans say the figure is so big that
the country can afford a $792 billion tax cut and still find plenty
of money for needs like adding a prescription drug benefit to
Medicare and increasing spending on the military. But Democrats
argue that the surplus projections are based on a series of
questionable premises: that the economy will avoid a protracted
downturn; that unexplained surges in revenue will continue, and
that the forecasting ability of budget analysts will prove far more
accurate than it has in the past. The biggest problem with the
projections, Democrats say, is that they assume an unrealistically
low level of increases in government spending. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTRADE-MARKETPLACE (Washington) _ A report by the North
American Securities Administrators Association finds that
day-trading firms mislead their investor-customers with promises of
quick riches, fail to supervise their operations and make improper
loans to customers to keep them trading. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-DOLLAR (Rome) _ The euro has regained some ground in recent
weeks, helped in part by data showing signs of strength in Europe's
three largest economies. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m, stocks were up slightly: The
Dow Jones industrial average was up 28, the S&AMP;P 500 up 9 points,
the Nasdaq composite index up 4 points; the 30-year Treasury bond
was yielding 6.22 percent. In Europe, stocks were also slightly
higher, with London up 0.32 percent and Frankfurt up 1.53 percent.
In Asia, Tokyo's Nikkei closed up 0.62 percent, the Hang Seng in
Hong Kong was down 1.68 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-DUMPING (Mexico City) _ Commerce Department is expected to
announce whether it will pursue an anti-dumping complaint filed by
a group of small, independent oil producers against Mexico, Iraq,
Saudi Arabia and Venezuela. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   EMC-DATA-GENERAL (Undated) _ EMC Corp., the top maker of
corporate computer storage systems, has agreed to buy rival Data
General Corp. for about $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIR-CUTBACK (London) _ British Airways announces it will cut
back on loss-making routes and switch to more small planes. The
plan was announced as the company reported that first-quarter
earnings fell 84 percent, its worst first quarter in seven years.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   MORRIS-WIATT (Hollywood) _ Jim Wiatt, who resigned on Friday as
co-chairman of ICM, will be become co-chief executive of a rival
talent agency, William Morris. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   TIMES-AMAZON (Undated) _ Amazon.com and The New York Times have
settled a legal dispute over Amazon.com's reference to The New York
Times Best Sellers list as part of Amazon.com's 50-percent-off-list
price program.
</P>
