<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH UPPER LIPS QUIVER AS AMERICANS BUY UP THEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It there's one thing that drives many Brits crazy, it's
the idea of Americans messing with their culture.
</P>
<P>
   So one might imagine the moans a few days ago when news emerged
that the American conglomerate SFX Entertainment had spent $250
million to buy the Apollo Group, which owns 10 of the most famous
theaters in London's West End, including the Lyceum and the
Dominion. To make matters worse, SFX, which also bought Boston's
Don Law Co., may snap up the Stoll Moss chain of theaters, which is
on the market for $160 million and which includes prestigious
venues such as the Garrick, the Palladium, and the Theatre Royal
Drury Lane.
</P>
<P>
   This followed a decision by the Royal Opera House, which hired
an American director last year in a desperate move to end its
financial troubles, to let the name of some rich American patron be
stamped on the front of its building in exchange for a $16 million
donation.
</P>
<P>
   It would mark the first time any one of Britain's four national
arts companies _ the Royal Opera, the English National Opera, the
Royal National Theatre, and the Royal Shakespeare Company _ has
allowed someone's name to be displayed on its building.
</P>
<P>
   While some in the arts community were quick to sniff at the idea
of the Royal Opera putting its prestige up for sale, Lucinda
Morrison, a spokeswoman for the National Theatre, was less
judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone offered us 10 million pounds, we'd consider it,''
she said. ``There is a sensitivity, especially in the national
theaters because they are just that, national theaters. But things
are moving that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutbacks in arts funding, which began under Margaret Thatcher
and have been alleviated only mildly under the ``Cool Britannia''
ideology of Prime Minister Tony Blair, have left the purveyors of
higher culture looking for money wherever they can. At the National
Theatre, the $17 million public grant held steady for five years
until it got a boost of $1.6 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the idea of Americans owning nearly all of the West End
or their money being needed to rescue the Royal Opera unsettles
many. Raymond Gubbay, a classical music promoter, described the
Royal Opera's fund-raising gambit as ``a rather tacky American
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   While news of the sell-off of West End theaters and the naming
rights to the Royal Opera House has broken in the same week, the
circumstances surrounding the two are considerably different. The
Royal Opera has been forced to cancel its performances this year as
it gets its financial house in order.
</P>
<P>
   But the West End and most of its 50 theaters have been having a
good run. The theaters employ about 27,000 people and sell more
than 11 million tickets a year. The theaters are on the market not
because they are losing money, but because their owners see a
profit to be made.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the Apollo Group is classic Horatio Alger. Paul
Gregg founded the company 22 years ago when he borrowed $40,000 to
buy his first provincial theater. He built the company into
Britain's largest privately owned entertainment group, with 23
theaters employing 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg says SFX's interest in the West End, or Theatreland, as
they call it here, ``is proof of a buoyant 9industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the West End sell-off is bound to provoke soul-searching
here. Already, debate rages over whether to call British-made films
like the Oscar-winning ``Shakespeare In Love'' British at all
because they are made with American money. And American imports
such as ``The Jerry Springer Show'' have been blamed for dumbing
down British television.
</P>
<P>
   The presumption is that American-owned properties will be more
interested in the bottom line than in edifying entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Theatre, Morrison said, the sudden infusion of
American capital should not be a surprise. ``The Yanks,'' she said,
``have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of the Globe's London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
