<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIFFED-PUBLISHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHER FUMES AS CHRETIEN BLOCKS A TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Hell hath no fury like a press baron denied a noble
title.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Black, erudite owner of a vast Toronto-based newspaper
empire stretching from Vancouver to Jerusalem, is suing the prime
minister of Canada, accusing Jean Chretien of abusing his political
power to prevent Black from being appointed to Britain's House of
Lords.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seems likely to make Canadian legal history. It marks
an extraordinary escalation of the simmering hostility between the
folksy but autocratic prime minister and Canada's most colorful
media mogul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dynamite,'' said Michael Bliss, a historian at the
University of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says Chretien was motivated by political malice, not
regard for Canadian law, when he interceded with Queen Elizabeth II
in June to prevent Black's elevation to a life peerage.
</P>
<P>
   The queen, who is also Canada's monarch, apparently backed away
from an appointment that seemed inevitable rather than become
embroiled in a quarrel between two powerful Canadian subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the suit maintains that Chretien's was an act of
particularly vicious sabotage, since officials of his own
government already had advised Black of no objections, provided he
did not seek to use the title in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks only a token amount in dollar damages _ $17,500,
a pittance to one of Canada's wealthiest citizens. It is intended
solely to clear Black's reputation and force Chretien to
acknowledge wrongdoing, friends and colleagues of Black's say.
</P>
<P>
   Black, 54, who also holds British citizenship, had been
scheduled to receive the nonhereditery title of Lord Black, along
with appointment to the House of Lords, on June 18. The honor,
endorsed by Britain's prime minister, Tony Blair, had been meant as
royal recognition of Black's prominence as publisher of London's
Daily Telegraph newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Black is also publisher of Canada's nationally circulated
National Post, an upstart daily launched last year and known for
its financial news, conservative editorial stance and aggressive
coverage of Chretien's government. In addition, Black publishes
scores of other papers.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Black's ascension to a lordship, Chretien
officials dug up an obscure, 80-year-old resolution by Canada's
Parliament asking the British monarch not to confer titles on
Canadian citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien brought the resolution to the attention of Queen
Elizabeth, making clear he opposed honors for Black.
</P>
<P>
   But according to legal analysts, the musty 1919 resolution
rooted out by Chretien's staff has no legal force. It was
apparently meant then as just a bit of naughty
thumbing-the-nose-at-royalty by a young country still not fully
weaned from Britain's colonial embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Chretien Saturday defended his decision. ``I want
to make clear that I was guided in this matter by longstanding
Canadian policy and custom,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a fair number of prominent Canadians living in Britain
_ including the founder of Canada's other national daily, the Globe
and Mail _ have received well-publicized peerages and noble titles
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, perhaps, Black is a full British citizen, and
presumably entitled to any honor offered by his adopted land.
Canada specifically permits dual citizenship, and in modern times
has not objected to expatriate Canadians receiving noble honors
from Britain or other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien's loathing of Black is known, almost reminiscent of
Richard N. Nixon's hatred of Katherine Graham, publisher of the
Washington Post during the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no hint of serious corruption during Chretien's
six years in office. But Black's National Post _ unabashedly
conservative in a country that is far more left-leaning than the
United States _ has given prominent coverage to a few fairly minor
government deals that suggest some impropriety, if not illegality,
on the part of Chretien and well-connected associates. The
editorial page has been more stingingly critical of Chretien's
governance than any other major paper.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, it's that coverage, and those
editorials, that have motivated Chretien to block Black's lordship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister shouldn't be allowed, because he's mad at
the National Post coverage, to interfere with anyone's rights,''
said Peter Atkinson, vice president of Black's holding company,
Hollinger Inc. ``What Black's outraged with, and can't live with,
and intends to take to court, is this interference by the prime
minister in his rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
