<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-NEWSPAPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACQUISITION CREATES NEW NEWS DYNAMICS IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ and VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The media landscape is shifting. The region's
economy is sizzling. And three newspaper groups are likely to spend
the next few years slugging it out for readers, advertisers and
journalistic laurels in the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Hearst Corporation announced it was buying the
morning San Francisco Chronicle, the largest newspaper in Northern
California, and putting the afternoon San Francisco Examiner up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The move sets the stage for a fierce battle for readers between
Hearst; Knight Ridder Inc., publisher of the San Jose Mercury News
and the Contra Costa Times; and Dean Singleton's ANG Newspapers,
which publishes five newspapers mostly in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last five years, we've seen an increased presence of
Knight Ridder, we've seen an increased presence of Singleton, and
now we're going to see an increased presence of the Hearst chain in
the San Francisco Bay Area,'' said Felix Gutierrez, executive
director of the Freedom Forum Pacific Coast Center in San
Francisco, a foundation that studies First Amendment and press
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they do with the newspaper and how they handle it will be
the determining factor of how well it's received,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, which is privately held, publishes 12 daily newspapers
as well as weeklies and magazines such as Cosmopolitan, Redbook and
Esquire. Through its Hearst-Argyle affiliate, the company owns 26
television stations and seven radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder, which moved its headquarters to San Jose from
Miami in 1998, publishes 31 daily newspapers. The company is
publicly held.
</P>
<P>
   ANG is controlled by MediaNews Inc., a private company that also
owns the Denver Post, the Los Angeles Daily News and other media
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's announcement effectively ends the 34-year-old joint
operating agreement (JOA) that guaranteed a 50-50 split of revenue
for the Chronicle and the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Financial details of the purchase were not released. Hearst
bought the Chronicle as well as SF Gate, the newspaper's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   While many media observers doubt a qualified buyer for the
Examiner will emerge, the fate of the afternoon newspaper and its
217 employees remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst executives said that if no one purchases the Examiner,
the newspaper will be combined into the larger morning operation.
The Chronicle, with 380 employees, has a daily circulation of
482,268 readers, while the Examiner has 114,776.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have a great Hearst newspaper here going forward
under the Chronicle banner,'' said Frank A. Bennack Jr., president
and chief executive officer of Hearst Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ridder, chairman and chief executive of Knight Ridder, said
Saturday that his company did not envision a change in strategy to
win readers in the economically robust Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Ridder said his company would be interested in purchasing the
Examiner, under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Hearst would sell their position as it exists today, where
they have 50 percent of the JOA, then we would be interested,''
Ridder said. ``If they're only going to sell their home delivery
circulation list, which is very small, and the name, then we would
not be interested and I doubt anybody else would be either.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennack said Friday that Hearst's acquisition of the Chronicle
in effect ends the JOA.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton has said he considered buying the Chronicle but would
not be interested in buying the Examiner, the flagship newspaper of
the Hearst media empire, and doubted whether others would.
</P>
<P>
   With Hearst's acquisition of the Chronicle, some newspaper
specialists predict a suburban newspaper war in a region with 18
daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be fatally optimistic ... there is a chance here to
create one very strong, enterprising, aggressive newspaper,'' said
James Naughton, president of the Poynter Institute, a media think
tank based in St. Petersburg, Fla. ``With just one paper it ought
to be in a position to strengthen its coverage. And if it doesn't,
shame on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The closure of the Bulletin in Philadelphia nearly two decades
ago spurred the Philadelphia Inquirer, a Knight Ridder newspaper,
to step up its coverage, both locally and nationally, said
Naughton, a former Inquirer editor, who envisions a similar
transformation in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia should be a lesson to San Francisco. It is
inevitable that the (Hearst) owners will make more money, but I
hope they put a substantial amount of that money back into the news
product.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new Hearst morning newspaper would likely attract readers in
outlying areas, an effort that could bring the company into a
collision with Knight Ridder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, the Chronicle and the Examiner weren't as
assiduous at courting the suburbs as it now looks like they should
have been,'' said Tom Goldstein, former dean of the Graduate School
of Journalism at the University of California at Berkeley and now
dean of Columbia University's Graduate School of Journalism in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume Hearst hasn't figured out their strategy yet, but
they can look at a map as well as I,'' Goldstein said. ``They'll
want to push out to the region _ San Francisco by dint of geography
isn't going to grow. Knight Ridder has ringed San Francisco in a
crescent, from Monterey to Contra Costa County. Hearst Corporation
has the resources to create a dynamic competition which hasn't
existed until lately.''
</P>
<P>
   P. Scott McKibben, president and publisher of MediaNews Inc.'s
ANG Newspapers, said his chain is not likely to shift its emphasis
from the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our circulation has continued to grow in recent years because
we're sitting in a market where suburban sprawl is growing and
developing,'' said McKibben, whose chain includes the Oakland
Tribune, the Tri-Valley Herald in Pleasanton, the Hayward Daily
Review, the Fremont Argus and the San Mateo County Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like our position. I don't see our strategy changing in
light of the buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Close, executive editor of San Francisco-based Pacific
News Service, an alternative news agency used by the Examiner and
other media outlets, said the Chronicle had lost its voice in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Close said she hoped the underdog image, which she said has
given the Examiner some of its energy, did not get lost in the
event the newspapers merge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it won't gain the exalted view of itself the Chronicle
has,'' she said. ``My hope is the spirit of optimism and
inclusivity ... will continue to drive the staff and the editors of
the Examiner as we go through this transition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
