<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GENERATIONS AND CULTURES CLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN LUPO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A jump in violent crime among Cape Verdean youth has prompted
social workers to raise an issue that has confronted immigrant
families for well over a century: Who's in charge, the parents or
their children?
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant parents may feel alienated from a culture, a language,
and a political system that confuse them. Their offspring, on the
other hand, assimilate rapidly, enabling them to run family affairs
and assert an independence that can scare their elders.
</P>
<P>
   The result, says Victor DoCouto, executive director of the
Massachusetts Alliance of Portuguese Speakers, is what he
experienced as a 6-year-old immigrant from the Azores in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked up the language like a sponge,'' DoCoutu recalled.
``By the time I was 9 or 10, I was the family social worker. Back
on the islands, my old man didn't need me for anything except maybe
to go out and play. Here, he needed me for everything, to fill out
forms for job applications, to read the mail. My mother took me out
of school on days when she needed me to go to the hospital and act
as an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it did for me,'' he said, ``was to empower me to the
point where I don't think it is healthy. It places you in a power
position. If you're not really careful, you can really wield that,
and some kids do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clash of cultures and values that has bedeviled immigrant
families throughout history, the implications are often harmless.
</P>
<P>
   One day, for example, in the back of Uncle Pete's Hickory Ribs
restaurant in East Boston, two Latino couples came in with their
children. The restaurant is owned by an Italian-American man and
his Thai wife; the cooks are Latinos, and the food is pure Southern
barbeque. In the back, the Latino couples conversed with their kids
in Spanish; when the youngsters spoke to one another, they did so
in English. The whole scene resembled what most Americans desire of
immigration and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the implications can be deadly, as the offspring
of immigrants totally reject the culture of their origins or,
worse, fall for the lure of easy money and become youth gang
members and, later, adult criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, critics of immigration have blamed violent
crime on newcomers. Indeed, some immigrants were bad overseas and
saw no reason to convert once they got here.
</P>
<P>
   But, as historian James Truslow Adams cautioned 70 years ago,
``It is impossible to blame the situation on the `foreigners.' The
overwhelming mass of them were law-abiding in their own lands. If
they became lawless here, it must be largely due to the American
atmosphere and conditions. There seems to be plenty of evidence to
prove that the immigrants are made lawless by America rather than
that America is made lawless by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime is the extreme end of the shock of change that has often
overwhelmed every immigrant group from the Irish of the 1840s to
the Cape Verdeans of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The American Irish,'' William V. Shannon wrote of
the immigrant peasant, ``America, he learned, was not the land of
the good peasant. It was the first of many sad disillusionments to
observe that in this new homeland the ruthless fellow, the mean,
tight-fisted man who grabbed what he could and shared nothing, made
out best. Much of the sense of status was lost. The ex-peasant
could not keep his place because he could not find it. He had to go
out and fight to find whatever place he could.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter in 1906 to the editor of the Yiddish-language
newspaper ``The Jewish Forward,'' a woman from New York's Lower
East Side told of finding a man shivering in the cold because, she
said, his children had neglected him, even though his two sons and
a daughter were making a good living. ``And with all this,'' she
wrote, ``he stands on the street and waits for the door of a
certain woman to open, who gives him each morning a few glasses of
tea and bread and thus keeps him alive. It is outrageous when such
a thing is passed over.''
</P>
<P>
   Muriel Heiberger, executive director of the Massachusetts
Immigrant and Refugee Advocacy Coalition, sees generational
conflict and cultural shock in immigrant families as ``a kind of
common thread that does run through the migration regardless of the
time period in which it took place.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Heiberger cautioned, ``It has sped up dramatically. The
late-20th-century experience is not exactly the same as that of
your and my grandparents. Technology, television, marketing have
created a common international youth culture that puts pressures on
immigrant kids. There was a kind of insularity in the old immigrant
communities that doesn't exist today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, the immigrant's children translated for their
parents and, perhaps, registered their young siblings for school.
Local political machines could fill in the gaps. The machines are
long gone, replaced by a confusing mix of federal, state, and local
government agencies and nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the traditional generational conflicts and the
complexities of dealing with large institutions are problems
specific to certain immigrant groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is, for example, a legalistic conflict,'' explained Paul
Watanabe, an associate professor of political science at the
University of Massachusetts at Boston, and codirector of the
Institute for Asian American Studies. ``For a long time, Asians
were prevented from becoming citizens. Yet their children, born in
the United States, were citizens. That creates an inevitable
tension in the legal status between children and parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Watanabe, a Japanese-American, said that when the US government
forcibly interned Japanese residents during World War II,
generational tensions ``went beyond the boiling point,'' because
the government used Japanese-American citizens to run the camps,
thereby relegating the patriarchal elders to ``childlike
powerlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's immigrants, he added, are largely from Asia and Latin
America and, therefore, also face racial hostility.
</P>
<P>
   DoCouto said the racial issue is particularly difficult for Cape
Verdeans, who may speak Portuguese and feel European but are
dark-skinned and live in African-American neighborhoods. ``So where
do the kids mainstream?'' he asks. ``Into black culture? Cape
Verdean? White culture?''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the generational issue even further is the reason
many newer immigrants are here. That may have less to do with
leaving one's homeland in search of a better economic life and more
to do with foreign policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Vietnamese, Cambodians, and Somalis, for example,
came here as refugees from political persecution.
</P>
<P>
   The Somali population in the Boston area numbers between 3,000
and 4,000, about 90 percent of whom were brought over in the last
five years by the US government, according to Abdiraham Yusuf,
chairman, and Abdulkadir Y. Hussein, executive director, at the
Somali Development Center in Jamaica Plain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When families came over voluntarily,'' said Yusuf, ``they
might not mind if their children assimilated as quickly as
possible. But we have families who in their wildest dreams never
thought they'd be in Boston, Massachusetts. They didn't know where
Boston was. They are from an underdeveloped nation that has gone
through a civil war. A great deal of adjustment is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   That means everything from explaining the welfare system to
convincing parents that their daughters' desire to wear faddish
teenage clothing does not imply loose morals.
</P>
<P>
   Many immigrant families make adjustments and compromises, not
without pain. Others cannot, and leave behind them the image of the
Irish peasant without a piece of land or the Jewish man waiting on
the streets of New York for a piece of bread and a sympathetic ear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alan Lupo is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
