<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0684 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYNIHAN SEES WHAT OTHERS DON'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Among other big things, Daniel Patrick Moynihan's
illustrious career in public service demonstrates the power of
analytical thinking in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The New York senator has contributed so many gems ahead of his
time in nearly four decades on the stage _ from his research on the
condition of ghetto families to his perception of Richard Nixon's
great opportunity as freshly elected president to be the American
Disraeli to his reflections on the blindness of the late-Cold War
CIA to the reality of Soviet weakness _ that one hesitates to pick
one.
</P>
<P>
   But as the chairman-for-life of the Bowtie Caucus rose last week
to lead the opposition to an irresponsible tax cut, it was hard not
to think of a classically Moynihan cut-like-a-diamond paragraph. To
wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans' dominant idea, at least for the moment, seems
to be that the social controls of modern government have become
tyrannical or, at the very least, exorbitantly expensive. This
oppression _ so the strategic analysis goes _ is made possible by
taxation, such that cutting taxes becomes an objective in its own
right, business cycles notwithstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   That would command respect, and journalistic envy, as
contemporary commentary under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But now consider that Moynihan wrote that for The New York Times
nearly 20 years ago, in the early summer of 1980, before Ronald
Reagan had even been elected. It was merely one observation in a
string of them that over time have come to define the terms of
national debate. It is no accident that people who have no
knowledge of Moynihan's astonishing track record see tax cuts well
down on their list of priorities, more as danger than as worthwhile
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, much of the political class was wasting time in
parlor games over whether people like then-Representative Jack Kemp
were correct in their ``new'' theory that government revenues would
be larger with lower tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Moynihan saw a deeper purpose, though not in Kemp's advocacy
per se. Moynihan saw Kemp's party moving away from opposition to
particular initiatives of government on their alleged demerits,
battles they had been losing consistently over issues from medical
care for the elderly to providing federal aid to poverty-impacted
school districts; he saw the Republicans embracing a new strategy
of attacking government itself and avoiding the burden of arguing
specifics, by trying to starve it through tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   And he was already warning by 1980 that the Republicans were
likely to prevail in the short term if they succeeded in attacking
government on behalf of working taxpayers as pseudo-populists,
leaving the Democrats as statist, status quo defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan proved Moynihan correct within days of assuming
office, though the senator had to endure much ridicule before
Reagan spoke of disciplining the child of government by cutting its
allowance.
</P>
<P>
   But there was much more to come:
</P>
<P>
   --It was Moynihan who pounced on the gimmickry and dishonesty of
budget director David Stockman (whom he had mentored at Harvard a
decade earlier) to show that hemorrhaging deficits had been
deliberately engineered.
</P>
<P>
   --It was Moynihan who first and most cogently saw through all
the schemes to ``balance'' the budget in formulaic ways that dodged
specific choices _ from amendments to the Constitution, the main
effect of which would be to make recessions far worse, to
``automatic'' spending cuts that politics and good sense would
never allow to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   --And it was Moynihan who more than a decade ago first caused a
stir by noting that operating surpluses in the Social Security
trust funds were being in effect embezzled to mask and fund
deficits in the rest of government. Today, his once-subversive
analysis is the basis of (at last) sound policy that the latest tax
cut scheme would severely undermine.
</P>
<P>
   All this, by the way, was prelude to Moynihan's signal
accomplishment as chairman of the Senate Finance Committee in
President Clinton's first term. It was Moynihan who guided the 1993
budget plan to passage, which in tandem with a first installment he
supported under President Bush in 1980, made a balanced budget
possible and created the crucial fiscal environment for the current
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   His typically reasoned and civil opposition last week came up
one vote short in an absurdly political atmosphere on the Senate
floor, but the Republican victory reeked of Pyrrhus's.
</P>
<P>
   After all we've learned, much of it from Moynihan, it is hard to
imagine we are anywhere near making the same colossal mistake again
after a $4 trillion run-up in the national debt that the senator
also foresaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NEW-YORK-2TAKES-B     08-09 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NEW-YORK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK MUSEUMS: NEW AND RENEWED 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Part of the mega-plan for the renovation/expansion of the Boston
Museum of Fine Arts is the overhaul of the galleries devoted to
Greek and Roman art _ now part of the Art of the Ancient World,
after MFA director Malcolm Rogers's recent restructuring. Boston's
classical galleries are currently Third World places, cooled by
electric fans, dingy, and out of date by any measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York has recently, and
triumphantly, restored seven of its Greek galleries _ at a reported
cost of $75 million. Unlike Boston's, stuck at the back of the
building, the Met's are just to the left of the main entrance, in
one of the museum's most conspicuous locations. Their centerpiece
is a 140-foot-long vaulted hall, now a forest of classical
sculpture, culminating at the far end with an Ionic column capital
the size of a room, excavated at Sardis, ancient capital of Lydia.
It's a stunning punctuation to a stunning vista.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know the Met's Greek galleries had been redone,
you wouldn't guess: That's their strength. Architect Kevin Roche
did nothing tricky here. He made the rooms look pretty much as they
did in 1917, when their design _ by McKim, Mead, and White _ was
accomplished. The same firm did the Boston Public Library; in both
buildings, the architects used skylights that were covered over
during World War II. The Met's _ deeply recessed into the curved
vaulting _ have now been uncovered and improved. The natural light
that animates the space below made me yearn to see the BPL's
skylights operational again (which they will be, in the course of
the library's ongoing restoration).
</P>
<P>
   The new addition to the design for the Met's Greek galleries is
four unobtrusive doorways connecting the main hall with side
spaces, giving a sense of openness and ease of passage, and making
you feel that while the arrangement of objects is chronological,
you can create your own route.
</P>
<P>
   And what objects these are. Many would argue that the classical
collections the Met began acquiring when it was founded, in 1870,
are preeminent in the Western Hemisphere. The new installation is
dense, in a traditional, 19th-century style, so you have to be
selective if you're not going to spend the rest of your life here.
I focused first on the haunting, mute, almost featureless Cycladic
figures that read as ancient precursors of modern minimalism, then
on a recent acquisition, a terra-cotta chest-shaped Minoan coffin
painted with rambunctious, delightfully unrefined geometrics. The
so-called New York Kouros, circa 590-580 BCE, is one of the
earliest surviving figurative statues from Attica and one of the
Met's treasures. Two and a half millennia after its creation, its
rigid, simplified, uncompromising pose captivated 20th-century
artists including Picasso. A marble grave stele of a little girl
shows the chubby child clutching her two pet doves, as if saying
farewell. To cheer up after a sad moment in front of her, I turned
to a red-figured terra-cotta vessel in the form of a lobster claw,
thinking it would be more at home in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Museums are ruled by marketing, and the Met's classical
galleries now end with a satellite gift shop. Beyond that is the
restaurant, a huge, colonnaded atrium that began life as a gallery
for Roman sculpture _ which it will be again. The Met is ousting
the dining facility to restore the room to its original use, to
make a progression from Greek to Roman that makes sense. A
computer-generated photo shows what the new Roman Court will look
like _ a setting more fitting for statues of Caesar than Caesar
salad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A great many classical sculptures have lost their heads through
vandalism or the wear and tear of time. Polish-born contemporary
sculptor Magdalena Abakanowicz makes her figures headless
intentionally, emphasizing their universality. Often, they line up
in quasi-military formations, as if parading to some unknown
destination. They're marching on top of the Met this summer, in a
powerful installation on the Iris and B. Gerald Cantor Roof Garden.
Silhouetted against the Manhattan skyline, looming over Central
Park, they read like silent witnesses to urban folly. You can see
Abakanowicz works the world over, but this rooftop setting gives
them particular meaning, a sense of remove from everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   In communist Poland, Abakanowicz had to scrounge stuff to make
art, using everything from twigs to fabric. She became famous for
huge relief weavings, and figures of burlap and sisal. Her current
figures are bronze, but the surfaces are heavily scarred by knives,
rags, and the artist's hands, as if to recall her former methods
and materials. The bronze is the color of mud, making the figures
look like they were made of primal ooze.
</P>
<P>
   Abakanowicz's ``Backward Seated Figures'' number 11, and they
sit facing away from you, toward the park, as if meditating.
They're hollow, as her figures tend to be, scooped out and
slouched, looking almost like beach chairs. Part of her message is
how little it takes not just to suggest a human being, but to make
you empathize with one. You want to view these figures from their
hollow fronts as well as their backs, to see what's missing as well
as what's there.
</P>
<P>
   While Abakanowicz most often creates collectives, her ``Figure
on Trunk'' stands alone, balancing on a tree trunk in turn balanced
on two round logs _ a precarious position, hinting that isolation
is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Most poignant of all the Met works are the 40 adolescent-size
bodies of ``Bambini,'' a Children's Crusade en route to who knows
where, as touching as that little girl in the Greek galleries
saying goodbye to her doves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Context counts immensely in displaying sculpture, as the new
installations at the Met demonstrate. In midtown, at Rockefeller
Center's Channel Gardens, which link Fifth Avenue to the Center
tower itself, is another instance of sculpture in a suitable
context, a group of Paul Manship's works on view through Sept. 6.
Most are on loan from Brookgreen Gardens in South Carolina, which
has extensive collections of early 20th-century sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Manship, who died in 1966, spent much of his career in
Gloucester, where a community of sculptors flourished in his era.
Trained academically, he moved into Art Deco, producing sleek,
streamlined figures of humans and animals, often related to myth.
His work is sometimes shown around Boston, but often poorly, in
cluttered surroundings that detract from its elegance and make it
look outmoded. In the Rockefeller Center gardens, a formal,
symmetrical setting of benches, lush plantings, fountains, and
water streaming down toward a sunken restaurant, Manship's gods and
goddesses look perfectly at home.
</P>
<P>
   He thought big. His 1924 ``Cycle of Life'' is a sundial in the
form of a sphere, laden with symbols of family life, the zodiac,
the elements, the hours of the day, all resting on a base of
turtles, ancient symbols of eternity. And he thought active. His
``Diana and Actaeon'' are running in opposite directions, leaping
balletically, she having just transformed him into a stag, the
scene made more hectic by growling hounds.
</P>
<P>
   This temporary installation complements the great Manship that
is a permanent part of Rockefeller Center, his exuberant 1934 gilt
bronze ``Prometheus,'' a sunstruck representation of the very first
sculptor, who fashioned man out of clay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Months before Rogers abruptly restructured the entire MFA,
putting senior staff members out of jobs, Maxwell Anderson did
something similar at the Whitney, rearranging curatorial
responsibilities and leaving some curators without portfolio. As a
result, the Whitney hemorrhaged staff and made headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But long before Anderson took over as director of the Whitney
Museum of American Art last year, the institution and controversay
were wedded. It's usually the shows that raise the ruckus, though,
not the backstage maneuvering. Whitney biennials are nearly always
trashed by nearly everybody. Like many of the recent biennials, the
current extravaganza, ``The American Century: Art &AMP; Culture
1900-2000,'' tries too hard and ends up wanting. It's the biggest
show in Whitney history, the museum's bid to regain its position as
the leading champion of American art. That position has been
threatened not only by the Whitney's weak programming, but from
increased competition from other major New York museums paying
closer attention to home-grown work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0688 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NEW-YORK-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     08-09 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NEW-YORK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... home-grown work.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Whitney splits the century down the middle: Part 1,
1900-1950, is up through Aug. 22; Part 2, covering 1950-2000, is up
Sept. 26 through mid-February. The curators of Part 2, Barbara
Haskell and Susan Cooke, have spread their net too wide, trying to
cover film, dance, architecture, music, literature _ all of
20th-century culture in addition to visual arts. Arranged
chronologically but also by theme, the show starts on the top
floor, with Gilded Age portraiture that's not gilt-edged. No
large-scale Sargent portraits of robber barons or socialites here,
just smaller or lesser examples of the genre, with the shining
exception of Thomas Eakins's austere 1900 ``The Thinker: Portrait
of Louis N. Kenton.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the themes you can trace in the show _ photography's
abstraction of the body, paintings that are precursors of Pop, the
aestheticizing of industrial design _ one of the more significant
is the rise of the city, literally and figuratively. It's the
implied subject of Alfred Stieglitz's 1907 photograph of
immigrants, ``The Steerage''; of paintings of the vertical
cityscape by Joseph Stella; of Paul Frankl's 1926 ``Skyscraper
Bookcase,'' undistinguished save for its shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney's jumbled galleries on several floors add to the
confused look of this overview that offers no revelations. So much
of this material has been examined in such depth that the
once-over-lightly approach is unhelpful to all but those with no
clue whatsoever of the subject. The show is short on star objects,
too, although some icons _ including Grant Wood's ``American
Gothic,'' Marcel Duchamp's ``Fountain,'' and Charles Demuth's ``The
Figure 5 in Gold'' _ are here. They're not put in any intelligible
context, though; they're just part of a seemingly endless lineup,
unenlightening and unentertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Part 2 promises to be better, if only because the second half of
the century was when America came to dominate the art world, with
Abstract Expressionism and succeeding isms. As for Part 1, the
Australian critic Robert Hughes provided a far more cohesive and
even more exciting overview of the same material, as well as the
rest of American art, in his 1997 book and television series
``American Visions: The Epic History of Art in America.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The chief curator of Part 2 of ``The American Century'' is Lisa
Phillips, who departed the Whitney in the wake of Anderson's
changes. Phillips has now become the second director of the New
Museum of Contemporary Art in SoHo, succeeding founding director
Marcia Tucker, herself a refugee from the Whitney 23 years ago,
after then-director Tom Armstrong fired her. Certain of her shows
had outraged even knowledgeable art lovers, and she'd decided that
the uptown museum was moving toward fundable art. ``Fundable''
didn't describe the art Tucker wanted to show, and the New Museum
quickly acquired a reputation for politicized, even scandalous
exhibitions, for nose-thumbing shows like the 1978 `` `Bad'
Painting.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Museum's rough-and-tumble aura has been diluted as other
museums across the country have taken up its causes, a wide variety
of marginalized art by marginalized artists: There are a lot of
curators out scouring the margins these days.
</P>
<P>
   For all Tucker's scoffing at fundable art, the New Museum is
doing some fund-raising of its own, completing a $6 million capital
campaign, its first. The museum unveiled a renovated and enlarged
facility last year, designed by Colin Cathcart, with expanded
gallery space and a revenue-generating bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Among the current shows is Tucker's swan song, ``The Time of Our
Lives,'' up through Oct. 17. Its theme is aging and ageism,
appropriate in a country where the percentage of those 65 and older
is growing faster than any other demographic group. ``The Time of
Our Lives,'' which includes work by over 60 artists in a wide range
of media, isn't unique in offering images of nude elderly bodies,
even sexually active elderly bodies, but it does a good job with
the what-is-beauty? question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giant'' of the title of Jeff Wall's Cibachrome
transparency is a huge, nude, older woman standing in the middle of
a public library, utterly unnoticed, a sly comment on the
invisibility of the old in society. Jacqueline Hayden's
black-and-white photo of an elderly, nude, sagging man and woman,
his hand on her nipple and hers on his thigh, suggests the memory
of sex rather than the prospect of it. But in the ``70 + 1''
hologram by Boston artist Harriet Casdin-Silver, the nude artist
clutches her breasts and closes her eyes in an expression of
ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   At the entrance of the show is a clever allusion to the grim
reaper, Bruce Cannon's ``The Time of Your Life,'' a deceptively
old-fashioned-looking clock able to calculate when, according to
insurance actuarial tables, you should die. Should you survive past
your assigned date, the clock sends messages of congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critical mass is critical in attracting masses of visitors to
museums. The SoHo block of Broadway between Houston and Prince
streets includes not only the New Museum, but the Museum for
African Art and the Guggenheim Museum SoHo as well, all housed in
historic buildings of substance and charm. The interior of the
African museum, which moved to its current site in 1993, was
designed by Maya Lin, acclaimed architect of the Vietnam Wall,
obviously working here on a next-to-nothing budget. She used color
and windowed rooms within rooms to break up an otherwise
unarticulated two-floor space.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's mission is not just to attract visitors to its own
building, but to send shows out to the wider world. Locally, both
the Worcester Art Museum and the Davis Museum at Wellesley College
have presented shows toured by the African museum. The current
exhibitions in SoHo are a typical mix: ``A Congo Chronicle: Patrice
Lumumba in Urban Art'' and ``Three African Traditions: The Art of
the Dogon, Fang, and Songye,'' both up through Aug. 15. The big
fall show sounds particularly promising: ``Liberated Voices:
Contemporary Art From South Africa,'' organized by Frank Herreman
and featuring art of the post-apartheid era. Among the 13 artists
in the show, an abbreviated Who's Who of South African art, is Paul
Stopforth, an emigre who has made Boston his home for more than a
decade. Stopforth's powerful 1980 triptych ``The Interrogators,''
the faces of the men who tortured apartheid martyr Steve Biko, will
be shown in this country for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim SoHo, which opened in 1992 with an Arata
Isozaki-designed interior and splashy shows that drew disappointing
numbers, closed this past winter for a reconfiguration. It's now
reopened with a long-term installation of Andy Warhol's largest and
last series, ``The Last Supper.''
</P>
<P>
   The space itself is spectacular, a pair of huge, long galleries
with columns running down their spines and immense windows along
several walls. The columns and windows limit what, and how much,
art can be shown here. But there's no denying that the galleries
are glorious, or that they suit the Warhols. It would be hard to
find another space big enough to accommodate them in quantity, and
quantity counts here.
</P>
<P>
   Warhol became as obsessed with Leonardo's ``Last Supper'' as
Picasso was with Velazquez's ``Las Meninas.'' The Pope of Pop
created over 100 variations on the ``Last Supper'' theme, and just
a month before his death in 1987, he exhibited 22 of them in Milan,
across the street from the church that houses the Leonardo.
</P>
<P>
   In Warholian fashion, the artist worked from cheap reproductions
of ``The Last Supper,'' and cropped and repeated the image as if it
were part of an ad campaign. He painted it in dark-on-dark, so it's
barely legible; he silk-screened it; he collaged and camouflaged
it; he added logos including the one for Wise potato chips. Rather
than a show of disrespect, the cumulative effect is fascination
bordering on reverence, a reminder of Warhol's devout Catholic
upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   When museums started moving to SoHo or opening branches there,
rents were still reasonable. But the neighborhood has changed, gone
upscale, making it harder for the museums to retain their hold on
the real estate. And so the Guggenheim SoHo's reconfiguration
includes renting out a prime street-level space to a soon-to-open
Prada store. Warhol, a consumer-culture and fashion junkie, would
have loved the juxtaposition of $1,000 pocketbooks on the ground
floor with Jesus upstairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEMLOCK-ART-BOS &LR;      08-09 1771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEMLOCK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMLOCKS FALLING PREY TO RELENTLESS INSECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMBURG, Conn. _ The big Hemlock trees at Burnham Brook once
grew so thick and close that other plants could not survive in
their shade. They were masters of this 450-acre wood, creating a
cool, open world beneath their boughs where visitors had escaped
the summer sun for generations.
</P>
<P>
   But, today, the wood looks like it was ravaged by a forest fire.
Seventy-foot hemlocks stand bare as far as the eye can see,
surrounded by their own fallen branches basking in the sunlight
that finally streams through the trees.
</P>
<P>
   This is the unfortunate handiwork of the woolly adelgid, a bug
no bigger than the period at the end of a sentence, which is
decimating some of the Northeast's oldest and most valuable
forests. What adelgids lack in size, they make up for in numbers,
swarming even the tiniest hemlocks by the tens of thousands and
literally sucking the life out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your future forest, at least as far as hemlocks are
concerned,'' said Harvard University forest ecologist Dave Orwig,
kneeling beside a six-inch hemlock seedling at Burnham Brook that
is already coated by the adelgids' white egg sacs. ``We could lose
hemlocks across broad areas for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The adelgid's assault threatens a species that has been an
important part of evergreen forests from Maine to Virginia for
8,000 years. Slow-growing and long-lived, hemlocks over the decades
can drive out other trees until all that remains is the dense green
foliage of the hemlocks, creating a shadowy, primeval forest floor.
</P>
<P>
   Most old growth forests in Massachusetts from Mount Greylock in
Adams to the Virginia Woods in Stoneham are dominated by hemlocks.
Mature hemlocks also play an important role in preventing soil
erosion around water bodies, since they grow readily in the moist
soil, and they are logged for everything from lumber to high-grade
mulch.
</P>
<P>
   Just 14 years after their arrival in New England, the quiet
insect aggressors have reached every mainland county in southern
New England (except Berkshire County in Massachusetts), invading
everywhere from the woods that surround Greater Boston's water
supply to the trees that shade the Brookline golf course where the
Ryder Cup golf tournament will be played next month.
</P>
<P>
   No one has yet found a way to stop the bugs' 12 to 18
mile-a-year northward advance from Virginia that has already
covered 11 states.
</P>
<P>
   The speed and thoroughness of the adelgids' invasion draws
comparisons to other infamous tree scourges such as Dutch elm
disease, the fungus-borne affliction that has killed many of the
graceful shade trees that have lined New England streets over the
last 50 years. Like the fungus, originally from Asia, that causes
the elm disease, the woolly adelgid comes originally from Japan and
has no natural enemies to control its population here. In its
native Japan, for reasons not fully understood, the adelgid poses
little threat to overall hemlock health.
</P>
<P>
   Property owners can protect individual hemlocks by spraying on
an oil coating or injecting the roots with a pesticide that kills
adelgids, but these remedies would be both overwhelmingly expensive
and impractical for use on almost all of the 3.2 million acres of
hemlock forest on the East Coast. Unless someone comes up with an
antidote that can be used widely, Orwig and fellow Harvard
ecologist David Foster say the hemlock's future is ``bleak.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, researchers are pinning their hopes on a tiny ladybug,
discovered in Japan by a Connecticut researcher, that apparently
eats nothing but woolly adelgids. This year, the US Forest Service
funded the release of 125,000 adelgid-eating ladybugs in eight
states in hopes that they would make themselves at home.
</P>
<P>
   The ladybugs ``are very aggressive and they do eat a lot of
adelgids. We just hope they can catch up with the adelgid, which
has gotten quite a head start,'' said Robert Chianese, chief of the
bureau of biological pest control at New Jersey's Department of
Agriculture, which reared the ladybugs for the experiments.
</P>
<P>
   However, even before the ladybugs were released in this state,
they were caught up in controversy. The Metropolitan District
Commission declined to take the ladybugs to help protect 3,000
hemlocks around the Quabbin Reservoir, Boston's water supply
located in central Massachusetts, because some MDC advisers feared
the imported bugs could cause unforeseen damage.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, officials at the Arnold Arboretum in Boston
were unable to obtain ladybugs, largely because Mark McClure of the
Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station, discoverer of the
adelgid-eating bug, felt the infestation at the arboretum was too
far advanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted it on a new infestation so the beetles stood a
chance of making a difference,'' explained Charles Burnham,
supervisor of the forest health program at the Department of
Environmental Management.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Souto of the US Forest Service office in Durham, N.H.,
the office that oversaw ladybug releases in New England, argued
that the Arboretum and other locations that could responsibly
manage them should get the ladybugs, equating them with an
experimental AIDS treatment that is risky but worthwhile because of
the severity of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference would be to get them out in the woods and get
people comfortable with handling them, Souto said.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, Massachusetts Department of Environmental
Management officials say they won't know if the Wilbraham
experiment was successful until November when the adelgids feed
actively. And three more years of monitoring will be needed before
state officials are satisfied the bugs are safe for wider use.
</P>
<P>
   With little immediate hope of a cure, the woolly adelgid spells
death for many hemlocks before it can even reach them, as property
owners cut the trees down before the infestation turns their wood
to mush. A quarter of the hemlock forests in Connecticut visited by
Harvard researchers have been logged, and forest managers in
Massachusetts are following suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking seriously at . . . getting a logging company to
come in here and log (public hemlock trees) because we're not going
to be able to save them,'' said Paul Willis, the tree warden in
Brookline, Mass. where the adelgid has already killed scores of
trees at the Putterham Meadows Golf Course.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the woolly adelgid hardly seemed a major threat when
it first arrived in the Pacific Northwest from Japan around 1921,
perhaps in a shipment of ornamental trees. Northwestern hemlocks
seemed to withstand the bugs just fine and, even when the adelgid
was inadvertently transported to Richmond, Virginia, in the 1950s,
ecologists believed it was an isolated problem.
</P>
<P>
   However, the adelgids picked up steam as birds and the winds
carried them north into prime hemlock territory of Pennsylvania and
New Jersey. Because each adelgid can reproduce alone, the arrival
of one bug can spell the beginning of the end for a forest. Today,
an estimated 90 percent of the hemlock forests in New Jersey are
infested.
</P>
<P>
   The adelgids crossed into Connecticut in 1985 on the winds of
Hurricane Gloria, and quickly dashed hopes that New England's
colder winters might slow them down. All but five of Connecticut's
169 municipalities now report adelgids, including Hamburg where the
damage is among the worst anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The infestation reached Massachusetts in 1989, bringing adelgids
to 85 communities and every mainland county except Berkshire so
far. Hoping to slow the advance, the three northern New England
states of Maine, New Hampshire, and Vermont have restricted hemlock
log imports, but few believe that is more than a stopgap measure.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's Orwig, who has visited 150 hemlock forests studying
the adelgid's effects, said he has been repeatedly surprised at the
intensity of the adelgid's attacks. At Burnham Brook, he assumed
the adelgids would die after the hemlocks did, but they remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's either just a huge army (of adelgids) out there, or
one got on'' each sapling and reproduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, damage from the infestation in southern New England has
been fairly invisible to the public, both because places such as
Burnham Brook are remote, and because adelgids are hard to detect
until the tree dies. The egg sacs on the bottom of needles are easy
to miss, and a tree can continue to live with them for two to nine
years before the needles drop off.
</P>
<P>
   But, forest managers all over New England are already making
tough decisions about the fate of the hemlocks, from paying $100
per tree for an injection that provides a year of protection to
simply watching the trees die.
</P>
<P>
   At the Arnold Arboretum, officials selected 200 to 300 trees for
preservation, mostly with horticultural oil, out of a collection of
about 2,400 hemlocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that, for most of the trees on Hemlock Hill, we are
going to let nature take its course . . . The adelgid will probably
take most of them,'' said the arboretum's Peter Del Tredici.
</P>
<P>
   At the Quabbin Reservoir, MDC officials have shied away from
treatments of all kind _ oil is hazardous to water, anyway _
concluding that the dead hemlocks will not jeopardize water quality
as long as new trees grow in their place to prevent erosion.
``Forest cover is what we're concerned about,'' said Dave Small,
the MDC's forest and park regional coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   While managers wrestle with the unpleasant choices, researchers
continue looking for a silver bullet to stop the adelgids. McClure
of the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station estimates that
the Japanese ladybugs are 45 to 90 percent effective in killing
adelgids, and early field research shows that the bugs can survive
Northeastern weather.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists also are studying other potential bio-weapons, such
as adelgid-killing fungi, Chinese beetles, and other predators. And
researchers at the National Arboretum in Washington are trying to
develop a hybrid Eastern hemlock that can resist the adelgids.
</P>
<P>
   But all the potential solutions don't matter much to forests
that are already in the path of the adelgid, such as Brookline,
where the town recently put up $40,000 to remove 120 dead hemlocks.
Asked town arborist George Barlow, ``What good is (a solution) 10
years from now if all the trees are dead?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
