<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FAMILY-RULINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULINGS BROADEN VIEW OF THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The two rulings, coming just a week apart this summer,
made legally plain what has been culturally clear for years: a
family is no longer just Mom, Dad and the kids.
</P>
<P>
   By boldly granting visitation rights to two non-parents _
including a lesbian who had helped raise her former partner's
biological child and an aunt _ the state's highest court waded
confidently into one of the thorniest social and political debates
in contemporary American society: the evolving notion of
``family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that . . . (a) `family' may no longer be
constituted simply of a wage-earning father, his dependent wife,
and the couple's children,'' wrote Supreme Judicial Court Justice
Margaret Marshall last month, in yet a third decision dealing with
non-traditional families.
</P>
<P>
   And while the high court struck down a City of Boston policy
granting health benefits to the partners of homosexual and
heterosexual city employees _ saying it was against the law _ the
court suggested that it might be time for lawmakers to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adjustments in the legislation to reflect these new social and
economic realities must come from the Legislature,'' Marshall wrote
for the majority.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation where families now come in a dizzying array of
configurations, many say the SJC's expansive notion of family is
much-welcome and long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is facing the realities of families today,'' said
Robert Volk, an associate professor of law at Boston University who
specializes in gay and lesbian rights. ``Families have changed, and
what constitutes a family has changed, and the court is saying that
it realizes that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see the court's recent rulings as a disturbing trend
designed to undermine the traditional family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we understand there are very untraditional domestic
arrangements today, the question is, `Which kind of family do we
want to make normative?' '' said C.J. Doyle, executive director of
the Catholic Action League of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe a traditional family of a mother and father raising
a child is the best way to socialize a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, legal recognition of non-traditional families ``is a
breaking wave, and Massachusetts is not the only state that's doing
this,'' said Mary E. O'Connell, a professor of law at Northeastern
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is doing it in a rather aggressive and very
child-centered way, and it's doing it judicially rather than
legislatively,'' O'Connell said. ``The court's taking a big step,
and it knows it's taking a big step, and it's taking it very
carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's focus on family comes at a time when paternity suits
rival divorce filings in volume, ever-growing numbers of
grandparents are involved in custody battles and most states allow
same-sex couples to adopt children.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the court's liberal leaning on custody and
visitation cases is, in Volk's view, a ``refreshing breath of
realism from the judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   But some family law practitioners, who witness the ravages of
divorce and custody battles daily, believe the high court is
overstepping its bounds, and worry that the recent rulings raise
more questions than they answer.
</P>
<P>
   What's next, they wonder? Visitation rights for stepparents and
au pairs? And how do matters like child support and alimony factor
into the SJC's recent decisions?
</P>
<P>
   Still, legal experts cautioned that the court's recent rulings
were highly ``fact-specific.'' In the case of the aunt, for
example, the child referred to the woman as ``mom'' and had lived
with her for most of her life. By no means, then, does the SJC's
ruling mean all aunts will win visitation privileges in the future,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just assume now that because you lived in the same
household with a child and had a wonderful relationship with that
child, that's going to mean something'' in court, said Boston
attorney Elaine Epstein, a family law specialist.
</P>
<P>
   In Epstein's judgment, the SJC's recent rulings are ``positive
in that they make a statement that the court wishes to keep pace
with the times, and negative in a sense of opening up a new set of
doors without defining what's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Charles Fried , in a stinging 14-page dissent in the
lesbian visitation case, warned against opening those doors,
calling the majority's decision a ``denigration of parental
rights'' and an ``unwarranted judicial intrusion into family
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have accused the high court of dabbling in
``judicial lawmaking'' by deciding issues better resolved by
elected lawmakers, while others believe the SJC is properly
pressuring legislators to address hot-button ``family values''
issues head-on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of stuff the Legislature would really rather
not have to address because it's inflammatory to particular
constituencies,'' said Boston attorney Peter Zupcofska,
vice-chairman of the Boston Bar Association's family law section.
</P>
<P>
   But Epstein says the court should get credit for taking on
issues the Legislature would just as soon dodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at all three decisions together, they send the
message that if the Legislature isn't going to deal with the new
reality of non-traditional families, then the court will,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
