<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DARK-SKY-BOS &LR;      08-09 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DARK-SKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SKY PRESERVE' HAS GAZERS SEEING STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORRANCE BARRENS, Ontario _ To cheers from amateur astronomers,
seekers of starry night romance and other aficionados of the night,
Ontario has decreed a permanent blackout on this 4,900-acre tract
of scrubland on the shores of Lake Muskoka, creating the world's
first ``dark-sky preserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is not to protect some rare bat, nocturnal rat, or
night-blooming flower but to guard the sweeping beauty of the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim is simply to preserve the view that everyone used to
get from the backyard,'' said Peter Goering, a retired Toronto
architect, amateur astronomer, and one of the prime movers behind
creation of the star park.
</P>
<P>
   The brighter lights of bigger cities have transformed the
post-sundown sky _ at least for most North Americans _ into a pale
imitation of the great spectacle much more widely visible only a
generation or so ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years, the glare of lights has washed the stars from
the sky over too much of Canada and the United States,'' said
Goering, a director of the Muskoka Heritage Foundation, a
preservation group whose members have led the campaign for the
unique star park. ``There are fewer and fewer accessible places
left where the night sky isn't affected by artificial brightness.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Canada, like the US, has many wilderness realms where
one can see the stars. But they are mostly distant and difficult to
reach. Real patches of darkness close to settled regions are
becoming increasingly rare as outdoor lighting becomes more
brilliant and pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light pollution is a big problem for amateur astronomers,''
said J. Randy Attwood, president of the Royal Astronomical Society
of Canada. ``The designs of new outdoor lighting send the light up
into the sky. . . What that means is that you cannot look at faint
objects through telescopes if you are in downtown because the light
going up causes a glare.''
</P>
<P>
   But the just-designated star park is not intended as the
exclusive haunt of lense-peering star spotters. The hope, say
supporters, is that it will draw many who simply want to enjoy the
unsullied wonders of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see the stars, yes, but also the chance to listen to the
insects of the darkness, to hear the whoosh of wings of night
birds,'' said Goering. ``A lot of life carries on under cover of
blackness.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrance Barrens, about 150 miles northeast of Toronto, lies
within easy reach of one of North America's most densely inhabited
regions. With its boulder-strewn flats, scrubby trees, and low
horizons, the barrens are an ideal spot for studying stars through
a telescope or simply marveling at the sparkling panorama of
celestial light visible to the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a particularly good place for star-gazing,'' said
Stuart Mallany, heritage specialist with Ontario's Ministry of
Natural Resources, which oversees the reserve. ``The absence of
light pollution in the night skies over the reserve is
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Although several cities in North America, especially in the
southwest US, have passed regulations to curtail outdoor lighting
around observatories and other sensitive spots, Ontario is the
first jurisdiction to create an official star park.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Torrance Barrens preserve has drawn
international attention from those who fear that humankind is
literally losing sight of the vast panorama of planets and
constellations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exciting news, a real breakthrough for night-lovers,
Canada is definitely showing the way,'' said Robert Gent, spokesman
for the Arizona-based International Dark-Sky Association, which has
members in 68 countries. ``It's good to know there is now a small
place in Canada set aside for people to gaze in wonder upon the
star-filled infinity of creation, instead of just gawking at the
infinity of McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   Designation of the star park _ which does not become official
until completion of a public review that is not expected to draw
any opposition _ comes at a time when many amateur astronomers and
other night sky observers fear they are fighting a losing battle
against flood-lit malls, high-powered security lights, advertising
beacons, and other artificial glare that, dark-sky advocates claim,
is intensifying everywhere in the developed world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light pollution has come in a great rush over the last few
decades,'' said Gent. ``We're being blinded by the light, losing
our view of the heavens in the glare. In this era, there are
individuals who are born, live, and die without ever having seen
the beauty of the night sky.''
</P>
<P>
   The change is not just in the number of lights but the kinds of
lights. For example, brilliant sodium vapor lights, used on
streets, parking lots, and even as outdoor home security lights,
tend to cast much of their glow upwards, obscuring the view,
instead of simply illuminating the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Torrance Barrens site is seen as especially well-suited for
a star park because it is bounded to the north by Lake Muskoka and
undeveloped Crown forest _ that is, land owned by the Candian
government. Municipal governments adjoining the barrens to the
south have indicated a willingness to restrict outdoor lighting, at
least within a five-mile swath of the preserve.
</P>
<P>
   The lake-dotted region is famous in Canada as ``cottage
country,'' a hugely popular vacation destination for denizens of
Toronto, much like Cape Cod or the Green Mountains is for people of
urban Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Goering has been summering near the barrens for 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really rather strange and unfortunate that even in this
remote district we have to set aside a special area for viewing the
night sky,'' he said. ``But for North Americans, the dark places
are becoming fewer and farther in between.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
