<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFINING-HILLARY-BOS &LR;      08-09 1706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFINING-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING HILLARY, REALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in the lazy, hazy daze of summer, the clash was compelling:
Hillary vs. Hillary, a duel between calculated self-presentation
and salacious celebrity titillation.
</P>
<P>
   In Talk, Tina Brown's new magazine, it was Hillary as she wants
to be seen: the aggrieved but understanding wife, sticking by a
tomcatting husband because she believes in their marriage despite
its obvious troubles.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Bill and Hillary: The Marriage,'' the gossipy new book
by celebrity biographer Chris Andersen, it was an altogether
different Hillary, a Machiavellian mate complicit in many of
Clinton's deceptions, denials, and coverups.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary No. 1 _ call her Sympathetic Hillary _ is a saddened and
suffering, but ultimately forgiving, spouse, a wife with a deep
abiding love for her husband even though he has deceived her, a
woman who has struggled to put her life back together after her
husband's affair with Monica Lewinsky, working through anger and
bitterness to reach understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I survived because of a combination of soul-searching
and relying on friends, the support of people who give advice,
religious faith, long and hard discussions,'' she told Talk in its
initial issue last week. ``You know people have a lot of daily
problems in relationships. Everybody was some dysfunction in their
families. They have to deal with it. You don't just walk away if
you love someone _ you help the person.''
</P>
<P>
   The Talk flashpoint quickly became Hillary's seeming suggestion
that the root cause of her husband's infidelity lay in the
psychological scarring he suffered as a tyke caught in emotional
conflict between mother and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   That was seemingly news to the president, but welcome news
nonetheless, and his aides spoke approvingly of Mrs. Clinton's
remarks until, faced with incredulity elsewhere, she said her
comments weren't meant to excuse his philandering.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Hillary No. 2, the Hillary of ``Bill and Hillary: The
Marriage,'' which hit bookstores even as Tina's triumph was
becoming the Talk of the town.
</P>
<P>
   Although Andersen's book purports to be ``a uniquely American
love story,'' the Hillary who emerges from its pages is a modern
Lady Macbeth, a cold, calculating, power-hungry figure who has long
known about many of her husband's affairs, but who has helped to
keep them secret or to contain the political harm after public
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Call her Faustian Hillary. According to this account, Faustian
Hillary shares neither bed nor bedroom with her husband and hasn't
for years. She is a woman, the book suggests, who repaid her
spouse's frenetic philandering by having an affair with Vince
Foster, the late Arkansas friend who became deputy White House
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   This Hillary, Andersen suggests, hired a private detective in
early 1982 to uncover Bill's infidelities _ not to confront her
husband, but to help do damage control during his successful
campaign to retake the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling still, in Andersen's presentation, Hillary tried
to pressure Juanita Hickey Broaddrick, the Arkansas woman who has
subsequently charged that Bill Clinton raped her in 1978, to keep
quiet about the alleged attack.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Clinton has vowed to say no more about her
marriage, and her press office says there will be no comment on
Andersen's book, those two images were left vying for primacy in
the public imagination as she experimented with running for the US
Senate from New York. Which Hillary a majority of voters choose to
accept will greatly influence any Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first interpretation makes her much more human, much more
likable,'' said Shirley Glass, a Baltimore clinical psychologist
and marital therapist. ``It is much more somebody we can idenitfy
with. But if they conclude that (the Clinton marriage) is a
Faustian bargain, it makes her very cool and calculating and not
likable, not someone you want to identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   Most seasoned political observers assume that the controlling
first lady had thought long and hard about the results she hoped to
achieve in the Talk interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind she had carefully figured out
what she was going to say,'' said historian and author Doris Kearns
Goodwin. ``I think she probably thinks it showed her being loyal
and strong and forebearing, which are the traits in the polls that
people are giving her credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   But if ``The Intimate Hillary'' was a coup for Tina Brown and
her new magazine, the result backfired on Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``To bring it all back up strikes me as a real error in
judgment,'' said Goodwin. ``I don't think it was a wise thing to
do, especially to have brought up the presumed reasons for the
infidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the first couple's backpedaling, already their opponents
are chortling, sardonically noting that a problem Mrs. Clinton once
blamed on a ``vast right-wing conspiracy'' is now apparently the
fault of Clinton's mother and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Further, cultural critic Barbara Dafoe Whitehead, author of
``The Divorce Culture,'' says Mrs. Clinton's efforts to equate her
husband's seemingly frenetic philandering with the problems that
beset average American marriages struck a false note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people find it hard to identify with her
willingness to tolerate that level of extramarital infidelity,''
said Whitehead. ``It really goes against what most Americans
believe about marriage: that you are monogamous and that it is
mutually binding on both men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   Then add in the venue and timing of the story, which seemed
political and self-serving, a way of ensuring a favorable story on
the eve of a presumed campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have heard from a lot of people who were borderline
Hillary or favorable to Hillary is that they have gotten more
negative toward her since the Talk piece because they now think she
is just as bad as he is in trying to manipulate them,'' said Debbie
Then, social psychologist and author of ``Women Who Stay With Men
Who Stray.''
</P>
<P>
   Late-week revelations that Mrs. Clinton's family tree includes a
step-grandfather who was Jewish _ information that could help her
in New York _ might well add to that skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Sympathetic Hillary made a thorough hash of her
attempt to cast her marriage in an understandable light, what of
Andersen's book, which piles troubling tale atop off-putting
anecdote?
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, an erstwhile People magazine senior editor, has made a
living serving up salacious tittle-tattle on celebrities such as
Princess Di, the royal family, and Jack and Jackie Kennedy. His
Jackie, for example, was addicted to speed, suffered from eating
disorders, had affairs both during and after her marriage to JFK,
and was beaten by Aristotle Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen is accustomed to trafficking in tawdriness, in other
words. The problem is, at least as far as Bill Clinton is
concerned, rejecting tawdry stories as unlikely merely because of
the sheer shabbiness of the alleged conduct favors hope over
experience. Still, even if the president has forfeited the benefit
of the doubt, does that necessarily mean it should no longer be
afforded Hillary?
</P>
<P>
   And as far as the new book is concerned, doubt abounds. Andersen
has talked to scores of sources, but some of his assertions are
thinly or ambiguously sourced, and supposition too frequently
supplants proof. Take his suggestion that Hillary pressured
Broaddrick to keep quiet about the sexual assault Broaddrick has
since alleged occurred in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   According to the book, at a Clinton fund-raiser three weeks
after the alleged attack, Hillary pointedly sought Broaddrick out,
took her hand, and thanked her for all she had done for Clinton and
``all you'll keep doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Broaddrick says she tried to pull away, Hillary kept
her hand for a moment longer. ``She was looking me straight in the
eye and I understood perfectly what she'' was ``saying,''
Broaddrick recounts. ``I knew exactly what she meant _ that I was
to keep my mouth shut. That meant that she knew almost from the
beginning _ that he must have confessed at least something to her.
But apparently it was something she was willing to overlook.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one far-reaching ``apparently.'' Unless Broaddrick is
telepathic, to go from a thank you to a supposition of pressure and
thus a presumed knowledge of the alleged rape is to make a rather
large inferential leap. Even Broaddrick has had post-publication
doubts, saying she's really not sure what Hillary knew or meant at
the time of the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen's status as something of a bottom-feeder in the sea of
celebrity is one reason some political experts doubt the new book,
whatever its truths, will seriously hurt Mrs. Clinton. ``I don't
have to accept him as a serious journalist. He writes about
celebrities,'' says Stephen Hess, a senior fellow in governmental
studies at the Brookings Institution. Neither have the media, at
least so far. Instead, Andersen's book has mostly made for light
living stories and gossip column fodder.
</P>
<P>
   A second reason those charges seem unlikely to stick is simpler
still: Chronic Clinton Fatigue Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really burned out on the personal lives of the
Clintons,'' says Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center
for the People and the Press, who has polled on the issue. ``They
want to move on.'
</P>
<P>
   So, oddly, if Hillary was hurt last week, the damage was mostly
self-inflicted. Which is not to say Sympathetic Hillary has
vanquished her evil-twin image once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   That's a longer struggle. If she does run for the Senate, the
voters should get a better fix on who Hillary, outside the White
House bubble, really is. Only a political magician can hide her
real self over the course of a long campaign. And judging by her
fumble-fingered performance last week, Hillary is no Houdini.
</P>
<P>
   As for the slim chance that a Faustian Hillary could fool New
York into thinking her something she's not? Well, if you can fake
it there, you can fake it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
