<HEADER>
A0711 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-09 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING BACK THE CLOCK IN THE CALIFORNIA HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLUMAS NATIONAL FOREST, Calif. _ Plenty of people wish they
could turn the years back to an earlier time, like the days of the
frontier, of Joe Walker, Kit Carson and Jim Bridger.
</P>
<P>
   Two fellows in the Sierra foothills do exactly that almost every
weekend. Their names are Ron Stover and Bill Clemons, who have
created Swamp Creek Outfitters and Guide Service, which specializes
in setting up camps and adventures modeled after the era of the
1830s and the Rocky Mountain fur trade.
</P>
<P>
   To get the picture, they set up everything, plan all the
adventures for the campers they host. At the same time, if you try
packing anything modern, such as a radio, flashlight or an item
made out of plastic or nylon, well, ``We tell them to keep it out
of our sight,'' Stover said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in our camp, including our ice chest, is dated for
1830s or earlier,'' Stover said. ``Not many people do this kind of
thing and it's become a dying piece of history. Our goal is try and
teach kids and adults about the outdoors, to capture some of the
lost skills.''
</P>
<P>
   On this weekend trip, Stover and Clemons have set up a camp at
Long Lake in remote Plumas National Forest, which can be reached
with an extremely rugged 4-wheeler or a 5-mile hike, one way. If
you were to visit you would discover a camp that looks like a scene
out of ``Jeremiah Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   It is like an artist's painting of a camp from the 1830s. From a
distance, the first thing you'd spot is what appears to be a small
Indian encampment, with two teepees, a one-pole tent (resembles a
pyramid), and a wedge tent (shaped like inverted V, popular in the
Civil War and for hundreds of year before that).
</P>
<P>
   As you get closer, you will see the signs of recent activity,
furs, deer-hide bags, traps (not set, of course) and for music, a
drum and a flute, and Stover and Clemons will likely be
demonstrating woodsmanship skills of the time period. That might
include shooting bows and arrows, flintlock muzzleloaders, how to
start a campfire with flint and steel, how to tan hides, and how to
set up a weather-resistant camp with nothing more than Carson had,
a tarp and a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to go to primitive areas that best recapture the
period,'' Stover said. ``That means extremely remote and beautiful
places with unfished streams.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the adventure is learning the respect of nature and
safety in all applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the woods out fishing, camping or hunting 200 days a
year,'' Stover said. ``It's not our job, but we take people out as
often as we can, which ends up a few weekends a month. What we do
is outfit people to come and do this, and then share the ways of
the mountain man.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the 1830s, many mountain men went by nicknames, such as
Liver-Eating Johnson and Hatchet Jack. So do Stover and Clemons.
</P>
<P>
   Stover goes by ``K.B.'' because he's the head cook, and Clemons
by Broken Drum because, right, he broke his drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were having fun one night, watching the stars and banging
on the drum, while people were dancing around the campfire, hooting
and hollering,'' Clemons said. ``I was having so much fun that when
I hit it with the drum beater, it went right through skin.''
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, Clemons stared at his drum, and spoke the
obvious in disbelief, ``I broke my drum,'' and a nickname was born.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these fellows fits the part. At camp, they dress in
leather buckskins, and Clemons always wears a beaver felt hat. They
are also big guys, over 250 pounds, and Clemons has a
neatly-trimmed beard.
</P>
<P>
   No one else is offering trips like this to the public in
California. The experience generates close bonding between family
members, memories of a lifetime, and a chance to relive history.
</P>
<P>
   For a camping/trapping expedition, four days and three nights,
the cost is $525 and includes having your camp outfitted, including
all equipment, food and cooking provided, along with guide service;
photographic hunts and a variety of discounts are also available.
The trapping is educational, which means no animals are taken.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For a brochure, write Swamp Creek, P.O. Box 13, Stirling, CA
95978, phone 530-873-4397, or contact via the Internet at
www.Swampcreek.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
