r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX     08-09 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY SCOUTS NEED TO ALTER GAY POLICY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey's Supreme Court made a gutsy, highly controversial
decision this past week when it ruled that the Boy Scouts of
America cannot exclude gays from its organization.
</P>
<P>
   The legal arguments in the case are complicated. They revolve
around whether the BSA is a sufficiently public and broad-based
organization to fall under New Jersey's Law Against Discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a lawyer. I don't know how the U.S. Supreme Court will
rule if it agrees to hear an appeal of the New Jersey case that the
BSA, based in Irving, Texas, is expected to file.
</P>
<P>
   I know, however, that I'm weary of seeing people being
discriminated against, ridiculed or excluded from organizations
merely because they are gay.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jersey case, the court ruled unanimously that James Dale,
29, a former assistant scoutmaster and Eagle Scout, was improperly
kicked out of the Boy Scouts when he was 19 because he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   I was cheered by the compassionate sentiments expressed by the
Jersey court in its ruling, as well as by the reaction of the
state's Republican governor, Christie Whitman, to the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The court's chief justice, Deborah Poritz, compared Dale's
struggle for fair and equal treatment to those of women and
minorities against bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad truth is that excluded groups and individuals have
been prevented from full participation in the social, economic and
political life of our country,'' Poritz wrote. ``The human price of
this bigotry has been enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   A person's sexual preference should be a private matter, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the troop leader is a good leader, there is no reason to
worry about his sexual preferences,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the BSA constitutes a ``public accommodation''
under the Jersey law in that it historically has had a broad-based
membership and has traditionally partnered with various public
entities.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, the court said the Boy Scouts have had local
membership drives that include ``School Nights'' conducted in
public schools. It also cites the Scouts' longtime close ties to
the military and their use of military facilities. The court noted
that many fire and police agencies have helped sponsor scouting
units.
</P>
<P>
   The BSA contends it is a private organization that has the right
to establish its own membership and leadership standards. After the
Jersey court's ruling, BSA spokesman John Holland said, ``The
Scouts are committed to upholding traditional values, and we do not
believe avowed homosexuals can serve as role models for the Scout
oath and law.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey court's ruling currently affects only that state.
But if the U.S. Supreme Court were to rule in an appeal of the
case, there could be nationwide implications.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the BSA has a legal right to exclude gays,
it should voluntarily end its discriminatory exclusion of them.
People such as Dale, who apparently was an exemplary Boy Scout,
shouldn't be booted out of the organization just because they have
a sexual orientation different from that of the majority of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Jersey court called membership in the BSA ``an American
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   One of America's greatest traditions is to be tolerant of
differences in people.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think gay people ``choose'' their sexual orientation,
any more than heterosexual people ``choose'' theirs. When it comes
to sexual orientation, some people just naturally lean one way and
some the other.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider the ridicule, physical violence, social
ostracism, rejection by family members and discrimination that many
gay people suffer, why would anyone think that they willfully
``choose'' to be gay?
</P>
<P>
   I would like to see a federal law passed to outlaw
discrimination against gays in hiring, housing and public
accommodations such as hotels and restaurants. Some states and
cities already have such laws.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are federal, state and local laws on the books
that outlaw discrimination against people based on their race,
gender, religion, national origin and disability. Sexual
orientation should be added to that list. That would mean you
couldn't fire people, refuse to rent an apartment to them or bar
them from a restaurant merely because they are homosexual,
heterosexual or bisexual.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's a genuine legal question as to whether the Boy
Scouts should be subject to anti-discrimination laws such as the
New Jersey statute.
</P>
<P>
   But I would hope that the organization of which I was a proud
member as a boy will see fit to change its outdated, exclusionary
policy toward gays.
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is an editorial writer and columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7724 or
jzsmith(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
