<HEADER>
A0745 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMAL-HAVEN-ART-SPI &LR;      08-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-HAVEN-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PATIENTS' KEEP ARRIVING AT SANCTUARY FOR ABUSED FARM ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SULTAN, Wash. _ On some days, Susan Michaels fields as many as
80 calls.
</P>
<P>
   One caller has a tip on six ducks shot by blow darts in Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Another wonders whether her sanctuary can take two sick pygmy
goats found dumped in Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   A third has another problem: An abandoned rooster needs a home.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life at Pasado's Safe Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The animal sanctuary, the first in the Pacific Northwest for
abused and neglected farm animals, celebrated its first anniversary
this past weekend with an open house and a ``Bow-Wow Bash'' for the
hundreds of volunteers who make it all possible.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since it's opening, the haven, named in memory of a
donkey beaten and strangled at a Bellevue park in 1992, has taken
in hundreds of animals that had been starved, abandoned and shot.
</P>
<P>
   They include 200 rabbits, 45 chickens, two cows, two donkeys,
two turkeys, two pigs, three goats, six dogs, 28 cats and one
three-legged sheep.
</P>
<P>
   There's Tommy the longhorn calf, favoring one side as he walks
with four bullet wounds inflicted by teenage tormenters.
</P>
<P>
   There's Hope, the sickly Holstein calf who was slurping from a
bottle when the shelter opened last year. Since then, she's grown
into a sturdy 1,500-pound teenager of a cow.
</P>
<P>
   And there's Lucille the pink pig, who was being auctioned as a
breeder sow. On this day, she wags her tufted tail as Michaels, who
founded the sanctuary with her husband, rubs Lucille's stomach and
feeds her carrots.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary, says Richard Huffman, of the Lynnwood-based
Progressive Animal Welfare Society, has helped fill a void in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   PAWS operates shelters for domestic and wild animals, but not
for farm animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole other subgroup of animals that just kind of
falls through the cracks ... and that's where Susan comes in,''
Huffman said.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary takes in the animals, rehabilitates them, and, in
many cases, finds them new homes.
</P>
<P>
   But Michaels' other role has been as a savvy promoter of animal
welfare. She's made the sanctuary a prominent voice, whether
offering rewards in animal cruelty cases, educating school classes
who regularly visit the sanctuary classrooms or sponsoring events,
such as a vegan Thanksgiving where the turkey guests were gobbling
as loudly as the humans.
</P>
<P>
   One of her proudest achievements this year was convincing the
Highline School District south of Seattle to remove a
chick-hatching project from the science kits it distributed
throughout area schools.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the animals at the sanctuary has a name, part of a
conscious effort by Michaels and her husband, Mark Steinway, to
present the animals as individuals rather than producers of milk
and meat.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the sanctuary came to Michaels after she helped
lobby for tougher animal cruelty laws in the wake of Pasado's
death.
</P>
<P>
   A former TV personality who later owned women's formalwear
shops, she sold her businesses, sold her Bellevue home and bought
25 acres of land near Sultan, in Snohomish County about 30 miles
northeast of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary has no paid staff. It gets by with a combination
of Steinway's salary as a video editor and the goodwill army of
volunteers who donate food, labor and materials.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinary costs are their main expense, Steinway said.
</P>
<P>
   Bins of produce from the homegrocer.com warehouse are a regular
boon _ especially for the 200-odd rabbits rescued from a Redmond
development.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 people each month stop in for work parties to build
fences and stalls, plant apple trees for the animals' future treats
and dig ditches.
</P>
<P>
   A new barn, paid for with a $30,000 grant through the Northwest
Animal Rights Network, will be dedicated today, a rooster weather
vane proudly turning overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Less-visible but no less significant are the off-site
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   A Rolodex in Michaels' office has a fat section of cards under R
for ``rescue,'' with a network of area residents willing to take in
animals after they've been rehabilitated at the haven.
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue residents Joanne and Brendan Brannen joined after they
heard about the haven through an in-house e-mail when Joanne
Brannen worked at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Former ``dog and cat people,'' they now have two goats, two
sheep, a rooster and chickens on their fenced Bellevue property.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Brannen said she made the commitment after meeting Hope
the calf on a visit to the haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just feeding that animal with a bottle, it was amazing,'' she
said. ``It was no different than a dog and a cat, and yet the
treatment is so different.'' The Brannens now plan to buy a larger
property near the haven to allow them to take in more animals.
Another couple has already bought 15 nearby acres for the same
purpose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
