<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Aug.
10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YUCCA-NUKE (Undated) _ Scientists ponder the suitability of
the nation's burial group, Yucca Mountain, for its most deadly
radioactive waste. By Jon Christenson. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAIN-PAIN (Undated) _ Moving pictures of the brain now are
showing doctors just how pain works and how severe the pain is.
Eventually, they hope that knowledge will help in treating pain. By
Holcomb B. Noble. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GOD-PARTICLE (Undated) _ The race to find an elusive but
all-important particle called the Higgs boson heated up last week
when Europe's most powerful accelerator reached an energy that may
bring the target within range. Because of its presumably vital
importance to universal existence, the Higgs boson was dubbed ``The
God Particle'' in the title of a book by Dr. Leon Lederman, a Nobel
laureate in physics. The god-like importance ascribed to the Higgs
is based on the belief that it endows all the constituents of
matter with mass; it is the universal giver of heft. By Malcolm W.
Browne. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOOMSDAY (Undated) _ Amid the summer news doldrums, what
could be more invigorating than a warning that physicists may be on
the verge of destroying the world? Luckily, this and similar alarms
can be taken with a large grain of salt, and viewed in the proper
light, disaster warnings can be fun. The idea that human beings
could actually obliterate their planet may be scary, but like a
roller-coaster ride, it is thrilling. Even in the face of doomsday
speculation, most reasonable people are pretty sure that the global
roller coaster will stay on the track despite the hair-raising
ride. By Malcolm W. Browne. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLUTO (Undated) _ Two telescopes in Hawaii have seen beyond
previous limits of visibility to make intriguing discoveries about
the surface composition of the planet Pluto and Saturn's largest
satellite, Titan. One telescope revealed the existence of the
hydrocarbon ethane on Pluto's surface, potentially significant
because it may be a remnant component of the original interstellar
gas cloud that collapsed to form the solar system. Another
telescope detected what may be liquid or frozen seas of
hydrocarbons on Titan, which could be the only ones known in the
solar system other than those on Earth. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ECLIPSE (Undated) _ The solar eclipse that will sweep across
Europe, the Middle East and the Indian subcontinent on Wednesday
promises to be one of the most watched in history. By Henry
Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on
ocelots' reaction to Obsession, parrots that eat clay and robot
championships. By Henry fountain. (690 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: The
insulin pump is changing the lives of more than 50,000 people who
are now using it. And many more could easily use it. By Jane E.
Brody. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VIAGRA-WOMEN (Undated) _ A small study shows that women
taking antidepressants can overcome the side effects affecting
their sex lives with doses of Viagra an hour before encounters. By
Anne Eisenberg. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BULLIES (Undated) _ When bullies and victims are the same
people. By Susan Gilbert. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HOSPITAL-RISK (Undated) _ Hospital patients often subject
themselves to risk just by being in a hospital, where mistakes
often happen. By Sandeep Juahar, M.D. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHAPE-RECOGNITION (Undated) _ Scientists have long assumed
that people must see shape in the same way at all sizes. Otherwise,
they would recognize friends or the letter ``a'' differently at
each distance or size. Yet the artist Chuck Close is exhibiting
paintings that refute this assumption, showing that size can
dramatically affect what shape we see. By Denis Pelli. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-WEIGHTS (Undated) _ Lightweight, high-speed
weight-training techniques now are being recommended as a part of
essential training for serious and recreational athletes alike. By
Liz Neporent. (740 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Optimism and self-confidence may prove to be potent weapons in
staving off a recurrence of heart disease, if a new study by
Carnegie Mellon researchers is any indication. Patients in the
study who evidenced a positive outlook, greater self-control and
higher self-esteem after angioplasty surgery were less likely to
suffer a heart attack, undergo bypass surgery, or require a second
angioplasty in the next six months. (265 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Two women taking Chinese herbal preparations to treat eczema
suffered kidney failure, raising new questions about the safety of
the remedies, according to a report in the British medical journal
The Lancet. (330 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Chocolate, a new report indicates, contains high levels of
catechins, substances with antioxidant properties that may help
fight cancer and heart disease. (220 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Supplying oxygen to patients awaiting surgery after suffering
a detached retina may help decrease damage to the eye, according to
a California researcher who has successfully tested his theory on
cats. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SLIMANE-FASHION (Undated) _ Heidi Slimane, Yves Saint-Laurent
men's wear designer. By Cathy Horne.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS-FASHION (Undated) _ News and notes on fashion. By Cathy
Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ENGLAND-IMAGE (Washington) _ A Critic's Notebook:
``Picturing Old New England: Image and Memory,'' a revisionist
exhibition at the National Museum of American Art. By Holland
Cotter. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   LAST-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Last Life,'' by Claire Messud
(Harcourt Brace). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column. By Harvey
Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-DODGERS (New York) _ Los Angeles Dodgers at the Mets,
7:40 p.m. EDT start. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND (Oakland, Calif.) _ N.Y. Yankees at the
Oakland A's, 10:05 p.m. EDT start. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-LUKAS (Sarotoga Springs, N.Y.) _ D. Wayne Lukas is
inducted into the Racing Hall of Fame in a year in which he came
close to winning the Triple Crown. By Joseph Durso.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS-STRAHAN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Giants and Michael
Strahan come to an agreement on a long-term deal that will make the
defensive end the highest-paid defensive player in the NFL. By Bill
Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BROWNS-COWBOYS (Canton, Ohio) _ The new Cleveland Browns
make their debut in the Hall of Fame preseason game, with their
opponent being none other than the Dallas Cowboys. Because Canton
is near Cleveland, the stand should be filled with jubilant Browns
fans welcoming their new team. Game time is 8:05 p.m. EDT. By
Thomas George.
</P>
