<HEADER>
A0751 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HITCHCOCK-FILMS-LADN     08-09 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITCHCOCK-FILMS-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Here's a look at Alfred Hitchcock's films,
starting with what is considered his breakthrough film, ``The
Lodger,'' a story of Jack the Ripper. Titles with slashes indicate
the British name before the slash and the American name following
the slash. ``Sabotage,'' for instance, was released as ``A Woman
Alone'' in the United States, though today it is known by its
British title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lodger''/``The Case of Jonathan Drew'' (1926) _ director,
screenwriter
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mountain Eagle'' (1926) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Downhill'' (1927) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy Virtue'' (1927) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ring'' (1927) _ director, screenwriter, story
</P>
<P>
   ``Champagne'' (1928) _ director, screenwriter, adaptation
</P>
<P>
   ``The Farmer's Wife'' (1928) _ director, screenwriter
</P>
<P>
   ``Blackmail'' (1929) _ director, screenwriter, adaptation
</P>
<P>
   ``The Manxman'' (1929) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Juno and the Paycock'' (1930) _ director, adaptation
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder!'' (1930) _ director, screenwriter, adaptation
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'''' (1930) _ director. German-language version of
``Murder''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skin Game'' (1931) _ director, screenwriter, adaptation
</P>
<P>
   ``Number Seventeen'' (1932) _ director, co-screenwriter
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich and Strange''/``East of Shanghai'' (1932) _ director,
adaptation
</P>
<P>
   ``Strauss's Great Waltz''/``Waltzes From Vienna'' (1933) _
director
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Who Knew Too Much'' (1934) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``The 39 Steps'' (1935) _ director. This is one of Hitchcock's
favorite films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sabotage''/``A Woman Alone'' (1936) _ director. Hitchcock
thought he made a mistake in the way he handled the time-bomb
scene. ``It was wrong to build up the audience's suspense and not
to relieve it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secret Agent'' (1936) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Young and Innocent'' (1937) _ director. Francois Truffaut
noted that it has one of the longest crane shots ever made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lady Vanishes'' (1938) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamaica Inn'' (1939) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign Correspondent'' (1940) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebecca'' (1940) _ director. According to director Peter
Bogdanovich, David O. Selznick wanted the camera at the end of the
film to pull back to show the smoke from the burning building
forming the letter ``R'' in the sky. Hitchcock's response ``Can you
imagine!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. &AMP; Mrs. Smith'' (1941) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Suspicion'' (1941) _ director. Hitchcock put a light bulb
inside a glass of milk that Cary Grant brings to Joan Fontaine to
help make it look more suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saboteur'' (1942) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadow of a Doubt'' (1943) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Adventure Malgache'' (1944) _ director, a documentary short
never released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bon Voyage'' (1944) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifeboat'' (1944) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Spellbound'' (1945) _ director. It includes a dream sequence
using surrealist artist Salvador Dali sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notorious'' (1946) _ producer, director. When Cary Grant
breaks that bottle of champagne, he finds ``some kind of metal
ore.'' Originally, Hitchcock thought the idea of uranium 235, from
which the future atomic bomb would be made, might be interesting,
but they made it industrial diamonds.But the FBI was interested,
this being shot before Hiroshima. Hitchcock was followed for three
months. The production code at the time censored ``protracted
kissing.'' Hitchcock had Cary Grant and Ingrid Bergman kiss ``in
stages'' _ 18 kisses in two minutes, 38 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Paradine Case'' (1948) _ director
</P>
<P>
   ``Rope'' (1948) _ producer, director. Inspired by the Leopold
and Loeb murder case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Capricorn'' (1949) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Stage Fright'' (1950) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangers on a Train'' (1951) _ producer, director. Hitchcock
set the tone for the film in the opening shot of shoes, with the
styles of the shoes and gaits of the two main characters showing
their different personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Confess'' (1953) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Dial M for Murder'' (1954) _ producer, director. It was
originally filmed in 3-D, perfect for the Master. Note Grace Kelly
reaching through the screen for those scissors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window'' (1954) _ producer, director. The camera never
leaves the room, unless it's outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Catch a Thief'' (1955) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``The Trouble With Harry'' (1955) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Who Knew Too Much'' (1956) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wrong Man'' (1957) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertigo'' (1958) producer, director. For the effect of
dizziness as James Stewart looks over the staircase, the camera
physically moved backward, as the lens zoomed forward. To do this,
a model of the staircase was made and laid on its side on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``North by Northwest'' (1959) _ producer, director. According to
screenwriter Ernest Lehman, Hitchcock thought a good title would be
``The Man in Lincoln's Nose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Psycho'' (1960)_ producer, director. The film's working title
was ``Wimpy.'' The shower scene took one week to film. It used 70
different setups and 57 edits for 45 seconds on the screen (1,080
frames of film).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Birds'' (1963) _ producer, director. There were more than
370 trick shots in this picture and a mixture of fake birds and
trained birds, including trained seagulls, to circle and dive at
the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marnie'' (1954) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Torn Curtain'' (1966) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Topaz'' (1969) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Frenzy'' (1972) _ producer, director
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Plot'' (1976) _ producer, director &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
