<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-IOWA (Des Moines) _ Part of Iowa is affluent urban and
surbuban, part is bleak farm country. These two Iowas add an
element of unpredictability in the straw poll for the 2000 GOP
nomination. By Michael Kranish. 1580 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-NH (Hopkinton, N.H.) _ One shakes hands with a random
dozen. The other is greeted by hundreds of potential voters lining
the sidewalks. Such is the difference between Bill Bradley and Al
Gore. By Jill Zuckman. 1175 words.
</P>
<P>
   DEFINING-HILLARY (Undated) _ The release of the Talk magazine
interview and a new book on the Clintons' marriage focuses
attention on the two sides of Hillary. By Scot Lehigh. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   LYME-VICTIMS (Falmouth, Mass.) _ Doctors estimate there are
thousands of patients suffering debilitating mental illnesses _
their affliction misdiagnosed and long mistreated _ because they
contracted Lyme disease before it was widely known. By Yvonne
Abraham. 1300 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ETHNIC-SYMBOLS (Boston) _ A controversy surrounding emblems in a
racially diverse city begs to answer one question: At what point
does an emblem become a source of pride for one group and a threat
to another? By Tatsha Robertson. 1150 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-FAMILY-RULINGS (Boston) _ In three recent cases,
Massachusetts' highest court has issued boldly liberal decisions
that acknowledge the place of nontraditional families in modern
life. Some family law practitioners believe the court is
overstepping. By Sacha Pfeiffer. 930 words.
</P>
