A0769 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HITCHCOCK-CAMEOS-LADN     08-09 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITCHCOCK-CAMEOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK WAS ALSO MASTER OF THE CAMEO
</HEADLINE>
 For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Alfred Hitchcock's cameos in his movies began out
of necessity. In order to fill out some scenes in his 1926 film
``The Lodger,'' he cast himself as an extra. Hitch didn't have
cameos in all of his films, notably ``Suspicion'' (1941), ``The Man
Who Knew Too Much'' (1934), ``Jamaica Inn'' (1939) and ``Secret
Agent'' (1936). In ``The Wrong Man'' (1957), he didn't make a cameo
but did introduce the film. In later films, when the cameo was
expected, he would make his presence known early so the audience
wouldn't be distracted looking for him, but that wasn't always the
case. In 1946's ``Notorious'' he appeared halfway through the film.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the films Hitch made cameos in and where you can find
him:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lodger'' (1926): First of the famous cameo roles, and you
get twice as much of him _ first you see him seated at a desk in a
newsroom, and later, wearing a cap and leaning against a railing,
he's one of the bystanders watching the arrest of Ivor Novello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blackmail'' (1929): Bothered by a little boy while trying to
read a book on the subway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder!'' (1930): Passer-by on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 39 Steps'' (1935): Passer-by on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young and Innocent'' (1937): One of his longer appearances
(about 20 seconds) as a clumsy press photographer taking a photo of
the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lady Vanishes'' (1938): Smoking a cigarette in a London
railway station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebecca'' (1940): Standing outside a phone booth while George
Sanders makes a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign Correspondent'' (1940): Reading a newspaper on the
street, just before Joel McCrea meets Van Meer (Albert Basserman).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. &AMP; Mrs. Smith'' (1941): On the street, not noticing Robert
Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saboteur'' (1942): At the newsstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadow of a Doubt'' (1943): Playing cards on a train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifeboat'' (1944): Pictured in a before-and-after weight
reduction advertisement in a newspaper being read by William
Bendix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spellbound'' (1945): Getting off a crowded hotel elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notorious'' (1946): Drinking champagne at a party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Paradine Case'' (1948): Carrying a cello case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rope'' (1948): Crossing the street during the opening credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Capricorn'' (1949): Another double bill _ first, at the
governor's house, and second, on the steps of the government house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stage Fright'' (1950): Turning back in the street to look at
Jane Wyman, who's talking to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangers on a Train'' (1951): Boarding a train, carrying a
bass violin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Confess'' (1953): Crossing the screen at the top of a long
staircase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dial M for Murder'' (1954): In a class-reunion photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window'' (1954): Winding a clock in an apartment while
another character plays the piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Catch a Thief'' (1955): On a bus, next to Cary Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Trouble With Harry'' (1955): At an outdoor exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Who Knew Too Much'' (1956): Watching acrobats in a
Marrakesh marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertigo'' (1958): Crossing the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``North by Northwest'' (1959): Running to catch a bus with the
door slamming in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psycho'' (1960): Standing outside the real estate office,
wearing a 10-gallon hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Birds'' (1963): Exiting a pet shop, with two Scottie dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marnie'' (1964): Coming out of a hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Torn Curtain'' (1966): In the hotel lobby, with a baby on his
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Topaz'' (1969): At the airport in a wheelchair attended by a
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frenzy'' (1972): Spectator in a crowd scene watching a body
being pulled from the Thames River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Plot'' (1976): In silhouette, seen behind the door of
the office of ``births and deaths.''
</P>
</TEXT>
