<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-09 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRE-PAID CELLPHONE CARDS STARTING TO CONNECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We thought we'd discovered all the good cellular phone deals
until we got an e-mail last week from Tom Metro, a computer
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   He asked us why we never wrote about pre-paid cell phone cards
as a low-cost way for skeptics to try wireless phone service. Metro
had been shopping around for a plan for his elderly mother, who
wants a cell phone for emergencies only. He found a Cellular One
pre-paid analog plan for $90 that includes 120 minutes and lasts an
entire year.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cost for each minute is a hefty 75 cents, this plan's
one-year $90 cost compares favorably to most standard monthly plans
that cost at least $200 a year. And the offer lasts a year, while
most pre-paid minutes expire in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   With analog handsets so cheap these days (maybe even free if you
can find someone who has abandoned an analog handset after
converting to a digital phone), this pre-paid option struck Metro
as a smart solution for a safety-oriented user.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. And he's also onto a new trend in the wireless
world: promoting pre-paid cards not only to serve those who don't
financially qualify for standard contracts, but to first-timers or
transient folks who don't want big commitments or monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless analysts say companies in New York, Miami, and
Philadelphia have already slashed prices on pre-paid cards and
sweetened the terms to attract a wide mix of consumers. Some
discount resellers are getting into the act there as well.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the pre-paid cellular phone market is just starting
to heat up. AT&AMP;T Wireless has yet to offer any pre-paid cards here,
but other major carriers have begun lowering prices and tinkering
with terms of their pre-paid cards.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Thigpen, vice president and general manager of pre-paid
services for Boston Communications Group in Woburn, Mass., which
runs pre-paid card systems for carriers, said Boston lags behind
other cities in this niche market. But he sees signs that carriers
view these cards as ways to draw in first-time users, as well as
teenagers, college students, or temporary residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're extending beyond the credit-challenged,'' he said,
using a phrase frequently heard in the industry to describe people
with nonexistent or bad credit histories that disqualify them for
standard contracts.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a cell phone with any regularity you're far better
off going with a standard contract, assuming you qualify. Permanent
charges on standard plans are as low as a dime or a quarter a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the most aggressive pre-paid seller is Omnipoint, and
roughly half its customers are pre-paid users. This company's $50
pre-paid card buys 125 minutes, for instance. It comes to 40 cents
a minute, the lowest pre-paid price in the Boston market. Minutes
expire in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS revamped its pre-paid offerings this past May,
promoting lower per-minute prices and no expiration dates. But
there's two negative surprises in the package: There's a $125
activation fee and you must pay a 50-cent daily maintenance charge
on top of your usage, which amounts to a $15 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Duncan, marketing manager for Sprint PCS in New England,
said the company is trying to turn its ``credit-challenged''
customers in another direction, to its ``Account Spending Limit''
program that puts a spending lid on an account. In this way, people
can go with cheaper per-minute standard contracts.
</P>
<P>
   If you must buy your own handset, keep in mind that analog ones
may become defunct in a year or so as the entire cellular world
goes digital. Don't pay a lot for an analog phone if you have to
buy one.
</P>
<P>
   While a Yankee Group study finds that prepaid accounts represent
about 4 percent of wireless subscribers, analysts predict more
people will flock to this option as prices drop and expiration
dates become more distant. That's likely to bring in many who might
now be on the sidelines, turned off by the upfront costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies are starting to focus more on the neophytes and
skeptics,'' said Lowenstein of the Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
E-commerce and sales tax
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the growth of Internet buying, we've gotten more questions
about when buyers have to pay Massachusetts sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   State revenue officials say Internet purchases are viewed the
same as mail-order buys. If the company selling the product has ``a
physical presence in Massachusetts'' _ such as a retail store,
warehouse, phone banks or sales offices _ it must collect sales tax
from the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this covers only ``taxable items'' as defined by this
state. So if you buy a $50 sweater on-line from the Gap clothing
store, which has a physical presence here, the store can't collect
sales tax because a clothing item under $175 is not taxable.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, associate general counsel for the state Department
of Revenue, said shipping and handling charges are generally
considered exempt from sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Now get this: The law goes further to say that if the company
does not have a physical presence here and you buy a taxable item
from them, such as a computer, it is your responsibility to send in
the appropriate sales tax amount to the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   (State revenue officials say this is a ``tough tax to
collect.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   --Cell phones and 911: If you have a spare cell phone, keep in
mind that Federal Communications Commission rules require carriers
to put through any 911 emergency call on any handset. That includes
handsets that no longer have an active service contract. That means
if you had an old analog phone with Cellular One, but let the
service contract lapse, you can still use that phone for 911 calls.
Cellular One has to put through the call, at its own expense. So
spare cell phones, which might now be used as a child's toy, might
be better off charged-up and in a car's glove compartment.
</P>
<P>
   --Minimum purchases on credit cards? A reader recently asked if
merchants are allowed to set minimum purchase requirements when
using a Visa card. She recently wanted to charge $5 in gasoline.
She said the clerk insisted on an $8 minimum for credit card
purchases. The clerk also offered to charge $8, then return $3 back
in cash. There's no state or federal law on the subject, but Visa
regulations prohibit merchants from setting minimum purchase
requirements or giving cash back. If such violations are brought to
Visa's attention, their contract can be terminated. Said a Visa
spokeswoman: ``Technically, you can charge a pack of gum.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(We want your consumer ideas and tips. Please call 617-474-2510 or
e-mail Wen at wen(at)globe.com or Mohl at mohl(at)globe.com. Their
postal address is PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYNIHAN SEES WHAT OTHERS DON'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Among other big things, Daniel Patrick Moynihan's
illustrious career in public service demonstrates the power of
analytical thinking in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The New York senator has contributed so many gems ahead of his
time in nearly four decades on the stage _ from his research on the
condition of ghetto families to his perception of Richard Nixon's
great opportunity as freshly elected president to be the American
Disraeli to his reflections on the blindness of the late-Cold War
CIA to the reality of Soviet weakness _ that one hesitates to pick
one.
</P>
<P>
   But as the chairman-for-life of the Bowtie Caucus rose last week
to lead the opposition to an irresponsible tax cut, it was hard not
to think of a classically Moynihan cut-like-a-diamond paragraph. To
wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans' dominant idea, at least for the moment, seems
to be that the social controls of modern government have become
tyrannical or, at the very least, exorbitantly expensive. This
oppression _ so the strategic analysis goes _ is made possible by
taxation, such that cutting taxes becomes an objective in its own
right, business cycles notwithstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   That would command respect, and journalistic envy, as
contemporary commentary under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But now consider that Moynihan wrote that for The New York Times
nearly 20 years ago, in the early summer of 1980, before Ronald
Reagan had even been elected. It was merely one observation in a
string of them that over time have come to define the terms of
national debate. It is no accident that people who have no
knowledge of Moynihan's astonishing track record see tax cuts well
down on their list of priorities, more as danger than as worthwhile
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, much of the political class was wasting time in
parlor games over whether people like then-Representative Jack Kemp
were correct in their ``new'' theory that government revenues would
be larger with lower tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Moynihan saw a deeper purpose, though not in Kemp's advocacy
per se. Moynihan saw Kemp's party moving away from opposition to
particular initiatives of government on their alleged demerits,
battles they had been losing consistently over issues from medical
care for the elderly to providing federal aid to poverty-impacted
school districts; he saw the Republicans embracing a new strategy
of attacking government itself and avoiding the burden of arguing
specifics, by trying to starve it through tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   And he was already warning by 1980 that the Republicans were
likely to prevail in the short term if they succeeded in attacking
government on behalf of working taxpayers as pseudo-populists,
leaving the Democrats as statist, status quo defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan proved Moynihan correct within days of assuming
office, though the senator had to endure much ridicule before
Reagan spoke of disciplining the child of government by cutting its
allowance.
</P>
<P>
   But there was much more to come:
</P>
<P>
   --It was Moynihan who pounced on the gimmickry and dishonesty of
budget director David Stockman (whom he had mentored at Harvard a
decade earlier) to show that hemorrhaging deficits had been
deliberately engineered.
</P>
<P>
   --It was Moynihan who first and most cogently saw through all
the schemes to ``balance'' the budget in formulaic ways that dodged
specific choices _ from amendments to the Constitution, the main
effect of which would be to make recessions far worse, to
``automatic'' spending cuts that politics and good sense would
never allow to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   --And it was Moynihan who more than a decade ago first caused a
stir by noting that operating surpluses in the Social Security
trust funds were being in effect embezzled to mask and fund
deficits in the rest of government. Today, his once-subversive
analysis is the basis of (at last) sound policy that the latest tax
cut scheme would severely undermine.
</P>
<P>
   All this, by the way, was prelude to Moynihan's signal
accomplishment as chairman of the Senate Finance Committee in
President Clinton's first term. It was Moynihan who guided the 1993
budget plan to passage, which in tandem with a first installment he
supported under President Bush in 1980, made a balanced budget
possible and created the crucial fiscal environment for the current
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   His typically reasoned and civil opposition last week came up
one vote short in an absurdly political atmosphere on the Senate
floor, but the Republican victory reeked of Pyrrhus's.
</P>
<P>
   After all we've learned, much of it from Moynihan, it is hard to
imagine we are anywhere near making the same colossal mistake again
after a $4 trillion run-up in the national debt that the senator
also foresaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0798 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENT-LATINO-BOS &LR;      08-09 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-LATINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKY'S ONLY ONE STAR IN A HUGE LATIN GALAXY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Music writers call him a one-hit wonder. Others assail him as
``too pop.'' And while Americans bop their heads to the beat of
Ricky Martin's snare drum, the predictions of his demise drop like
bombs. But don't believe a word they say.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them don't know Latin music. They base their predictions
on lesser Latino artists who have come and gone. Most of those
critics had never heard of Martin _ an artist who's been recording
for 15 years _ until his smash single, ``Livin' La Vida Loca.'' As
copies of his self-titled English debut were snatched off the
shelves, with more than 5 million copies sold so far, the critics
had to answer to readers who wanted to know: Why haven't you
written about him?
</P>
<P>
   That's when the scurrying began. Writers flipped through press
releases, searched their electronic libraries to find out what had
been written, listened to the CD a few times, and _ with deadlines
looming _ cranked out superficial reviews. Their idea of context
was ``La Macarena.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Christopher Columbus, the critics thought they had
discovered something. But Ricky's not new. After four years
performing with the Puerto Rican boy group Menudo, he put out four
solo albums.
</P>
<P>
   The critics say he's ``not Latin enough,'' but they'd be hard
pressed to define what that means. Latin pop isn't English verses
set to Latin music. It's not watered-down Latin music. It's not a
new genre, made for American consumers. It is its own vast
category, decades old, just like Latin rock, Latin hip-hop, and
Latin jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Without understanding the history of how Latin pop came to be,
the critics are at a loss. They've got a pocketful of stereotypical
words that they can't use: exotic, spicy, sexy, sultry. Mainstream
music writers sprinkle those words into copy, in an attempt to
capture the essence of music that is foreign to them. And when an
artist like Martin comes along, with vibrant music that sounds
familiar, they get suspicious. That's what happens when they ignore
the music of an entire continent.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of Latinos _ Marc Anthony, Los Trio-O, Selena _ have had
huge US success with little marketing. One of the biggest surprises
this year came from a group of elderly Cuban musicians who recorded
long-forgotten danzons and sons on ``Buena Vista Social Club.'' It
sold more than 421,000 units in the United States, according to
SoundScan, and picked up a Grammy along the way _ proof that
Americans are hungry for musica Latina.
</P>
<P>
   The critics _ who should be ahead of the trends, introducing us
to new sounds _ realized they missed the story, so now they want to
dismiss Ricky.
</P>
<P>
   And they're missing another trend that's been unfolding in
recent years: the wave of young Latino artists experimenting with
new sounds. Artists like Shakira, Fulanito, Mana, Ilegales, A. B.
Quintanilla Y Los Kumbia Kings, and Dark Latin Groove.
</P>
<P>
   They avoid writing about Latin music, yet less popular genres,
including American folk, get ink. (While we're on the subject, how
can they continue to ignore hip-hop, considering it is the most
influential genre of our time?)
</P>
<P>
   What makes Ricky Martin's music exciting is his incorporation of
rock and jazz. When an American rock artist mixes different sounds,
it's called fusion. And when artists such as Sting or even Madonna
blend in bits of flamenco guitar or beats from a conga, they call
it ``experimental projects.'' But when Latino musicians borrow
elements of rock, critics call it watered down.
</P>
<P>
   Though Latinos love traditional music _ rancheros, plenas,
cumbias, boleros, merengues _ we've long embraced newer musical
styles. It's time for critics to do the same, considering that the
American public, tired of the yawning rhythms of rock, has.
</P>
<P>
   When Ricky Martin performed at the Grammy awards this year,
singing his international hit, ``La Copa de la Vida,'' he brought
down the house. Until then, most Americans hadn't heard of him,
even though millions of copies of ``The Cup of Life'' had sold
throughout Europe, Latin America, and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, as I drove around Puerto Rico, Ricky's homeland,
his voice seemed to echo everywhere, from bustling San Juan to
quaint rural towns. The island's governor, Pedro Rossello, adopted
it as a theme song while campaigning for statehood before the
plebescite. Campaign vans with monster stereo systems blared
Martin's pulsating music. The hypnotic rhythms made you want to
dance in your sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as that sound rumbles throughout America, I have to wonder:
Will the critics be ready for the next Latin music star? Or will
they dust off those ``Macarena'' reviews?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Cindy Rodriguez's e-mail address is
c(underscore)rodriguez(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0807 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     08-09 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CAN WE KNOW WHOM WE'RE ELECTING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Across America, people are reacting negatively to an increasing
phoniness in American politics. The avalanche of big private money
into political campaigns is not only corrupting legislation, it's
drying up originality and genuineness among candidates.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, the gates to congressional service are opened to
those who can raise big money from private contributors for
television commercials and professional campaign consultants, and
closed to those _ regardless of vision, commitment and ability _
who cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln wouldn't have made it in today's environment.
Nor would Harry Truman.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, 95 percent of the contested congressional races
went to the candidate who raised and spent the most money. It was
history's first billion-dollar election.
</P>
<P>
   Among the world's leading democracies, ours is distinguished by
two dismal statistics. We spend the most, per capita, on our
campaigns _ ads, commercials and ballyhoo. And we have the lowest
turnout of voters among those legally qualified to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we claim to be the foremost example of self-government.
Shame!
</P>
<P>
   The repeated refusal of Congress to address campaign finances
drives an ever-bigger wedge between lawmakers and the public.
Dominance by money shrinks the electorate's faith in our system,
promoting a crass commercial hucksterism that disconnects
candidates from the average citizen. It puts its premium on
phoniness, its hope in gullibility.
</P>
<P>
   The public isn't really deceived. It's just increasingly turned
off. William Safire, New York Times columnist and former
presidential speech writer, recently offered a perceptive column
pleading with politicians to stop playing roles and be themselves!
</P>
<P>
   Safire's target was the growing habit among office seekers to
hire professional consultants to adjust their public personas, much
as aging actors engage plastic surgeons to make them look younger
than they are.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate objects of this advice were Hillary Clinton, New
York Mayor Rudy Giuliani and Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin. Paid political gurus, Safire reports, are trying to make
over each with a new and different personality. But his broader
message is to politicos in general: Be yourself.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Fort Worth Star Telegram columnist Bill Thompson
offered the same advice _ be yourself _ to Vice President Al Gore
and presidential hopeful Bill Bradley. Both, Thompson wrote, have
``enlisted the aid of consultants and coaches'' to help them
``become more magnetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Thompson adds (and I agree) that the longer one talks with
either man, the more clear it becomes that he is thoughtful,
creative and possessed of intellectual depth and principle.
</P>
<P>
   But how _ in the current system of political practice, can the
average citizen expect to know? Given the slick slogans and
repetitive, market-tested simplifications carefully crafted to help
candidates ``stick to message'' and dodge controversial questions _
can we ever come to feel that we know a candidate?
</P>
<P>
   Most advanced democracies give candidates free and equal
television time for serious discussion of issues. People appreciate
it. They vote. Here, where TV time is exorbitant, politicians
address complex questions with slogans. They don't reveal thought _
they conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling over the country in recent years, speaking often to
college audiences, I sometimes encounter a young person seeking
advice on how to get started in elective politics. I give what
suggestions I can.
</P>
<P>
   Usually I'll ask, ``Why do you want to be in Congress?'' With
discouraging frequency, I'm getting answers that have less and less
to do with public needs or legislative solutions, what an
officeholder can do for the country. Instead, I'm hearing what
being in office might do for the individual's career goals.
</P>
<P>
   For a young law student to covet the experience and public
exposure he'd get by serving as an assistant district attorney
doesn't bother me if I think the youth qualified. But I am
disturbed when a bright, ambitious young person aspires to go to
Congress, or the Legislature, without the faintest notion of what
issues he or she would support.
</P>
<P>
   Some years back, a brilliant young man set out to be elected to
the Texas Legislature as a calculated steppingstone to higher
office. Steeped in the techniques of sampling opinion, he based his
appeal solely upon issues he had market-tested through opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
   He cut three separate 50-second videotapes advocating these
issues and sought to test these tapes before small focus groups of
friends to decide which of the three to use on television. ``I want
you to listen carefully to these,'' he asked, ``and tell me in
which of the three you think I seem the most sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   He was surprised when I said, ``The way to seem sincere is to be
sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, that's about all Harry Truman had going for him. But it
was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we need to re-examine that word. ``Sincere.'' It stems
from two Latin words, meaning literally ``without wax.'' Roman
merchants had begun importing artifacts and ceramics goods from the
Greek islands. Some were cracked or damaged in transit, and the
cracks were cleverly concealed by waxy veneers.
</P>
<P>
   To identify a genuine article that hadn't been cosmetically
repaired, reputable marketers would use the words ``sin cerussa. It
was a guarantee of value, of authenticity. Sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   There's a parallel in politics, or ought to be. That's what Bill
Safire and Bill Thompson are saying, I think. The danger of modern
political practice is its nauseating emphasis upon image at the
expense of substance.
</P>
<P>
   The public deserves something better from us who seek to serve.
The least that people deserve is ourselves, our real selves _ our
unadorned, unembellished, honest-to-God selves.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
