<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDAL10-COX     08-09 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDAL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AWARD TO CARTERS IS NATION'S HIGHEST CIVILIAN HONOR
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Presidential Medal of Freedom, presented Monday
by President Clinton to former President Jimmy Carter and his wife,
Rosalynn, is the nation's highest civilian honor.
</P>
<P>
   Established by President Truman in 1945 to recognize outstanding
wartime service, the medal was reintroduced as an annual honor for
distinguished civilian service during peacetime by President
Kennedy in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy changed the award's name from ``Medal of Freedom'' to
``Presidential Medal of Freedom'' and announced it would honor
those who have made ``especially meritorious'' contributions to
national security, world peace, or cultural, public or private
endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   The medal, redesigned with the advice of Kennedy and his wife,
Jacqueline, is a white star with gold eagles and 13 silver stars on
a blue field.
</P>
<P>
   In a White House ceremony Thursday, Clinton will present the
medal to eight additional honorees: former Treasury Secretary Lloyd
M. Bentsen, World Jewish Congress President Edgar M. Bronfman Sr.,
labor activist Evy Dubrow, social worker Sister M. Isolina Ferr,
former President Gerald R. Ford, civil rights attorney Oliver White
Hill, diplomat and negotiator Max Kampelman, and environmentalist
Edgar Wayburn.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has awarded more than 70 of the medals since he took
office in 1993. Previous recipients include former Supreme Court
justice Thurgood Marshall, civil rights pioneer Rosa Parks, gun
control advocate Jim Brady and former German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl. Nine sports figures have received the award, including Jesse
Owens, Joe DiMaggio and Arthur Ashe.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential medal is distinct from the Congressional Gold
Medal, the highest award that Congress can bestow.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
