friends to decide which of the three to use on television. ``I want
you to listen carefully to these,'' he asked, ``and tell me in
which of the three you think I seem the most sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   He was surprised when I said, ``The way to seem sincere is to be
sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, that's about all Harry Truman had going for him. But it
was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we need to re-examine that word. ``Sincere.'' It stems
from two Latin words, meaning literally ``without wax.'' Roman
merchants had begun importing artifacts and ceramics goods from the
Greek islands. Some were cracked or damaged in transit, and the
cracks were cleverly concealed by waxy veneers.
</P>
<P>
   To identify a genuine article that hadn't been cosmetically
repaired, reputable marketers would use the words ``sin cerussa. It
was a guarantee of value, of authenticity. Sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   There's a parallel in politics, or ought to be. That's what Bill
Safire and Bill Thompson are saying, I think. The danger of modern
political practice is its nauseating emphasis upon image at the
expense of substance.
</P>
<P>
   The public deserves something better from us who seek to serve.
The least that people deserve is ourselves, our real selves _ our
unadorned, unembellished, honest-to-God selves.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
