<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLABCHURCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH REACHES OUT TO CHILDREN ON THE FRINGE OF HOMELESSNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAIME JORDAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It took the tears of a 6-year-old to open
Vesta Wilson's heart to the importance of her mission.
</P>
<P>
   It was three years ago when she gave Larry, now 9, a bag of
miniature race cars for his birthday. She hugged him and said,
``Larry, I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   He began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever told me they loved me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry is typical of the nearly 40 children Wilson sees each week
at Sunday School at Church on the Slab, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Gray, of Daily Bread Ministries, founded Church on the Slab
in 1989 to feed the homeless while providing a spiritual outlet.
The ``slab'' is a concrete foundation just off Interstate 35W in a
poor area of Fort Worth. Every Sunday morning, the drifters gather
under a huge tent to eat a hot meal and to sway to keyboard music,
clap their hands and fall to the floor in the throes of spiritual
passion.
</P>
<P>
   And every Sunday morning, the children gather at a donated
building next to the slab for their spiritual nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the children live with their grandparents, Wilson said.
Their mothers are dead, in jail or living on the streets. Few
children know their fathers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really difficult for children in those situations to ever
be able to do anything but be back on the streets,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   So she comes back week after week, determined to alter their
fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's the children and being able to make a difference
in those children so they don't end up like these men who are out
there, give them some kind of hope that Jesus can make a difference
in their lives,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the school, the children gather around two tables. On a
recent Sunday, the children read about creation and played a game
to reinforce the lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of the group, 6-year-old Lulu, sat curled on a
teacher's lap, her finger in her mouth, her shoes off, exposing
dusty feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the baby of the kids,'' said Sunday-school teacher
Brenda Rutledge of Euless, a Fort Worth suburb. ``They always pick
on her, and I won't let them pick on her.''
</P>
<P>
   Children who attend the Sunday school get more than lessons.
Past outings have included camping trips and Texas Rangers baseball
games.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best gift, however, is the hugs.
</P>
<P>
   As the morning progressed, the teachers ended virtually every
statement with some gesture of love, a hug or words.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's husband, Jim, said he can't believe the change in some
of the children.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it's hard to break a cycle of violence and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three are getting a bit older, and I think they're
gang-banging; in fact I know they are,'' Jim Wilson said. Still,
many occasionally stop by to say, ``Hi, Miss Vesta,'' and get a
hug.
</P>
<P>
   It's often hard to tell from the faces of the children the
circumstances to which they return after every service. Tommy,
known to the group as Spud, laughed so hard at his own jokes that
he nearly fell out of his chair on several occasions. And when it
came time to pass the mission plate, the children contributed
almost $3.
</P>
<P>
   But other times, there are obvious signs of what they've
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Like 7-year-old Shane, who was cut from his dying mother's womb.
Shane's mother, clad in a brother's hat and coat, was mistaken for
someone's enemy as she was crossing a street to a store and was
struck repeatedly by a car. Shane survived but weighed only 1 pound
at birth. Today, his tiny frame, about the size of a typical
4-year-old, carries the burden of his prematurity. But his grin
spreads wide across his face, balancing his eyes, which continually
creep inward.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the midst of the despair, the teachers continue to come
back. Many times, they're the only constant in the lives of the
children, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go off to be missionaries,'' Rutledge said. ``This is
our mission field. The kids need us here. You're on the front lines
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said there is one factor separating the children from the
pocket of poverty that surrounds them. It's God's love, she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what she tries to show Shane and Lulu and the others who
come regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like they have a choice, but they do,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
