<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACKINGLOSTKIDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GPS TRACKING SYSTEM FINDS MISSING KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How far would you go to protect your child? Bill Brown and Dan
Booker, two South Carolina businessmen and grandparents, are
betting you'd go pretty far. Far enough, maybe, to track your child
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Booker's company, Grandparents Inc., has developed a
tracking system that uses global positioning satellite (GPS)
technology to find missing children anywhere in the United States.
The device weighs less than 2 pounds, is about the size of a
cellular phone and can be carried in a backpack or even hidden in
clothing. If a child carrying the device is kidnapped or
disappears, parents can contact local police, who in turn call the
South Carolina tracking center. The child can then be located in
about 30 seconds, the developers say.
</P>
<P>
   The Protect Me Toys device uses the same technology as the
LoJack tracking system installed in some vehicles. Police can
locate stolen cars using a satellite: Call the automobile, and you
know where it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where our system is different,'' Brown said, ``is you don't
have to use a 40-pound battery.''
</P>
<P>
   When the call is made to the device, a map pops up on the
tracker's computer screen. A panda bear icon shows where the device
and the child are, including the street they are on and the exact
speed and direction they are moving.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Booker aren't selling the devices at retail locations.
Instead, they're hoping corporate sponsors will buy the devices and
distribute them to kids for free. The partners want to make sure
it's not ``just a rich man's toy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think somebody's income should determine whether or
not they can protect their child,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   But the high cost of high tech (the price may eventually be
shaved down from about $500 to $200 each, with a monthly service
fee) means this sort of mass distribution may be slow going. To
distribute the gadgets they have now, the men go through district
attorneys and law enforcement officials _ people who know about the
kids in their area who are at the highest risk for kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Booker and Brown say they hope the portable units can be made
smaller as technology progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on a new system right now that we hope to get
small enough to put in the top of a pair of tennis shoes,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown points out that the system he and Booker
developed works through the FBI and police departments _ ``We don't
track these things for the parents'' _ the tracking device has
potential for widespread use beyond kidnapping cases. Some experts,
concerned with privacy issues, say this could be a problem if
access to such a system moved beyond authorities to ordinary
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly seems that for its intended use, this is
certainly a good thing,'' said Frank Colosi, a Fort Worth attorney
and American Civil Liberties Union representative. ``But the
problem with any technology is it can be used on any of us when we
don't even know about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody deserves some privacy, and the older you get, the
more privacy you're entitled to,'' he said. ``There's a question
(with children who are) 15 or 16 if this is an intrusion on their
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Colosi also points out that the widespread use of personal
tracking systems could trigger a trust-no-one mentality that could
lead toward a ``fortressed society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People will start thinking there is no safety anywhere for
anybody,'' he said. ``We end up living in a society that I'm not
sure anybody really wants to live in.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, though, this sort of debate is academic, and the
Protect Me Toys tracker is only intended to protect at-risk
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing anybody can do that's 100 percent,'' Brown
said. ``This at least gives you an opportunity _ a big opportunity
_ to save a child's life.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
