<SLUG> BC-FEARLESSFLIER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH? HA! I'M MORE WORRIED ABOUT THAT AIRLINE FOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am not exactly a frequent flier. I've flown, at most, maybe
300 times in the past 15 years. That's just enough that I tune out
when they start giving the pre-flight instructions, although not
enough that I'd have any idea what to do if the plane actually
started going down.
</P>
<P>
   That's because I don't believe my plane will ever crash. And
that's because I am part of the silent majority; I am a fearless
flier.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics do sound ominous. It's estimated that one in four
Americans is at least somewhat afraid of flying. An estimated one
in 10 won't get on a plane. But look at it the other way; that
means far more than half of the public thinks flying is not much
different than catching a bus.
</P>
<P>
   Like me. I think it's far more dangerous to eat the in-flight
meal than to go somewhere on a plane. It's not that I am an
unusually brave soul; I'm scared of plenty of things, including
spiders, the dark, undercooked pork, Wal-Mart, and, inexplicably,
heights.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there have been only two times on aircraft when I've been
even a little bit afraid: once on a small commuter jet going to
Aspen that seemed certain to slam into one of the Rocky Mountains;
and once on a puddle-jumper prop plane going from one island in the
Caymans to another (we kept circling and circling, waiting for
somebody to shoo some cows off the grass runway).
</P>
<P>
   Both situations were over in a few minutes, before an air-sick
bag was called for. The flight attendant on the Aspen flight
quickly assisted the one passenger who took ill from the
topsy-turvy turns. And the cows-on-the-landing-strip story made for
a good laugh down the road. Neither would prevent me, or most
people, probably, from getting into the air again.
</P>
<P>
   See, when you look at the alternatives, planes look pretty good.
Air travel is cheap (relatively speaking), fast and, if it's not
exactly comfortable, it's usually bearable, even in coach. Until
the United States gets its act together on rail service, there's no
better way to get from one side of the country to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Safety just isn't a big concern for many of us, which makes
sense if you look at it from a practical standpoint. The airlines
make money (and, at last count, a lot of it) by getting people from
one place to another safely, so it's in their best interest to keep
those things in the air. Forget that truism about there being no
such thing as bad publicity _ a jet going down and killing 110
people or so is very bad publicity indeed. Just ask ValuJet.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the women and men who fly commercial jets have had
years of experience and training. (Which is not something you can
say about a lot of the people with whom you're sharing the
interstate.) And, because they're up there with you, they have a
vested interest in getting back on the ground safely.
</P>
<P>
   But practical matters aren't the only aspect. For those of us
who love to travel, who live for exploring new cities and stumbling
across unfamiliar territory, air travel is at worst a necessary
evil, at best a fun part of the journey.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for jets, few of us would ever have the chance to
see Europe or Africa or Asia, to see the Louvre or the Great
Pyramids or the Great Wall. In fact, many of us would rarely get
home for Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   And to experience those things, I'm willing to assume a little
bit of risk.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
