<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-MORA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM MORA'S YOUTHFUL LOOK BELIES HIS THICK SKIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Don't tell Jim Mora about pressure. The man
has known nothing else since he walked into the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Mora about pressure and you'll hear stories about his
coaching in New Orleans earlier this decade, working as a secondary
coach under his father Jim, the team's head coach from 1986-95.
Back then, the young Jim wasn't a popular man at times.
</P>
<P>
   He was daddy's boy. An easy target for fans upset with a
struggling team, one who heard comments that could make even Howard
Stern cringe. But Mora was something else as well. He was learning
lessons that would only help him cope with the title and
responsibility he now holds, as defensive coordinator of the San
Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Mora heard his share of criticism last season when the 49ers'
secondary, the unit he coached, struggled. Now he could be in for
even worse if his defense can't improve on last year's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I learned from New Orleans is that you can't let
that kind of stuff bother you,'' said Mora, who coached in New
Orleans from 1992-96. ``I heard cheers like, `Keep the coach and
fire the son.' You have to understand that people like to express
their opinions but if you're doing the best you can do, you can't
worry about it. The thing I've always been able to do is not let
this job define who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   One glimpse at Jim Mora and the first thing you wonder is if he
swiped the secret formula that keeps Dick Clark from aging.
</P>
<P>
   His birth date tells you he turns 38 in November. His impish
face and abundance of skittish energy suggest otherwise. This is a
coach who likely will be carded in bars well into his 50s.
</P>
<P>
   That youthful appearance also makes you wonder something else:
Is one of the league's youngest coordinators ready to take over a
defense that was the weak link of last year's team? His background
indicates that he is.
</P>
<P>
   Mora broke into coaching as a 23-year-old secondary coach with
the San Diego Chargers in 1985. He has tutored under established
coaches like Gunther Cunningham and Vic Fangio, not to mention the
insight he gained from his father. Steve Mariucci, the head coach
of the 49ers, didn't have to know much else before choosing Mora as
the successor to John Marshall, who left to join George Seifert's
staff in Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``A personal philosophy of mine is to promote from within,''
Mariucci said. ``I wanted someone who could blend in quickly, and I
didn't want to change our scheme. We had a good young coach who was
ready to do the job. He was anxious and he also had opportunities
elsewhere. So we figured he was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Darnell Walker said Mora ``has a lot of knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about how old he is. He's been in football so long and
he's been through the ups and downs. A lot of coaches have
different philosophies, but what a defense ultimately does is take
on the coordinator's personality. He's so hyped and energetic that
you know it will be fun playing for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The task that lies ahead of Mora isn't an easy one. The 49ers'
defense fell apart last season. The secondary was either
ineffective or injured, the linebackers inconsistent and the
defensive line so thin by season's end that the team called Charles
Haley out of retirement. The end result was a unit that surrendered
333.9 yards per game and ranked 23rd in the league in total
defense.
</P>
<P>
   There are still questions. Cornerback remains an area of
uncertainty and the defensive line won't be solid until defensive
tackle Bryant Young returns from the broken right leg he suffered
last season. Those factors mean that Mora starts the year under the
microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make excuses for last year, but we dealt with
a lot of factors,'' Mora said. ``We lost some key personalities
from the year before, guys like Dana Stubblefield and Kevin Greene.
We had injuries at cornerback and we were breaking in a new
linebacker in Winfred Tubbs. We got off to a slow start. But we
expect things to be better because we have a more consistent
unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora's philosophy has been to simplify the defensive package. He
wants his players attacking, flying around the field, creating
chaos and avoiding as many mental mistakes as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of free agency, with personnel changing so much,
Mora doesn't consider it wise to keep players thinking about too
many things. So far, the response has been positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing a great job,'' said linebacker Ken Norton Jr. ``We
see that he wants to be aggressive and come after people. He
doesn't want to sit back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll also be interested to see how things play out. Right
now, everything looks good in practice. We'll see how he handles
things when it's third-and-2 and he has to make a tough call. We
all know he can do it, but that test is still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora understands what he'll have to do to prove himself. But
when you have his age and his family name, you start gearing up for
such moments long before they arrive. Even as the new coordinator,
he has seen enough to not let this job beat him down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
