A0817 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARSPANGLED-JIMI-TEX     08-09 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARSPANGLED-JIMI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDRIX MADE IT AN ANTHEM OF ANGUISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early on the morning of Aug. 18, 1969, Jimi Hendrix was Artie
Kornfeld's alarm clock.
</P>
<P>
   Kornfeld was one of Woodstock's four producers, and the night
before, he'd been given Thorazine to help him sleep and to get over
being dosed by psilocybin, a powerful hallucinogen. Lying in a
backstage trailer, he was startled into consciousness by Hendrix's
guitar picking out the melody to ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' and
then exploding into howls of pure noise, feedback, almost-human
shrieks of agony.
</P>
<P>
   He ran to the stage and stood transfixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he added the bombs and everything, it represented all
those years we had bomb tests and we had to hide under our desks at
school, and the constant fear of being drafted, and every week
hearing another kid I went to school with had been killed in
Vietnam,'' Kornfeld says. ``It was the whole story of the
frustration of a generation, but it left you with hope that the
flag was still waving.''
</P>
<P>
   The song symbolizes the entire event and the mind-set of young
people during that tumultuous summer of moonwalks and Charles
Manson, and it stands as a milestone of Hendrix's career, certainly
one of his most famous concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Mick Jagger has called it the most politically important rock
statement of the '60s, and former Living Colour guitarist Vernon
Reid compared it with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s ``I Have a
Dream'' speech. Last month, ``Live at Woodstock,'' a two-CD set
featuring nearly the entire two-hours-plus performance (including
several previously unreleased songs) was released by MCA Records. A
remastered version of the 1970 film ``Jimi Hendrix: Live at
Woodstock'' was released the same day, along with an expanded DVD
version of the recent ``Band of Gypsies'' documentary.
</P>
<P>
   It's a measure of just how far removed young rockers are from
their famous forefathers that Limp Bizkit frontman Fred Durst
recently opined in ``USA Today'' that Hendrix's ``Banner'' doesn't
sound ``that good. It was just a classic moment, a memory. I wasn't
there. I don't get it. I'll never get it.''
</P>
<P>
   But millions have. Hendrix's version of the national anthem has
attained near-mythic proportions in the 30 years since it was
recorded. If people think of one song from Woodstock, they probably
think of ``Banner,'' the way Hendrix turned it into a turbulent,
unholy war cry of anguish, exploding bombs and screams, how he made
the song sound like Vietnam, the riots in the wake of King's death,
the constant clashes between anti-war protesters and the police.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, though, that Hendrix's ``Banner'' _ and his entire
Woodstock set _ was a contradiction: While it was his most overt
political statement and one of his most well-remembered shows, it
was not even close to being his best performance.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it even seen by most of the people who attended the
show. Due to long delays, torrential rain and disorganization,
Hendrix didn't hit the stage until after the three-day festival was
technically over.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one-tenth of the crowd of 400,000 that had filled Max
Yasgur's dairy farm Friday, Saturday and Sunday was left: Hendrix
faced a motley crew of sleepy, hungry stragglers and a huge, muddy
field strewn with tons of trash.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hendrix's career was in turmoil: He'd broken up the
three-man Jimi Hendrix Experience two months earlier after a
performance at a pop festival in Denver. He'd then spent weeks in
upstate New York, jamming with friends and trying to fashion a new
sound and a new band _ dubbed Gypsy Sun and Rainbows _ that mixed
the hard, blues-based psychedelic rock of the past with Latin
percussion and funk.
</P>
<P>
   It was an underrehearsed band that hit the stage that Monday
morning, and the largest one Hendrix had ever fronted. In addition
to old hand Mitch Mitchell on drums, Hendrix also had enlisted
bassist Billy Cox, percussionists Juma Sultan and Jerry Velez and,
for the first time, a rhythm guitarist (Larry Lee). And the band's
sloppiness and lack of cohesion is often plainly evident.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hendrix was torn as to just how political he would
be. According to Brad Tolinski, editor in chief of ``Guitar
World,'' the Black Panthers had been pressuring Hendrix to become
more vocally political and to endorse their organization.
</P>
<P>
   But Hendrix had resisted; he was obviously in favor of peace and
love and good feelings, but he had made very few political
statements in the past. By playing ``Banner,'' Tolinski says,
Hendrix was ``commenting on society the best way he knew. You
didn't need to have him say anything about it. It's all there. It
was the way he could say what he wanted to say the most
comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix produced the dazzling variety of sounds through a
Uni-Vibe, a Fuzz Face distortion pedal, a wah-wah pedal and
feedback from his amplifiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why his whole thing can't be duplicated,'' says
Tolinski. ``It was all about the interaction of the guitar and the
electronics and the spontaneous reaction to the sound the amps were
making. It's like a Jackson Pollock action painting _ reacting to
the way the paint was hitting the canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a half-hour after he played ``Banner,'' Hendrix
concluded his 16-song set with his 1967 hit ``Hey Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   He would jettison most of the band after just two more shows and
go back out again as a trio with Cox and drummer Buddy Miles. His
New Year's Eve show at New York's Fillmore East would be recorded
and released as ``Band of Gypsies.'' On July 4, 1970, he played the
second Atlanta Pop Festival with Jethro Tull, Rare Earth and
others.
</P>
<P>
   And little less than two months later, after a troubled European
tour and a final show on an island in Germany, Hendrix would
overdose on barbiturates and choke to death in London.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing years, his legend would continue to grow as
literally dozens of releases (many of them studio jams never meant
for the public) would flood the stores.
</P>
<P>
   As rock fans young and old looked back to the late '60s for
inspiration, his abilities would attain a near-mythic status, his
songs seen as the benchmark for guitar playing. And ``Banner'' is
forever part and parcel of that legacy, the moment when he spoke
for his generation through his six strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimi was so far ahead of the curve,'' says Tolinski. ``Jeff
Beck told me, `Forget it. When Jimi came along he made the rest of
'em sound like schoolteachers.' And nobody else has ever really
come close.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
