<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CCE-COX     08-09 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CCE on the comeback trail
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Murphy's Law _ anything that can go wrong will go
wrong _ paints too rosy a picture of life.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Henry Schimberg believes in the wake of the European
health scare that engulfed his Atlanta-based bottling company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we were working under Schimberg's Law,'' said
the 66-year-old president and chief executive of Coca-Cola
Enterprises. ``Schimberg's Law is very simple: Murphy was an
optimist.''
</P>
<P>
   Schimberg, who has been in the soft drink business for more than
40 years, said the June recall of all Coca-Cola products in Belgium
ranked as the worst professional experience of his life. Two
CCE-owned plants _ one in Belgium and the other in France _
produced the beverages that caused illnesses to nearly 250
Belgians.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one is good and 10 is as bad as it gets, this is a 9.85,''
Schimberg said last week in his first in-depth interview about the
crisis. ``I don't know how you can get much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   He then invoked a 19th-century quotation from Friedrich
Nietzsche: ``What doesn't kill us makes us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire Coca-Cola system is counting on that principle as it
attempts to recover from the largest and most damaging recall in
its 113-year history.
</P>
<P>
   CCE withdrew some 17 million beverage cases from the Belgian
market at a cost of $103 million. That figure doesn't include the
tens of millions of dollars in lost sales still piling up for CCE
and Coca-Cola Co., which owns 40 percent of the world's largest
soft drink bottler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have one overriding issue, and that is to regain
the confidence of the customers in every country affected by the
recall,'' Schimberg said. In addition to Belgium and France,
several other European nations imposed full or partial bans on Coke
products for about two weeks in June.
</P>
<P>
   To recover from this debacle, CCE and Coca-Cola Co. have teamed
up on a multipronged marketing and advertising strategy that
appears to be working. The goal is to contain the reverberating
effects on Coke's image and sales to the second and third quarters,
preventing any spillover beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving in the right direction at a fast speed,'' said
Philippe Lenfant, CCE's general manager in Belgium. He has been on
the front line of the crisis since June 8, when the first
teen-agers reported getting sick.
</P>
<P>
   Lenfant added, however, that there has not been a full recovery
yet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a July survey of European consumers by the Goldman
Sachs investment firm found a ``meaningful'' 14 percent with a
deteriorating overall perception of Coca-Cola products. In
addition, 81 percent of Coca-Cola consumers indicated they will
definitely continue to buy company products in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In both Belgium and France, CCE and Coca-Cola Co. are tracking
consumer sentiment on a daily basis. While officials would not
reveal the specific results, they said there was significant
improvement in July.
</P>
<P>
   But accurate sales figures are still hard to come by, especially
in Belgium, because executives don't really know how to separate
three different types of purchases:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales related to the restocking of retail shelves and consumer
refrigerators after the recall;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales driven by the super-promotional efforts now under way;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales that would have been registered regardless of the other
two variables.
</P>
<P>
   Still, June's pessimism has been washed away by recent events.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more fun today than six weeks ago,'' Lenfant said
during a lengthy interview with several CCE officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the recovery to be very quick,'' added Dominique
Reiniche, CCE's general manager in France.
</P>
<P>
   Executives attribute the partial turnaround to the considerable
brand strength Coca-Cola had before the health scare, as well as to
the intensity with which it has been trying to repair the
situation. An enormous amount of time, energy and money is being
spent trying to preserve Coke's leading market share _ 64 percent
in Belgium and 55 percent in France, according to Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proof will be how they manage to reassure people,'' said
Goldman Sachs analyst Marc Cohen. ``It must be executed well. I
think they're doing OK so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, when the product bans were lifted in late June, the
companies concentrated their advertising and marketing efforts on
apologizing to consumers, thanking them for their previous loyalty
and telling them that Coca-Cola will work hard to regain it.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola and CCE also tried to explain the limited nature of
the quality and health problems. They pointed out that the causes
of the nausea and vomiting _ defective carbon dioxide and a
fungicide that got on the outside of some cans _ did not pose a
health threat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the apology and education phases behind them, the
companies are aggressively marketing their brands in more
traditional ways, emphasizing the standard summertime themes of
pleasure and refreshment under the general umbrella, ``Your
Coca-Cola is back.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the system is involved in many more
promotions than it would have been had the health scare not
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in Belgium, Coke and CCE have organized
product-sampling events outside thousands of stores every weekend
over the past several weeks. The last such events end today,
indicating that the companies feel the need to reassure consumers
is waning.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the companies are trucking in sand to stage beach parties,
and they're sponsoring about 100 other events at which Coke is
given away.
</P>
<P>
   Going forward, the companies are planning to mount special
programs to bolster their image at schools, where many of the
sicknesses occurred, as well as in small shops and pubs that often
get overlooked in favor of the larger supermarkets. But the system
is no longer in a position to take anything for granted as it tries
to regain some retail shelf space lost to competitors during the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts come after trying to get a free bottle of Coke
into every Belgian household. What's more, 2,500 employee
``ambassadors'' were each dispatched with a free case of Coke to
share with friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In France, meanwhile, 5 million leaflets were distributed in
stores to complement a substantial media advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The other key part of the comeback, especially for CCE, which
bottles and distributes the beverages, is on the production side.
</P>
<P>
   The company's manufacturing system is now meeting about 90
percent of existing demand because it had to go into overdrive to
restock the pipeline with beverages following the recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've asked our employees to work like hell,'' Lenfant said.
``We were forced to take back 17 million cases in a couple of
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Since getting the green light to resume production, CCE's plants
have been operating around the clock, seven days a week. In normal
times, they only would be operating one or two shifts a day, five
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   It will take until the third week of August to get all of Coke's
beverages in all of their different sizes and containers back on
the shelves in the appropriate numbers, Lenfant said.
</P>
<P>
   While employees have been working extremely hard, CCE executives
said, they haven't grown weary yet because of the positive momentum
that appears to be building.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get Coca-Cola in the blood,'' said Norman Findley,
president of CCE's European operations. ``Those first weeks were
very difficult, the most difficult in my 23 years in the Coke
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, with a turnaround under way, Findley subscribes
less to Murphy's and Schimberg's laws and more to a paraphrase of
Charles Dickens: ``This was the worst of times and the best of
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
