<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEE-QANDA-COX     08-09 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEE-QANDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schimberg: Price increases fixed 'deteriorating situation'
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a recent interview, Coca-Cola Enterprises President and
Chief Executive Henry Schimberg fielded questions on a variety of
financial and management topics:
</P>
<P>
   Financial issues
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do you think your stock price, which has been
depressed, is headed over the next year? (It closed Friday at
$27.31 1/4, down 23 percent for the year.)
</P>
<P>
   A: The analysts are predicting anything from a low over the next
12 months of $36 to a high of $50, with a median in the low- to
mid-$40s. I see no reason that we shouldn't achieve those levels,
based on our performance.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The median, the high or the low?
</P>
<P>
   A: At a minimum, the median.
</P>
<P>
   QWhat can you say about second-half earnings?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm comfortable with the analysts' projections about our
earnings over the balance of this year. (Analysts estimate the
company will earn about 15 cents a share in the last half of the
year, compared with 12 cents for the same period last year,
according to First Call.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: CCE has raised U.S. supermarket prices for its beverages
considerably _ about 5.5 percent in the second quarter, compared
with a year ago. But the move has cut into case sales. Why did you
do it?
</P>
<P>
   A: We had a situation in the United States where we were selling
product at wholesale and retail at lower levels than they were
selling a decade ago, which doesn't make much economic sense. We
were inhibiting bottler profitability and significantly diminishing
retailer profitability. As leaders in the marketplace, we had, from
my standpoint, no choice but to take action to correct a
deteriorating situation. ... We had to make the move to build
shareholder value over the long term, and we understood it would
impact sales and market share in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you increase supermarket prices further in the near
future?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think what we're looking for now is to solidify what we've
accomplished in terms of pricing, as opposed to moving pricing even
more.
</P>
<P>
   Q: CCE made $3.7 billion in acquisitions in 1997 and $1.2
billion last year. But so far this year you have been less active
on the acquisition front. Are you taking a breather?
</P>
<P>
   A: Certainly the level of acquisitions made last year requires
some digestion on our part. Basically, our acquisition strategy at
this point is really opportunistically generated. As people come to
us with a desire to sell, and we can at nondilutive levels, we will
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Management issues
</P>
<P>
   Q: You implemented a decentralized management structure after
coming to CCE in 1991, which many analysts credit with turning
around the company. Please explain it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Local markets ought to be determinants of our action ...
within the context of a series of policies and goals that are
centrally prescribed. So a decentralized operating environment is
not an anarchistic one. In fact, in order to really be successful,
it requires a greater level of discipline than a centralized one.
... Not only is the execution local, but local people have to be
held accountable for that execution. You cannot have that level of
accountability if you try to over-centralize the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did the decentralization help you during the European
health crisis?
</P>
<P>
   A: Local people were at the heart of the negotiations with
regulators over there. It validates the whole concept of local
marketing strategies. The people who worked at CCE interfacing with
these regulatory agencies are nationals. They understand the
customs and mores of the countries where they operate. I think that
helped us significantly in conducting a more effective dialogue
with the agencies and ministers than would have been the case had
we not had this grass-roots infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you retire in April as planned?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Who will succeed you?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is a committee of the board that is focused on
succession. Fortunately, for us, we have a lot of very competent
and viable internal candidates. (CCE recently named two principal
operating officers, Norman Findley and John Alm, who are considered
front-runners to succeed Schimberg by some analysts.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the company looking at outside candidates as well?
</P>
<P>
   A: CCE is not looking outside the company.
</P>
<P>
   Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
