<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ECLIPSE-0810-C     08-09 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ECLIPSE-0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVEN PARTIAL ECLIPSE PUTS MIDEAST ON EDGE
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ Even on a normal day, people in the
Middle East are tense and sensitive to symbolism, so it's no wonder
an eclipse sets them on edge.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Bible tells us there was a solar eclipse the day
Jesus Christ died in Jerusalem: ``Darkness came over the whole
earth,'' states Luke 23:44.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Middle East, which will be brushed by the path of the
eclipse Wednesday, people have been blitzed by cautionary
advertising campaigns and officials are nervously making
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan, Syria and the areas under the Palestinian Authority,
Wednesday has been declared a national holiday in order to avoid
exposing workers to the temptation of looking skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have four children. I have to take care,'' said David
Mansour, who plans to close his souvenir shop on Bethlehem's Manger
Square to spend Wednesday inside with his family.
</P>
<P>
   He said some believe the eclipse could cause earthquakes, and a
religious committee warned people to wear white clothes that
reflect the sun's rays.
</P>
<P>
   Most Palestinians consider the eclipse nothing more than a minor
threat to eye safety. But, special eclipse-related prayers, calling
on God's mercy and protection, are planned in many mosques from
about noon until about 4 p.m. (local time) Wednesday. The eclipse
peaks here at 2:41 p.m. (local time) with 80 percent coverage of
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Authority Minister of Health Riad Zanoon Sunday
declared a ``state of emergency'' in local health facilities and
warned people not to use use the day off for trips to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tony Morgan, an ophthalmologist at Jerusalem's St. John's
Hospital for the Eyes, said he backed the warnings to stay inside
for families with children who might get curious and gaze at the
phenomenon. He noted, though, that the rays of an eclipse are no
stronger than the sun's normal rays.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis, meanwhile, peppered the approach of the solar event --
the last full eclipse of the millennium -- with their usual dash of
politics. Many are headed to the Golan Heights, land captured from
Syria in 1967, thought to be a prime viewing spot because of its
northern location and high altitude.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wing Likud Party is holding an eclipse rally there,
using the occasion to kick off a campaign against the proposed
return of the land to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Farther off in Iran, which has more than 60 cities in the direct
line of the eclipse's so-called Path of Totality, residents are
looking forward to a commercial boom.
</P>
<P>
   European tourists are flocking to the tourism-hungry country.
Newspapers noted that the visitors even include a team of
astronomers from the United States, often maligned as the home of
``World Arrogance'' by Iranian politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
