<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-09 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES AND FLIERS DESERVE RESPECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Syd Kearney, my colleague, relates a recent experience with a
flight from New Orleans to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers boarding the aircraft were in a festive mood _
Imagine that. In New Orleans? _ but one woman's demeanor, to put it
kindly, extended beyond accepted behavior.
</P>
<P>
   When a flight attendant, then the pilot, threatened to remove
her prior to departure, the passenger finally took her seat. But
she created more commotion en route, then ignored pleas to remain
seated as the jet taxied to the gate upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe,'' the harried flight attendant sighed as
Kearney debarked, ``that these people are demanding a passenger
rights bill?''
</P>
<P>
   At least this passenger didn't try to kick or strangle anybody,
the plight of too many flight attendants recently.
</P>
<P>
   But the episode underscores the growing tension in the
not-so-friendly skies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOSTILE ENVIRONMENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, ``air rage'' has escalated at an alarming _ and
dangerous _ rate. One employee for Houston-based Continental
Airlines was critically injured during a scuffle with a passenger
at Newark, N.J., several days ago, prompting airline president
Gordon Bethune to call for legislation banning violent fliers from
U.S. airlines. Six people, including a Delta flight attendant, were
injured during an in-flight altercation. In another incident, a
passenger tried, without success, to open an exit door midair.
</P>
<P>
   There is no excuse for such abusive behavior. And no reason for
airlines to tolerate it. Bans. Fines. Jail. Whatever it takes,
innocent passengers _ the vast majority _ need protection along
with airline employees.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, travelers have been clamoring all year for
better treatment from airlines. After several legislators
introduced passenger rights bills, the airlines vowed to address
concerns and make adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, these two issues _ air rage and passenger rights
_ may seem largely unrelated. Just because a flight is delayed and
we're provided misleading information about the reasons, we don't
have the right to punch out the gate agent. Just because we're
squeezed into a middle seat, idled on the tarmac for two hours and
fed only peanuts, we're not obliged to scream at a flight
attendant.
</P>
<P>
   We're still a nation of laws. And common decency.
</P>
<P>
   But the attendant on Kearney's flight was wrong to equate all
passengers with the actions of a small minority.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECURITY NEEDED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what do we do about air rage other than invoke stronger
punishment and hope it serves as a deterrent? Flight attendants are
trained in safety first, then in service; they aren't
law-enforcement personnel and shouldn't be charged with the
responsibility of maintaining order. Certainly, 911 calls don't
accomplish much at 37,000 feet. Airlines tell us they can't afford
to place uniformed police aboard every aircraft, at least not
without raising fares significantly. And I can imagine the outcry
from flight attendants _ already unduly victimized _ if even one
were replaced so that security officers were integrated as a
routine part of on-board crews.
</P>
<P>
   But think about it. How many other public forums this huge _
hundreds of thousands of travelers on airplanes worldwide every day
_ aren't protected by clearly recognizable authority figures? It's
sad that we must entertain the thought, but what price is a flight
attendant's safety? Or life? A passenger's security?
</P>
<P>
   What we can and must do is focus squarely on the root causes. My
theory is that much of the disturbing behavior _ not all of it;
some people, alas, are simply crazy _ mirrors our overall
fast-paced and angst-ridden society and is influenced by the
remarkable growth in popularity of air travel for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, the pages of this newspaper include reports of
violence in and around our city born of pressure or tension. Of
people feeling crowded and put upon. Of involvement with alcohol or
drugs _ or both. Of confusion and conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Is modern-day air travel any different?
</P>
<P>
   For a recent story, Washington Post reporter Don Phillips took
18 domestic flights in 21 days, and one significant finding was
experiencing seven ``delay'' points _ from a traffic jam en route
to the airport to long lines in the departure lounge _ prior to
takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, we're often frustrated even before boarding a
flight. Then, because airlines are determined to milk every drop of
potential passenger revenue _ and because we keep buying tickets in
record numbers _ we're jammed into seats as if we were cattle. With
so many airplanes needed to satisfy demand, we wait sometimes for
an hour to take off. Chances are, we face pressures at our
destination. If our flight is late or if weather is bad and the
ride bumpy, the tension multiplies. And some fliers resort to booze
or pills, or a combination, in a misguided attempt to calm nerves.
</P>
<P>
   In short _ and don't misunderstand, this does not justify rage _
many passengers aboard an airplane today are not in the best of
moods. They're not mad at the flight attendant; they're upset at
the system (a system whose faults sometimes are beyond the
airline's control).
</P>
<P>
   Neither are flight attendants and gate agents always bubbly with
enthusiasm, understandable in that they don't relish being cursed,
doused with liquor _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   We need to work together to find ways to make the overall air
travel experience _ from booking a reservation to easing delays to
claiming baggage _ less pressure-packed.
</P>
<P>
   I remember when people eagerly looked forward to flying as one
of life's truly special experiences. In practical terms, it was
also available to only a select few. Today, moving about the world
in a jetliner is affordable to more travelers than ever. It's
safer, too. But it's rarely special.
</P>
<P>
   This is simplistic, I know, and perhaps, given the horrible
massacres in schools and office buildings, it's a wasted wish: But
a little more mutual respect for each other _ airlines and
passengers _ couldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
