<HEADER>
A0826 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV15-NY     08-09 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY CHINESE ARE FORCED TO ARGUE IN ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We believe there is one nation and two countries,'' said Chen
Chien-jen, chief spokesman of the Republic of China on Taiwan,
speaking in English.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Faison, The New York Times' man in Beijing, asked him to
say that in Chinese. Chen was stumped. ``We are still looking for
the right words,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because in Chinese,  &UR; state &LR; ,  &UR; country &LR;  and  &UR; nation &LR;  are
expressed in the same word:  &UR; guojia &LR; , pronounced gwo-jah. But the
Chinese leaders on Taiwan, which Beijing considers a renegade
province of China, want to put a few degrees of separation between
the two political entities. How to do this without declaring
independence, which might start a war? ``So they use the English
words,'' writes Faison, ``even though Taiwan is a Chinese-speaking
country, or state, or nation _ or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Chinese language often uses pronunciation to express
different nuances of meaning, the English language has a glorious
range of synonymy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nation &LR; , from the Latin of the same name, stems from ``breed,
stock, race'' _ leading to the notion of ``a people.'' When we
speak of the Iroquois Nation, or the Nation of Islam, we mean the
culture, religion, race and/or language that binds people who may
be dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hates our sacred  &UR; nation &LR; ,'' says Shylock in Shakespeare's
``Merchant of Venice.'' (The Chinese word for this racial sense is
 &UR; minzu &LR; .) Although that early sense is still in use, in the last
two centuries the primary meaning of  &UR; nation &LR;  has shifted to ``an
independent political unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that later sense the same as a  &UR; country &LR; ? Yes. Its Latin root
is  &UR; contra &LR; , ``against,'' originally the land or region separate
from, or up against, other discrete areas. Though it has a second
sense of ``bucolic region'' as in ``I can't stand the beach; let's
go to the country,'' the primary meaning is ``an independent state;
native land.'' (U.S. presidents traditionally began their inaugural
addresses with ``My countrymen'' until it was desexed to ``Fellow
citizens.'')
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the old meaning of  &UR; nation &LR;  can be used to make a
contrast with the new meaning of  &UR; country &LR; , as in: ``The Kurds are
the largest  &UR; nation &LR;  in the world without a  &UR; country &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Note the use above of ``independent state.'' The use of the
modifier  &UR; independent &LR;  shows that  &UR; state &LR;  need not be wholly
separate from a  &UR; nation &LR; . The 50 American states are not sovereign,
no matter what they say in Texas and Hawaii (the only states that
were once sovereign nations).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; State &LR; , from the French  &UR; etat &LR; , ``class, ranking,'' is a unit
of government that may or may not be independent, which is why it
requires a qualifier. Palestinians, for example, rarely say they
want a state; they specify an independent, or separate, or ``our
own'' state.
</P>
<P>
   Now we can see what the spokesman for Taiwan was getting at when
he said ``one  &UR; nation &LR;  and two  &UR; countries &LR; .'' He meant the early
sense of  &UR; nation &LR;  _ in this case, ``the Chinese people'' _ with one
part of that people on Taiwan set up against,  &UR; contra &LR; , in a
country next to but apart from the mother country.
</P>
<P>
   Mainland China is not having any of this English linguistic hair
splitting. It insists on ``one China,'' a fiction of both sides
that U.S. policy gladly acknowledged in the Shanghai Communique of
1972, provided ultimate reunification would be peaceful. The point
here is that Chinese prefer their own language to gloss over
differences but turn to English to introduce degrees of difference.
Our language is as subtle as their minds.
</P>
<P>
   JAIL MAIL
</P>
<P>
   Though the spy Aldrich Ames has been falling behind in his
correspondence with this column, a new jailbird has taken his
place.
</P>
<P>
   From confinement in Eastlake, Mich., comes this whimsical poem
from the inmate Dr. Jack Kevorkian:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Whenever language gets frowzy, &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Irregular mavens quite tousey &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Use their NIT-picking pride &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; As ``insecticide'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To kill solecisms that are LOUSY. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The play on  &UR; nit &LR;  as an egg of a  &UR; louse &LR;  is obvious, but the
 &UR; frowzy-tousey &LR;  rhyme deserves scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Frowzy &LR;  _ meaning ``musty, smelly'' _ can be found in the poet
John Dryden's ``With  &UR; Frowzy &LR;  Pores, that taint the ambient Air.''
A more recent sense is ``dingy, slatternly, unkempt,'' and my
medical correspondent nicely applies this sense of sloppiness to
language criticized in this space.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tousey &LR;  is on a road less traveled. It, too, means
``disheveled, shaggy.''
</P>
<P>
   Most often seen in modern language as  &UR; tousled &LR; , ``rumpled,''
its origin is in the verb  &UR; touse &LR; , now rare, ``to push around,
handle roughly,'' as in Shakespeare's ``We'll  &UR; touze &LR;  you joynt by
joynt.'' It is the source of the noun  &UR; tussle &LR; , ``minor fight;
scuffle.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Kevorkian contribution on the vagaries of pronunciation
in English:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The ubiquitous diphthong o-u &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Is tough to pronounce for there's coup, &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Slough, dough, ought, rough &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; All, of course, joust enough &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To becloud a dour nous when &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; you're through. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In encouraging him thus, am I engaged in assisted linguicide?
</P>
<P>
   ACRONYMANIA
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, an organization that hands out free condoms to
prostitutes calls itself the Sex Worker Education and Advocacy
Taskforce (SWEAT).
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, an anti-drug outfit calls itself Children Requiring
a Caring Kommunity (CRACK).
</P>
<P>
   Serious business should eschew jazzy acronyms. Time for Citizens
Militant on Nomenclature (C'MON).
</P>
</TEXT>
