<HEADER>
A0827 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-09 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSIGHTLY WEBBING ACTUALLY HELPS TREES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the web that is starting to cover trunks and heavy
branches of oak trees, and what should we do if it is a hazard to
the trees' health? From the street it looks like a trickle of water
coming down the trunk. Closer inspection shows a fine, white,
smooth web.
</P>
<P>
   A: The same webbing is now on our crape myrtles, and it is the
protective covering of bark lice, beneficial insects that clean
bugs and fungi from our trees. I would let them do their work, and
eventually they will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an 8-foot angel's trumpet that bloomed two times in
the spring. The summer rains came _ every day for weeks _ and my
beautiful plant turned yellow and shed leaves. Some new leaves are
coming on, but there are no signs of blooming. Please tell me if
there is anything I can do.
</P>
<P>
   A: One cause of yellow, dropping leaves is too much moisture. It
could be that your soil usually drains adequately but could not
quite accommodate all the extra rain. You can improve the drainage,
if you feel it's necessary, by working in a little sand and
compost. Sometimes great fluctuations in moisture will cause
yellowing leaves.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if your tree is on the rebound. Give it time to put
on new foliage _ and the temperatures time to drop a little _ and
I'll bet your plant begins to flower again. My angel's trumpet
blooms are most abundant when it's not so hot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have several fig trees in my large, shady back yard. They
seem healthy but do not produce figs. Do they need fertilizer? Or
do they need more sun?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fig trees need abundant sun to be productive. A full or
nearly full day is ideal. These plants thrive in deep, organically
enriched soil. They need a lot of water, but good drainage is
necessary. And they benefit greatly from a heavy layer of mulch.
Given these conditions, there is usually no need to fertilize.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to inadequate sunlight, other causes of poor fruit
production are:
</P>
<P>
   Fig trees may show vigorous vegetative growth at the expense of
fruiting. So once a fast-growing plant slows, it should produce
figs.
</P>
<P>
   Stress can slow or prevent fruit production, so give figs plenty
of water and keep them heavily mulched. Lack of water causes fruit
to drop.
</P>
<P>
   Fig trees will produce best with little or no pruning.
</P>
<P>
   Fig trees usually need two to three years to mature and bear.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are spider webs in some of my trees. Some are large,
and some look like they are just beginning to grow. Please tell me
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   A: Tent caterpillars produce webs in trees in spring. Fall
webworms spin large webs later in the summer. The latter especially
like pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Tent caterpillars often produce webs where limbs join the trunk,
and the larvae crawl out and eat the leaves. Fall webworms produce
silky webs on the ends of the branches. The caterpillars eat the
leaves within the webs, and as the foliage disappears, the
caterpillars enlarge the web to encase more leaves. While an
infestation is unsightly, the trees usually rebound.
</P>
<P>
   We can forget the tent caterpillar for now, but we can treat
current webworm outbreaks. Spray and penetrate webbed foliage with
a pesticide. Bacillus thuringiensis, or Bt, is one effective
treatment. It is difficult to treat tall trees unless you have a
high-pressure sprayer.
</P>
<P>
   Bt and other pesticides will harm butterfly larvae, so aim
carefully or use extended limb trimmers to cut out the webs.
Destroy these right away.
</P>
<P>
   Fall webworms spend winter in dark-brown cocoons, often attached
to a trunk, or in organic matter on the ground. The moths emerge in
the spring or summer. They lay their eggs, and in approximately 10
days the larvae begin their work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have lost all the trees in my back yard to pine bark
beetles. What would be a good, fast-growing tree that would provide
shade in a short amount of time?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would visit a nursery that specializes in trees and study
the appearance, growth habits and sizes of various trees. Keep in
mind that fast-growing trees can have weaker wood that is more
subject to wind damage.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-growing Drummond red maple provides abundant shade and
will grow in partial shade or in full sun, in sand, clay or loam.
This native tree also is tolerant of poorly draining soil. As it
stretches toward a possible height of 90 feet, the smooth, gray
bark becomes fissured into ridges. Fast-growing trees may have
shorter lives than slower-growing trees _ the Drummond should live
about 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting trees native to Texas is the river
birch, which provides filtered shade. Often multitrunked, this
graceful tree has beautiful silvery-cinnamon bark that peels in
papery sheets.
</P>
<P>
   As its name implies, the river birch likes moisture and is a
good weapon against erosion. This tree is a natural for the poorly
draining soils of Houston, but I've seen it do well in a raised bed
and in drier conditions. The river birch is also a fast grower, in
sun or partial shade, and can reach a height from 30 to 90 feet.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many great trees, I would take the time to look at
several now while they have their foliage. These include the green
ash, `Drake' elm and the swamp chestnut oak, which provides fairly
good fall color.
</P>
<P>
   After selecting the one best for your needs, plant the tree this
fall. You can, of course, plant a container-grown tree most any
time, but it's so hot and dry now, transplanting stress will be
greater.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The volume of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
