<SLUG> BC-BBA-McGWIRE-As-HNS </SLUG>
  
 THERE WAS LIFE BEFORE THE CARDINALS FOR McGWIRE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN SHEA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Will anyone remember that Mark McGwire hit his
first 363 home runs with the Oakland A's?
</P>
<P>
   Or 49 homers as a rookie? Or 50 in his final full season in
Oakland? Or used to take batting practice in peace? Or played in
the A's organization for 13 1/2 years?
</P>
<P>
   We've seen so much of McGwire the last two seasons that it's
become difficult to picture him in any color but St. Louis red. No
doubt he'll be remembered more for what he did in a Cardinals
jersey than an A's jersey, even though he helped Oakland to three
World Series and hasn't gotten a sniff of the playoffs in St.
Louis, where fans seem to act as if they've had the guy all along
and watched every one of those 500 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   At least A's fans can rest assured that St. Louis _ even though
the talk is that McGwire would go into the Hall of Fame as a
Cardinal _ wouldn't have celebrated No. 500 without a huge assist
from Oakland, where it all started.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't something that just happened,'' said Jim Lefebvre,
one of McGwire's batting coaches with the A's. ``Seventy was
something new, but he has hit them in the 50s for a while. The only
thing that set him back was injuries. Now he's healthy and he's
showing what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis has cashed in on the blood and sweat sacrificed by
McGwire, who missed practically two full seasons in Oakland with
foot injuries and considered retiring because his professional and
personal lives were a mess.
</P>
<P>
   Now all is well as he ponders 600 and maybe 700. He's 35 and
still in his prime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've exceeded every expectation I've ever had for myself,''
McGwire said. ``I almost gave this game up. It's the ones who
overcome adversity who stay the strongest. And I give credit to my
mind. My mind is so strong in that box. I am so focused.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is one of 16 players in the 500 club, and no one got
there faster. He needed 5,487 at-bats, an average of one homer
every 11.23 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as home runs per at-bat, he's the all-time leader,''
Lefebvre said. ``That's all you need to know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GRAHAM-PROFILE-H     08-09 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GRAHAM-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM TURNS HEADS AS HOLLYWOOD'S LATEST FUNNY GIRL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Blending sexiness, comic giddiness and blond
tresses has been a successful Hollywood recipe for the few
actresses who get the mix just right.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe tops a short list of actresses _ Judy Holliday,
Carole Lombard and Goldie Hawn _ who have made a career of playing
blondes who can turn a tease into titters.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Cameron Diaz auditioned for the list. Heather Graham
is the latest pretender to the golden giggles club.
</P>
<P>
   Graham certainly has the hair and the come-hither style. But
that's just part of the formula.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Graham takes a shot at the final ingredient in two
comedies. She's already grabbed laughs and magazine covers as a
sexy secret agent in ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' Her
next comedy, ``Bowfinger,'' has her flirting funny opposite Steve
Martin and Eddie Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   As Felicity Shagwell in ``Austin Powers,'' she's a hip '60s CIA
agent willing to sleep with anyone _ and we do mean anyone _ to do
her job or get a laugh. That included shooting a gross-out love
scene with star Mike Myers while he was wearing the body suit for
400-pound Scottish assassin Fat Bastard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really looking forward to that day,'' Graham says, in
what is presumably disguised sarcasm. ``It was really special. We
really bonded. It was kind of embarrassing because I got a little
overheated, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarcastic or not, Graham passed muster with Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heather was great,'' he says of working with her. ``She's very
silly, likes to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bowfinger,'' she's Daisy, a wholesome-looking Midwestern
girl who seems all naivete when she hits Hollywood looking to
become a star. But Daisy also considers her sexual charms,
liberally shared, the key to getting what she wants.
</P>
<P>
   Catching her having sex with another man, Bowfinger (Martin),
one of her many lovers, accusingly says to Daisy, ``You slept with
him!''
</P>
<P>
   ``So?'' answers Daisy with so much innocence that Bowfinger can
only mumble, ``I never looked at it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The two roles go a long way to establish Graham as the comely
comic of the hour. But does Graham have the desire to be pegged as
cinema's sexy comedian?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty fun,'' Graham says in a high, sharp voice often
punctuated with giggling that sounds less than spontaneous. ``I
mean, like I want to play a range of different things. As long as
you're not only just sexy and racy, that there are other aspects to
you, it's good, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Graham sometimes sounds as if she's still auditioning for the
role: highly energetic, silly and a bit, well, scattered. But
perhaps it's just the voice and patter. One hopes so, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up with Graham in Los Angeles just before ``Austin
Powers'' opened in June, and again by phone a few days ago, as she
was touting ``Bowfinger.''
</P>
<P>
   In L.A., Graham, 29, is dressed considerably less provocatively
than as Felicity Shagwell in ``Austin Powers'' and less innocently
than as Daisy in ``Bowfinger:'' a black top, slit up the sides,
over black Capri pants and gray slip-on shoes. Sorry, no crocheted
peekaboo '60s outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had the guts,'' she says. ``I loved the boots. But
now that I've worn them in a movie, it would seem pretty stupid if
I was walking around wearing my character's wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   The dark duds contrast with Graham's pale face _ energized a bit
by pink blush and lipstick _ and her long, straight, light hair.
Rather tall, her height is emphasized by her thinness. Her long
fingers _ which restlessly push back wayward curling strands of
hair, _ end in unadorned nails, cut short.
</P>
<P>
   Graham considers her breakthrough part the teen-looking porn
star Rollergirl, yet another mix of sexuality, innocence and humor,
in 1997's controversial ``Boogie Nights.'' But she was already a
Hollywood veteran of two dozen movies. She began doing small movie
and TV roles at age 16 and had a significant role in ``Drugstore
Cowboy'' in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I had been acting before then in school,'' she says.
``I guess I just always admired movies, and it was a way for me to
get attention and distinguish myself. I always got to play cool
parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this year Graham was named 1999 Female Star of Tomorrow at
ShoWest, the film industry's annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   Her films include ``Twin Peaks: Fire Walk With Me''; ``Six
Degrees of Separation,'' with then-newcomer Will Smith; the
con-artist film ``Diggstown`` (co-star James Woods became her lover
for a while, though he was 45, she was 22); Even Cowgirls Get the
Blues; Swingers; Lost in Space (during which she became
romantically involved with director Stephen Hopkins); and ''Scream
2.``
</P>
<P>
   She also got attention for her acting _ and other things _ in
``Two Girls and a Guy,'' a distinctive three-character independent
film comedy drama. Graham and Robert Downey had a sex scene that
had no nudity but was so enthusiastic it almost got the movie an
NC-17 rating. It was trimmed after being submitted to the rating
board repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for her role as the teen porno star Rollergirl, a
part that was rewritten to be larger when Graham was signed, she
watched the filming of a real porn movie, an experience, she says,
that left her first shocked, then bored.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was born in Milwaukee and raised a Roman Catholic in
Virginia and Los Angeles. Her father was in the FBI, though she
says she doesn't know much about what he did, and her mother a
schoolteacher and writer.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Austin Powers'' and ``Bowfinger,'' Graham apprenticed her
comedy talents with three of the most successful comedians in film:
Mike Myers, Steve Martin and Eddie Murphy. She found each had a
different approach to his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is new to it, really excited and enjoying his success. He
really keeps the crew laughing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The first day working with Myers, she was left dazzled by his
improvisation of scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of shocked,'' she says. ``He sort of went off
(making up things), and I just went `Oh my God.' But you just have
to enjoy it. I just try to think about the story because you could
drive yourself crazy, probably.''
</P>
<P>
   Working on ``Bowfinger'' was a lot saner, since Martin wrote the
script, there were two weeks to rehearse, and Murphy is an old
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's been around awhile. But he's funny and confident and
more quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve's been around the longest. I wouldn't say he's more
restrained or intellectual, though in his personality he's very
intellectual. Steve is definitely going for a sophisticated style
of comedy. I felt like he was doing his own vision.''
</P>
<P>
   When Graham's character first arrives in ``Bowfinger,''
literally getting off the bus in true Hollywood tradition, she
seems naive to the ways of the world, which endears her to every
man she meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was innocent to the ways of moviemaking,'' Graham
says, ``but I don't know if she was so innocent to the ways of
life. She has an idea how to get what she wants, even if she hasn't
done it.''
</P>
<P>
   From her recent experience playing sexy roles, Graham concludes
that Americans have some odd attitudes about sex and the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can blow someone's head off, rip their heart out of their
chest, explode 500 bodies in front of your eyes, but if you show
someone having sex, it's incredibly racy,'' Graham says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems kind of sad. At least having sex is pro-life, you
know what I mean? Having sex is normal. Killing people isn't. Why
is that all right to watch and (sex) isn't?''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences won't have to wait long after ``Bowfinger'' to see
more of Graham. She has several films finished or in production. In
``Committed,'' she plays a wife who refuses to give up on the
husband (Luke Wilson) who leaves her. In ``Alien Love Triangle,''
one part of a three-story film (possibly to be called Alien Love)
about alien romances, Graham stars with Kenneth Branagh and
Courteney Cox.
</P>
<P>
   She's also planning to shoot a film with her current love,
filmmaker Ed Burns, who lives with her in her Hollywood Hills home.
Burns wrote and directed ``She's the One'' and ``The Brothers
McMullen'' and co-starred in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's writing a script right now,'' Graham says. ``It's about
cops and set in New York in the late '60s, early '70s, based on
some of the stories his dad told him.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham sees her current success after so many years as a
combination of elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have more confidence,'' she says. ``I am getting
more of a body of work and better at choosing my job. And there is
an element of timing and luck and, mmmm, I don't know. Maybe I'm a
little more together?''
</P>
<P>
   She likes sexy, comic roles, but she hopes there will be other
things in her future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to try not to be just the sexy girl,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's other stuff I want to do, too. I hope I get a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
