<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PROGNOSIS: Expecting the Best Is Good for the Heart &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Optimism and self-confidence may prove potent weapons in staving
off a recurrence of heart disease, if a new study by Carnegie
Mellon University researchers is any indication. Patients in the
study who had a positive outlook, greater self-control and higher
self-esteem after angioplasty surgery were less likely to suffer a
heart attack, undergo bypass surgery, or require a second
angioplasty in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers reported their findings in the July-August issue
of the journal Psychosomatics. Dr. Vicki Helgeson, a psychology
professor at Carnegie Mellon, and Dr. Heidi Fritz of the University
of Pittsburgh gave self-evaluations to 298 patients _ 199 men and
99 women _ hospitalized for angioplasty to relieve blockage in
major arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Patients were asked how confident they were that they could
alter health-damaging behaviors like smoking, how much they
exercised, how optimistic or pessimistic they were in their outlook
on life, and how much support they received from family, friends
and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, the patients were interviewed again.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who were more pessimistic, scoring low on the
psychological measures, were nearly three times as likely to have
more arterial blockage as people with a sunnier approach, the
researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RISKS AND REMEDIES: Kidney Toxins in a Nice Cup of Herb Tea &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Two women taking Chinese herbal preparations to treat eczema
have suffered kidney failure, according to a report in the Aug. 7
issue of The Lancet, a British medical journal. The cases raise new
questions about the safety of the remedies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cases are of great concern, since the herbal preparations
were from different sources and were prescribed for eczema,'' wrote
Dr. Graham Lord, a clinical research fellow at the Imperial College
School of Medicine in London, and his colleagues at the Hammersmith
and Charing Cross Hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In the first case, a 49-year-old woman, who had been taking an
herbal preparation in tablets for two years, complained to her
doctors of headaches and high blood pressure. The symptoms
progressed rapidly to renal failure, Lord wrote, and the woman had
a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, a 57-year-old woman who had been drinking an
herbal tea for six years, was admitted to the hospital with kidney
failure. She is still awaiting a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail exchange, Lord explained that the remedies used by
the women were made from a mixture of many Chinese herbs. But both
preparations contained mu tong, a Chinese name that can refer to
three different plants.
</P>
<P>
   The mu tong used in the remedies the women took, a laboratory
found, contained aristolochic acid, a chemical toxic to human
kidneys. Aristolochic acid was also found in Chinese herbs added to
a slimming formula linked to an outbreak of kidney failure in
Belgium in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese herbal medicine practitioners in the United States say
mu tong is also sold here, usually mixed with other herbs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NUTRITION: Chocolate, a Sweet Way to Fight Illness? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, bite into that Hershey bar. Chocolate, a new report
indicates, contains high levels of catechins, substances with
antioxidant properties that may help fight cancer and heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ilja Arts of the National Institute of Public Health and
Environment in the Netherlands said she and her colleagues, authors
of a short report last week in The Lancet, did not expect to find
large amounts of catechins in chocolate. In fact, she said, they
set out to study tea.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long suspected that tea, which also contains
catechins, may have a protective effect. But studies examining the
link between tea and reduced risk of disease have come up with
mixed results. And some studies, Dr. Arts said, even show an
increased risk with high tea consumption. To explore further, the
researchers looked for other foods that contained catechins. Dark
chocolate, they found, contained 53.5 milligrams per 100 grams,
about four times the amount of in brewed tea. Milk chocolate had
15.9 milligrams per 100 grams, just slightly more than tea.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean chocolate fights illness? ``We hope to clarify
whether or not catechins can protect against chronic diseases,''
Dr. Arts said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TREATMENT: Oxygen May Help Save Threatened Eyes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Giving oxygen to patients with detached retinas while they await
remedial surgery may help decrease damage to the affected eyes,
according to a California researcher who has successfully tested
his theory on cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that oxygen therapy reduces the amount of
damage to the photoreceptor cells of the retina,'' said Dr. Steven
K. Fisher, director of Neuroscience Research Institute at the
University of California at Santa Barbara. He suggests that
patients with retinal detachment be provided with oxygen
immediately upon diagnosis to protect cells until the retina is
reattached.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the August issue of The American Journal of
Ophthalmology, Fisher noted that photoreceptors, the
light-sensitive cells in the retina, have only one source of
oxygen, and if deprived, die rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 cats, Fisher reported, oxygen given immediately after
their retinas were surgically detached reduced damage to the eyes.
The researcher said he was planning additional research to see if
the same applied to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Retinal detachments occur mostly in middle-aged or older adults,
and in people with diabetes, but may also result from injuries in
sports like boxing and bungee jumping. Emergency surgery is usually
required, because a detached retina can lead to serious vision loss
or blindness.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gregory Dellone-Larkin, research director of the Department
of Emergency Medicine at the University of Pittsburgh, acknowledged
the potential value of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that too much oxygen could sometimes be
harmful, and in emphysema patients has led to death. He also said
that cat and human retinas differed substantially and recommended
more research.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
