A0869 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SHAPE-RECOGNITION     08-09 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SHAPE-RECOGNITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTIST'S WORK BLURS LINES BETWEEN ART AND SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Denis Pelli is a professor of psychology and neural science at New
York University.  
 By DENIS PELLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We humans are remarkably capable of recognizing objects, but
science has no explanation for how we do it.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long assumed, though, that we must see shape in
the same way at all sizes. Otherwise we would recognize our friend
or the letter ``a'' differently at each distance or size. Yet the
artist Chuck Close is exhibiting paintings that refute this
assumption, showing that size can dramatically affect what shape we
see.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of Close's paintings are of heads, produced by
photographing the subject, drawing a grid onto the photo and a
similar grid on a much larger canvas, and copying one square at a
time from photo to canvas. Close usually fills each square on his
canvas with a ``mark'' that preserves the average color, although
not the internal form, of the square on the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Seen from a great distance, the portrait is an accurate
reproduction of the photo. Looking at Bill II (1991), reproduced at
one-third actual size, or any of Close's paintings from 1987 to
1997 at their actual size, one can move forward and back, again and
again, and the face, solid from afar (greater than eight feet),
always collapses into flat marks when seen from near.
</P>
<P>
   The observer is crossing a threshold. This duality _ solid from
far and flat from near _ shows that size affects perceived shape,
disproving the popular assumption of size independence.
</P>
<P>
   As reported in the current issue of Science, to investigate
further, my students and I measured this effect with the paintings
in the Chuck Close retrospective exhibition, now at the Hayward
Gallery in London.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit has scores of block portraits with a wide range of
marks per face, face size, mark size and mark type, which include
watercolor dots, fingerprints and ink stick scribbles.
</P>
<P>
   We asked each observer, while looking at the painting, to move
forward and backward to find the viewing distance at which the nose
emerges from the canvas. From afar, the side-lit nose appears to
stick out from the canvas. As the viewer approaches, the nose
suddenly collapses, becoming a flat patch of unevenly colored skin.
</P>
<P>
   The results show that the duality depends on a component we call
visual mark size, which is simply the width of the mark relative to
the viewer's distance from the painting. Portraits of all sizes are
seen as flat when seen from more than 200 mark widths away; they
appear solid when seen from less than 200 mark widths.
</P>
<P>
   There are well-known antecedents to Close's block paintings,
like the block portrait of Lincoln published in 1973 by two
scientists, Dr. Leon Harmon and Dr. Bela Julesz; Dr. Richard
Gregory's dalmatian photo; the pointillist paintings, and the
ancient mosaics at Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
   But they all had small blocks, less than half an inch wide, not
big enough to disintegrate readily into flat marks at ordinary
viewing distances, so viewers did not experience the duality seen
in Close's recent work.
</P>
<P>
   Can the duality be explained by optical blur? By taking off
one's glasses (or putting on someone else's), one can blur the
image, wiping out the grid, which reveals the face, as viewers of
Close's paintings often discover for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Vision scientists have supposed that increasing the viewing
distance reveals the face simply because it increases the eye's
blur enough to wipe out the grid. However, as readers can confirm
by looking at Bill II, one need only back up 8 feet to see the nose
and face emerge, far short of the great distance of 32 feet needed
to wipe out the grid. The duality cannot be explained by blur; it's
perceptual.
</P>
<P>
   Can art be science? Close, as an artist, has been studying the
effect of size from the beginning:
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``The self portrait from 1967-68 is the first portrait
head that I painted. THe idea was to make something that was so
large that it could not be readily seen as a whole and force the
viewer to scan the image in a Brobdingnagian way, as if they were
Gulliver's Lilliputians crawling over the surface of the face,
falling into a nostril and tripping over a mustache hair.''(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   Close was more thorough than his scientific colleagues; the size
of the marks in his block portraits increased by 15 percent a year
from 1973 (quarter-inch) to 1997 (nearly four inches). He made sure
that exhibitions of his work would convey the idea, canceling a
retrospective that could not provide long viewing distances. He had
the idea and communicated it to the public, with compelling
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   So credit Close with discovering this size-dependent breakdown
of our ability to extract shape from shading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
