<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Scent Drives Animals Wild &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Science has discovered that Calvin Klein's Obsession is an
ocelot's too.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Dallas Zoo, studying different scents as part
of a program to help protect a subspecies of ocelot in southern
Texas, discovered that the spotted cats responded more intensely to
Calvin Klein's Obsession for Men cologne than to several natural
attractants. ``They roll and rub and drool and lick for several
minutes,'' said Cynthia Bennett, the zoo's research curator.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to test Obsession came on a lark. The zoo's gorillas
love the perfume advertising strips found in magazines, Dr. Bennett
said, so one day her research assistant brought in a Calvin Klein
strip for the ocelots.
</P>
<P>
   There are only about 100 to 150 of the Texas subspecies left,
and their favored habitat, thorny scrub underbrush, is
disappearing. The goal of the research is to use scents to guide
the ocelots to more favorable habitats and encourage breeding.
</P>
<P>
   Attractants will also be used to help take an accurate census of
the cats. When the animals rub against a scented spot, they deposit
hair follicles that can be used, through DNA testing, to identify
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bennett does not plan to use Obsession directly, but rather
will analyze its components. She already has a good idea that it is
the musk in the cologne that is driving the cats wild.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other attractants tested were rat and bobcat feces.
``Calvin Klein didn't have a lot of competition, if you think about
it,'' Dr. Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dirt's Cleansing Effects &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to eating, even parrots can occasionally
overindulge. And just as a person can turn to an antacid or other
remedy, a parrot, it turns out, can turn to clay.
</P>
<P>
   Many vertebrates (including people in some cultures) eat soil, a
behavior known as geophagy. While it is not clear exactly why it
occurs, soil eating has, among other things, been thought to aid
digestion through grinding in the digestive tract, add minerals to
the diet, and remove toxins that are found in certain foods.
</P>
<P>
   In the Peruvian Amazon, macaws and other parrots frequent the
cliff walls of eroding riverbanks, where they seek out specific
clay soils, eating small chunks to supplement their usual fare of
seeds. Researchers from the Wildlife Conservation Society, the
Oceanic Society and the University of California at Davis set out
to study the biochemical functions of this behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In one experiment, they fed a group of macaws a harmless
compound mixed with Amazonian clay, and another group the compound
alone. The results, reported in The Journal of Chemical Ecology,
showed that the clay-eating group never developed high levels of
the compound in the blood, while the other group did.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the clay did little to aid digestion
through grinding or add minerals to the diet, and did not
appreciably reduce the acidity of gastric juices, another common
theory. But by removing compounds through adsorption, the clay
enables the birds to vary their diets by eating toxin-containing
seeds, which are plentiful in the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; World Champion Robots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A five-robot team from Cornell University has won the 1999 Robot
World Cup soccer championship (small size division), played in
Stockholm at the same time as an international conference on
artificial intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament featured 18 teams in the division for robots less
than 7 inches in diameter, which competed on a table-tennis table,
passing and shooting an orange golf ball. The robots incorporated
sensors, computers and radios to work as a team without human
control.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell, which defeated the Free University of Berlin 15-0 in
the finals, went undefeated, including a come-from-behind victory
against a Korean team made possible when Cornell's human crew
realized that a chair was casting a shadow that confused the robot
goalie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
