<SLUG> BC-SCI-ECLIPSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL AUDIENCE FOR HUGE ECLIPSE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The solar eclipse that will sweep across Europe, the Middle East
and the Indian subcontinent on Wednesday promises to be one of the
most watched in history. The European portion of the itinerary
alone reads like one of those if-it's-Tuesday-it-must-be-Belgium
tours: Cornwall, Paris, Stuttgart, Munich, Vienna, Budapest and
Bucharest are all within or near the 60-mile-wide path of totality,
where the moon will completely cover the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Even people in the northeastern United States will have a chance
to see a partial eclipse at sunrise, weather permitting. In New
York, about one-third of the sun will be obscured when it rises at
6:02 a.m., with coverage diminishing to zero in a half-hour.
Farther north and east, the situation improves. In Boston, for
example, the sun will be about two-thirds covered when it rises at
5:47.
</P>
<P>
   Experts caution that even a partial eclipse can harm the eyes.
It should be viewed through a special solar filter (sunglasses or
photographic filters are inadequate) or by projecting the image
through a pencil-size hole in a piece of cardboard onto a sheet of
paper.
</P>
<P>
   The eclipse comes near what is known as solar maximum, the end
of an 11-year cycle when flares and other events increase. So the
corona, the sun's outer atmosphere that is only visible during a
total eclipse, may be particularly spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   But astronomers also hope to learn more about why the corona is
so hot _ millions of degrees, when the sun's surface is a mere
6,000. Data from research spacecraft have suggested that magnetic
fields near the surface may play a role.
</P>
<P>
   A team from Williams College is in Ramnicu-Valcea, Romania,
where the duration of totality will be the longest at just under
two and a half minutes, to try to observe rapid oscillations in the
corona that would be evidence of magnetic fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   The team, led by Jay Pasachoff, the head of the school's
astronomy department, is working in conjunction with one of the
orbiting observatories, the Transition Region and Coronal Explorer.
But that spacecraft can take only one photograph every 10 seconds
or so; since the oscillations would be on the order of one every
second, the ability of the ground-based crew to make a rapid series
of images is critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect example of how eclipse results can overlap and
collaborate with space results,'' Pasachoff said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-GOD-PARTICLE-NYT &LR;      08-09 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GOD-PARTICLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABS CLOSE IN ON THE `GOD PARTICLE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The race to find an elusive but all-important particle called
the Higgs boson heated up last week when Europe's most powerful
accelerator reached an energy that may bring the target within
range.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its presumably vital importance to universal
existence, the Higgs boson was dubbed ``The God Particle'' in the
title of a book by Dr. Leon Lederman, a Nobel laureate in physics.
</P>
<P>
   The godlike importance ascribed to the Higgs is based on the
belief that its interactions endow all the constituents of matter
with mass; it is the universal giver of heft.
</P>
<P>
   To create the ephemeral Higgs in the laboratory requires a
collision of two ordinary particles _ protons or electrons _ so
their combined collision energy exceeds the energy of the Higgs.
Last Wednesday the European Laboratory for Particle Physics (CERN)
near Geneva announced it had successfully boosted the energy of its
10-year-old Large Electron-Positron accelerator to 100 billion
electron-volts.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement means that CERN can run its LEP accelerator
``flat out, during its last years of service,'' a spokesman said,
with electrons and antielectrons hitting each other at combined
energies of 200 billion electron-volts. If the lightest Higgs
particle weighs less than this, it may be created and found in a
matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   But if the lightest Higgs is marginally heavier than this, it
will be beyond the reach of the LEP accelerator, and the prize
might go to CERN's major rival, the Fermi National Accelerator
Laboratory at Batavia, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Fermilab recently completed a major upgrade of its Tevatron
proton-antiproton accelerator that will pump far more colliding
particles into its beams than was possible before. Many more
collisions will occur, giving Fermilab physicists a better chance
of finding the rare events expected to signal the creation and
discovery of Higgs bosons.
</P>
<P>
   There may be as many as five different Higgs particles working
together as part of the ``Higgs mechanism'' _ a hypothetical system
that could explain why all other particles have the masses they do.
</P>
<P>
   A study of the Higgs mechanism, if it is found, could also tidy
up known flaws in the ``Standard Model'' theory, which accounts for
the different types of quarks and leptons that make up all matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Higgs boson is named for Dr. Peter Higgs, a Scottish
theorist, who in the 1960s found hints of the particle's existence
in equations describing the known constituents of matter.
</P>
<P>
   No one can predict how massive the Higgs will turn out to be,
except that it must be very heavy. But the lightest possible Higgs
boson may weigh as little as 109 billion electron-volts _ somewhat
less than the mass of an atom of silver.
</P>
<P>
   If the lightest Higgs particle weighs a little more than an atom
of silver, the Europeans will fail to find a Higgs in the next few
months and Fermilab will have a good chance of making the discovery
a little later. Lederman, a former director of Fermilab, likens the
situation to a horse race.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between CERN and Fermilab for the Higgs particle
is reminiscent of a similar race in the 1980s for the W and Z
bosons _ ``vector'' particles that transmit the ``weak'' nuclear
force between other particles.
</P>
<P>
   The CERN proton accelerator's energy was barely sufficient for
the quest. But a Dutch physicist, Dr. Simon van der Meer, and
CERN's director at the time, Dr. Carlo Rubbia, found an ingenious
way to bunch colliding protons together, and the technique enabled
them to snag the W and Z bosons.
</P>
<P>
   Rubbia and van der Meer were awarded the 1984 Nobel Prize for
their discovery. Almost certainly, a Nobel Prize also awaits the
winner of the Higgs race.
</P>
<P>
   But both Europe's LEP accelerator and Fermilab's Tevatron are
past their prime.
</P>
<P>
   Next year CERN's LEP accelerator will shut down to make way for
a new accelerator, the Large Hadron Collider, which will occupy the
same circular 17-mile tunnel that now holds LEP. When the new
hadron collider begins operation in 2005 it will be by far the most
powerful and important accelerator in the world, easily
outdistancing Fermilab's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   If the current search by Fermilab and CERN for the Higgs boson
turns up dry, CERN's new hadron machine will have a much better
chance of finding not only the Higgs but also one or more exotic
``supersymmetric'' particles.
</P>
<P>
   Many theorists believe that for every particle known to exist
there is a complementary particle that has yet to be discovered.
The discovery of such a supersymmetric particle would prompt a
revolution in physics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0881 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BULLIES-NYT &LR;      08-09 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BULLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLIES AND VICTIMS ARE ALIKE IN MAKEUP, STUDIES SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By SUSAN GILBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bullies are often pictured as brawny thugs, their victims as
bespectacled weaklings. But new research suggests that such
characterizations are at best misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Studies are finding that bullies and victims are often the same
people, being bullied one day and bullying the next. And children
who end up on either side of the bully-victim equation often suffer
from serious emotional problems, including depression, anxiety and
suicidal tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   In one study, for example, published last week in the British
Medical Journal, Dr. Riittakerttu Kaltiala-Heino, senior assistant
professor of social psychiatry at the University of Tampere in
Finland, surveyed 16,410 Finish students ages 14 to 16. Nearly
one-third of the children who admitted to bullying others
frequently, Dr. Kaltiala-Heino found, also said they were victims
of bullying. Most of the children who identified themselves as
bullies, victims, or both, she said, were boys.
</P>
<P>
   Using questionnaires designed to diagnose depression and assess
the risk of suicide, Dr. Kaltiala-Heino also found that bullies and
victims were more similar than different in their psychological
makeup. Depression was roughly as common among bullies as it was
among victims. And severe suicidal thoughts _ known to be common
among children who are victimized _ were even more prevalent among
bullies. Students were considered to have severe suicidal thoughts
if they agreed to either of two statements: ``I have definite plans
about committing suicide'' or ``I would kill myself if I had the
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Depression and suicidal thoughts, Dr. Kaltiala-Heino said, were
most common among the subgroup of children who frequently were
bullies as well as victims. For example, 44 percent of the girls
and 23 percent of the boys in this group were depressed, compared
with the 26 percent of girls and 16 percent of boys who were
victims only.
</P>
<P>
   A second study, appearing in the same issue of the journal,
reached similar conclusions. The researchers, who surveyed 3,918
Australian children, ages 11 to 15, reported that half the bullies
were also targets, and that most were boys. In this study the
bully-victim subgroup also had the poorest psychosocial profile.
``Bullies who are also bullied exhibit characteristics of both
these groups,'' said Chris Rissel, an epidemiologist at Central
Sydney Area Health Services in Australia, and a co-author of the
study.
</P>
<P>
   Bullies in the study evidenced high rates of smoking and
reported several psychological and psychosomatic symptoms,
including headaches, stomachaches, sadness and trouble in sleeping.
But children who identified themselves as both bullies and victims
had higher rates of these problems. Victims scored the highest on
measures of loneliness and were most likely to say they were
ostracized by other children. The subgroup scored a close second in
these categories.
</P>
<P>
   That a significant number of bullies in both studies said they
were also victims makes sense, the researchers and other experts in
the field said. ``Most psychologists agree that bullying and
aggression are learned behaviors,'' said Dr. Ronald D. Stephens,
executive director of the National School Safety Center, an
advocacy group in Westlake Village, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Limber, assistant director at the Institute for
Families in Society at the University of South Carolina in
Columbus, said many bullies who are also victims may suffer from
attention deficit-hyperactivity disorder, and as a result tend to
become irritable and combative. ``They may be targets of bullying
because of their own behavior but they also tend to bully other
children,'' Dr. Limber said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say it is not clear whether the incidence of
bullying is increasing. But studies confirm what most people, based
on their own experience, have always suspected: In the nation's
schools, physical and emotional intimidation is common.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 survey of 6,000 children in grades 4 to 6, for example,
showed that 1 in 4 reported that they had been bullied repeatedly
over several months. About 1 in 10 said they were bullied one or
more times a week. And 1 in 5 of the children admitted to being
bullies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, researchers disagreed on exactly how bullying
should be defined. But most now describe it as any act of physical
or oral aggression by a person against someone who is weaker _ that
is, smaller, less popular, or less secure. Hitting, taunting, or
manipulating others into doing things against their will are
examples of bullying, as is ostracizing another person.
</P>
<P>
   And most experts agree that bullying is rarely a problem
children can work out on their own. Instead, they say, bullies and
victims need help from parents, schools and even therapists.
Otherwise, the bullying may increase and the emotional problems of
the children may become more severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults should never ignore bullying or explain it away,'' said
Dr. Kaltiala-Heino. ``The worst thing is to pretend that nothing
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the high rates of psychological symptoms associated with
bullying, the researchers said, a crucial step in reducing the
problem is for bullies and victims to get appropriate counseling.
Family doctors and other health care professionals can help, they
suggested, by asking their young patients about problems at school.
</P>
<P>
   But schools can also play a role by adopting anti-bullying
programs, which provide a forum for disciplining bullies, helping
parents to identify the signs of bullying and referring bullies and
their victims for counseling. One such program in Norwegian
schools, Dr. Limber said, cut bullying in half within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results from a similar program, designed by Dr.
Limber and tested in 20 South Carolina middle schools in 1995,
indicate that bullying declined after one year. By contrast, she
said, bullying increased in a group of middle schools in the state
that did not use the program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
