<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLER-BEES-HNS &LR;      08-09 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-BEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS STUDYING WHY `KILLER BEES' HAVE NOT ADVANCED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TERRY KLIEWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's the story still waiting to be written, the
headline yet to be set in type: KILLER BEES INVADE HOUSTON.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't read it here, not today, anyway. That's because
the bees in question are nowhere to be found near Houston, the
fourth-largest city in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons still unclear to scientists, the Africanized
honeybees we've come to know and fear as ``killer bees'' have
stopped their march across southeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-1994, bee experts were baffled that the aggressive
insects, which first crossed the Texas-Mexico border four years
earlier, had halted their eastward march about 50 miles west of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The experts still aren't sure what's going on. Although the bees
continue to turn up in new areas north of us, they remain no-shows
around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news, I suppose, is there's no news,'' says Paul Jackson,
chief apiary inspector for Texas. ``There's very little change in
things'' since the first wave of publicity earlier in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   From his headquarters at Texas A&AMP;M University in College
Station, Jackson has a front-row seat for the bee invasion, if it
comes.
</P>
<P>
   Brazos County, home of the Texas A&AMP;M campus, is not listed as
killer bee turf, which means no such bees have been collected
there. They have been found to the south in Washington County and
to the west in Milam County.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Brazos County on the same bee bubble as Harris County,
which includes most of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when it comes to Africanized honeybee migration
patterns, such things as county lines, river routes, and mountain
ranges and deserts don't account for much.
</P>
<P>
   The intrepid bees have crossed them all since they first got
loose in Brazil more than 40 years ago in an experiment gone awry.
Since then, they've been on a Genghis Khan-like sweep north through
South America and now into the southwestern portion of North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Prolific and hardy, they've muscled their way over, under,
around and through more docile, indigenous bees and now are waiting
somewhere along Interstate 10, an ominous buzz in our western
skies.
</P>
<P>
   Should we worry? Not really, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The migration is inevitable. Kim Kaplan of the Agricultural
Research Service, an agency of the U.S. Department of Agriculture,
says nothing can or should be done to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything you do to kill Africanized honeybees is going to kill
the European variety, too,'' she says. ``Killing bees is not a good
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the USDA has no firm answers as to why the bees
have stopped their invasion of the South at Houston's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not going to stop their migration,'' Kaplan
explains, ``then there's no point to researching why they're moving
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan, like Jackson, has theories. She begins with varroa
mites, which she says have taken a huge toll on European and
African honeybees in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny parasites kill bees and other susceptible insects by
boring into their bodies and draining them of liquids _ bug blood,
as it were.
</P>
<P>
   If mites mean fewer bees, then there's less pressure on the
colonies to strike out in search of new sources of water and
flowering vegetation, says Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson thinks the migrating Africanized bees may have run into
double trouble when they pushed out of South Texas _ roughly the
part of the state south of a line from about Victoria to Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   First, there were the mites, which the invaders didn't have to
contend with significantly until they reached the Corpus Christi
area, Jackson says. Second, there were agricultural pesticides,
starting in the Rio Grande Valley orchards and vegetable fields,
and extending northward into the rice fields and cornfields of the
Gulf Plains.
</P>
<P>
   By holding bee populations down, the poisons effectively induced
otherwise migratory colonies to linger longer in a given area.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rule, the farther you move east, the more woods (as
opposed to fields) there will be and, in them, there will be more
mites and feral (native) bees that already have hives,'' says
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Mother Nature doesn't necessarily have a welcome
mat out for the migrating bees in East Texas or anywhere farther
eastward in the Deep South, despite its beckoning subtropical
climate.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, where the bees once were forecast to arrive by
1992, officials are still keeping watch. Jackson says Texas
continues to check its traps in East Texas for signs of
Louisiana-bound Africanized bees. Traps in Texas run on an
east-west line from about Beaumont to Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Phillips, a public information and education specialist
with the Texas Apiary Inspection Service, says the notion that the
bees are in one place, but not in another, can be a little
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are counties in Texas where they are not, that are all
but encircled by counties where they are,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's reasonable to suppose that the bees in such situations
wander across county lines occasionally. ``We just haven't run into
them yet, so they are not `there' yet,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons such determinations matter.
</P>
<P>
   The first is commercial. Beekeepers want to know the whereabouts
of Africanized bees so they can protect their own hives of European
bees, or at least be prepared if they get an influx of the African
variety.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the European type is more docile and produces much
more honey than its African counterpart, although Jackson says some
interbred bees perform pretty well as honey producers.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas track-and-trap effort is part of a quarantine system
administered by Jackon's office to better serve the honey industry.
When Africanized honeybees show up in a county, it is quarantined
by the apiary service until further notice.
</P>
<P>
   The designation means local beekeepers can move their hives
within the county but not elsewhere, without state certification.
This curtails inadvertent shipment of Africanized bee queens to
non-Africanized areas. Of course, bees in the wild still come and
go as they please.
</P>
<P>
   Texas now has 113 of its 254 counties quarantined, Phillips
reports. The most recent additions, Bosque, Hill and Somervell
counties in central Texas, went behind the Killer Bee Curtain in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason to track bees is that the quarantine notices
serve as public-safety alerts.
</P>
<P>
   Although Africanized bees generally don't live up to their
menacing ``killer'' nickname, they have been responsible for human
and animal deaths. Like black widow or brown recluse spiders, they
can be a hazard and ought to be treated with great caution, says
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   By now, it's pretty well-known that the bees aren't more
poisonous than ordinary bees, but they are more aggressive and
potentially more lethal. If the bees have a strategy for dealing
with provocation, it is: Hit quick. Hit hard. Keep hitting.
</P>
<P>
   The mere presence of a person or animal within 20 or 30 feet of
a killer beehive can be enough to touch off a black-and-yellow
blizzard of angry bees. They're willing to die by the hundreds in
an out-of-proportion stinging attack, and they're happy to chase
their prey as far as a half-mile.
</P>
<P>
   Experts advise people who are attacked to run and keep running
to escape, try to get indoors or into heavy brush where the bees
cannot follow, and seek first aid quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But the odds of encountering killer bees probably are not too
different from the odds of encountering a rattlesnake. Much depends
on where you are, what you're doing and what season it is, the
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Bend County demonstrates just how varied the killer bee
infiltrations and encounters can be.
</P>
<P>
   As the only southeast Texas county east of the Brazos River
where the bees have been trapped, Fort Bend has been under
quarantine since 1993 _ a likely place, one would assume, to bump
into the nasty bees. Jackson says stinging incidents usually peak
within two years of the bees' appearance in a locale.
</P>
<P>
   But only one Africanized honeybee attack has been documented
there _ at a vegetable stand in Rosenberg in 1996. That's one
encounter in six years. The obvious question looms: Are the bees
still in Fort Bend?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: maybe, which is pretty much the picture in Harris
County, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably not be able to prove the bees aren't in Harris
County, which is like trying to prove a negative in an argument,''
says Phillips, whose duties include documentation of stinging
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if they're there, we'd hear about them. So far, we haven't
heard anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
