<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-HNS &LR;      08-09 1637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAKES HIGH IN IOWA POLL FOR BUSH, OTHER HOPEFULS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While most Americans endure the dog days of summer,
the Republican presidential candidates will be diving into their
first key presidential contest Saturday in Ames, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll, a fund-raiser for the state's Republican Party,
has historically played only a marginal role in determining who
wins the Iowa caucuses or becomes the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But the event has gained more prominence this year because of
the participation of Republican presidential front-runner George W.
Bush, who boasts that he intends to win.
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll will help gauge the strength of Bush's
organization and those of his rivals as well as the depth of his
appeal in this key primary caucus state.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not do as well as expected, the governor is sure to
hear criticism that his campaign is more hype than substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be the first chink in the armor of George W. Bush,''
said Hugh Winebrenner, a professor of public administration at
Drake University in Des Moines who has chronicled the history of
the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are even higher for the other eight participating GOP
candidates, who need to do well to persuade potential backers to
bankroll their struggling efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The results could also set up the stand-in for front-runner
status if Bush stumbles. Many of the candidates are striving to be
at least in the top half, if not the top three.
</P>
<P>
   ``They desperately need some good news to buck up their
supporters to continue to fund-raise,'' said Winebrenner, adding
that a strong showing by Bush could ``be one more nail in the
coffins of several campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who has devoted almost
all his time in Iowa but still lags in fund raising and in polls,
has said he needs to perform well in Ames.
</P>
<P>
   But others are taking the event more lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a do-or-die or a make-or-break for us,'' said
Monte Shaw, the Iowa campaign coordinator for Elizabeth Dole, who
has been drawing large crowds in the state as she trails in polling
and money.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he viewed the event as ``a way to ramp up our
organization a little early.''
</P>
<P>
   State Republican officials estimate that as many as 15,000
people will attend the event at the Hilton Coliseum on the Iowa
State University campus.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the forum has not only drawn national media
attention but has become a financial bonanza for the state
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP charges $25 for a ticket that enables one to participate
in the straw poll and hear the candidates' 10-minute speeches. The
campaigns generally defray the ticket cost for supporters, as well
as provide transportation to Ames.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the
candidates appear to be taking the straw poll seriously. McCain,
who has opposed the ethanol tax subsidy dear to many rural Iowans,
has said he will not participate and has instead been spending time
in other primary states, particularly South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great fund-raiser for the Iowa Republican Party. I
congratulate them for the scam,'' McCain told cable television's
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other candidates, however, have been barnstorming
across Iowa, hitting town hall meetings, VFW posts and centers for
senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's bank account and endorsement lists dwarf those of
his rivals, he has spent far less time than his competitors in a
state that has traditionally demanded personal attention from
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, the Texas governor has campaigned in the state
only six days, including a recent two-day visit. By comparison,
Alexander has logged more than 70 days and magazine mogul Steve
Forbes has devoted almost 50 days.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Bush campaign is going all-out to win the
straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has brought in volunteers from Texas to help locate
potential straw poll participants.
</P>
<P>
   And to ensure its supporters make it to Ames, the Bush campaign
has rented 99 buses to transport supporters from across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Once at the event, Bush backers will be feted at a tent party
that includes a barbecue spread and a host of entertainers and
sports celebrities, including country singer Tracy Byrd, world
champion bass fisher Johnny Morris and San Antonio Spurs basketball
player Sean Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to stage the party in a prime location, the Bush campaign
shelled out more than anybody else at a silent auction, $43,000 for
a 60,000-square-foot plot across from the coliseum. The
next-highest bidder, Forbes, paid $8,000 for an adjacent
40,000-square-foot plot.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has run TV ads that spoof the land deal and feature an
auctioneer trying to sell the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Eric Woolson defended the expenditures: ``You
have to do things to make it easy for people to attend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has also been attacked for relying on powerful
allies outside of Iowa to help win the poll. According to a memo
that surfaced earlier this year, the campaign planned to use
Washington-based trade associations to prod Iowa affiliates to
persuade 700 people to show up at the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Woolson would not confirm that the Washington lobbying effort
was paying off. But he said: ``Are we encouraging specific groups
to turn out for the governor? Yes we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Iowa observers believe that Forbes, a multimillionaire who
has been willing to tap into his fortune to build up his campaign,
may be Bush's most formidable rival in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' officials were reluctant to divulge details of their
battle plan, however. When asked how many buses had been leased to
bring in backers, a campaign official replied: ``That's a state
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign has also been accused of using questionable
tactics to increase turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the director of the state Christian Coalition told the
Des Moines Register that a Forbes campaign representative
approached a temporary employment agency she runs last February and
inquired about hiring workers to bolster his tally in the straw
poll.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign denied the allegation. The national office
of the Christian Coalition also disputed the charges leveled by
state director Bobbie Gobel and later fired her.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican officials note that the party cracked down on
controversial practices in the past, including the busing in of
out-of-state residents. Before voting this year, all participants
must show photo identification that establishes them as Iowans.
</P>
<P>
   Some have questioned the long-term impact of a function that
draws only a fraction of the people who generally turn out for the
early winter caucuses. Furthermore, Iowa, which is overwhelmingly
white and rural, is hardly representative of the increasingly
diverse U.S. electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all pretty stupid,'' said John Haskell, a professor of
political science at Drake University. Nevertheless, Haskell said
the perception has grown that these events matter, particularly
with an increasingly front-loaded primary season that forces
candidates to raise money earlier than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Stewart, the state GOP's executive director, defended the
straw poll's significance, arguing that it measures the current
health of the campaigns, particularly in terms of money and
grass-roots organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only real midterm exam that the candidates have,''
said Stewart, who also said the straw poll does give an early
indication of who the nominee will be. He noted that over the last
20 years, the party's nominee had come from one of the top three in
Ames.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the outcomes of the straw polls have both been
prescient and misleading. In 1995, Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas tied
with front-running Sen. Bob Dole in the straw poll, leading some
analysts to predict that Dole was losing steam. However, by the
time the voting in the Iowa caucus was done, Gramm's campaign had
fizzled. Dole won the caucus and the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, George Bush defied conventional wisdom by beating
Ronald Reagan in the straw poll. Bush went on to win the Iowa
caucuses, but Reagan later rebounded and won the nomination and the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, the straw poll turned into a liability for
Bush, when he suffered a devastating loss to Pat Robertson and
Dole. Bush also lost the Iowa caucuses, but won the nomination and
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's strong showing also signaled the growing clout of
the religious conservatives within the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the straw poll this year may indicate the
diminishing clout of social conservatives, as many of them appeared
to be splintered among Forbes, Dan Quayle, Gary Bauer, Pat Buchanan
and Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   While Buchanan did well last time in both the caucuses and the
straw poll, his third try for the White House does not appear to be
electrifying supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also has been struggling to raise money and does not
appear to have a strong state organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who has spent considerable time in the state, appears to
be making the most headway.
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the conservative Family Research Council has
lambasted Bush for abandoning Republican principles on such issues
as abortion and human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   Marlys Popma, Bauer's deputy political director, said she
believed voters might retaliate against the Texas governor as the
perception grows that he has been anointed by the party elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has spent more time at fund-raisers (in the country's power
centers) than he has in Iowa,'' Popma said.
</P>
<P>
   Woolson dismissed the attacks on Bush as coming from campaigns
``that don't have resources.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
