u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FITNESS-WEIGHTS-A     08-09 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-WEIGHTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE FOR SPORTS EXERCISE: GO BALLISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fitness experts call them ``explosive'' or ``ballistic''
training exercises. And according to the American College of Sports
Medicine, which endorsed the lightweight, high-speed techniques in
a statement last month, they are a good way to increase strength.
</P>
<P>
   Movements advocated by the organization include faster versions
of traditional exercises, like squats and bench presses, and
plyometrics, a group of exercises that involve jumping on and off
high platforms, tossing around weighted balls and leaping in the
air while holding weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Explosive movements are effective because they not only
increase strength but the speed with which you can call strength
into play,'' said Dr. Steven Fleck, chairman of the sports science
department at Colorado College, Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Fleck points out that in a traditional, nonballistic weight
training repetition, full muscle power is not required until about
a second after beginning. In contrast, during a ballistic
repetition, maximum power is needed much faster _ in two-tenths of
a second or less, the same speed as in athletic skills like
throwing a softball or sprinting down a soccer field. For this
reason, Fleck recommends explosive weight training as an essential
training tool for serious and recreational athletes alike.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, athletes have long practiced explosive weight training.
Pat Manocchia, owner of La Palestra, an exclusive gym located on
Manhattan's Upper West Side, has trained his clients using
plyometric and other high-speed training methods for more than five
years.
</P>
<P>
   He often includes in his clients' training programs ``depth
jumps,'' an exercise that involves hopping off a 12-to-24-inch high
box onto the floor, then springing back up again.
</P>
<P>
   Manocchia's clients, who range from professional football
players to seasoned marathoners, do as many as four, 90-second
depth jump sets during a workout. ``In any athletic movement, be it
a golf swing, jump shot, or tennis serve, your muscles must be able
to generate speed,'' Manocchia explained. ``This type of movement
helps develop these qualities so you perform better and get injured
less often.`
</P>
<P>
   Research seems to support Manocchia's assertions. In a study
published earlier this year in the journal Medicine and Science in
Sports and Exercise, 16 elite male volleyball players performed a
typical preseason training program that included cardiovascular
conditioning and moderately paced weight training. Half the
subjects also added plyometric jumps and other explosive movements
to their repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of eight weeks, the plyometric group demonstrated a 6
percent improvement in jumping ability; the control group showed
virtually no improvement. The researchers concluded that their
results lend support to the effectiveness of ballistic training.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Steven Plisk, director of sports conditioning for
Yale University in New Haven, Conn., also recommends explosive
training for older exercisers. According to Plisk, most everyday
activities have an explosive quality. ``If you step off a curb when
a car is coming, it's not how much weight you can move _ it's how
fast you can move it out of the way,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Plisk said that explosive movements can help older people
improve mobility because they usually involve several muscle groups
working simultaneously in conjunction with each other, much the
same as they do during everyday actions. ``Jumping moves, for
instance, require a coordinated effort of virtually every muscle in
your body. Besides building strength, they also promotes balance,
agility, and coordination, all of which help you to rise from a
chair, walk across the room, and perform countless other basic
activities easily and gracefully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' Fleck cautioned, ``ballistic exercise is an
advanced technique and not something you should do if you're an
inexperienced weight trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   He recommends starting a program of six to 12 weeks consisting
of slower paced weight work to build a strength base, then
gradually incorporating ballistic movements. ``Perfect form and
technique are essential so it's a good idea to get some instruction
when you're first learning new explosive training moves,'' he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
