<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0810-COX     08-09 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VLADIMIR PUTIN: THE 'GRAY CARDINAL' WHO WOULD BE KING
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-YELTSIN-0810.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A little more than a year ago, Vladimir Putin was an
obscure bureaucrat and former spy, among the dozens of players who
fade in and out of President Boris Yeltsin's circle of Kremlin
advisers, government appointees and political pawns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 46-year-old Putin has become the most conspicuous
politician in Moscow who, if he can prove his staying power, could
become Russia's next president in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin tapped Putin as the latest in a line of prime ministers
to run the distressed Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kremlin decided Putin is more reliable and tougher'' than
the man he replaces, Sergei Stepashin and a line of previous prime
ministers, said Andrei Piontkovsky, a political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The sandy-haired and soft-spoken Putin received on Monday an
unconditional endorsement from Yeltsin as the man Russians should
choose to replace him when his term expires next summer. It is a
nod Yeltsin has been reluctant to give anyone else until now.
</P>
<P>
   But little is known about Putin beyond his extensive and shadowy
career in the Soviet and Russian security services, and the intense
loyalty he purportedly shows to his political masters.
</P>
<P>
   The man who would replace Yeltsin is touted as a smart and savvy
administrator. He made a successful leap from cold warrior to new
Russian policymaker. But there is not much of a record to suggest
his political leanings or depth of commitment to democracy and
market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation from Leningrad University in 1975, Putin was a
Soviet-era spy. He served a posting in foreign espionage as an
agent in Germany. Following the collapse of the Soviet Union in
1991, Putin retired from the Russian KGB with the rank of colonel
and went to work for the local government in St. Petersburg
(formerly Leningrad).
</P>
<P>
   He rose to the post of vice mayor under liberal mayor Anatoly
Sobchak. Known as a colorless, but effective, administrator he
earned the nickname the ``gray cardinal'' -- operating in the
shadows of his boss.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he came to Moscow in a move arranged by market reformer
Anatoly Chubais, a close Yeltsin advisor in the mid-1990's. Putin
became the deputy Kremlin administrator and later was put in charge
of the Kremlin's relations with Russia's powerful regional
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Putin was named head of the domestic security
service, the FSB, an arm of the former KGB, and in March was also
named secretary of the president's Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   With more experience in security than politics, some analysts
question whether Putin is suited for the job of prime minister, or
president. He is an awkward public speaker and rarely appears on
television.
</P>
<P>
   His rise to prominence is the result of an act more suited to a
monarchy than a democracy. Putin's ascendancy comes because the
imperial president -- a man long ago dubbed Tsar Boris because of
his vast constitutional powers -- has chosen Putin as his heir.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appearance of Putin on the political scene in Russia
inspires anxiety rather than hope for the future of the country,''
said political analyst Andrei Cherkizov.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
