NYT-08-09-99 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-0810-C     08-09 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YELTSIN PICKS HIS SUCCESSOR AFTER SACKING ANOTHER PM
 &HT;    825&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-PUTIN-0810.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin thrust Russia into yet another
political crisis Monday by abruptly firing the prime minister he
appointed only three months ago and replacing him with a man
Yeltsin said should become the troubled country's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Stepashin, who was appointed in May, became the fourth
prime minister sacked by Yeltsin in the past 17 months. Visibly
stunned, he appeared on television before a morning cabinet meeting
to announce that he and the government had been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement is an ex-KGB spy during the Soviet era who most
recently was head of Russia's security service, the FSB. Vladimir
Putin, 46, became acting prime minister and received Yeltsin's
explicit endorsement to run for president next year with the
Kremlin's backing.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden move, apparently motivated solely by election-season
politics, raised anew questions about Yeltsin's failing health and
his ability to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain madness,'' Boris Nemtsov, a former deputy
prime minister, said in a Russian radio interview. ``The people
have grown tired of watching an ill leader who is not capable of
doing his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov called it ``100 percent
lunacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The national currency, the ruble, and the Moscow stock market
fell sharply after the morning announcement. Seeking to calm
financial markets, Putin said there would be no changes in the
government cabinet members controlling Russia's foreign and
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   The government shuffle comes one year after mounting financial
woes and similar political turmoil last August hastened a national
economic crisis from which Russia is still seeking to recover.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of parliament, the Duma, is scheduled to begin
considering Putin's nomination for prime minister on Monday. Some
analysts predicted that he could receive fairly swift confirmation
from the Communist-controlled Duma, in part because legislators
want to avoid a protracted fight as they prepare for parliamentary
elections in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Duma is skeptical and cynical. They've ceased to care who
the prime minister is,'' said Andrei Piontkovsky, director of the
Strategic Studies Center, a Moscow think tank.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration reacted cautiously,
saying it is ready to work with Putin. ``Clearly it is within
President Yeltsin's prerogative'' to make such a change, said David
Leavy, a national security spokesman for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials most recently worked with Putin in resolving
Russia's role in the NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo, Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
   While Stepashin's firing was dramatic, it was not entirely
unexpected. The move was widely viewed in Moscow as a ploy to
promote the loyal Putin and to protect the political and financial
after-life of Yeltsin's inner circle -- known as ``the family'' --
when the president's term expires next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family probably looked for a more reliable figure that
could serve as Yeltsin's successor, the main thing being to
preserve the very existence of the family,'' said Communist
parliament member Viktor Illyukhin.
</P>
<P>
   National parliamentary elections are scheduled for Dec. 19 and
the presidential election is set to take place next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition political parties have been maneuvering in recent
weeks to consolidate their power, wooing former Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov, a potential presidential candidate and --
according to some reports -- Stepashin, too. Last week, the Moscow
mayor and presidential aspirant, Yuri Luzhkov, sealed a deal with
influential regional leaders that virtually marked the start of the
2000 presidential campaign year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, Yeltsin is prohibited from seeking a
third term to office. In a nationally televised address, Yeltsin
called Putin ``a man who in my opinion is capable of uniting
society, based on the broadest political forces, to ensure the
continuation of reforms in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin added: ``I trust him. I also want everyone who goes to
the (presidential) polls in July 2000 to make their choice to trust
him too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's blessing may prove to be a curse. Yeltsin has
remained for more than a year dismally low in public opinion polls
and his endorsement of Putin is likely to mean little to Russian
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has ``put a hex on Putin,'' said Gennady Seleznyov,
chairman of the Duma. ``All those whom Yeltsin once called his
successor have no political future now,'' Seleznyov said, adding
that the president ``cannot and must not deprive the people of the
right to make their own choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Kremlin connection gives the uncharismatic and
politically untested Putin a vast resource of financing and media
support from the business tycoons aligned with Yeltsin since he won
reelection in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Putin declared his candidacy in his first remarks after being
nominated by Yeltsin. ``I will undoubtedly run for president,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin had just returned Sunday night from visiting the
embattled southern border, where Russian forces have been drawn in
recent days into heavy fighting with Islamic militants in the
mountainous Russian border republic of Dagestan. The region is near
the breakaway republic of Chechnya, where Russia fought a
disastrous war from 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and Yeltsin opponents have suggested that the
Kremlin could use the combat against the insurgent militants as a
pretext for declaring emergency rule and thus postponing the
parliamentary and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The communist leader, Zyuganov predicted Monday that Yeltsin
would impose emergency rule as a rationale for remaining in office.
</P>
<P>
   In his departing remarks to the cabinet, Stepashin said Russia
risks losing control of the Dagestan republic.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, who had been a former interior minister, had himself
been considered a possible handpicked successor for Yeltsin. By
most accounts, his was growing into the job as prime minister and
traveled last month to Washington on a relations-mending mission as
the U.S. and Russia seek to overcome the strains from NATO's war
against Yugoslavia over the Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin on Monday offered no reason for firing Stepashin and
praised him ``for his good work''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, a clearly shaken Stepashin told the cabinet: ``I
was open with President Yeltsin about what I thought of my
dismissal.'' He reportedly rejected offers to take a prominent
cabinet post in a government led by Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
