<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAY-TRADING10-COX     08-09 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-TRADING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'DAY TRADERS' LOSING THEIR MARKET GAMBLE, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    660&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS and ALAN JUDD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most ``day traders'' suffer substantial stock
market losses, state securities regulators said in a report Monday
that criticized brokers for failing to adequately warn their
customers of the high risks.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Securities Administrators Association said
most day traders were unlikely to profit because they sold winning
stocks quickly, but held on to losing ones in hopes they would
recover.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing accounts at one brokerage firm, the group
concluded that 70 percent of all those who engage in rapid-fire
trading ``will not only lose, but will almost certainly lose
everything they invest.''
</P>
<P>
   One such big loser was Mark O. Barton, who murdered nine people
at two Atlanta day trading firms last month, as well as his wife
and two children, before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has obtained Barton's
trading records from both Momentum Securities and All-Tech
Investment Group. The SEC will probe whether Barton pursued the
typical strategy of letting his losses ride on his way to dropping
as much as $450,000 on volatile Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators' survey of typical day-trading conduct was
released 11 days after Barton's shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying report, based on a seven-month probe of a
dozen day-trading firms, the regulators said the firms often misled
investors with tales of potential wealth, accepted customers who
insufficient funds to invest over time, and failed to keep accurate
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day trading is ... a particularly risky program of trading
that warrants heightened suitability and disclosure requirements,''
said the report. It urged regulators to step up their monitoring
role and to ban banning private lending between clients, which
sometimes allows big losers to continue trading after losing their
original stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``If day-trading firms want to become part of the mainstream,
they need to play by the same rules the rest of Wall Street
follows,'' said Peter Hildreth, president of the association, which
represents securities regulators in the 50 states, Canada and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't get their act together they will be under
increasing regulatory pressure,'' said Hildreth, who also serves as
New Hampshire's director of securities regulation.
</P>
<P>
   At a crowded press conference, David Shellenberger, the primary
author of the 46-page report and chief of licensing at the
Massachusetts Securities Division, said ``day trading is
fundamentally no different than going to Las Vegas or Atlantic
City.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, Shellenberger said it would be ``a
Herculean task'' for day traders to keep track of all trades _ for
some, hundreds in a few hours _ so they could file income tax
returns on profits and losses, as the law requires.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum Securities, in whose Atlanta office Barton killed four
people,
</P>
<P>
   did not directly respond to the report. But the Electronic
Traders Association, headed by Momentum's president, James H. Lee,
said in a statement, ``We will cooperate with lawmakers and
regulators to encourage appropriate regulation to protect day
traders and to make securities markets more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   The traders association questioned the validity of the survey
that came with the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere near 70 percent'' of day traders lose their money,
said Saul Cohen, counsel for the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a large number of people losing all their money,
wouldn't you think you would have the SEC all over it?'' Cohen
asked. ``There's a kind of lack of common sense and logic ... to
the numbers in the report.''
</P>
<P>
   The traders association also objected to the idea of changing
the current rule allowing customers to make loans to one another.
That is a commonly accepted practice in the securities industry and
is not limited to day traders, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Houtkin, chief executive officer of All-Tech Investment
Services Inc., reacted more strongly in a telephone interview from
the company's headquarters in Montvale, N.J., calling the report
``a piece of trash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a self-serving document,'' Houtkin said. ``I would have a
hard time being associated with this document, it's just that
poorly done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We give people a real shot to be successful. We give people
direct access to the market,'' he said. ``For them to come out
against us is just such an outrage, it makes me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Complaints against day trading firms are rare, Houtkin said,
adding that regulators shouldn't adopt a tougher stance against the
industry just because of Barton's shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a madman who happened to be a day trader,'' he
said. ``To create a link between the two borders on
irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory group's survey involved a detailed study of 30
accounts chosen at random at All-Tech's Watertown, Mass., office.
</P>
<P>
   The results defied the classic definition of day trading, which
calls for all stock positions to be liquidated before the end of
each session, thus allowing for a fresh start on the next trading
day.
</P>
<P>
   The actual trading pattern, however, showed the average losing
trade was held twice as long (9.53 days), as the average winning
trade (4.52 days). The average intraday trade also went into the
losing column.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, these short-term traders were cutting their profits
short and letting their losses run,'' noted Ronald Johnson, an
investment consultant from Palm Harbor, Fla., who conducted the
analysis. Such a course runs directly counter to the widely held
market strategy of cutting losses quickly and leaving profits on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the full report may be obtained at the association's
Internet site (http://www.nasaa.org).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
