<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOVA-APES-NYTR &LR;      08-09 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOVA-APES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTRESS WHO STARRED IN `PLANET OF THE APES' AMAZED AT FILM'S
APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PACE   
 TimesDaily, Florence, Ala.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year marked the 30th anniversary of a genuine milestone in
science-fiction moviemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planet of the Apes,'' a frightening, futuristic thriller about
a world in which apes are the dominant species and humans are mute
savages, revolutionized the genre with its mature,
thought-provoking marriage of imagination and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Released in 1968, ``Planet of the Apes'' inspired four hit
sequels, two short-lived television series and millions of devoted
fans. Through it all, original ``Apes'' heroine Linda Harrison now
54 and a favorite attraction at science fiction conventions _
remains pleasantly amazed by the movie's timeless appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew for years that it was popular, but I had no idea of the
depth and breadth of its fan base until I started doing
conventions,'' said Harrison, who played the silent but pivotal
role of Nova, a human primitive who becomes the mate of a stranded
astronaut played by Charlton Heston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's had a profound effect on people, and the audience is
still growing,'' Harrison said. ``It's very much alive today &UR; , &LR; 
even more so than when we first made it.''
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the film's 30th-anniversary celebration,
20th Century-Fox has staged an ambitious ``Apes'' revival.
Highlights include the production of a comprehensive documentary,
``Behind the Planet of the Apes,'' plus the release of digitally
restored, wide-screen editions of all five ``Apes'' features
``Planet of the Apes,'' ``Beneath the Planet of the Apes,''
``Escape from the Planet of the Apes,'' ``Conquest of the Planet of
the Apes'' and ``Battle for the Planet of the Apes'' in a deluxe
edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first `Apes' came out during the time of the Vietnam War,
the civil-rights struggle and assassinations,'' Harrison said.
``Profound issues that needed attention were at the forefront of
people's minds. I don't believe that the filmmakers set out to make
a political picture at all. I think the writers were just
reflecting what their experience was at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Planet of the Apes'' was based on a novel by French writer
Pierre Boulle, who also wrote ``The Bridge on the River Kwai.'' The
movie centers on a crew of astronauts who travel forward in time,
landing on an alien planet where simians are the civilized rulers
and humans are hunted like beasts. As Nova, Harrison used her
skills as a former acrobat to perfect her highly physical,
``subhuman'' role _ with no dialogue whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The director, Franklin J. Schaffner, was such a reflective and
thoughtful man,'' Harrison said. ``We just seemed to talk about her
and think about her and how she would react in different
situations. Nova may not have had advanced mental capacity, but she
was a human being, and she had feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of ``Planet of the Apes,'' all but one
astronaut dies either in the crash of their spacecraft or at the
hands of the apes. The sole survivor is their leader, Taylor
(Heston), whose intelligence and ability to speak alarms the apes
and threatens their rigid sense of absolute supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nova naturally was drawn to this incredible white man who
could speak and whose intelligence was much more advanced,''
Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by two sympathetic chimpanzee scientists (Roddy McDowall
and Kim Hunter), Taylor finally escapes with Nova, his only human
companion, into a barren region called the Forbidden Zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planet of the Apes'' has a startling conclusion. Riding
horseback along the shoreline, Taylor and Nova come face-to-face
with the decaying remnants of the Statue of Liberty and the
revelation that the ``Planet of the Apes'' is the Earth of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   While Fox was considering a screen version of Boulle's
controversial novel, Harrison _ a contract player and former
Maryland beauty queen _ was dating her future husband, producer and
studio executive Richard Zanuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember clearly when Dick first introduced the idea of the
movie to me,'' Harrison said. ``We were in a restaurant, and he was
enormously excited about it. He went on with great enthusiasm,
telling me the whole plot of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Harrison was enlisted to play the
progressive-minded chimpanzee Zira (the part eventually played by
Hunter) in test footage shot to determine the viability of the ape
makeup. The brief footage shown for the first time in the
``Behind'' documentary features Heston, Harrison, James Brolin (in
McDowall's role) and screen legend Edward G. Robinson (as the
aristocratic orangutan Dr. Zaius). Robinson disliked the
uncomfortable ape makeup and was replaced by Maurice Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison and Zanuck, the son of Hollywood mogul Darryl F.
Zanuck, married in 1968 and had two sons, Harrison and Dean, who
are now both in the movie business. The couple divorced after eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison reprised her role as the shapely, raven-haired,
scantily clad Nova in the first ``Apes'' sequel, ``Beneath the
Planet of the Apes'' (1970). Heston's character disappears in the
opening scene, and Nova spends the rest of the film searching for
him with a newly arrived astronaut (James Franciscus). In an
apocalyptic conclusion, Nova dies after screaming her first and
last word ``Taylor!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, they had planned to end the first movie with the
implication that I was pregnant with Taylor's child,'' Harrison
said. ``At the last minute they decided against it. They were
afraid it would add an element to the story that they couldn't
resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ``Apes'' films, Harrison's credits include
``Way, Way Out'' (1966) with Jerry Lewis and Gene Kelly's ``A Guide
for the Married Man'' (1967), plus the television series
``Bracken's World'' (1969-71) and appearances on ``Batman'' and
``Barnaby Jones.'' In 1975, billed as Augusta Summerland, she
reunited with Heston for ``Airport '75.''
</P>
<P>
   She recently performed a cameo in ``Runaway Bride,'' starring
Richard Gere and Julia Roberts. The romantic comedy was shot in
Harrison's hometown of Berlin, Md. Her role, however, was cut from
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played myself, Linda Harrison, the girl who was Nova in
`Planet of the Apes,''' she said. ``I enjoyed the experience, and
I'm excited about the film because it was shot in Berlin.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Apes'' anniversary and persistent rumors of a Hollywood
remake _ with directors as diverse as James Cameron and Oliver
Stone _ have intensified interest in Harrison and her ``Apes''
co-stars. In addition to her appearances at sci-fi conventions,
Harrison has own Web site at www.lindaharrison.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web site and conventions are a way for me to reach out to
people,'' said Harrison. ``People who are basically strangers come
up to me, ask me to sign autographs and tell me things that touch
me deeply. It's important for me to speak with them and share time
with them. There's a bond happening between us, and I consider that
a wonderful privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   (The TimesDaily in Florence, Ala., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
