<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0948 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DALLAS-DOWNTOWN-HNS &LR;      08-09 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-DOWNTOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG D MEANS DOWNTOWN IN DALLAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dorcy Siegel grew up in North Dallas in a spacious home
with a generous yard and a short drive to shopping malls and movie
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Now she lives in a 600-square-foot apartment with no yard, far
from the nearest mall. She wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely unique experience.'' she says. ``I can walk
to work. I can walk to the gym. Last Saturday night, I had about 35
people over and we walked to the Gold Bar in the Titche-Goettinger
building (a department store turned into loft apartments). It was a
novelty for them to actually walk somewhere in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   An urban planner, she lives in downtown Dallas in the Kirby
Residences, one of many loft developments that, along with dozens
of more conventional townhouse and apartment units sprouting just
outside the central business district, are beginning to remake the
face and culture of a city that once seemed hell-bent on escaping
from itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine living anywhere else,'' Siegel says. ``It's
like a campus feel. I have a rooftop pool. Two of my friends live
two stories above me. Everything's familiar and comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   She is typical of the ``urban pioneers'' who are driving an
almost insatiable demand for downtown living.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happening in a lot of cities,'' says Greg Willett of M/PF
Research. Downtown Houston also is undergoing a major residential
makeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Dallas and Atlanta are ahead of everyone else and Dallas
is better positioned than most markets,'' said Willett.
</P>
<P>
   Loft living is not exactly new to Dallas, but when the first
units were carved out of abandoned warehouses more than 15 years
ago, the tenants were mostly artists or photographers needing cheap
living and working space or twentysomethings drifting through their
Bohemian phase. They stayed until they could afford something
better, or the novelty faded, or they married or had children. Then
they sought more conventional digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no demand (for downtown residences) because it
wasn't offered,'' Willett says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 M/PF was hired by the Central Dallas Association to
determine the potential demand if upscale living quarters were
available. The results were surprising even to those most
optimistic about a rebirth of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a latent market,'' says Larry Fonts, president of
the CDA. ``That (research) determined there was a 24,500-unit
demand. Today, we have satisfied about half of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would want to live in downtown Dallas? By the end of the
1970s, the flight to the suburbs had threatened downtown's
viability even as an office park. Retailers moved to the malls, and
corporations were building headquarters in places such as Plano and
Las Colinas and points north. Once-fashionable inner-city
neighborhoods were going to slums and were selling at scrap prices.
</P>
<P>
   Then, an odd thing happened on the sprawl toward the Red River _
not a giant sucking sound, but a faint sipping that was drawing
fragments of the population back to the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   Their motives were mixed. Some were young and adventurous and
simply found the suburbs too monotonous. Others tired of long
commutes. Some sought liberation from the time and monetary demands
of maintaining a large house and yard when their children were no
longer around.
</P>
<P>
   And, suburbia had lost much of its idyllic luster. Crime,
disease, congestion, high taxes and other ills of the inner city
had also spread outward. Plano was wracked by a cluster of teen
suicides, followed by a wave of teen heroin overdose deaths. In
Allen, the school district is involved in a controversy over metal
detectors at the entrances to its classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report titled ``The Social and Health Landscape of
Urban and Suburban America,'' the National Public Health and
Hospital Institute noted that poverty among suburban children under
the age of 6 had increased 50 percent during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Inner cities also were becoming safer. Between 1990 and 1997,
violent crime declined 37 percent in Dallas, while falling by only
21 percent in its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   For many, living downtown became an attractive option, as well
as an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lofts were romanticized,'' says Bennett Miller, one of the
pioneer loft developers in Dallas. ``People saw pictures of them in
magazines and newspapers from places like New York. They were
colorful and had a heavy romantic appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   With old warehouses and factory buildings available at prices
below outlying properties and with tax incentives on the table,
builders began conversions that went far beyond the starving
artist's studios. Rooftop pools, laundry rooms, fitness centers,
security patrols and enclosed parking were the norm. A restaurant
or bar on the premises was not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the loft units were leased before they were completed.
According to population estimates by the North Central Texas
Council of Governments, 31,000 people now live inside the ``freeway
ring'' of downtown Dallas and within a one-mile perimeter of it. An
additional 100,000 live within a three-mile perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown rents are relatively high _ $1 to $1.50 a square foot
per month, but the new urban dweller apparently can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last spring by the CDA found that almost half of
downtown residents have college degrees, three-fourths are
unmarried and two-thirds hold professional or managerial positions.
Their median income is $88,158.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are renters by choice,'' says Ed Ducoff, president of
Pace Realty, which manages the 1900 Elm lofts in the old
Titche-Goettinger building. ``They could easily afford a suburban
home if that's what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Jenkins, manager of the Santa Fe Terminal lofts, located
in a high-rise building that originally was a train station,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just had more 800-foot units,'' she sighs. ``We could
fill as many of those as we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Santa Fe, most of the loft developments have been small
_ 90 to 150 units _ but recently Matthews Southwest announced plans
to convert a massive old Sears, Roebuck and Co. catalog merchandise
center _ 30 acres of vacant buildings _ on the southern edge of
downtown into 450 apartments averaging 1,700 square feet. Retail
shops and restaurants and a Gilley's country-western entertainment
center will be a part of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the lofts, the perimeter of downtown is sprouting
large apartment, condominium and townhouse developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, we have an urban neighborhood,'' says Fonts,
who sold his North Dallas home and moved to a townhouse near
Dallas' new light rail station at City Place, a multiuse
development just north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who want an urban lifestyle. They want the
convenience of being near their jobs. They want the security of
being able to lock the door and going away for the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   After migrating to downtown a year ago, Fonts says, he and his
wife discovered that the convenience ``vastly outweighed any sense
of inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My insurance costs went down. My utilities went down. My
homeowner's association fees are less than my pool maintenance
costs used to be, and I still have a pool. I'm less than seven
minutes to my office, door to door. There's a 16-screen movie
palace at City Place.''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants of McKinney Avenue _ the main drag of ``Uptown''
Dallas _ and the live-music night life of Deep Ellum are just
blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of public and private efforts combined to make
downtown an attractive residential option, Fonts says, and
downtown's new trains have been a major player.
</P>
<P>
   Developers of the Adams Mark hotel _ the largest in Texas _ have
cited rail as a factor in the decision to build the 2,000-room
hotel in downtown Dallas; Pete Coughlin of Maxwell Southwest says
the rail line played a large role in making the old Sears facility
viable for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rail line changes the whole nature of your location,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   New apartments are going up near the renovated and expanded
Farmer's Market. Ground has been broken on a new downtown sports
complex that eventually will result in more apartments, restaurants
and shops north of the West End entertainment district. Development
of parks and lakes on the Trinity River also is considered another
step toward rounding out the downtown neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the Dallas-Fort Worth area has grown from 3 million
to 5 million people and projections are for the population to pass
7 million in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Developers are betting that downtown will share in that growth,
but some, including Bennett Miller, the pioneer of lofts, warn of
potential pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of amenities are still missing,'' Miller says. ``There
are no good schools downtown, no grocery stores. There is not the
kind of street life you see in New York or Chicago or Boston. It
will take a generation or two for that to come about.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the movement back to town appears to be more than a
fleeting fad. Dallas is running out of old buildings that can be
adapted to lofts and new ones, built to resemble old warehouses,
are filling up with occupants willing to forgo many of the suburban
trappings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a large grocery store belongs downtown,'' says
Dorcy Siegel. ``Dallas is still a driving town and I don't have to
drive much more than a mile to a supermarket. But I can still get
my Popsicle at the little store down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
