<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-09 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY GUYS, IT'S AUGUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How did voters ever get the notion that the elected
politicians in the nation's capital are isolated from the real
world and out of touch with their constituents?
</P>
<P>
   Voters aren't stupid, that's how.
</P>
<P>
   The latest confirmation of the gap between ordinary folk and the
officials who represent them is the brilliant notion of both
Democrats and Republicans to devote this month to selling their
competing visions of how best to spend the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Congress passed a massive $795 billion
tax cut bill with goodies for everyone last week, the largest since
the President Reagan-sponsored cuts of 1981 that were so extreme
they had to be partially reversed. President Clinton has vowed to
veto the bill, charging it's a reckless giveaway to the rich that
would jeopardize basic domestic programs and long-term funding of
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of promptly sending their partisan measure to the
president, the Republicans will sit on it during the congressional
summer recess to give themselves time to drum up support in the
public opinion polls. When Congress returns in September, the GOP
figures that voters will be clamoring for tax cuts and the
president will capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   Hasn't anyone noticed that August is the month the real world
goes on vacation? Just envision the excitement at the beach as
families put down their romance novels, throw away their snow cones
and debate the merits of the two approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to do today, daddy?'' the little boy asks. ``Will you
take me fishing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, son, we'll have more fun than that,'' the father replies.
``We'll discuss all the thrilling ways to spend the federal
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Give it a rest, Washington suits. Nobody except political
junkies, who have already made up their minds on this issue anyway,
will be listening.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need August to discover that voters bring more common
sense to such clumsy, inflamed ideological debate than their
political leaders do.
</P>
<P>
   Voters tell the pollsters that tax cuts are fine: who wouldn't
want to pay less taxes?
</P>
<P>
   But they also say they give their highest priority to using the
projected surplus to pay down the national debt, protect Medicare
and spend on education, child care and other programs. They want to
use the surplus wisely for the general good, not waste it.
</P>
<P>
   The political truth is that both sides can make a persuasive
case, but they are so philosophically far apart that they both
can't be right.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for their huge tax cuts, the GOP will have to cut labor,
health, social services and education drastically to get around
prior budget spending ceilings, gutting programs that voters like.
But they claim individuals would rather have a few more nickels in
their pockets than supportive government services.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I think the president is correct to insist upon using the
surplus _ the ultimate size of which is very much in doubt _ to
strengthen Medicare and Social Security for the baby boomer crunch
to come. The surplus figures are based on shifting assumptions,
contradictory projections and phony budget gimmicks. Who knows?
Best to play it safe.
</P>
<P>
   Once the huge estimated sum is given away in tax breaks, it will
be gone forever. And if the economy sags, we will be back to huge
deficits. Risking that is really stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, lecturing vacationers won't make any difference.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody professes to desire a compromise, in which the
president goes for a scaled-down, half-sized tax cut and the
Republicans grant some financial leeway for programs like Medicare
prescription drug benefits. Hardly anybody thinks that will happen.
It's too obviously sensible.
</P>
<P>
   Sensible is mushy politics. Confrontation is more useful in
election years.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay gave away the GOP game last week
when he conceded Republicans are passing bills that deliberately
siphon away nearly all the non-Social Security surplus on tax cuts,
leaving Clinton no money for his own priorities without raiding
Social Security. The idea is to then argue that Clinton's spending
plans threaten the elderly's retirement lifeline, not the GOP tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans don't want a legislative record, they want
issues on which to campaign in year 2000. It is less clear what the
Democrats want, but they wouldn't mind pointing fingers instead of
counting achievements, either.
</P>
<P>
   The likely outcome is that neither side will compromise, Clinton
will veto as promised, and the world will go on. The GOP learned
its lesson in previous budget confrontations; Congress will duck
rather than let the government be shut down again by a mindless
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Under an accounting gimmick, Congress can continue to operate on
last year's budget levels, in effect stalling until the next
election changes the political equation. Program allocations and
tax status will remain the same. No progress will be made but no
damage done either.
</P>
<P>
   Not a great solution. But everyone can live with it. So enjoy
your vacation.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
