<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN-COX     08-09 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES &AMP; SHORT STORIES: Of communistss and happy meals
 &HT;    (Eds: Sixth in a series. Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
reported from Eastern Europe during a visit 10 years ago, just
before the fall of the Berlin Wall. This summer he returned to
write about the changes that have led three former Eastern Bloc
countries _ Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland _ to become the
newest members of NATO. At the end of the series, CoxNet will
compile these columns into our weekly Focus page, good for running
as a Perspective-type page or op-ed feature.
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE - Last time I dined at the Hotel Europa, they begged me
to return soon.
</P>
<P>
   That was ten years ago. The people of Prague, still very much in
the grip of the communist regime, were strapped for hard currency,
and I was paying with dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Another journalist and I had been the restaurant's only
customers on that misty fall night in 1989. The hotel's string
quartet played just for us as we sampled vintage wine that, I like
to think, the Hotel Europa had stashed from the communists for a
special occasion. It was as wonderful a dinner as I ever remember.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, on Wenceslas Square since 1889, nowadays is so busy
that I had to make three return trips before the head waiter could
take time out to talk with me.
</P>
<P>
   Its rising popularity is due somewhat to that of the movie,
``Titanic.'' The dining room, awash in Old World elegance and
crowned with a lavish turn-of-the-century skylight of leaded glass,
could have been a set from the film. It's worth eating here just to
be here.
</P>
<P>
   My friend the head waiter, Peter Boochaz, now 36, was likewise
here ten years ago. Then he was part of the kitchen help, just
starting out. Neither of us remembered the other, but no matter. We
had been there together, that much we were sure of.
</P>
<P>
   A different time, it was. And yet...
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed, but in some ways not so different,'' he
said. ``What you still remember is still with you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still with him.
</P>
<P>
   He asked that I not use a tape recorder for our interview. ``It
reminds me too much of the interrogations.''
</P>
<P>
   Press him on that topic, and he won't talk even for note-taking.
``I never did anything,'' he said, dismissing the subject with a
wave of his hand and the billowing smoke from a constant cigarette.
``It's nothing worth talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   You could easily imagine Boochaz in a spy role, more so for the
movies. He's that handsome - tall, dark and dimpled _ and with an
accent reminiscent of Charles Boyer.
</P>
<P>
   He has a wife and three children, the oldest by an earlier
marriage. He blames himself for the failure of his first marriage.
After the fall of communism, when the free market economy seemed to
promise everything for everybody, he said he gave himself too much
to his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I needed was a 48-hour day - 46 1/2 hours for work, one
hour for sex and a half hour for whatever else.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is success to be had under capitalism, but not
enough to go around to everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have our rich, and we have our poor, but the middle
class does not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to the next generation to change that, he said,
``or maybe the next two or three generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything he sees is changing for the better.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Republic, as a new member of NATO, signed on to the
war in Kosovo. But not him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like war, not the Cold War, not the war in Kosovo,''
he said. ``Kosovo involved a struggle of religions. I like all
religions.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say he doesn't like the U.S. - leastwise he'd like
to know more about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not just to know how to make money. Money is only paper.
I'd like to hike your forests, to ski your mountains, to know and
experience the beauty of your country.''
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing new, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Czech people, even when our borders were closed, our
mind-set was always with the West.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what has changed ...
</P>
<P>
   I hope not the food, I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the food is still wonderful,'' he said warmly.
</P>
<P>
   Then he stopped, frowned and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take that back,'' he said. ``For Prague, the food has
changed. Now we have McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VICEPRESIDENT-COMMENT     08-09 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICEPRESIDENT-COMMENTARY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: statesman Adlai Stevenson. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's mark 1900 as the strategic turning point for the destiny
of the vice presidency. Renomination was a foregone conclusion for
William McKinley, the popular incumbent reckoned as unbeatable. But
party bosses speculating on the GOP's long-range future believed it
necessary to neutralize one Theodore Roosevelt, the 42-year-old
Rough Rider legend of the Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
   They put Teddy on the ticket with McKinley and supposed he was
defused. Instead, TR became president when McKinley was
assassinated, barely into his second term. By his remarkable energy
and undoubted charisma, the first of the Presidents Roosevelt
dominated the Republican Party as handily as he controlled
Congress. In 1904 he was the first vice president since Van Buren
to be elected in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   William Howard Taft, all 300 pounds of him, was Roosevelt's
personal choice to succeed him, and he waltzed to victory in the
1908 election. But because Roosevelt couldn't control Taft, the two
parted ways, and TR ran as a third-party ``Bull Moose'' Progressive
in 1912, causing the split that threw the election to the
Democrats' Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   However, Theodore Roosevelt merely was the exception to prove
the rule for vice presidential substance. Wilson's veep, Thomas
Marshall, is immortalized for having declared, ``What this country
needs is a good five-cent cigar.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles G. Dawes, Calvin Coolidge's vice president, is
remembered mainly as a songwriter _ ``Many a tear has to fall, but
`It's All in the Game.''' And Harry Truman's beloved veep, Alben
Barkley, was a venerable statesman in the Curtis-Garner mold.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge himself had been a strategic afterthought, a New
Englander to balance a ticket led by Ohio's Warren Gamaliel
Harding. The sudden death of Harding in 1923 catapulted Coolidge
into the presidency; and unprecedented prosperity not of his own
doing catapulted Coolidge into unprecedented popularity. After his
election with Dawes in 1924, he did not choose to run in '28. Had
he so chosen, he could not have lost, regardless of who might have
been identified as his second banana.
</P>
<P>
   It was rather a different story in 1944. FDR was the Democrats'
``indispensable man'' seeking a fourth term, and most in the
party's inner sanctum sensed his impending death. They engineered
to have Harry Truman become FDR's third vice president (following
Garner and Henry Wallace) in the certain belief that Truman would
become our 33rd president.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since then, the vice presidency has had considerable
political clout. In 1952 Dwight Eisenhower chose as his running
mate a rising star, Richard Nixon, then only 39; and most vice
presidents since Nixon have had their party's nomination for the
presidency: Nixon; Lyndon Johnson; Hubert Humphrey; Gerald Ford;
Walter Mondale; George Bush ... and don't bet against Al Gore. (The
only exceptions have been the Nixon tandem of Spiro Agnew and
Nelson Rockefeller, and Bush's curiously chosen Dan Quayle.)
</P>
<P>
   Relationships between presidents and their first lieutenants
also have changed remarkably. During the eight years that he was
vice president, John Garner saw FDR a total of nine times and
visited with him ``twice. Harry Truman revealed in his memoirs that
when he was suddenly whisked into the presidency, he had seen
little of FDR and had not been briefed on any matters of policy.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, Johnson, Bush, Gore _ all have been strategically
involved in affairs of state. So now the vice presidency isn't a
banishment _ it's a steppingstone worth several gallons of spit,
warm or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is a former books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VICEPRESIDENT-COMMENT     08-09 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICEPRESIDENT-COMMENTARY-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NO. 2 SPOT: TODAY'S VICE PRESIDENCY ISN'T WHAT IT USED TO BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Nance Garner, constrained by the office during Franklin D.
Roosevelt's first two terms, later described the vice presidency as
``not worth a pitcher of warm spit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cactus Jack,'' from Uvalde, Texas, was speaker of the U.S.
House of Representatives when he was Texas' ``favorite son'' choice
for the presidential nod at the 1932 Democratic convention. Jim
Farley, architect for FDR's successful quest for the nomination,
engineered the deal that put the raffish, delightfully crude Garner
on the ticket with the patrician Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly or wrongly, most Americans blamed President Herbert
Hoover for the Great Depression, so in the general election the
Democrats rode roughshod over the GOP ticket of Hoover and the
incumbent vice president, sweet old Charles Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Their party affiliations notwithstanding, Garner and Curtis were
longtime close friends. When the government changed hands, Curtis
said: ``Jack, your career is over now. They're putting you out to
pasture, as they did me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was how it used to be with the vice presidency. Not any
more.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a formidable charge by Bill Bradley or some other
development not presently foreseeable, Al Gore will be the
Democratic standard bearer for the national election in 2000. This
illustrates vividly how the vice presidency has been upgraded in
very recent times.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president may often be a ribbon-cutting stand-in for
the chief executive, but he (or she) still has almost no official
responsibility beyond presiding over the Senate. But nowadays the
veeps are younger than before and are keenly identified with their
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   John Adams was vice president to George Washington; and when
Adams became our second president, his vice president was a
political antagonist _ Thomas Jefferson, no less. It was during
Jefferson's tenure as our third president that a two-party system
became sharply defined, and the vice presidency lost its luster.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the 19th century did a vice president graduate to
the top spot via a national election. That was in 1836, when Martin
Van Buren was essentially a puppet, representing the continuity of
Andrew Jackson's Democratic administration when Jackson honored
George Washington's precedent by not seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Van Buren's own re-election bid was derailed
by the fabled Whig tandem of ``Tippecanoe and Tyler too,'' but with
ironic result. Tippecanoe was William Henry Harrison, military hero
of the early Indian wars; and John Tyler was no Whig at all, but a
Democrat opposed to the Jackson-Van Buren governmental style. Tyler
was also a Virginian, imparting geographic balance to the ticket
led by Indiana's Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Taking office at age 68, Harrison died after only one month in
office, all of it spent in bed. He signed no legislation, so Tyler
in effect had a complete term as president. He was also a vigorous
chief executive who played a decisive role in the annexation of
Texas. Yet not in four years could he gain control of the Whig
machinery, and he was denied nomination in 1844.
</P>
<P>
   The second president to die in office was Zachary Taylor, also a
Whig, also a military hero (Mexican War). The 1850 death of ``Old
Rough and Ready'' opened the presidency to Millard Fillmore, a
formidable candidate for the title of our worst president ever.
Fillmore sought to retain the presidency but also was sent packing
by the Whig hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Whigs in 1852 trotted out yet another vaunted
soldier; and when Winfield Scott was swamped by Democrat Franklin
Pierce, the Whigs were finished ... but were reconstituted soon
after, more spectacularly, as the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln in 1860 became the first Republican elected to
the presidency. The Civil War was still unresolved when Lincoln's
re-election bid four years later proposed a new vice president. The
presence on the ticket of Tennessee's Andrew Johnson, a former
Democrat, may well have swung a close election to the Republicans;
but in the wake of Lincoln's assassination, the party gave Johnson
nothing but trouble. He was a lame-duck president both before and
after he barely survived impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The 1880 election delivered an impressive young Republican to
the White House; but less than a year later, James Garfield was
dead at age 49, assassinated by a disappointed office-seeker.
Ascending to the presidency was Chester Alan Arthur, a party
regular and a man of considerable charm. Arthur avoided controversy
and appeared to have control of the GOP machinery, but he too was
unable to secure nomination in his own right, yielding the bid to
James G. Blaine, characterized by the Democrats as ``the
continental liar from the state of Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   The generals of party politics appeared not to have learned a
lesson from history. Both the Democrats and the Republicans
continued to designate benign elders as vice presidential fodder.
They all seemed to resemble the first Adlai Stevenson, who was one
of Grover Cleveland's veeps and was great-grandfather to the
20th-century statesman Adlai Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
