<P>
   TRADERMAIN _ ATLANTA _ In another time and another place, Mark
Barton might have been a high-stakes gambler who spent his days _
and money _ at the horse track or the craps tables. But his
addiction was a more modern one, born of the high-tech age. He
plunked down huge bets not on long-shot nags but on a long-shot
method for trading stocks, devised for bold, rich and naive
speculators. And suckers. He was one of a few thousand Americans to
embark on a ``career'' in online trading _ in his case day trading,
a financially dangerous pursuit that may sound more legitimate than
betting on horses, but in reality is much the same. So were his
results. On Monday, the North American Securities Administrators
Association, which represents stock regulators in every state,
called for a stiff crackdown on day trading to protect people like
Barton from losing their shirts in a game in which they have little
chance of winning. (Hendricks, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/ TRADER-ONLINE _ ATLANTA _ An estimated 6,000 people trade
daily or very often in day trading offices, while about 4.6 million
people buy and sell online from home, though relatively few do it
daily, Internet research firms say. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRADERS _ ATLANTA _State securities regulators are expected to
say that day trading firms need to do a better job of explaining
the financial risks involved in day trading and making sure their
customers can bear that risk. The report, being released in
Washington, is the result of a months-long study of the day trading
industry. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
