A0972 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     08-09 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV11-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS FED UP WITH WARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, Aug. 11.)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Washington last week a panel of 20 prominent researchers and
scientists announced that they will no longer be warning Americans
about anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're done. It's over. That's it,'' said professor Sigmund
Tofu, a man who has spent the past 10 years trying to explain to
Americans the difference between ``good'' and ``bad'' cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of being jeered and mocked by people every time we
revise our opinion on an important health issue,'' said Dr. Beavis
Fenfen, author of the ground-breaking report ``Eat More Eggs Until
You Die.''
</P>
<P>
   In a press release, the panel presented the results of a poll
that showed that 60 percent of Americans think food warnings are
``a bunch of hooey'' and 80 percent believe that scientists will
someday come to the conclusion that a diet of cheese nachos and
butter-pecan ice cream is good for the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you people are waiting for us to say that three Big Macs a
day will improve your cardiovascular fitness, then you're in for a
long wait,'' said Dr. Mitral Endoscopy. ``However, we are seeing
evidence that a quart or more a day of Secret Sauce can lower the
risk of bladder cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that only 20 percent of Americans heed health
warnings today compared to 71 percent 25 years ago. Forty percent
of Americans say they avert their eyes when they come across a new
health warning in their daily newspaper and 12 percent admitted
that they threw a heavy object at their TV screen when it was
announced recently that margarine may be bad for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You people seem to think we're making this stuff up as we go
just to jerk you around,'' said professor O.K. Transfatti. ``That
is simply not true but just to be on the safe side, we have applied
for a $200 million federal grant to study the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Public annoyance with new research findings found its focus last
year with the creation of Citizens Riled Over Contradictions
(CROC), a group of citizens that claims that scientists have made
it impossible for a person to lead a healthy life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of guilt,'' said CROC organizer I.B.
Shrill. ``We're used to guilt. We've lived with guilt all our
lives. In the old days, if we ate an egg, we felt guilty. If we
shook a few grains of salt on our salad, we felt guilty. If a drop
of alcohol touched our lips, we felt guilty. That was OK. At least
we knew what we were supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, all bets are off. Nobody knows what's right and wrong
anymore. You know what I had for dinner last night? A salted,
hard-boiled egg and a glass of red wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago that was the dietary equivalent of jumping off a
cliff. Today, it's a healthy meal. Tomorrow? Who knows? Some
pencil-necked geek in a lab somewhere might discover that broccoli
causes cancer in laboratory rats, if they eat the equivalent of 20
pounds a day of the stuff over 5 years, but 30 hot dogs a day
improves the memory, though I don't know what you'd be remembering,
other than the fact it's time to eat another hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really care what scientists tell us to do. If they
want us to eat salmon until we swim upriver and spawn, great. If
they want us to guzzle eight glasses of olive oil a day, that's
fine, too. Just tell us what to do and stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell us a year later or 10 years later that a grilled
salmon steak brushed with olive oil will make my skin peel off and
my liver turn green. I don't want to hear it. I can't spend the
rest of my life worrying about whether peanut butter is good for me
or the next best thing to swallowing cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   ``CROC is glad to hear that scientists will no longer be issuing
any warnings of any kind because, quite frankly, we're tired of
listening.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
