<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOT-ROD-FEVER-NYTR &LR;      08-09 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-ROD-FEVER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEED, POWER AND THE LITTLE RACE THAT ROARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By LOWELL COHN   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ They drove me over to the waiver trailer. A
nice lady handed me a piece of paper, which she asked me to sign.
It said I would not hold the National Hot Rod Association, Sears
Point Raceway and their heirs responsible if a drag racer blew up
in my vicinity, sending shrapnel-like pieces of metal into my
spleen, liver, frontal lobes, etc.
</P>
<P>
   I signed.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for my signature, I was taken in a golf cart to the
starting line for the NHRA Autolite Nationals, held Sunday at Sears
Point. The starting line is a narrow strip of concrete filled with
fumes. I stood between two top-fuel vehicles, about two feet away
from each one. They are basically rockets on wheels. It was like
standing on the launch pad at Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   I was feeling pretty excited, until David Lamm, who handles
media relations for the NHRA, said, ``This is louder than Van
Halen. If you're around these cars long enough they will damage
your hearing even if you wear earplugs. The sound will penetrate
your cranium.''
</P>
<P>
   I had visions of sound waves invading my skull and erasing my
memory bank.
</P>
<P>
   The cars began revving their engines. I was wearing earplugs,
but I felt my cranium begin to vibrate and my brain turning to
pudding. My ears hurt. I remembered something else Lamm had said.
``They're going to hit the throttle and you're going to feel like
you're going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   A pleasant thought.
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``It'll vibrate your organs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which ones?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers were getting ready to compete in the first round of
eliminations. They were looking at a set of lights called the
Christmas tree which count down to the start _ a bunch of amber
lights, then green. The Christmas tree turned green. The cars took
off. The word loud does not begin to describe it. The world turned
into a roar which was outside me and inside me. And there was
nothing else but the roar, except for my small intestine doing the
hula.
</P>
<P>
   I blinked, and when I looked up the cars were flying far down
the track in a haze. The Earth seemed to slide. Suddenly their
parachutes had deployed. That was it. The end.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Vandergriff, the winner, had gone a quarter of a mile in 4.5
seconds, reaching a top speed of 317 mph. The loser, Garth
Widdison, couldn't manage anything in excess of 276 mph. Slowpoke.
</P>
<P>
   All over my face I found tiny specks of black, the result of
flying tire rubber. The remnants of nitromethane fuel hung in the
air in a gray haze. Nitromethane is the result of a chemical
reaction between nitric acid and propane. Don't use that stuff in
your Honda.
</P>
<P>
   A little later, they had eliminations in the Funny Car division.
You expected clowns from Barnum &AMP; Bailey to tool around the track
in old VW bugs. Forget that. Funny cars go just as fast as top-fuel
cars. They have the same engines, which generate 6,000 horsepower
and they are just as loud. It's just that they look like stock
cars, and the engine is front-mounted, and the entire body lifts up
from the front.
</P>
<P>
   John Force, the Jeff Gordon of drag racing, was going against
Chuck Beal, a 56-year-old engineer who works 40 hours a week in a
think tank in San Diego. Risking his life in a funny car is Beal's
weekend hobby. He prefers that to something safer, like knitting.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas tree flashed green. The earth roared. They took
off. Right away, Force spun his tires. That problem was nothing
compared with what happened to Beal. The body of his car burst into
flame and disintegrated before everyone's startled eyes. At the
end, he was driving a convertible _ an exposed chassis and a
steering wheel, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Beal won. Don't ask me how. And afterward Beal tried to
explain the thrill of navigating all that power and speed for one
quarter of a mile. ``Stepping on the pedal,'' he said, ``is like
stepping on a stick of dynamite.''
</P>
<P>
   Sign me up.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Force described the feeling of hurtling down the
track: ``I like the car bouncing around. I like hitting the
throttle and knowing all hell can break loose. I like getting from
A to B when fire breaks out, and going through all the reactions
that are right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, who wouldn't like that, especially the part about the
burning cockpit? Oh by the way, Force refuses to breathe during the
race. Why? It's something about not inhaling flames if the car gets
torched.
</P>
<P>
   So, why are fans interested in dragsters? Sears Point doesn't
release attendance figures, but the grandstands were filled on
Sunday, spectators spilling onto the scorched hills above the
track.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say this. Americans are obsessed with speed and power _
with Roger Clemens' 100-mph heat, with Mike Tyson's right-hand
knockout punch, with Terrell Davis busting through the line for a
touchdown. But none of this approaches top-fuel drag racing, guided
missiles blasting down the track in the most direct, uncomplicated
demonstration of power and speed in sports.
</P>
<P>
   They say baseball expresses the soul of America. Maybe it does
and maybe it doesn't. But one thing is pretty obvious. You didn't
have to look far to find America's soul on Sunday. It was at Sears
Point. And it roared.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
