u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PLUTO-ART-NYT &LR;      08-09 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLUTO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH A GLASS DARKLY, GLIMPSES OF PLUTO AND TITAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 (HLW)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In new observations of the outer solar system, two telescopes in
Hawaii have seen beyond previous limits of visibility to make
intriguing discoveries about the surface composition of the planet
Pluto and Saturn's largest satellite, Titan.
</P>
<P>
   One telescope revealed the existence of the hydrocarbon ethane
on Pluto's surface. The discovery is potentially significant
because the ethane may be a remnant component of the original
interstellar gas cloud that collapsed to form the solar system 4.5
billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another telescope detected what may be liquid or frozen seas of
hydrocarbons on Titan. If these are indeed seas, they would be the
only ones known in the solar system other than those on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Pluto observations were conducted by astronomers using
Japan's new Subaru Telescope, at the summit of Mauna Kea on the
island of Hawaii. The pictures were taken with an infrared camera
designed to study the light from objects to determine their
chemical composition and other characteristics. They were among the
first pictures that clearly separated Pluto from its satellite
Charon, which are only 12,200 miles apart, so close that their
images usually appear blurred together.
</P>
<P>
   Pluto is the most distant and smallest planet of the Sun, with a
diameter of 1,413 miles. Charon (pronounced KAIR-on) was not
discovered until 1978. Its diameter of 728 miles, about half the
size of Pluto, is unusually large for a satellite to be in relation
to its planetary companion.
</P>
<P>
   The new observations not only confirmed that Pluto is covered in
frozen nitrogen, methane, and carbon monoxide; they also detected
light betraying the existence of ethane ice. Temperatures on
Pluto's surface are as low as minus 387 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement of the findings, Dr. Ian Shelton, an
astronomer and spokesman for the Subaru Telescope, said that
further analysis of the data could determine if the ethane is
primordial material from which the solar system was formed. It may
have been preserved by the extreme cold at the fringes of the
planetary system. Alternatively, the ethane may have been created
since the beginning of the solar system by the reaction of
ultraviolet sunlight on primordial methane.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, astronomers said, a study of the ethane could
add to the skimpy knowledge about physical conditions on Pluto. For
one thing, the ethane apparently does not exist as individual
grains but is dissolved instead within the much more plentiful
nitrogen ice on Pluto's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers confirmed that water ice covered much of the
satellite Charon's surface and is absent on Pluto; in fact, judging
by their distinctive light signatures, the two bodies have
completely different surface compositions. The astronomers said
this supported the hypothesis that the Pluto-Charon system formed
out of the shattered remains of a collision sometime early in the
solar system's history.
</P>
<P>
   The observations of Saturn's moon Titan were conducted at the
Keck Telescope, also on Mauna Kea, by astronomers from the
University of California at Berkeley and at Los Angeles, and at the
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, in Livermore, Calif. The
results are published in the current issue of Icarus, a journal for
planetary sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Titan is one of the largest moons, larger than the planet
Mercury, and the only body in the solar system with a nitrogen-rich
atmosphere like Earth's. A dense smog fills Titan's sky and
obscures the surface. But by taking hundreds of infrared
``snapshots'' and merging them through computer processing,
astronomers at Keck were able to map surface features 150 miles in
size.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the extremely dark regions, astronomers said, could be
vast pools of hydrocarbons. For a long time, scientists have
speculated that ethane smog could condense and rain onto Titan's
surface as a black liquid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dark material could be a sea of liquid methane, ethane or
other hydrocarbons,'' said Dr. Bruce Macintosh, a Livermore
astrophysicist. ``It's one of the darkest things in the solar
system. It could also be solid organic material.''
</P>
<P>
   Seas or not, the dark regions suggest the existence of complex
organic chemical processes on Titan that make the huge moon
resemble the pre-biotic Earth more than any other place in the
solar system, the scientists concluded. They expect more definitive
answers in 2004, when the American-European spacecraft Cassini is
supposed to reach Saturn and send a probe to the surface of Titan,
solid or liquid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
