<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brown's much-hyped Talk walks the walk
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After making a splashy debut a week ago in New York, Talk
($2.95), Tina Brown's slick new magazine, has finally made its way
to the hinterlands. The first issues arrived in Atlanta over the
weekend and quickly sold out at several newsstands. In addition to
the much-hyped Hillary Rodham Clinton interview about her husband's
sex problems, Talk is crammed with fine writing by Martin Amis, Tom
Stoppard and others, and stunning _ and sexy _ photographs of
Gwyneth Paltrow posing for her ``dream roles'' as Barbarella and as
a leather bikini-clad dominatrix. One of the most compelling
articles is Eddie Dean's account of down-and-out life in a Virginia
trailer park, which begins this way: ``My new neighbor is naked
except for shorts and a 4-foot-long python around his thick, hairy
neck.'' Yes, the magazine has been overhyped, but it looks as if
Brown has another winner, just as she did at Vanity Fair and The
New Yorker. In the end, Talk is more than just talk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rags to witches: Time ($3.50) critic Richard Zoglin traces the
history of cheapo horror flicks that made a bundle, while Newsweek
($3.50) speculates on the movie's impact on future Hollywood
projects. The verdict? Don't expect the big studios to start
turning out $35,000 films. Also of note: Former Atlanta journalist
Susan Faludi has written an insightful essay on the recent
workplace shootings in Atlanta and Pelham, Ala. The Pulitzer
Prize-winning author of ``Backlash: The Undeclared War Against
American Women'' blames such violent outbursts on men's changing
role in society. ``In an ornamental culture where worth is measured
by bicep and SUV size, by image and celebrity, men feel severed
from fellowship and a tangible craft, valued only for their stock
market portfolios.'' Faludi delves deeper into the subject in her
forthcoming book, ``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the American Man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The first 1,000 years: As we prepare for the next millennium,
U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.95) takes a look at what the world was
like in A.D. 1000. Apparently it was the best of times, it was the
worst of times. Europe was in the midst of the Dark Ages, but
Islamic civilizations enjoyed a high level of culture and
enlightenment. In daily life, canon law encouraged men to beat
their wives for their own good. Noble ladies, however, were allowed
to do the same to their servants. There was no lottery, but in the
Mississippi Valley, gamblers sometimes lost everything they owned
by betting on chunkey, a game in which participants threw spears at
a rolling stone.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Future trends: Assuming we survive Y2K, what can we expect in
the next millennium? Vibe ($3.99) took a peek in its crystal ball
to look at the people, places and things on the verge of changing
the world. Among the predictions: Philadelphia will be the next
hip-hop mecca, Starburst hard candy will be the next hot sweet
treat, stylists will use scalp stains to match your hair,
three-dimensional hologram swim goggles from Speedo will make pool
plunges more entertaining and companies will pay you to get tattoos
advertising their brands.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A smaller world: Thirty-six years ago, Lyndon Johnson said he
hoped the world would not ``narrow into a neighborhood before it
has broadened into a brotherhood.'' That was before cell phones,
the Internet and CNN. As National Geographic ($3) explains in its
August issue, the world's diverse cultures are in danger of
becoming homogenized. Nowadays it's not unusual to find men in
Shanghai who own a life-size Michael Jordan cutout or Californians
having henna designs applied to their hands. That's not necessarily
bad, says writer Erla Zwingle. ``Cultures don't become more
uniform; instead, both old and new tend to transform each other.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Changing styles: Glamour ($2.99) appears to be focusing less
on fashion and more on stories of substance. The September issue
features articles on the Norplant lawsuits and child protective
services that can virtually kidnap children and a poignant essay by
Kim Webdale, whose sister, Kendra, was pushed to her death on a New
York subway. But there's still plenty of celebrity fluff, including
the revelations that Mrs. Clinton once wanted to be an astronaut,
can swear like a sailor and was so naive in the 1970s that she
thought the tracking dogs in an Arkansas prison were inmates' pets.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
