<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN10-C     08-09 1857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teens take over television: Do you care?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're over 25 and still feel young, just wait till you get a
load of the new fall TV series. You'll feel like a major geezer.
</P>
<P>
   Popular culture, especially movies and music, has always focused
on youth. Top-selling recording artists? Kids. Biggest movie draws?
Young actors, many not actually kids themselves, who nevertheless
appeal to kids.
</P>
<P>
   Come fall, television joins the teeny-bopper brigade in a big
way. Of the 38 new series scheduled to debut on the six broadcast
networks, nearly half are about kids, teens and early
twentysomethings. The vast majority of them are specifically about
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   When ``thirtysomething'' came out a few years ago, it was a big
deal. These characters were considered young. Then came
``Friends,'' which lowered the popular age to 20s. Then they were
young; thirtysomethings were not. Now, with the success of WB hits
``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Felicity,''
there's a mad chase for teen actors and, presumably, teen viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Are teen-agers really that interesting? How many stories can
these super-young lives spawn? And is this narrow focus on teens,
the segment of the population least likely to watch TV, a good idea
business-wise for the sagging commercial networks?
</P>
<P>
   Viewers, ultimately, will decide by tuning in or not. In the
spirit of preseason optimism, however, industry experts
resoundingly answer yes, lots and you betcha to the aforementioned
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen-agers have one foot firmly planted in childhood and the
other tentatively moving toward adulthood,'' said Robert Thompson,
director of Syracuse University's Center for the Study of Popular
Television. ``That's interesting in and of itself. And you've got
this nature-vs.-culture thing going on, too, in which biology is
telling kids one thing by the age of 12 or 13 and culture is
telling them something entirely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides dealing with raging hormones, teen-agers also are in the
process of breaking away emotionally from their parents and
declaring their independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that the ultimate American story?'' Thompson said.
``Teens and revolution are very nice metaphors. There's a lot of
dramatic stuff to be milled there. These kids are romantically
available, in the prime of their physical lives, discovering
themselves intellectually. I'm surprised it
</P>
<P>
   hasn't been tapped before.''
</P>
<P>
   WB, the fledgling network that saw its ratings take off like a
comet last season, has succeeded almost exclusively with teen
programming. Joining existing WB shows will be five new teen-themed
series. Fox, which started out as a youth-oriented network and then
matured a bit, returns to its teen roots in September with five new
teen-appeal shows. Fox's only real hit last season was the
teen-populated ``That '70s Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These new teen shows are filling a void,'' said Mike Greco,
manager of broadcast research for the New York advertising agency
BBDO. ``Besides the Friday teen shows on ABC, there aren't many
shows targeting teens on the Big Three. The WB, the No. 1 network
among teens, found a niche with shows that appeal to 12- to
34-year-olds. Fox did the same thing when it started out. It's a
smart strategy. I don't think ABC and NBC are abandoning their
18-49 audience. They're just trying to capitalize on the success of
other shows.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most promising new teen shows is NBC's hourlong
comedy-drama ``Freaks and Geeks,'' about an endearing group of
friends lurking on the fringe of the in-crowd in a Midwestern high
school in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking to keep our audience young,'' said
Shelley McCrory, senior vice president of prime-time development
for NBC. ``We don't want to give our teen audience away to the
smaller networks, but we can't survive with just teen-agers. We
have to reach huge numbers for our shows to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the high school shows that were pitched to us were
too narrow. We think `Freaks and Geeks' will appeal to teens and
young adults. It's relatable, and it's funny, not heavy-handed. We
want to paint a picture of high school that's realistic and makes
you laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   The slam on ABC's much-praised ``My So-Called Life'' a few years
ago was that it was too realistic. All that teen angst was
off-putting to many adults and reminded teen-agers just how
miserable their lives really were. NBC doesn't plan to make that
mistake with ``Freaks and Geeks,'' which leans heavily toward
``Wonder Years''-style sweetness and goofiness.
</P>
<P>
   But the series also must be careful to ring true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teens do have a radar that tells them when something is not
real,'' McCrory said. ``These characters are not overly glamorous.
It's not a soap.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a thinly-veiled slap at WB's ``Dawson's Creek,''
populated by teens so gorgeous and sexy there isn't one pimple or
crooked tooth among them. But maybe we shouldn't criticize TV for
its idealized portrayals. Almost every character on television,
with the possible exception of Dennis Franz on ``NYPD Blue,'' looks
much better than people in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is a peculiarly television problem. Movie stars
aren't exactly ugly. And how many Greeks and Romans even remotely
resembled the gorgeous paintings and statues that represented them?
Probably very few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they're idealized,'' said Syracuse's Thompson. ``The
networks want people to sit down and enjoy this fantasy with these
incredible hunks and babes. But to succeed, these teen shows must
speak the way those people actually speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen lingo has permeated the larger culture for generations.
Phrases like ``far out,'' ``groovy'' and ``you know'' bubbled up
from American adolescents. It's, like, cool to talk young, ya know?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the time is ripe now for the teen invasion because network
television, which recently turned 50, is getting old. Cable is
young and fresh, but network TV is having a midlife crisis. New
shows fail at a breathtaking rate and even established hits like
``ER'' and ``Frasier'' have seen drastic audience declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 30 to 40 years of cops, doctors and lawyers, there's a
sense that TV has worn out those genres,'' Thompson said. ``We've
had so many brilliantly done legal dramas, especially in the past
decade, the question is, is there really that much to say? Sitcoms,
cop shows, lawyer shows and hospital shows are good, yeoman labor
in the field, but, really, it's all been done.''
</P>
<P>
   So here comes the teen army to save the day. Who will watch the
new shows? Teen-agers make up only a tiny segment of the TV
audience. They're too busy _ going to movies, playing video games,
renting videos, working on computers, dashing off to clubs and
sports practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teens are more fickle, and they're harder to pin down,'' said
NBC's McCrory. ``But finding young viewers is a priority because
we're looking to keep the next generation coming to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Conaway, a 13-year-old eighth-grader in Austin, Texas,
doesn't watch much TV during the week because he's busy doing
homework. Weekends don't see much TV time, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm usually out on the weekends,'' Conaway said. ``I don't
watch anything except maybe `Saturday Night Live.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Conaway, whose favorite show is the teen-less ``Simpsons,'' said
he might be more inclined to check out the new series this fall
because they're geared to teens. But he prefers comedies to
teen-angst dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Kaufman, another Austinite, a 15-year-old high school
sophomore and dedicated gymnast, said she'd be more inclined to
watch the shows with teen-agers, too _ if she had time.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the week I go to school, go to the gym and then come
home and do my homework,'' Kaufman said. ``A lot of my friends have
to be home to watch certain shows, like `Dawson's Creek,' but I
just don't have time.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers have always salivated over 20- to 30-year-old
viewers. They're on their own and spending a good chunk of the
money they've just started earning. But teen-agers? You'd think
advertisers wouldn't care about them. The younger ones don't go out
unless somebody takes them, and most of the money they have comes
from parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason advertisers want teens is because teens are
setting up their loyalties to specific brands, and they're more
inclined to try new products,'' said Chris Geraci, vice president
for national TV buying for BBDO. ``For years Hollywood has listened
to the ad community say that younger demos are important, but older
demos watch TV, so it's a challenge to put something on that young
teens will watch. When they do, it's instantly appealing to
advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers of teen-favored products like movies, music and soft
drinks, are thrilled with the coming fall season, loaded as it is
with teen shows. According to Geraci, up-front ad sales have been
especially strong, stronger than last year, in fact, despite the
drop in overall ratings last season.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the biggest segment of the audience, viewers between 30
and 50, will find much of the teen-themed programming sophomoric.
And at least one network, CBS, has declined to join the teen parade
at all. Network President Leslie Moonves has repeatedly said his
network likes young viewers but prefers going after a mass
audience. That includes ``older folks'' in the 25-54 age range. Not
a bad plan.
</P>
<P>
   CBS finished first in overall ratings last season, with popular
shows such as ``Touched by an Angel'' and ``60 Minutes'' topping
the Nielsens. NBC was second in overall viewers but had more
programs, like ``ER'' and ``Friends,'' that appeal to the young
viewers advertisers covet. CBS seemingly is alone in its pursuit of
aging baby boomers and older viewers. The network doesn't have a
single teen show on its schedule for fall.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-teen contingency thinks the same aging boomer audience
will flock to teen-themed shows that are done well.
</P>
<P>
   ``As boomers reach their 40s and 50s, maybe we should not be
surprised if they turn from thirtysomething shows to
teensomething,'' Thompson said. ``It becomes kind of a bummer to
identify with older characters. I'm not sure people in their 80s
want to watch shows about people in their 80s, especially given the
narcissistic quality of boomers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a huge group of old folks tuning in to
``Freaks and Geeks,'' but anything's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the youth trend end up? Will we have a merry band of
6- to 10-year-old kids leading the way in a couple of years? The
Big Three insist they have no grade-school ensemble shows on the
drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always gonna have cute kids on sitcoms, but in the end,
a 10- or 11-year-old just isn't very interesting, except to their
parents,'' Thompson said. ``I'd be shocked if next year we've got a
`Dawson's Creek Preschool.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: dholloway(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
