<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABA-DEATH-COX     08-09 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABA-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Human rights lawyer says symposium sends partisan message, wants
meetings cancelled
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An upcoming judicial symposium on the death penalty at
the Chateau Elan resort in Braselton, Ga. should be cancelled
because it ``lacks balance and fails to satisfy the appearance of
impartiality,'' a human rights lawyer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, Stephen
Bright, director of the Atlanta-based Southern Center for Human
Rights, said the symposium appears to be sending a partisan
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program appears to be geared almost exclusively to
restricting and expediting capital cases while ignoring some of the
more fundamental and important problems of the way in which death
is imposed and reviewed in the circuit,'' Bright said in a letter
to Chief Judge R. Lanier Anderson III of Macon.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Anderson, an appointee of President
Jimmy Carter, disputed any notion that the symposium is geared to
expedite death cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the purpose of the meeting at all,'' he said.
``Rather, the purpose is to share information on the procedures in
each court and whatever problems occur in the handling of these
cases. We want to make the overall processing of capital cases
fairer to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson noted that the symposium will consider the levels of
funding for state and federal lawyers who represent capital
defendants, among other topics.
</P>
<P>
   Bright released his letter during a panel discussion on judicial
independence at the American Bar Association's annual meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   The ``State Capital Cases Symposium'' is scheduled for Aug.
19-21. Its agenda lists numerous panel sessions, as well as a
reception and dinner on Aug. 19 and an early adjournment on Aug. 20
for ``golf and other amenities.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Supreme Courts of Alabama, Florida and Georgia _
the three states that make up the 11th Circuit _ are among the 93
invitees, as are federal judges, members of state attorneys general
offices, state prosecutors and a number of death-penalty defense
lawyers, including a lawyer from Bright's office.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda includes a session on the federal perspective led by
Judge Ed Carnes of the 11th Circuit. Judge Edith Hollan Jones of
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, will
lead another panel about capital cases in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bright criticized their leading roles, describing Carnes and
Jones as ``particularly outspoken and strident proponents'' of
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall tenor of the symposium has the appearance of an
effort to turn the state courts and the 11th Circuit into the kind
of death mills that the state and federal courts in Texas have
become,'' Bright wrote, noting that in recent years Texas courts
have upheld death sentences in cases where the defendant's lawyers
fell asleep during trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very dire and sad situation in Texas,'' said
Charles Baird, a former Texas appeals court judge and a speaker at
the ABA panel. ``It's just an assembly line of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hanlon, a Florida lawyer who heads Holland &AMP; Knight's
indigent defense team, said he was going to give Bright's letter to
Chief Justice Major Harding of the Florida Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll ask him to take it very seriously,'' said Hanlon, a
speaker at the ABA panel discussion. ``I'm deeply concerned about
this symposium. The whole tenor of its agenda appears to be
slanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
