   WITCHES-FORT HOOD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT HOOD, Texas _ In flowing capes, medieval garb or plain
black T-shirts, civilians and off-duty soldiers joined hands and
jumped a smoldering bonfire after worshipping pagan deities,
sipping homemade honey wine and consuming ears of corn that had
been left in the fire too long. ``We are a circle within a circle
with no beginning and never ending,'' intoned 60 men, women and
children encircling the blaze. ``Horned one, lover son, leaper in
the corn, deep in the mother, die and be reborn,'' they chanted to
the god Pan. These are the witches, or Wiccans, of Fort Hood, the
nation's largest military base. By BARRY SHLACHTER. Story has moved
in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRACKING LOST KIDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ How far would you go to protect your child? Bill Brown
and Dan Booker, two South Carolina businessmen and grandparents,
are betting you'd go pretty far. Far enough, maybe, to track your
child across the country. Brown and Booker's company, Grandparents
Inc., has developed a tracking system that uses global positioning
satellite (GPS) technology to find missing children anywhere in the
United States. By ALYSON WARD. Story has moved in ``a'' general
news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
