<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADER-ONLINE-COX     08-09 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADER-ONLINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home traders tend to transact less than office traders
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An estimated 6,000 people trade daily or very often in
day trading offices, while about 4.6 million people buy and sell
online from home, though relatively few do it daily, Internet
research firms say.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable statistics on the number of day traders and online
investors are hard to come by. But there's general agreement that
for people who go into day trading, they're better off at day
trading firms, which have more sophisticated technology than most
folks do at home.
</P>
<P>
   People who trade from home don't get orders executed as fast as
those in day-trading offices, because home-traders' orders have to
go through brokers. Often, that can mean home-traders miss a window
of dramatic movement, said Nancy Condon of the National Association
of Securities Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials don't know how many people lose money, or how
much in day trading. One study, by Momentum Securities, one of the
biggest day trading firms, claimed 58 percent of customers lost
money within the first three months. The average loss was $21,479,
the company said, while the 42 percent who reported making money
earned an average $36,222.
</P>
<P>
   It also said two-thirds of traders who survived a three to six
month ``learning curve'' started making money.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators are dubious. The three-month study involved only
107 traders. And it didn't say how many traders made it through the
initial three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Texas said their research suggests that at least 80
percent of customers wind up in the red.
</P>
<P>
   The average home-based investor executes fewer than 15 trades a
year. The average day trader executes dozens daily, involving an
average of 700 shares each trade. Some make hundreds of trades a
day; most traders don't hold their positions for more than seven
minutes. That speed explains why about 3 percent of day traders
account for 60 percent of the day trading volume, says Dan Burke, a
senior analyst for Gomez Advisors in Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their small size in the universe of tens of millions of
investors, online traders have considerable clout, accounting for
up to 25 percent of volume on the over-the-counter market and more
than $5.5 billion in daily transactions. And that will rise
steadily, because 15,000 new online accounts are being opened every
day. Burke estimates that will rise to 18 million by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In general, commissions are comparable although strategies are
different. Traders working in day trading offices buy and sell,
sometimes as fast their fingers can move across a keyboard. Most
home traders don't day trade, but instead buy and hold, just as
they would at a discount or full service brokerage firm, said Marc
Beauchamp of the North American Securities Administration
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would recommend that even in the age of the Internet,
investors should do what they've always done: Find good companies
in growth industries and hold for the long term. The more you
trade, studies have shown, the worse you'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing inherently crooked about day trading, he added,
``it's just very risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
