<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1015 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULF-WAR-VETS-HNS &LR;      08-09 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-WAR-VETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE'S AILMENTS ATTRIBUTED TO MYSTERIOUS GULF DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HESPERIA, Calif. _ Former Marine Brent Roberts is one of a
number of ailing Gulf War veterans facing impoverishment. Across
the country, veterans are losing jobs as disabling diseases rob
their bodies of strength, endurance and vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who served in the Persian Gulf War, has endured years
of aching muscles and joints, migraine headaches, intestinal pain,
an inability to keep food down _ among the ailments he brought home
from the 1991 war.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors can't identify the cause, but they've labeled his
illness Persian Gulf syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Once able to carry a 40-pound combat pack on 5-mile runs,
Roberts now uses a cane just to stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I went through all our savings,'' said Roberts,
who left his $60,000-per-year job as an assistant manager at Bally
of Switzerland on July 24, 1996, because he could not endure the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing left. My parents are tapped out. My in-laws
are doing everything for us now. They put us in a house they own,
so we don't have to worry about rent. If it weren't for them, we
would be homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after an eight-year fight to win disability benefits,
Roberts finally had ``awesome'' news to share with his family. The
Department of Veterans Affairs had determined he was disabled and
unable to work, a decision worth $2,220 in monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   His struggle for benefits, begun in 1991 before his health
decline began, ended when Roberts, 30, convinced Rep. Jerry Lewis,
R-Calif., to help him.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, veterans are losing jobs as disabling
diseases rob their bodies of strength, endurance and vitality:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Sacramento, a 46-year-old registered nurse was forced to
abandon a top hospital administrative post.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Oklahoma, a 31-year-old postal carrier left a job when the
joint and muscle pain that wracked his body made it impossible to
walk a 12-mile mail route.
</P>
<P>
   _ In North Carolina, a 51-year-old business owner lost his
construction company and home in foreclosure proceedings to pay his
medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how widespread the problem is, because no agency is
monitoring the plight of the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including Roberts, have filed for bankruptcy because of
mounting debts and loss of income.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts hung on to his job until he could no longer work at the
Bally store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't keep myself up without balancing on something,'' he
said. ``I was in extreme pain, even when I was completely doped up
on pain medication.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Bally, Roberts collected state disability benefits
for one year, the maximum period. His annual income plummeted to
$14,400. But the payments helped keep Roberts, his wife, Rachel,
and their infant daughter, Bailie, afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts expected a quick return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd be off work a couple months, maybe have
surgery,'' he said. ``I never dreamed it would go on this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts wasn't surprised the day he came home and his pickup
truck was missing from the driveway _ repossessed. Rachel Roberts
cried the day her Honda sedan was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Roberts had filed a claim for VA disability benefits,
designed to compensate veterans who are unable to work because of
chronic illnesses or wounds related to their military service.
</P>
<P>
   The VA provides monthly payments after ``rating'' the extent of
a veteran's disability. A veteran with a 10 percent rating gets $96
per month. At 50 percent, the sum rises to $576. A 100 percent
rating translates to $1,989.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts applied for VA benefits three times, beginning in 1991.
His claim was rejected twice because the VA said his illnesses were
not related to military service. In late 1998, the claim was
forwarded to the Board of Veteran's Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, Roberts' weight, normally 165 pounds, had dropped to
110.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't hold down meat or dairy products,'' he said. ``I
was down to skin and bones.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, a VA doctor, Lawrence Sandberg, gave a name to
Roberts' constellation of symptoms: Persian Gulf syndrome. In a
1998 follow-up letter, Sandberg wrote: ``This is a rare diagnosis
and, as you probably realize, not readily treatable.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 112,000 Gulf War veterans have been examined by VA and
Pentagon doctors. About 90 percent are sick; of those, 80 percent
have diagnosed ailments, and 20 percent have conditions that remain
undiagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, Roberts was one of 36 Gulf War veterans chosen for
a clinical study on ``Desert Storm Syndrome'' conducted by Touro
Infirmary in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federally funded study, half of the veterans received
large doses of FDA-approved antibiotics, and half received
placebos. The treatment was designed to test the Dr. Edward Hyman's
theory that a bacteria was causing the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said he was analyzing the results and would soon submit
his findings to a medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   When Hyman examined Roberts, he wrote: ``At this point, he is
disabled and completely unable to work. If he walks a short
distance, he gets tired and weak and short of breath. He walks with
a wobble.''
</P>
<P>
   At Touro, Roberts received three weeks of intravenous
antibiotics, a physically grueling treatment. When he returned
home, Roberts took medication for another 14 weeks under Hyman's
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is convinced the experimental treatment has slowed the
progress of the disease, and is the key to his future health.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't found Hyman, I would be in a wheelchair and unable
to walk,'' said Roberts, who learned about Hyman's study on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting recently at his kitchen table, Roberts showed off
souvenirs from the Gulf War: Saudi Arabian paper money, Iraqi
binoculars and framed photos with his buddies posing with M-16s and
rockets next to a jeep in the Kuwait desert.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Roberts rifled through a stack of documents he has
accumulated in his battle with the VA.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most precious mementos is a letter written by Dr.
Michael Ing, chief of the Infectious Diseases Section of the VA
Medical Center in Loma Linda, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get a doctor to be on your side through this
whole process,'' Roberts said. ``If you can't get the doctors to
understand what you're feeling and going through, you're not going
to be able to go any further with your claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Ing examined Roberts in late 1998, following evaluations by
eight different specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in excellent health before serving in the U.S. Marine
Corps during the Persian Gulf War in 1990-91,'' Ing wrote Jan. 4,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said that since service in the war, Roberts had
suffer from multiple symptoms, including rashes, weight loss,
anorexia, multiple gastrointestinal symptoms and short-term memory
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Despite extensive evaluations, the VA has ``been unable to
arrive at any other explanation for his symptoms other than his
recent service,'' Ing wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
