<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SHIFT AFTER JOHNSON DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Plan A _ in the person of Ted Johnson _ spent
Monday afternoon with his left arm opened up on a Massachusetts
General Hospital operating table, his career once again placed in
suspended animation.
</P>
<P>
   Plan B _ in the person of rookie linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer _
spent his morning, afternoon, and evening here, his career path
gone from plodding beginner to warp-speed wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   Not even two weeks into training camp, there are new rules on
the Patriots playing field. Until further notice, the 21-year-old
Katzenmoyer will plug into Johnson's spot at middle linebacker and
Tedy Bruschi, who started regularly on defense last year for the
first time, will be barking the defensive commands that formerly
rolled from Johnson's tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to make a quick turn here,'' said head coach Pete
Carroll. ``All I can tell you is, we never knew this was going to
come up, but we're just as lucky as we could be to have a guy like
Andy, who can fill in the spot _ a high-quality athlete with
ability to learn _ and we are very fortunate that we can turn to a
guy like this.''
</P>
<P>
   There really is no Plan C, of course. Veteran Marty Moore is an
insurance policy that the front office hopes remains tucked away in
the depth-chart safety deposit box. When Johnson left Saturday's
scrimmage with a torn biceps tendon, his season essentially
finished, Carroll and his staff made the instinctive reaction to
thust the middle linbacker's job on Katzenmoyer and anoint Bruschi
as the commander-in-chief of defensive chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to help Andy along,'' said Bruschi, summing up his new
life, ``and make some line calls.''
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate void is obvious to everyone, no matter how
Katzenmoyer's career might bloom or how well Bruschi might grow
into the spokesman's role. Johnson, who tore up the opposite biceps
late last year, has been the leader of the defensive pack for four
years. He led the club in tackles in '96 (115) and '97 (127) and
posted a career-best 142 last season before his biceps frayed under
the force of a Jerome Bettis dash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy's the middle of our defense,'' said Bruschi. ``He's the
heart and soul of the linebackers. Ted Johnson is our guy; it's a
huge loss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never going to replace Teddy Johnson and all the things
that he brings in one season,'' added Carroll, ``but we certainly
can play a high class of football with the guys that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Johnson going down, the highly touted Katzenmoyer, the
28th pick in this year's draft, hadn't landed himself a spot in the
starting lineup. A middle linebacker for his three years at Ohio
State, he was shifted to an outside spot here even before he signed
his contract, and immediately found himself in a duel with Bruschi
for a starter's job.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday's scrimmage, Bruschi had a clear lock on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how Andy was going to get in the lineup, to tell
you the truth,'' said Carroll. ``Going in, we were going to see how
he would fit in and where he was best suited. If he was going to
wind up starting, he was going to have to beat someone out. He's
capable of being a starter in this league for a long time. Now he's
got to learn his spot, and I think he can do a good job for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the process is the standard two-a-day drill.
Katzenmoyer, the first freshman to start at linebacker in Ohio
State history, hunkered down in drills at Bryant College. Friday
night, when the Redskins come to Foxboro Stadium, he'll have his
first taste of live NFL action. For the next month, he'll be fed a
steady diet of repetitions, teammates' advice, coaches' tactics,
and techniques. If Plan B remains Plan B for a month, he'll be out
there Sept. 12 when the Patriots face the Jets _ Tuna Bowl in
Perpetuity _ in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Is Katzenmoyer such a quick study?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have a choice,'' he said following the morning
workout. ``I'll be ready to go from square one.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knows the reality of the position, replacing Johnson, a
budding icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll be compared the whole year to Ted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson exited last season, the shift in numbers was
remarkable. In 13 games, with Johnson the center of the defense,
opposing runners managed only 87 yards per game, 3.3 yards per
carry. In the final four games, in which the Patriots went 1-3, the
defense gave up an average of 144 yards along the ground, 4.0 yards
per carry.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer can't be expected to enter with nearly the same
effectiveness as Johnson. It remains to be seen whether he can even
perform at the NFL level. He wouldn't be the first highly touted
draft pick to float into obscurity, leaving behind the empty and
echoing praise of agents, coaches, and player personnel directors.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll, ever the Californian optimist, believes he has seen
glimpses of potential greatness in Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what we know,'' said Carroll. ``He's an incredible
athlete playing the linebacker spot. I've never seen anyone as
light on his feet, around 260 pounds. He's natural. He has
instincts and feel for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   However, questions remain with regard to how Katzenmoyer's
career evolved _ some would say unraveled _ at Ohio State. After a
stellar freshman year, he was projected as a potential Top 5 pick
in the draft. His numbers improved as a sophomore, but as a junior
he too often was seen face-down on the field, the victim of failed
blitzes. As his tackles dropped, his stock fell, the questions
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The portion of his game that I think came under scrutiny last
year,'' explained Carroll, ``they ran him through the line of
scrimmage _ they did a lot blitzes _ and when you do that, it's
feast or famine. He would run through the line of scrimmage, and
sometimes get knocked upfield and sometimes it would look like he
was out of the play, and not even trying. But he was running their
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, when you attack the line of scrimmage when you are
blitzing, and people get down into your legs, you often get knocked
down, which is the common thing they talked about. You know, `He
gets cut a lot.' This is an extraordinary athlete. He won't be on
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England defense won't be the all-out blitz machine that
Katzenmoyer led at OSU. Foot speed and agility his strengths, he'll
be moving more laterally, containing and pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just won't be on the ground in the system that we play,''
said Carroll. ``He'll be playing the football, running around. I
don't care what anyone else says about him, those are the things
that we saw and that we're seeing on the practice field. We're
really happy to have him here, and I really think he's going to be
a big factor for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bruschi won't be far away, aiding Katzenmoyer in
adjusting to offenses, barking out orders for the rest of the
up-front defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the position that Tedy moves into that he's really
equipped for,'' said Carroll. ``This is really a bright, savvy
football player. He understands the game as well as a player can
understand it. Even though he's a relatively young player, this guy
has natural instincts for the game, and he will help players around
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
