A1024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIKES-MOTORS08-COX     08-09 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKES-MOTORS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Relax and enjoy biking with motorized assistance
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've been wanting to enjoy the summer months by bicycling
along bike trails, but you're not sure you're physically able to
pedal long distances and up hills, you might want to check out a
bike with an electric motor.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycles are an energy-efficient way of getting around and
adding a motor can make a bike easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   With most electrical assist bikes, the rider must pedal to get
the bike going at about five miles an hour, then he or she can
engage the rechargeable electric motor to increase the cruising
speed or to help with pedaling up hills. The rider has the option
of cutting the motor off to conserve the batteries on easy terrain
and turning it on again when the going is tougher.
</P>
<P>
   CSW Total EV (for electric vehicles) is based in Tulsa, Okla.,
and offers two lines of electric bicycles and accessories, Zap and
USPD, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Zap line features the ElectriCruisers, bikes with an
electric motor wedded to a frame with a retro look.
</P>
<P>
   ElectriCruisers have old-fashioned spring saddles, upright
handlebars and white wall tires. It comes in a model with classic
fenders and one with a lowered cross bar, the traditional ``girl's
bike'' configuration. They sell for $700 to $850.
</P>
<P>
   The Zap PowerBike looks more like a modern mountain bike. It
offers 21 speeds and can get up to 18 miles an hour. It has a range
of up to 15 miles and sells for about $900.
</P>
<P>
   The USPD Mountain Bicycle is very similar to the Zap PowerBike
and also sells for $900. The manufacturer says the Mountain Bicycle
is particularly good in off-trail situations.
</P>
<P>
   Zap and USPD also sell conversion kits to add electric motors to
existing bikes. The kits sell for $450 to $600.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are powered tricycles for about $1,000
</P>
<P>
   Both companies offer bikes specially designed for police
patrols.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
