A1032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-FLAG-NYT &LR;      08-09 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S PARLIAMENT ESTABLISHES NATIONAL FLAG AND ANTHEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a move that spoke of strongly rising nationalist
sentiment among Japan's politicians, the upper house of Parliament
voted resoundingly Monday to designate the rising-sun flag and
longtime unofficial anthem as legal symbols of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But far from a simple matter of symbols, by the time of the vote
Monday the debate had turned into a battle among politicians and
intellectuals over the very identity and direction of this country
a half century after its defeat in World War II. In the end, the
vote proved to be heavily lopsided, with the conservative governing
coalition led by Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi passing the measure,
166-71.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bills called the legislation part of an effort
to make Japan a ``normal country'' again, a land that can be openly
self-confident and proud of itself and its national symbols after
decades of international timidity and lingering shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hinomaru'' _ the rising-sun flag _ ``is a symbol of the
modernization of Japan,'' said Takashi Ito, a professor of modern
and contemporary history at the National Graduate Institute of
Policy Studies in Tokyo. ``And even if we agree that the kimigayo''
_ the anthem _ ``refers to the emperor, the emperor is now the
symbol of a Japan which lives with a democratic Constitution given
to it by the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The anthem is interpreted by many as a paean to ``His Majesty's
Reign.'' According to the Japanese Information Center, the words
are based on a poem from ``Kokin Wakashu,'' a collection from the
10th century whose author is unknown. The music was composed by a
court musician in 1880 and was first performed in 1880 on Nov. 3 to
celebrate the birthday of Emperor Meiji.
</P>
<P>
   The flag, which was banned during the American occupation after
World War II, was first widely adopted by Japanese sailor-merchants
in the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering sense of penance that hangs over Japan results in
part from the imposition of a ``peace constitution'' by the United
States, which forever prohibits Japan ``from threat or the use of
force as a means of waging war.'' It also results from the
country's need to atone _ even if mostly silently _ for the
atrocities inflicted by Japan's colonialist aggression in the early
half of the century.
</P>
<P>
   For many opponents of the legislation approved Monday, the
measures are only the opening sally in a series of dangerous
muscle-flexing initiatives to come. They see the moves as intended
to give the government both greater powers over the citizenry at
home and much more leeway in its conduct of national security
policies abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the funeral of democracy,'' Kiyomi Tsujimoto, deputy
secretary-general of the Social Democratic Party of Japan, said in
protesting the hurried debate on the bill. ``We ought to be
deciding on a new flag and anthem. But if they wanted to make the
old ones official, it should have been referred to a national
referendum.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's session, legislators also began to consider a bill
allowing the government to conduct wiretaps of suspected members of
organized crime rings. And in coming months, the Parliament is
expected to approve a bill requiring all Japanese to be assigned a
national identity number from birth.
</P>
<P>
   A recent public opinion poll by the newspaper Asahi Shimbun
shows the Japanese supporting the adoption of the flag by 59
percent to 35 percent, with a much slimmer margin, 47 percent to 45
percent, in favor of the anthem in praise of the emperor. And there
has been scarcely a murmur of protest about the measures among the
people, even as opposition politicians and some intellectuals have
railed against them.
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger milestone comes in January when Parliament is
expected to debate a revision of the constitution to give more
explicit sanction to Japan's ``collective self-defense.'' The
measure has been urged on the country by Washington, which has long
sought to secure greater military cooperation from Japan in the
event of a conflict on the Korean peninsula or elsewhere in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   This revision has long been in discussion, but received an
unexpected fillip from Japanese anxiety over the expected test
launching of a new long-range missile by North Korea in the next
few weeks. An earlier version of the missile was tested last August
and passed through Japanese airspace, helping to galvanize public
opinion in favor of stronger defense measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
