loans to customers to keep them trading. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-PROFILE (Des Moines, Iowa) _ A profile of the candidate:
When Elizabeth Dole ventured into this state in March, she was not
greeted like another mere presidential candidate but like a
superstar. But Mrs. Dole had no organizational backbone to
capitalize on the enthusiasm. And now the kleig lights have
shifted. Mrs. Dole is no longer widely viewed by the Republican
establishment as the obvious alternative should the front-runner,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, collapse. Instead of being a star,
she has faded into the chorus with the other rivals to Bush,
struggling to fight her way back. A profile of the candidate, one
of a series. By Richard L. Berke. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-SARAJEVO (Sarajevo) _ The marks of war are nearly erased
from Sarajevo. Sheets of glass have been fitted into the high
rises, and the shell holes have been plastered over. But the
Bosnian capital, which held together a mish-mash of ethnic groups
and hung on to life during almost four years of siege by the
Bosnian Serbs, has lost its sense of purpose, its direction and
many say its soul. By Chris Hedges. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND-CHANGE (Bangkok, Thailand) _ There is a battle being
fought here between the cultures of Thailand's past and its
possible future _ part of a broad shift in Asia toward more open
and democratic societies. And throughout the region, an
increasingly affluent and better-educated middle class is
challenging the paternalistic order of the past, whether in violent
upheaval in Indonesia or incremental change in Thailand. By Seth
Mydans. 1,200 words.
</P>
