<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADERSIDE-COX     08-09 1608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADERSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The fast and furious world of a day trader
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Day trader John E. Berner has at least one thing in
common with a concert pianist: his fingers must move quickly and
land in the right spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be quick,'' says Berner, a 31-year-old Atlanta day
trader whose fingers must hit the correct computer keys _ or the
mouse _ if he is to benefit from a sudden 12 1/2 cents or 25 cents
change in the price of a stock.
</P>
<P>
   He contends he perfected his manual dexterity during many hours
in video arcades as he was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first video game generation, isn't it?'' he quips.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was also the video arcade experience that prepared
him for an occupation that requires intense concentration on
another kind of screen, attached to a computer. It contains a
color-coded tableau of constantly changing numbers representing
stock prices and volumes and the ticker symbols of publicly traded
companies and brokerage accounts and numbers of trades and whether
he's ahead or behind at any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   Berner does his trading in the Atlanta office of Cornerstone
Securities, an Austin, Texas-based day trading company.
</P>
<P>
   Even for someone familiar with stock market basics, day trading
at first glance is intimidating and certainly not for the faint of
heart.
</P>
<P>
   It's definitely not a video game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to buy 500 shares of Salem Communications,'' Berner
says of a stock he has been eyeing. A click on the computer key and
it's done.
</P>
<P>
   The clock reads 10:10 a.m. as shares of the California-based
radio broadcasting company are bought for $23.62 1/2 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to keep it,'' Berner quickly adds. Buying
and holding is not the idea. Selling on a fractional price move is.
Even small profits add up at the end of the day, if there are
enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   Another click of the computer keyboard and the Salem
Communications shares disappear from one box and instantly show up
in another right next to it, ready for sale at $23.75 when a day
trader somewhere in America takes an interest in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   In this situation, the ticker symbol and the price at which
Berner offers the stock reside in a ``box'' devoted exclusively to
day traders. It's called ``the island,'' after Island ECN, an
electronic communications network that connects Berner to other day
traders.
</P>
<P>
   If he wished, he could offer the stock to securities brokers as
well, but this time he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Another trader _ who knows where? _ offers to buy the stock at
$23.75 and _ click _ Berner pounces, hitting a key that accepts the
offer and sells all 500 shares.
</P>
<P>
   The clock reads 10:10 and 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In just 10 seconds he makes a profit, minus commission. It's
small, but he made the trade mainly to demonstrate how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, Berner will do as many as 100 trades. And
they're not all winners.
</P>
<P>
   A log of Berner's trades in July on behalf of a New York-based
hedge fund shows 65 trades, almost half of which _ 31 _ were
losers. But in the end he posted a profit of $59,787.42 for the
month. Berner gets a percentage fee for the money he earns for the
hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   He also trades for his own account. His log for Aug. 4 shows 85
transactions: $624,403 in purchases and $640,108 in sales for a
gain of $15,705. From that, Berner had to deduct commissions of
$586 and $21.56 in other fees.
</P>
<P>
   For his own account, Berner specializes in arbitrage, a complex
and tricky practice involving the simultaneous purchase and sale of
two sets of shares in order to benefit from the spread between the
stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Berner's arbitrage is typically between the shares of companies
that are merging. A case in point is Metromedia Fiber Network, a
White Plains, N.Y., fiber-optic communications company that has
agreed to buy AboveNet Communications of San Jose, Calif., for
$1.37 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   An arbitrage trade using these stocks goes like this: Berner
buys 1,000 shares of AboveNet Communications for $26.31 per share
and sells short 1,000 shares of Metromedia Fiber Network at $25.50.
Shorting is the sale of borrowed shares on expectation that the
price will drop so the stock can be repurchased for a profit at the
cheaper price.
</P>
<P>
   The trick in arbitrage is to make money on the spread between
the two stocks. In this case it's $3.65, based on the merger
exchange formula of 1.175 Metromedia Fiber Network shares for every
share of AboveNet Communications.
</P>
<P>
   When the spread changes, it means something is happening to at
least one share price and maybe both. Berner may open a trade with
a wide spread he hopes will narrow, or a narrow spread he hopes
will widen. He is hoping this one will narrow, and looks for a
target spread of $3.40 per share. It may happen quickly, or it may
take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   He dare not look away from the computer screen for more than an
instant because he's watching the movements of two sets of numbers,
either of which could make or break the trade.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the spread finally hits $3.40 and he moves. He
sells AboveNet Communications at $26.31, not losing but not making
anything either. But he also buys Metromedia Fiber Network for
$25.25 and on that trade makes a profit of $250.
</P>
<P>
   Berner uses computers and software that connect directly to the
Nasdaq Stock Market via Island ECN, one of seven electronic
communications networks. There is an ECN that connects to the New
York Stock Exchange but day traders prefer the wholly automated
Nasdaq market to the Big Board's auction, or floor trading, system.
</P>
<P>
   These terminals display the same real time price quotes that
stock brokers and market makers see, but which are not available to
typical investors, even those who have on-line trading accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Berner is interested in Internet stocks, but his trading summary
also shows activity in stocks such as Coca-Cola, Delta Air Lines,
United Airlines, Union Carbide and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   He came to day trading from the securities business, and says he
has no intention of quitting any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles native and former Chicago resident, he came to
Atlanta in 1991 to work for Lehman Brothers as a stock broker. He
joined the hedge fund in 1994 and started day trading in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   He is guarded in his comments about the hedge fund, but most
such funds engage in the kind of arbitrage that Berner uses for his
own account.
</P>
<P>
   He does say his broker's background at Lehman Brothers didn't
make day trading easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, I went through the same leaning curve as
anyone else,'' says Berner. ``What set me apart was that I was very
well aware of the damage that can be done by someone who doesn't
know what he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, he joins 20 or more traders in the Buckhead
office of Cornerstone Securities .
</P>
<P>
   The environment is decidedly casual _ jeans and golf shirts are
prominent, occasionally sandals, few if any ties. Even the security
guard doesn't wear a uniform. Background noise comes from the
steady chatter of CNBC on one TV screen and CNN from another. Lunch
is brought in from a nearby bar-be-cue restaurant so the traders
can eat at their terminals.
</P>
<P>
   The traders are Cornerstone Securities clients, not employees,
and they pay commissions depending on trading activity _ 1 1/2
cents per share on volumes of more than 100,000 shares daily to 2
cents for fewer than 40,000 shares. Other activities carry a
variety of fees, including 3 cents per share for phone orders and a
$750 seat fee for traders who don't trade a minimum of 50,000
shares per month.
</P>
<P>
   According to some published reports, day traders must pay
up-front fees of at least $25,000 and as much as $75,000 to become
a day trader.
</P>
<P>
   But company spokesman Lee Maverick in Austin said Cornerstone
Securities does not have such a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerstone Securities does require its clients to take its
12-week training course, said Maverick. The training focuses on
short-term trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still zero guarantee that you will be successful at
day trading after the training,'' said Maverick.
</P>
<P>
   He said Cornerstone Securities explains the risks, not only in
the 12-week classes but in open houses and half-day seminars for
persons who have expressed an interest in day trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to scare people away,'' said Maverick. ``We lay it down
as black and white as we can. We hope it is serious people who come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Berner, too, thinks education must be emphasized for anyone
looking at day trading as a profession or a pastime.
</P>
<P>
   He also takes issue with those who regard day trading as
``nothing but gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Day trading is gambling only if you don't know what you're
doing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, day trading will probably be forever linked to
the name of Mark O. Barton, whose murder rampage in the Atlanta
offices of two other day trading companies brought the mostly
obscure practice to the public's attention. Authorities believe
that huge financial losses may have been a factor in Barton's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Barton also frightened Berner's parents.
</P>
<P>
   They were driving back to their Los Angeles home from a trip
when they heard on the radio that nine day traders had been killed
in Atlanta's Buckhead financial district. Neither the firms where
the shootings took place nor the victims were named.
</P>
<P>
   His parents stopped immediately, Berner said, and didn't stop
phoning until they reached him.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
