A1040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-HONGKONG-NYT &LR;      08-09 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HONGKONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING REJECTS VATICAN'S BID FOR PAPAL TRIP TO HONG KONG  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China has turned down efforts by the Vatican
to arrange a visit by Pope John Paul II to Hong Kong when he tours
Asia later this year, dashing hopes among Catholics in China that
ties between Rome and Beijing might improve.
</P>
<P>
   The real obstacle to the visit seems not to be the Vatican's
relationship with Taiwan so much as the wariness among Chinese
leaders about the pope's moral authority over 10 million Catholics
in China.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them worship in underground churches to evade the
Communist Party's ban on recognizing the pope as the Catholic
Church's supreme earthly authority.
</P>
<P>
   A possible visit by the pope to Hong Kong was supported by some
Catholic leaders in China, even those who swear allegiance to the
party, in the hope that it would be a first step toward warmer ties
between Rome and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's secretary of state, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, has
said in the past that Rome would gladly move away from Taiwan if it
can establish ties with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   China's foreign ministry issued a statement Monday containing
its familiar criticism of the Vatican's ties with Taiwan, which
Beijing has considered a renegade province since the Chinese civil
war ended in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, the Vatican still maintains so-called diplomatic
relations with Taiwan,'' the statement said. ``Hong Kong is a
special administrative region of China. The issues involving the
pope visiting Hong Kong are rather complicated. The Vatican is
clear on this.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong newspaper reported Monday that Chinese officials had
rebuffed inquiries from Rome made after the pope expressed interest
in visiting the territory, over which China resumed sovereignty in
1997. The newspaper, The South China Morning Post, ran an
accompanying editorial saying the decision called into question the
high degree of autonomy that Hong Kong had been promised.
</P>
<P>
   Although Beijing's foreign ministry did not say so, the two
matters excluded from Hong Kong's theoretical autonomy are foreign
affairs and defense. Relations with the pope, recognized as the
head of state of the Vatican, clearly falls under China's
jurisdiction over foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   A visit by the pope to Hong Kong would have been the first since
Pope Paul VI visited in 1970. Hong Kong has about 370,000
practicing Catholics _ 250,000 ethnic Chinese and roughly 120,000
Filipinos, most of whom work as domestic helpers.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Seung, a spokeswoman for the Catholic Diocese of Hong Kong,
said that local Catholic leaders learned several weeks ago that the
pope would not be visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officially, we have not heard any explanation from Rome at
all,'' Ms. Seung said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As excited as Hong Kong Catholics would have been by a visit by
the pope, the larger issue that looms behind any such proposal is
the question of a long-term rapprochement between Beijing and Rome,
which have had not formal diplomatic ties since the Communist Party
came to power in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   A Catholic bishop in Shanghai said in an interview with an
Italian magazine several months ago that the Vatican and China had
held secret talks about improving relations but had yet to achieve
any significant progress. The bishop, Jin Luxian, expressed a
yearning for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope represents the supreme leader of all the world's
Catholics, including those in China,'' Jin said at the time, adding
that he dreamed of seeing a papal nuncio in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   China is officially atheist and bans Christian worship outside
the ``patriotic churches'' set up under the control of the
Communist Party, which is inherently suspicious of any organization
it does not control. Many Chinese leaders are also wary of the role
that the Catholic Church played in the downfall of Communist rule
in Poland in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations in Hong Kong condemned Beijing's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong Human Rights Monitor said the move represented a
symbolic loss of freedom for Hong Kong. ``The decision that the
pope is not welcome lends a disastrous message around the world
that Hong Kong is no longer the free place that it was,'' the
organization said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
