<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMERA OFFERS E-PHOTO CAPABILITY FOR UNDER $90
</HEADLINE>
 (Weekly Digital L.A. column) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Among the cool gadgets that have come across my
desk lately _ and I get to see lots of cool gadgets _ is the JamCm
from K-B Interactive Gear.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nifty little digital camera, mostly targeted for children
or informal users who have computers and like to take snapshots. It
walks a middle ground between the pricey megapixel boxes that
deliver near-professional quality for several hundred dollars and
the cheap, low-resolution toys such as Mattel's Barbie camera that
came out last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, the JamCm works on both Macintoshes and PCs, using
that ever-so-flexible USB port and an included cable. It also comes
with a serial port and cable to connect to older PCs.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-release version I tested also came with a raft of
software, including Microsoft's Picture It! 99 and ArcSoft's Photo
Fantasy that together allow you to easily transfer shots from the
camera to the computer, where you can clean them up, dress them up
and ship them off to e-mail or the printer.
</P>
<P>
   The company was still getting its Macintosh drivers and
photo-editing software together, so I can't speak for how well it
works on those machines. But on the PC side, importing snapshots
into Picture It! was, well, a snap.
</P>
<P>
   Picture quality was solid, especially for an $89 camera. The
camera actually gives you three resolution choices, with the best a
quite respectable 640 by 480.
</P>
<P>
   The results aren't in quite the same league as traditional film,
but it's not like no-focus snapshot cameras typically provide much
greater control. And unlike those snapshot cameras, you don't have
any developing hassles.
</P>
<P>
   Once it's in the computer, you can do a lot of fun things.
</P>
<P>
   The extremely lightweight camera body is a bright yellow with
black rubber grips that protect it from rough handling. Operation
is extremely simple, boiled down to two buttons and an LCD screen.
</P>
<P>
   The only knock? It only takes eight shots before you need to
download the ``film'' to your computer, at least at the highest
resolution (you can squeeze 48 shots off at 240-by-180 resolution,
but that starts to get pretty fuzzy). But hey, you can't have
everything, at least not yet. For now, anyway, the JamCm is
slamming good fun. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
COOL TOOL OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's MP-3 music revolution has been bubbling along at
a pretty remarkable rate lately, with a new generation of portable
players coming out the next several weeks in preparation for this
Christmas gift season.
</P>
<P>
   I like these tiny, lightweight music players as much for their
potential as their reality, though they'll definitely be a lot
better with another generation or two of development behind.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, none can keep up with the toy I saw Compaq engineers
showing off at this week's Herring on Hollywood conference in
Century City.
</P>
<P>
   The Compaq player is about the size of a cassette Walkman,
making it two or three times bigger than the tiny Diamond Rio or
Creative Technologies Nomad MP-3 players.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those machines, which have only enough internal
memory to store about 30 minutes of music (with removable,
expensive flash memory cards that add another half hour each), the
Compaq player has an internal four-gigabyte hard drive that will
store up to 70 hours of tunes, about enough to drive across the
country without hearing the same song twice.
</P>
<P>
   The player probably won't be stuffing anyone's stocking this
Christmas, however. Developed by the wizards at the old Digital
Electronic Corp. research lab (now part of Compaq), it's a product
waiting for a partner.
</P>
<P>
   When Compaq does find a consumer electronics company to help
make and market the player, however, expect it to sell well. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE GAMING UNDERGROUND
</P>
<P>
   The NeoGeo Pocket Color gaming machine is actually going to be
available in the stores of half-a-dozen large chains, including K-B
Toys, Babbage's and Electronics Boutique beginning this weekend.
The list price is $69.99.
</P>
<P>
   The handheld machine, previously only available through SNK's
Internet site, has a great 16-bit color screen, analog controller
stick and decent array of titles at its debut.
</P>
<P>
   But whether it'll become a serious challenger to Nintendo's
handheld titan, the four-bit Game Boy Color (and the Game Boy's
hundreds of titles) is another thing. Check out the NeoGeo if you
get a chance, however. The technology, for a handheld, is quite
impressive, and it does include a decent of variety of games such
as PacMan. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
