<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADERMAIN-COX     08-09 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADERMAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day trading: Legitimate career or gambler's paradise?
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In another time and another place, Mark O. Barton
might just have been a high-stakes gambler who spent his days _ and
money _ at the horse track or the craps tables.
</P>
<P>
   But his addiction was a more modern one, born of the high-tech
age. He plunked down huge bets not on long-shot nags but on a
long-shot method for trading stocks, devised for bold, rich and
naive speculators. And suckers.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of a few thousand Americans to embark on a ``career''
in online trading _ in his case day trading, a financially
dangerous pursuit that may sound more legitimate than betting on
horses, but in reality is much the same.
</P>
<P>
   So were his results.
</P>
<P>
   Like most gamblers, he lost, and in a big way, squandering some
$450,000 at the two Buckhead day trading firms where he later
killed nine people.
</P>
<P>
   Whether his losses drove him to murder will never be known, but
securities regulators have been warning for months about the
financial risks in day trading, basically a get-rich-scheme in
which a handful of brokerages offer training, computers and loans
to dreamers fed up with the normal workaday world.
</P>
<P>
   But no amount of training can overcome the volatility of the
stock market, and the quick access to electronic trading
accelerates the gambling pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you were required to leave the house to be separated from
your money,'' said Stuart Vyse, a Connecticut College psychologist
who specializes in collective behavior. ``Unfortunately, day
trading on the Internet has the same psychological appeal as
playing a slot machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eric Hollander, director of the Compulsive, Impulsive and
Anxiety Disorders Program at Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New
York, said day trading is a form of pathological gambling by people
who ``crave high levels of stimulation and like to live on the
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals who have pathological gambling problems are at
increased risk for having financial difficulties, marital problems,
legal complications, job-related problems, all due to wagering
behavior,'' he said. ``When you put all that together, the rate of
suicide or aggressive behavior is extremely high in these
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton, by family, police and accounts in court documents, was
that kind of person. The man fellow traders called ``Rocket''
because of the highs he hit when his stocks soared, hit deep lows
when his picks lost, such as the time he turned to his wife last
Christmas and said, ``I've lost it all. I need help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Doyle, an analyst for Forrester Research, a Cambridge,
Mass.-based ``E commerce'' research firm, said day trading is
gambling, whether done in office settings or from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have investable net assets of a million dollars,
it's a crappy idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day trading industry would like to hold it out as a viable
career opportunity, and it's not,'' said Marc Beauchamp of the
North American Securities Administrators Association, which
represents stock regulators in every state. ``Their advertising
suggests, 'Hey, come on down, and you'll get rich.' But the
evidence we've developed suggests the majority, perhaps the vast
majority, lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   Day trading is a dangerous trend for Main Street as well as Wall
Street, because it's the day traders who're mostly responsible for
wild fluctuations in the prices of scores of Internet stocks, said
Fred Allvine, head of the Stock Market Project at Georgia Tech. And
an increase in day trading, he added, can only add fuel to the
speculative fires that have been driving the stock market at a
frenzied pace for the past few years and could eventually cause it
to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling in the market, or in the lotteries or in Las Vegas,
is all part of the get-rich-quick schemes that are are going on,''
he said. ``Gambling is prohibited in many states and not permitted
because of the destructive nature of these activities. Yet we
permit some of the public to be fooled by thinking they are going
to win the lottery or hit the jackpot through day trading.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the past few years, he added, the public seems to have
forgotten what gambling means. They're fooled by ``all the wealth
they see around them,'' he said, though much of it is illusory.
</P>
<P>
   Even the industry, which consists of about 60 firms with more
than 280 offices around the country, concedes day trading isn't for
the faint of heart. Momentum Securities, one of the firms where
Barton traded and returned to kill four people, points out in
bold-faced type in its literature that ``extreme loss'' is a
distinct possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``In your initial months of trading, you will lose money,''
conceded Jeff Eller, a spokesman for both Momentum Securities and
the Electronic Traders Association, a Houston-based trade group.
Eller maintained that some day traders make money, but allowed,
``It's not for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Not by a long shot, said Beauchamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been made out to be glamorous and all that, but in fact,
it's very risky, very stressful, very hard work,'' he said. ``It's
not fraud, but in short order you can lose a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Most day trading firms, including Momentum Securities and
All-Tech Investment Group, in whose Atlanta offices Barton killed
five people, require customers to take training courses, put up at
least $50,000, have a net worth of $100,000 or more and income from
something other than day trading, Eller said.
</P>
<P>
   In Barton's case, he listed annual income of $85,000 on his
registration form at Momentum Securities, where he went after
losing thousands at All-Tech Investment Group. He also listed
annual income of $40,000 for his wife, whom he murdered along with
his two children before taking his guns to Buckhead. Barton also
pledged that he'd taken a $5,000 training course from All-Tech
Investment Group, that he knew what he was doing and fully
understood the risks. All-Tech Investment Group declined any
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But federal and industry regulators don't think the quick-check
applications spell out the risks in strong enough terms. And by
providing computers, work space and loans, regulators say firms
like All-Tech Investment Group and Momentum Securities encourage
traders to get in over their heads. In some cases, day traders have
used retirement money or second mortgages to try to recoup losses
and pay back loans.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, advertisements tout day trading as a career, as a
glamorous lifestyle, said Mike Shokouhi, a spokesman for the
National Association of Securities Dealers, which represents
mainstream Wall Street brokers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they do have speedier links to the market than do
home-based Internet traders. That means traders can execute a deal
faster, thereby cashing in on slight but significant market
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms seem to all but guarantee profit, Beauchamp said,
though the opposite is known to be true, at least during the first
six months or so of trading. One newspaper ad asked, ``How would
you like to get rich day trading?'' An ad for one of several how-to
books asks ``Are you ready to quit your day job?''
</P>
<P>
   Barton wrote on his Momentum Securities application he'd seen an
ad while watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows the number of day traders, but Dan Burke, a senior
analyst for Gomez Advisors in Concord, Mass., puts it as high as
6,000. That's not counting 4.6 million people who have the
capability to trade daily from home via the Internet, he said,
because relatively few trade so often.
</P>
<P>
   Most professional investors, like top officials of the National
Association of Securities Dealers, the Securities Industry
Association and state regulators, share the view that day trading
is too risky to be a primary source of income.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip M. Larkins, an analyst for Atlanta's Legacy South
investment firm, said he's never day traded in 30 years in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not investing, it's just a form of very rapid-fire
speculation,'' he said. ``It's just definitely not a good idea for
the average person. We get occasional calls from clients who've
heard about day trading, and we tell them it's sheer speculation, a
gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Eric Sundquist contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
