<HEADLINE>
CHANGRA X-RAY OBSERVATORY HITS INTENDED OPERATING ORBIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA's $1.55 billion Chandra X-ray Observatory, deployed by the
shuttle Columbia last month, has successfully maneuvered into its
intended operating orbit, the space agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The final maneuvers, placing the 40-foot long space telescope in
an elongated orbit with high and low points of 86,487 miles and
5,999 miles, were conducted over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual orbit places Chandra above interference from the
Earth's Van Allen radiation belts for its observations.
</P>
<P>
   Though both the final high and low points of the orbit are lower
than pre-mission targets of 86,992 miles and 6,214 miles, they are
nonetheless within the ranges established prior to launching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything continues to go extremely well with activation of
the world's most powerful X-ray telescope,'' said Fred Wojtalik,
NASA's Chandra program manager.
</P>
<P>
   With remote commands, ground control teams may elect to open the
telescope's 7-foot-long outer door later this week, allowing X-rays
from space into the telescope for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers are in the process of activating and calibrating
Chandra's science instruments. They do not plan to take and
publicly present their first science observations until late this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia astronauts blasted off with Chandra late July 22
and deployed the telescope with its large expendable booster into
an orbit 173 miles above the Earth several hours later. Two burns
by the booster and a handful more by the telescope's internal
propulsion system over the period that followed placed the
instrument in its observation orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The X-ray observatory was developed over two decades for studies
of the most energetic processes in the universe, including black
holes, stellar explosions, galactic collisions and distant quasars.
</P>
<P>
   As the third of NASA's Great Observatories, Chandra joins the
Hubble Space Telescope and the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory. All
were intended to help astronomers explain the evolution of the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
