<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAXSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Owner of Channel 14, PaxTV ready to sell
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Paxson Communications has hired an investment banker
and may sell off a stake in its television holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The West Palm Beach, Fla.-based company said Monday it hired
Salomon Smith Barney to explore whether to merge or sell to another
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson, which airs the PaxTV network, owns 72 stations
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling last Thursday by the Federal Communications Commission
promoted Paxson's hiring of an investment banker. The agency, which
regulates the television and radio industries, decided to let
companies own two stations in the top 50 markets.
</P>
<P>
   This ruling, which lets the big television groups expand their
holdings, has made Paxson's stations valuable. Many of the stations
are in the top markets such as Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson Chairman Lowell W. Paxson said Thursday that his company
has been considering several moves with other industry interests,
including those in radio, television and cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   One possible scenario, said Paxson, was to sell up to 32 percent
of the company's stock to one of the big four networks. It would be
in exchange for a programming alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have a major station owner or a network come in ... and
have a synergistic relationship by supplying programming to one
another,'' Paxson said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson also said he would be willing to sell his entire station
group for the right price.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
