<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1049 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-2TAKES-     08-09 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 August 9, 1999  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My friend Pat Strum's daughter, Jennifer, who lives in Chicago,
was about to be married. A bridal shower was being planned for her
by her mother-in-law in Chicago, who suggested that she register
her gift preferences in a few stores there for the convenience of
guests. Her mother, who lives in Westchester, couldn't get out to
the Middle West to help her daughter choose some of the items, but
she came up with a very 90's thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in your car now, take your cell phone and drive to the
Bed, Bath and Beyond there,'' she said. ``I'll drive to the store
here and call you when I get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, mother and daughter were on the phone as they went
up and down the aisles, one in Chicago, one in Westchester,
shopping and selecting everything from pots and pans to dishes and
sheets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ELLEN R. GOLDIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Oberfield and his wife, Sharon, were walking along
Broadway when they noticed a large crowd by the curb and a taxi
stopped in the middle lane with its hazard lights blinking. The
driver was leaning out the window, screaming at a woman who was
standing in front of his cab. She, arms crossed, faced him
defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   The woman apparently had been crossing Broadway as the light
changed. The cab had almost struck her and she was not going to
move until the driver apologized. The onlookers were debating the
situation: ``She was jaywalking''; ``he almost killed her''; ``he
could at least say he was sorry''; ``you know men never
apologize,'' etc.
</P>
<P>
   The police finally arrived. The crowd speculated whether one or
the other or both would be arrested. The verdict: the driver, the
woman and the crowd were all told to move on. As she strolled off,
the woman looked back at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must all be really bored,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another street vignette:
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Morris and her husband were walking near 54th Street
and Avenue of the Americas last month when they noticed a crowd
staring at the side of a building. Possibly a man rappelling down
off the roof? Not at all. It was an enormous iguana (an estimated 3
feet long), clinging vertically to the brick face about six stories
up, basking in the sun. The police were on hand, perhaps to arrest
the iguana or perhaps to make sure that no one was injured if it
fell, but everyone seemed more amused than concerned. Finally,
after one scary moment when it seemed to lose its footing, the
iguana managed to climb back onto a ledge and into the building.
The drama ended. The audience applauded and dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   I was on a flight recently from La Guardia to Chicago and
Spokane when our very full plane was held on the ground because of
weather. After about three hours, our flight attendant announced
that there was a family of refugees from Kosovo on the flight who
did not speak English and were confused about the long delay. He
asked if anyone spoke a language they might understand; he had
tried German with no success.
</P>
<P>
   One of the passengers tried French and I tried Russian, to no
avail. We learned from their tickets that they were going to
Spokane. We realized, however, that we could not possibly explain
all the contingencies facing them, like where they would go if we
had to remain in New York or Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   I then remembered that there were several ethnic Albanians from
the former Yugoslavia who worked in my Manhattan apartment
building. I reached one of them on a cell phone, explained the
various contingencies to him and then handed the phone to the
mother. When she heard his voice explaining the situation in her
native tongue, she broke out in a smile and chatted animatedly
while the surrounding passengers cheered.
</P>
<P>
   The flight did make it to Spokane that same night, and hopefully
the family's long journey was eased by one of the many unique
aspects of New York.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _PATRICIA HEWITT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Washington, Georgina Ardalan was crossing an
intersection where construction work was taking place. The traffic
lights were in a muddle, causing havoc among the cars. She was late
for an appointment, and began weaving and dodging her way around
the vehicles. When she got to the other side, a traffic officer
screamed, ``Where you from?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you ask?'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Cause you cross the street like a New Yorker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She laughed and yelled back, ``I'll take that as a compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   After hailing a taxi on the Upper East Side on a scorching hot
and humid day, I automatically jumped into the back seat. The
windows were closed but no air was coming through the vents. Almost
immediately, the driver pulled back the partition and said ``You
better get up here, you'll suffocate back there.'' I hesitated for
only a micro-second before getting into the front seat, where the
weak air-conditioning made breathing possible.
</P>
<P>
   This is unique, I said to myself. Now what is front-seat
passenger etiquette? It wouldn't be polite to read my magazine. It
would be rude to simply stare out of the window. ``Wow, it really
is hot,'' I offered lamely. ``Yes,'' he replied, smiling and
looking straight at me. ``I just got back from visiting my family
in Trinidad. It was better weather there.''
</P>
<P>
   We went on to chat about our families and how many years we had
lived in New York (35 for me, 10 for him), the Yankees, the Mets
and the coming Senate race. I felt like I was on a date. I thanked
him when we reached my destination and almost forgot to pay the
fare as I opened the door. ``Oops, I'm sorry,'' I said, handing him
the money. ``That's O.K.,'' he said. ``It wasn't like a regular
ride, it was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I agreed. ``See you next heat wave.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _FRANNY HELLER ZORN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS THIS DIRTY? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Doc,` said the young man lying down on the couch, `You've got to
help me!
</P>
<P>
   Every night I have the same horrible dream. I'm lying in bed
when all of a sudden five drop dead gorgeous women rush in and
start tearing off my clothes.`
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatrist nodded, `And what do you do?`
</P>
<P>
   `I push them away!`
</P>
<P>
   `I see. And what can I do to help you with this?`
</P>
<P>
   The patient implored, `Please, Break my arms!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU KNOW YOU'RE IN TROUBLE WHEN... &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _A black cat crosses your path and drops dead.
</P>
<P>
   _You take an assertiveness training course and you're afraid to
tell your spouse.
</P>
<P>
   _The bride's family throws rocks instead of rice.
</P>
<P>
   _Your plants do better when you DON'T talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   All your modeling jobs are for cartoonists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAD TALK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Three boys are in the schoolyard bragging about their fathers.
The first boy says, ``My Dad scribbles a few words on a piece of
paper, he calls it a poem, they give him $50.''
</P>
<P>
   The second boy says, ``That's nothing. My Dad scribbles a few
words on a piece of paper, he calls it a song, they give him
$100.''
</P>
<P>
   The third boy says, ``I got you both beat. My Dad scribbles a
few words on a piece of paper, he calls it a sermon. And, it takes
eight people to collect all the money!''
</P>
