<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-2     08-09 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN AGAIN REPLACES PRIME MINISTER, THIS TIME WITH EX-KGB
AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also RUSSIA-PUTIN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on recent changes in Russian government is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As the race to succeed him next year threatens to slip
out of his control, Russian President Boris Yeltsin tipped his
hand, and Russia's political apple cart, by firing his prime
minister on Monday and replacing him with a former KGB officer and
loyal aide whom he named as his candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a politician who regularly uses surprise as a
weapon, Yeltsin's latest move, naming Vladimir Putin to succeed
Sergei Stepashin _ his fourth government shake-up in 17 months _
was met with more dismay than shock. Even former allies accused him
of playing politics at the expense of the increasingly fragile
authority of Russia's central government.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this smacks very much of the agony and madness of the
Kremlin, and it is all hard to explain,'' said Boris Nemtsov, a
former member of Yeltsin's team who himself was once tapped briefly
as a potential heir. ``The only explanation that comes to mind is
that Yeltsin does not believe that Stepashin can be his successor
or thinks he is unworthy of being his successor.''
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov was even more biting.
``Who will take any prime minister seriously if they are changed
like gloves?'' he asked in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although Putin, 46, quickly sought to reassure the country, and
the current cabinet that he would make no changes, news of
Stepashin's abrupt dismissal caused a drop in the value of the
Russian ruble, and knocked down prices on Russia's stock exchange,
which in recent months had been rebounding from last August's
devastating financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As Muscovites openly voiced their disgust at the Kremlin's
latest game of musical chairs, Western governments and the
International Monetary Fund _ holders of Russia's mountain of debts
_ were more cautious, saying publicly that they were certain Moscow
would keep to its promised course.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and later Putin reassured Russians that they intend to
have the nation's scheduled elections go ahead as planned. ``In one
year for the first time in the country's history the first
president of Russia will transfer power to a fresh, newly elected
president.'' Yeltsin said in a televised address to the nation.
``In any case he will be your president, respected Russians, he who
has won in honest and clean elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, a former interior minister and faithful Yeltsin
supporter who was catapulted into the prime minister's job just
three months ago, was unexpectedly called to the Kremlin early
Monday morning and told he was being fired.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before, Stepashin had flown back to Moscow from the
southern province of Dagestan where he had been dispatched to
oversee an effort by federal forces to quell an armed rebellion by
Islamic extremists. Despite the timing, few experts think that
Stepashin's handling of the flare-up of violence in the volatile
north Caucuses was the immediate reason for Yeltsin's decision to
dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   In his televised address to the nation, Yeltsin had no criticism
of Stepashin, but made it clear that the 47-year-old soft-spoken
former police officer had failed to qualify himself as a strong
presidential contender capable of keeping Yeltsin's foes at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Yeltsin praised Putin as ``the person capable of
consolidating society, the person who, basing himself on the
broadest political forces, is capable of ensuring a continuation of
reforms in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust him,'' said the president, who spoke slowly, looking
straight at the camera. ``But I also want all those who in July
2000 will come to the polling stations and make their choice to
have similar confidence in him. I think Putin will have enough time
to show his worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin on Monday also officially opened Russia's upcoming
election season, by signing a formal decree setting Dec. 19 for
regularly scheduled elections to the 450-seat lower house of the
parliament, or Duma. Presidential elections will follow in July
2000, when Yeltsin's second and final term comes to an end,
according to the Russian constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's anointment of Putin on Monday was another confirmation
that the battle over who will lead Russia into the post-Yeltsin era
is already underway. An opening shot was fired last week not by the
presidential administration, but by Moscow's ambitious Mayor Yuri
Luzhkov, and a handful of regional governors who formed an
electoral alliance in defiance of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   That alliance, which many believe will attract former Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov back into politics, ultimately as a
presidential candidate, may have triggered Yeltsin's abrupt move
Monday. For several days, Russian newspapers have speculated that
the president would cast about for ways to regain the political
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's nomination must now be confirmed by the Duma, which is
scheduled to return from vacation and take its first vote on the
new prime minister next Monday. If it votes three times against the
president's candidate, the Russian constitution says it must be
disbanded. Since a majority of parliamentary deputies don't want to
lose their seats and privileges before the December elections, most
analysts expect that Putin _ like Stepashin before him _ will be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, having been through this drill repeatedly
during the Yeltsin presidency, attempted to play down the
significance of the Russian leader's latest government shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should blow this out of proportion,'' said
James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman. ``We have focused
our policy on the policies of Russian reform and the policies of
the Russian government, not the personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, . ``We do have some experience with Mr. Putin and
have a constructive relationship with him.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
