713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   LA-PROPERTY (Los Angeles) _ Driven by a strong economy and
sizzling real estate market, property values in Los Angeles County
this year soared a combined $30 billion, or 6 percent, county
Assessor Kenneth P. Hahn reported Monday. By Douglas Haberman.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-CARDS (Los Angeles) _ The modern baseball card is in
big trouble. That's the word from many industry analysts and
Southern California dealers who say overproduction, an investment
mentality and greed are threatening a hobby that exploded into a
billion-dollar industry in the early '90s. By Jason Takenouchi.
(Will also move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
files.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-2     08-09 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
MOSCOW: with him.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putin, a former KGB agent who spent years in Germany during the
Cold War era, came to Moscow in 1996 from St. Petersburg where he
had served as first vice mayor to Mayor Anatoli Sobchak, one of the
leaders of Russia's early democratic movement. He served as
Yeltsin's deputy chief of staff and since last year as head of
Russia's internal intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kremlin, where his most recent job was secretary to the
Security Council, he has maintained a low-profile but has a
reputation as a tough administrator, whose power lies largely in
his continuing command of the domestic branch of the old KGB.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stepashin, Putin has no direct experience in electoral
politics and his cool, aloof manner sets him apart from Russia's
other more loquacious politicians. But analysts here suggest that
he was favored for the role of presidential aspirant because he may
be more ready than his predecessor to use his office to bring
Russia's powerful regional leaders in line behind the Kremlin's
election strategy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russia's governors, who hold executive power in the country's 89
regions, have become an increasingly powerful force on the national
political scene, as Moscow takes stock of their considerable
influence on voters back home, through local media, budgets and
their hold on local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, named prime minister in May after Yeltsin fired
Primakov, had tried to stay out of partisan politics, even as
Yeltsin's inner circle _ which includes his chief of staff
Aleksandr Voloshin and his youngest daughter Tatyana Dyachenko _
spent the summer picking fights with that part of the Russian media
that has cast its lot with Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   In a telling interview given to the newspaper Izvestia last
Friday, Stepashin pledged to keep a neutral role in the upcoming
election battles, which may not have been the message the Kremlin
wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even if he proves to be a more effective political player, few
observers Monday gave Putin a real chance to become a viable
presidential candidate, given the depth of popular antipathy to his
mentor. For more than a year now, Yeltsin's own popularity rating
has been in the single digits, as broad swaths of the Russian
population _ from disgruntled pensioners to disgusted entrepreneurs
_ blame him for the country's economic stagnation and rampant
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``A recommendation by Mr. Yeltsin, this is the kiss of death,''
said Leonid Dobrokhotov, an adviser to Zyuganov, the Communist
Party leader.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the universal loathing of him in the country, any
recommendation by him of any politician, even the best, points the
way to the grave,'' Dobrokhotov said. ``We are on the finishing
line of the Yeltsin regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Anatoly Chubais, a leader of a new right-wing party made up
of top liberal reformers, was quoted by one news agency source
Monday as saying that Stepashin's removal was ``a very risky step
with possible grave political consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As he demonstrated Monday, Yeltsin is still willing to wield the
considerable power vested in his office to try to turn the
political tide. As in the hard-fought election campaign of 1996, he
and his administration can still use or withhold money from the
federal budget to reward or punish wayward regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But some politicians say that even these powers have diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two, three years ago, he had these opportunities, and he used
those opportunities,'' said Vladimir Ryzhkov, a parliamentary
leader in the Our Home is Russia Party, during a television
appearance last week. ``What has happened in these days has proved
one thing: Mr. Yeltsin's power has run out. The Russian
establishment, or at least its upper layer, has turned away from
Yeltsin.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here are divided over Yeltsin's motives. Some argue
that he is intent on bequeathing to Russia, as his parting legacy,
a government and a president who are committed to completing the
country's transformation into a functioning democracy, with a
market-based economy. The rise of a Primakov-Luzhkov team, backed
by a coalition made up of Soviet-era industrial directors and some
of Russia's more autocratic governors, is seen by Yeltsin's circle
as a threat to those goals.
</P>
<P>
   But others see Yeltsin as a lame-duck politician who is
desperately struggling to guarantee his immunity, and that of his
family, once he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is in a state of panic,'' said Dobrokhotov. ``He is not
concerned about his legacy, or about Russia and its fate.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dobrokhotov said Yeltsin is afraid of ``a Ceausescu scenario,''
referring to the summary execution in December 1989 of Romania's
despised communist dictator, ``of being forced to pay the bill for
the terrible crisis he has put the country through.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as some caution, a year is a long time in Russian
politics where alliances and promises can evaporate as quickly as
they are made. And Yeltsin's renewed activity suggests that he will
do his best to win back control of political events.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Berezovsky, a prominent financier and media magnate whose
influence in the Kremlin rose after the fall of his arch-foe,
Primakov, suggested in an interview Monday with the news agency
Interfax that Yeltsin's strategy has not yet been fully laid out.
</P>
<P>
   According to Berezovsky, the dismissal of Stepashin is part of
the Kremlin's plan to ``create their own political force capable of
fighting for parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two or three weeks will clarify the reasons for this
decision,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
