<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAFRICA-$ADV15     08-09 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAFRICA-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AFRICA, A SMALL STEP TO BIGGER GAME PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 15)  
(yn) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ One of the dreams of the creators
of African game parks is to tear down national borders and let the
animals roam freely so that migration habits and grazing patterns
determine a park's boundaries. Naturally, politics gets in the way,
whether it's the politics of cartographers in the Colonial Office
during Victoria's reign, or the touchy border disputes of modern
African states.
</P>
<P>
   In April, South Africa and Botswana announced that they had
agreed to make one of those dreams come closer to reality. They
signed an agreement to jointly manage two parks contiguous to each
other, the Gemsbok National Park in Botswana and the Kalahari
Gemsbok National Park in far northwestern South Africa. The
combined park, 14,000 square miles in size (about as big as
Massachusetts, Connecticut and Rhode Island combined), will be
called the Kgalagadi Transfrontier Park (pronounced
kuh-HAHL-uh-HOD-ee, the name is an attempt to get closer than
``Kalahari'' to the original word for ``place of thirst'' used by
the San people, or Bushmen).
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two parks will still run its own affairs and build
its own tourist facilities, but they will adhere to a master plan.
They will share entrance fees equally but keep the money they earn
from renting out chalets and camp sites.
</P>
<P>
   The two parks have operated largely as one since the Botswana
park was founded in 1938 (the South African one was founded in
1931). There is no fence. The border is the dry bed of the Nossob
River, which is up to half a mile wide in some places; the road
going along it meanders back and forth between the two countries.
The parks are remote; just to drive to the entrance from
Johannesburg or Gabarone, Botswana, 400 to 600 miles, can take two
days.
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife, which includes just about everything except
elephants, giraffes and zebra, is concentrated in the Nossob and
Auob riverbeds. Between them are the rust-red Kalahari dunes. The
area gets about eight inches of rain a year and is classified as
semi-desert, but the rains are unpredictable, so the antelopes and
the predators that follow them wander great distances for water and
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Government and private groups have long envisioned cross-border
parks. Perhaps the closest is the Limpopo Valley Peace Park, which
would combine bits of the area where South Africa, Zimbabwe and
Botswana meet. South Africa is already developing a new park in the
area, the Vembe-Dongola Park. It has some land and some animals,
according to Salifou Diddo, a spokesman for the South African
National Parks, but no overnight or eating facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to acquire more farmland, encourage indigenous
vegetation and move in animals from other parks. If the park is
created, it will still be split by the Limpopo River (that ``great
gray-green greasy Limpopo'' of the Rudyard Kipling story ``How the
Elephant Got Its Trunk''), so the border will still exist.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe has parkland on its own side, but is afflicted by
severe economic problems. Its currency has plummeted in the last
two years and people are suffering from huge increases in the price
of food and gasoline, so parkland is one of the government's lowest
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The most ambitious dream is to amalgamate South Africa's crown
jewel, Kruger National Park, with the Banhine and Zinave National
Parks in Mozambique and Gonarezhou National Park in Zimbabwe into a
megapark of 36,000 square miles, bigger than Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a long way off. Mozambique is one of the poorest
countries in the world, and the relative wealth of South Africa is
as big a draw to illegal immigrants as the United States is in
Central America. There is a barbed-wire fence along the border; it
used to be electrified, with the voltage set to kill. It's switched
off now, but the military still patrols the fence.
</P>
<P>
   More ominously, some immigrants who do slip through are hunted
down by Kruger lion prides. Lions who develop a taste for human
flesh then must be killed by Kruger rangers for fear that they will
put tourists on their menu. One dissected lion was found with a
purse containing Mozambican currency in his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Mozambique is too poor to mount serious poaching patrols.
Its last rhinoceros was said to have been shot from a Cuban
helicopter during the 1980s civil war; there used to be a small
cross-border park on its southern border with South Africa, but
many elephants that went north using an old riverbed migration
route never came back, so South Africa closed the border there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd need some security that, if we took the fence down, it
wouldn't be open season on our animals,'' Diddo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
