<HEADLINE>
CAMPING ON PRINCE EDWARD I  
 NASHVILLE'S CAROUSEL  
 CD-ROM MAPS OF EUROPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Marialisa Calta's article about New Brunswick, ``In
Canada, a Resort Town by a Bay'' (June 27), implied she camped on
Prince Edward Island. Could she recommend a family campground on
the north shore? _ Karen Reidy, Trumbull, Conn.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Ms. Calta did indeed camp on Prince Edward Island and she
recommends the three Prince Edward Island National Park campgrounds
_ Cavendish, Rustico Island and Stanhope _ and Cabot Beach
Provincial Park.
</P>
<P>
   The best national park area for children is probably Stanhope,
since it is not only close to beaches but also has a playground and
open areas. Cavendish is on the beach but no fires are allowed
there, according to Marc Ampleman, a park spokesman, and Rustico
Island is more isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Green Gables Golf Course is in the park and there are tennis
courts there and at Brackley. The park stages special events _
puppet shows, games and races, and nature walks _ at various sites
all summer. Many of these are free; call (902) 894-4246 for
information.
</P>
<P>
   The rates at Stanhope and Cavendish, which are open till Sept.
26, are $11.35 to $14 a night, and at Rustico, which closes Aug.
30, $10 to $11.35, at $1.50 Canadian to the dollar. A family pass
to enter the park is $4.65 a day; individual passes are $1 to $2.
For reservations, call (800) 414-6765.
</P>
<P>
   Cabot Beach Provincial Park, in Malpeque, (902) 836-8945, has a
playground, children's programs, a baseball field, guided nature
walks and supervised swimming in Malpeque Bay. There are 10 hot
showers, laundry facilities and a campers' store at the campground,
which closes Sept. 18. Rates are $10 to $13.35.
</P>
<P>
   There are also private camping areas on the north shore. These
generally offer more amenities, like restaurants and miniature
golf. For example, Marco Polo Land is a 100-acre site on Route 13
in Cavendish, a mile from the beach. It has two heated pools, a
tennis court, a game room with pool tables and a store.
</P>
<P>
   There are five washrooms with toilets and hot and cold showers.
Of its 500 camping sites, 242 have water, electrical and sewage
hookups. These cost $14 to $17.50 plus tax for up to four people,
or $86 to $106 a week. Marco Polo Land is open till mid-October;
(800) 665-2352.
</P>
<P>
   Vacationland Travel Park at Brackley Beach, about three miles
from Brackley Bay, has 300 sites on 30 acres. All have electricity
and water hookups, and cost $14.75 a night, tax included (one night
free if you stay a week). There are 12 hot showers, a heated pool,
miniature golf and bingo. Closes mid-September; (800) 529-0066.
</P>
<P>
   More information on campgrounds and tourism in the province is
available from the Island Information Service, Post Office Box
2000, Charlottetown, Prince Edward Island, Canada C1A 7N8; (888)
734-7529; www2.gov.pe.ca. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I would like to take my family to see the carousel
designed by Red Grooms in Nashville. Do you know of any weekend
specials for hotels and air fares this fall? _ Marilyn Capaldi, New
York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. The fanciful Tennessee Fox Trot Carousel created by the
artist Red Grooms, a Nashville native, opened downtown in
Riverfront Park, Broadway at First Avenue, last November. On this
merry-go-round, rather than horses, you ride people _ hand-painted
icons out of Tennessee's past: Davy Crockett, Andrew Jackson, the
country singer Kitty Wells, the Olympic athlete Wilma Rudolph and
32 others.
</P>
<P>
   The carousel costs $2 a ride. It is open, weather permitting, 11
a.m. to 9 p.m. Monday to Saturday and noon to 6 on Sunday. For
information, contact the Nashvile Convention and Visitors Bureau,
161 Fourth Avenue North, Nashville, Tenn. 37219; (615) 259-4700,
fax (615) 254-6278; www.nashvillecvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau can book hotel rooms for Thursday to Sunday at
discounted rates of $59 to $109, according to Terry Clements, the
director of visitor development. It also offers a book of discount
coupons for attractions, dining and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Clements said that he did not know of any airline deals, but
noted that Nashville is served by Southwest Airlines, the discount
carrier, (800) 435-9792; www.southwest.com. Southwest has seven
flights a day to Nashville from Islip, N.Y., for as low as $162
round trip, so starting your trip with a 50-mile drive to Long
Island will probably save you money. Other airlines serving
Nashville include American, TWA and United. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Are there CD-ROM maps for European cities and
country routes similar to Microsoft's Streets USA? _ Joseph F.
Boyle, Nanticoke, Pa.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. It turns out that Microsoft makes such a product _ the Auto
Route Express Europe 2000 CD-ROM, covering 45 countries from
Ireland to the Urals and 1.7 million miles of roads. It allows a
traveler to plan customized trips, search for destinations and
print out maps and directions. It can also be used with a global
positioning system to determine your location.
</P>
<P>
   It requires an operating system of Windows 95 or later or
Windows NT Workstation 4.00, and minimums of 16 megabytes (32
recommended) of RAM, 85 MB of hard-disk space and a double speed
CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   For England, Scotland and Wales, you could choose Microsoft's
Auto Express Great Britain. Rob McIntosh, international products
manager for Microsoft, said the Britain program includes all
streets in every city, whereas the Europe program does not show
some small streets.
</P>
<P>
   These products, however, are also difficult to find in America,
he said. You can seek information at www.microsoft.com/uk or
(44-345) 002-000. Elstead Maps, a British mail-order company, also
carries the products, and at a discount. The list price for each is
about $95, at $1.59 to the pound, but Elstead sells them for about
$79, plus $8 shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Elstead also carries a Dutch product, the AND Route 99 World!
CD-ROM, which maps everywhere but Antarctica. It does not offer as
much detail as Auto Route Express 2000, according to Stephen
Colebrooke of Elstead, but does provide printable optimum and
alternative routes and multiple-destination trips. It is about $67.
Contact Elstead at (44-1252) 703-472, fax (44-1252) 703-971, or
www.elstead.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   The Eartha Global Explorer by Delorme of Yarmouth, Maine, (207)
846-7000, www.delorme.com, is another world atlas, showing major
highways and streets. It can plan trips by mass transit and be used
with a GPS receiver. Cost: $39.
</P>
</TEXT>
