<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PALACE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-09 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PALACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS TO RESTORE SUMMER PALACE LEADS TO DEBATES OVER THE VALUE OF
RUINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ On the northwestern outskirts of Beijing there once
existed a vast, enchanting playground of imperial halls and
gardens, artificial lakes and even a cluster of rococo palaces
designed by European Jesuits in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was sacked by British and French troops in 1860 _ to
the continuing outrage and shame of the Chinese _ the 870-acre
estate included more than a thousand bridges, re-creations of
China's finest landscapes and, for royal amusement, a make-believe
town populated by eunuchs. The emperors who had this fantasy land
built named it Yuanmingyuan _ the Garden of Perfect Brightness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been an imperial pleasure-ground that can
surpass it,'' the Emperor Qianlong wrote in 1742.
</P>
<P>
   Its plunderers agreed. ``You can scarcely imagine the beauty and
magnificence of the palaces we burnt,'' Capt. Charles Gordon of the
British army wrote after watching the orgy of looting.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the remnants of what is known in English as the Old
Summer Palace are the subject of an angry debate in Beijing, with
clashing visions of how to commemorate the past and a battle of
esthetic sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   This debate, being carried on in private meetings and in the
press, pits those who want to recreate the splendors of the former
estate as a for-profit tourist attraction against those who believe
in the quiet power of ruins. It is especially emotional because
this onetime imperial headquarters is so freighted with
nationalistic baggage.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1860, during the Second Opium War, when colonial
powers forced trade terms on China fostering the opium trade, a
British-French force razed the grounds in reprisal for China's
execution of allied prisoners. Stoked by history textbooks and
government propaganda, anger over the ransacking of the Old Summer
Palace still sizzles.
</P>
<P>
   The ruins are ``the most palpable symbol of the near-century of
national humiliation that the country experienced,'' said Geremie
R. Barme, an expert on Chinese culture at Australian National
University. More than once this spring, Chinese condemning what
they say was NATO's perfidy in the bombing of the Chinese Embassy
in Belgrade drew parallels with the fate of the Old Summer Palace.
</P>
<P>
   But today, its hallowed grounds have by universal agreement
become a monument to a different kind of national disgrace. Over
the years, large areas were taken over by farmers, squatters,
garbage dumps and more recently a State Council Guest House and a
fancy villa development. The portion salvaged in a public park
includes tacky carnival games, a dismal zoo and an island given
over to a ``Primitive People's Totem Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The only overt reminder of former glory is the sector of the
Western-style palaces, which were built of stone that survived the
conflagration. There, amid chaotic rubble, some walls have been
partly saved or restored, providing the standard backdrop for
photographs by visitors _ mostly Chinese who, as they climb through
the ruins, often shake their heads muttering phrases like ``What a
terrible thing they did'' or ``It was so beautiful, and they
destroyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   A decades-old debate over the future of the estate has flared
anew with the proposal by a well-connected real-estate developer
and fast-food king to re-create many of the palaces and landscapes
on a for-profit basis.
</P>
<P>
   The developer, Chen Liqun, 44, insists that the past would be
honored by restoring the grounds to their original splendor. He
says he would add a selection of ethnic restaurants and other
``appropriate'' activities. To help bring in tourists he might
also, he said, want to use part of the original estate for an
``Eastern Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that the Old Summer Palace will be reborn and
once again shine in the eyes of the world,'' Chen said at the
Beijing headquarters he built for his company, Million Land House
Group _ a melange of ornate European styles with a large statue of
a sword-wielding knight in shining armor out front, meant to
symbolize the entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``By rebuilding what was once lost, we can also stimulate
domestic demand and economic development,'' Chen said. He figures
that much of the original estate could be re-created for about $250
million, part of which he would put up, while the rest he would
raise by selling shares to ethnic Chinese the world over. He says
he would concentrate on the former Chinese palaces and landscapes,
leaving the European-style stone ruins alone for now.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's proposal is certainly in keeping with tradition in China,
which has a mania for building replicas or totally restoring
historical sites like the Great Wall. Wu Hung, a Chinese-born art
historian at the University of Chicago, notes that the Chinese have
generally not shared the passion of Westerners for architectural
ruins as esthetically and historically meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen's and other similar proposals have infuriated a range
of cultural historians, archeologists and architects here, who say
an ersatz theme park would debase the site's historical
significance.
</P>
<P>
   These critics say the historical and patriotic meaning of the
Old Summer Palace lies more in its destruction than in its original
form. They argue for transforming it into an outdoor museum and
much of the remaining area devoted to quiet greens and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ruins have their own esthetic validity,'' said Qin
Youguo, dean of architecture at Qinghua University in Beijing.
``These ruins were a witness to events in history. That's why they
are important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruins provide a space for contemplation, they give people time
to think,'' Qin said. He asked rhetorically whether the Venus de
Milo would be improved by re-attaching her arms.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``To restore the ruins of the Old Summer Palace would be
tantamount to faking a `beautiful' product,'' another opponent, Ye
Tingfang, a professor of literature at the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, said in a recent article. ``Ruins are also a kind
of beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   The developer, Chen, though, has the support of some historians
as well as several local officials who, among other things, may
welcome an expensive new construction project.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Chen says he is confident that the rebuilding can begin within
the next year or two. But no one seems sure which of many
overlapping government agencies has the power _ or the nerve _ to
make a binding decision. For now, all the two sides agree on is
that something must be done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
