<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON CYBER TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A MATURING SERVICE www.expedia.com
</P>
<P>
   Expedia, the travel Web site, has been revamped with additional
and improved features. The new look is bright and as clean as the
fullness of the pages allows.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new features are Fare Compare, Modify Search, and
E-Mail Itineraries. For Fare Compare, you choose from a list of
major airports and give the earliest date you might leave. The site
searches for the lowest fares Expedia's 6.3 million members have
actually paid, not just the lowest published fares, which are also
available.
</P>
<P>
   Modify Search, simply means that you can change the terms of a
search, like the departure date, at any time rather than backing up
to the page where you entered the terms. E-Mail Itineraries lets
you send your itinerary to the people who have to know what you are
up to.
</P>
<P>
   These may be minor conveniences, and there are many more
additions and upgrades, but as the Web matures, such minor
conveniences are the main things that separate one site from
another.
</P>
<P>
   You can use Expedia without being a member, although there is no
membership fee; only your name and e-mail address are required.
When booking time comes, of course, a credit card number must be
given. Expedia covers a customer's liability up to $50, where the
credit card company's protection usually kicks in, if the card is
used without authorization on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the expected travel services _ booking flights,
reserving rooms, shopping for cruises, resorts, sports _ in May,
Expedia inaugurated a separate expanded section for business
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, it connects to Mileage Miner, a service that
keeps track of frequent-traveler accounts. And early last month,
Expedia followed up with a section with ``family friendly'' travel
deals and articles with tips on keeping the kids happy, or at least
bearable, on a journey.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Expedia was formerly MSN Expedia; the name has
changed, but it remains a Microsoft company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALL THE BASICS travel.yahoo.com
</P>
<P>
   Most of the basic travel services offered by Expedia are also
available on Yahoo Travel, a dedicated travel site spun off from
the popular Yahoo search engine. You can reserve airline seats at
the lowest published fares, hotel rooms and rental cars, find deals
and link to thousands of other sites.
</P>
<P>
   You can also learn about tipping etiquette in the Third World,
dress codes in obscure destinations and where to swim with
dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Destinations can be searched by activities or by such
``Lifestyles,'' as Yahoo calls them, as Jewish, senior or
vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Travel has a chummier, chattier feel than Expedia. But the
most important factor in finding and booking trips on line is
getting comfortable with the service. Both Expedia and Yahoo Travel
are well designed.
</P>
</TEXT>
