<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 15) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the River Thames, A Place for Toasting
</P>
<P>
   For those who enjoy wine and would like to learn more of its
history, a new attraction in London, Vinopolis _ City of Wine, is
the place to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Financed by 500 private investors, the two-and-a-half-acre site
under vaulted arches at Southwark Bridge on the South Bank of the
Thames is the brainchild of the London wine merchant Duncan
Vaughn-Arbuckle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An audiocassette tour, the Wine Odyssey, takes visitors through
displays focusing on the world's winegrowing regions, starting in
Georgia, where wine was first made 7,000 years ago. Among the
tour's highlights are silver-encased vine cuttings and
8,000-year-old vessels from Georgia; a simulated ride aboard a
Vespa through the towns and countryside of Italy's wine regions,
and an elevator trimmed in bubbles that goes to a mezzanine level
devoted to Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Touch-screen computers throughout the tour provide information
on wine, including which to drink with which foods. The tour can
take up to four hours.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Wine Odyssey ends in the Grand Tasting Hall, where, included
in the admission fee of about $16, visitors can taste five premium
wines from around the world. Five more samples can be bought for
about $4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other features include the Vinopolis Vaults, where 1,000 wines,
glassware, books and other items are for sale. Four restaurants
designed by two leading London restaurateurs, Claudio Pulze and
Trevor Gulliver, will eventually open; the first, seating 70
people, opened this month.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, a permanent art gallery opens, featuring works from
the contemporary art collection of Donald Hess, who founded The
Hess Collection Winery in Napa Valley. The first exhibition will
feature 27 woodcuts and large paintings by the Swiss artist Franz
Gertsch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vinopolis _ City of Wine, 1 Bank End, London, is open daily.
Information and reservations: (44-870) 444-7777, or on the Web at
www.evinopolis.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following Shackleton, In Far More Comfort &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marine Expeditions, one of the largest operators of voyages to
the Antarctic and the Arctic, is offering a 21-day trip this fall
that retraces Sir Ernest Shackleton's foray to Antarctica in 1914. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His attempt to be the first man to lead an exploration party
across Antarctica failed when he and his crew were halted in the
Weddell Sea by the onset of a cold snap that locked their ship in
ice and they were forced to abandon it.
</P>
<P>
   The crew endured treacherous sea voyages, frostbitten crossings
of unmapped mountain ranges and months adrift on floating pack ice,
but every man who set sail survived. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Passengers on the Marine Expeditions trip will arrive in Buenos
Aires and fly to Ushuaia on the southern tip of South America.
There, they will board the 235-foot Marine Spirit and head for
Antarctica and the South Shetland Islands, Paulet Island and the
Erebus and Terror Gulf following the route of Shackleton. The ship
will stop at Elephant Island to see where Shackleton's party first
made landfall.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers will hike on the Antarctic mainland, visit whaling
stations and see majestic ice floes. Lectures will focus on the
original voyage and ongoing oceanography, glaciology and
climatology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Shackleton, Sir Ernest's cousin, will share excerpts of
the explorer's diaries. Adelie and Alice Hurley, daughters of the
original expedition's photographer, Frank Hurley, will also be on
the cruise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trip is scheduled for Nov. 23 to Dec. 13. Prices per person
in double occupancy range from $5,595 to $7,895, plus tax. Air fare
is included from New York and Miami. Information: (800) 263-9147 or
visit www.marineex.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hovering Over Alaska To Get Close to Wildlife
</P>
<P>
   Kruegers Wildife Alaskan Adventures in Soldotna, Alaska, is
offering visitors a chance to board ecologically friendly
hovercraft and explore remote, shallow rivers that are the habitats
of bears, wolves, moose, salmon and 129 species of birds.
</P>
<P>
   These vessels, which fly about eight inches above the water, are
frequently used by companies and government agencies, but they had
not been available to tourists in Alaska until various governmental
agencies approved their use this summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the Kruegers' trips, up to nine participants meet at the
Nikiski Airport in Kenai, a two-and-a-half-hour drive south of
Anchorage. There, they board a five-passenger plane and fly about a
half-hour to Blockade Glacier on the west side of the Cook Inlet,
then ride four-passenger hovercraft up and down the McArthur and
Chakachatna Rivers. The hovercraft can stop at various spots to let
passengers explore on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour trips are offered year-round, with winter
activities including cross-country skiing and snowmobiling.
</P>
<P>
   The excursion costs $349 a person, including round-trip air fare
from Nikiski Airport. Contact Kruegers Alaskan Wild Adventures,
Post Office Box 3198, Soldotna, Alaska 99669; (907) 262-2538.
</P>
<P>
   _ Melissa A. Trainer
</P>
<P>
   The Age of the Pharaohs Dawns Again at the Met
</P>
<P>
   Egypt comes to Manhattan in a big way this fall when the
Metropolitan Museum of Art presents ``Egyptian Art in the Age of
the Pyramids'' beginning Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   With 250 works borrowed from more than 30 museums in Egypt,
Europe and North America, the exhibition focuses on Dynasties 3
through 6, about 2650 B.C. to 2150 B.C. This was a time when
semidivine kings like Khufu, Khafre and Menkaure ruled and the
famous pyramids were built for them in Giza.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptures and decorative objects of the period, created for
use in the temples and tombs around the pyramids, are considered to
be the first truly great examples of Egyptian art.
</P>
<P>
   The show features a painted limestone stele from the tomb of
Wep-em-nefret, a prince and priest who lived during the reign of
Khufu (2551 to 2528 B.C.); a monumental seated statue of Hemiunu,
the probable architect of the Great Pyramid at Giza; four ``reserve
heads,'' enigmatic sculptures that are thought to be idealized
portraits of their owners; and a limestone statue of Kai, a
powerful vizier in the late-2400s B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Some objects, like four statues of an official named Nikare and
a set of five relief sculptures from the tomb of a noble named
Metjetji, are reunited for the first time since excavation in the
first half of this century. Others, like a seated statue of a dwarf
named Per-ni-ankhu carved from basalt and four limestone statuettes
of a royal acquaintance named Inty-shedu, are recent finds.
</P>
<P>
   Arranged chronologically, the exhibition incorporates recent
research that redated some objects, thus presenting them in a new
context.
</P>
<P>
   The Met is also showing tools used in the construction of the
pyramids and a facing stone from the Great Pyramid, as well as
several scale models illustrating the period's architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will remain on view until Jan. 9, then travel to
the Royal Ontario Museum in Toronto, Feb. 13 to May 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Museum of Art, is open daily except Monday.
Suggested admission is $10. Information: (212) 535-7710 or on the
Web at www.metmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith H. Dobrzynski
</P>
</TEXT>
