<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROJECTED BUDGET SURPLUSES A MIRAGE, GROUP SAYS
 &HT;    410&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton and congressional Republicans
face off over how to spend the projected budget surplus, a
Washington research group said Monday there may be little, or no,
extra money to haggle over.
</P>
<P>
   As things look now, the federal budget is likely to remain about
$20 billion in the red next year, the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities estimated.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a $34 billion swing from the $14 billion surplus
the Congressional Budget Office projects, and a $25 billion shift
from the White House estimates of a $5 billion surplus for the next
budget year.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, it means the 10-year, $1-trillion surplus
that the White House and congressional Republicans are battling
over how to spend may never materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the trillion-dollar surplus is not real,'' said Robert
Greenstein, executive director of the budget center.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he said, is that rosy budget projections assume
that spending limits agreed upon in 1997 will be met. To hit those
targets, Greenstein said, federal spending will have to be cut a
whopping $775 billion over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Greenstein said, that's wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party has the stomach for deep cuts,'' Greenstein said
in a telephone interview. ``The notion of $775 billion over 10
years in cuts is utterly unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, he said, Republicans and Democrats might be expected to
hold future spending at this year's levels, plus a slight annual
increase to keep up with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of discipline, combined with continued economic growth
topping 2 percent a year, would result in perhaps $112 billion in
federal budget surpluses over the coming 10 years _ just over
one-tenth of the $1 trillion level projected by the White House and
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans want to give most of that _ $792 billion _ back
to taxpayers in the form of a tax cut. Clinton has said he'll go
along with a tax cut of no more than $300 billion, though he's
signaled a willingness to compromise at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   But that debate misses the point, said Greenstein, because the
surplus is, so far, ``a mirage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It only materializes if Congress and the White House make
decisions they have not yet made to cut programs they have not yet
cut,'' said Greenstein, who said his center plans to publish a
report on the issue later this week. ``The evidence, it gets
clearer every day, is that these cuts aren't going to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the 1997 balanced budget agreement, Congress
is required by law to remain within certain spending ceilings, or
caps, in most areas of discretionary spending. That excludes
mandatory payments such as Social Security, Medicare and other
``entitlement'' programs guaranteed by law.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting those caps, said Greenstein, will require cuts amounting
to an average $78 billion a year over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't likely to happen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the partisan squabbling over the budget for fiscal 2000,
which begins Oct. 1, Greenstein said that budget ``gimmicks'' are
being used by both parties to give the appearance of a surplus when
none is likely to exist.
</P>
<P>
   For example, congressional budgeteers have labeled as
``emergency'' spending _ exempt from the statutory budget caps _
$11 billion worth of planned spending that Greenstein said should
be part of the regular budget. The money is going to fund the 2000
census and farm subsidies, neither of which are surprises.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, he said, Congress is low-balling spending in
several key areas _ defense and transportation among them _ that
the Congressional Budget Office estimates will actually cost
taxpayers $14 billion more than politicians now claim.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in an estimated $8 billion in revenues forgone by
Republican-proposed changes in taxes and fees, said Greenstein, and
a few other variances, and the meager surplus being projected for
next year turns into a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
