<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-COPS-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        IT'S TOO EXPENSIVE TO HIRE MORE COPS UNDER CLINTON PLAN,
MAYOR DECIDES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 9, -- Philadelphia can't afford to participate
again in President Clinton's program to put more police officers on
the street, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Ed Rendell has decided he won't apply for assistance under
Clinton's Community Oriented Policing Services (COPS) matching
grant program because it would cost the city too much to pay its
portion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor feels it won't be financially possible to hire any
more officers under that program,'' said. Lt. Susan Slawson, a
spokeswoman for the Philadelphia police department. ``Our budget
just doesn't allow for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's cost for the 753 officers already hired under the
program since 1995 will reach $44 million a year by 2002, when the
federal assistance runs out. Under the block grant program, the
costs to local police departments over time rise from 25 percent to
100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a significant chunk of money,'' said Rendell's
spokesman Kevin Feeley. ``It's a major concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the city's police department budget has grown almost
30 percent from $299.9 million to $388 million in 2000, Feeley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we have taken full advantage of the program,''
Feeley said. ``At the moment, the budget doesn't call for us to ask
for more federal help. It is a terrific partnership, just not one
we can afford right now or at least in the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Clinton's program reached its goal of adding 100,000 new
officers to the street. But the funding was scheduled to run out in
2000. The program offers block grants that pay up to 75 percent of
the cost of new officers' salaries and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Clinton proposed continuing and expanding the COPS
program by putting 30,000 to 50,000 more community policing
officers to the beat over the next five years -- at a cost of $600
million.
</P>
<P>
   Since Philadelphia isn't reapplying for grant money, it won't be
impacted by Congress' recent moves to cut back funding for the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as part of the annual budget battle, the House
proposed $268 million for the program. But the Senate asked for
$495 million in its version of the funding. Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-DE, has said he plans to introduce a bill that reauthorizes and
fully funds the President's request for hiring 50,000 more
officers.
</P>
<P>
   A conference committee will work out the differences in the
proposals when Congress returns in September.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has threatened to veto a bill that cuts the
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
