<SLUG> BC-HINDU-PRIEST-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAIL SET FOR HINDU PRIEST IN SEX CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn.: Ark.) 
 
By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Bail for a Hindu priest was set at $50,000 Monday on a
charge that surfaced after he was convicted and sentenced to
probation in June for the sexual assault of a Little Rock, Ark.,
woman.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Ted Poe set the bail at the request of
defense attorneys for Bhogeshwernand Sharma, 37. He must also post
an additional $10,000 bail before he can be released from jail
while appealing his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Sharma was still in custody late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma was placed on 10 years probation June 23 for the April 3,
1998, sexual assault of the 21-year-old Arkansas woman, which took
place at his Harris County home. As part of that probation, Poe
ordered him to serve 180 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   That woman said Sharma assaulted her when she and her mother
came to Houston to visit Sharma and his family. She said he bullied
her into sex under the pretext that it was a religious ritual to
``cleanse her womb.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman's mother and aunt testified that Sharma did the same
thing to them in Arkansas in September 1997. Sharma has not been
charged there, but the two women told their stories to jurors in
the 21-year-old's case in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the verdict in Sharma's case was announced,
prosecutors filed a new sexual assault charge against him.
</P>
<P>
   That charge alleges he sexually assaulted a 20-year-old Hindu
woman Jan. 6 in Houston _ days before he was charged with the April
1998 assault _ using the same ploy.
</P>
<P>
   Poe initially denied Sharma bail on the new charge, which meant
that once he had served notice of appeal in the case involving the
Arkansas woman he would not be credited for the 180 days in jail he
was serving as part of the probation.
</P>
<P>
   But his defense lawyers recently filed a lengthy motion seeking
bail. Poe, who had previously promised to review Sharma's bond
status, granted it.
</P>
<P>
   If Sharma makes bail, Poe said he must report to the court once
a week, wear an electronic monitor, surrender his passport and not
go to a passport office or airport. He cannot leave his house to
work unless his employment is verified, and he can't leave Harris
County, which includes most of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The travel and passport restrictions were imposed, in part,
because authorities say they believe Sharma tried to flee the
country after he was originally charged.
</P>
<P>
   If he is freed, Sharma will have to return to jail to serve the
180 days if his appeal fails, or if he is convicted and sentenced
to jail time on the new charge.
</P>
<P>
   The case involving the Houston woman has not been presented to a
grand jury yet. Prosecutors say they are waiting on physical
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
