A1087 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-SARAJEVO-ART-1     08-09 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-SARAJEVO-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SARAJEVO, THE LINGERING DESPAIR OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ The marks of war are nearly
erased from Sarajevo. Sheets of glass have been fitted into the
high rises and the shell holes have been plastered over.
</P>
<P>
   The newly painted trolleys rumble nosily down the tracks of the
central boulevard Zmaja od Bosne, known during the war as Snipers
Alley. Water, a commodity once so precious that mothers dashed
under artillery fire to water trucks, gushes miraculously from the
taps.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bosnian capital, which held together a blend of Muslims,
Croats and Serbs, and hung on to life during almost four years of
siege by the Bosnian Serbs, has lost its sense of purpose, its
direction, and many say its soul. The smooth, plaster facades of
apartment blocks, painted purple, red, blue and yellow, shelter
people who, for the most part, survive on the beneficence of
others. Less than 20 percent of the inhabitants are native to the
city. The $5.1 billion international reconstruction effort, which
has physically mended Sarajevo, masks a despair that will take a
generation to vanquish.
</P>
<P>
   Men, out of work, often wounded physically or emotionally, waste
hours in dingy coffee shops. The young gather in the lines for
visas outside foreign embassies. At night they meet in jammed,
smoky clubs like Fis or The Stage where they can buy marijuana,
ecstasy and heroin. An army of war invalids lies trapped indoors.
Most of them lack proper medical attention, and many lie alone in
rooms, tended by elderly parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is inside,'' said an angry 70-year-old man, who would
not give his name as he stood outside his small house fitting new
aluminum drainpipes to the roof. ``He can't get up. Every night my
wife has to go in and turn him over so he can go to the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands in the city, where half the work force is jobless,
live in apartments that belong to someone else, someone who lives
across the ethnic divide, still a universe away in this partitioned
country. There remains a collective exhaustion and bewilderment
that makes routine life daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never again be able to live such a strong, horrible and
wonderful life,'' said Boba Lizdek, 32, a book translator. ``My
world is no longer homogeneous. It is as if I see life through
pieces of a mirror that lies in fragments.''
</P>
<P>
   The suburb of Dobrinja, built as the athletes' village for the
1984 winter Olympics, was on the front line during the war, which
began in April 1992 when Serbian forces attacked the city and ended
in 1995 with the Dayton peace agreement. Sections of Dobrinja are
in ruins, the walls and roofs gone, the bricks and cement chewed up
by shell and bullet holes. There are crude grave markers poking up
at odd angles from tiny, overgrown parks and lonely patches of
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The renovated buildings, often next to the gutted remains, gleam
with spotless white plaster and terra cotta tiled roofs. The
balconies hold boxes of carnations. The streets are quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Murdija Badzic, 51, lives in a small second-floor apartment she
and her husband rebuilt for $10,000 a year ago. It is clean, with
new carpets, a semicircular blue sofa in the living room and
freshly painted walls.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1992 Serbian troops occupied this part of the city,
herding Mrs. Badzic and four of her eight children to a prison
camp. She was forced to walk barefoot. In that instant all the
mementos of her life, her photos, the children's favorite toys, the
wedding gifts and the collection of trinkets that remind couples of
the passage of time, vanished. The two-room apartment holds nothing
of the old life. The only photo on the wall is of her eldest son,
Husein, a soldier killed in the war.
</P>
<P>
   The couple live with their remaining two sons. The young men,
unemployed since the end of the war, have applied to emigrate to
the United States. When Mrs. Badzic spoke of the war, nervously
taking long drags on her cigarette, her youngest son, Aladin, 24,
abruptly left the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive him,'' she said. ``He cannot talk about the war. He
cannot hear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian soldiers during the two-week detention threatened
Aladin, who was 16, with mock executions. He was severely beaten.
He did not speak for two months following his release from the
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The young man, darkened to a chocolate brown after days on the
Croatian coast, had long hair, a silver bracelet and a Volkswagen
parked in front of the house. As his mother, her eyes wet, spoke,
he gunned his car and screeched off into the city center.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the siege he went to the morgue to pick up his elder
brother,'' she said. ``He came home and gave me a tranquilizer and
a packet of cigarettes. He told me what happened. I thought I would
not live another 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drop a fork I jump,'' she said. ``Any noise makes me
fearful. We have two balconies on our apartment, but I cannot sit
on the one that faces the airport, the one that faces where the
Serbs had their guns. I still cannot look.''
</P>
<P>
   In the empty street below, Huso Kovac, 58, swung himself forward
with the help of hand-held aluminum crutches. He said he dislikes
spending days in his apartment, which previously belonged to a
Serb. He moves laboriously about the neighborhood, resting at times
on the cement walls and staring at the road.
</P>
<P>
   Kovac worked before the war in Sutjeska, the national park that
was the site of one of the most famous Partisan battles in World
War II. When he speaks of the yearly anniversaries of the battle,
which always saw the arrival of Tito, his eyes light up. It is the
only time he smiles.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his leg in 1993 as he and his Muslim neighbors fled from
Sutjeska over Mt. Igman to Sarajevo. He receives a pension of $100
a month. His only son died in the war. His daughter's husband was
also killed. She cares for their two small children alone on her
widow's pension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust anyone anymore,'' he said. ``This is what the
war has taught me, not to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   He shifts his hands to grip the handles and moves away.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The only Serbian enclave in the city is a rim of forlorn
buildings at the edge of Dobrinja. These buildings were not handed
over to the Muslim-led government under the Dayton peace agreement.
The wartime Bosnian Serb leaders, none of whom live here, have
christened the neighborhood the ``Serb Sarajevo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go into the city to buy something, but I would never
stop to have a coffee,'' said Dalibor Bugarin, a 21-year-old Serb,
as a helicopter passed overhead. ``I do not feel comfortable. We
lost our house in Sarajevo and will never get it back. We just want
to get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   But even for those minorities in the city, where more than 90
percent of the 350,000 people are Muslim, life is a constant battle
to abide by the politically correct version of the war. Nearly all
Croats and Serbs who once lived here, and who made up half of the
city's population, lost their apartments. Despite international
pressure, few have been able to return home. Mile Sadzak, 37, who
has a doctorate in economics, is unemployed. The city, where he was
born, is filled, he said, with outsiders, those who fled here from
villages razed by the Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not a member of the ruling party you do not work,''
he said. ``There are thousands of us who walk the streets and do
nothing. The intellectuals have been pushed out of the new
nationalist system. I miss my friends. I miss the old city. I have
lost confidence. When we speak together we must think about what we
will say. Croats will only go to Croat doctors. Muslims will only
go to Muslim doctors. If a few of us Croats are together and a
Muslim friend comes over we fall silent. The mood changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lizdek sat in the late afternoon with her mother, Radmila,
in their small apartment. Her mother, a Serb, lost her parents and
four of her six brothers and sisters in World War II, the victims
of Muslim soldiers allied with the fascist Ustashe forces. As a
12-year-old girl, separated from her family in 1942, she joined
Tito's First Proletarian Brigade. She moved for three years through
the mountains in the fight against the Germans, affectionately
nicknamed ``Mala,'' or ``little girl,'' by the Communist
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lizdek, 70, opened a book that held two dried flowers,
given to her daughter Boba by Tito and his wife, Jovanka, at the
1973 anniversary of Sutjeska. ``We were walking in a long column in
1942 when I saw a woman from my village,'' she said. ``She told me
my mother and brothers had been killed. I started to weep. The
column halted and the commander Moshe Pijade galloped over on his
horse. He asked what had happened. They told him Radmila's mother
and brothers were dead. He put me on the horse and told me to stop
crying. He said the proletariat does not cry; it sings. We began to
sing the Partisan song `Through the Forests and the Mountains.' The
whole column began to sing. This is how I survived the death of my
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   But the heroics and romance of the last war, so much a part of
her daughter's life, have been extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived through two wars,'' said Ms. Lizdek, ``the virtual war
explained to me by my mother and the real war. I felt my mother's
war deeply as a little girl. I heard the idealized fiction of the
life before the war, the gardens, flowers, fruits of my
grandfather's home. War seemed a normal part of my life. ``I was
prepared for war. But I am fragile now. I did not need this
experience. My mother did not need this experience. She did not
need to lose her family. I only realize this now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
