<HEADLINE>
BC ALUMNUS GIVES $5M TO SUPPORT RETREAT PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The son of devoutly religious parents, John A. McNeice
Jr. subscribes to the biblical adage: ``To whom much has been
given, much is expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old retired CEO of the Colonial Group made a fortune
in the mutual fund industry, and has spent much of his time giving
his money away _ a good portion of it going to Jesuit education and
Catholic charities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he has decided to make an extraordinary gift to his alma
mata, Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   The Jesuit university announced Monday that McNeice had donated
$5 million to the school _ a gift that is being described as the
nation's largest single endowment for student spirituality and
volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McNeice has done so much for Jesuit education and
Catholic causes,'' said BC President Rev. William P. Leahy.
``Boston College is indebted to him for this wonderful gift, which
will enable future generations of leaders to develop their
God-given talents and use them in the service of others.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift, which will provide support for BC's volunteer service
and student religious retreat programs, is given at a time when the
interest in spirituality and volunteerism is growing at secular and
religious colleges around the country. Thousands of students are
looking beyond books, sports, and traditional extracurriculars for
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   At BC, the popularity of volunteer projects and spiritual
retreats has outpaced the number of programs. Each year, 1,200
students give more than 80,000 hours in volunteer service programs
ranging from homeless shelters in Boston to poor villages in
Central America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   On the spiritual front, nearly 1,700 students take part in
retreat and spiritual formation activities sponsored by BC's
chaplain's office. The most popular of these are the Kairos
Retreats, student-led weekend gatherings, where younger students
meet in groups with upperclassmen to discuss the challenges of the
quest for spirituality in a busy college setting and an
increasingly secular world.
</P>
<P>
   McNeice, a 1954 graduate of BC and a member of the BC board of
trustees, said he was impressed by the breadth and quality of
volunteer programs and retreat offerings at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Jesuit tradition to form men and women for all
people,'' McNeice said. ``I was brought up with a Jesuit education
and this struck me as a way that I could make a contribution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
