<SLUG> BC-BOSCOLL-DEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC ACADEMIC VP AND FACULTY DEAN RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A top Boston College official, David R. Burgess,
resigned Monday, citing a desire to pursue teaching and research.
</P>
<P>
   The college announced the unexpected resignation just a year
after Burgess assumed the post of academic vice president and dean
of faculties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case where it was just decided by David and the BC
administration that this would be the best move for him,'' said
Jack Dunn, a college spokesman. ``I've spoken with David and he
seemed at peace with the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgess will be succeeded by John J. Neuhauser, the dean of BC's
Wallace E. Carroll School of Management.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to BC, Burgess had served as a professor and
chairman in the Department of Biological Sciences at the University
of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess declined to comment, but a college official said he had
expressed a desire to focus his attention on his chief love, cell
biology. He plans eventually to return to the classroom as a
professor at BC, according to college officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Burgess brought fresh perspectives to Boston College
during his tenure as academic vice president,'' said President
William P. Leahy in a prepared statement. ``I thank him for the
time and energy he devoted to enhancing all aspects of
undergraduate, graduate, and professional education on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuhauser, who has been at BC since 1969, became dean of the
Carroll School of Management in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is highly respected by students, faculty, and his fellow
deans,'' said Leahy. ``I am confident that Jack's experience,
commitment, and knowledge of BC will enable him to provide strong
academic leadership for our University as we move into the next
millennium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
