u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMC-DATAGEN-BOS &LR;      08-09 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMC-DATAGEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1B EMC-DATA GENERAL DEAL UNITES STORAGE TECHNOLOGIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Ruettgers is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMC Corp. has agreed to buy Data General Corp. for stock worth
about $1.05 billion, expanding the reach of the computer storage
giant while ushering out one of the most storied companies of the
Massachusetts technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   Data Generalwas once a leading maker of minicomputers but failed
to capitalize on the rapid growth of the personal computer market.
</P>
<P>
   EMC, meanwhile, has capitalized on the booming demand for
computerized information-storage systems and last year sold nearly
$4 billion worth of products and services, compared to Data
General's total sales of $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   EMC said it will use Data General's line of storage products,
known as Clariion, to supplement systems selling for between
$50,000 to $100,000, which are aimed at small- to mid-sized
business customers.
</P>
<P>
   The deal values Data General's shares at 41 percent above their
closing price on Friday, but EMC chief executive Michael Ruettgers
said the premium is justified by the new products jis company will
now be able to offer its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we looked at this market it became clear that we lacked a
product that matched what our customers wanted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some layoffs are likely to result from the purchase, EMC said,
perhaps from among Data General's work force. Data General, based
in Westborough, Mass., employs 5,000 workers, 1,800 of them based
in Westborough and Southborough.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruettgers noted that overall demand for computer storage
systems continues to grow, adding that ``I don't think you'll see
significant layoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers also said that EMC, based in Hopkinton, Mass., expects
to hire 1,500 people soon, mainly in Massachusetts. EMC now employs
11,200 worldwide, including 4,600 in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Data General represents the final chapter for one of
the best-known technology companies in Massachusetts. Its rise,
along with that of Wang Global and Digital Equipment Corp., did
much to build the reputation of Route 128 as a major technology
center. The effort of a group of Data General engineers to build a
super-minicomputer was the subject of a 1981 book by Tracy Kidder,
``The Soul of a New Machine,'' which won the Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   But Data General had trouble translating its technical expertise
into growth. Its sales of $1.46 billion last year weren't much
greater than than its 1989 sales of $1.31 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock trades at just a fraction of its high of 76, reached
on Sept. 30, 1983, and it lost hundreds of millions of dollars as
it updated its server and storage lines.
</P>
<P>
   Data General's sale comes just three months after the company
announced plans to spend $100 million to hire 450 new sales and
marketing employees, a big push it said would pump up Clariion
sales.
</P>
<P>
   However, at a press conference Monday, Data General chief
executive Ronald Skates said even that effort would not have
brought sufficient product to market to keep up competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Without the support of EMC's larger sales force, Skates said,
``we just weren't going to get there fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Skates said he will remain with EMC to help advise during the
transition but said he hasn't decided whether he will continue
after the acquisition is completed later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boards of both companies approved the agreement over the
weekend. The purchase still requires approvals from regulators and
from Data General shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, EMC will issue 0.3262 shares
of its stock for each of Data General's 56.7 million total shares.
Under that ratio, each Data General share would be valued $18.59
based on EMC's closing price Monday. Shares in EMC fell 3 points to
close at 57 in New York Stock Exchange trading. Shares in Data
General rose 4 1/4 to close at 17 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   EMC will also assume about $212 million in Data General debt,
but said that will be offset by a greater amount of cash on Data
General's books. EMC will take an unspecified charge in the fourth
quarter related to the acquisition, which it said will begin to add
to earnings in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also gives EMC control over Data General's Aviion line
of server computers, which accounted for an estimated $560 million
of Data General sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts questioned whether storage-specialist EMC could
operate the server unit effectively, but EMC pledged to run it for
at least two years under the terms of the deal. Ruettgers said the
company didn't plan on reselling the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts who follow the company said they approved of the
terms of the deal, agreeing that it would allow EMC to offer
cheaper, mid-range products to customers lacking the resources to
buy its systems.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. managing director Steven Milunovich said the
deal would have the added benefit of keeping Data General out of
the hands of EMC competitors such as Hitachi or Hewlett-Packard Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a smart move strategically, and defensively,'' Milunovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. analyst Chris Ely also said the agreement
made sense. ``If they're light in one area it's low- to mid-range
systems,'' Ely said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of opportunity, particularly if they can take
the software they sell with large systems and adopt it for the
smaller ones'' made by Data General, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of a sale have swirled around Data General for years, but
Skates and Ruettgers said they didn't begin speaking in earnest
until late May, after Data General announced its sales force
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to sell the company he headed for ten years, Skates
said he felt ``a certain poignancy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
