<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-PROFILE-ART-2TAK     08-09 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. DOLE, DESPITE SLOW START, BELIEVES SHE CAN STILL TOPPLE BUSH
BANDWAGON
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Iowa, N.H., Ohio, Texas, Utah)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ When Elizabeth Dole ventured into Iowa in
February, she was not greeted like another mere presidential
candidate but like a superstar. Television cameras trailed her
every move. In nearby Ames, she drew an unheard of outpouring: more
than 2,000 Iowans at one event, pressing to get close to the first
woman to wage a potent bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Dole had no organizational backbone to capitalize on
the enthusiasm. There were no campaign aides at the events to take
down the names of potential supporters _ a fundamental organizing
tool in this state. There were no envelopes for people to send in
donations. And there was no follow up; weeks passed before Mrs.
Dole delivered a detailed policy speech or hired a finance director
to solicit contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Now the klieg lights have shifted. Mrs. Dole is no longer widely
viewed by the Republican establishment as the obvious alternative
should the front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, collapse.
Instead of being a star, she has faded into the chorus with the
other rivals to Bush, struggling to fight her way back. Monday, on
a return visit to Ames, Mrs. Dole drew 70 people at one event and
150 at another _ respectable but hardly record crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to boil down to a race between Bush and me,''
Mrs. Dole said in an interview. ``Every single poll has me beating
Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Brushing asides queries about her campaign's languid start, she
added forcefully, ``I'm not going to be distracted by anything, the
kinds of questions you're asking, because that doesn't distract me.
I'm running my effort. And they can run theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous measures of how Mrs. Dole has lost ground:
Polls in the pivotal states of Iowa and New Hampshire show that
Mrs. Dole, who once registered a distant but unmistakable second
place to Bush, has slipped. Her fund-raising has been sluggish. She
has not captured many weighty endorsements. And Mrs. Dole's
endeavor to persuade Republicans of her viability suffered a
further setback in May when her husband, Bob Dole, the party's
nominee in 1996, questioned in an interview whether Mrs. Dole would
even stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   When Republican strategists are asked about the state of the
Dole campaign, they invariably respond with two words: missed
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a lot of excitement early on but she was a little slow
to capitalize on it so that when Bush got in he went from no
organization to a great one overnight,'' said Steve Duprey,
chairman of the New Hampshire Republican Party. ``She had a real
opportunity from February to May before Bush got here. For some
reason it's taken her longer to get the organizational apparatus
cranked up. I think the level of interest, at least in New
Hampshire, initially overwhelmed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is far too early to dismiss Mrs. Dole, until recently
the president of the Red Cross, and a former Secretary of
Transportation and Secretary of Labor and a Harvard Law School
graduate. While Mrs. Dole is not the sensation she was months ago,
she still draws crowds teeming with intrigued women and young
people (and even some Democrats) who flock to her appearances in
tiny Iowa towns like Coralville and Maquoketa. She has assembled
state organizations where aides now take down the names of
prospective supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole has begun to build a financial base by tapping into
support from women around the country. Forty-three percent of her
contributions have come from women; in all federal elections, women
account for roughly 25 percent. And her campaign recently signed up
22 women on her finance committee, each of whom agreed to raise
$10,000. (By the end of June she had raised $3.5 million, compared
with $36.3 million for Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, who is 63, has also become more comfortable on the
stump. She still likes to stick to a carefully choreographed
routine. But unlike in the early days of her campaign, Mrs. Dole
fields questions from voters and no longer dispatches aides to
shield her from the press.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning move for a politician who has long found it
painful to talk to the press, she even picked up the telephone to
call a New York Times reporter unsolicited. ``Is it OK if I visit
with you like this from time to time?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As her campaign bus rolled through the corn and soy fields of
eastern Iowa the other day, with only one reporter in tow, Mrs.
Dole scoffed at the notion that she had let her candidacy languish.
She said Bush, whom she referred to as ``W,'' had been assembling
his campaign since 1996, and that every other Republican contender
except Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah got a head start because she did
not step down as president of the Red Cross until January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other candidate except Hatch was at this some years ago,
including W. I was at the Red Cross,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``They are
totally nonpartisan, and I've only been out of the Red Cross six
months. We were starting so overnight that you don't just have
everything in place.''
</P>
<P>
   As the interview proceeded, Mrs. Dole departed from her usual
carefully parsed responses and dismissed any thought that she could
have geared up faster. ``Don't you think when this has been going
on just for six months that that's a rather unfair comment?'' she
said. ``Let's look at Bush. They've been at it for a long, long
time. You know that. Because there's no way they could have had $36
million if they hadn't been planning this for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding increasingly defensive as she sought to draw a contrast
with Bush, Mrs. Dole asserted, ``The others have got to speak up
also. I think we have been specific. Would you agree to that?''
Wincing at a question about missed opportunities, she added, ``I'm
hearing the enthusiasm and the excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   She repeatedly cited polls showing that she could defeat _ or
wrestle to a dead heat _ Vice President Al Gore in a general
election.
</P>
<P>
   But the best gauge of whether Mrs. Dole can pull herself back
into her starting spot as the No. 2 contender will be at a straw
poll in Ames on Saturday. ``We are going to make history,'' she
tells crowds. ``This is important on the 14th.''
</P>
<P>
   The event is important because it will become clear whether Mrs.
Dole has developed the organizational strength and political appeal
to transform the excitement over her candidacy into commitment from
people (including many newcomers to politics) who are willing to
traipse to Ames to vote for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you can translate the interest into political support
is, I suppose, the fundamental question this campaign faces,'' said
Thomas A. Daffron, Mrs. Dole's campaign manager. ``We don't know
the answer to that yet. There isn't any history. There isn't any
barometer. There hasn't been a female candidate for president who
was serious.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While the idea of the first woman president excites many voters,
it also injects some risk and uncertainty in the party's headstrong
quest to retake the White House. The uncertainty placed immense
pressure on Mrs. Dole to demonstrate _ and do so early _ that hers
was a campaign that could win. She has also had to overcome the
fact that Mrs. Dole has never been elected to anything. So her
initial organizational difficulties made some Republicans even more
apprehensive. While most Republicans say the country is ready to
elect a female president, a full third say it is not, according to
an NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll taken in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm ready for a woman,'' Barbara Beck, a
retired store manager, said after hearing Mrs. Dole speaking
recently at a picnic near Laconia, N.H. ``I wonder if she'd be
strong enough. I just don't know if a woman could keep it together.
She's too cutsey. I want some desk slammer. I want someone to
holler a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole said she never encounters such remarks. ``I'm hearing
from women who will say to me, `I've driven my daughter half way
across this state to shake your hand!''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republican strategists argue that Mrs. Dole missed yet
another opportunity by keeping a low profile and refusing on
national interview programs to take advantage of her sex and her
star quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her calculation is that there's sufficient time to do it in
the fall,'' said Ari Fleischer, Mrs. Dole's communications
director. Asked if that was his calculation as well, he said, ''I'm
a press guy. You can never do too much. But I accept this.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by interviews with dozens of Republicans at Mrs. Dole's
events in Iowa and New Hampshire, she has an uphill battle to
convince even her admirers that she can take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always impressed me as dynamic _ she'd make a great
leader,'' said Christine Gerling Cole, 44, an information
specialist from Davenport, Iowa, said after a Dole event. Asked if
Mrs. Dole will win the nomination, she said, ``My gut feeling is
that she has a good chance at the vice presidency. My gut is that
the country is not ready for a woman president. Maybe I'm wrong. I
hope I am.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stevens, 80, a lawyer from Muscatine, Iowa, put it this
way: ``She gives all the right answers _ she's got a thick record
of accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked if she can win the nomination, he said flatly, ``No.
I'm afraid that Bush has got too much money already. That's the
problem. And if I think he's got the best shot, I would vote for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a standard speech she delivers almost word-for-word from
memory, Mrs. Dole recites her vast executive experience and laments
what she says is ``a deficit in our basic American values.'' She
has proposed a crusade against illegal drug use and describes
improving public schools as a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Dole has done little to distinguish herself from Bush's
friendly faced conservatism. She drew the most attention when she
broke from the pack and called for prohibiting concealed weapons
and supporting child proof trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should have taken advantage of the early attention to lay
out some of her stands on taxes and welfare and crime,'' said Ed
Gillepsie, who ran the campaign of Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who
withdrew from the race last month. ``I'm still not sure you could
identify one striking policy or substantive aspect of the Dole
campaign right now apart from the tack on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A big part of Mrs. Dole's woes may be beyond her control: she is
simply swamped by Bush. On June 30, Mrs. Dole consented to a rare
national television interview on the NBC ``Today'' program to put
forth the message that there would be no turning back from her
quest for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Dole's appearance was only an asterisk because hours
later, Bush announced his $36 million war chest. From that day
forward, press calls to the Dole headquarters outside Washington
have declined dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press followed the money and gave much less consideration
to anything else,'' Fleischer said. ``It's not that Elizabeth Dole
went down; it's that George Bush went up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-MAYORS-NYT &LR;      08-09 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MAYORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TOWN OHIO MAYORS ARE SPLIT OVER LOSS OF JUDICIAL DUTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMWOOD PLACE, Ohio _ By Superior Court fiat, judicial gavels
are being snatched from the hands of small-town mayors across this
state, striking down an old tradition and leaving Mayor Richard
Ellison ruefully asking what's wrong with local justice proving
more kindhearted than blind?
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, who earns $6,900 a year as a one-stop symbol of law and
order and management in this humble blue-collar village of 2,900,
further asks what's so biased about a mayor's cutting compassionate
slack when he sits in judgment of some of the very people who
elected him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I only maxed out one guy in my court in the last six years,''
said the mayor, a non-lawyer who described how he threw the book at
a nasty drunk who had destroyed the tree flourishing outside
Charley's Bar a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three days in jail and $600,'' said Ellison, sounding
judicious as he mourned the end of this state's ``strong mayor''
tradition of having local mayors, most of whom are not lawyers,
hear minor criminal cases ranging from disorderly conduct to
drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a traumatic thing, involving real-life circumstances,''
he declared, grateful to live so close to his neighbors when he has
to judge them. ``There's more opportunity for compassion. It gives
you a good feeling to go home and say, `I think I got the message
across and didn't have to wipe out some family's fortune.'''
</P>
<P>
   But a recent federal appellate decision found the system had
more potential for bias than for compassion. Since mayors control
town budgets and police forces, the judges said, it could be unfair
to have them judge cases with local police officers as witnesses
and fines that could boost municipal coffers.
</P>
<P>
   A good part of the 400 mayoral courts in the state will be
affected and face the option of hiring trained lawyers as part-time
magistrates, said Augustin F. O'Neil, the lawyer who successfully
challenged the age-old mayors court system before the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the 6th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of an era?'' said O'Neil, hardly dewy-eyed at the loss
of this vestige of Ohio's small-town life. ``It should be the end
of an era. Frontier justice is what we have here,'' he said, citing
the Magna Carta in his successful argument that for a
revenue-hungry mayor to serve constituents as both police
administrator and judge presented a conflict of authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with power and egos, just as any time politics is
involved,'' O'Neil declared in an interview. He said some of the
``strong mayors'' _ those who run a municipality without the
insulation of a separate city manager _ were as dictatorial as
big-city machine bosses. ``A lot of these burgs generate big
revenues from mayors courts. Under that robe, a mayor in effect
wears a badge.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, a 64-year-old retired truck-company manager who has
presided at thousands of cases, sadly dissents, fearing the ruling
is a step toward ``metropolitan'' government of centralized court
systems in which smaller jurisdictions like his will eventually be
eclipsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the criminal factor so much as that personal, that
family, that social and emotional value,'' said Ellison, who always
presided in jacket and tie, never a robe. ``A family I know might
stand before me heartbroken over some dirt-bag son or brother or
cousin. They talk directly to me, hoping for some mitigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor understands the basis of the court ruling for he
recalls his boyhood days of peddling newspapers in the now-departed
illegal gambling dens of this hamlet before the interstate highway
was built. ``A mayor could be a dictator in those days, but they
were benevolent dictators,'' said Ellison, honoring the memory of
such predecessors as Art ``Butch'' Wise, a butcher remembered for a
heart of gold and an iron hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there was Otto Hessler, came over from Lichtenstein
as a young man and ran the village for 27 years,'' Ellison said.
``If you needed anything _ a ton of coal in a hard winter _ Otto
was the man who'd get it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayors of Ohio are hardly unanimous in regretting the loss
of their gavels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayors now are facing the possibility of liability _ that's
the crux of their problem,'' said John E. Gotherman, counsel of the
Ohio Municipal League, a nonprofit association of village and city
executives. ``Most mayors are concerned to protect their
municipalities and themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling grew out of a 1994 case in Macedonia in which a
citizen charged his civil rights had been violated when the mayor
responded spiritedly to an unpaid traffic ticket with an arrest
warrant plus a contempt-of-court charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly won't miss the hassle,'' said Mayor Elbert
Tannreuther of Monroe, who has sat in judgment of more than 10,000
cases in the last 13 years in his city of 7,000 residents. ``The
people you see in court today include a lot of repeaters, people
with just absolutely no respect for the system. I wasn't built that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tannreuther said he found the court a catch basin for the city's
underlife more than a place of wayward charm. ``It was
depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison agreed it could be depressing _ but also redeeming. ``I
worked closely with Bob Newman, a legitimate liberal, as
prosecutor,'' said the mayor, who describes himself as an
unreconstructed Goldwater man. ``We weren't out to hang anyone,
because that hundred-dollar fine might mean a bicycle for some
guy's kid. And the 15 grand we'll pay for a magistrate _ well, that
could go for a new roof for town hall.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil, the lawyer who challenged the mayors courts, said there
must be more to small-town life than nostalgia for the old ways.
``Justice needs to be blind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellison, who has read bits of law in his years as a judge,
cited his own favorite prescription, a maxim from British law, he
said, on how to be a successful judge: ``First of all, be a
gentleman. If you know a little law, so much the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
