<SLUG> BC-TIMES-AMAZON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES AND AMAZON.COM SETTLE DISPUTE OVER BEST-SELLER
LIST  
 (DW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amazon.com and The New York Times Co. have settled
their legal dispute over the online bookseller's use of the
newspaper's weekly best-seller list to sell discounted books.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said in a statement Monday that they had reached
an agreement that would permit Amazon to continue publishing the
list of popular titles. The dispute had prompted the bookseller to
go to federal court in June seeking a ruling that would allow it to
continue to use the list.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced Monday formalizes many of the steps that
Amazon took in the early stage of the disagreement after the Times
Co. demanded that the bookseller stop publishing the best-seller
list in the absence of a licensing agreement. According to the
statement, Amazon agreed to list the best-selling books in
alphabetical order, post the lists after publication in the
newspaper and include disclaimers that The Times was not affiliated
with Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Amazon has agreed to continue providing weekly sales
data to the newspaper. It has been supplying such data, which the
paper uses to help compile the best-seller lists, for more than two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't threaten to withhold their data, but it was very
clear to us that their data is of benefit to us,'' said Nancy
Nielsen, a spokeswoman for the Times Co. ``So when we made the
settlement, it was written going forward that this was a quid pro
quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Curry, a spokesman for Amazon, said the company, based in
Seattle, would file documents to drop its lawsuit and that the
agreement had restored ``marital harmony after a brief spat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that this is an agreement that benefits the
book-reading public,'' Curry said. ``You have a widely recognized
list of best sellers on line so that people can readily know that
these books are available at Amazon.com. And from The Times'
perspective, the integrity of the best-seller list'' will be
maintained ``because it will include sales data from the biggest
seller of on-line books.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Amazon was already following the elements of the
agreement, Ms. Nielsen said that the written statement was a
promise to continue taking the same steps.
</P>
<P>
   The original legal action came during a price war over best
sellers on The New York Times lists, spreading from Amazon's Web
site to Barnesandnoble.com and Borders.com. The newspaper also
sought to stop the use of the best-seller lists on Borders.com but
did not send a warning letter to Barnesandnoble.com. The New York
Times has a business relationship with Barnesandnoble.com, which
includes a licensing agreement stipulating when that bookseller can
post the lists.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Borders, Rich Fahle, said the bookseller was
negotiating with the Times Co. to resolve the matter. Unlike
Amazon, Borders continues to publish the list in the traditional
numerical order of rankings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
