<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABA-CARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `A force for good' and a bold voice: Clinton bestows Medal of
Freedom to Carter
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton gave the Presidential Medal of
Freedom, the nation's highest civilian award, to former President
Jimmy Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, in a ceremony at the Carter
Center on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton saluted Carter for making human rights a cornerstone of
his foreign policy and for brokering the Camp David peace agreement
between Egypt and Israel. He also cited Carter's support for the
Panama Canal treaty, which gives Panama control of the canal on
Dec. 31, and for re-establishing diplomatic relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   He said Carter has been a force for good since leaving the White
House in January 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a universally respected international statesman, he has
worked to advance peace, democracy and human rights and to diminish
hunger and disease around the globe,'' Clinton said in a citation
read at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lauded Rosalynn Carter for working to improve care for
seniors and the mentally ill. He also cited her support for women's
equality and increased childhood immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, through their many good works and their powerful
example, they have lifted the dignity of people everywhere,'' the
citation said. ``For this, they have earned a unique place in our
history and the respect and gratitude of all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton presented the medals at the Carter Center, a nonprofit
organization in Atlanta that the Carters founded in 1982 to resolve
conflicts, promote democracy and fight disease, hunger, poverty and
oppression around the world. The president has awarded medals of
freedom to 62 other people since he took office in 1993. He plans
to give freedom medals on Wednesday to former President Gerald R.
Ford and seven others.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Carter are the only Democrats to live in the White
House since Richard Nixon took office in 1969, but their
relationship has been strained at times. Analysts say Clinton
blamed Carter in part for his failed bid for re-election as
Arkansas governor in 1980. Several Cuban refugees sent to Arkansas
in by the federal government rioted, and Clinton asked President
Carter not to send any more refugees. Weeks later, though, the
federal government sent more Cuban refugees to Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton became president, Carter has sometimes expressed
reservations about Clinton's foreign policy, but he has also served
as a diplomatic troubleshooter in Haiti and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   This past spring, Carter was publicly critical of the U.S.-led
NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. He called the campaign ``senseless''
and ``brutal'' in the way it inflicted suffering on civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bixler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
