<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT POSTPONES MIDEAST TRIP AT ISRAEL'S REQUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced on
Monday that at Israel's request, she had postponed a trip to the
Middle East until at least the end of the month while the new
Israeli government tries to persuade the Palestinians to accept
changes in their latest land-for-security agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Albright had been scheduled to leave for the region this week.
But she said through a spokesman that she delayed the trip at the
request of Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who is trying to sort through
problems with the Palestinians over the timing of the pullout of
Israeli troops from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan now is to go towards the end of the month, the
beginning of next month,'' said James P. Rubin, the spokesman. ``It
is Secretary Albright's view and expectation that the Israelis and
Palestinians will work together seriously and constructively during
this period.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright is hoping to use the trip to push forward on two
tracks: toward carrying out the long-stalled Wye River agreement
between the Israelis and the Palestinians, which calls for an
Israeli withdrawal from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank, and
toward revived peace talks between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that Albright would be visiting Israel, Gaza and
Syria on the trip, and he left open the possibility that she might
also visit Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Albright's first visit to the Middle East since
Barak, whose election was welcomed enthusiastically by the Clinton
administration, took office last month and vowed to seek early
peace settlements with the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that before deciding to delay her trip, Albright
consulted with Barak; Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader; and
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria. Asked at a news
conference about Arafat's reaction to the delay, Rubin said that
the Palestinian leader ``expressed understanding with the timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has asked Arafat to consider a revised approach to the Wye
River accords, which were reached last October near Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to concede territory before negotiations start on a
permanent peace, the new Israeli leader wants the third and last
part of the Israeli troop withdrawal promised under Wye to be
suspended and ultimately made part of a final peace agreement with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Under Barak's proposal, the two sides would move quickly to
negotiations for a final peace agreement to resolve the most
difficult issues between them, including the status of Jerusalem
and the future of Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Barak asked Arafat to spend two weeks reflecting on the
proposal, and that period ends on Tuesday. The Palestinians have
publicly rejected the proposed delay in the troop withdrawals and
the attempt to link them to the so-called permanent status talks.
But Israeli officials say that the Palestinian response to them in
private has been more nuanced and flexible.
</P>
<P>
   One senior official said that except for a break of 24 hours,
negotiations with the Palestinians had been going on at many
levels. He described the talks as ``friendly, intensive and
progressing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that although a two-week time frame had been set,
negotiations were likely to continue all week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Haim Ramon, a special minister in Barak's office, said that
compromise seemed possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our proposal were to be implemented, the Palestinians would
get 75 percent of what they expect by Nov. 15,'' he said in a
telephone interview. ``The debate is over the final 25 percent, so
the difference between us is not that dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports of progress, Palestinians officials continued on
Monday to publicly reject the idea of delays in carrying out the
Wye accord. ``They are not understanding the messages we are
sending,'' said Nabil Shaath, a Palestinian planning minister and a
close associate of Arafat.
</P>
</TEXT>
