</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CABINET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN OUSTS CABINET, APPOINTS NEW PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Political unknown Vladimir Putin took power as Russia's
latest acting prime minister Monday and _ on Boris N. Yeltsin's
orders _ launched a campaign to inherit Russia's presidency from
his sudden benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, facing an armed rebellion in southern Russia and
provoking new political turmoil at home, gave no explanation for
naming his fourth government in 17 months and choosing as his
hoped-for successor an inexperienced politician not known to most
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's nomination to replace Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin
took the United States and other Western governments by surprise
and shook Russia's already feeble financial markets. Even Kremlin
watchers familiar with Yeltsin's mercurial leadership style were
taken aback when he said he would like to see Putin as Russia's
next president.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, 46, said he had not not been planning to run for the post
_ elections are just 11 months away _ but added he was accustomed
to taking orders and would follow Yeltsin's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The firing of Stepashin, after only 89 days in power, makes it
unlikely that Russia will enact the reforms needed to pull the
nation out of its economic crisis. Analysts said members of the
president's inner circle thought Putin would be tougher in dealing
with Yeltsin's political opponents in upcoming parliamentary and
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup thrust Russia into another disruptive political
crisis, distracting attention from the Caucasus mountains, where
federal troops and Islamic rebels squared off in the rugged
Dagestan region where the militants have seized several villages.
As fighting raged for a third day, Stepashin warned that Moscow
risks losing the unruly southern province to the east of breakaway
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the situation in Dagestan is very difficult. I think we
could really lose Dagestan,'' Stepashin said at a final meeting
with his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   In making the announcement, the often-ill Yeltsin looked puffy
and spoke extremely slowly, with long pauses in between words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have decided to name a man,'' Yeltsin said, ``who in my
opinion is capable of uniting society, based on the broadest
political forces, to ensure the continuation of reforms in Russia.
I trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   For Russians who once saw their president as the strapping
leader of this country's democratic transformation, the nationally
televised spectacle of Yeltsin annointing a bland career
intelligence officer as the man who will lead Russia ``into the
21st century'' underscored just how far the Kremlin chief, aging
and ailing, has drifted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does he think this is, a dynasty?'' commented Mikhail
Berger, editor of the daily newspaper Segodnya. ``What kind of
democratic society has successors?''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Constitution bars Yeltsin from a third term, and the
Russian media has speculated that he and his advisers are
considering the possibility of postponing or canceling elections in
a bid to extend his tenure. Perhaps seeking to dispel such fears,
Yeltsin also Monday set December 19 as the date for elections to
the State Duma, the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Few believe Putin, a putative liberal for a career spy but a
politically inexperienced bureaucrat and an unknown to most
Russians, has any chance of being elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's complete madness,'' former First Deputy Prime Minister
Boris Nemtsov, once seen as Yeltsin's favored potential successor,
told Ekho Moskvy radio. ``It...is difficult to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's approval ratings have been in single digits for the
entire year and leading presidential candidates _ such as Moscow
Mayor Yury Luzhkov _ express open hostility to the Kremlin in an
apparent effort to distance themselves from the unpopular regime.
</P>
<P>
   Most Russian politicians saw Yeltsin's latest shakeups as a sign
of desperation in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who will take a prime minister seriously if they change them
like gloves?,'' Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov asked in a
radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov also expressed concern that the Kremlin was planning a
state of emergency and the dissolution of parliament. Seeking to
avoid provoking the increasingly isolated, but still powerful
Kremlin, opposition leaders indicated that Putin stood a good
chance of being approved when the Duma votes on his candidacy next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently caught off guard, the Clinton administration reacted
cautiously to the latest political upheaval in Russia, saying it is
ready to work with President Boris Yeltsin's new choice for prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly it is within President Yeltsin's prerogative'' to make
such a chance, said David Leavy, a national security spokesman for
the White House. He expressed hope that a government led by Putin
would give new impetus to arms control talks.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise shakeup came after Stepashin returned from a visit
to Dagestan, where Russian forces launched an air and artillery
attack on the weekend against the gunmen, who are believed to be
members of a separatist Muslim movement. Fighting in the region is
the worst since the war between Russian troops and Muslim
separatists in neighboring Chechnya, the breakaway region that won
defacto independence in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Four Russian policemen were accidentally killed Sunday when
Russian helicopter gunships mistook them for rebels, the Dagestani
Interior Ministry press service said Monday. In addition, at least
15 Russian troops were wounded in fighting with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin met with Yeltsin Monday morning for what he thought
would be a briefing on the standoff in Dagestan. Instead, he got
his walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning I visited the president and he signed a decree on
my resignation. He thanked me _ and fired me,'' a visibly shaken
Stepashin told the Cabinet in a speech that was broadcast on
Russian television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expressed my position concerning the resignation to Boris
Nikolayevich, but this is his right,'' Stepashin said. ``I told the
president that I have been, am, and will remain with him until the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stepashin reportedly rejected Yeltsin's offer to head
Russia's Security Council, one of two posts vacated by Putin
Monday. Yeltsin named Nikolai Patrushev, the FSB's deputy director
and a lifetime security official, as acting head of the agency to
replace Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said there would be no sweeping changes in the Cabinet,
although technically all its members were fired and will have to be
reappointed. Russia just won a major debt restructuring deal with
foreign creditors and protracted government turmoil could hold up
new talks on debt rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
   The battered Russian economy also reacted to Yeltsin's shakeup.
Trading on the Russian stock exchange was suspended Monday after
the benchmark Russian Trading System index fell 11 percent in the
first hour. Trading later resumed and the index rallied to 101.72,
down 1.4 percent from Friday's close at 103.15.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble currency also began to fall immediately upon news of
Stepashin's dismissal, going from 24.9 to the US dollar to 25.9 in
street trading. Russia's Central Bank headed off a deeper plunge
with heavy intervention on Moscow's currency exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
