<SLUG> BC-MA-DELEGATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEEHAN WAR CHEST ALMOST $1.3 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gearing up for a race he once vowed not to run,
Representative Martin T. Meehan has amassed a campaign fund of
nearly $1.3 million for the 2000 election, one of the nation's
largest war chests for a House incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, a Lowell Democrat who earlier this year dropped his 1991
pledge to serve no more than eight years in the House, raised
nearly $325,000 in the first half of 1999, vaulting him onto the
Top 10 list of incumbents with the most cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the newest House member from Massachusetts _
Representative Michael E. Capuano of Somerville _ is struggling to
build a substantial reelection fund as he faces the prospect of a
well-financed challenge in the Democratic primary in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Capuano, who has yet to recover $50,000 in personal loans from a
bruising 1998 campaign, raised $131,654 in the first six months of
1999 and ended the period with $67,000 on hand, according to his
mid-year report to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are significant because party leaders urge House
members to vigorously raise money in the first six months of the
two-year election cycle to try to intimidate prospective
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Capuano's cash total is particularly striking in contrast with
his predecessor, former Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II of
Brighton, who continues to control one of the largest House
campaign funds, nearly $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kennedy has not raised money this year, his decision
not to dissolve the House fund is a sign he is keeping open his
political options during his hiatus in the private sector as head
of his non-profit business, Citizens Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, too, is weighing his future options, including a
possible bid for the governorship in 2002. In abandoning his pledge
to leave the House by 2000, Meehan said earlier this year that he
had decided to seek a fifth term in part to continue leading the
effort to overhaul the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   The system has been bountiful for Meehan, largely because he has
been able to accumulate campaign money in the absence of a strong
Republican challenge since he first won the seat in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Meehan trails only eight House members, including
such fund-raising titans as the Democratic leader, Representative
Richard A. Gephardt, in the size of his campaign fund. The leader
is Representative Rick A. Lazio of New York, who has $3.1 million
on hand as he weighs a possible bid for the Republican nomination
for Senate in 2000. Lazio is expected to address the issue at a
news conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, GOP officials vowed to attack Meehan both for
changing his position on term limits and for his massive campaign
kitty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meehan has made a lot of hay out of the issue of campaign
finance reform, but he continues to lead the delegation in not just
the amount of money he raises but in the hoarding of it,'' said
state Representative Brian Cresta of Wakefield, chairman of the
Massachusetts Republican State Committee. ``It really points to his
credibilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan was vacationing and was not available to comment. His
chief of staff, Bill McCann, said Meehan will continue to abide by
the current campaign laws even as he tries to change them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running for reelection,'' McCann said, ``and one of the
unfortunate realities of our system is that it can be very
expensive. That's why he's trying to pass real campaign finance
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Capuano's staff said he had met his six-month goal of
eliminating debt other than his personal loans and is gearing up
for the reelection campaign. ``He has an aggressive fund-raising
schedule, beginning in September and beyond,'' said Capuano's press
secretary, Allison Mills.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of campaign cash on hand, Capuano was ranked 402d by
the Federal Election Commission among House members and a small
number of challengers who were obligated to file mid-year reports.
Representative John F. Tierney, a Salem Democrat, was ranked 396th
with a campaign fund of $71,919.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney won close races in 1996 and 1998 against former
Representative Peter G. Torkildsen, a Danvers Republican.
Torkildsen is not expected to run again in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
