<SLUG> BC-EURO-DOLLAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTINENTAL EUROPE'S CORE ECONOMIES SHOW SIGNS OF RECOVERY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, France, Italy, Spain, Portugal, Ireland)   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ After a half-year of economic inertia, continental
Europe's three core economies have begun to show clear signs of
recovery, the result not only of a gradual strengthening of
emerging market economies in Asia and Latin America, but of
tentative changes aimed at making European economies more nimble.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, France, and to a lesser degree, Italy, have been
reporting increased demand from abroad for goods and services for
the first time since late 1998. In France and Germany, consumer
spending is reinforcing the recovery. In Italy, the first fruits of
government fiscal austerity are evident, promising to help the
country catch up with its northern neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The continent's big core countries had in recent months all but
abdicated the role of economic engines to smaller economies on the
European fringes, like Spain, Portugal and Ireland. Lately,
however, growth has been so vigorous throughout the region that Wim
Duisenberg, the head of the European central bank, cautioned last
month that anti-inflationary bias was creeping into the monetary
considerations of the bank, which sets European monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the new single currency, the euro, for which
Duisenberg's bank is responsible, became an unexpected
consideration earlier this year, when the dismal performance of
these core European economies, by comparison with the United
States, caused the value of the euro to plummet by July to a low of
$1.0136, before it began a modest recovery, settling in New York
Monday at $1.0712..
</P>
<P>
   If there are risks to the new spurt of growth, they are perhaps
most evident in Italy, said J. Paul Horne, European equity market
economist at Salomon Smith Barney. But even there, larger than
expected government surpluses in July prompted many economists to
reduce their estimates of how big a percentage of economic output
the government deficit will be in 1999. In May, the Rome
goverment's upward revision of that estimate, from 2 percent to 2.4
percent, was a contributing factor in sending the euro into its
downward plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in Germany, manufacturers reported rising orders in June
for a third consecutive month. In July, a strong increase in a
monthly survey of retailers amounted to a confirmation of growing
consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnaround is definitely here,'' said Ralph Solveen,
senior economist at Commerzbank in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by such signs, Commerzbank has confirmed its 1.6 percent
forecast for German economic growth this year, even as the
International Monetary Fund recently downgraded its estimate to 1.4
percent. The data prompted Deutsche Bank, Germany's largest, to
revise upward its estimate for next year to 3 percent, ahead of the
IMF's and its own previous estimate of 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, the recovery was domestic-driven,'' said Ulrich
Beckmann, senior economist at Deutsche Bank Research. ``Now
overseas growth is kicking in.''
</P>
<P>
   That overseas growth is expected to benefit Italy as well. Like
Germany, it relies strongly on such heavily export-driven
industries as machine building and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, orders to Italian industry have been inching
up on a month-to-month basis _ 1.1 percent in July _ though they
continue to decline when compared with last year's figures. Yet the
growth surge in Germany, where Italy ships 55 percent of its
exports, makes an Italian revival seem to many all but a matter of
time.
</P>
<P>
   In recent Italian surveys, business confidence has been strong,
and consumption of durable goods, like cars, is rising. Italy's
leading economic daily, Il Sole 24-Ore, recently compared the
economy to a column of stalled cars. The lead vehicles were already
moving, it said, and it was but a matter of time before those in
the middle and at the end were set in motion, too.
</P>
<P>
   For all three countries, said Horne, growth prospects depend
more on the performance of close neighbors than of emerging market
economies.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 European countries embracing the euro _ led by Germany,
France and Italy _ conduct about 40 percent of their trade with
only two partners _ the United States and Britain. While the U. S.
economy remains strong, Britain, which has not yet adopted the
euro, is showing signs of recovery. In July, British retail sales
were their strongest in 18 months, while the service sector
expanded more robustly than at any time since early 1998. ``Britain
touched bottom in the first quarter,'' said Horne.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of providing a measure of permanence to the current
upswing, the governments in Italy and Germany have committed
themselves to cutbacks in state spending and changes in taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany laid out a
radical agenda to slash state spending, freeze pensions, and cut
the government's share of the national economy over the next
several years, to about 40 percent from nearly half today.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the change has already begun. Part of the greatly
improved government fiscal condition reported in July was due to an
overhaul of tax collection methods. In September, government and
labor union representatives will begin discussing radical reform of
the pension system, to bring down the share of wages represented by
payments for various social security programs.
</P>
<P>
   All three economies continue to be slowed by levels of
unemployment that are roughly double those of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in France, where consumer spending has rivaled export growth
in bearing the economy aloft, consumer confidence has been
stiffened not only by soaring financial markets but also by job
creation because of more flexible labor markets.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Barthalon, chief economist at Paribas in Paris, said that
legislative changes permitting temporary employment, notably of
young people, had contributed this year to a 2 percent increase in
private employment. Moreover, he said, while economists once
assumed that 3 percent growth was required before the French
economy began creating jobs, that level now appears to be only 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the strength of financial markets also buoyed French
consumer confidence. ``Wealthy people are obviously feeling
wealthier,'' he said. Moreover, he said, anecdotal evidence
suggested a trickle down effect to middle class families.
</P>
<P>
   Paribas, he said, had not raised its growth forecast for France,
which is 2.3 percent this year and 2.5 percent for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were less pessimistic at the turn of the year,'' he said.
`'We didn't believe that the emerging markets crisis would spread
to the larger Western economies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
