<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ABA-COX     08-09 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ABA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speech controversy: Clinton addresses ABA members
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton on Monday called on Congress to
break the gridlock on his judicial nominations, blaming the
Republican-controlled Senate with creating ``a mounting vacancy
crisis in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply cannot afford to allow political considerations to
keep our courts vacant and to keep justice waiting,'' Clinton told
the American Bar Association's annual meeting here. `` . . . We
know that justice delayed is justice denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came just hours after a morning ABA panel
discussion on judicial independence during which speakers strongly
criticized the president's most recent judicial nominees. The
speakers claimed Clinton has capitulated to conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Influential GOP lawmakers have ``tragically discouraged the
White House from nominating someone who's shown sensitivity on
human rights,'' said George Kendall of the NAACP Legal Defense and
Education Fund.
</P>
<P>
   During a 25-minute speech, Clinton also called on the ABA's
400,000 members to press Congress to level ``inequities'' in
federal sentencing guidelines and to maintain funding of the Legal
Services Corporation, the federal funded agency that provides legal
aid for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments were warmly received by the ABA membership.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in the day, the conservative Southeastern Legal
Foundations sharply condemned the ABA for allowing Clinton to give
the keynote speech.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has filed an ethics complaint against Clinton in
Arkansas, where the president received his law license. Last week,
the federal judge who oversaw the Paula Jones sexual harassment
case against Clinton fined the president $90,000 for legal fees and
expenses as a result of a civil contempt citation against him for
giving false testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is with a profound sense of disappointment that the
national platform offered by the ABA convention will undoubtedly
appear to the American people as tacit approval for the actions of
an attorney recently held in civil contempt for misrepresentation
under oath,'' said L. Lynn Hogue, a foundation executive.
</P>
<P>
   But many attorneys in the audience said they had little problem
with Clinton speaking before the nation's largest legal
organization in the shadow of the contempt fine. After the speech
throngs of lawyers came forward to shake Clinton's hand or take his
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Kamau King, an Atlanta lawyer, said he thinks the fine was
absurd. ``What did he do?'' he said. ``He lied so his wife wouldn't
find out he had an affair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably any other attorney would have been disbarred for
perjury,'' Milwaukee attorney Oyvind Wistrom said after the speech.
``If he were disbarred, I'd feel very differently about him
speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   ABA President Philip Anderson, a Little Rock, Ark., lawyer who
offered Clinton a job after he suffered a gubernatorial defeat in
1980, said Clinton's address touched on exactly the issues
considered most important by the ABA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going into an election year,'' he said. ``We cannot
afford to have our judicial system crippled with vacancies.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the collection of judges he has nominated to the
federal bench ``the most diverse group in American history.''
Nearly half are women and minorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton noted, he nominated the first
African-American judges to sit on the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Richmond, Va., and the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, Clinton nominated Fulton County Superior Court
Judge Gail Tusan to the U.S. District Court bench in Atlanta. If
confirmed, she would be the first black woman to preside on that
court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Clinton said, the nomination process ground to a halt
in the Senate. During that election year, he said, not a single
circuit appeals court judge was confirmed by the Senate, the first
time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   After U.S. Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist warned
that the growing number of vacancies could undermine the legal
system's ability to administer justice, the Senate moved to fill 65
vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Clinton said, he has nominated 61 judicial
candidates, 16 of whom are due to fill ``emergency'' vacancies
because of caseload backlogs. The Senate has confirmed only 11 of
these.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not _ not, I repeat _ have another replay of 1996,''
he said. ``The worst effects of the slowdown are making themselves
felt across the country. Exploding civil and criminal court dockets
affect the lives of tens of thousands of Americans. They strain our
justice system to the breaking point.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to Clinton on Sunday, U.S. Sen. Orrin Hatch
(R-Utah), chairman of the judiciary committee, said action on
judicial nominations has proceeded ``in a balanced and thorough
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to acknowledge that he is not pressing forward
with nominees that may be considered controversial or liberal by
GOP lawmakers. He said he has worked hard to avoid ``major
ideological fights of the kind we saw in previous years over
judicial nominees.''
</P>
<P>
   He could very well have been referring to Judge Rosemary
Barkett, the former chief justice of the Florida Supreme Court, who
was confirmed to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta
after a grueling confirmation battle.
</P>
<P>
   Since Barkett's confirmation _ and since Republicans gained
majority control of the Senate _ the White House has put forward
few controversial nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's last two 11th Circuit nominees serve as good examples.
One, Stanley Marcus, was nominated to the lower-court federal bench
by President Reagan. The most recent, Charles Wilson, is the top
federal prosecutor in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Both were quickly approved by the Senate. Stephen Bright,
director of the Atlanta-based Southern Center for Human Rights,
sharply criticized Clinton's nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in today's climate he would nominate someone of
the likes of Thurgood Marshall,'' said Bright, referring to the
late U.S. Supreme Court justice and civil rights attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Jingle Davis contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
