<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALEXANDER-COX     08-09 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEXANDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAMPAIGN 2000: Alexander banking on Iowa's love of underdogs
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ In Washington, the pundits are speculating
about when he will drop out. In New York, Don Imus has been joking
on the radio about the sanity of his contributors.
</P>
<P>
   But in northeastern Iowa, it's a glorious day. The heat wave has
broken, and the endless fields of tall corn convey a hypnotic sense
of wholesomeness, as Republican presidential hopeful Lamar
Alexander's small entourage sails along through an ocean of green
toward its next small-town stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days are better than others. When the crowd's a little
better than expected or your opponent says something dumb. . . .
It's pretty good training for the job, actually,'' the former
Tennessee governor and U.S. education secretary muses, looking out
the window and reflecting on what he has learned about agriculture,
education and other subjects on his many visits to this key caucus
state.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander jokes with audiences that George W. Bush rides a jet
called ``Great Expectations,'' while he rides a Winnebago called
``Exceeding Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, actually, the Winnebago is out for repairs and the
candidate is riding a Ford Econoline, loaned by a car dealer friend
of his national chairman, former four-term Iowa Gov. Terry
Branstad. Alexander's son, Will, and a staffer follow in the Ford
Explorer that was Will's reward for making all A's in his freshman
year at the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Both Alexander and Branstad are decked out in khakis and red
Alexander-for-president polo shirts for the day, which begins with
breakfast with 20 Republicans at a restaurant in New Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   If he has any hope of getting back into a race in which he has
been swamped by the Bush gold rush, it depends on the strategy
forged by Branstad and several key Alexander staffers who cut their
political teeth in Branstad's campaigns. The Iowan pulled some big
upsets by outworking his opponents and focusing on rural counties,
and he hopes to do the same for Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowans pull for the underdog. They pull for the small school
in the basketball tournament. They respect hard work and
humility,'' Branstad says.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander says he will be in the race through the caucuses early
next year, but the likelihood is he will need to pull off a
surprise and finish in the top three in this Saturday's GOP straw
poll in Ames, or his campaign will face death by closed checkbook.
Bush and Steve Forbes are outspending him nearly 10-to-1, employing
paid telephone banks to turn out Iowa Republicans for the event.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, Alexander and Branstad, with a few aides and
reporters, were pushing forward, against the wind of lowered
expectations, on a highway tour of 64 of Iowa's 99 counties before
the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   In Vinton, where a dozen people have gathered for a sack lunch
hosted by a state senator, Alexander debates briefly on trade
issues with 81-year-old George Hoherz.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were pretty persuasive today. I've enjoyed listening to
you more than I thought I would,'' the retired broker says
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make progress in small steps,'' Alexander replies,
slightly encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, to small groups of mostly gray-haired Iowans,
Alexander tells two stories that are the core of his message.
</P>
<P>
   One is about the dramatic events that led him to be sworn in as
governor three days early in 1979, to head off a pardons-for-pay
scheme by outgoing Tennessee Democrat Ray Blanton. The other is
about a Fort Dodge principal who was embarrassed at the jokes his
students made on a recent class trip to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He promises he'll be a president who won't embarrass the voters,
who'll help parents teach their children right from wrong in a
coarser, more complicated culture than the one in which he grew up
in Maryville, Tenn., the son of a principal and a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Under other circumstances, Alexander might seem well positioned
for his second run at the Republican nomination. He has been
chairman of the National Governors' Conference and co-director of
Empower America, the conservative advocacy group. He has founded a
company that delivers on-sight day care and narrated a Discovery
Channel series on good schools.
</P>
<P>
   But whereas he had the field to himself as a moderate
alternative to Bob Dole four years ago, the middle ground this year
is crowded with Bush and Elizabeth Dole in the race. Most
critically, Bush has sopped up the money and media attention
Alexander got in his first outing.
</P>
<P>
   If they let ``big money'' decide this race before it even
begins, Alexander warns Iowans at each stop, the Iowa Caucuses
could soon become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This presidential election is not about raising money. It's
about raising children, raising farm prices and raising
standards,'' he says that night in Cedar Rapids at a backyard ice
cream social hosted by supporters Bill and Judy Chadima.
</P>
<P>
   The Alexander supporters who come to events like this tend to
identify with his middle-class, Main Street roots, and to distrust
Bush's wealth and family name.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that resonates is he started out like everybody
else,'' says Karen Malacek, one of the Republicans who has come to
the Chadimas to see him. ``I daresay in today's political field,
Abraham Lincoln would be one of the `others.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, Alexander speaks to a group of about a
hundred at an insurance company in Grinnell, an event put together
by his county chairman, Alan Clark. Leaning on the door of the
Econoline afterwards, Clark apologizes for the small showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a mob,'' Alexander replies. In fact, it's his biggest
crowd in two days. On the bus, he gets some pointed questions from
reporters about his prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you create a national organization, you can't let it go
away, because you can't put it back together again,'' he says. He's
talking about how he made the decision to run a second time, but at
least indirectly he seems to be speaking to the question of what
keeps him going.
</P>
<P>
   Some days are better than others. Speaking to the Pachyderm Club
in Marshalltown, Alexander seems for the first time to be visibly
down. Then a well-worn anecdote about Minnie Pearl gets a big laugh
and he's up again, plugging his proposal to replace MTBE, an
oil-based gasoline additive which the EPA says pollutes
groundwater, with ethanol, a move he claims could raise corn prices
35 to 50 cents a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   It's on to a brief stop at the Des Moines headquarters, where
his daughter Kathryn is checking on straw poll arrangements and
Alexander's brother-in-law, the Rev. Bill Karl, is manning a phone.
A Dallas minister, he drove up the night before to help.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's wife, Honey, recovering from a torn rotator cuff
Alexander says she got lugging his bag through an airport, will be
joining him this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see that this is what you have to do to get where you
want to be,'' says son Will, who admits that campaigning this
summer has given him the political bug. ``You have to deal with the
small crowds and the lack of attention. You've got to go with what
you know works and just keep pushing through it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it's on to the next small town, rolling through the
verdant countryside in the quest for votes, for as long as this
campaign lasts.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
