</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-TRADERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW REPORT CITES HIGH RISK OF DAY TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first detailed analysis of profits in the netherworld of
electronic day trading, a panel of state regulators said the risks
of the new and controversial form of investing are even more
ominous than they had suspected.
</P>
<P>
   Fully 70 percent of 30 randomly selected day traders lost money
and ultimately faced what the regulators called a nearly total
``risk of ruin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most traders will not only lose but almost certainly lose
everything they invest,'' according to the report, released Monday
at a meeting of the North American Securities Administrators
Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis comes just weeks after Mark O. Barton walked into
two Atlanta day-trading offices where he had accumulated
mountainous losses and opened fire on fellow day traders and office
workers. He killed nine people before fleeing in a black van and
turning a gun on himself. Authorities later found his murdered wife
and children in a suburban apartment along with a note alluding to
his big day-trading losses.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy threw a spotlight on the increasingly popular
practice of day trading, the most recent craze in the high-stakes
frontier of electronic finance. According to industry estimates,
4,000 to 7,000 members of a new breed of thrill-seeking amateur
traders are now pursuing their fortunes in some 287 boutiques
around the country that regulators have likened to gambling
parlors.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by promises of easy money, dedicated day traders work
eight hours a day, five days a week, staring at banks of computer
screens that provide direct electronic links to the markets. Often,
they perform hundreds of transactions a day, paying commissions for
each trade. They buy blocks of shares, holding them sometimes for
only seconds, hoping the price will briefly rise so they can dump
the shares for a profit. Instead of relying on stock-market
knowledge, they live by lightning reactions to minuscule price
movements.
</P>
<P>
   While the industry has said most day-traders make money if they
stick with it long enough, touting the success stories of those who
parlayed small accounts into multimillion-dollar fortunes,
regulators have struggled to sound a note of caution. But until now
there's been little hard data to rely on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, we've been able to substantiate what common sense
told us anyway,'' said Phil Feigin, executive director of NASAA.
``You just can't win often enough to make it worth your while. It's
essentially hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   The study examined 30 randomly selected accounts at the
Watertown, Mass. branch of All-Tech Investment Group, which
Massachusetts securities regulators shut down late last year,
charging abuses that ranged from forgery to deceptive marketing.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of the most profitable accounts found that even
those ``did not produce a return commensurate with the risk to
which they were exposed,'' the report said. And while 30 percent of
the accounts examined were profitable, those traders appeared to
rely more on luck than market savvy, making money from one big
winning trade and losing on the vast majority of their stock
transactions, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the analysis showed the day traders were required to
pay such high commissions on their trades that it would be
difficult to be profitable on a consistent basis.
</P>
<P>
   Firms need an endless supply of day-trading clients and the
commissions they generate to cover high capital and operating costs
that run upwards of $30,000 per customer, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely clear that the average public investor should
refrain from short-term trading,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Day-trading advocates immediately lashed out at the study,
saying most day-trading firms make clear to prospective clients the
risks of day trading and carefully screen applicants, taking only
those with enough money to absorb losses.
</P>
<P>
   They also criticized the study for focusing on accounts at a
single firm. ``Simply put, the study . . . is not a representative
sample of the industry,'' said Saul Cohen, an attorney for the
Electronic Traders Association.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the association wants to work with regulators in
enforcing existing regulations. ``All day-trading firms can and
must strive to improve their disclosure mechanisms and their
ethical practices,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said securities regulators should step up inspections
of day-trading firms and enforce limits on traders' ability to
trade with borrowed money.
</P>
</TEXT>
