<HEADER>
A1142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORSE-LUKAS-NYT &LR;      08-09 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-LUKAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKAS GETS HIS TURN AND ENTERS THE HALL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Wis., N.J.)   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ D. Wayne Lukas, the most successful and
at times the most second-guessed trainer in racing, was inducted
into the sport's Hall of Fame Monday. In an upbeat and otherwise
healing speech that drew standing ovations, ``I make no apologies
for what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been criticized by certain people in the industry who
don't always agree with what we do,'' he said. ``But it's my nature
to push the envelope every time. If you want a coach who wants to
walk the ball up the court, you better get another guy because
we're going to run and press all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who was elected by a landslide in his first year on the
ballot, was inducted with a show-stopping speech that ranged from
gratitude to humility to unyielding affirmation for his strict
style. He recalled that when his filly Winning Colors won the
Kentucky Derby in 1988, he said: ``My turn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Aug. 9, 1999, it's my turn,'' he said. ``What does it
all mean? It means that whenever champions gather, when all
champions from different sports gather, I'm just going to stand up
and say, `I belong.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas won his turn before a full house in the sales pavilion two
blocks from the Saratoga Race Course, which is marking its 131st
year of racing in the Adirondacks. The audience was enriched with
an array of Hall of Fame jockeys and trainers, including Angel
Cordero Jr., Ron Turcotte, Jerry Bailey, John Nerud and Allen
Jerkens.
</P>
<P>
   He was inducted along with the jockey Russell Baze _ who has won
more than 6,000 races and who rode 400 winners for seven straight
years, mostly in northern California _ and with three champion
horses from the past: Gun Bow, who raced in the 1960s and twice
outran the great Kelso; Exceller, who beat Seattle Slew and
Affirmed in the Jockey Club Gold Cup in 1978, and Miesque, the
European filly who won the Breeders' Cup Mile in 1987 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who is 63, was surrounded on the stage by tangible
evidence of his success: six men who became trainers after starting
their careers as his assistant. Todd Pletcher, Mark Hennig, Kiaran
McLaughlin, Dallas Stewart, Randy Bradshaw and Jeff Lukas, his son,
served as presenters when Lukas received his Hall of Fame plaque,
and they flanked him when he accepted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young men were going to be outstanding horsemen even if
they hadn't worked for Wayne Lukas,'' he said. ``There was a
trade-off here, and I got the best of it. Those records and numbers
on this plaque would never have happened if it weren't for these
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The records and numbers include $200 million won in purses, 14
years as the country's leading money winner, 19 champions, 13
winners in the Breeders' Cup, 4 victories in the Kentucky Derby, 12
victories in all Triple Crown races, 6 straight Triple Crown races
won and a career record of 3,750 winners and more than 500 stakes
winners, including Criminal Type, Lady's Secret, Capote, Flanders,
Serena's Song, Gulch, Terlingua, Timber Country and this year's
Derby and Preakness winner, Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has been a master at taking smart juveniles and turning
them into classic winners and champions, but he has been criticized
for rigorous training methods on horses who later broke down. Yet
he kept winning at a revolutionary rate.
</P>
<P>
   He was denied entry into the Hall of Fame in recent years
because he may not have been a licensed trainer of thoroughbreds
for the required 25 years. But Lukas, who started as a trainer of
quarter horses, insisted that he had trained thoroughbreds far
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reflect on 45 years with horses,'' he said, ``and ask: Why
me? Why am I so lucky? A boy growing up in a community of 8,000 in
the heart of Wisconsin where the snow gets as high as this
microphone, and making it to Saratoga.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   With the Hall of Fame jockey Jerry Bailey riding, Marquette, the
6-5 favorite, won the National Museum of Racing Hall of Fame
Handicap on Monday by 1\ lengths over Phi Beta Doc. He ran the mile
and one-eighth on the turf in 1:49 1/5. ... Menifee, winner of the
$1 million Haskell at Monmouth Park. N.J., on Sunday, returned to
Saratoga with Elliott Walden, his trainer, who will aim for the
Travers on Aug. 28. Ecton Park, another Walden colt and winner of
the Jim Dandy, was showing no sign of fatigue but was not likely to
run in the Travers. Cat Thief, second in the Haskell, was expected
back at Saratoga on Tuesday. Forestry, third in the Haskell,
arrived at Saratoga in good shape, but his trainer, Bob Baffert,
said, ``I want to see how he is training over the track before
making any decision on the Travers.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
