<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, AUGUST 10
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-AMERICA-ONLINE-NYT (moved on Friday, July 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, July 2,
about the growth and prospects of America Online in the Money &AMP;
Business section on July 4 imprecisely summarized a comment by
Stephen M. Case, the company's chairman. As Mr. Case informed The
Times this week, he was describing the view put forward by
Microsoft's lawyers in recent antitrust litigation, not expressing
his own view, when he said: ``Windows is the past. In the future,
AOL is the next Microsoft.'' Mr. Case's view is that personal
computers will continue to be the predominant Internet access
device and that Windows will continue to be the predominant
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GERDAU-AMERISTEEL-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Aug. 4,
about the proposed purchase of a controlling stake in the
Ameristeel Corporation of Florida by Gerdau S.A., a large
steelmaker in Brazil, misstated the financial condition of
Companhia Siderurgica Nacional, or CSN, Brazil's largest
steelmaker. CSN, which has been the subject of speculation as a
possible purchase by Gerdau, has $700 million in cash on hand. It
has not had difficulty servicing its foreign debt since the
Brazilian currency was devalued in January.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MEINKAMPF-LIBEL-NYT (moved on Sunday, Aug. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 8,
about on-line sales of literature banned in Germany omitted the
given name of the associate dean of the Simon Wiesenthal Center. He
is Rabbi Abraham Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   BC-IRRELEVANT-MAGS-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, Aug. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 8,
about the declining ability of magazines to stir debate misstated
the birthplace of Willie Morris, the former editor of Harper's
Magazine. He was born in Jackson, Miss., not Yazoo City, where he
was raised. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
