<SLUG> BC-CONDE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SIREN CALLS SOUGHT FOR CONDE NAST'S WEB OF SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A leading Web publisher is embarking on an elaborate
advertising and marketing effort both on and off line, hoping,
among other things, to add more fizz to Phys.com, encourage
curiosity about Epicurious.com and stimulate computer users to
check in with Concierge.com.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher is Conde Net, the interactive division of Advance
Publications. Through another division, Conde Nast Publications,
Advance owns familiar magazines like Architectural Digest, Bon
Appetit, Conde Nast Traveler, Details, GQ, Glamour, Gourmet,
Mademoiselle, The New Yorker, Self and Vanity Fair. The Conde Net
Web sites are inspired by their print siblings but offer different
content to help dispel perceptions that they are merely on-line
versions of dead-tree media.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, with a budget estimated at more than $20 million,
is indicative of myriad Web publishers' attempts to attract
attention in a media category that has grown cluttered in, well,
Internet time. After all, before a Web site's content can become
sticky _ that is, appealing enough to generate relatively long
visits _ someone has to reach out and touch the site in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plethora of dot-coms makes it hard to establish a brand,''
said Sarah Chubb, director for Conde Net in New York. ``We know who
it is we want, but it's harder to get them because of all that's
out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to communicate the richness of the content to
those who have not seen it before, and even to those who have not
been on line before.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the primary reason for the presence of the off-line
media on the schedule along with ads on Web sites. There will be
television and radio commercials, newspaper and magazine
advertisements, ads on postcards and possibly other pitches like
posters in stores and outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The Conde Net sites to be promoted by the campaign are Phys.com,
for health and fitness topics aimed at women; Epicurious.com, for
food and cooking topics; Concierge.com, a site for travel planning
that had been known as Epicurious Travel and is scheduled to be
reintroduced a week from Tuesday, and Swoon.com, for what Conde Net
describes as ``dating, mating and relating'' topics for men and
women.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for one or two more sites to be introduced by the end
of the year, Ms. Chubb said, adding that one of them would probably
be devoted to fashion, a Conde Nast mainstay in Vogue and other
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The creative chores for Phys.com and Concierge.com are being
handled by Robaire &AMP; Hogshead in Venice, Calif. Ads for the
travel-related site present it as the best choice ``whatever your
plans,'' whether they involve a trip to visit castles in
Transylvania or to attend the annual garlic festival in Gilroy,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for Phys.com carries the theme ``Fitness from the
outside in.'' The television spots and print ads are centered on
silhouettes of nude women that while tasteful might not be
sufficiently so for reproduction in a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The Phys.com campaign takes a low-key, wry tone. Here are some
lines: ``If you don't shape your body, Twinkies will,'' ``You know
how you feel in your favorite dress? Feel that way naked'' and
``Pretty is something you're born with. But beautiful, that's an
equal-opportunity adjective.''
</P>
<P>
   Media duties for Phys.com, Concierge.com and Swoon.com are being
handled by CIA VSM Media in New York, part of CIA Medianetwork. The
Swoon.com creative duties are handled in-house.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the creative and media assignments for Epicurious.com,
the first and largest of the sites, have been awarded to
Margeotes/Fertitta &AMP; Partners, part of the MDC Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in concept development,'' said George A. Fertitta,
president at Margeotes/Fertitta, a New York agency that has handled
campaigns for other Web sites like About.com and for MediaOne
Express, a high-speed Internet access service. Though
Margeotes/Fertitta has worked before for Conde Nast, this is its
initial assignment from Conde Net.
</P>
<P>
   The core of Epicurious.com is a recipe database, Ms. Chubb said,
adding that E-commerce is to be added in October under an agreement
with Williams-Sonoma Inc. in San Francisco, the retailer of
cookware and related products.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers on the Conde Net sites include Eastman Kodak Co.,
Ford Motor Co., Gap Inc., General Motors Corp., the Kraft Foods
unit of Philip Morris Cos., Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., Seagram Co. and
Visa.
</P>
<P>
   The sites are also turning out to generate revenue for Advance
Publications in another way, by selling subscriptions to Conde Nast
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chubb offered a fascinating footnote: Of the 70 percent of
on-line subscribers in January who paid with credit cards, the
names of 80 percent of them were not already on file in the
voluminous Conde Nast consumer database, one of the most
comprehensive in consumer marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your Net gains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
