A1152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGAFEATURE-COX     08-09 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGAFEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PGA becomes drive toward an easy Ryder
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINAH, Ill. _ Every other year, it often becomes the more
intriguing aspect to PGA Championship week. The race to win the
season's final major is one thing; the race to the Ryder Cup is
something totally different.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday night, with the Wanamaker Trophy presented, the points
standings will have determined the top 10 players on the U.S. Ryder
Cup team that will play Europe, Sept. 24-26, at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass. On Monday morning in the Medinah Country Club
media center, Ben Crenshaw will make his two ``captain's picks.''
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, nobody will be writing about the PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a foregone conclusion, with the 11th and 12th
players almost automatically added to the team. This year, with 300
final points still available at Medinah, the decision is not quite
so clear-cut
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, by moving up to 11th in the standings with a
runner-up finish Sunday at the Buick Open, has all but clinched one
of Crenshaw's spots. But the second selection is hardly set.
Nothing against Steve Stricker, John Huston or Chris Perry (at Nos.
12-14), but Crenshaw seems more likely to pick known Ryder Cup
commodities with more experience.
</P>
<P>
   The second selection might be No. 16 Fred Couples, who gets more
excited about this event than he does about the average PGA Tour
stop, or No. 22 Lee Janzen, the two-time U.S. Open champion and
two-time Ryder Cup participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one pick may be fairly obvious,'' Crenshaw said. ``The
other one is obviously going to keep me up at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who hasn't won on the PGA Tour since the 1996 Tour
Championship, is pained even to thinkof watching a Ryder Cup from
his living room, after appearances at Oak Hill in 1995 and two
years ago at Valderrama. His record is 3-2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Miffed that both events evolved into European victories, Lehman
longs to be part of a potential retribution week at Brookline. Had
he not blown a four-shot lead in the Buick Open, he would have
jumped automatically into the top 10. He needs to finish alone in
ninth place or better this week to lock up a top-10 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love all that man-on-man stuff,'' Lehman said. ``Ryder Cup,
Presidents Cup, Skins game, Wendy's Three-Tour Challenge _ anything
where it's just you against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples, who has made five Ryder Cup appearances, with a 7-9-4
record, might not be all that inspired these days, after inheriting
a family with his second marriage. But Crenshaw said, ``I know
he'll be there enthusiastic, if I call on him.'' Couples would need
a fourth-place finish Sunday to make the top 10 on points.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are subject to second-guessing, the captain's picks
often bring more attention than players making it through the
two-year points process.
</P>
<P>
   Less than thrilled with the recent comments by David Duval and
others about compensation, Crenshaw welcomed contrasting attitudes
from gung-ho players such as Lehman, who said he would pay his own
money to play; Davis Love III; and Payne Stewart, who clinched a
spot on the team at Pinehurst and already is excited about
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat's off to (Stewart),'' Crenshaw said. ``Obivously, it's
wonderful for the Ryder Cup to hear his comments. He very much
believes in the competition. I think that's pretty extraordinary at
this time in his life to set a goal like that and achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
