<HEADER>
A1154 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THAILAND-CHANGE-2TAKE     08-09 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAILAND-CHANGE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH IN AUTHORITY IS VICTIM OF THAILAND'S ECONOMIC CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ When Sumalee Limpaovart's 6-year-old
daughter was rejected by an exclusive government school earlier
this year, Mrs. Sumalee did something that would have been
unthinkable here only a few years ago: She challenged the decision,
using a new freedom-of-information law to demand the test scores of
the other children.
</P>
<P>
   What started as one mother's private outrage has swelled into a
very public challenge against Thailand's closed and corrupt
bureaucracy, part of a struggle that has turned a society built on
harmony and civility into one that is increasingly argumentative,
litigious and noisy as it searches for democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Mrs. Sumalee found what she had suspected: Fully
one-third of the students admitted had failed the entrance exam;
they got in because of their families' status or gifts to the
school.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one of the many small, sharp battles that are being
fought today between Thailand's past and its possible future.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle reflects an unexpected fallout from the financial
crisis that struck Asia: the shock of the crash prompted widespread
challenges to the political and social status quo, with a bolder
and better-educated middle class challenging the paternalistic
order of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians and bureaucrats who have been in a position to
impose their top-down rule have to contend now with rising public
expectations and rising public pressure,'' said Kavi Chongkitavarn,
a columnist for the newspaper The Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand has found itself culturally adrift, its landscape
disfigured by expensive half-built highways, empty office
buildings, defunct businesses and ruined banks. Though the worst
seems to be past, Thailand must now lower its sights for future
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Politically and socially, the crash only served to clarify the
issues and sharpen the conflicts, several analysts said. People are
demanding more accountability.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand, politicians and the public concluded that a
political system hobbled by rigidity, secrecy and corruption had
contributed to its economic vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in countries as disparate as Singapore, Vietnam and
Malaysia, calls for political openness have grown more insistent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tightly controlled democracy of Singapore, an opposition
politician, Chee Soon Juan, has challenged limits on free speech,
drawing quiet support as he speaks out publicly, then serves brief
jail terms for giving a speech without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   In Communist Vietnam, demands for more democracy have
increasingly circulated underground and peasants have rioted
against corruption. The government has responded by arresting
critics but also by holding highly publicized trials of corrupt
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Malaysia the dismissal and arrest last fall of the former
deputy prime minister, Anwar Ibrahim, ignited a huge and unexpected
outpouring of support, suggesting broad discontent with the
country's suppression of civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Most dramatic was the uprising in Indonesia last year, fueled by
both economic and political grievances, that ousted the longtime
strongman, President Suharto, and immediately replaced him with a
thriving, chaotic democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand a long, slow struggle for democratic reforms took a
big step forward in 1997 with the passage of a new Constitution
that is a blueprint for openness and human rights, a step brought
to the fore in part by the economic decline.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to survey Thai society and say that very little
has changed. Politicians still buy their votes and still represent
wealthy and powerful families and interests. Corruption still
governs life, from law enforcement to the justice system to
government contracts. Wealth and power remain for the most part in
the hands of a small elite.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, primarily because of the new Constitution, the rules of
the game have changed and the country's traditional centers of
power are being challenged:
</P>
<P>
   _The political power of the military has been significantly
reduced. Its procurement activities and secret funds are under
scrutiny. Its control of radio and television is being challenged.
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai took the job of defense minister for
himself, only the second civilian ever to hold the job.
</P>
<P>
   _ The power to issue search and arrest warrants has been taken
from the police and is to be given to the courts, a significant
step in curbing police abuses.
</P>
<P>
   _ An independent Electoral Commission has been formed, removing
the power to manage elections from the powerful and politically
controlled Ministry of Interior.
</P>
<P>
   _ The power of the bureaucracy is to be reduced by a
constitutional mandate for public hearings, though political
analysts foresee a long struggle for full implementation. Pressures
have grown to open up the process of policy formulation to public
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   _ Women's groups and women in the legislature are pressing for
their rights, beginning with the right of married women to keep
their maiden names. The male-dominated Parliament is resisting
desperately, warning of the destruction of family values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Thailand is the most exciting country in Asia today
because every day is a battle,'' said William J. Klausner, a
long-time American analyst of Thai culture who is a professor of
political science at Chulalongkorn University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only in the past few years that the Thais have coined
words for transparency, good governance, civil society, public
hearings and sexual harassment,'' he said. ``Every country in Asia
is at some point in this process, with Vietnam and Burma at one
end, the Philippines and Thailand at the other, and Malaysia and
Indonesia in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   That process may have been muted during the decade or more when
economies were growing and people were content with their lot.
There are those who say Thailand lost touch with its values in a
mad dash for wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people not only sold their soul but they sold their
daughters to become prostitutes,'' said Sulak Sivaraksa, a leading
social critic. ``They blindly believed that money would make them
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution may exist on paper in Thailand, but as Mrs.
Sumalee found, every attempt to implement it seems to become a
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to sound hopeful and optimistic,'' said Suwanna
Satha-Anand, a professor of philosophy at Chulalongkorn University.
``But I come from the perspective of philosophy and tend to see the
deep structures of things. I think cultural conditioning is still
very deep and difficult to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sumalee's challenge involves the potent weapon of public
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   When she began, her neighbors warned her against her crusade.
``They said, `Don't you know that this is the way things work
here?''' Mrs. Sumalee said. ```Do you think you can change the
system all by yourself?'''
</P>
<P>
   But already another parent has filed a similar
freedom-of-information challenge at a second school. And it now
appears likely that all government-run schools will be required in
the future to open their test scores to the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
