<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PURSUES BLACK VOTERS IN A TEXAS FORAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Vice President Al Gore on Monday continued his efforts
to woo black voters as he ventured on another political foray into
Texas, seeking to position himself for what he hopes will be an
eventual presidential race against the Republican front-runner,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Though he never mentioned the governor by name, Gore repeatedly
contrasted himself with Bush by raising issues like gun control,
hate crimes legislation, school vouchers and affirmative action.
Gore also criticized the $792 billion tax cut legislation recently
passed by the Republican-controlled Congress, and endorsed by Bush,
as ``some of the worst handiwork of the Republican right.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the legislation would undermine Social Security and
Medicare. ''It takes courage and conscience to cross those
conservatives who have no compassion,'' Gore said to members of the
National Urban League, who are holding their annual convention in
Houston this week.
</P>
<P>
   The scripted line, which Gore repeated several times during his
speech, was a deliberate rebuke to the ``compassionate
conservatism'' line that has become the early slogan of Bush's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, when he addressed the group in a short
welcoming speech, Bush touted educational reforms in Texas and
talked about the need to help people who have not benefited from
the recent era of prosperity. In front of a group traditionally
sympathetic to Democrats, Bush mentioned ``compassionate'' far more
often than he did ``conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, who is seeking the Democratic presidential nomination,
made certain to raise issues of particular concern to his
predominantly black audience. He called on the House to pass a
pending federal hate crimes bill and criticized the Texas
Legislature for failing to pass a similar bill named after a black
man who was tied to a truck and dragged to his death.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he had met with the family of the man, James Byrd Jr.,
earlier in the day. Though Bush never took a position on the
politically sensitive bill, Democrats blamed his legislative allies
for killing it.
</P>
<P>
   With the process about to get underway for conducting the 2000
census, Gore criticized elected officials in both parties who
opposed changing the counting method. Minority groups, in
particular, have said that the census vastly underestimates the
numbers of blacks and Hispanics, and Gore agreed, saying that Texas
alone had missed out on $1 billion in federal benefits because of
an undercount of its minority population.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also called for background checks of people who purchase
weapons at gun shows. Bush also has publicly supported such checks,
but gun control activists in Texas blamed his allies in the
Legislature for killing a bill this year that would have required
them. Bush did sign a law that prohibits Texas cities from filing
liability lawsuits against gun manufacturers. Several other cities
are suing gun makers, seeking reimbursement for health care and
public safety costs for gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who spoke in Houston less than two weeks ago at the
convention of the Hispanic advocacy organization, the National
Council of La Raza, also ticked off a laundry list of unfavorable
statistics about Texas to an audience of people mostly from other
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, here in Texas, can we be satisfied when
African-Americans are twice as likely to drop out of school, when
on a national basis the black and white high school graduation
rates are just about equal?'' he asked. ``Here in Texas, can we be
satisfied when this state has one of the most regressive tax
systems in the nation? Can we possibly be satisfied when Texas has
the second highest percentage of uninsured children in America?''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism is in direct contrast to Bush's standard stump
speech in which he paints Texas not only as an economic dynamo but
also as a state where conservative policies have improved reading
scores, particularly for minority children, and where diversity is
embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bush, another person that Gore pointedly did not mention
by name was former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who is also
running for the Democratic presidential nomination and who is
scheduled to address the National Urban League on Tuesday. In his
campaign, Bradley has spoken often about race and has made several
overtures to black voters. Last weekend, both he and Gore addressed
the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition in Chicago at a conference organized by
the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Gore reminded his audience Monday of what he described as the
benefits gained by minorities under the Clinton administration,
citing a string of African-American Cabinet appointees and policies
such as empowerment zones and federal loan programs for minority
businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
