<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRST-PICTURESHOW-LAD     08-09 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-PICTURESHOW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGE MUSICAL PAYS TRIBUTE TO WOMEN OF FILM'S SILENT ERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Given Hollywood's historic infatuation with
expensive high-tech toys, it makes perfect sense to Estelle Parsons
that the silent-film era, like the present age, was dominated by
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so much a man's world then,'' says the veteran
Oscar-winning actress, speaking of the industry's infancy. ``Like
with computers (today), it's certainly not a woman's world. Men
characteristically are much more interested in tinkering with any
kind of inanimate object!''
</P>
<P>
   That cheerful thought prompts a sudden explosion from Parsons, a
sound roughly between a cackle and a deranged howitzer.
</P>
<P>
   It also draws a laugh from composer Jeanine Tesori, who has
joined Parsons in a backstage discussion of ``The First Picture
Show,'' a musical play that klieg-lights the silent era's most
unsung but currently hottest heroes: women directors and
screenwriters.
</P>
<P>
   In the show, which opens a six-week run Wednesday at the Mark
Taper Forum, Parsons plays feisty 99-year-old Anne First, a former
Hollywood director and silent film pioneer, now confined to an
old-folks' home.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of her female colleagues, Anne was shoved aside by
male studio honchos when the talkies arrived and movies
metamorphosed from a curiosity into a highly lucrative business.
</P>
<P>
   With a score by Tesori that melds Victorian parlor tunes,
vaudeville, Tin Pan Alley and classical music, ``The First Picture
Show'' is co-authored and jointly directed by David Gordon and Ain
Gordon, the father-son team known for their multimedia, avant
garde-ish assemblages of text-based performance, dance movement and
music.
</P>
<P>
   Originally commissioned by the Mark Taper, the show is a
co-production with the American Conservatory Theater in San
Francisco, where it was presented earlier this year. In Los
Angeles, the cast of 14 will portray 40 different characters. Ellen
Greene portrays Anne in her younger years and also plays her
great-great-niece, a documentary filmmaker determined to tell the
old woman's story.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of women in early Hollywood has consumed large vats
of critical ink lately. A number of recent biographies have
detailed the contributions to film of women directors such as Lois
Weber and Alice Guy Blache (quite possibly the first director, of
any gender, to helm a narrative film) and screenwriters Frances
Marion, Anita Loos, Tess Slesinger and others. Earlier this summer,
the Los Angeles County Museum of Art presented a film series
devoted to some of their works.
</P>
<P>
   But a few years ago, when the Gordons first started talking with
Taper producing artistic director Gordon Davidson about a new show
focusing on censorship in the silent-movie era, they envisioned
their main character as a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're guys, and so we thought of guys,'' Ain Gordon explains
with self-amusement. ``And then I went off to Lincoln Center
looking for information about the censorship, and really I just was
kind of scanning the bookshelves, trying to see what was there. And
I just saw this book that said, `Early Women Directors.' And I sort
of blithely said, `What early women directors? There weren't any.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I pulled it out of the shelf and found that I was not only
totally wrong but not knowledgeable and a fool! And I called David
and said, `There are all these women, and I think we should change
the character to a woman.'''
</P>
<P>
   What shocked the Gordons was the sheer number of women working
in silent-era Hollywood. Though vastly outnumbered by their male
colleagues, a few of these women were incredibly prolific and
financially successful. The Paris-born Blache (1875-1968), for
example, produced, directed and otherwise oversaw nearly 300 films,
primarily between 1896 and 1920, an astonishing number that puts
her in a class with D.W. Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew? Not, she admits, composer Tesori.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until David and Ain gave me all of these incredibly
thick books to read'' that Tesori says she began to comprehend
women's early contributions to film.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Tesori says, because silent movies were still a
game with no rules, women weren't compelled to limit themselves to
weepy melodramas or other stereotypically ``feminine'' genres. They
did everything their male peers were doing: comedies, action films,
historical movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was Lois Weber who started in New Jersey and did
these incredible train shots where she was shooting it from a
car,'' Tesori says. ``The picture I saw, it was really moving! They
were going literally alongside the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, like Tesori, was unfamiliar with early women filmmakers
when she first read the show's script. But she had no trouble
relating personally to the challenges they faced.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has spent the better part of her career on stage,
Parsons, 71, is primarily known to general audiences for her role
as Roseanne's irascible mother on the highly rated sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years ago, she won a best supporting actress Oscar as
the hysterical Blanche in the 1967 ``Bonnie and Clyde,'' an honor
that Parsons has said ``didn't mean a thing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in a previous career, Parsons broke ground as the nation's
first female political reporter for a TV network when the ``Today''
show went on the air. At that time, television was considered an
upstart business not to be taken very seriously _ much as the
movies had been half a century earlier. Consequently, the industry
briefly opened its doors to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very much like (the early days of silent movies), where
whoever was there just did stuff,'' Parsons says. ``And then it
gets more and more stratified or something, codified, organized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of funny, because when women's lib came, there was
this little sense of, `Oh, you're all going to do what I did, and
I'm special because I did it?!'''
</P>
<P>
   Tesori also has a first-hand sense of what it's like blazing
show-biz trails. She belongs to the tiny sorority of women writers
working in the Broadway musical theater, a group that also includes
lyricist Lynn Ahrens (``Ragtime'') and director Julie Taymor (``The
Lion King'').
</P>
<P>
   A former Broadway conductor, Tesori made her musical theater
breakthrough two years ago with ``Violet,'' with lyrics and book by
Brian Crawley. Inspired by Doris Betts' short story ``The Ugliest
Pilgrim,'' it tells of a young woman whose determination to heal a
disfiguring facial scar leads to a journey of spiritual salvation.
It opened in March 1997 at Playwrights Horizons in New York City
and went on to win the New York Drama Critics Circle Award for best
new musical.
</P>
<P>
   Tesori's score, with its ambitious blending of elements of
bluegrass, gospel, country and pop, caught the Gordons' attention
around the time they started working on ``The First Picture Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The show was a lot about women, and we thought it would be
nice if part of the creative team was a woman,'' Ain Gordon says.
``I had some friends who had worked with her (Tesori), and we
talked to lots of people, but we were very interested in her. We
were very lucky. We wooed her.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Parsons, the actress was cast soon after she read the
scipt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Estelle Parsons was interested in (you), would you say
no?'' David Gordon asks, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Parsons' stature as a grand dame of the American stage
is matched by her reputation as an exacting straight-shooter with a
peppery wit. Even Tesori, no shrinking violet herself, says that
Parsons ``used to terrify me'' at first.
</P>
<P>
   But the two women immediately found they shared a style of
working that involved hammering out ideas non-stop and defending
them vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   Tesori also says that, as a new mother, she particularly admires
Parsons for juggling a show-biz career with a family (Parsons and
her lawyer husband have twin daughters, now 34, and a 16-year-old
son, Abraham).
</P>
<P>
   During pre-production, Parsons and Tesori discussed whether a
woman like Anne First could've looked to any older career women for
inspiration. Probably not, they concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I read about women's success, and this is my own
prism perhaps, I always want to know do they have kids,'' Tesori
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I am truly, mostly inspired by people who do that,
because I think that's being an artist in two ways. And you know, I
look at people like Estelle and I see Abraham and he's a great kid
and I think, `OK, I'm going to keep going.' &UR;  &LR; '' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
What: &LR;  ``The First Picture Show.'' &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  Mark Taper Forum, Music Center of Los Angeles County, 135
N. Grand Ave., downtown. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  Wednesday through Sept. 19. Performances 8 p.m. Tuesdays
through Fridays, 2:30 and 8 p.m. Saturdays; 2:30 and 7:30 p.m.
Sundays. &UR;  &QL; 
Tickets: &LR;  $25 to $40. Call (213) 628-2772. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
