<SLUG> BC-FBC-OLEMISS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ole Miss: Cutcliffe has heart of a Rebel
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mississippi coach David Cutcliffe lists it as one of
the strangest and most agonizing experiences of his career.
</P>
<P>
   His team, the Tennessee Volunteers, was playing Florida State
for the national championship, and he was sitting by himself on a
couch in a rented house in Oxford, Miss., watching the game on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the first half by myself, which was strange and kind
of agonizing,'' said Cutcliffe, a 17-year Tennessee assistant
before taking over the Rebels in December when Tommy Tuberville
left to become Auburn's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I couldn't take it anymore. I called (former
Tennessee quarterback) Jerry Colquitt at halftime and told him to
come over and watch it with me. . . . It was an emotional time for
me because of all the relationships I had with those coaches and
those players.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever agony Cutcliffe might have suffered because of the
Vols' win didn't compare with the relief his new players felt when
he was hired.
</P>
<P>
   Cutcliffe, who accepted the job the Monday before Tennessee's
appearance in the SEC Championship Game on Dec. 5, elected to start
the next week. Not coincidentally, the Rebels accepted a bid to
play in the Independence Bowl a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cutliffe might not have realized it at the time, his
decision to forgo possibly winning a national title to begin his
work with the Rebels sent a clear message to the Ole Miss players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant everything in the world to us,'' senior offensive
lineman Todd Wade said. ``It showed that he was dedicated and
committed to being our coach. I don't know what we would've done if
he hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior linebacker Armegis Spearman said: ``That was one of the
biggest things that sold all the players on him as our coach. I
think about it myself, and I'm not sure if I wouldn't have gone to
the championship. That was probably one of the most difficult
decisions of his life, and I respect him for making the one that he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was significant to Cutcliffe in several ways. Not
only was he able to learn about his new team and personnel, he also
was able to get a leg up on recruiting and prove himself to the Ole
Miss faithful. The Rebels thumped Texas Tech 35-18 in the
Independence Bowl, and Cutcliffe's head-coaching career was off to
a flying start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made all the difference in the world,'' Cutcliffe said. ``I
say a prayer of thanks every day that I had a chance to coach that
bowl game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rebels' success in Shreveport, La., only fueled the high
expectations for this season. Ole Miss returns 17 starters from
last year's 7-5 squad and is sanction-free and back to a full
allotment of 85 scholarships for the first time in four years,
after NCAA probation.
</P>
<P>
   At the SEC Football Kickoff last month, Mississippi received 11
first-place votes to win the SEC West Cutcliffe is guarded about
his team's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably a chaser,'' he said. ``We're not a team that
has won a championship or tied for one or even been in a race for
it. So, we have to go out and prove ourselves every Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rebels appear to have the talent to be able to stay in the
race. Among the eight returnees on offense are quarterback Romaro
Miller, who passed for 2,273 yards last year; running back Deuce
McAllister, who became only the second back in school history to
rush for more than 1,000 yards, 1,082; and Wade, a 6-foot-7,
320-pound tackle who earned preseason All-SEC honors.
</P>
<P>
   The defense returns nine starters, led by Spearman, who also was
a preseason All-SEC selection, and senior tackle Kendrick Clancy,
who ``nobody could block in the spring,'' Cutcliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   As for missing the Vols' championship game, Cutcliffe said he's
over that. A little gift from Phillip Fulmer helped the healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I did get a championship ring,'' Cutcliffe said, holding
up the ring finger of his right hand, ``and I'm very proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
