u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ABA-HNS &LR;      08-09 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ABA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES SENATE TO END ITS SLOWDOWN OF JUDICIAL CONFIRMATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Declaring a ``mounting vacancy crisis'' exists in the
federal courts, President Clinton on Monday pressed the
Republican-led Senate to end its slowdown of judicial
confirmations.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton bestowed the Presidential Medal of Freedom on
former President Carter and his wife, Rosalynn.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took aim at the Senate during an address to the American
Bar Association, where he accused the GOP of returning to the
political foot-dragging that marked the 1996 presidential election
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply cannot afford to allow political considerations to
keep our courts vacant and to keep justice waiting,'' Clinton told
the attorneys, adding he would make a renewed push for
confirmations once Congress returns from its August recess.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, halted the confirmation process for six months this year
to force Clinton to nominate a conservative Republican ally, Ted
Stewart, to the Utah bench.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton submitted Stewart's name last month and Hatch's panel
sent the nomination to the floor within 48 hours, far faster than
usual. Some circuit court seats have been vacant for 16 months.
Stewart's nomination, opposed by environmental groups, remains
pending on the Senate calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination process also will likely become entangled in the
2000 presidential campaign. Republicans, if they follow past
patterns of the congressional majority, may become hesitant to act
on judicial confirmations in hope that a GOP candidate will win the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he has made 61 judicial nominations and the Senate
has confirmed 11 and an additional 13 have been reported out of
committee. He said 16 of the 61 vacancies are in jurisdictions
where emergencies have been declared because of the high case
loads.
</P>
<P>
   He likened the Senate slowdown to the political calculations
made in 1996 when Republicans confirmed only 17 judges and refused
to confirm any nominations for the circuit courts during the
election year. There are 800 federal judicial positions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the high vacancy rates and growing case loads
prompted Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist to warn the
Senate that it was undermining the legal system. Clinton
acknowledged that after Rehnquist's warnings Hatch worked with the
administration in a bipartisan effort to fill 65 vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no sooner had we begun to remedy the rising emergency
than, once again, the politics of the Senate began to stop the
confirmation process in its track,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The ABA rallied behind Clinton's call as five former ABA
presidents sent a letter to Senate leaders calling for an end to
``this unprecedented slowdown'' because of the expense and delay
caused in federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The ABA letter also said minority and women judicial candidates
are being disproportionately affected. It noted that of the 10
nominations pending for more than one year, seven are either
minorities or women. Of the 11 judges confirmed this year, eight
are white men, it noted.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Clinton traveled to the Carter Center where he pinned
the Medal of Freedom on the former president and his wife. The
citation praised the Carters for their ``extraordinary
partnership'' in devoting their lives to human rights, democracy,
health care and women's rights around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy and Rosalynn Carter have done more good things for more
people in more places than any other couple on the face of the
Earth,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter called the ceremony ``one of the most beautiful events of
my life.'' He also playfully jabbed Clinton for his upcoming
retirement, suggesting an ex-president's golfing partners are not
so generous with mulligans.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a one-term president defeated in his 1980 re-election
bid by Ronald Reagan, said he and his wife left Washington ``in
something of despair and embarrassment and disappointment and
frustration'' but found a new life in bringing ``the blessings of
America'' to those hungry for freedom and democracy around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have given us unlimited chances, unlimited
opportunities,'' said Rosalynn Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will present the same award later this week to former
President Ford and to former Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen. The Medal of
Freedom is the highest civilian honor bestowed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
