u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      08-09 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING IS SLUGGISH AS MARKET LABORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A sharp rise in long-term interest rates battered
Internet and technology stocks again Monday, pushing the Nasdaq
composite index down for the seventh time in eight sessions.
</P>
<P>
   During a sluggish trading session, the main market gauges staged
small, intermittent rallies that could not be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market is laboring,'' said Andrew Brooks, head of equity
trading at T. Rowe Price Associates in Baltimore. ``It tried to
rally a bunch of times, but then faltered. And until we get a
clearer read from the Fed about when they are finished raising
interest rates, this sort of activity is likely to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy-makers are widely expected to raise
short-term interest rates at their next meeting, on Aug. 24, and
bond traders have been pushing up long-term bond yields ahead of
that session.
</P>
<P>
   In a further negative response to strong July employment data
that were released on Friday, the yield on the benchmark 30-year
bond rose as high as 6.25 percent and settled at 6.23 percent, its
highest level since Nov. 4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Segments of the stock market weathered the rise in rates, but
technology and Internet stocks were punished.
</P>
<P>
   As one consequence, the Nasdaq, which is heavily laden with
technology issues, fell 28.99 points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,518.98.
With the decline, the Nasdaq is down 12 percent from its peak on
July 16, and in the midst of a correction. Wall Street defines a
correction as a selloff of 10 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks fared even worse. TheStreet.com's Internet index
fell 18.36 points, or 3.7 percent, to 480.03.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in technology companies like Cisco Systems, MCI
Worldcom and EMC also pulled down the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index somewhat; it fell 2.49 points, or two-tenths of 1 percent, to
1,297.80.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average slipped, but its decline was
limited because of strength in stocks like Alcoa, General Motors,
Goodyear and financial companies. The blue-chip index dropped 6.33
points, or less than a tenth of 1 percent, to 10,707.70.
</P>
<P>
   Small company stocks continued to struggle. The Russell 2000
index of smaller companies fell 2.15 points, or five-tenths of a
percent, to 425.89.
</P>
<P>
   Market strategists said the slide was likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved from a declining interest rate and inflation
environment to an environment in which interest rates and inflation
are rising,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First
Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very different environment from the last four
years, and the market is marking down prices to reflect that
change,'' he added. ``And the essential message is that the
adjustment process is not finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, declining stocks on the New York Stock Exchange
outpaced advancing issues, this time by a ratio of 3-to-2. Trading
volume on the Big Board was light, at 684.4 million shares. On
Nasdaq, 748.2 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next month, said Nora McAuley-Gitin, a technical
strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., the Dow could test
its June lows of about 10,400 points. If it breaks through that
level, it could fall as low as 10,000, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual stocks, MCI Worldcom fell 3 13/16, to 77 7/16
after the long-distance carrier said it would offer evening
telephone calls for 5 cents a minute. The step follows a similar
move made three weeks ago by its rival, Sprint Corp., and analysts
said a new round of price cuts in the long-distance market could
ensue.
</P>
<P>
   EMC, which said Monday that it had agreed to buy Data General
for $1.22 billion in debt and stock, stumbled after the deal was
announced. EMC closed at 57 1/4 a share, down 2 3/4; Data General
soared 4 5/16, to 17 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Chip makers were the best performers among technology stocks
Monday. Advanced Micro Devices rose 1 7/8 a share, to 19 1/4, after
it introduced its new Athlon microprocessor to compete with Intel's
fastest chips. Intel, which has bucked the trend among technology
companies recently, continued to power ahead. The stock closed at
73 7/16, up 1 7/8. And Applied Materials gained 3 3/16, to 77 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Big losers among Internet stocks included Yahoo, which fell 5
3/4 a share, to 121 3/16; Amazon.com, which dropped 4 1/16, to 85
1/2, and Ebay, which lost 3 5/8, to 79 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, Alcoa gained 3 a share, to 65 5/8. GM rose 2
1/4, to 62 1/2. And J.P. Morgan closed at 124 15/16, up 2.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, though, fell after the chemical maker said the number of
shares in its Conoco exchange offer exceeded the number it planned
to accept and that it would prorate the offer. Investors who bought
DuPont earlier with the idea of converting shares into Conoco might
sell those shares if they are left out of the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont fell 2 3/4, to 71 1/8. Conoco rose 3/4, to 26 5/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
