A1182 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAMPS-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      08-09 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAMPS-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYING STAMPS CAN NOW MEAN JUST A TRIP TO THE COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Beginning another chapter in the history of mail,
the U.S. Postal Service on Monday announced the nationwide
availability of postage that customers can buy over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The stamps downloaded from cyberspace, to be called PC Postage,
are the first new form of postage since the advent of the postage
meter in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service will not offer the digital stamps itself, but
instead will rely on the private sector. Postal officials said
Monday that two start-up companies, E-Stamp Corp. and Stamps.com,
which have been selling the electronic stamps on a test basis, can
now sell their products nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Stamp purchasers will pay for their postage with credit cards
and then will be able to print a special barcode that can be put on
an envelope. Each barcode has a unique digital signature to prevent
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life just became a little bit easier for those who mail,''
said Pam Gibert, a Postal Service vice president. ``With PC
Postage, you can purchase and print postage 24 hours a day, 7 days
a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who use the digital postal service are expected to
be small and medium-sized businesses. Both E-Stamp and Stamps.com
will charge a fee _ about 10 percent _ in addition to the cost of
the stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Two other companies, Pitney Bowes and Neopost, are also offering
the electronic stamps on a test basis and are hoping to eventually
be approved by the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Postal Service announced it was accepting proposals
for the digital delivery of postage, setting off a race among
several start-up companies eager to cash in on the Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service's invitation was based loosely on a design
created by E-Stamp of San Mateo, Calif. E-Stamp's plan requires the
customer to buy a small device that attaches to the back of a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   But Stamps.com, which is located in Santa Monica, Calif., gained
an advantage when it proposed a system with no special hardware
required.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one former postmaster general, Marvin Runyon, who
retired in early 1998, has put his money on Stamps.com. Runyon
invested in the company in February and became a director on the
company's board. The company would not disclose how much Runyon
invested.
</P>
<P>
   Stamps.com sold its first shares of stock to the public in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Fournier, a health insurance broker in Novato, Calif., has
been using the electronic postage since December. Fournier
estimates that the digital stamps have saved him at least 16 hours
that he otherwise would have spent standing in line at the post
office.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he shows up at the post office with a package,
the postal employees often gather around admiring the electronic
stamp. ``They say, `Boy, that's neat,''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
