<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HAMMERS AT BUSH'S STANCE ON INCOME TAX CUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to include updated information) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Vice President Al Gore bashed Gov. George W. Bush's
position on income tax cuts Monday but said it was too early in the
presidential campaign to utter Bush's name.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he disagrees with Bush about helping disadvantaged
people, Gore cited Bush's support for the $792 billion tax-cut bill
passed by the Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really beyond me how any serious candidate for president
could countenance support for a proposal of that kind. It's
reckless,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the leading candidate for the Democratic presidential
nomination in 2000, took his party's line that the tax cut would
unjustly benefit the rich. President Clinton has pledged to veto
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the leading candidate for the Republican nomination for
president, has said he supports the GOP tax-cut bill as the best
way to share the surplus with taxpayers. But after hearing that the
bill also includes a plan for the states to return some money to
the federal government, Bush expressed general support this weekend
for allowing states to keep their money.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole also said
Clinton should sign the tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's remarks about Bush's policies tracked his speech a few
moments earlier to the National Urban League convention in Houston.
Without mentioning Bush by name, he highlighted his disagreements
with the governor on gun control, hate-crime legislation and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vice president's campaign aides have said for weeks
that Gore has trained his sights on Bush, and Gore's remarks have
been widely reported as criticisms of Bush, the vice president said
that it is too early for him to attack Bush by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the holster fits, wear it. If the shoe fits, wear it. Well,
that phrase is a rhetorical phrase that invites you to fill in the
blanks,'' Gore said. ``I just don't feel that we are at the point
in this campaign yet where (using Bush's name) feels appropriate to
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing more complicated than that. Just a gut feeling on my
part,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush clobbers Gore in national voter polls on a would-be general
election match-up.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said he was pleased with this showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy being an underdog,'' he said. ``I am perfectly happy
with where I am 15 months from the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that in his first race for public office, for a U.S.
House seat from Tennessee in 1976, he was expected to finish ``back
in the pack'' behind a leader of the state legislature. Gore, whose
father was a U.S. senator from Tennessee, won the race.
</P>
<P>
   Underdog status aside, Gore said ``there is occasionally a gap''
between how voters feel and how he is being portrayed by the
national media: as a vexed and bumbling candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think that's fine,'' he remarked. ``I have no
complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore dodged questions about whether he will try during the
Clinton administration to outlaw ``racial profiling,'' the police
practice of identifying possible criminal suspects based solely on
their race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has promised to end the policy if elected president.
Democratic opponent Bill Bradley has suggested that Gore should
press Clinton to carry out the deed now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you'll have to ask the president that,'' Gore said when
asked about Bradley's statement. ``The Justice Department has a
number of options under review, and I could give you my position. I
would make it the first civil-rights act of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   But will Gore encourage Clinton to sign an executive order that
puts a ban into place?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, he (Clinton) has done more to advance the case of
civil rights than any president since Lyndon Johnson,'' Gore
responded. ``I think that his record is one that withstands any
scrutiny or attack. As for the state of his dialogue with the
Justice Department, you'll just have to ask him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore brushed aside the idea that any of his presidential
campaign proposals are goals he could have accomplished as the vice
president for almost eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud of what I was able to accomplish from
within,'' he said, adding that the Clinton administration has
brought about a cleaner environment, record-high job growth and the
budget surplus. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
