<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAISING THE REFORM PARTY, BUCHANAN UNNERVES GOP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., N.H.)   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Pat Buchanan praised the Reform Party Monday
in the strongest signal thus far that he is considering seeking
that party's presidential nomination and bolting the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who is now competing for the Republican presidential
nomination, was particularly complimentary of Gov. Jesse Ventura of
Minnesota, the Reform Party's highest ranking elected official, who
could himself seek its presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election of Jesse Ventura was a very healthy thing for
American politics,'' Buchanan said in response to a question from
the audience after he announced his proposals for family farms.
``It keeps these other parties on their toes.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the Reform Party, he said, ``is a reflection of the
fact that the two national parties in Washington, D.C., are more
and more beginning to look like two wings of the same old party,
with the differences between them almost inconsequential.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``There's a vacuum in American politics and third
parties have begun to fill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by reporters after the event, Buchanan refused to
rule out the prospect that he could leave the Republican Party. He
acknowledged that his sister and close adviser, Bay Buchanan, has
talked to Reform Party officials about the possibility that he
might leave the Republican fold. ``My sister talked to somebody
three or four weeks ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a conservative television commentator, was
uncharacteristically tight-lipped when asked about his intentions.
He suggested that rival campaigns were spreading rumors about a
defection to discredit him in the run-up to a straw poll in Ames,
Iowa, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said they were concerned that if Buchanan
makes a third-party run he would deprive their party's eventual
nominee of precious support from conservatives. They said they were
far more unnerved by Buchanan's prospective desertion than that
earlier this summer of Sen. Robert C. Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Smith quit the presidential campaign and Republican Party,
saying the party had abandoned its principles. But the senator is
far less prominent than Buchanan, who has twice before waged
insurgent bids for the Republican nomination. Republican leaders
recalled that Buchanan has long been a devoted Republican who was
an aide in the Nixon White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that Pat Buchanan loves his party and, like
Ronald Reagan, that he would try to change it from the inside of
doing anything to hurt it,'' said David Israelite, the Republican
National Committee's political director.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Buchanan sought to join the Reform Party, his nomination
would be far from assured. The party is already troubled with
tensions between Ventura and its founder, Ross Perot, who lost his
effort to install his own candidate to head the party.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Buchanan's hard-edged conservative stands on issues
like abortion and gay rights contrast with the Reform Party's more
libertarian streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Buchanan, I don't believe, is necessarily a good fit
because Pat Buchanan puts social issues on the front burner,''
Ventura said on Sunday on the CBS News program ``Face the Nation.''
``We in the Reform Party do not put social issues as a
front-burning item. We're more into the normal political government
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps in a nod to Ventura, a former professional wrestler,
Buchanan Monday likened Republicans and Democrats to wrestlers. He
said the leading Republican contender, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, held positions that closely resembled those of President
Clinton on issues like immigration, trade policy and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a professional wrestling match, when one fellow wins
one week and the other wins the next week,'' Buchanan said. ``And
they go out and have a couple of beers after the wrestling match is
over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
