<HEADER>
A1186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JAMAL-COX     08-09 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAMAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson set for face-to-face at camp
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ The great holdout may be about to end.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson and agent Jim Sims
are expected to meet today or Wednesday with coach Dan Reeves and
general manager Harold Richardson in an attempt to get the player
in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is seeking a new contract, and Sims said he's willing
to drop his request for an $8 million signing bonus to about $7.5
million to end the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Richardson) said if Jamal shows some commitment to wanting to
be there, he would consider the structure we (last) talked about,''
said Sims, who cut short a European vacation and on Friday faxed
another proposal to Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Jamal, `If they want to see you, you should go.' He's
not going to go to practice. If we don't get a deal done, or don't
see they're committed, we'll turn around and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves anticipated meeting today with Anderson and Sims, but
learned late Monday that Sims may not make it from Oakland until
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson arrived in Atlanta from Salt Lake City before dawn
Monday, and could show up at camp today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to hear it face to face. I don't know what
difference that makes,'' Reeves said of the team's most recent
offer for a five-year deal worth about $28 million with a $7
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visiting training camp is not good faith. Coming in here and
working out, living up to your contract, that's good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The final year of Anderson's contract calls for $2.6 million in
salary and bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   There is general agreement on a new five-year deal worth $28
million to $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson originally sought a $10 million signing bonus. The
Falcons offered about $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Sims reduced the bonus request to about $8 million;
the Falcons moved toward $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves froze contract talks July 28, the day before training
camp, saying there would be no movement until Anderson showed.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, Anderson and Sims said the player wouldn't show up
without a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   They are now looking for a signing bonus of around $7.5 million,
and they want more money early in the contract. Anderson is seeking
more than $13 million the first three years; the Falcons' last
offer was for around $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold told me money can be moved from the fifth year (when
Anderson's salary would be $9 million),'' Sims said. ``And they can
increase the third year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like the four of us (Reeves, Richardson, Anderson and
Sims) to sit down and negotiate. These were Harold's words: `If
Jamal shows commitment, we'll move numbers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's market value has been more defined by the contract
signed last week by Rams running back Marshall Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   That seven-year deal included a $7 million signing bonus, and
the first four years of the contract are worth about $19.5 million,
similar to what Atlanta offered Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   But Faulk will get a 1999 salary of $2.6 million while the
Falcons offered Anderson considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faulk did what he had to do,'' Sims said. ``There's really not
any comparison other than they're both running backs. The Falcons'
proposal is substantially lower the first two years (than
Faulk's).''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves wants to get on with matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see it resolved because nobody wins this way.
I feel very comfortable we're being fair,'' he said. ``They don't
feel that way. If you don't feel that way . . . come in and . . .
sign (a new contract), or live up to the other one.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
