<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAFING SOURCE OF ELECTRICAL SHORT ABOARD SHUTTLE, NASA SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The electrical short during last month's launching of the
shuttle Columbia was caused by a wire rubbing on a screw head, NASA
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The repeated chafing over many flights had worn away the wire's
insulation. Technicians should have applied Teflon tape to the wire
before the launch as a protective measure, said James Hartsfield, a
spokesman for NASA's shuttle program.
</P>
<P>
   Managers have ordered new inspections on the shuttle Endeavour
to check for similar wear. Endeavour is scheduled for a Sept. 16
liftoff with a sophisticated radar system to map the Earth's
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Eileen Collins, the first ever woman spacecraft
commander, the shuttle Columbia blasted off late July 22 with the
$1.55 billion Chandra X-ray Observatory. Five seconds after launch,
a short disrupted the primary computers on two of Columbia's three
main engines.
</P>
<P>
   Backup controllers took over, but had they faltered Collins and
her four crewmates would have been forced to attempt an
unprecedented emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's engine controllers were ruled out as the source of
the short soon after Columbia returned to the Kennedy Space Center
in Florida from its successful five-day flight. Over the weekend,
engineers found a charred segment of an electrical wire leading
from the shuttle's crew compartment to the engine compartment.
</P>
<P>
   The short occurred in the shuttle's mid-body, in an
unpressurized area beneath the payload bay, where further burning
was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield said the chafed wiring was close to a screw head that
was ``roughened.'' The insulation around the original wire had been
rubbed away by repeated contact with the fastener over 26 shuttle
flights and 20 ferry flights during which Columbia had been bolted
atop a Boeing 747 jumbo jet and transported across country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard procedure, although it is up to the
interpretation of the technician working on it, is that when you
see a screw or a rough place in proximity to any of the wiring on
the orbiter is that you put some protective tape over the wiring,''
said Hartsfield. ``The point is our procedures would keep you from
having this kind of situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the electrical short, Columbia also experienced a
small leak of explosive hydrogen during its climb to orbit. The
leak caused the shuttle to reach a slightly lower orbit than
planned. Had it been worse, the leak could have prompted an
emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers believe a loose, 1-inch-long pin inside one of the
rocket engines was hurled through the combustion chamber, striking
three small coolant lines filled with hydrogen in the nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three reusable rocket engines assigned to Endeavour's
upcoming flight also had an identical pin in its oxygen injection
system. Another engine without a pin has been substituted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
