<HEADLINE>
THE BEST AND THE BRIGHTEST FLOCK TO WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a constant parade of celebrities appearing at
congressional hearings, reports the Hill, including such familiar
faces as  &UR; Mary Tyler Moore &LR;  (who speaks on funding for diabetes
research),  &UR; John Travolta &LR;  (freedom for Scientologists);  &UR; Ted &LR; 
 &UR; Danson &LR;  (the oceans),  &UR; Sugar Ray Leonard &LR;  (anti-drug abuse) and
 &UR; Richard Gere &LR;  (Tibet).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eric Dezenhall &LR; , Washington consultant and author of ``Nail
'Em!: Confronting High-Profile Attacks on Celebrities and
Businesses'' (Prometheus; $27.95), said that celebrities are a
``huge, huge draw,'' and that ``in terms of getting your issue on
Leno, you can't beat it. There's a 100 percent chance that a
celebrity will get media coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, pitfalls. ``They &LR;  key to using a
celebrity,'' he said, ``is rationing, to know what they're there
for and what they're not there for. Really, some of them are just
breathtakingly stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. After naming a congressional bill, &LR;  ``Put Your Money Where
Your Mouth Is: The VA Dentists Equity Act,'' Rep.  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Filner &LR; , D-Calif., was apparently so pleased with himself that he
asked other lawmakers to follow suit: ``I hereby challenge my
colleagues to do their best _ be it corny, cheesy, juvenile or wry
_ at least make the title of your bill something fun! Who knows
what a little laughter may accomplish?''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. Elsewhere in congressional flights of fancy, Rep.  &UR; Sue &LR; 
 &UR; Myrick &LR; , R-N.C., has sent all her colleagues a letter _ quoted in
Roll Call _ that begins by praising the altruism of the late
 &UR; Mother Teresa &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The letter goes on: ``Recently, my husband and I bought a
picture-perfect watermelon, took it to our apartment and sat it on
the kitchen floor, intending to savor the summer treat in a couple
of days. Upon returning that evening, we were overwhelmed by an
incredibly putrid odor. The watermelon had erupted, sending an
unbelievable torrent of rotten liquid across the kitchen, under the
dishwasher, under the wall into the dining area, saturating yards
of carpet. We had no warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of America as a beautiful watermelon,'' continues
Myrick, tying this metaphor in to the concept of Mother Teresa's
commitment to trying to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Myrick's chief of staff told Roll Call that the letter had been
well-  &LR; received, &LR;  and that his boss had been approached by a number
of members who said they appreciated it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
