<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KY-PLUTONIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON PROMISES TO HELP KENTUCKY URANIUM WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., S.C., Ohio, Wash.)  (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department will expand its promise of
finding and compensating workers made sick in its bomb-production
factories to include employees at a giant Kentucky plant that
processed uranium for bombs and military reactors, Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear wastes and plutonium, which are even more dangerous than
uranium, were mixed in with the uranium at the Paducah Gaseous
Diffusion Plant.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the department would look at health of employees
at the plant, where uranium is sorted to separate the type that is
easily split in reactors and bombs. Industrial hygeine at the plant
was poor for decades, department officials say, but they are now
looking into how those problems may have been made more serious by
the presence of plutonium and other materials. Uranium is a toxic
metal but is not highly radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   A contractor, Lockheed Martin Energy Systems, prepared a report
in 1992 that said the plant had used more than 100,000 tons of
recycled uranium that included plutonium and other contaminants
that were far more dangerous than those in the compound based on
virgin uranium that Paducah usually processed. A trade journal,
Nuclear Fuel, carried an article on the report at the time, and
environmentalists have intermittently discussed the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson made his announcement after The Washington Post
reported on Sunday that plant workers may have been made sick by
plutonium, but he said his department had been looking into the
matter since June, because ``we had an inkling of the problem
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts familiar with the situation said the ``inkling''
was a suit brought under the False Claims Act against contractors
who operated the plant for the government. The act allows private
parties to sue if they believe the government has been cheated. The
suit, which was brought by the Natural Resources Defense Council,
an environmental group, is now sealed to give the Justice
Department an opportunity to decide if it wants to join. The suit
reportedly accuses the contractors of improperly disposing of
materials and polluting the surrounding land.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department and other agencies have documented
extensive contamination at the site, in western Kentucky near the
Ohio River.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Monday, Richardson said the
department and its predecessor, the Atomic Energy Commission, knew
that the recycled material had been used and were aware of a 1992
study by a contractor, Martin Marietta Energy Systems, reviewing
the use of the recycled material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it's an issue now,'' Richardson said, ``is that I
have now made a determination that if a worker has an ailment that
is connected with any type of radiation, then the government must
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said, ``We owe a great debt to the work force at
Paducah, and we are fully investigating these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson announced last month that the department would seek
to compensate weapons plant employees made ill by exposure to
beryllium, a metal used in making nuclear bombs. He said on Monday
that he would try to add to that legislation, which has not yet
been submitted to Congress, to cover those exposed to radioactive
materials at Paducah as well.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said they were reviewing records of urine
samples taken from Paducah workers over the years, and might also
ask workers and former workers to submit to body scans to test for
radioactive materials.
</P>
<P>
   The recycled uranium, a small amount of which was sent to
similar plants, at Oak Ridge, Tenn., and Portsmouth, Ohio, was
mostly uranium that had run through reactors at the Hanford nuclear
reservation, in Washington state, or Savannah River, near Aiken,
S.C., in the process of making plutonium for bombs. But the
chemical processing plants that sorted out the plutonium did not
recover all of it before it went to Paducah and the other plants;
likewise, some highly radioactive fission products remained in the
uranium.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said that the plutonium would be a hazard but that other
materials, including Technetium-99, might be more of a hazard
because they are far more radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 report by Lockheed Martin said that the use of the
recycled material, from 1953 to 1976, would make the Paducah plant
much harder to decontaminate, because workers who did the job would
have to wear respirators and protective clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Michaels, the department's assistant secretary for
environment, safety and health, who met with union officials at
Paducah on Monday afternoon, said in a telephone interview, ``I
will do everything in my power to get to the bottom of these
allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're to determine are there any hazards now facing the
workers or the community, and if we've done anything in the past
that has made people sick, we want to take care of them.''
Thousands of workers were employed by the plants during the decades
that the recycled uranium was processed.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said a preliminary evaluation in June had found no
imminent hazards at the plant, much of which is now privately owned
and operated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
