<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BANK-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS' RECOVERY IN INDONESIA IS COMPLICATED BY SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ The head of the powerful agency entrusted with
bailing out Indonesia's graft-ridden financial system offered to
resign Monday as allegations of corruption threatened to discredit
his own organization.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a scandal that highlights the paradoxes of a
government's efforts to disinfect itself, the chairman of the
Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency, Glenn M.S. Yusuf, said that
he was ready to step aside temporarily so that his agency could be
cleared of charges that a senior official helped President B.J.
Habibie's political party siphon 550 billion rupiah ($78 million)
in campaign funds from a bank under the agency's control, Bank
Bali.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to conduct a proper investigation, it is better
that related parties, including myself, step aside if needed,''
Yusuf said. The agency said it was investigating the matter and
would publish the results, possibly within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's finance minister said Friday that Indonesia's
Supreme Audit Agency, which answers directly to Indonesia's House
of Representatives, would also look into the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's necessary for IBRA that we clarify the case,'' Finance
Minister Bambang Subianto told reporters at a seminar on investment
in Indonesia, referring to the bank restructuring agency's acronym.
This effort is part of the government trying to avoid the emergence
of other problems which, in turn, could hamper the bank
restructuring process.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie faces a difficult re-election campaign in November
following his party's second-place finish in June's national
parliamentary elections. The latest scandal buttresses allegations
by opposition politicians that his party, Golkar, is using
government money to help finance Habibie's campaign. Both Golkar
and the rival Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle, which won
the most votes in June parliamentary elections, announced that they
would conduct their own investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta's business leaders also watching the Bank Bali case to
see how the bank restructuring agency weather's the latest assault
on its integrity. The agency was created early last year at the
behest of the International Monetary Fund, which has provided more
than $40 billion in aid to Indonesia to help it recover from the
Asia economic crisis that began two years ago. Since then, IBRA has
closed 66 banks, taken over 12, merged 4 into the nation's largest
single bank and is meanwhile helping raise the more than $35
billion needed to save the country's 9 surviving banks. Its
takeovers have left the agency with a portfolio of assets
equivalent to at least one-fifth of the entire Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
   The agency needs to raise 17 trillion rupiah by spring from
asset sales to help the government offset 34 trillion rupiah in
interest payments on bonds it has issued to help recapitalize the
nation's surviving banks. Doing so means wresting control of assets
from the nation's powerful political elite, people with close
connections to Habibie and Suharto.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Bank Bali imbroglio is just the latest obstacle the agency
has faced. In addition to aggravating bureaucratic tangles, Yusuf
has been criticized because he is also heads an investment bank
advising the agency. Foreign investors have accuse the agency of
stalling on asset sales to prevent them from falling into foreign
hands; local property owners accuse the agency of trying to sell
the nation out.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Britain's Standard Chartered PLC agreed to buy a fifth
of family-owned Bank Bali, but the deal fell through in part
because Standard Chartered discovered that the cost of
recapitalizing the bank was roughly double initial estimates. IBRA
was forced to take the bank over last month while a new deal was
worked out for Standard Chartered to double its purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Then late last month, a prominent Indonesian legal expert
accused the agency's deputy chairman, Pande Lubis, of arranging for
Bank Bali to pay 550 billion rupiah to businessmen to help it
secure the repayment of 904 billion rupiah in delinquent interbank
loans from two banks IBRA had already taken over. Most of the fees
Bank Bali paid allegedly ended up at a local finance company called
Era Giat Prima. The head of that company, Setya Novanto, is also
vice treasurer of Golkar, the political party of former president
Suharto and current president, Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   Pande has issued no statement concerning the charges, and he
could not be reached for comment. Reports Monday said he had been
temporarily suspended from the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Yusuf has said the agency had discovered the payments when it
nationalized Bank Bali July 23, and that part of the 550 billion
rupiah had indeed been paid to Era Giat Prima. In a statement last
week, IBRA said that its payments to Bank Bali were part of its
continuing work to honor obligations between banks and that Bank
Bali's agreement with Era Giat Prima had not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
