<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE SECURITIES REGULATORS URGE DAY-TRADING CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   Many day-trading firms use deceptive marketing practices to lure
customers into a stock trading strategy that will probably cause
them to lose money, and then they help to keep them trading by
arranging what could be illegal loans, according to the North
American Securities Administrators Association, a group of state
regulators. In a report, the regulators urged the firms to do a
better job of screening potential customers and to disclose more
fully the risks. The group also asked national regulators to step
up their enforcement of trading rules and to ban some of the
day-trading industry's most common lending practices.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANCED MICRO INTRODUCES CHIP
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Devices introduced the Athlon microprocessor,
which has higher performance than the fastest chips made by Intel,
and said that IBM and Compaq had already committed to using the
chip in some computers. Shipments of the Athlon to computer makers
began last month, the company said, adding that it expected PCs
that use the chip to be available later this month. Advanced Micro
shares closed at $19.25, up $1.875.
</P>
<P>
   TRUSTEE FOR A.R. BARON IN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The trustee for the liquidation of A.R. Baron, a brokerage firm
that defrauded investors of $75 million before it failed in 1996,
is in negotiations with Bear Stearns Securities to resolve claims
relating to the smaller firm's failure. A resolution may require
Bear Stearns to pay more than the $38.5 million it agreed to in a
settlement with the S.E.C. last week.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. DISMISSES OIL TRADE ALLEGATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department dismissed accusations of unfair trade
practices against Mexico and three other oil-exporting countries,
heading off a potential economic and political crisis for Mexico
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   RETAILERS SETTLE SWEATSHOP SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom, J. Crew and other retailers settled accusations
against them in a Federal suit that poses one of the biggest
challenges ever against American sweatshops.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA BANS IMPORT OF FRENCH WINE
</P>
<P>
   In a move that baffles French officials and businessmen, Chinese
customs authorities have suspended the import of all wine from
France. The authorities have also ordered retailers in many cities
to take French wine off the shelves, citing reports that vineyards
in a few provinces of southern France were ignoring a ban on a
byproduct of bovine blood because of concern over the possibility
of a connection with ``mad cow'' disease. French officials say none
of the vineyards have ever exported wine anywhere, much less to
China.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL SCANDAL IN INDONESIA
</P>
<P>
   The head of the agency entrusted with bailing out Indonesia's
financial system offered to step down as accusations of corruption
threatened to discredit his organization.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WORLDCOM CUTS SOME RATES
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom said that it had cut its evening, overnight and
weekend calling rates to as little as 5 cents a minute, a move that
is likely to add to price pressure in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH OF LABOR LEADER ALTERS TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected death of a labor leader over the weekend makes it
likely that Ford will be the lead company in negotiations for an
industrywide labor contract.
</P>
<P>
   POSTAGE TO BE SOLD ON INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service announced the availability of postage,
called PC Postage, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   WIATT JOINS WILLIAM MORRIS AGENCY
</P>
<P>
   Three days after resigning as co-chairman of International
Creative Management, a top talent agency, James Wiatt was named
president of the rival William Morris agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
