<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO KILLERS INSPIRED YOUTH IN GEORGIA SHOOTING, NOTE SAYS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ A 15-year-old boy charged in the shooting of six
classmates at his high school here on May 20 had left a letter
under his bed expressing admiration for the two teen-agers who
killed 12 students, a teacher and themselves at a Colorado high
school exactly a month earlier, according to testimony in a
juvenile-court hearing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is being held in this suburb east of Atlanta to
determine whether the boy, T.J. Solomon, should be tried as an
adult.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon's letter, handwritten on notebook paper, was read aloud
by a Georgia Bureau of Investigation agent. It revealed teen-age
despair, at one point saying that ``even the smallest of scars can
run deep,'' and expressed allegiance to his ``brothers and sisters
related to the trench coat mafia.'' The so-called trench coat mafia
was a group of social outcasts at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., who dressed in black trench coats. The Columbine
killers, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, were fringe members of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his letter, Solomon wrote that he would be
``laughing at my victims as they drop to their knees. Praying for
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents said that in addition to the letter they had found
beneath Solomon's bed three pages of bomb-building instructions
printed from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was apparently unable to carry out his threat of
planting bombs in his school, Solomon walked into Heritage High
School with a sawed-off .22-caliber rifle strapped to his leg and a
.357-caliber handgun tucked into his pants, then fired into a
crowded common area just before the homeroom bell rang.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was reached by the juvenile-court judge, William
Schneider, and the hearing is scheduled to continue on Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Classmates of Solomon, some of them friends and some of them
victims, testified at the hearing that Solomon had bragged that he
could do better than the Columbine shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it should have happened to our school a long time
ago,'' said Trey Carver, a freshman who said he had frequently
eaten lunch with Solomon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
