<SLUG> BC-BARON-BEARSTEARNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARON CASE TRUSTEE CONTINUES PRESSURE ON BEAR STEARNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The trustee for the liquidation of A.R. Baron, a
brokerage firm that defrauded investors of $75 million before it
failed in 1996, is in negotiations with Bear Stearns Securities
Corp. to resolve claims relating to the smaller firm's failure.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution of the matter may require Bear Stearns to pay more
than the $38.5 million it agreed to in a settlement with the
Securities and Exchange Commission last week.
</P>
<P>
   If the trustee's negotiations with the clearing unit of the Bear
Stearns Companies are not successful, the trustee is prepared to
sue the brokerage firm to reach its objective of paying Baron
customers and creditors all of their allowable claims.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bear Stearns agreed to settle SEC charges that it
helped commit a securities fraud in its role of processing trades
for Baron. The SEC charged that Bear Stearns ignored obvious and
repeated evidence of securities fraud at Baron and did what it
could to keep the smaller firm and its fraudulent practices going.
Bear Stearns neither admitted nor denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its settlement, Bear Stearns agreed to pay $38.5
million in fines and restitution to Baron clients wronged by the
firm's misconduct. The restitution fund will receive $30 million
under the settlement and should be set up by early September.
</P>
<P>
   Distributions are to be overseen by the A.R. Baron trustee,
James W. Giddens, a lawyer at Hughes Hubbard &AMP; Reed in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns said its settlement deal was ``a prudent business
decision undertaken to end what has become a distraction for the
company, its shareholders, its employees and its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giddens clearly thinks that the firm's full responsibilities
in the matter have not yet been resolved. ``Serious settlement
discussions have been going on for several weeks,'' he said. ``We
hope to resolve this matter satisfactorily by the time the
restitution fund is created in early September. But in view of the
egregious nature of Bear Stearns' conduct and substantial losses
suffered by A.R. Baron customers, we are fully prepared to litigate
the estate's claims, if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Bear Stearns declined to comment on settlement
talks the firm is conducting with the Baron trustee.
</P>
<P>
   The trustee has initiated lawsuits against more than 100
principals and insiders of Baron seeking to recover some $80
million. ``Our objective is to pay all A.R. Baron creditors 100
percent of their allowable claims,'' Giddens said. Customers of the
firm asserting that they lost money through Baron's manipulation of
stocks or other illegal activities account for the bulk of the
claims Giddens is seeking to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Included among these customers are roughly 10 arbitration cases
brought against Bear Stearns by Baron investors who lost money when
the firm failed.
</P>
<P>
   A class-action suit is also pending against Bear Stearns for its
role in the Baron failure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
