<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT CANDIDATES LIST NARROWED TO 15 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The list of finalists for two vacancies on the state's
highest court has been narrowed to 15, including an Indonesian-born
probate judge, a former legal aide to former Governor John Volpe,
and an openly gay appeals court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci is set to announce his nominees to
replace justices Charles Fried and Herbert Wilkins before Labor
Day, in what may be the closest-watched appointments of his term so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, who has an opportunity to dramatically reshape the
Supreme Judicial Court during his term, will consider 15 lawyers,
including 11 women and several racial minorities, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor faces some pressure to diversify the seven-member
court, after choosing white men for most of 34 lower court slots.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists include 12 judges and three practicing lawyers.
Five appeals court judges are under consideration. They include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Barbara Lenk, a Harvard Law School graduate and openly gay
former partner at Brown, Rudnick, Freed &AMP; Gesmer. Lenk did first
amendment work at the firm. In 1993, she became a Superior Court
judge for three years. She served as chair of the board of editors
for the Boston Bar Journal. She also has a PhD from Yale in
political philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   -- Francis Spina, who has been an appeals court judge since
1997, and served on the Superior Court for four years. The graduate
of Boston College Law School is from Pittsfield, and launched his
career with the Western Massachusetts Legal Services. An
Italian-American, he also served as an assistant district attorney
in Berkshire County and spent about a decade in private practice.
He is also the former president of the Berkshire Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   -- Christopher Armstrong, who became an associate justice in
1972. He graduated from Yale University and Yale Law School. He is
no stranger to politics, having served as assistant legal council
to former governor's John Volpe and was chief counsel to former
Gov. Sargent.
</P>
<P>
   -- Charlotte Anne Perretta, a Suffolk Law School alum, who
became an associate Appeals Court Justice in 1978. An appointee of
former Governor Michael S. Dukakis, she began her career working
with Crane, Inker &AMP; Oteri.
</P>
<P>
   -- Elizabeth A. Porada, a Northampton native who also served as
a district and Superior court judge. Porada, a graduate of
Radcliffe and Boston University Law School, also practiced law in
Northampton for 18 yeras.
</P>
<P>
   Several Superior Court judges have also made the cut, including:
</P>
<P>
   -- Judith Cowin, a 1970 Harvard Law School graduate, who went to
Wellesley College as an undergraduate. She was a prosecutor in the
Norfolk County DA's office from 1979 to 1991, when she ascended to
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   -- Margot Botsford, who was appointed to the Superior Court in
1989 by Dukakis. The New York native graduated cum laude from
Barnard College and Northeastern University School of Law, and
worked at Hill &AMP; Barlow and the attorney general's office. She is
considered a long-shot because of her ties to Dukakis. She is
married to Stephen Rosenfeld, who was Dukakis' legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   -- Martha Sosman, who co-founded an all-female law firm with a
group of women from a US attorney's office in Boston. She graduated
from the University of Michigan Law School in 1979 and went to
Foley, Hoag. Sosman, a gifted pianist, was also an assistant U.S.
attorney under William F. Weld.
</P>
<P>
   -- Daniel Toomey, who Weld appointed to the Superior Court in
1992. He was born in Cambridge, went to Boston University Law
School and Boston College. Toomey has been a district court judge,
also served as an assistant attorney general, a first assistant
district attorney and was the chief appeals attorney for the
Massachusetts Defenders Committee.
</P>
<P>
   -- Allan van Gestel, who was a parnter at Goodwin, Procter &AMP;
Hoar for 26 years, where he did very complex civil litigation
cases. Van Gestel lacks the long track record of the other judges,
having joined the court in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates from the bench include:
</P>
<P>
   --Timothy Gailey, a district court judge in Lynn. Gailey is a
graduate of Harvard College and Harvard Law School, and was a law
clerk for the US Court of Appeals in Boston. Gailey worked at the
Executive Office of Consumer Affairs in the late 1980s, and also
served as the state Insurance Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   -- Middlesex Probate court judge Fernande R.V. Duffly, born in
Indonesia, was at Warner &AMP; Stackpole from 1978 to 1992, including
six years as a partner.
</P>
<P>
   There are also three women who are not currently serving as
judges:
</P>
<P>
   -- Margaret Burnham, an African-American, who is a partner at
Burnham &AMP; Hines, which specializes in civil and criminal
litigation. She began her career with the NAACP Defense Fund in New
York. She served on the Boston Municipal Court in 1977 until 1983,
when she was named executive director of the National Conference of
Black Lawyers. She is married to well-known criminal defense lawyer
Max Stern. Burnham is considered an expert in legal history and
constitutional civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   -- Renee Landers, also an African-American, is active in the
Boston Bar Association, where she chairs the diversity committee.
Landers started her career at Ropes &AMP; Gray. She went to BC Law and
later taught there. From 1993 to 1996 she served as deputy
assistant attorney general for policy development at the US
Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cynthia Cohen is a personal injury lawyer at Meehan, Boyle &AMP;
Cohen of Boston, which has held the record for a personal injury
settlement. She is in line to become the next president of the
Massachusetts Bar Association and is also very active in Democratic
political circles. She lives in Cambridge, graduated from Brown
University and Harvard Law School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
