<SLUG> BC-MCI-WORLDCOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS AT MCI WORLDCOM HIT ITS DATA NETWORK USERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Ill.)   (af)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hundreds of corporate users of one of MCI Worldcom Inc.'s big
data networks were suffering problems ranging from slowdowns to
outright failures Monday. The problems began Thursday night, the
company said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom is the nation's No. 2 long-distance communications
carrier, after AT&AMP;T Corp. Last April, AT&AMP;T suffered a similar
problem, one that diluted the quarterly financial results for the
company's unit that serves business customers. As did AT&AMP;T, MCI
Worldcom is having a problem with one of its frame relay networks.
</P>
<P>
   Frame relay is a data networking technology used by many
companies to connect offices in different cities. In addition to
proprietary data, Internet information and sometimes telephone
calls can be transported using frame relay technology.
</P>
<P>
   Of the several thousand customers of the MCI frame relay
network, about 30 percent had been affecte by the problems, which
were concentrated on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   An MCI spokesman said the data communications unit, which
includes the frame relay operation, generated $1.8 billion in
revenue last quarter. The company's total revenue was $8.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Data Research Associates Inc., a company based in
St. Louis that develops software for library networks, said Monday
afternoon that they were suffering serious problems with their
frame relay service provided by MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   Bridge News reported Monday that the Chicago Board of Trade's
electronic trading system had not worked properly since Thursday
because of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The problems began Thursday as the company upgraded software for
frame relay switches made by Lucent Technologies Inc. Spokesmen for
both companies, however, said that the underlying cause had not yet
been determined and that MCI Worldcom had conducted similar
upgrades in recent weeks without incident.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom said the network glitches were not related to the
so-called Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's frame relay failures were caused by improper software for
switches made by Cisco Systems Inc., one of Lucent's main
competitors. AT&AMP;T cited the failure for a decline in earnings
before interest and taxes in the company's business-services unit
in the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
