<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRIS-WIATT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LEAVING ICM, JAMES WIATT BECOMES PRESIDENT OF WILLIAM
MORRIS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Only three days after resigning as co-chairman of
International Creative Management, a top talent agency, James A.
Wiatt was named president of the rival William Morris agency
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt took along such high-priced clients as Eddie Murphy and
Sylvester Stallone as well as directors including Nora Ephron,
Penny Marshall, Richard Donner and Reny Harlin and Kevin
Williamson, the writer-producer.
</P>
<P>
   Though somewhat expected, the speed of the change startled other
talent agents in Hollywood. The swiftness is underscored by the
fact that by Tuesday, Wiatt will start working for the longtime
rival to ICM. On Tuesday night, Wiatt plans to attend the premiere
of ``Bowfinger,'' a comedy starring Murphy, accompanied by some
William Morris agents.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt quit ICM on Friday after numerous disagreements with Jeff
Berg, the co-chairman and longtime head of the talent agency. At
William Morris, Wiatt will replace Arnold Rifkin, who represented
Bruce Willis, Whoopi Goldberg and several other stars.
</P>
<P>
   Rifkin said he did not want to extend his current contract,
which had a year left. But several agents at William Morris said
that the agency's board was somewhat unhappy that more high-priced
clients had not been signed in recent years, and Wiatt's
availability led them to make the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to inject this agency with a different vitamin,''
said one top agent at William Morris. Several William Morris agents
said they had mixed emotions about the departure of Rifkin, a
sometimes difficult but also dynamic figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Morris agency described Rifkin's departure after seven years
as ``friendly and amicable'' and said that he would remain in his
office until Labor Day to work with Wiatt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make this a clean, classy exit,'' said Rifkin,
who was expected to depart with a hefty severance package.
``There's no acrimony. I'm going to help Jimmy make the
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Rifkin said he was unsure about his future. ``I've been an agent
for 25 years,'' he said. ``I can't say I know anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis, Rifkin's most important client, said, ``I continue
to support my friend and partner of 15 years in whatever choice he
makes in business and his life.'' The movie star said that he
remained Rifkin's ``biggest fan.''
</P>
<P>
   The fallout of the agency change is expected to ripple across
Hollywood. Wiatt's former agency, ICM, was the most hurt by the
departures. Though top executives there said that Murphy and other
stars were booked in films for several years and that the agency
would continue to collect its fees, Wiatt's exit may lead to
further departures by agents, and their clients, to William Morris.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, William Morris may face the exit of several agents
because of Wiatt's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   But Wiatt, who met several William Morris agents separately at
his home Monday morning, said: ``I'd be surprised if anybody left.
Why would they leave? I'm pretty good at making people feel good,
and I want to provide an environment where people wouldn't want to
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt said he had never been to the William Morris agency
headquarters in Beverly Hills, less than two miles from the offices
of ICM.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I'll ever walk into the William Morris agency
will be tomorrow morning,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
