<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ASKS COURT TO ALLOW UNCENSORED SCHOOL PRAYER AT EVENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ala., Colo., Kansas, La., Miss., Neb., S.C. and Tenn.) 
 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas has joined eight other states in asking
the U.S. Supreme Court to allow uncensored prayer at public school
commencements and sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief filed Monday, the states maintained that a 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals ruling that allows student-initiated,
non-sectarian, non-proselytizing prayer at commencements but not at
sporting events conflicts with a recent 11th Circuit Court of
appeals ruling that student-initiated prayer is protected by
constitutional free-speech protections.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe Independent School District in Galveston County has
appealed the 5th Circuit ruling to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The states asked that the Supreme Court consider the Santa Fe
case so the law will be the same all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush added his name to the brief filed by
Attorney General John Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   Other states joining in the filing of the brief by Texas
officials are Alabama, Colorado, Kansas, Louisiana, Mississippi,
Nebraska, South Carolina and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows students to gather for voluntary prayer at school
but prohibits school districts and officials from initiating and
sponsoring prayer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
