<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CASTLE-SFCHRON &LR;      08-09 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CASTLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERROR IN THE BLOOD: HORROR FILMMAKER'S DAUGHTER IS UP TO
HER  FATHER'S OLD TRICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STACK  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIBURON, Calif. _ Terry Castle may be the only movie producer in
America who can get away with splattering fake blood on
kindergartners. The daughter of legendary B-grade horror filmmaker
William Castle says it's in her genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the blood to the classroom for fun but also to show
kids that in the movies it's just Karo syrup and not really all
that scary,'' said Castle, 41. ``What was scary was accidentally
splattering the stuff on the teacher's dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Castle, who lives in Marin County, north of San Francisco, and
is former executive in charge of production for Nickelodeon's ``Are
You Afraid of the Dark?,'' keeps an exhausting schedule these days,
carpooling kids in a Volvo station wagon while also producing
films.
</P>
<P>
   She's on a mission to return her father's name to the limelight.
William Castle, one of Hollywood's most audacious showmen in the
'50s and '60s (he also produced ``Rosemary's Baby''), died in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Castle is co-producer of a forthcoming Warner Bros. remake
of her father's 1958 cult classic ``House on Haunted Hill,'' which
starred Vincent Price. On the production team are high-profile
moviemakers Joel Silver, Robert Zemeckis (``Forrest Gump'') and Gil
Adler. Geoffrey Rush stars with Famke Janssen (``GoldenEye'') in
the movie, due out this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Castle said the production team, under the banner of Dark Castle
Productions, may also retool other Castle classics such as ``The
Tingler,'' ``Macabre'' and ``Homicidal.'' Zemeckis is a longtime
fan of Castle's films.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond her deals with Warner Bros., Castle has reopened her
father's old production company. It gives her dibs on an array of
scripts and promotional gimmicks that were never used.
</P>
<P>
   ``William Castle Productions is up and running again,'' she said
in her small Marin office, surrounded by photographs and
memorabilia of Castle's glory days as producer, director and one of
Hollywood's marketing geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a remarkable creative force,'' she said. ``Ideas would
spill out of him. He'd make a film in seven days. The original
`House on Haunted Hill' had a budget of $150,000. In a few months
it made $2 million.''
</P>
<P>
   With that film, Castle introduced one of his most noted
gimmicks, a creation called Emergo. At a certain point in the
movie, a skeleton flew above the audience and in front of the
screen, carried on a rope attached to pulleys.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Castle said, audiences were ``scared witless.''
``Later, when everybody knew it was fake, they'd just throw popcorn
at the bones,'' she said. ``But they always had fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Castle said the revived William Castle Productions is developing
a psychological thriller, ``Point Dume,'' about a young woman who
learns that she is to become a murder victim. The picture, named
after a rocky outcropping north of Malibu, is being written by D.J.
MacHale, creator of ``Are You Afraid of the Dark?''
</P>
<P>
   Castle also plans films for teens and preteens, and last week
she announced development of a kids' thriller set in a medieval
castle, titled ``Rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father started his theatrical career at age 15, working with
Bela Lugosi on a stage version of ``Dracula.'' As a young man he
took over Orson Welles' Stony Creek Theatre company in Connecticut.
Impressed by his gifts as a showman, hotshot producer Harry Cohn
beckoned him to Hollywood. There, Castle blazed a trail of amusing
schlock films and concocted outlandish stunts to lure audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was afraid people wouldn't go to see his films,''
his daughter said. ``He was driven. He wanted audiences to have
fun, and he'd do anything to make sure they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Castle gimmick was a buzzing device called Percepto,
which was wired into theater seats for ``The Tingler.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad probably buzzed 20 million butts with that film,''
Castle said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1959 film, which also starred Price, was about a lobsterlike
organism that lived on people's spines and came to life when they
were frightened. During the movie, the screen would go black and a
voice (Castle's) would announce: ``Attention! The Tingler is loose
in the theater'' and advise people to scream for their lives. As a
few people got their bottoms buzzed, the audience would go nuts.
</P>
<P>
   That particular gimmick became ``the fondest moviegoing memory
of my youth,'' said director John Waters, who has often called
Castle a genius and once revealed that as a child he wished he
could have visited the filmmaker instead of Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Retrospectives at art-film houses like New York City's Film
Forum, the Nuart in Los Angeles and the UC Theatre in Berkeley,
Calif., have celebrated Castle's odd, trashy sense of humor _ he
offered insurance policies against ``death by fright'' for
``Macabre'' (1958) and established ``fright breaks'' and a
``coward's corner'' in theaters for ``Homicidal,'' a 1961
``Psycho'' takeoff. With that film, he also offered money-back
guarantees to people if they got too scared.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Castle is married to Tom Newell, a former CBS lawyer and
now senior vice president of the Internet digital sports startup
Quokka.com. They have two children, Kyle, 6, and William, 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such a great family experience as a kid,'' Castle said.
``Dad was always a great storyteller and one of those doting dad
types. If I had a temperature of 99, he'd drop everything and be
home pacing at the foot of my bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom, Ellen, hated all the Hollywood stuff, and she kept him
grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Castle, a former actress who worked for the Resistance in
World War II Holland, now lives in Marin County. Terry Castle's
older sister, Georgiana, died five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Castle entertained notions of becoming an actress. ``I
wanted the part that Diane Baker played in `Strait-Jacket,''' she
said. The 1964 thriller, directed by her father, starred Joan
Crawford as an enraged wife who murders her unfaithful husband and
his mistress with an ax. Her young daughter (played by Baker)
witnesses the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father coached me and told me to look scared, so I
practiced and practiced for weeks,'' said Terry Castle. But on the
first day of shooting, her mother wouldn't let her do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably a good thing because I can't act. But when the
film opened and we went to see it, I sat on my dad's lap watching
Diane Baker and I told him, `I could have done it better.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
