<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-COMPLAINTS-     08-09 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-COMPLAINTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE COMMISSIONER WEIGHS CHANGE IN HOW MISCONDUCT IS
INVESTIGATED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir is considering a
plan to change the way the Police Department disciplines officers
to give the Civilian Complaint Review Board a greater role in
investigating police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that while no final decision had been made on the
plan, which would reduce the department's role in the
investigations, ``I would hope that it would happen in the
relatively near future.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussion of the changes in the department's disciplinary
process comes as the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Eastern
District of New York is weighing a possible lawsuit against New
York City, in part because of their finding that the Police
Department has often failed to aggressively punish officers
implicated in brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said there is no connection between his consideration of
changes and any federal actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are discussing now is a position I have had way before
the Eastern District investigation ever began,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the police have generally taken a dim view of the
investigative prowess of the review board. Even when the board
finds misconduct by an officer, the department usually
re-investigates the case before deciding whether to file formal
disciplinary charges.
</P>
<P>
   But now police officials said they believe the review board,
fortified by additional funding and the hiring of more seasoned
investigators, has improved so much that it may be possible to rely
almost exclusively on the board's investigative work.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner outlined the possible changes on July 28 in a
meeting with members of the review board. Under the plan that was
discussed, police officials would still review misconduct cases for
lapses in evidence but would have the CCRB investigators close any
holes, instead of police staff.
</P>
<P>
   The changes under consideration would address what critics
contend is an important defect in the disciplinary process: that an
extra layer of investigation by the police has not only undermined
the independence of the civilian review panel _ which has the power
to look into complaints but no power to discipline officers _ but
also failed to reliably produce stronger cases that resulted in
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the misconduct cases referred to the Police
Department each year by the civilian panel never result in any
disciplinary action against the officers involved. Often, the
police review determines that the evidence collected by the
civilian panel is insufficient to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   For cases in which the department ultimately files charges, most
officers face an administrative trial within the department. If
found guilty, a recommendation for punishment is forwarded to the
police commissioner, who can accept it or reject it.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say that, without their efforts to review and
bolster the cases they receive, even fewer officers would be
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a role that the department assumed to protect
investigations that we believed were inadequate,'' Safir said
Monday. ``But we assumed that role inappropriately in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said that the plan being discussed ``would make
the CCRB totally independent as far as the investigations are
concerned. One of the issues has always been the police
investigating themselves. Well, we would not be investigating
ourselves, even though I think that we do a very good job of
investigating ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene R. Lopez, the executive director of the review board,
declined comment on what he described as a private discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Although some 100 municipalities in the country have civilian
panels that review allegations of police misconduct, it is rare to
find a city where the findings of the civilian panel are
re-investigated by the police, according to Samuel Walker, a
professor at the University of Nebraska at Omaha who has studied
the civilian review process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to reinvestigate, why bother having a
civilian panel in the first place?'' Walker said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last year, police officials ruled on 374 cases in which the
Civilian Complaint Review Board had recommended disciplinary action
against officers. In 47 percent of those cases, the officers
received some form of punishment, from a reprimand to being fired.
But dozens of other cases were dismissed by police officials for a
variety of reasons, including their finding that the evidence was
insufficient to support charges or because the statute of
limitations had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said the failure to charge so many officers against
whom civilian complaints have been upheld is evidence of the Police
Department's reluctance to punish its own. But Safir has noted that
the number of officers disciplined as a result of citizen
complaints has more than doubled since 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
