</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BEIJING -- Aug. 09, 1999 -- CHINA-PALACE, 08-09 -- The
remnants of what is known in English as the Old Summer Palace are
the subject of an angry debate in Beijing, with clashing visions of
how to commemorate the past and a battle of esthetic sensibilities.
This debate, being carried on in private meetings and in the press,
pits those who want to recreate the splendors of the former estate
as a for-profit tourist attraction against those who believe in the
quiet power of ruins. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Aug. 09, 1999 -- BIKES-MOTORS-COX, 08-08 --
Motorized two wheelers such as the USPD mountain bicycle make the
most intimidating hills conquerable. With most electrical assist
bikes, the rider must pedal to get the bike going at about five
miles an hour, then he or she can engage the rechargeable electric
motor to increase the cruising speed or to help with pedaling up
hills. (CSW/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) YUCCA MOUNTAIN, Nev. -- Aug. 10, 1999 --
SCI-YUCCA-NUKE-3, 08-10 -- Workers leave the entrance to a
five-mile tunnel that was drilled by a huge boring machine into
Yucca Mountain, about 100 miles northwest of Las Vegas. The site is
being considered by the Energy Department as a repository for
nuclear waste. (Jon Christensen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- Aug. 9, 1999 --
BOSNIA-SARAJEVO-2, 08-09 -- Many parts of the Bosnian capital near
former front line areas remain off limits due to mines and
unexploded ordanance. Sarajevo, which held together a blend of
ethnic groups and hung on to life during almost four years of siege
by the Bosnian Serbs, has lost its sense of purpose, its direction,
and many say its soul. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- Aug. 9, 1999 --
BOSNIA-SARAJEVO, 08-09 -- Murdija Bandic, left, and her son Aladin
in their rebuilt home in the Sarajevo suburb of Dobrinja last week.
During the war, their home was destroyed and they were captured and
held by Serb forces. The Bosnian capital, which held together a
blend of ethnic groups and hung on to life during almost four years
of siege by the Bosnian Serbs, has lost its sense of purpose, its
direction, and many say its soul. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- FBN-GIANTS-STRAHAN, 08-09
-- Michael Strahan, center, at the New York Giants training camp
last week. In the background are linebacker Corey Widmer, left, and
Mike Haluchak, the assistant coach for linebackers. Strahan signed
a four-year, $32 million contract with the Giants on Monday, making
him the NFL's second-highest-paid defensive player. (David
Jennings/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON, Mass. -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- SCI-HEMLOCK-BOS, 08-09
-- The city is cuting down these hemlock trees infected with the
woolly adelgid, a bug no bigger than the period at the end of a
sentence. The insect is decimating some of the Northeast's oldest
and most valuable forests. What adelgids lack in size, they make up
for in numbers, swarming even the tiniest hemlocks by the tens of
thousands and literally sucking the life out of them (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FALMOUTH, Mass. -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- LYME-VICTIMS-BOS,
08-09 -- Elizabeth Pykosz, who had Lyme Disease that went
undetected for some time, in front of one of her paintings at her
home recently. Doctors estimate there are thousands of patients
like Pykosz, suffering crippling psychiatric problems and taking
heavy doses of psychotropic drugs, not knowing that Lyme has caused
their illness or that they might be helped with antibiotics. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) YUCCA MOUNTAIN, Nev. -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- SCI-YUCCA-NUKE-2,
08-09 -- An aerial view of one of the entrances to Yucca Mountain,
about 100 miles northwest of Las Vegas, a site being considered by
the Energy Department as a repository for nuclear waste. (Yucca
Mountain Project/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) YUCCA MOUNTAIN, Nev. -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- SCI-YUCCA-NUKE-1,
08-09 -- A sample of calcite crystals found inside Yucca Mountain,
about 100 miles northwest of Las Vegas, which is being considered
as a repository for nuclear waste. Some scientists say the crystals
are evidence of intermittent upwellings of underground water, which
would speed the spread of radioactive materials stored in the
mounthain. The Department of Energy is seeking to demonstrate that
these crystals were formed in the same volcanic process that made
the mountain, and that the water table is stable at a level
hundreds of feet below where the nuclear waste would go. (Jon
Christenson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- SCI-FITNESS-WEIGHTS, 08-09 --
High-speed movements, demonstrated by Mark Tenore and overseen by
Pat Manocchia at La Palestra in midtown Manhattan, are being added
to workout regimens. Fitness experts call them ``explosive'' or
``ballistic'' training exercises. And according to the American
College of Sports Medicine, which endorsed the lightweight,
high-speed techniques in a statement last month, they are a good
way to increase strength (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON, Texas -- Aug. 9, 1999 --
RELIGION-RABBI-TALMUD-HNS, 08-09 -- Rabbi Judith Abrams operates
Maqom, an award-winning cyber-school for adult Talmud studies, from
her home in southwest Houston. The cyber-school earned Abrams a
1999 Covenant Award for Jewish Educators for contributing to the
transmission of Jewish values, knowledge and identity. The New
York-based Covenant Foundation selected three educators, including
Abrams, from more than 400 nominees. The award, which carries a
$20,000 prize, will be given to Abrams on Nov. 16 at an awards
ceremony in Atlanta. (Carlos Antonio Rios/Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
