a visit to New York earlier this month. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York
Times Photo) (/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 09, 1999 -- SURPLUS-PARTIES, 08-09 --
``The best thing we can do for the economy is to increase savings,
and the best way the government has of increasing savings is paying
down the debt,'' says Robert Bixby, the policy director of the
Concord Coalition, a fiscal monitoring group. ``Reducing the debt
will increase capital investment and productivity, which helps keep
economic growth going.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) EASTHAM, Mass. -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- TALKING-TO-THOREAU,
08-09 -- John Bartow, a retired high school English teacher,
dressed as Henry David Thoreau, during a tour of Salt Pond on Cape
Cod. Eight times a week, for an hour or more, Barto, as Thoreau,
walks with visitors or presents lectures, never stepping out of
muslin-shirted character, always answering their questions from the
immense compendium of Thoreauviana he holds in his head. (Jared
Leeds/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Aug. 9, 1999 -- DOLE-PROFILE ,
08-09 --Elizabeth Dole speaks the audience about her views on
abortion in April. When Mrs. Dole ventured into presidential
campaign territory, she was not greeted like another mere candidate
but like a superstar. But Mrs. Dole had no organizational backbone
to capitalize on the enthusiasm. And now the kleig lights have
shifted. Mrs. Dole is no longer widely viewed by the Republican
establishment as the obvious alternative should the front-runner,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, collapse. Instead of being a star,
she has faded into the chorus with the other rivals to Bush.
(Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
