<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1235 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARRATRY-HNS &LR;      08-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRATRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON FAMILY ACCUSES TEXAS LAWYER OF BARRATRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Seattle, Wash.) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ One of Texas' wealthiest and politically powerful
lawyers has been accused of ambulance chasing by the parents of a
commercial diver, who say Walter Umphrey solicited them as legal
clients while they were at a Port Arthur funeral home to arrange
for their son's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Karen and Peter Pilkington of the Seattle suburb of Bellevue say
they were introduced to Umphrey on March 6, 1996, at the
Clayton-Thompson funeral home in Groves, outside of Port Arthur,
which is about 80 miles east of downtown Houston. Their son, Brian
Pilkington, a 23-year-old working for a Houston dive contractor,
died March 4, 1996, while conducting an underwater inspection of an
offshore drilling rig.
</P>
<P>
   According to corporate records kept by the Texas Secretary of
State, Umphrey is listed as vice president and treasurer of the
funeral home where the solicitation took place.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilkingtons' complaint alleges that a person he believes was
Charles Hansen, director of the funeral home, told them Umphrey was
a childhood friend who ``was now `one of the most famous and best
lawyers in Texas.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen offered to arrange for a meeting quickly with Umphrey,
and the lawyer, wearing work boots and overalls, was waiting to
meet them at the funeral home an hour later after the family
returned from lunch, the complaint states.
</P>
<P>
   Umphrey, one of a group of Texas lawyers sharing a $3.3 billion
payment for negotiating a settlement in the state's tobacco
lawsuit, did not return calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a heavy political contributor, having donated $1.1
million to mostly Democratic candidates during the 1996 and 1998
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, reached at the funeral home, said he did not remember
the Pilkington family or Umphrey coming to the funeral home to meet
them. ``I couldn't remember a thing about that,'' said Hansen, who
declined to discuss the matter further and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the circumstances, as we then knew them,
surrounding our son's death, and Mr. Umphrey said that he would be
able to help us get compensation for his death,'' according to the
complaint the Pilkington family sent to the Texas State Bar, the
state agency that polices lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He added that he shouldn't really meet us in those
circumstances but that he had a proper office in Beaumont and that
if we were interested in retaining him we should go there to tie up
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt distressed that we were having a business meeting and
discussing financial matters whilst our son was laying in the next
room. It seemed unnatural. Nevertheless, we agreed to enlist the
Respondent's assistance and to travel to his office,'' the
complaint states.
</P>
<P>
   A legal contract was signed in Umphrey's office by the diver's
widow, Julie Pilkington. Karen and Peter Pilkington were later
added as plaintiffs to the lawsuit brought by David Brandom, a
partner in Umphrey's firm who handled the case.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, brought against Houston oil drilling firm Cliffs
Drilling Co., the dive contractor who employed Brian Pilkington,
and two other defendants, was settled for a reported $2.25 million
in 1998, of which the Beaumont law firm received nearly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Pilkington, contacted in Seattle, said he has presented
the Umphrey law firm with a bill for $300,000 to repay him for the
time and money he spent convincing the U.S. Coast Guard to re-open
its investigation into his son's death and reveal the facts,
something he instructed the Texas firm to do. Pilkington said
Umphrey and his associates were only interested in money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My primary concern was to learn the truth, not go after the
people with the deepest pockets,'' Pilkington said. ``We weren't
after the money. We wanted to find out what the hell happened, and
to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambulance chasing is the common term for barratry, which under
Texas law is a third degree felony if an attorney or his agents
directly contact accident victims or their survivors to solicit
employment, either in person or by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Barratry is also a violation of the Texas Disciplinary Rules of
Professional Conduct for lawyers, and subjects an attorney to
sanctions ranging from a private reprimand to loss of his law
license.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Miller, acting general counsel for the State Bar of Texas,
said agency rules prevented her from disclosing whether a complaint
had been lodged by the Pilkingtons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our grievance system is confidential up to a certain point in
the process ... I can't confirm or not if we have received one or
it's pending,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
