<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ERITREA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDING A SENSELESS WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wars, once started, are often difficult to end. Eritrea's
acceptance of a plan to end its 15-month conflict with Ethiopia
offers hope that both nations will see the folly of continuing to
fight over border lands that have little value either economically
or symbolically.
</P>
<P>
   The war seems to have developed a momentum of its own, with each
nation wasting resources on arms purchases, accusing the other of
human rights violations, and arming factions in nearby Somalia. If
the fighting continues, the entire Horn of Africa could be
destabilized.
</P>
<P>
   That outcome would be particularly tragic because, unlike other
African nations, both Eritrea and Ethiopia have stable governments
led by two exceptional leaders, Isaias Afwerki in Eritrea and Meles
Zenawi in Ethiopia. They should have been able to resolve their
disagreements without war.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea, with 3 1/2 million people, retains an unfortunate sense
of superiority because of its David vs. Goliath victory over
Ethiopia in its war of independence, which ended eight years ago.
Ethiopia's Zenawi, who came to power amid the detritus of defeat,
represents a small ethnic group in a heterogeneous nation of 55
million people. The latest war may have been a force for national
unity.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea's machinations in Somalia are intended to encourage
separatism on Ethiopia's southern flank. The cost of Ethiopian
mobilization imperils economic programs that demonstrate the
advantages of a large nation. Conflict can go only so far to hold a
country together.
</P>
<P>
   As for Eritrea, the urgent task is to coexist with Ethiopia,
whose population is the prime market for Eritrean goods and
services. War is no way to keep old customers or win new ones.
</P>
<P>
   An Ethiopian spokesman said his government is seeking
clarifications from the Organization of African Unity on details of
the latest peace plan. The OAU and diplomats from the United States
have shown persistence and skill in attempting to broker a peace
agreement, but only the Eritrean and Ethiopian governments can
definitively act to end this meaningless war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
