<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-DUMPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERCE DEPT. DISMISSES CLAIM OF UNFAIR PRACTICES AGAINST OIL
PRODUCERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Okla., Texas, Alaska, Hawaii, Calif.)  By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Department of Commerce in Washington dismissed
accusations of unfair trade practices against Mexico and three
other crude oil-exporting countries Monday, heading off a potential
economic and political crisis for Mexico and the United States, its
biggest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   The charges had come from 12 independent oil producers in
Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas, asserting that Mexico, Venezuela and
Saudi Arabia, as well as Iraq _which the United Nations has
recently permitted to increase oil exports _ had been selling crude
oil in the United States at prices below production costs, a
violation of American anti-dumping laws.
</P>
<P>
   All four countries denied the dumping charge, but Mexico, which
ships 75 percent of its oil exports to the United States, was the
most outspoken. Shortly after the complaint was filed in late June,
Mexico retaliated by suspending plans to eliminate a tariff on
natural gas imported from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The independent oil companies, which had banded together as a
group calling themselves Save Domestic Oil, had asked the Clinton
administration to impose duties on Mexico and the other countries
that would have forced them out of the U.S. market. Save Domestic
Oil said it planned an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Tellez, Mexico's secretary of energy, said in an interview
that he was ``very happy'' with the Commerce Department's decision.
``It was a very wise and just decision,'' he said. ``We are not
dumping oil on any international market.''
</P>
<P>
   Tellez said he expected that Mexico would put an end to its
tariff on imports of natural gas from the United States in ``a
matter of days.''
</P>
<P>
   George Baker, an energy consultant in Houston, said the Commerce
decision averted ``a deterioration in U.S.-Mexico relations and
some major economic shocks in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gasoline prices would have probably gone up in the U.S.,'' he
said. ``A big chunk of Mexican government revenue comes from
petroleum sales to the U.S. They would have had to scramble to find
other customers and would have had to cut back production as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Commerce officials said they had decided not to
pursue the dumping charges after surveying more than 800 American
oil producers, large and small, and finding that more than half the
companies felt that no dumping was taking place. By law, at least
half the industry must support a claim of dumping before the
Commerce Department can start a formal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The independent producers had told Commerce officials that small
oil companies in the United States had lost $15 billion in expected
revenues between late 1997 and June, when the complaint was filed.
Oil prices dropped to as low as $10 a barrel in late 1998, but a
barrel has gone back up to $15, the low end of the range where it
has mostly traded since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The independent producers blamed the slump on pricing by Mexico
and the other three countries. The countries provided about half of
the 8 million barrels of oil that were imported in 1998 into the
states other than Alaska, Hawaii, California and four other Western
states. Those seven use little oil from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the dumping charges, including the American
Petroleum Institute, a Washington trade group that represents most
major American oil companies as well as some independents, said the
drop in oil prices had come not from dumping but from market
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a worldwide phenomenon brought about by some fairly
significant surprises,'' said Edward Porter, a senior economist at
the American Petroleum Institute, citing the economic turmoil in
Asia and Russia as well as unusually warm weather in the United
States, as well as the U.N. decision permitting increased exports
by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Charles O. Verrill, Jr., the lead lawyer for Save Domestic Oil,
said the major American oil companies opposed the complaint because
they are the main customers of Mexico and the other countries and
want the lowest possible prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have steadily reduced their exploration and production in
the United States,'' Verrill said. ``They have sold much of that
production to the independents and increased their refining
capacity, making them dependent on imported oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, the secretary of energy, said last month that
he had tried unsuccessfully to meet with Save Domestic Oil
representatives and that he was ``extremely concerned'' about the
potential impact of their charges on consumers and trade relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
