<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAW-FORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAW OFFICIAL'S DEATH PUTS LABOR-CONTRACT FOCUS ON FORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The unexpected death of a labor leader over the
weekend makes it likely that the Ford Motor Co. will be the lead
company in labor negotiations covering the auto industry's 405,000
blue-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Laskowski, a vice president of the United Automobile
Workers union, died on Sunday, apparently of a heart attack, the
union said Monday. Laskowski, 59, led the labor team negotiating
with DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   Three-year labor contracts with DaimlerChrysler, Ford and the
General Motors Corp. expire on Sept. 14, and the auto industry is
busily negotiating new contracts with the union.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, each company proposes terms for a new contract and
the union chooses the best offer, then begins negotiating with a
single auto maker. Once it reaches agreement with that company, it
requires the other two auto makers to follow the same pattern in
their union contracts. The union's top concern this year is job
security.
</P>
<P>
   With a leadership vacuum created by the death of Laskowski,
DaimlerChrysler seems unlikely to be chosen. GM is also unlikely to
become the target company because it has a poor relationship with
the union. That leaves Ford, which has the closest relationship
with the union and has set the pattern during the last two
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW has not yet named a successor for Laskowski, but the
union's board met as scheduled Monday. The union is expected to
announce late this month or in early September which company will
be the negotiating target.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, workers nationwide are scheduled to vote to authorize
strikes at each company, as is the custom entering the final
stretch of negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
