<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICRO-CHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCED MICRO INTRODUCES A FASTER CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a make-or-break move, Advanced Micro Devices
Inc. introduced a microprocessor Monday with higher performance
than the fastest chips made by the Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With a top speed of 650 MHz, Advanced Micro's new chip, known as
the Athlon, edges out Intel, which just last week introduced a
600-MHz version of its flagship microprocessor, the Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro said the International Business Machines Corp.
and the Compaq Computer Corp. had already committed themselves to
using the Athlon in some computers. Shipments to computer
manufacturers began last month, the company said, adding that it
expected PCs that use the chip to be available later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro shares closed at $19.25, up $1.875, on the New
York Stock Exchange. Intel shares closed at $73.4375, up $1.875, in
NASDAQ trading.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro has been locked in a price war with Intel that
has left the company awash in red ink. Without a high-performance
product, the company has had no choice but to battle Intel at the
low end. But Intel can afford to offer deep discounts on its
low-end products, partly because it has the most efficient
manufacturing operations in the business, and partly because the
slim margins are offset by premium pricing for high-end processors
used in work stations and servers.
</P>
<P>
   The Athlon is available in a range of clock speeds, from 500 to
650 MHz, but Advanced Micro said that at each speed, its chip
outperformed the comparable Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a technical standpoint, it is the strongest product AMD
has ever shipped,'' said Michael Slater, editor of The
Microprocessor Report, an industry newsletter. ``Pretty much no
matter now you measure it, it comes out stronger than Pentium III.
If they can now deliver on its potential, it clearly could change
their position in the marketplace. They now can compete at the high
end, where Intel cannot be as aggressive, because they need the
profit margins from those products.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether Advanced Micro can deliver Athlon
chips in a timely manner and in volumes large enough to matter. The
company has introduced faster chips than Intel's products in the
past only to stumble in manufacturing and to cede the market
opportunity to its rival.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of S. Atiq Raza last month as Advanced Micro's
president and chief operating officer is also cause for concern as
the company faces the challenge of producing the Athlon.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the 650-MHz AMD Athlon processor is priced at
$849 when purchased in 1,000-unit lots; the 600-MHz AMD Athlon
processor is priced at $615; the 550-MHz AMD Athlon processor is
priced at $449; and the 500-MHz AMD Athlon processor is priced at
$249.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's 600-MHz Pentium III is $669; the 550-MHz processor is
$658; the 500-MHz processor is $423; and the 450-MHz processor is
$230.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is whether there is a volume market for
high-performance processors, when a low-end Celeron from Intel _
or, indeed, Advanced Micro's own K-6 processor _ meets most
people's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had they introduced this product three years ago, the market
would have been clamoring for it, but the need and price support
for high-performance Intel-compatible processors have evaporated,''
said Drew Peck, an analyst with S.G. Cowen. ``Given the woeful
state of software, the performance advantage may not be noticeable
at all, so you could not expect well-informed customers to pay a
premium for it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2206EDT &QL; 
