<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1250 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD     08-09 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN AGAIN REPLACES PRIME MINISTER, THIS TIME WITH EX-KGB AGENT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds: SUBS first two grafs to rephrase lede, add pronouncer for
Putin and change `naming' to `nominating' in 2nd graf for
clarity.) (See also RUSSIA-PUTIN) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic on recent changes in Russian government is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As the race to succeed him next year threatens to slip
out of his control, Russian President Boris Yeltsin tipped his
hand, and Russia's political apple cart, by firing his prime
minister on Monday and replacing him with a former KGB officer and
loyal aide who he said was his favorite to become the next
president.
</P>
<P>
   From a politician who regularly uses surprise as a weapon,
Yeltsin's latest move, nominating Vladimir Putin (pronounced
POO-teen) to succeed Sergei Stepashin _ his fourth government
shake-up in 17 months _ was met with more dismay than shock. Even
former allies accused him of playing politics at the expense of the
increasingly fragile authority of Russia's central government.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this smacks very much of the agony and madness of the
Kremlin, and it is all hard to explain,'' said Boris Nemtsov, a
former member of Yeltsin's team who himself was once tapped briefly
as a potential heir. ``The only explanation that comes to mind is
that Yeltsin does not believe that Stepashin can be his successor
or thinks he is unworthy of being his successor.''
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov was even more biting.
``Who will take any prime minister seriously if they are changed
like gloves?'' he asked in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although Putin, 46, quickly sought to reassure the country, and
the current cabinet that he would make no changes, news of
Stepashin's abrupt dismissal caused a drop in the value of the
Russian ruble, and knocked down prices on Russia's stock exchange,
which in recent months had been rebounding from last August's
devastating financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As Muscovites openly voiced their disgust at the Kremlin's
latest game of musical chairs, Western governments and the
International Monetary Fund _ holders of Russia's mountain of debts
_ were more cautious, saying publicly that they were certain Moscow
would keep to its promised course.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and later Putin reassured Russians that they intend to
have the nation's scheduled elections go ahead as planned. ``In one
year for the first time in the country's history the first
president of Russia will transfer power to a fresh, newly elected
president.'' Yeltsin said in a televised address to the nation.
``In any case he will be your president, respected Russians, he who
has won in honest and clean elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, a former interior minister and faithful Yeltsin
supporter who was catapulted into the prime minister's job just
three months ago, was unexpectedly called to the Kremlin early
Monday morning and told he was being fired.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before, Stepashin had flown back to Moscow from the
southern province of Dagestan where he had been dispatched to
oversee efforts by federal forces to quell an armed rebellion by
Islamic extremists. Despite the timing, few experts think that
Stepashin's handling of the flare-up of violence in the volatile
north Caucasus was the immediate reason for Yeltsin's decision to
dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   In his televised address to the nation, Yeltsin made no specific
criticisms of Stepashin, but made it clear that the 47-year-old
soft-spoken former police officer had failed to qualify as a strong
presidential contender capable of keeping Yeltsin's foes at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Yeltsin praised Putin as ``the person capable of
consolidating society, the person who, basing himself on the
broadest political forces, is capable of ensuring a continuation of
reforms in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust him,'' said the president, who spoke slowly, looking
straight at the camera. ``But I also want all those who in July
2000 will come to the polling stations and make their choice to
have similar confidence in him. I think Putin will have enough time
to show his worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin on Monday also officially opened Russia's election
season by signing a formal decree setting Dec. 19 as the date for
elections to the 450-seat lower house of the parliament, or Duma.
Presidential elections are to follow in July 2000, when Yeltsin's
second and final term comes to an end, according to the Russian
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's anointment of Putin on Monday was another confirmation
that the battle over who will lead Russia into the post-Yeltsin era
is already underway. An opening shot was fired last week not by the
presidential administration, but by Moscow's ambitious Mayor Yuri
Luzhkov, and a handful of regional governors who formed an
electoral alliance in defiance of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   That alliance, which many believe will attract former Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov back into politics, ultimately as a
presidential candidate, may have triggered Yeltsin's abrupt move
Monday. For several days, Russian newspapers have speculated that
the president would cast about for ways to regain the political
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's nomination must now be confirmed by the Duma, which is
scheduled to return from vacation and take its first vote on the
new prime minister next Monday. If it votes three times against the
president's candidate, the Russian constitution says it must be
disbanded. Since a majority of parliamentary deputies don't want to
lose their seats and privileges before the December elections, most
analysts expect that Putin _ like Stepashin before him _ will be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, having been through this drill repeatedly
during the Yeltsin presidency, attempted to play down the
significance of the Russian leader's latest government shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should blow this out of proportion,'' said
James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman. ``We have focused
our policy on the policies of Russian reform and the policies of
the Russian government, not the personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, . ``We do have some experience with Mr. Putin and
have a constructive relationship with him.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Putin, a former KGB agent who spent years in Germany during the
Cold War era, came to Moscow in 1996 from St. Petersburg where he
had served as first vice mayor to Mayor Anatoli Sobchak, one of the
leaders of Russia's early democratic movement. He served as
Yeltsin's deputy chief of staff and since last year as head of
Russia's internal intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kremlin, where his most recent job was secretary to the
Security Council, he has maintained a low-profile but has a
reputation as a tough administrator, whose power lies largely in
his continuing command of the domestic branch of the old KGB.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stepashin, Putin has no direct experience in electoral
politics and his cool, aloof manner sets him apart from Russia's
other more loquacious politicians. But analysts here suggest that
he was favored for the role of presidential aspirant because he may
be more ready than his predecessor to use his office to bring
Russia's powerful regional leaders in line behind the Kremlin's
election strategy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russia's governors, who hold executive power in the country's 89
regions, have become an increasingly powerful force on the national
political scene, as Moscow takes stock of their considerable
influence on voters back home, through local media, budgets and
their hold on local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, named prime minister in May after Yeltsin fired
Primakov, had tried to stay out of partisan politics, even as
Yeltsin's inner circle _ which includes his chief of staff
Aleksandr Voloshin and his youngest daughter Tatyana Dyachenko _
spent the summer picking fights with that part of the Russian media
that has cast its lot with Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   In a telling interview given to the newspaper Izvestia last
Friday, Stepashin pledged to keep a neutral role in the upcoming
election battles, which may not have been the message the Kremlin
wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even if he proves to be a more effective political player, few
observers Monday gave Putin a real chance to become a viable
presidential candidate, given the depth of popular antipathy to his
mentor. For more than a year now, Yeltsin's own popularity rating
has been in the single digits, as broad swaths of the Russian
population _ from disgruntled pensioners to disgusted entrepreneurs
_ blame him for the country's economic stagnation and rampant
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``A recommendation by Mr. Yeltsin, this is the kiss of death,''
said Leonid Dobrokhotov, an adviser to Zyuganov, the Communist
Party leader.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the universal loathing of him in the country, any
recommendation by him of any politician, even the best, points the
way to the grave,'' Dobrokhotov said. ``We are on the finishing
line of the Yeltsin regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Anatoly Chubais, a leader of a new right-wing party made up
of top liberal reformers, was quoted by one news agency source
Monday as saying that Stepashin's removal was ``a very risky step
with possible grave political consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As he demonstrated Monday, Yeltsin is still willing to wield the
considerable power vested in his office to try to turn the
political tide. As in the hard-fought election campaign of 1996, he
and his administration can still use or withhold money from the
federal budget to reward or punish wayward regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But some politicians say that even these powers have diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two, three years ago, he had these opportunities, and he used
those opportunities,'' said Vladimir Ryzhkov, a parliamentary
leader in the Our Home is Russia Party, during a television
appearance last week. ``What has happened in these days has proved
one thing: Mr. Yeltsin's power has run out. The Russian
establishment, or at least its upper layer, has turned away from
Yeltsin.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here are divided over Yeltsin's motives. Some argue
that he is intent on bequeathing to Russia, as his parting legacy,
a government and a president who are committed to completing the
country's transformation into a functioning democracy, with a
market-based economy. The rise of a Primakov-Luzhkov team, backed
by a coalition made up of Soviet-era industrial directors and some
of Russia's more autocratic governors, is seen by Yeltsin's circle
as a threat to those goals.
</P>
<P>
   But others see Yeltsin as a lame-duck politician who is
desperately struggling to guarantee his immunity, and that of his
family, once he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is in a state of panic,'' said Dobrokhotov. ``He is not
concerned about his legacy, or about Russia and its fate.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dobrokhotov said Yeltsin is afraid of ``a Ceausescu scenario,''
referring to the summary execution in December 1989 of Romania's
despised communist dictator, ``of being forced to pay the bill for
the terrible crisis he has put the country through.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as some caution, a year is a long time in Russian
politics where alliances and promises can evaporate as quickly as
they are made. And Yeltsin's renewed activity suggests that he will
do his best to win back control of political events.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Berezovsky, a prominent financier and media magnate whose
influence in the Kremlin rose after the fall of his arch-foe,
Primakov, suggested in an interview Monday with the news agency
Interfax that Yeltsin's strategy has not yet been fully laid out.
</P>
<P>
   According to Berezovsky, the dismissal of Stepashin is part of
the Kremlin's plan to ``create their own political force capable of
fighting for parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two or three weeks will clarify the reasons for this
decision,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
