<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BANK-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK ROBBERY SUSPECT SHOT TO DEATH BY POLICE NEAR WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Spelling of `Chmielnicki' in 7th graf is correct.) 
(yn) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As lunchtime crowds scrambled for cover, the police
shot to death a bank robbery suspect near Wall Street Monday after
he pulled a gun on them. A bystander was also wounded in the
chaotic scene.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire echoed through the canyons of the Financial District as
people thronged the streets for lunch on one of the few cool
workdays of the summer. People described cowering behind planters
and garbage bins as officers unleashed dozens of shots at the
fleeing suspect, who had apparently been wounded by the police when
they first confronted him in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The gunfire erupted just blocks from the Federal Reserve Bank
and the New York Stock Exchange, and witnesses described a panicky
scene as people dived for cover. They said that at least one man
appeared to have been injured in the stampede.
</P>
<P>
   All told, a half-dozen police officers fired more than 35 shots
at the suspected robber, a senior police official said. And while
several civilian witnesses reported seeing the man shoot at the
police, the official said, crime scene detectives had yet to find
any forensic evidence, such as spent shell casings, to prove that
he had fired his weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Magid, 57, was delivering a door to the area. ``I was
coming out of my truck with the door, and I see a lot of people
coming out of the building and hear about a dozen shots. A police
officer says, ```Duck _ get out of the way!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the door on the floor _ I just dropped it right
there,'' Magid said. ``Fifteen minutes later I picked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Chmielnicki, a legal secretary who works a block away,
said that she was sitting on a bench just outside the glass walls
of the bank when the shooting started. ``The door just shattered,''
she recalled. ``I thought it had blown out or something. Then I
heard the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The police then rushed her to safety behind one of the planters
that line Cedar Street, where she skinned her leg diving for cover.
``I was saying `Thank God' because I wasn't shot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The chase and gunfire began when the police were called to the
HSBC Bank at 140 Broadway, near Cedar Street, around 12:50 p.m.
after employees there spotted a man they believe had robbed their
branch in June, said Assistant Chief William Taylor, the commander
of Manhattan detectives. When the first police officer entered the
bank's lobby, the police said, the robbery suspect took out a
handgun and trained it on her.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the suspect fired at the officer was still unclear
Monday night, officials said. The police officer, Bernadette
Batignani, 29, a six-year veteran, began shooting at the suspect
when he refused repeated commands to drop his weapon, the police
said. The wounded gunman then made his way into the street, where
he was shot by more officers, and eventually ran around the corner
to Pine Street near Broadway, where he finally collapsed, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Rosenberg, 59, who works for the city's Department of
Sanitation, was shot in the buttocks as she stood at Cedar and
Nassau Streets, the police said. It was not clear on Monday night
whether Ms. Rosenberg was shot by the police officers or by the
bank robbery suspect, police officials said. She was taken to
Bellevue Hospital, where she was listed in stable condition, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The police were working to identify the dead man on Monday
night. Identification found in his wallet bore the name Robert
Striker, 54, several police officials said. But police officials
said they would check the dead man's fingerprints Tuesday, after an
autopsy is performed, before officially identifying him as Striker,
who has been arrested more than 20 times since 1962 and who
sometimes used the alias Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   The man's weapon, a .25-caliber semi-automatic handgun, was
found on Cedar and Nassau Streets, the senior police official said,
adding that the gun, which can usually fire six or seven shots, had
two rounds in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
