<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT_S     08-09 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Microsoft Case Enters a Final Phase 
 &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The long-running antitrust case against Microsoft Corp. will enter
one of its final phases today when the Department of Justice and
Microsoft file separate ``findings of fact'' to Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson, who is presiding over the trial.
<P>
   These documents will outline what each side believes to be the
undisputed facts established over the course of the trial, which
began nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are likely to have wildly different
interpretations of the facts.
</P>
<P>
   The government will attempt to prove that Microsoft abused its
near-monopoly in operating systems and will focus on incriminating
e-mails, contradictory testimony from Microsoft executives and
claims that Microsoft strong-armed partners such as Intel and
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is expected to claim that it never intended to
dominate markets and that its actions benefited consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The papers will be far from succinct. A Microsoft lawyer said
his office will submit about 400 pages of documents, while the
government is expected to file upwards of 1,000 pages, according to
observers.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft lawyer, who asked not to be identified, said his
side's papers will show that the government failed to prove that
consumers were hurt when Microsoft tied together its Internet
Explorer Web browser into its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The compelling issue that will determine the outcome of the
case is the government has failed completely to show any consumer
harm,'' said the Microsoft lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, he said, consumers benefited because they got
Explorer for free when they bought Windows. Also, the browser was
already installed on most new PCs, so they didn't have to download
it from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer conceded that the price of Windows increased slightly
over the years but refuted criticism that this proves monopolistic
practices. ``If we really had a monopoly, the price of Windows
would be over a thousand bucks,'' he said. Windows, which operates
more than three-quarters of all personal computers, costs about
$200 at retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   The government team refused to comment on its filing. But
sources close to the government said they expect Justice to drive
home the point that Microsoft tried to win the so-called browser
war by forcing Windows users to use Microsoft's Web browser instead
of competing ones such as Netscape Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Manishin, a former antitrust attorney for the Justice
department, said he expects the government's findings of fact will
``connect the dots,'' showing that Microsoft used its near-monopoly
in operating systems to gain control of many other markets, not
just browsers.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the government's allegation that Microsoft created a
Windows-only version of Java, a programming language developed by
Sun Microsystems. Java does not require compliance with the Windows
operating systems and thus poses a potential threat to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Justice also charged that Microsoft attempted to control the
market for operating systems for servers, the powerful computers
that run corporate networks and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company is accused of using an overly aggressive strategy to
get its NT server software into the market and muscle out the
competing Unix software from companies such as Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The server is the next frontier, and Microsoft is using the
same tactics to gain a monopoly position here,'' said Tony Picardi,
a software analyst with International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   All these actions, according to critics, add up to Microsoft
restricting competition in the market, inhibiting innovation and
ultimately hurting the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone sees it that way. Jessica Melugin, a policy
fellow with the Center for Freedom and Technology in San Francisco,
said anything that stifles the natural development of a market _
such as government interference _ is invariably a disservice to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer industry has changed so much since the start of
this trial, it's impossible to regulate,'' she said. ``A lot of the
government's issues with Microsoft, like its contentions over the
browser, just aren't relevant any more.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Microsoft claims that Netscape is an even more
formidable competitor in the browser market since it was purchased
last year by America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The big question, Melugin said, is, ``Does the government really
want to mess with an industry that moves so quickly?''
</P>
<P>
   The findings of fact will be made public today. Both parties
will submit revised versions on September 10 to respond to issues
addressed by the opposing side. Closing arguments are scheduled to
begin about two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft lawyer said he expects Judge  &LR; Jackson to hand down
a final ruling in December at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   At an American Bar Association gathering yesterday, Jackson said
he is determined avoid a Vietnam-like morass.
</P>
<P>
   As for which way the judge will rule, at this point, it's
anyone's guess. ``I don't think the court will have the political
will to break up Microsoft into separate pieces,'' said Tony
Picardi. ``But I think the court may mandate that the browser be
taken out of the (Windows) operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
