<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 EBay Hires Gateway Tech Guru  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Online auctioneer eBay, plagued by a series of outages in recent
weeks, yesterday named a former Gateway executive to oversee
technical operations _ just hours after the latest snafu.
<P>
   Maynard Webb, 43, had been chief information officer at the No.2
direct seller of personal computers. As president of eBay
Technologies, he will report directly to eBay's chief executive,
Meg Whitman, and will coordinate the activities of the company's
newly hired chief technology officer and chief information officer.
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, eBay's system went kerblooey again Sunday night
for nearly three hours. Company spokesman Kevin Pursglove said the
site's credit-card-processing facilities went down at about 8 p.m.,
bringing most auctions to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   This snag followed a more severe outage Friday when hardware and
network problems conspired to knock eBay offline for about 10
hours, followed by several more hours of limited service.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which plunged more then 10 percent Friday,
fell another $3.63 yesterday, to $79.63.
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove said Webb was on hand Friday as eBay's engineers
scrambled to bring the site back online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like he was ready to roll his sleeves up and jump
right in,'' Pursglove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maynard's reputation in information technology is highly
regarded throughout the industry,'' Whitman said in a statement.
``We are confident that he possesses the vision and hands-on
experience to help ensure eBay's site stability moving forward and
to help scale eBay's system for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   One site-stabilizing factor will be eBay's new ``warm backup''
system, &UR;  &LR; intended to restore service within a couple of hours of a
system crash.
</P>
<P>
   While the warm backup would not have helped Friday without a
reliable network connection, Pursglove said he didn't know why the
system failed to kick in Sunday night. ``There's no explanation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The warm backup was installed following a 21-hour outage in
June, causing eBay's stock to tumble 18 percent. It's now down more
than 60 percent since soaring to a high of $209.25 in April.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting to Webb &UR;  &LR; are former IBM executive Mark Ryan, the
company's new chief technology officer, and former Sun Microsystems
executive Bob Quinn, the chief information officer. Both were hired
since the June system failure.
</P>
<P>
   According to a company statement, the three are charged with
``taking eBay's system to the next level.'' In other words, it's
their job to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
