<HEADER>
A1262 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-PROFILE-1STLD-WR     08-09 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-PROFILE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
DES MOINES, Iowa: was serious.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though the idea of the first female president excites many
voters, it also injects some risk and uncertainty in the Republican
Party's headstrong quest to retake the White House. The uncertainty
placed immense pressure on Mrs. Dole to demonstrate _ and do so
early _ that hers was a campaign that could win. She has also had
to overcome the fact that Mrs. Dole has never been elected to
anything. So her initial organizational difficulties made some
Republicans even more apprehensive. While most Republicans say the
country is ready to elect a female president, a full third say it
is not, according to an NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll taken in
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm ready for a woman,'' Barbara Beck, a
retired store manager, said after hearing Mrs. Dole speak recently
at a picnic near Laconia, N.H. ``I wonder if she'd be strong
enough. I just don't know if a woman could keep it together. She's
too cutsey. I want some desk slammer. I want someone to holler a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole said she has never encountered such remarks. ``I'm
hearing from women who will say to me, `I've driven my daughter
halfway across this state to shake your hand!''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating her campaign is that Mrs. Dole herself seems
conflicted over how much to emphasize her sex. She implores
audiences to help her ``make history.'' But out of concern that she
not be seen as waging a narrow campaign based only on gender, she
later sought to play down that line, saying in an interview: ``I
don't want people to vote for me because I'm a woman. I want them
to vote for me because they feel I'm the best qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Republican strategists argue that Mrs. Dole missed yet
another opportunity by keeping a low profile, refusing to appear on
national interview programs to take advantage of her sex and her
star quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her calculation is that there's sufficient time to do it in
the fall,'' said Ari Fleischer, Mrs. Dole's communications
director. Asked if that was his calculation as well, he said: ``I'm
a press guy. You can never do too much. But I accept this.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by interviews with dozens of Republicans at Mrs. Dole's
events in Iowa and New Hampshire, she has an uphill battle to
convince even her admirers that she can take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always impressed me as dynamic _ she'd make a great
leader,'' Christine Gerling Cole, 44, an information specialist
from Davenport, Iowa, said after a Dole event. Asked if Mrs. Dole
will win the nomination, she said, ``My gut feeling is that she has
a good chance at the vice presidency. My gut is that the country is
not ready for a woman president. Maybe I'm wrong. I hope I am.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stevens, 80, a lawyer from Muscatine, Iowa, put it this
way: ``She gives all the right answers _ she's got a thick record
of accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked if she can win the nomination, he said flatly, ``No.
I'm afraid that Bush has got too much money already. That's the
problem. And if I think he's got the best shot, I would vote for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a standard speech she delivers almost word-for-word from
memory, Mrs. Dole recites her vast executive experience and laments
what she says is ``a deficit in our basic American values.'' She
has proposed a crusade against illegal drug use and describes
improving public schools as a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Dole has done little to distinguish herself from Bush's
friendly faced conservatism. She drew the most attention when she
broke from the pack and called for prohibiting concealed weapons
and supporting child proof trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should have taken advantage of the early attention to lay
out some of her stands on taxes and welfare and crime,'' said Ed
Gillepsie, who ran the campaign of Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who
withdrew from the race last month. ``I'm still not sure you could
identify one striking policy or substantive aspect of the Dole
campaign right now apart from the tack on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A big part of Mrs. Dole's woes may be beyond her control: she is
simply swamped by Bush. On June 30, Mrs. Dole consented to a rare
national television interview on the NBC ``Today'' program to put
forth the message that there would be no turning back from her
quest for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Dole's appearance was only an asterisk because hours
later, Bush announced his $36-million war chest. From that day
forward, press calls to the Dole headquarters outside Washington
have declined dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press followed the money and gave much less consideration
to anything else,'' Fleischer said. ``It's not that Elizabeth Dole
went down; it's that George Bush went up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
