<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-PACIFIC </SLUG>
  
 Pacific Exchange's Big Change  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Pacific Exchange is preparing to shift from a membership
organization to a publicly owned, for-profit business, in the most
radical change in its structure in its 117-year history.
<P>
   Last month, the exchange's board of governors approved such a
plan for its money-losing stock exchange, the smaller of its two
operations. Pacific insiders said the proposal could pave the way
for a similar reorganization of its much larger and highly
lucrative options exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the first step,`` said board member Sam
Terner. ``If this is successful, then we would like to (do the same
with) options and maybe take the whole thing public.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's move comes as stock and options exchanges around the
world come to grips with the unprecedented challenge posed by new
breeds of computerized trading systems linking buyers and sellers
directly, bypassing traditional trading floors and middlemen.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the loss of market share to computer-based trading
systems, the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock Market,
the two biggest stock trading organizations in the United States,
have both unveiled plans to junk their membership structures and
reorganize as profit-seeking corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Market experts say membership organizations aren't nimble enough
to compete, given the frantic pace of change in securities markets.
</P>
<P>
   Converting to for-profit status and selling shares to the public
would provide exchanges with a hoard of cash. Structuring as a
corporation rather than as an association would also let an
exchange be quick on its feet and not have to have important
matters approved by members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exchanges are saying `Let's get away from our members,'
who have vested interests in the status quo,'' said Junius W.
Peake, a finance professor at the University of Northern Colorado.
``Membership-dominated exchanges are an endangered species.``
</P>
<P>
   Pacific has more than 550 members who own exchange seats
entitling them to trade both stocks and stock options. Only about
72 of those seats are used for trading stock.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco bourse is the nation's third-largest options
exchange, but it is an also-ran in the stock exchange business.
</P>
<P>
   Under its reorganization plan, exchange members would no longer
automatically be able to trade stock. Instead, anyone, whether a
seat owner or not, would have to buy a license for a fee of $2,000
a month to trade stock.
</P>
<P>
   If its approved by members and the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the new system would be phased in over a nine-month
period beginning before year end.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange seats, which sell for about $450,000 each, would still
entitle owners to trade options. Eventually, though, Pacific will
probably junk the membership system for options, too, insiders
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's stock operation, like those of other regional
exchanges, has been in decline for years, as the New York exchange
and Nasdaq grabbed the lion's share of the business.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when Pacific planned to merge with the Chicago Board
Options Exchange, the exchange crafted a plan to sell or spin off
stock trading. When the merger collapsed, Pacific took steps to
make stock trading profitable again, such as planning to shut
costly trading floors in Los Angeles and San Francisco and have
floor brokers set up shop in their own offices.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new reorganization plan, Pacific would subsidize its
stock-trading subsidiary for 18 months, at the end of which it
would sell, spin off or liquidate if it fails to make money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
