<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     08-09 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Investor Didn't Lose Out In Spin-Off 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I purchased some Barnes &AMP; Noble stock several months ago, hoping
to capture some of the value from their online book sales. But in
May, they spun off the online operation _ Barnesandnoble.com _ in
an initial public offering, and I was left with the
bricks-and-mortar piece, whose stock price tanked. Is this legal?
Was I extremely naive? I am still in shock.
<P>
   A: It's not as bad as you think.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble (the bricks-and-mortar version) spun off only
about 18 percent of the shares of Barnesandnoble.com. It still
holds 41 percent, while the remaining 41 percent is owned by its
partner in the online venture _ the German book retailer
Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Barnes &AMP; Noble stock has skidded about 20 percent
since the company spun off Barnesandnoble.com. But as a shareholder
of Barnes &AMP; Noble, you participate indirectly in the stock
performance of Barnesandnoble.com because of the parent company's
continued stake in the online operation. It is reflected in the
price of your Barnes &AMP; Noble shares.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, your company received about $225 million in cash as
its portion of the IPO proceeds. If management knows what it is
doing, that money will be used to enhance the profitability of the
present assets and perhaps to acquire additional assets.
</P>
<P>
   I should point out that there is no law that required you to
keep your Barnes &AMP; Noble stock after the company announced its
plans for a Barnesandnoble.com spin-off. You could have sold your
stock then and there, and later invested the proceeds in
Barnesandnoble.com. Because the online operation is what attracted
you in the first place, that might have been your most appropriate
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that your company didn't gut itself. It got
fair value _ or something close to it _ for the assets it sold.
That's the way most publicly held companies behave. If they didn't,
they would have the regulators and their institutional shareholders
on their heads in no time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Buying Vanguard Fund
</P>
<P>
   Q: You recently wrote about index funds and, in particular,
about the Vanguard Index Trust 500 fund, whose performance is
designed to track the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index. How do I invest
in that fund? Also, is it good only for a long-term-retirement type
of investment, as distinguished from money I might need before
retirement?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are interested in buying shares in the fund, write to
the Vanguard Financial Center, P.O. Box 2600, Valley Forge, PA
19482. Or call toll-free at (800) 662-7447. Ask for a fund
prospectus and for any other fund literature they have available.
</P>
<P>
   As to how good an investment it is, that will hinge on the
future performance of the S&AMP;P 500 index, which is unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   The index is made up of the largest publicly held companies in
the United States. That sounds good on the surface, though some
experts say that the S&AMP;P 500 has become overpriced in recent years
and that it is due for a correction.
</P>
<P>
   The index has had its good years and its bad during its
seven-decade existence _ though it hasn't actually declined since
1990. In recent years, the passively managed Vanguard fund steadily
has outperformed the great majority of managed funds.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no guarantee that this will continue to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether this should be a long-term investment: ideally,
yes. The stock market's long-term performance is far more reliable
than its short-term performance. You are taking a modest risk if
you invest money in the stock market that you need in five years.
If you need it in two years or less, the risk is substantial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
How to Get In on IPOs
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been hearing a lot about initial public offerings and
was wondering: How can I buy shares in an IPO?
</P>
<P>
   A: Several years ago, I would have advised you to become rich
and befriend an investment banker. IPOs used to be strictly elite
affairs for people who gave plenty of brokerage and other business
to Wall Street firms.
</P>
<P>
   While that still is largely true, the IPO process has become a
bit more democratic in the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Retail customers of such brokerage firms as Charles Schwab,
Fidelity Investments, E-Trade and Wit Capital can get limited
amounts of IPO shares underwritten by such high-powered investment
bankers as BancBoston Robertson Stephens, Credit Suisse First
Boston, Goldman Sachs, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, Lehman Brothers, J.P.
Morgan Securities and Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Another investment banker that offers IPOs to the general public
is W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co. However, it offers them through a so-called
Dutch auction bidding process _ called an ``Open IPO'' _ which
results in an offering price close to the stock's intrinsic market
value. As a result, the Open IPOs don't make huge price gains on
the first day, as usually happens with conventional IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you are attracted to IPOs in hopes of a first-day
bonanza, forget about Open IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
