<DOCNO> NYT19990809.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-Y2K_SFCHRON &LR;      08-09 1586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-Y2K </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Shielding Your Portfolio From Y2K Losses  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
With less than five months remaining until the end of the year, it
is time for investors to think about ways to protect their
portfolios from a potential Year 2000 stock-market disaster.
<P>
   Not that a disaster necessarily will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have been working full steam to purge the world's
computer systems of all the errant chips and software that might
think 2000 is 1900. If the effort falls short, commerce _ or much
of it _ could grind to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   However, most computer people and economists contend that there
is no longer any need to fear a Y2K meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   They say the widely discussed doomsday scenario _ replete with
massive power failures, transportation breakdowns, bank and
brokerage collapses, looting, food riots _ is a product of
ill-informed, overwrought minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the probabilities are very high that on Jan. 1, 2000,
nothing very unusual is going to happen,'' declared Robert T.
Parry, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco, in a
recent speech. Regulators and executives in virtually all
industries have made strong progress toward Y2K compliance, he
observed.
</P>
<P>
   But he also conceded that ``probabilities aren't certainties.''
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers old enough to remember back more than five years
know that stocks can plummet 30 or 40 percent in a short time.
Trade deficits, oil shocks and inflationary spirals have inflicted
severe damage on the market in decades past.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K doomsday scenario _ if it becomes a reality _ could do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   So, how does someone who owns stocks or mutual funds prepare for
it?
</P>
<P>
   You can choose from three plausible strategies:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_You can take the long-term view and do nothing, on the premise
that the stock market always recovers (eventually) from even the
steepest declines. If you have a solid blue-chip portfolio, that
could be the right choice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_You can sell at least some of your stocks or fund shares and hold
the cash to reinvest next year, after the dust settles. The most
likely candidates for sale might include foreign securities or U.S.
companies with a heavy foreign presence, because Y2K compliance is
lagging overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. is clearly the leader in Y2K compliance,'' observes
Chris Hill, a spokesman for the Motley Fool online investment site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_You can, in effect, insure your portfolio against a calamitous
drop by buying put options on individual stocks and stock market
indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Not many experts expect Y2K to cause a market crash _ or at
least not many will admit it. On the other hand, no one absolutely
will dismiss the possibility, because no one knows for certain
where the Y2K glitch still lurks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall impact on the U.S. economy is going to be fairly
limited,'' says Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells Capital
Management in San Francisco. ``It should be perceptible but
containable _ not a major disruption.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INTERNATIONAL CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   But he adds: ``The biggest question mark is how does the
international scene affect us? The extent to which preparations
have been made overseas is a big question mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg offers this ray of hope: ``The industries that are
most exposed overseas and those here, like banks, which deal with
an array of industries in their lending decisions, are the
industries that took the greatest precautions and are furthest
along.''
</P>
<P>
   He concludes: ``Industries will recover as any problems are
dealt with. Individual investors should be encouraged to take the
longer view, as they should in every facet of their investment
decisions. They should be investing with a long-term strategy. If
they have a good long-term portfolio, they should leave it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Salamone, director of trading with the Investment Research
Institute in Cincinnati, argues that the stock market ``is a
discounting mechanism'' and that what may happen after the turn of
the year already should be reflected in current stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, he acknowledges that the market obviously is not
discounting ``catastrophes, such as planes falling out of the sky _
the worst sort of scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   Could the market's recent slump _ with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index down more than 7 percent from the high reached on July 16 _
reflect fears about Y2K?
</P>
<P>
   Salamone says it is more likely that the market mainly is
discounting expected increases in interest rates in the wake of
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's repeated warnings about
inflation. ``The market's biggest challenge is the Fed as we go
forward,'' he contends.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, a market strategist with Salomon Smith Barney in
New York, says he isn't sure that Y2K will be ``the end of the
world'' or even ``a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says investors might want ``some liquidity to take
advantage of any pullback in the market _ if there is such. I would
take money out of lesser-quality securities that may have performed
poorly already.''
</P>
<P>
   However, investors don't necessarily have to sell securities to
protect their holdings. They can do it instead by purchasing put
options, which can be used to offset declines in many hundreds of
individual stocks or in a broad assortment of indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Put options give you the right to sell a stock or index at a
fixed price before a fixed deadline. They, therefore, rise in value
as prices fall.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy them on various options exchanges from other
investors or from brokerage firms that make a market in options.
</P>
<P>
   The latest option prices can be found in such
investment-oriented newspapers as the Wall Street Journal, and
during trading hours, they can be tracked on market-quote machines
or on brokerage firm Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOW PUT OPTIONS WORK
</P>
<P>
   Put options are the opposite of call options, which give you the
right to buy securities at a fixed price before a fixed deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Most investors consider options too speculative or mysterious to
mess with. But they can be understood, if not mastered, with a few
hours of study.
</P>
<P>
   Options can be bought through just about any broker, offline or
online.
</P>
<P>
   However, because they are indeed speculative _ it is common for
investors to lose all the money they pay for an option _ your
broker might refuse to let you buy them if your financial resources
seem too limited.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem with options, apart from the speculative
danger, is that they can be expensive. If you buy put options in
anticipation of a market meltdown and the market goes up instead,
you will have wasted a significant portion of your assets.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, you have to think of put options as similar to
medical insurance: You pay the premium, but maybe you don't get
sick. But that's OK, too _ right?
</P>
<P>
   Each put option corresponds to 100 shares of an individual
stock, or to 100 times the value of a stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, for example, Coca-Cola stock was selling for
$60.88 per share _ $6,087.50 for a 100-share lot. At the same time,
a put option allowing you to sell 100 shares of Coke at $60 per
share before next February 19 could be bought for $450.
</P>
<P>
   That $450 premium amounted to more than 7 percent of the value
of the 100 Coke shares _ a stiff price to pay for six months' worth
of insurance. But if Y2K were to send Coke's price tumbling below
$55.50 per share by February, the price you paid for the put option
would be justified because its value would rise above $450.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock fell to $50 per share, for example, you would lose
$1,087.50 in market value on the stock, but your loss would be
partly offset by a $550 gain in the value of the put option. The 18
percent decline in the stock price would translate to only a 9
percent decline for you because you were protected by the put.
</P>
<P>
   Why, you may ask, shouldn't a worried investor simply sell a
stock that seems worrisome rather than fooling around with put
options?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that once you sell the stock, you lose your chance
to profit if the price surprises you and goes higher. The neat
thing about a put option is that if you are wrong and the stock
remains strong, you still own the stock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOOD FOR INDEXES
</P>
<P>
   It usually is more cost-efficient to buy put options on an index
rather than individual stocks _ assuming that you expect the market
in general to tank. Index options tend to be more reasonably
priced, and you don't have to pay multiple commissions.
</P>
<P>
   However, it doesn't make sense for people with small portfolios
to protect them with index options because indexes are much
higher-priced than most stocks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was priced late
last week at 1,313.71, which means that a single S&AMP;P 500 put option
would protect a portfolio with assets of 100 times that much, or
$131,371.
</P>
<P>
   A put option allowing you to sell the index at 1,200 before next
March 18 was selling at a hefty $6,375, or nearly 5 percent of the
$131,371 total.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, to make things simple, that your portfolio is worth
exactly $131,371, and that its performance exactly tracks the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   If the S&AMP;P 500 were to plunge 30 percent below last week's
level, the value of your put would rise to $28,040 _ nearly $22,000
above your purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   The net result is that a 30 percent drop in the market would
result in only a 14 percent drop in the value of your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
