<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-BACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns, backers are back
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: Ohio editors.)
 &HT;    By Christine Vasconez and Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ High-fives, chants and cheers overtook the once
tearful, grimacing faces of Cleveland Browns fans Monday night as
the ``new'' team played the Dallas Cowboys in Canton.
</P>
<P>
   Fans packed bars like Damon's in Kettering to celebrate the
Browns comeback as an expansion team, after it left Ohio for
Maryland, where the team is now called the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly a momentous occasion,'' said Eric Gayheart about
the exhibition game. ``It's been three years since they've played.
It's nice to see them on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the Browns are back, it's a beautiful time,'' said
Gayheart, who sat across the table from his foe, a Cowboy fan.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Hamilton, a fan for almost 30 years, said, ``to me this
first game is a rebirth, part of history like Neil Armstrong's
first step on the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Many die-hard Browns fans mourned the team leaving Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying a lot and I didn't watch football for awhile,''
said Hamilton, who brought his 11-year-old daughter to Damon's. ``I
think every fan said you may take the team, but not the name or
colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayheart, who was converted from a Bengals fan to a Browns fan
in the early '80s by his uncle, said ``it's like a part of you was
taken away. I felt something missing.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other backers never let their love for the Browns die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd come out to a big atmosphere to grab the game,''
said Jesse Showalter, who wore a replica of quarterback Tim Couch's
No.2 jersey. ``It's been three long years since I've been able to
root for a team and the day has finally come.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Ohio's card-carrying Browns Backers had their own
predictions about the season as they planted themselves in front of
television sets in their respective communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I didn't even want to attend Monday's
game because I really felt it was a night to be with other members
of my chapter,'' said Piqua's Greg Foutz, 48, president of the
1,100-member Miami Valley Browns Backers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Browns Backers is one of the largest sports-oriented fan clubs
in the nation. Of the dozens of BB chapters scattered about Ohio,
the Piqua-based branch is the largest.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate Dayton area has at least two chapters _ the
Greater Dayton Browns Backers and the Northwest Browns Backers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Foutz and his cronies were divided into two camps to
catch the televised game.
</P>
<P>
   Some were decked out in orange and brown caps, shirts and
what-have-you at the End Zone Lounge in Covington.
</P>
<P>
   Others huddled around TVs at Slammer's Nightclub Inc. in
Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so big, we can't all fit into one bar any more,'' Foutz
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
