<HEADER>
A1268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OOPS BALL, AS PLAYED BY CHECKETTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just when we appeared to be experiencing a summer
free of Knicks conspiracy, here comes the news that Dave Checketts
has apparently been at it again. Exploring his options, trying to
make another impact hire, without consulting us first.
</P>
<P>
   I'm actually half-serious about this. It was reported Monday in
Salt Lake City and later confirmed that Checketts has reached back
to his Utah roots in an attempt to hire Scott Layden to run the
basketball operations at Madison Square Garden. That's what
Checketts gets paid to do, but something was obviously missing
here. It's called a news release, and it should have been handed
out weeks ago, and this is what it could have said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Knicks are in the process of seeking a new
director of basketball operations and are considering several
candidates, including Ed Tapscott, who is currently holding the
position on an interim basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a period of relative calm that included a reported
extension of Coach Jeff Van Gundy's contract created the false
public impression that Tapscott would soon officially be named
Ernie Grunfeld's successor, when Checketts returned from vacation.
Tapscott worked the college draft and just the other day signed
John Wallace as a free agent. Then came Monday's Layden report and,
once again, the operative word for the way Checketts has gone about
his business was ``oops.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts never owed Tapscott the job, though it sure would be a
welcome change in the way most professional sports teams operate if
an African-American assistant like Tapscott could occasionally
inherit a big job the way white men so often do. It's always useful
to remember that Van Gundy had never been a head coach anywhere
important when he was given the Knicks job. Grunfeld was Al
Bianchi's right-hand man _ the way Tapscott was his _ when he was
promoted back in the Pat Riley days. Riley himself was a washed-up
jock, a coaching nobody, when the Lakers' owner, Jerry Buss, handed
him the best team in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tapscott, a lawyer, college coach and onetime player agent, has
more than enough credentials and experience in the Knicks'
organization to be given the shot. At the very least, no matter who
winds up with the job, Checketts comes off as strangely oblivious
to a sensitive issue, when you would have thought he'd have known
better.
</P>
<P>
   For years around these parts, Checketts has had the reputation
as something of a public relations authority, a real smoothie, but
that unflappable exterior cracked during the cloak-and-dagger Phil
Jackson affair last spring. It wasn't Checketts' pursuit of Jackson
that was ill advised; it was the sloppy Nixonian cover-up. Contract
extension notwithstanding, you wonder if Van Gundy will ever truly
trust Checketts or work harmoniously with him.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing here, or playing amateur psychologist, but that has
to be why Checketts has been out West, trying to persuade Layden to
return to his own eastern roots in New York. Checketts has a
personal agenda, the need for a trustworthy organizational ally,
one of ``his guys'' completely in charge. Tapscott was hired by
Grunfeld, who was fed his last supper by Checketts just before the
Knicks turned their season around. Van Gundy, meanwhile, was hung
out so badly during the playoffs that he needed his father to come
down to the Garden one Sunday afternoon to give him a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Layden is highly respected, at 42 a young veteran who has kept
the Jazz in contention as the core of the team has aged. Then
again, Karl Malone and John Stockton were already on the Utah
roster when Layden took over 11 years ago, seven years after he
joined the Jazz, then coached by his father, Frank. Layden has also
worked his entire career in an organization which is the Knicks'
polar opposite. In Utah, the team president doesn't become a
corporate sacrifice and cheap motivational tool in the final
desperation lap of a disappointing season. Layden, I would imagine,
was likely getting an earful on that very subject when he was
meeting with his Utah superiors late into the day.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the result, it's nice to know we will have the Knicks
to liven things up around here before long, with their own special
brand of family dysfunction. Van Gundy has now been reminded that
while he won himself a huge contract, he'd better mind his X's and
O's. Tapscott has got a lesson in the social pitfalls of corporate
climbing. Just when people began to speculate that the Knicks were
finally all on the same page, moving forward after the finals, here
came the news that Checketts still wanted to shake up the mix,
bring another slice of Utah to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
