<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON STOPS OFF TO LISTEN TO BROOKLYNITES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After weeks of traveling throughout New York state,
Hillary Rodham Clinton's listening tour stopped Monday for the
first time in New York City, where she held a discussion about
education in a section of Brooklyn that is expected to be solidly
behind her all-but-announced campaign for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's 90-minute session took her to the Concord Baptist
Church, a landmark religious institution in the borough's Bedford
Stuyvesant section.
</P>
<P>
   She listened to a host of people offer criticisms and
observations about problems in inner-city education, from the need
for smaller class sizes and improved after-school programs to
dissatisfaction about the lack of foreign-language courses.
</P>
<P>
   The comments and questions were all polite, and some of the 250
participants _ the largest gathering to date on Mrs. Clinton's
listening tour _ were openly supportive of her anticipated
candidacy. When Mary Pinkett, a City Councilwoman from Brooklyn,
addressed Mrs. Clinton as ``Senator-to-be Clinton,'' the entire
room erupted in applause.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton seemed intent on blunting criticism from some
politicians that, while traveling from Binghamton to Elmira to
Rochester in recent weeks, she had ignored traditionally Democratic
strongholds in New York City, particularly in black and Hispanic
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mrs. Clinton's appearance in Brooklyn, the Rev. Al
Sharpton continued his criticism of her by complaining that she had
not yet met with a number of black and Hispanic politicians and
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she meets with everyone all over the state and has not
met with a David Dinkins or Al Sharpton, the message she is sending
to the black and Latino community, the largest and most consistent
Democratic voters, is very much of concern to me.'' He added, ``I
think some of that public complaint is what led her to go to
Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton won strong praise from the Democratic Party
officials who met with her Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very interested in the issues affecting people here,''
said Angel Rodriguez, a City Councilman from the Sunset Park
section of Brooklyn. ``I felt she was listening to what we were
saying. That's not what you get from the current administration.
Giuliani doesn't listen,'' he said, referring to Mrs. Clinton's
potential Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton spent much of her day immersed in activities that
candidates typically undertake to lay the foundation of a campaign.
She held a private meeting at a Brooklyn hotel with about 40
prominent Democrats from the city and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the people who are the real political infrastructure
of the Democratic Party,'' said Assemblyman Clarence Norman Jr.,
the Brooklyn Democratic Party chairman. ``They all clearly
indicated enthusiastically that we're going to collectively be
behind the first lady if she decides to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Mrs. Clinton attended a $1,000-a-person reception
that was expected to raise $100,000 for her campaign exploratory
committee. The reception was held at the Manhattan home of Patricia
Kenner, the owner of a bus company, her aides said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
