<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves triumph in eighth, beat Astros 5-3
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves needed to be resourceful with the NL
Central-leading Astros in town for the first of a three-game series
and the Mets a half-game in first place in the East going into
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz was just the man for the job.
</P>
<P>
   In his never-ending search for a way to throw with less elbow
pain, he dropped down and threw some pitches from the side. The
ploy helped limit the Astros to two runs despite 11 hits, and the
Braves' lineup proved resourceful enough in the late innings to
beat the Astros 5-3. The winning hit was a two-run single by
Pascual Matos in the eigthth after he just missed a home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had won only one of Smoltz's previous six starts,
three of them as he was heading back onto the disabled list, four
on his way off. Now comes the hard part with Shane Reynolds and
Jose Lima to contend with the next two days. They have combined for
29 wins and given the Astros' starting rotation two big reasons to
lead the majors with a 3.79 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Twice the Braves came back from one-run down, first on a two-out
Ryan Klesko liner past Jeff Bagwell in the third inning and the
second on a total team effort in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back singles by Greg Myers and Jose Hernandez started it
off, and a sacrifice by Ozzie Guillen got them into scoring
position. Gerald Williams tied it at 2 with a sacrifice fly to
center, and after Keith Lockhart drew a walk, Chipper Jones drove
in the go-ahead run by singling softly to left.
</P>
<P>
   That was the end of the night for Chris Holt, who added some
more hard luck to his season. Holt entered the game with a 2-11
record, with the Astros scoring only 3.1 runs per game in those 11
losses. He wasn't even that fortunate Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz dropped down to mix in some low 90s fastballs from a new
angle with his over the top fastball in the mid 90s.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz gave up 11 hits, 10 of them singles, but the Astros
managed runs off him only on a Carl Everett single up the middle in
the third inning and a looping two-out, two-strike single by Tim
Bogar in the sixth inning. Smoltz got out of a first-and-third jam
in the seventh by striking out Jeff Bagwell and coaxing a double
play out of Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones left some spike imprints in the center-field wall
as he robbed Bill Spiers of extra bases in the third inning. Jones
sprinted back toward the 400 mark, then sprung up and cradled the
ball in his glove just before hitting the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
