<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEATSHOP-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 COMPANIES AGREE TO MONITORING OF MARIANAS PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four major retailers Monday settled claims brought against them
in a class-action suit that amounted to the biggest legal challenge
ever posed against sweatshops on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   The retailers _ Nordstrom, Gymboree, Cutter &AMP; Buck and J. Crew,
a subsidiary of the Texas Pacific Group _ agreed to require
independent monitoring for compliance with basic minimum labor
standards at the factories they use in the Northern Marianas, a
U.S. commonwealth in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The four companies were among 18 American retailers and apparel
manufacturers accused in the lawsuit of conspiring with Marianas
factory owners to deprive 15,000 apparel workers of their basic
rights and to keep many of them in involuntary servitude, all with
the aim of holding down production costs.
</P>
<P>
   Another four retailers that Albert Meyerhoff, the chief lawyer
for the plaintiffs, had threatened to add as defendants said Monday
that they had agreed in principle to settle as well. Like the first
four, these retailers _ Polo/Ralph Lauren, Donna Karan
International, Phillips-Van Heusen and Chadwick's of Boston _
pledged to require independent monitoring of Marianas factories and
to help finance such monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, seeking more than $1 billion in damages, was filed
in January on behalf of a potential class of 50,000 workers and
former workers, most of them on the Marianas' largest island,
Saipan, a booming site for garment manufacturers who ship to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Among the remaining defendants are the Gap, Tommy Hilfiger and
Wal-Mart, all of which deny wrongdoing and say they already have
strict codes of conduct for their contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord reached Monday, which requires the approval of
the Federal District Court in Los Angeles, the four settling
retailers pledged to pay a total of $1.25 million for monitoring
Marianas factories and to require that those factories honor basic
rights like overtime pay and safe food and water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement establishes a monitoring program with teeth,''
said Lora Jo Foo, president of Sweatshop Watch, a labor rights
group. ``It will make a difference in the lives of thousands of
Saipan garment workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit charged that many of the workers, for the most part
citizens of China, had promised recruiters up to $10,000 each to
transport them to Saipan, where, the suit maintained, they worked
in indentured servitude to pay those fees. In the settlement, the
four companies pledged not to use factories that employ workers who
have paid recruitment fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlement uses the economic leverage of these prestigious
American retailers to influence the labor practices of these
foreign-owned factories,'' Meyerhoff said. ``We must ask ourselves,
`If this agreement is good enough for Ralph Lauren and Nordstrom,
why isn't it good enough for Tommy Hilfiger or Wal-Mart?'''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement calls for a respected nonprofit monitoring
organization, Verite, based in Amherst, Mass., to inspect the
Marianas factories. This monitoring will include unannounced
factory visits and investigation of complaints by workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long, drawn-out battle didn't make good sense to us even
though we remain confident about our ability to successfully defend
ourselves,'' said Erik Nordstrom, Nordstrom's co-president. ``We
feel these resources are better spent elsewhere and could be used
toward making a good-faith effort to furthering our commitment to
using vendors who comply with the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutter &AMP; Buck also issued a statement, saying that it was
confident it would have prevailed in the lawsuit but that it
thought it should put the matter behind it in a way that would help
improve the working environment at the factories it uses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
