A1276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-ART-     08-09 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MAGAZINE EDITOR EXPECTED TO DUST OFF ARMANI'S IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, Matthias Vriens, the editor in chief of
Dutch, the avant-garde fashion magazine, was talking about moving
it from Paris to New York, where it might draw on the same artistic
vitality that already has attracted European designers like Helmut
Lang and Alexander McQueen.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the plug has been pulled on that possibility, because last
week it was announced that Vriens would be moving to Milan to
become creative director of Giorgio Armani.
</P>
<P>
   What can this mean to Armani, the successful but aging fashion
house, which will celebrate its 25th anniversary next year?
Probably a lot, to judge from Armani's choice of a farsighted
editor whose magazine represents the vanguard in fashion and
photography.
</P>
<P>
   At Dutch, Vriens, 36, sought out new photographers and typically
devoted an entire issue to a single theme, like the influence of
Yves Saint Laurent. A modest man with a sly sense of humor, Vriens
has been known to take relatively banal ideas, like publishing
childhood snapshots of designers opposite current images of
themselves or their work, and create strangely meaningful effects.
At Armani, he will surely have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like making a magazine, I'll be working with visuals for
Mr. Armani,'' said Vriens, who will oversee advertising campaigns,
packaging design and retail merchandising. ``It's the same job, but
from the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Armani built his reputation on soft-tailored sportswear
_ and still commands the respect of retailers because a
significantly high percentage of his clothes sell at full price _
the designer has lost ground in less tangible ways.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five or six years, companies like Gucci and Prada
have evolved into marketing powerhouses, and while much of their
business comes from nonapparel items like shoes and handbags, they
have used advertising and sensational runway shows to exploit their
fashion reputations.
</P>
<P>
   Armani, by contrast, has seemed almost stubbornly to refuse to
play this modern shill game, a natural response perhaps from an
$840 million company with six labels, more than 200 stores and a
slew of licenses, all more or less controlled by a single
individual.
</P>
<P>
   But Armani is changing, in a fashion. Three months ago, he hired
Andrew Grossman, an experienced American retailing executive, as
chief operating officer of the company's American subsidiary. At
the same time, Robert Triefus was put in charge of corporate
communications.
</P>
<P>
   It was Triefus, formerly with Calvin Klein, who helped compose a
short list of candidates for creative director, a new position now
filled by Vriens.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that Armani has heard rumblings from the fashion
press that his image has not moved forward, Triefus said the latest
changes came from the designer himself. ``He wants to feel that,
aside from design, the company is communicating in a modern way,''
Triefus said.
</P>
<P>
   Vriens, who is known as Matty, will have his work cut out for
him. Aside from giving Armani's advertising a fresh look, he will
be involved with the spring runway shows in Milan, which will take
place not in Armani's palazzo, now thoroughly familiar to the
fashion press, but in a new location. Next year, the company will
introduce cosmetics and home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Vriens, who is Dutch and, for now, converses with Armani in
French, said they share an affinity for photography and film.
Recalling their first meeting, when Armani was perusing a copy of
Dutch (which, just to confuse matters, is published in English),
Vriens said the designer told him, ``You have a strong point of
view.''
</P>
<P>
   But this doesn't mean that Armani can't teach an editor a few
tricks. When Vriens recently pitched an idea, he said Armani calmly
told him he had already tried it and then reminded him, ``So we
need to move on, Matty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
