<SLUG> BC-TIMES-FOUNDATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK ROSENTHAL TO FOLLOW GELB AS HEAD OF TIMES FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jack Rosenthal, an assistant managing editor of The
New York Times, was named Monday to succeed Arthur Gelb as
president of The New York Times Co. Foundation. The announcement
was made by Arthur Sulzberger Jr., chairman of New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment is effective Feb. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1956, The Times Foundation is a private charity that
provides grants to nonprofit institutions and administers The New
York Times Neediest Cases Fund and the recently established college
scholarship program. Last year, the foundation made $5 million in
grants and raised a record $6.7 million for the Neediest Cases.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal, 64, has been an assistant managing editor since 1993
as well as editor in chief of The New York Times Magazine. In 1982,
as editorial page editor, he was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for
editorial writing.
</P>
<P>
   A former correspondent for Life magazine, Rosenthal joined The
Times as national urban affairs correspondent in 1969. In 1968, he
was the principal author of the Kerner Commission report on race
relations. Rosenthal graduated from Harvard University in 1956 with
a B.A. degree in history.
</P>
<P>
   Gelb, 75, has been president of The New York Times Co.
Foundation since Sept. 1, 1990. He retired as managing editor of
The Times earlier that year, completing a career in the newsroom
that began in 1944, when he started as a copy boy. He received a
B.A. degree in English from New York University in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   He held numerous positions at The Times, including drama critic,
chief cultural correspondent and cultural news editor, and was
metropolitan editor from 1967 to 1976. As deputy managing editor in
the late 1970s, he played an important role in the creation of new
daily feature sections _ Weekend, Living, Home, SportsMonday and
Science Times.
</P>
<P>
   Gelb will continue to oversee the scholarship program and write
a new three-volume biography and television documentary on Eugene
O'Neill, as well as a memoir about his career at The Times. With
his wife, Barbara, Gelb wrote ``O'Neill,'' the definitive biography
of the playwright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
