<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR'S BIRTH DAY A TIME TO REMEMBER JOYS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Someone apparently worn down by the hassles of daily
life composed what's become a well-traveled e-mail _ I've received
several copies and seen it posted on a couple of office boards _
that's called a ``resignation from adulthood.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter suffers from a schmaltzy tone, but there are times
when most of us can relate and wish to see life through younger,
more innocent eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to live simple again,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my day to consist of computer crashes, mountains
of paperwork, depressing news, how to survive more days in the
month than there is money in the bank, doctor bills, gossip,
illness and the loss of loved ones. I want to believe in the power
of smiles, hugs, a kind word, truth, justice, peace, dreams, the
imagination, mankind and making angels &UR; in the snow.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter made me think of E.B. White, the incandescent writer
born 100 years ago this summer. Though he would have shuddered at
its syntax, he would have respected the impulse.
</P>
<P>
   White was this century's greatest essayist, a poet and co-author
of ``The'' ``Elements of Style,'' the wisest writing guide ever
published. But none of his work surpassed his children's classic,``
Charlotte's Web''.
</P>
<P>
   Published in 1953, the book has sold more than 10 million
copies. Eudora Welty's review in the ``New York Times'' concluded:
``As a piece of work it is just about perfect.'' In a poll of
educators and authors two decades ago, it was named the best
children's story in American history.
</P>
<P>
   The book tells of a runt pig named Wilbur, whose life is saved
twice _ first by Fern, an 8-year-old farm girl, then by Charlotte,
a clever gray spider. The story line grew out of the death of one
of the author's own pigs on his Maine farm.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else he wrote, the book reveals White's
philosophy of life, expressed by all three characters.
</P>
<P>
   Through Fern, he celebrated a child's love of the world and the
view that nature's creations don't live on the Earth solely to
serve human desires.
</P>
<P>
   When told that Wilbur would be killed because he was a runt who
``will never amount to anything,'' she pleaded that being born
small wasn't his fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ``I'' had been very small at birth, would you have killed
me?'' she asked, persuading her father to spare the pig.
</P>
<P>
   Through Charlotte, he extolled the values of friendship and
looking out for the well-being of others. In her last conversation
with Wilbur, the pig asked why she had been done so much for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been my friend,'' she told him. ``That in itself is a
tremendous thing. . . . After all, what's a life anyway? We're
born, we live a little while, we die. A spider's life can't help
being something of a mess, with all this trapping and eating of
flies. By helping you, perhaps I was trying to lift up my life a
trifle.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Wilbur, he spoke up for simple, everyday pleasures.
Wilbur was thrilled to be alive and considered the barn ``the best
place to be . . . this warm delicious cellar, with the garrulous
geese, the changing seasons, the passage of swallows, the nearness
of rats, the sameness of sheep, the love of spiders, the smell of
manure, and the glory of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   White, who died in 1985, spent two years writing the book, then
another year drafting revisions. Its magic comes from the childlike
sensibility it brings to such adult themes as loneliness, fear,
callousness, sacrifice and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integrity of White's view of the world owed much to the
boy he kept in touch with despite his own loss of innocence,''
wrote Scott Elledge, his biographer.
</P>
<P>
   White would say you don't need to resign from adulthood to see
life as a child sees it. In fact, he would say people can deal with
all manner of adult burdens and at the same time savor the power of
smiles, hugs, truth, imagination and angels in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   The joys and wonder of life don't go away as we get older, they
get covered up. They're still with us, dormant, waiting. Once in a
while someone comes along and tells a story that stirs our
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Happy birthday, E.B. White. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
