<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLIMANE-FASHION-ART-N     08-09 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLIMANE-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT MAN FROM SAINT LAURENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble with explaining Hedi Slimane and his remarkable rise
as the men's wear designer at Yves Saint Laurent _ the 20 percent
sales increase in the last year, the panting of stylists _ is that
it's a little like trying to explain why a woman falls in love with
the guy next door. One day she sees him as Mr. Ordinary, and the
next she's falling down in a swoon of delight. And all because she
suddenly turned her head and saw him in a different light.
</P>
<P>
   That, in a nutshell, is how a designer with no formal training
or obvious qualifications, apart from a tendency to be obsessive,
took a sleepy men's wear label and almost single-handedly (he has a
team; let's be fair) transformed it into one of the hottest names
in the business. Vince Ehly, the men's sportswear buyer at Barneys
New York, said that demand for Slimane's clothes is strong,
especially in Los Angeles, where his slender, elongating suits are
a hit with stylists catering to people in the movie industry.
Two-thirds of the spring collection sold at full price, Ehly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did as well as our more established collections,'' said
Ehly, who couldn't account for the rush, except to say, ``Here
comes Hedi, and the clothes look so different than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Slimane (pronounced slim-ON) was hired,
Saint Laurent's men's wear was pretty much confined to a couple of
company-owned boutiques in New York and Paris, and a franchise in
London. And that's about as far as interest went. But today you can
find the clothes at Fred Segal in Los Angles, Collette in Paris and
Jeffrey in New York. This fall, Saks Fifth Avenue will start
carrying the line. Not long ago, Stephen Gan, the Visionaire
editor, who is a close friend of Slimane's, was in Cologne,
Germany, where, he noted with a sense of deja vu, the salesmen at
the ultra-hip boutique Citta di Bologna were all in Saint Laurent.
``I hadn't seen anything like that since the 1980s,'' Gan said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, interest in Slimane's clothes _ the flat-front
trousers that drape subtly through the hips, the razor-sharp
shoulders that instantly say Saint Laurent _ has been almost an
underground thing. But that's changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a fever,'' said Jim Moore, the fashion editor at
GQ magazine. ``There are guys now who will say, `Oh, I only wear
Saint Laurent and Gucci.''
</P>
<P>
   It's rare to hear so much enthusiasm for fashion, and
practically unheard of about a men's wear designer _ particularly
one whose clean, elegant style is so wildly at odds with the
shapeless, insipid sportswear that flattened the recent New York
men's shows. But perhaps that is why Slimane's clothes are
different. Their sex appeal is not based on over-the-top
embellishment or the latest inflated attitude. Rather, it comes
from the same honest principles that have always driven fashion:
cut, proportion and silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   Slimane has been in New York for the last couple of weeks,
visiting friends, and it was during the men's shows, in fact, which
he didn't attend, that he sat down over a sandwich at the Mercer
Hotel and talked about men, fashion and what he called ``the
psychology of people looking at Saint Laurent.''
</P>
<P>
   At 31, he is coolly elegant, with gray-blue eyes, and a crest of
hair that rises up on his head like a fin. He was born in Paris to
an Italian mother and a Tunisian father, who was an accountant.
Aside from going with his mother to buy fabric for her dressmaking
business, and waking to the hum of her sewing machine, nothing in
his background prepared him for fashion. At school, he said, he
studied political science with an idea of becoming a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Slimane conceded that it's difficult to explain how a novice
designer could be plucked from obscurity and put at one of the most
venerable houses in Paris. But he suggested that the reason was
somehow wrapped up in the mystique of Saint Laurent and, more, in
the mercurial nature of its chairman, Pierre Berge. ``I don't think
this house perhaps likes to hire known designers,'' said Slimane,
who was working for the Paris press agent Jean-Jacques Picart when
he was hired. Before that, he worked for the designer Jose Levy.
``It's something that makes Saint Laurent particular.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiring an unknown like Slimane for a men's-wear line that wasn't
exactly setting off fireworks probably didn't pose much of a risk,
either. Saint Laurent designed the collection in its early years,
but through the 1980s it gradually fell to others until the line
had almost no identity.
</P>
<P>
   As Slimane has gained more confidence, the thing that everyone
comments on is how much his collections evoke the style of Saint
Laurent without in the least seeming a homage. There is the
influence of the classic Saint Laurent tuxedo, or ``smoking,'' as
the French call it, and of course, the leather trench coat and the
see-through top, which is a nod to Saint Laurent's daring style in
the mid- &UR; ' &LR; 60s. But Slimane has given them a fresh currency on men.
``They're bold, without any fear,'' said Jeffrey Kalinsky, who owns
Jeffrey, which opened last week on West 14th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it doesn't really seem appropriate in men's wear, I like
the idea of defining a silhouette,'' Slimane said.
</P>
<P>
   As Gan pointed out, having access to a couture house has given
Slimane's men's wear a deeper sensibility. ``It's very different,''
Slimane said. ``Saint Laurent has a real fashion culture. It's a
fashion house. So you have a creative freedom that is rare.'' He
has sought out the house's longtime suppliers for such things as
furs, jewelry and hats, all of which he has used, along with
sandals and tough-looking T-shirts, to slyly manipulate the gender
boundaries in clothes. Which Saint Laurent did, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then Slimane said: ``There's a feeling you have when you work at
Saint Laurent. It's very strong and very emotional. And it's part
of history. You know, when you go to the couture show, they still
read out the numbers like they did in the 1950s. This feeling is so
important to me, because it's something you sense that is fading.
It's also very important to the people of Paris, because it's their
link to the history of fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But after five seasons at Saint Laurent, doesn't the brightest
young talent in men's wear find there is less mystery, which is
also part of the house's formidable legend and is fading fast?
Slimane laughed. ``Oh, no,'' he said. ``I think there is more,
really. That's what I love about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a funny way this is what sets Slimane himself apart: the
allure of the clothes can't be completely explained. ``You know,''
he said, ``men are not supposed to be mysterious. That's what you
say about women. But I think men can have a little of it, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
