<HEADLINE>
NAVAJOS BATTLE BOOTLEGGING WITH NEW LAWS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL DONOVAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDOW ROCK - The Navajo Nation began its war on reservation
bootleggers last week with the approval of a number of new laws
that they hope will strip away their &UR; profits.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from a number of reservation communities who say
they wanted action and not rhetoric, members of the Navajo Nation
Council agreed to increase jail sentences and fines, allow the
courts to confiscate the bootlegger's property and paved the way
for families affected by bootlegging sales to take him to tribal
court for civil damages.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is being done, said Herbert Clah, director of public
safety for the tribe, because bootlegging has become the business
of choice for more and more tribal members because of the massive
unemployment _ up to 75 percent in some areas _ on the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's profitable,` he said. ``There was one woman
bootlegger prosecuted recently federally because she was making
$150,000 a year in profits. She had five brand new homes and had
bought new cars for all of her children.`
</P>
<P>
   Tribal police estimate that a good-sized bootlegging operation
on the reservation _ and there are a couple of hundred of these on
the 25,000 square-mile reservation _ make as much as $40,000 a year
in profits, tax-free. Part-timers, who may work only doing fairs or
when there is a local pow-wow or rodeo, can net several hundred
dollars for one day's work.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more communities began seeing the downside of the
bootlegging business as car fatalities blamed on drunken drivers
and domestic violence cases began rising. For the past decade,
Indian Health Service officials have listed alcohol abuse as the
number one cause of death among the 220,000-member tribe.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion against bootleggers began in Tuba City where
community members began drawing up a list of local bootleggers and
publicly told them that their days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew who the bootleggers were but no one wanted to do
anything about it,` said Hope MacDonald, head of the community's
planning committee that started working with local police and then
began putting pressure on council delegates to support changes that
were being proposed to stiffen reservation bootlegging laws.
</P>
<P>
   The new laws will increase fines from $500 to $5,000 and jail
sentences from six months to a year but everyone admits that the
increase in jail time may be more symbolic than threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bootleggers weren't getting any jail time when the penalty was
six months because the tribal jails were overcrowded,` said Clah.
Police officials had publicly complained about bootlegging
investigations that would take weeks ending up with the accused
getting a $50 fine and only spending a couple of hours in jail
while their paperwork was being done.
</P>
<P>
   Suing a bootlegger may be a futile effort since only a few of
the top bootleggers would have enough assets to justify taking them
to court, Clah said.
</P>
<P>
   So the key may be just how serious the tribe is about using
whatever space it has available in the tribal jails for bootleggers
and whether they carry through with their authority to seize cars
and property. There have also been threats that the tribe will
begin cancelling homesite leases for convicted bootleggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bootleggers will be watching what happens in the next few
months to see if we actually enforce the new laws,` said Clah. ``If
they see nothing happening to the other bootleggers in their area,
nothing will change.`
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the reservation have learned from the past that
tougher laws dont really result in changes.
</P>
<P>
   `They've had laws on the books before to control bootleggers and
they havent used them, so I dont think there will be much changed,`
said Beth Cascaddan, who lives in Kayenta. ``They've had the power
to take away homesite leases in the past and havent done it.`
</P>
<P>
   She added that even if the tribe gets tough, bootleggers will
find a way around the laws. ``There's just too much money to make
from it,` she said.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald said she also was sceptical about how much the new
laws will change because of lax enforcement by tribal law
enforcement officials in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not going to stop pushing the police now that new
laws have been passed. We look at this as the beginning of our
efforts,` she said.
</P>
<P>
   The community has asked tribal attorneys to draft an
inter-government agreement which they plan to take to officials in
Coconino County in an effort to go after liquor stores in
communities like Flagstaff that are making a profit by selling
liquor to the bootleggers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
