<SLUG> BC-GORE-URBAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE RECALLS DAD'S FIGHT TO HELP BLACKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LORI RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Vice President Al Gore on Monday evoked the memory of
his father and the battles that Southern senator fought for civil
rights earlier this century in an effort to woo blacks gathering in
Houston to the idea that Gore will continue fighting for civil
rights in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was intensely proud of my father's opposition to the poll
tax in the 1940s and support for civil rights in the 1950s and the
Voting Rights Act in 1965,'' Gore said, recalling battles fought by
his father, former Sen. Al Gore Sr., who died in December.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's lengthy and warmly received speech Monday to more than
3,000 National Urban League conferees at the George R. Brown
Convention Center came on the heels of brief and more coolly met
remarks by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
front-runner, on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is the front-runner for the 2000 Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S. Senate in those years, there was a document
drafted called the Southern Manifesto, and it became a great
symbolic rallying point for the opponents of integration,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore reminded the league that his father and fellow Tennessean
Estes Kefauver were the only Southern senators who refused to sign
``that hateful document.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In honor of my dad,'' Gore promised his receptive audience,
``I am determined that the gains we've made this century for civil
rights will be only the beginning of the gains we make in the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made repeated reference to his long friendship with league
Executive Director Hugh B. Price and other black notables on the
dais with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a kinship with the work you have been doing,'' Gore
said, reeling off a list of Clinton administration accomplishments
he said have culminated in the lowest black unemployment and
poverty rates in history.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was repeatedly applauded, addressed the league after a
personal meeting with the family of James Byrd, the East Texas
black man who was dragged to death behind a pickup by white
supremacists outside Jasper. One of the three defendants has been
convicted in the case. Trial is pending in the other cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say here, as I said to them privately, `God bless
you for leading us toward healing and reconciliation with dignity
and grace and courage,''' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That heinous crime wounded not only the Byrd family and the
Jasper community, it wounded the American spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore pledged he would fight for passage of the federal Hate
Crimes Prevention Act, which has been passed unanimously by the
Senate and is awaiting action by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me call on all political leaders in both parties to end
their silence and support hate crimes legislation,'' Gore said.
``One of our greatest presidents, Abraham Lincoln, said in the
famous words (of Edmund Burke), `All that is necessary for evil to
triumph is for good men to do nothing.'''
</P>
<P>
   The reference was one of many jabs toward Bush, who has come
under heavy criticism for failing to push a hate-crimes measure
through the Texas Legislature this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes courage and conscience to cross those conservatives
who have no compassion,'' Gore said, in what became a repeated
litany that poked fun at Bush's campaign theme of ``compassionate
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   At a separate session devoted to black political power in the
next century, Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, and civil-rights
leader Jesse Jackson said the ever-increasing influence of money in
political campaigns, noting Bush's considerable war chest in
particular, represents a disturbing trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is vulgar,'' said Jackson. ``What we need to do is make
that level of fund-raising illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also criticized Bush for his decision not to push the
hate-crimes bill through the Texas Legislature earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush Junior equivocates on hate crimes,'' Jackson said.
``Anyone who equivocates on hate crimes, they send us a message
that intelligent people must recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which included NAACP leader Kweisi Mfume, also
debated whether the Democratic Party is the best political option
for blacks, concluding that it remained so.
</P>
<P>
   The panel members also disagreed with the notion that the
growing number of Hispanics in the United States would weaken
blacks' political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said, the change would only help the groups work
together and form a stronger voice for minorities in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our politics are the same,'' Mfume said. ``That is, to find a
way to build coalitions one on top of the other to bring about
change and break down barriers, and to do that without apology.''
</P>
<P>
   While Price refused to draw comparisons between the two leading
presidential candidates, he praised Gore for hosting a series of
private, unpublicized, off-the-record discussions in his home the
last few years on urban and racial issues. Gore also attended the
last four consecutive conventions, Price said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten to know him very well,'' Price said, noting that
Gore has called him at home to solicit input. ``There's just a very
good working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the issues. Is he on the same page with us
about the issues that we care about _ and people heard a number of
high notes today that clearly resonated with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Price said conferees were pleased that Bush had attended the
opening ceremonies Sunday. ``I extended an invitation to him on the
spot to attend our annual conference in New York City next year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem is that it might conflict with the Republican
National Convention,'' which will be in late July 2000 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's only rival
for the Democratic nomination, will address the groupTuesday.
Bradley, a former New York Knicks basketball star, had made race a
central issue of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
