<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BRUMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILTON BRUMER, 97, ENGINEER FOR FAMED NEW YORK BRIDGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)  (mk) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milton Brumer, an engineer who managed the construction of such
mighty bridges as the Verrazano-Narrows over New York Bay, the
Throgs Neck over the East River in New York and the Walt Whitman
over the Delaware, died Thursday at a hospital in Boca Raton, Fla.
He was 97 and lived in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   In a career that spanned half a century, Brumer had prime
responsibility for major engineering projects all over the world.
He supervised construction of portions of the Garden State Parkway
in New Jersey, the New Jersey Turnpike, the Connecticut Turnpike,
the Long Island, N.Y., Expressway, the Palisades Interstate Parkway
in New York and New Jersey and the Ohio Turnpike. He was the
engineer in charge of numerous bridges of reinforced concrete and
steel for the Victoria Mines Railroad in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   He brought his expertise to New York City-area projects like the
Outerbridge Crossing, Goethals Bridge, George Washington Bridge,
Bayonne Bridge and the Lincoln Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Brumer started his career as an assistant engineer in 1923 with
Interborough Rapid Transit Co. and later worked for the
Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission as a tunnel designer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, Brumer joined the engineering consulting firm of Othmar
H. Ammann, the fabled builder of the George Washington Bridge, the
Triborough Bridge and other projects. By 1949, he had become a
partner in the firm, which was then known as Ammann and Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Brumer became president of the company in 1965, retiring in
1977. He was chief engineer and consultant on highway projects,
harbor improvements and tunnel construction throughout the
Northeast. When he was chief engineer of the building of the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, which links Brooklyn and Staten Island,
it was at the time of its completion, in 1964, the longest
suspension bridge in the world. Its size was surpassed by the
Humber Bridge in England in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Brumer was born in Philadelphia on Jan. 21, 1902, raised
in Brooklyn, and was a longtime resident of the Riverdale section
of the Bronx. He was recently nominated to the Hall of Fame of the
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, from which he received a
mechanical engineering degree and an honorary doctorate of
engineering. He also received a master's degree from the University
of Alabama. He was named Engineer of the Year in 1965 by the
American Society of Civil Engineers Metropolitan Section.
</P>
<P>
   Brumer's wife died in 1996. He is survived by two daughters,
Barbara Lee Brumer of Boca Raton and Carolyn Faith Graham of
Hartsdale, N.Y.; two granddaughters and four great-grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
