A1364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-TOUR-DE-USA-COX     08-09 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-DE-USA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cross-country cyclists discover america, selves
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the middle of the night, Jennifer Eyl zoomed down a
Colorado mountainside so fast that her contact flew out of her
right eye. Legally blind without that vision aid, she kept flying,
the lights of a van behind her trailing her down the steep, winding
road.
</P>
<P>
   The story would have been scary enough in a convertible or even
in a car with the windows down. But Eyl was pushing 65 mph on a
custom-made racing bike, on a four-woman relay team competing in
the Race Across America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a moment so thrilling I felt I was barely in my body,''
said Eyl, 27.
</P>
<P>
   Eyl and her friends took just six days to reach Savannah, Ga.
from California, fueled by $35,000 in sponsorships; other local
cyclists have set off at a more leisurely pace and with a fraction
of that financial commitment. Whatever their means, those athletes
share a desire to conquer the Everest of their sport: a bicycle
trip across the country. While most Americans see the country by
car or plane, a Tour de America affords a far more intimate view of
the heartland at lower speed and on the back roads.
</P>
<P>
   The adventure is not only physically punishing but mentally
exhilirating. Cross-country bikers recount unforgettable, sometimes
hair-raising moments such as Eyl's escapade in the Rockies, as well
as bucolic, introspective times on the endless plains. The cyclists
come to realize that their journey is not just about reaching their
destination, but discovering themselves and their homeland along
the way. Completing the long-planned trek rewards them with a sense
that life's possibilities are limitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you persevere at something, and take small strides every
day, you can accomplish a great goal,'' Brian Kaplan of Decatur
said, speaking on a crackling cellphone from an RV parked in an
Oregon campground. He expects to arrive at the Pacific Ocean today,
in the culmination of a ``journey of the soul'' across 14 states
that began June 14 in Rehoboth Beach, Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   With his 40th birthday next month, the environmental-health
scientist wanted to take on a monumental physical challenge, and
because he loved to bicycle, he thought about pedaling coast to
coast. ``But just doing it for that reason seemed pretty empty,''
he said, so he decided to use the trip to promote awareness of
mental illness, which has affected his brother for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan and his wife, Joan, started planning the $3,500 trek a
year ago. He arranged time off from his work by taking accrued
vacation followed by an unpaid leave. She quit her job as a Delta
Air Lines gate agent to drive the RV.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 80 miles a day on his Raleigh R300 touring bike,
Kaplan had time to ponder the optical illusion of Wyoming
stormclouds (''You wonder if you're coming to it or it's coming to
you''), the eerieness of the Idaho desert (''You hear about ghost
towns, but it really gives you an uneasy feeling'') and the stench
of road kill (''Even if you don't see it, you can smell it''). He
ascended one pass in Montana and, several hundred feet below, could
see the rocks in the bottom of a clear, unspoiled river.
</P>
<P>
   ``No trash, no people, just nature,'' Joan said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's journals detail how they have met people along the
way who have shared with them how they have struggled like Brian's
brother, and the trip has raised $22,000 so far for the National
Alliance for the Mentally Ill. Peachtree Settlement Funding, a
financial company, donated $10,000, and Whole Foods Market is
planning a welcome-back party for the couple later this month.
</P>
<P>
   That barnstorming aspect of a cross-country trip attracts
charities that sponsor group rides in exchange for pledges, and
it's the reason Oprah Winfrey's personal trainer, Bob Greene,
promoted his latest book by pedaling 3,335 miles from Los Angeles
to New York earlier this summer. But it's not what originally
attracted grass-roots cyclists.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycling cross-country caught on in 1976 when more than 4,000
cyclists set out on the Bikecentennial TransAmerica Bicycle Trail,
with half of them completing the 4,240-mile route. From that event
was born the nonprofit Adventure Cycling Association, which has
mapped 25,000 miles of American bicycling routes and annually sells
20,000 copies of its three cross-country maps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as big of a fringe activity as you might think,''
said Kevin Condit, marketing director of the Adventure Cycling
Association; Condit cycled from coast to coast in 1993. ``You might
stereotype the average cyclist that is going cross-country as a
college student or a teacher, but it's really not. It tends to be
someone who is older than you think, and men and women are evenly
split. We've had everyone from a 12-year-old to someone who's 85,
so physical ability is less important than you think. They just
need a mindset that they really want to explore the country under
their own power.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Eyl. She bicycled alone 3,000 miles from Atlanta to San
Francisco shortly after the Olympics, and almost immediately
started recruiting members and sponsors back East for the
high-speed RAAM chase. It was the challenge she needed to keep in
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not in good shape when you do this the first time,
you will be when you're done,'' she said. ``My legs were like
rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   On her solo trek westward, the University of Georgia
classical-history graduate loaded her bike with camping gear and
stopped at all sort of podunk attractions, such as a barbed-wire
museum in Kansas. ``The worst part was my mom crying every night
when I called,'' said Eyl. The trip took her three months.
</P>
<P>
   On RAAM, she never stopped, not by choice. While two riders
slept in the RV, the other pair alternated riding, supported by
three vans. Eyl kept going through bouts of projectile vomiting
caused by drinking too many fluids. Communication breakdowns
stalled the team for more than 10 hours and left emotions beyond
frayed. Eyl's team finished in a blur of six days, 22 hours and 14
minutes, and the only scenery she remembers is a Mennonite farm in
Tennessee, where a horse pulled a plow and a farmwife dressed in
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``RAAM is not just an athletic event; it's like a Mount Everest
expedition,'' she said. ``It takes physical strength and stamina
(and) so many other variables. And it creates a gusto of emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Rush, 42, of Atlanta chose the middle ground between
Eyl's sprint and Kaplan's marathon. To ease the financial hit of
taking time off from his work, he paid $3,600 to join the
month-long, 3,404-mile Fast Ride Across America sponsored by a
touring company named America by Bicycle. Raising money for the
Atlanta Bicycle Campaign made his trip tax-deductible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out being a physical challenge,'' Rush said, ``but
it turned out to be a mental and spiritual and emotional
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 110 miles a day from Los Angeles to Boston, an
ordeal that cut his body fat in half. He endured sleet in Arizona
so thick that he found himself riding behind a snowplow; deserts so
stark that a wolf crossed right in front of his LeMond Zurich
racer; and people so friendly that they formed an impromptu welcome
wagon after the mailman alerted them to their two-wheeled visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Rush became so close to the 16 fellow riders that
three of them shaved their heads to seal their friendship and
talked each other into sticking it out when some wanted to quit.
Today, they send e-mail letters to each other all the time. The
trip made him feel fortunate for what he has, including a line of
work that allowed him the freedom to take the trip. He doesn't feel
as impatient for success or material possessions, just for his next
adventure to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing I can do this,'' Rush said, ``makes me know I could do
almost anything I wanted to if I prepare for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyl said she wouldn't mind cycling across the country a third
time. ``Doing something like this changes your idea of what is
possible and makes you realize that boundaries and limitation are
usually self-imposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's odyssey changed him. When he looks in the mirror, he
sees a face that is thinner and longer because he's lost so much
body fat. ``We feel extremely upbeat about the next 40 years,'' he
said, and part of the reason is that, slowly and up close, he's
seen the country _ and himself _ in a way he never had before.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hiskey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
