<HEADLINE>
BOXING NOTEBOOK: TYSON SCRAPS DOUGLAS; HOLYFIELD JOINS TALKS; HOPE
FOR GONZALEZ-TSZYU 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson, the former heavyweight champion, is back to square
one in regard to an opponent for his Oct. 2 bout at the MGM Grand
in Las Vegas. James ``Buster'' Douglas has been scratched as a
possibility for that fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is anxious to return to the ring and is looking to fight
someone that will be physically and mentally ready to fight in
October,'' Tyson's promoter, Dan Goossen of America Presents, said
Monday. ``At this point, Douglas does not fit that description.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen and Tyson will now concentrate on the other two
candidates, Zeljko Mavrovic and Orlin Norris. Douglas, who scored a
stunning 10th-round knockout of Tyson in February 1990, may have
fallen out of contention because the Nevada State Athletic
Commission had planned to put him through a battery of physical
exams before allowing him to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was concerned that Douglas, now 39, had ballooned
to nearly 400 pounds and lapsed into a diabetic coma in 1994.
Douglas lost the weight and made a comeback in 1996, but some in
Tyson's camp feared he would not have passed the physical.
</P>
<P>
   A Meeting With HBO
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to salvage his heavyweight unification rematch with
Lennox Lewis in November, Evander Holyfield will join the promoter
Don King in negotiations with HBO executives on Thursday afternoon.
Negotiations for the rematch hit a snag when HBO inserted a clause
in the contract that would remove King as the lead promoter if he
was indicted for any wrongdoing associated with the first
Holyfield-Lewis bout.
</P>
<P>
   That bout, on March 13 at Madison Square Garden in New York,
ended in a controversial draw. King has refused to sign the
contract, saying the clause infringes on his personal liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to see what's going on for himself,'' King said of
Holyfield's meeting HBO officials. ``Hopefully, it can be worked
out. If not, we'll go from there. But I'm not compromising on
anything. You can't be a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Seth Abraham, the president of Time-Warner Sports,
was in London last Tuesday, holding discussions with Lewis about a
possible bout with Michael Grant for the November date that is set
aside for the Holyfield-Lewis rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham said he remained optimistic that the Holyfield-Lewis
rematch could be saved. He also said, ``Lewis needs to keep busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez-Tszyu on Showtime?
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited junior-welterweight bout between Miguel Angel
Gonzalez and Kostya Tszyu may finally take place on Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   There is still some dispute about the Gonzalez-Tszyu bout. The
promoter Dan Goossen believes he has a 50 percent stake in the bout
after reaching a settlement of a lawsuit against Don King last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen will be in New York next Wednesday to ask a judge to
clarify the situation on the bout. Showtime had been saving that
Aug. 21 pay-per-view date for Mike Tyson.
</P>
</TEXT>
