<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-SARAJEVO (Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina) _ The marks of
war are nearly erased from Sarajevo. Sheets of glass have been
fitted into the high rises, and the shell holes have been plastered
over. But the Bosnian capital, which held together a mish-mash of
ethnic groups and hung on to life during almost four years of siege
by the Bosnian Serbs, has lost its sense of purpose, its direction
and many say its soul. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT8,9,18) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND-CHANGE (Bangkok, Thailand) _ There is a battle being
fought here between the cultures of Thailand's past and its
possible future _ part of a broad shift in Asia toward more open
and democratic societies. And throughout the region, an
increasingly affluent and better-educated middle class is
challenging the paternalistic order of the past, whether in violent
upheaval in Indonesia or incremental change in Thailand. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ A profile of the new prime minister,
Vladimir Putin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PALACE (Beijing) _ On the northwestern outskirts of
Beijing there once existed a vast, enchanting playground of
imperial halls and gardens, artificial lakes and even a cluster of
rococo palaces designed by European Jesuits in the 18th century.
Before it was sacked by British and French troops in 1860, the
870-acre estate included more than a thousand bridges, re-creations
of China's finest landscapes and, for royal amusement, a
make-believe town populated by eunuchs. Today, the remnants of what
is known in English as the Old Summer Palace are the subject of an
angry debate in Beijing, with clashing visions of how to
commemorate the past and a battle of esthetic sensibilities. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
