<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A WELCOME OIL DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   If someone had wanted to make America's trade laws look
ridiculous, he might have come up with the strategy that was used
by a group of small domestic oil companies when they asked the
government for relief from the ``dumping'' of cheap crude oil into
America. It is good that the Commerce Department on Monday
dismissed the petition, but the fact that it could be filed at all
shows that the anti-dumping law is far too broad.
</P>
<P>
   To dismiss the case, the Commerce Department went to great
lengths to show that most of the domestic oil industry was opposed
to the petition. The scope of the law is such that if a majority of
the companies had wanted protection, the case would have had to
proceed _ probably leading to high tariffs on oil long before the
facts were determined. That is because the law calls for tariffs to
be collected while a case proceeds, with refunds to be made if the
exporter eventually prevails.
</P>
<P>
   The American anti-dumping law is so broad that a domestic
industry can claim relief based on the fact that a foreign company
managed to sell its product to someone else for more than it was
able to get from an American importer _ even if the price charged
here was above the exporter's costs. That was part of the case the
domestic companies made against Saudi Arabia, Mexico, Iraq and
Venezuela after world oil prices plunged last year.
</P>
<P>
   The application of anti-dumping laws in the case of an
international commodity such as oil is absurd, since it is the
market _ not any individual exporting country _ that sets the
price. Some of the countries being complained about have production
costs far below those of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States preaches free trade, but its anti-dumping law
provides a protectionist barrier that shields uncompetitive
industries. The law should be narrowed to assure that a case such
as the oil companies filed would be impossible even if the entire
industry wanted the protection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
